A2021 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHRONICLE-SFCHRON &LR;      05-11 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRONICLE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Chronicle Publishing Considers Strategy, Hires Investment
Banker  to Advise Owners 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Tom Abate &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (c) 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle Publishing Co., owner of the San Francisco
Chronicle, KRON-TV and several other media properties, said it has
hired an investment banking firm to ``review and evaluate the
company's financial, business and strategic plans.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Chronicle Publishing chief executive John Sias said the
move doesn't signal a sale, industry observers said hiring New
York's Donaldson Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette strongly suggests the privately
held company will put all or part of itself up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nine times out of 10 that's what happens when you hire an
investment banker,'' said John Morton, a media consultant in Silver
Spring, Md.
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle Publishing owns The San Francisco Chronicle and two
other newspapers, the Bloomington (Ill.) Pantagraph and the
Worcester (Mass.) Telegram &AMP; Gazette. It owns three TV stations:
KRON in San Francisco; KAKE in Wichita, Kan.; and WOWT in Omaha,
Neb.
</P>
<P>
   Other properties include Chronicle Books and MBI, a Wisconsin
book publisher. Online service SFGate and cable news channel BayTV
round out the company's holdings and give it a total employment of
about 3,200.
</P>
<P>
   If the company were put up for sale, the buyer probably could
not own The Chronicle and KRON. Chronicle Publishing is exempt from
Federal Communications Commission rules that generally prohibit
ownership of a TV station and daily newspaper in the same market.
However, the agency is expected to review whether the rules should
be scrapped.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Chronicle Publishing board declined comment. But
Francis Martin, a member of a family that controls one-sixth of the
company's shares, sought to dampen speculation about a sale or
breakup of the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have hired them (DLJ) to do an analysis of what our
strategic options might be,'' Martin said. ``We have not asked them
to come in and appraise the value of our assets.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Broadwater, managing director of Veronis Suhler &AMP;
Associates, a New York investment bank that specializes in media
deals, said there is a ``somewhat of a seller's market'' for
newspaper and television properties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interest in newspaper ownership is as strong as we've seen it
since the late 1980s,'' Broadwater said. ``TV broadcasting is
another area that is hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Any possible sale of The Chronicle involves New York's Hearst
Corp., publisher of the San Francisco Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   Until 2005, The Chronicle and the Examiner are under a
joint-operating agreement. Signed in 1965, the JOA allowed the two
papers to share noneditorial operations such as printing,
circulation and advertising. The papers equally share revenues and
expenses from their joint operation, the San Francisco Newspaper
Agency.
</P>
<P>
   The papers maintain separate newsrooms and separate ownership.
The agreement also dictates that The Chronicle publish in the
morning and the Examiner in the afternoon. Each paper contributes
sections to a combined Sunday edition.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst and Chronicle Publishing are privately held, and neither
has disclosed all the terms of the JOA. But it is widely assumed
the deal gives either paper first crack at buying the other, Morton
said.
</P>
<P>
   The JOA makes it difficult to estimate the value of The
Chronicle, he added, because an outside bidder would have to split
profits with Hearst Corp. until 2005, then face the prospect that
the Examiner might switch to morning publication after the JOA
expires, starting a costly newspaper war.
</P>
<P>
   Based on The Chronicle's current circulation of 475,000, Morton
estimated the paper could fetch $400 million to $1 billion or more.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Sacramento's McClatchy Newspapers paid $1.2 billion
for the Minneapolis Star Tribune, which had 387,000 subscribers at
the time. But Morton said the Star Trib wasn't encumbered by a JOA
and wasn't ringed by suburban newspaper chains, whereas The
Chronicle must compete with Knight Ridder Inc. in Santa Clara and
Contra Costa counties, Gannett Corp. in Marin and the Alameda
Newspaper Group in the East Bay.
</P>
<P>
   As one of the last, large family-owned newspapers in the nation,
The Chronicle would likely attract interest from all the large
newspaper chains, Morton said.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Flynn, a television industry analyst with Kagan Media
Appraisals in Carmel, said two recent broadcast deals provide
benchmarks for the potential worth of NBC affiliate KRON, the
largest of Chronicle Publishing's three broadcast properties.
</P>
<P>
   She said CBS paid $485 million last month to buy a CBS-affiliate
station in Dallas, the nation's seventh-largest media market. The
San Francisco Bay Area is No. 5 in market size. In another deal,
Hearst-Argyle Corp., Hearst's television arm, paid $530 million
last year to acquire KCRA-TV and two smaller TV properties in
Sacramento, ranked 20th market in size, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The final price anyone is willing to pay depends on the cash
flow and the profitability of the station, and just how much the
buyer wants to be in San Francisco,'' Flynn said.
</P>
<P>
   One source said that TV stations typically sell for 12 to 13
times cash flow. The source estimated that KRON's annual cash flow
is $40 million to $50 million, giving it a ballpark value of $480
million to $650 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle was founded in 1865 by two brothers, Michael and
Charles DeYoung. The company is still owned by their descendants.
But as shares have passed from generation to generation, control
has become widely dispersed.
</P>
<P>
   One-third of the shares are owned by Nan Tucker McEvoy and her
son Nion McEvoy, who also sits on the Chronicle Publishing board.
Members of the Theriot and Stent families together control another
third of the company. The Tobin and Martin families control the
remaining third.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992 and 1997, the family owners of Chronicle Publishing
called in outside investment bankers or consultants for advice. In
1992, this process led to the hiring of outside managers to replace
family members who had, until then, run the newspaper and
television operations.
</P>
<P>
   Until the mid-1990s, Nan McEvoy and members of the Tobin clan
constituted a shareholder majority in favor of retaining family
ownership. But that coalition broke down, leaving the McEvoys in
the minority.
</P>
<P>
   If DLJ should recommend the sale of the entire company, that
decision would need to be approved by a majority of the 10-member
board of directors and by shareholders owning a majority of the
stock, according to one source.
</P>
<P>
   But a majority of the board could vote to sell parts of the
company without shareholder approval, the source said.
</P>
<P>
   The company's bylaws apparently would let the board, which
consists of five family members and five outside directors, sell
the largest and most valuable properties, including The Chronicle
and KRON, without a shareholder vote.
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle staff writer Carol Emert contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
