<HEADLINE>
BOOS RAIN DOWN ON HULL IN HIS RETURN TO ST. LOUIS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ They booed Brett Hull when he stepped on the ice.
They booed Brett Hull when his name was announced. They booed him
loudest when he scored a goal.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Hull, once the favorite son of St. Louis _ once as big as
the Cardinals' Mark McGwire _ was given the villain treatment last
night as he returned for the playoffs in a Stars uniform. And while
Hull scored a goal in the Stars' 3-2 overtime loss, he left the
game mostly as just another player on another team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they're over it,'' he said. ``I mean, it's been a
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull, who scored most of his 586 career goals (13th all-time in
the NHL) in a Blues uniform, left the Blues as a free agent in the
summer and signed with the Stars. Going back, even in a loss, even
to be booed, was seen as a good thing, as part of his transition to
the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``He plays for the Dallas Stars,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock
said before the game. ``He's going to have to learn to get over it.
That's the business of hockey. There's too much at stake right now
for him to worry about anything other than contributing to our
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull said he did just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's done, this is old news,'' he said. ``I play for the
Stars.''
Lehtinen hurt
</P>
<P>
   Stars winger Jere Lehtinen _ one of the finalists to win the
Selke Trophy as best defensive forward in the NHL _ left last
night's game in the second period with a right knee sprain and did
not return. Lehtinen got tangled up with a Blues player in front of
the Stars' net.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock juggled his lines and ended up playing Jamie
Langenbrunner on the left wing with Hull and Mike Modano.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all over the map there for a while,'' Hitchcock said.
``But I thought Langenbrunner did a good job on the left side.''
Lukowich in
</P>
<P>
   Stars defenseman Shawn Chambers missed last night's game with a
knee sprain and is listed as day-to-day. He could return for Game
4, Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   In Chambers' place, rookie Brad Lukowich played his fourth game
of the playoffs. Lukowich has moved in and out of the lineup with
surprising ease, Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even think of him as a minor-league player anymore.
We've just got a good up-and-coming National Hockey League player
now,'' Hitchcock said. ``It's hard for him to come in and go out
like that, but when he did that in the first round, he didn't get
worse, he got better.''
Carbonneau to return
</P>
<P>
   Stars center Guy Carbonneau attended the funeral of his father
in Quebec yesterday and is expected to join the Stars today.
Carbonneau, who has missed the past five games with a knee injury,
is expected to play in Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   Also out for the Stars last night were: Chambers (knee), Doug
Lidster, Blake Sloan, Tony Hrkac, Jon Sim and Aaron Gavey. Gavey
was brought up from the Michigan K-Wings and will practice with the
Stars for the remainder of the playoffs.
Sloan scratched
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in the playoffs, Hitchcock made a healthy
scratch of winger Sloan. In place of Sloan, Hitchcock used Derek
Plante to center the third line of Mike Keane and Tony Hrkac and
inserted Pat Verbeek in Sloan's place on the fourth line with Dave
Reid and Brian Skrudland. Verbeek was returning from a one-game
suspension for a slashing incident in Game 1.
Streak alive
</P>
<P>
   Langenbrunner extended his career best playoff scoring streak to
six games. Langenbrunner assisted on Hull's first-period power-play
goal and has three goals and four assists during the streak.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
