<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKENOT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON FISHES FOR ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ While the Los Angeles Lakers pondered ways
to slow Charles Barkley, the Houston Rockets had their own
head-scratching sessions to figure out how to stop the Lakers'
offensive triad of Shaquille O'Neal, Glen Rice and, of course,
Derek Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so throw Kobe Bryant in there, too. Those four starters
combined for 93 points in Game 1 on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest surprise was Fisher's 20 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played much better than we anticipated, much better than we
wanted him to play,'' Houston's Scottie Pippen said. ``That sort of
hurt us.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest contribution was Rice's 29 points. And even more
impressive that it came against Pippen, one of the best defenders
in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize when you have a guy that's such a great player as
Scottie Pippen, you can't go out there and go half-speed,'' Rice
said. ``You gotta really go out there and try to take it to him as
much as possible. If you don't, he'll embarrass you out there, and
I don't wanna get embarrassed.''
</P>
<P>
   The hot-shooting Rice scored 20 points in the first half but was
relatively quiet in the second, taking only three shots in the
fourth quarter as Pippen played him tighter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He became a no-leave guy,'' Lakers coach Kurt Rambis said.
``(Pippen) made sure he was staying home on Glen to give him less
and less opportunities to get the basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, meant one fewer Rockets defender to double-team
O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   Rice's hot streak has been timely. Over the last three games,
Rice is averaging 30.3 points _ he averaged 7.0 in the two previous
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in a zone right now,'' O'Neal said, ``and when a guy like
that is in the zone, you gotta keep him in the zone.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Undaunted: O'Neal missed 3 of 4 free throws down the stretch
Sunday, including an instance when Barkley intentionally fouled him
after a defensive rebound, showing the lack of respect opponents
have for his foul shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm gonna hit them,'' O'Neal, a 53-percent career foul
shooter, vowed once again. ``I'm not worried, I'm not worried at
all. Do I look worried?''
</P>
<P>
   And he still dreams of making two free throws to win a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day, down by one, no seconds on the clock, I'm gonna hit
two in a row, and I'm flipping all of y'all off, all the media. No,
just kidding,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I like to shut you guys (reporters) up because I
know you guys think I can't do certain things. I can do it all. I'm
an all-purpose big man. Did you see, I got out, led the break,
threw the lob to Kobe (for a dunk on Sunday). Passing, give and go,
play defense at the end. I just like to shut people up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
