<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CHINA-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA'S GOVERNMENT WIDENS ROLE IN ANTI-U.S. PROTESTS AT EMBASSY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for updating, rewriting throughout)   (sw) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Chinese officials choreographed protests against the
American Embassy here on Monday, with a relentless procession of
tens of thousands of angry demonstrators that lasted into the
night.
</P>
<P>
   But on Tuesday morning only a few scattered protests occurred
around the embassy, a sign that the government had decided to
moderate the anti-American campaign after three days of sometimes
violent protests, set off by the bombing of the Chinese Embassy in
Belgrade during a NATO raid on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   And Tuesday morning, Chinese television and newspapers belatedly
reported for the first time that President Clinton and other NATO
leaders had made apologies for the attack.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear how far the reported apologies
would mollify an enraged population. In New York on Monday night a
senior Chinese diplomat, Liu Xiaoming, indicated that Clinton's
words to date were insufficient, saying, ``So far I have not seen a
formal and serious apology.''
</P>
<P>
   The marchers on Monday were ushered by police officers to within
25 feet of the embassy. Many chanted ``Down with American
imperialism!'' and sang the Chinese national anthem. The protests
were more controlled than those over the weekend. But young men
continued to heave pieces of concrete against the battered facade
right over the helmeted militiamen.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the situation over the weekend, when tens of
thousands of spontaneous anti-NATO protesters roamed almost at
will, the authorities had protest groups keep to a schedule and
designated their route.
</P>
<P>
   As it tightened control over the demonstrations and then halted
them, the governing Communist Party appeared to be attempting to
harness public passions, both to contain them and to reinforce its
control over society. In an elaborately staged display of national
unity, over the last two days government offices and social
organizations around the country were ordered to hold meetings and
issue denunciations of the bombing, people involved said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday most of the protesters were university students and
faculty members, but some state companies were also allowed to send
large delegations. Demonstrators said that as their organizations
applied for permission to come to the embassy, the Public Security
Bureau told them when and where to assemble.
</P>
<P>
   Students, workers and others who showed up on their own were
allowed to tag along with an approved group.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of how well the day's protests were staged,
representatives of major official religious groups arrived and
marched in sequence _ dozens of Buddhist monks, followed by a
contingent of Tibetans monks, then Taoists, then Catholic,
Protestant and Muslim leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I am a Chinese, why do you think I shouldn't come?''
snapped a Tibetan monk in a scarlet robe when asked why he was
marching.
</P>
<P>
   While Americans have been advised to exercise caution, the
American Embassy has not ordered dependents to leave. International
schools have closed. American consular officials in Chengdu, where
the official residence was burned early Sunday, and in Shenyang
have moved into hotels.
</P>
<P>
   At the American and British Embassies, the government deployed
thousands of troops from the People's Armed Police, a special
anti-riot force under the military, and large contingents remained
in place in the embassy district on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The American ambassador remained virtually trapped in the
embassy for three days because his security advisers feared what
might happen if he emerged. On Tuesday morning, conditions appeared
to be easing but the ambassador, James Sasser, and other officials
said they would remain inside the embassy until it was clear that
they could safely leave and return.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday afternoon, Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan telephoned
Sasser. Mr. Tang relayed four demands to ``U.S.-led NATO''
regarding the bombing of the embassy.
</P>
<P>
   The demands, as described by Chinese authorities, were these: an
``open and official apology'' to China and the victims' relatives;
a thorough investigation; prompt disclosure of the results of the
investigation, and ``to punish severely those responsible for the
attack.''
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Sasser said he had complained in
return that the state-run news media had not reported that Clinton,
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and the ambassador himself
had made apologies.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, even the most temperate demonstrators insisted that
Clinton had not done nearly enough to atone for the damage.
</P>
<P>
   Passions remained intense as the state-run news media continued
to stoke outrage by calling the bombing an intentional criminal
act. Tuesday's issue of the People's Daily, the Communist Party's
flagship, carried a brief report of NATO leaders' apologies on Page
6. But in a front-page commentary, it called the embassy bombing a
``barbaric crime'' and referred to ``NATO led by the United
States'' as an ``arch criminal.''
</P>
<P>
   Many people spend their evenings avidly watching television news
programs that have shown, for example, wrenching scenes of a
Chinese victim's father in Belgrade sobbing as he handles his dead
daughter's blood-stained quilt.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the bombing of the Chinese Embassy, President Jiang
Zemin, who has cultivated closer relations with the United States,
was under strong pressure from the military and the public to take
a stronger stance against the American-led attacks on Yugoslavia,
according to Chinese political analysts.
</P>
<P>
   China announced on Monday that it was suspending its official
dialogue with the United States over human rights and postponing
high-level military contacts and consultations on weapons
proliferation, arms control and international security. No mention
was made of talks on China's entry to the World Trade Organization,
which are at a climactic phase.
</P>
<P>
   Viktor Chernomyrdin, Russia's special envoy on the Yugoslav
crisis, arrived here on Monday for consultations and was meeting on
Tuesday with Prime Minister Zhu Rongji and President Jiang. Russia
and China are the strongest opponents of the NATO air attacks, and
many Chinese now say their country should develop stronger ties
with Russia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
