<HEADLINE>
DODGERS HAVE PLAYERS-ONLY MEETING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A day after left fielder Gary Sheffield said the
Los Angeles Dodgers were too lackadaisical in their approach, they
talked about it.
</P>
<P>
   Before opening a three-game series Monday against the Chicago
Cubs at Dodger Stadium, the Dodgers had a players-only meeting to
discuss what happened _ or didn't happen _ when they lost two of
three games to the lowly Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to play better than we are playing right now,'' right
fielder Raul Mondesi said. ``We played what, 30 games? You have to
be 25-5. You compare every player on this team to every player on
other teams, American League or National League. You go position by
position. We have talent.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers might have superior talent, but they entered Monday
with a 17-14 mark, 1{ games behind the San Francisco Giants in the
NL West.
</P>
<P>
   With high-profile free-agent acquisitions and trades during the
offseason and a payroll near $80 million, expectations called for
the Dodgers to be more than three games above .500 at this point in
the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have all the talent we have, that's the way you have to
play,'' Mondesi said. ``You have to win. You have to play better. I
don't care what time (guys) go to sleep, but by the time it's time
to play, they have to be ready to play 100 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers were coming off a 7-2 road trip in which it beat up
the poorest teams in baseball. But the meeting was called after the
Marlins (8-23) won their first series of the season by rallying
from a 4-0 deficit to beat the Dodgers on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to play well against the Cubs,'' Dodgers first baseman
Eric Karros said. ``Games against the Marlins are games we let get
away, but you don't dwell on it because you don't want something
like that to snowball.''
</P>
<P>
   __ The optimum roster: Dodgers center fielder Devon White,
bothered by a tight hamstring, all but declared himself out of the
three-game series with the Cubs. He said he couldn't play today and
it didn't make sense for him to play Wednesday because they're off
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Davey Johnson shared that belief, but it leaves the
Dodgers in a difficult spot with only three healthy outfielders.
The injury isn't severe enough to disable White, so utility
infielder Tripp Cromer will double as the emergency outfielder.
</P>
<P>
   This particular plight _ like every other one this season _
seems to stem from bullpen problems.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he wants 12 pitchers, which means going with the
usual seven infielders and five outfielders is impossible. The
current spin is that Antonio Osuna can't be used on consecutive
days because of bone spurs in his right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we need to stay at 12 pitchers with Osuna and the way
it's shaking out,'' Johnson said. ``If we get a good start out of
my left-hander (Carlos Perez today), maybe we can go to 11. Until I
see how much I can get out of Osuna. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were to ask me what my optimum balance would be; five
(outfielders), six (infielders), two (catchers) and 12
(pitchers).''
</P>
<P>
   However, with the Dodgers having both Thursday and Monday off,
the bullpen could survive with 11 pitchers. If so, the Dodgers
might think of recalling Trenidad Hubbard from Triple-A
Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's playing good down there, but how do I get him without
going down to 11?'' Johnson said. ``Ideally, you have six
(infielders) and five (outfielders). Until we do something there,
I'm kind of heavy. The way it is now, I'd like to get Trenidad
here. How I can get him here is your guess.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Around the horn: Jose Vizcaino started at shortstop in place
of Mark Grudzielanek. It was Vizcaino's seventh start in the last
eight games. . . . Todd Hollandsworth started for White in center
field. . . . Cubs slugger Sammy Sosa entered the game with seven
homers in the first 28 games. He hit his eighth homer last season
in the Cubs' 42nd game.
</P>
</TEXT>
