A2036 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     05-11 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAME 3 LOSS COULD BE JUST WHAT THE STARS NEEDED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Figuring out a way to win had become a post-season
habit for the Stars. As of last night, however, they now have
something new to ponder.
</P>
<P>
   How does this team handle losing?
</P>
<P>
   Pavol Demitra of the St. Louis Blues landed an overtime knockout
punch on the Stars. Just under three minutes into sudden death,
Demitra slipped the puck between the goal post and Ed Belfour's
skate, and it was hard to say who celebrated more _ the jubilant
Blues or a capacity crowd of Hull-haters at the Kiel Center.
</P>
<P>
   With this 3-2 bruise for the Stars in Game 3, a second-round
playoff sweat suddenly surfaced. The streak of six consecutive
Dallas postseason victories vanished, and four of those had come
after trailing in the third period. Here's a new thought _ momentum
might even be creeping St. Louis' way.
</P>
<P>
   The Blues make a case when they claim the better team didn't win
Game 2 at Reunion Arena, and the Stars certainly established no
dominance again last night. It could be said the best team did win
Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Ken Hitchcock, who was declaring the series a
draw in the postgame locker room. No, Hitch didn't flunk math. The
Stars are still up two games to one, but he was making a point in
saying ``these are now two evenly matched teams.''
</P>
<P>
   No one in the hockey world believes either Hitchcock's words or
his math, the Stars being heavily favored. But it also seems safe
to assume the Stars' coach has been waiting for a chance to poke at
his team with a sharp stick.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first two games \Ragainst St. Louis\S, we played just
good enough to win, but tonight that wasn't good enough,'' said
Hitchcock. ``What has to happen next is us taking our game to a
level we haven't approached yet \Rin the playoffs\S.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just one thing, or two things _ everything we've got
has to be drastically moved up. That starts with emotion and then
it applies to the whole strength of our game.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Hitchcock admitted it publicly, but he didn't say
``no'' when asked if last night loss was necessarily a bad thing.
</P>
<P>
   The road to the Stanley Cup is all about facing and surviving
pressure. With the Detroit Red Wings looming next, a stern test of
survival against the Blues could either be beneficial, or a
disaster if the series upset happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone expected us to go 16-and-0 in the
playoffs,'' shrugged forward Joe Nieuwendyk, who had his most
docile evening of the playoffs. ``You always hate to lose, but the
real key is to keep the highs of a win in check as well as the lows
of a loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Nieuwendyk added the obvious. ``There's no question we've
now got a series going here,'' he said
</P>
<P>
   Any more second periods for Dallas like last night, and it's a
series the Blues will win.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Hull's homecoming goal on, yes, a power play in the first
period allowed the evening to get away to a nice start. But the 1-0
lead the Stars carried into the second period came under immediate
siege. St. Louis took the game over on both ends of the ice,
blasting away at Belfour. The shot advantage was a massive 16-5 for
the Blues, who somehow managed only the tying goal.
</P>
<P>
   Ever wondered why Jere Lehtinen is considered the best defensive
forward in the NHL? Well, he went out early in the second period
with a knee injury, and didn't return. The Blues noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just hanging on, trying to get that period over
with,'' said Hitchcock. ``Once we got through it, we regrouped and
responded well in the third.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blues grabbed a 2-1 lead in the third period, the Stars tied
it with 10:51 left, and another of those bounce-back victories was
looming.
</P>
<P>
   Except this time, the awful power play was too much to overcome.
After the Hull goal, the joke started again about Belfour being
Dallas' best player on the power play.
</P>
<P>
   And this time Nieuwendyk also couldn't ride to the rescue. He
got off one shot in 63 minutes, with Pierre Turgeon getting most of
the defensive applause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give them credit for playing better defense overall, and
Turgeon had a good game,'' said Nieuwendyk. ``But I didn't think I
was getting any extra attention out there. They limited the good
scoring chances for all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   And now the Stars have a worry. Tomorrow night we find out if
that's a good thing or a real worry.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
