<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-WHITE-SOX-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSIVE MISCUES COST RANGERS IN LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The American League West, Rangers manager Johnny Oates
predicted this spring, will be decided by defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers should be concerned.
</P>
<P>
   Forget that the Rangers _ who collected a season-high 20 hits in
Sunday's victory in Toronto _ managed only six during their 5-2
defeat last night to the Chicago White Sox at Comiskey Park.
</P>
<P>
   Defense doomed the Rangers, who gift-wrapped and hand-delivered
the White Sox three runs with three plays not made in the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming out of spring training, I thought we would have a very
alert, defensive-type ballclub,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates
said. ``For whatever reason _ and it doesn't matter whether it's
hitting, pitching or defense _ it just seems like it comes and
goes.''
</P>
<P>
   That explains why the Rangers _ despite the major leagues'
sixth-highest payroll and a roster loaded with experienced veterans
_ will enter tonight's game only two games above .500 and 1 1/2
games in front of the Oakland Athletics in the AL West.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that we should be winning more games than
we are,'' said right-hander Rick Helling, who failed to field a
potential double-play ground ball through the middle during
Chicago's two-run fourth inning. ``Games like tonight don't help.''
</P>
<P>
   Right fielder Juan Gonzalez negated the second-inning,
bases-empty home run by Chicago's Magglio Ordonez with his
fourth-inning, run-scoring single. Yet, it would be Gonzalez and
Helling (3-4) most responsible for the White Sox's regaining the
lead during the bottom half of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The elements played a factor on both occasions.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez misplayed a deep fly ball off the bat of first baseman
Paul Konerko into a leadoff double. The ball carried to the warning
track and _ being hit by a right-handed batter and further aided by
wind _ continued its awkward slice toward the right-field foul
pole.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez struggled not only with the wind, he said, but picking
the ball up off the bat. Otherwise, Konerko's fly ball normally
results in an out. Helling walked Greg Norton during the next plate
appearance before then inducing what appeared to be a double-play
ground ball from left fielder Carlos Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Helling, though, deflected the ball into no-man's land.
Shortstop Kelly Dransfeldt fielded the deflection with no play to
be made anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never really saw that ball,'' said Helling, who blamed
Chicago's brisk wind for teary eyes that prevented him from seeing
the ground ball.
</P>
<P>
   Konerko scored on a double-play ground ball, and Norton scored
after catcher Brook Fordyce's two-out, two-strike single to right
field.
</P>
<P>
   That was all White Sox right-hander Jaime Navarro (2-3) needed.
Navarro allowed only one run on four hits and one walk during his
best performance this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really been on a roll lately,'' White Sox manager Jerry
Manuel said. ``We're confident that he has arrived and is back to
the form that made him one of the top pitchers in the National
League.''
</P>
<P>
   The seventh inning proved equally gruesome for the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago second baseman Ray Durham led off the inning with a
triple, but Helling induced an infield pop-up from shortstop Mike
Caruso to prevent another run.
</P>
<P>
   Helling issued an intentional walk to designated hitter Frank
Thomas to set up a potential inning-ending double play.
Right-hander Tim Crabtree, who relieved Helling, induced the
necessary ground ball.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Mark McLemore, though, failed to record one out _
much less two _ after bobbling the ball during the hurried attempt.
Durham scored on what became the Rangers' 10th error during the
past six games. The Rangers entered last night's game ranked 11th
among the league's 14 teams with a .978 fielding percentage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crabtree came in and did a great job by getting two
double-play ground balls,'' Helling said, ``and we didn't turn
either one.''
</P>
<P>
   The second potential ground-ball double play not turned that
inning did not matter.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers gave this game away long before then.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
