<SLUG> BC-HKN-BLUES-SIDER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVERTIME FAMILIAR GROUND FOR BLUES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Craig Conroy said he realizes that a loss last night
wouldn't have officially eliminated the Blues from the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   He let himself linger on ``officially.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To go down 3-0, after having to come back from down 3-1 last
series, that took all we had,'' Conroy said. ``Then to turn around
and try to come back from down 3-0 against this team ...''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't finish his sentence. In his mind, a loss in Game 3
last night would have been the same as eliminating the Blues.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, with a single flick of his wrist, Blues winger Pavol
Demitra propelled a Blues bunch teetering dangerously close to
elimination back into the series.
</P>
<P>
   His goal 163 seconds into overtime gave St. Louis a 3-2 victory
and sliced Dallas' best-of-seven series lead in half, 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could be up 2-1, too,'' Blues winger Scott Young said,
echoing a prevailing thought among his teammates that Game 2 had a
chance to be a St. Louis victory.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis has been performing this balancing act throughout the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Half of the Blues' playoff games have gone into overtime,
including Game 2 in this series, a 5-4 Stars' victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've had a lot of exposure to it,'' Blues coach Joel
Quenneville quipped.
</P>
<P>
   They are 3-2 in those games and 1-1 against the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overtime games, that's what happens,'' Young said. ``It's a
bounce here, a bounce there. One good play, one good rush. We could
definitely be down 3-0, or up 2-1.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference last night was that players the Blues weren't
necessarily expecting to score did.
</P>
<P>
   Blues center Jochen Hecht scored his first career playoff goal
to give the Blues a 2-1 lead early in the third period. Center Mike
Eastwood scored his first playoff goal this season to tie the game
at 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   And Demitra, who had been struggling until coming alive in Game
2, scored again. This time, it was the game winner in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to get contributions from every guy,'' Young said.
``There are lots of unsung heroes in the playoffs, and we're
getting that right now and that's why we're successful. Any team
that is successful throughout the playoffs is the team that gets
goals from the fourth line and the third line as well as the first
and second line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen that for two years with Detroit.''
</P>
<P>
   Young said he noticed a quieter atmosphere in St. Louis' locker
room before this overtime game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed a little bit quieter,'' he said. ``I don't know if
it's because they came back to tie the game up. The other games we
were facing elimination, so guys were pretty adamant about `No way,
we wanted to get eliminated.'
</P>
<P>
   ``If we did lose this game, it was almost like an elimination
game. Being down 3-0 to those guys, I think we realized that.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-99 0055EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990511.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 00:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2040 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BLUES-STARS-TEX     05-11 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BLUES-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ST. LOUIS WINS IN OT, TRAILS 2-1 IN SERIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The playoffs officially begin today for the Stars.
Now, they have a challenge to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   After winning six consecutive games to start the playoffs, the
Stars last night were handed a 3-2 overtime defeat at the hands of
the St. Louis Blues. Blues winger Pavol Demitra flicked in a goal
just 2:43 into overtime off a perfect cycle play in which Blues
winger Geoff Courtnall fed Demitra going to the net. It was the
kind of play the Stars have been making in crunch time during the
playoffs _ and the kind of mistake they had been avoiding.
</P>
<P>
   But the Blues were able to turn the tables and close the gap on
the best-of-seven Western Conference semifinals to 2-1 heading into
Game 4 at Kiel Center tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little bit of a wakeup call that says the competition
is here,'' Stars center Brian Skrudland said. ``And what it does is
it makes us start saying: We're the team that believes it's the
best, we're the team that's had the best regular-season record for
the past two seasons, we're the team with the expectations and we
need to be the team that relishes those expectations. We're the
team that needs to go after them.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock also reacted calmly to the loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we played well at times, and in overtime anything is
up for grabs,'' Hitchcock said. ``We knew this was going to be a
long series. It would have been nice to win this game, it could
have been this close, but we're going to have to rebound and play
even stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   The game was a microcosm of what the series likely will become.
The Stars were dominant in the first period and held the shots to
5-3 in their advantage, taking a 1-0 lead. The Blues were dominant
in the second period and had a 16-5 advantage in that span, tying
the game 1-1. The Stars came back to control much of the third
period, and the Blues dominated the short overtime, getting off
four shots in under three minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, the Blues dominate when they spring their speedy
forwards through the neutral zone and catch the Stars either taking
chances or simply sleeping _ a sort of fastbreak-style Showtime on
Ice. The Stars, meanwhile, have found an advantage when they slow
the game down and make forced plays to set up the attack in the
offensive zone _ a sort of four corners.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the two sides are smashing heads in deciding who is
going to control the flow of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They play their style of game and we have to get away from
that if we want to win,'' Stars defenseman Darryl Sydor said. ``We
got a little out of control, a little panicky and have a way of
doing that to us. We can't afford to do that. We have to be more
like we were in the first period.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars struck early as they scored for the first time on the
power play in the series and for only the third time in the
playoffs. Brett Hull came out of the penalty box after serving a
bench minor for too many men on the ice (the Blues made it a 4-on-4
with a Chris Pronger high stick) and scored off a Joe Nieuwendyk
feed. Hull, who played for 11 seasons and was returning to Kiel
Center for his first playoff game, was booed heartily for his
second playoff goal and second of the series.
</P>
<P>
   That lead held up as the Blues looked completely out of synch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had two great chances right after that, and if we could
have extended it ...,'' Hitchcock said, his voice trailing off.
``Right now, there's just not a lot of difference between the two
teams.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blues proved that in the second period as they outshot the
Stars, 16-5, and forced Stars goalie Ed Belfour into some
incredible saves before tying the game on a Mike Eastwood goal. The
Stars lost focus and almost lost the game right there, but stayed
composed enough to force a tie heading into the third period.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Blues rookie Jochen Hecht scored at the 4:52 mark of the
third period, and Kiel Center erupted, bringing a surge of energy
back to the series. Sydor made a blind pass that Blues defenseman
Ricard Persson picked off to set up the second goal, and Richard
Matvichuk took himself out of the play on the second goal when he
tried to behead Demitra. Both lapses were uncharacteristic of the
Stars, but showed how they reacted when the tempo and physical play
increased.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, for a while, we were a little panicky there,''
Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   But Sydor redeemed himself with an outstanding play to tie the
game at the 9:08 mark of the third period. The Stars defenseman
kept the puck in at the point, fed Pat Verbeek for a big shot and
then rushed to front of the net to poke in a rebound.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, the Stars thought they might have a chance at a
series sweep in overtime. After all, they had won two previous
overtime games in the playoffs and had come back from third-period
deficits on four occasions.
</P>
<P>
   But Demitra ended that with his third goal and his fourth point
in the past two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just playoff hockey, that's just the way it's been for
us pretty much every game these playoffs,'' Langenbrunner said.
``We came up here wanting to win one game and we still have that
opportunity. We've got to come out and play a better game.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
