<HEADLINE>
STARS FALL VICTIM TO BLUES' REVIVAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The playoffs officially begin today for the Stars.
Now, they have a challenge to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   After winning six consecutive games to start the playoffs, the
Stars on Monday night were handed a 3-2 overtime defeat at the
hands of the St. Louis Blues. Blues winger Pavol Demitra flicked in
a goal just 2:43 into overtime off a perfect cycle play in which
Blues winger Geoff Courtnall fed Demitra going to the net. It was
the kind of play the Stars have been making in crunch time during
the playoffs _ and the kind of mistake they had been avoiding.
</P>
<P>
   But the Blues were able to turn the tables and close the gap on
the best-of-seven Western Conference semifinals to 2-1 heading into
Game 4 at Kiel Center on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little bit of a wakeup call that says the competition
is here,'' Stars center Brian Skrudland said. ``And what it does is
it makes us start saying: We're the team that believes it's the
best, we're the team that's had the best regular-season record for
the past two seasons, we're the team with the expectations and we
need to be the team that relishes those expectations. We're the
team that needs to go after them.''
</P>
