<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELEBS-SAY-NO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELEBRITIES THANK KIDS FOR SAYING NO TO DRUGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
 
  
BY STEVE CARNEY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Unlike a lot of students, the kids at Parkman
Middle School stay late because they're staying out of trouble _
and Evander Holyfield, Johnny Gill and Erik Estrada stopped by to
say thanks.
</P>
<P>
   A dozen celebrities visited the school in suburban Woodland
Hills on Monday during a half-day party, a reward to the students
and volunteers involved in the school's DARE Plus program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came out here to congratulate the kids for staying off
drugs,'' said ``Baywatch'' hunk Michael Bergin, who sent the
12-year-old girls swooning with pecks to their cheeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had my own little DARE program growing up with my father,''
who was a state police sergeant in Connecticut, Bergin said. ``That
contributed to my path. Without that, I wouldn't be where I am
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Drug Abuse Resistance Education has been taught in Los Angeles
schools for many years, but its expansion to an after-school
program began seven years ago, four at Parkman.
</P>
<P>
   Central to the program is that adults lead after-school
activities for the kids, including creative writing, crochet,
ceramics and flag football, as well as giving career and college
advice. The rationale is that if students remain on campus, they
won't be on the street, bored and looking for trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``The teachers here are really cool. I learned about snakes and
animals'' in one after-school program, said sixth-grader Connie
Chan, 11.
</P>
<P>
   At the carnival, the school's 1,200 students ran from booth to
booth, shot baskets, played in the batting and pitching cages,
clambered on the inflatable Haunted Slide and listened to blaring
disco and hip hop.
</P>
<P>
   Former ``CHiPs'' star Erik Estrada said he volunteered Monday
because his two sons just completed the DARE program themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like `Just Say No.' They actually get informed,'' he
said. ``The kids are our future. You've got to invest in them.''
</P>
<P>
   Parkman's program, which is serving as a model for other
schools, has 650 students involved. The program uses no tax
dollars, and costs $60,000 a year in donations to operate, said
officials with DARE.
</P>
<P>
   When students use what they learn in their DARE classes to
refuse drugs, alcohol, tobacco and gang membership, ``that's a
victory for society,'' said Glenn A. Levant, DARE America founder.
And the celebrities help show students ``that somebody's
recognizing their silent heroism. The whole world is out there in
support of your being drug-free.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
