<HEADER>
A2048 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN     05-11 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL LAKERS HIT BOTTOM?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Bad mismatches: a 20-acre fire vs. a squirt
gun. Niagara Falls vs. an umbrella. The wind vs. Jimmy Johnson's
hair. Temptation vs. Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   And Charles Barkley's rear vs. almost anyone in his way.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley's back-down into the paint is as predictable as Barry
Sanders on third-and-inches. But Sanders gets the first down
anyway, and Barkley's rear-end will inevitably push defenders right
to the hoop for easy buckets, over and over and over.
</P>
<P>
   And so Barkley did Sunday, scoring 12 points in the fourth
quarter and rallying his Houston Rockets in a comeback bid that
fell just short.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Lakers got the victory in Game 1 of this
first-round playoff series, but after Barkley's 25-point game, they
spent much of Monday's practice searching for new ways to put out
forest fires with squirt guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to make some adjustments,'' coach Kurt Rambis
said.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably, that means more assistance for undersized power
forwards Robert Horry and J.R. Reid, who simply took turns standing
in Barkley's way. Reid fouled out in the effort, showing how futile
it can be to guard the powerfully built Barkley one on one.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a freak. He's only 6-6, but he's got a great, low center
of gravity, tremendously strong legs,'' Rambis said. ``He's got an
excellent game. He can hurt you going to the baseline or coming to
the middle. He can step out and hit jumpshots. He's quick off the
dribble, he's got tremendous first-step quickness, and he does a
great job of going after any of his missed shots inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``So it doesn't matter who you put on him _ he has an offensive
counter to the defensive weaknesses of whoever you have guarding
him.''
</P>
<P>
   At 6-10 each, Horry (235 pounds) and Reid (250) are taller than
Barkley but too lithe to prevent his backdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Horry and Reid) did some things wrong,'' Rambis said, ``but
if anybody had a way to stop Charles Barkley one on one, they would
have come up with it a long time ago. . . . He's basically
unstoppable inside.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Lakers prepared for tonight's Game 2 at the Forum, they
considered the full range of options. When they faced the Rockets
two weeks ago in Houston, they tried frequent double-teams, but the
savvy Barkley is an accomplished passer as well, and he kept
finding Scottie Pippen and Cuttino Mobley for open jumpers.
</P>
<P>
   Early in Sunday's game, they sent guards to ``dig'' at Barkley
once he began his move and held him to nine points in the first
half. But the Lakers settled for the one-on-one matchups most of
the second half.
</P>
<P>
   And once Barkley shifts into reverse and starts his banging,
there's little the average man can do.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, not really, you just got to hope that he misses,'' Horry
said. ``You've just got to play him as strong as possible. Really,
what he's doing is an offensive foul, if you want to really look at
it. But you just got to hope that you can hold him off and just try
to contest it.''
</P>
<P>
   What next?
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got options,'' Horry said confidently. ``I don't want to
say too much. I'm not going to let y'all get our game plan and have
them read it in the paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Late in Sunday's game, the Lakers even tried 330-pound Shaquille
O'Neal on Barkley, but that left Hakeem Olajuwon with easy shots
over shorter defenders.
</P>
<P>
   There are certain players in the NBA who match up with Barkley
but not many.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys who are big, strong and long and can move, those are the
guys who are going to have the best chance against him,'' Rambis
said. ``Guys that he's not going to be able to just push underneath
the basket. And whenever he does go up for a shot, they've got long
arms to be able to contest his shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Guys like Elden Campbell. The former Lakers power forward was
their best defender against Barkley, but he was traded to Charlotte
along with Eddie Jones for Reid and Glen Rice. No less an authority
than Barkley himself said the Lakers missed Campbell's presence.
</P>
<P>
   Now Barkley says he'll shoot 25 times if he gets single coverage
again. A couple of weeks ago, he literally laughed as he threw
Horry around like a papier-mache mannequin.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does that all the time _ any time he can back somebody
down, he laughs,'' Horry said. ``He can laugh all day as long as we
keep winning.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-99 0109EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
