<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOVER-KAN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITMAN'S CANDIES LAUNCHES TAKEOVER BID FOR ROCKY MOUNTAIN
CHOCOLATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Whitman's Candies Inc., which is owned by
Russell Stover Candies, launched a takeover bid Monday for Rocky
Mountain Chocolate Factory Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman's is offering $5.75 a share in cash for Rocky Mountain
Chocolate, which has its headquarters and a candy factory in
Durango, Colo. Rocky Mountain Chocolate has 2.6 million shares
outstanding, making the bid worth about $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Stover and Whitman's would gain a much larger retail
foothold by acquiring Rocky Mountain Chocolate. The Colorado
company has about 230 company and franchise stores _ including one
in Town Center Plaza in Leawood _ in the United States, Canada and
Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Stover, which bought Whitman's in 1993, has 50 retail
stores. Most of its sales are through other retailers, such as
discount stores and drugstores.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives us another channel,'' said Richard Masinton, chief
administrative officer of Whitman's, which shares offices with
Russell Stover in Kansas City. Russell Stover Candies is the
largest seller of boxed chocolates in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The offer expires June 16. Rocky Mountain Chocolate shares
traded at $3.50 Friday and closed Monday at $5.69 a share. Masinton
said Whitman's offer was a 73 percent premium from Rocky Mountain
Chocolate's 30-day average closing price.
</P>
<P>
   Rocky Mountain executives were not available for comment, but
the company announced that it had hired George K. Baum &AMP; Co. in
Kansas City to advise the company of alternatives that would
enhance shareholder value.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board of directors will carefully review the Russell
Stover offer as well as other alternatives,'' said Frank Crail,
Rocky Mountain's chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   The unsolicited bid from Whitman's comes after discussions with
Rocky Mountain Chocolate. Two months ago the Colorado company said
it would post less-than-expected earnings because of several
problems. A year ago the company's stock was trading at $7.75 a
share, more than double its Friday close.
</P>
<P>
   The company's executives in March said the disappointing
performance stemmed from problems such as an inadequate supply of
seasonal employees, production inefficiencies, higher-than-expected
shipping costs, and a write-down of the value of spoiled and
excessive supplies because of overproduction.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Ward, co-president of Whitman's and Russell Stover, said
the plan for Rocky Mountain would be to focus on its retail stores
and build on the Rocky Mountain brand name of chocolates.
</P>
<P>
   Ward said his companies would be able to provide production,
operating and manufacturing efficiencies in support of the Rocky
Mountain stores.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-99 0110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990511.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 01:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2051 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALLCENTERS-KAN-KAN &LR;      05-11 1877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALLCENTERS-KAN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE THAN 100 CALL CENTERS ARE QUIET, BUT BIG, PART OF AREA
ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Have you ordered a Pizza Hut delivery?
Checked a Vanguard Airlines flight time? Called for a ZIP code
number from the Postal Service?
</P>
<P>
   Have you tracked an Emery Expedite package? Sought technical
support for your Gateway computer? Checked with H&AMP;R Block about
your Rapid Refund?
</P>
<P>
   Have you paid your Missouri Gas Energy bill by phone? Talked to
a long-distance operator? Ordered out of a Disney catalog?
</P>
<P>
   Use the phone for these reasons _ and many more _ and you've
connected with a call center somewhere in the Kansas City area.
</P>
<P>
   On floors of Midtown office buildings, in suburban office parks
and nestled in industrial sites, more than 100 call centers quietly
have become a big part of the metropolitan economic base.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you just look at the 21 to 23 largest call centers, we
think you'd find 40,000 employees either working the phones or
providing support services,'' said Wayne Little, vice
president-work force development at the Kansas City Area
Development Council. ``Then you could probably add another 20,000
to 25,000 people with all the customer service phone banks in
smaller settings.''
</P>
<P>
   It adds up to a lot of people enmeshed in an industry that is
both praised _ as clean, rewarding and full of advancement
opportunities _ and maligned _ as high-pressure sweatshops plagued
with turnover _ depending on the work site and the source.
</P>
<P>
   In March this year, organizers convened the first meeting of the
Professional Teleservice Management Association of Greater Kansas
City, a new group of call center managers and directors. One of the
founders, Greg Malmgren, said he was stunned when he compiled a
mailing list of potential members.
</P>
<P>
   Malmgren, who launched an Overland Park office of TeleSource, a
staffing agency aimed at the call center industry, spent months on
proprietary market research to create the list. He tallied 90 call
centers in the metro area, employing anywhere from five persons to
thousands.
</P>
<P>
   To his list it is possible to add another dozen by reviewing
recent news stories about leases and construction announcements for
metro area call centers. Growth announcements occur monthly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Call centers are growing by leaps and bounds,'' said Jerry
Chappell, owner of ETC Enterprises, a Mission company that places
call centers in rural areas. ``Both inbound and outbound centers
are growing by 20 percent a year.''
</P>
<P>
   The growth of inbound centers is fueled by Internet sales and
customer service fulfillment at countless businesses. Outbound
centers are mushrooming because they're an increasingly
cost-effective way to do direct marketing.
</P>
<P>
   As might be expected for a phone-related industry, AT&AMP;T is the
call center giant in the metro area, with nearly 2,000 workers at a
couple of locations.
</P>
<P>
   Employing about 1,500 each at their call centers are Citicorp
Credit Services and Sprint. Citicorp has a big credit card service
center in northwest Kansas City. Sprint has long-distance and local
call centers at 10 locations sprinkled throughout the region _ from
18th and Vine, to Overland Park, to Gardner and Lawrence.
</P>
<P>
   Other major call center players include Gateway 2000, direct
marketer of personal computers, which employs 1,200 at its Kansas
City call center near Kemper Arena; and ADT Security Services and
American Century Investments, which each have about 900 call center
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Recent call center growth may have been meteoric, but the job
itself is nothing new. Business has been done over the phone for
years.
</P>
<P>
   At the start-up meeting of the teleservice association, MGE call
center supervisor Karen Johnson won a mug for being the
longest-tenured call center worker in attendance. She has worked in
the local industry for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   But the branding of call centers as distinct employment entities
really began in the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realized the specific challenges: technology combined with
recruitment, retention and customer service,'' said Dick Barr,
formerly at Citicorp and now at Vanguard Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Barr was among industry professionals who helped the
Metropolitan Community College's Business and Technology Center
research the local industry before the college system started a
call center training program.
</P>
<P>
   Barr started calling other call center managers a couple of
years ago to meet informally and discuss technology and hiring
issues. His ``users group'' realized that call centers didn't have
a high economic profile despite their employment base.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as 1994, it was hard to find the words ``call
center'' used in a news story. Now, call centers are an economic
buzzword, a name that sets economic development officials
salivating.
</P>
<P>
   What's not to like about a clean industry that nestles quietly
in any neighborhood and pays decent wages? According to area call
center managers interviewed, pay is averaging nearly $9 an hour to
start, with opportunity for raises, bonuses and career advancement.
</P>
<P>
   Tenured call center workers at some companies are making more
than $17 an hour. Pay is especially good at union shops, where
workers are represented by locals of the Communication Workers of
America or the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers.
</P>
<P>
   Pay also is good at call centers where certain professional
skills, such as computer or financial expertise, are required. And,
at the top of the call center hierarchy, some managers and
directors can earn into the six figures at a handful of the biggest
shops.
</P>
<P>
   Still, money isn't the sole motivator for call center growth.
Corporate customer service executives quickly cite the Kansas City
area's appeal to the industry:
</P>
<P>
   - The Central time zone makes it easier to staff call centers to
meet the needs of both East and West coast callers.
</P>
<P>
   - The vaunted Midwestern work ethic lets companies expect and
get higher productivity.
</P>
<P>
   - The relatively well-educated population provides an easily
trainable labor pool.
</P>
<P>
   - Comparatively low-cost commercial and residential real estate
(compared with that in many other large cities) helps attract call
center facilities as well as workers.
</P>
<P>
   - The fairly accent-free Midwest speech is a plus for companies
that want their customer service representatives to be understood
on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Aerial Communications ``did extensive market research before
deciding to locate one of its two call centers in Kansas City,''
said Marsha Bjerkan, director of Aerial's call center in Lenexa.
(The other center is in Tampa, Fla.) ``The labor market was so
attractive here, plus the state of Kansas gave us a good incentive
package.''
</P>
<P>
   The industry's pluses aren't proof that call centers are perfect
places of employment. In fact, the reputation as high-stress,
desk-bound sweatshops was, at some locations, deserved.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, there's a burgeoning ancillary trade in mental health
counseling, book publishing, workplace training and motivational
speaking that feeds off call center stress.
</P>
<P>
   And, like any service trade, call centers are plagued by high
turnover and seasonal ups and downs.
</P>
<P>
   Malmgren estimated the turnover rates range from as low as 15
percent at some of the better-paying, lower-stress call centers to
as high as 75 percent or more a year at some of the lower-paying
centers that do high-stress telemarketing or collections work.
</P>
<P>
   Reducing turnover is high on priority lists for call center
managers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm dead set on keeping people,'' said Scott Crosby of Emery
Expedite. ``I can't afford a revolving door. I will do anything,
try anything, to motivate. We're a 24 by 7. We have to keep a good
staff going.''
</P>
<P>
   ``24 by 7'' is industry jargon for 24 hours a day, 7 days a
week.
</P>
<P>
   Some call centers, such as an in-house one at Hallmark Cards
that supports its network of retailers, operate only during regular
business hours. Others, such as phone companies and some catalog
order businesses, staff around the clock.
</P>
<P>
   The headache of predicting call volume and staffing to meet it
keeps call center managers awake at nights.
</P>
<P>
   Then, too, there's the matter of the metropolitan area's low
unemployment rate. Finding qualified workers is hard for any
business, much less one that requires accuracy, communication and
computer skills from an entry-level labor pool.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of Kansas City area call centers are inbound, not
outbound. Outbound often means telemarketing, which has its own
particular brand of sales quota pressures.
</P>
<P>
   Inbound centers, which receive calls from customers who want
information or service, have stress, too. That stress comes from
both people and technology.
</P>
<P>
   In inbound centers, automated call distributors relentlessly
shoot calls to the next available service representative. You don't
even hear a phone ring. Headsets simply click a warning, and
there's another customer on the line.
</P>
<P>
   Well-managed centers program in off-the-phone time so that
workers aren't fending off a nonstop call barrage for their entire
shift. But the unyielding work pace, and the relative lack of
control over one's daily agenda contributes to worker burnout.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the monitoring of calls by supervisors, which makes
some employees crumple under ``Big Brother is watching'' fears.
</P>
<P>
   The ongoing challenge for call center managers and individual
workers is to maintain morale. And that's not easy when workers
have to deal with the public _ a public that may be irate,
frustrated, surly or just plain needy.
</P>
<P>
   To help reduce turnover and provide polite, informed customer
service, the MGE call center is one that in the last few years has
turned to aggressive pre-employment testing of job applicants.
</P>
<P>
   First, the company tested their best call center workers to
learn what personality characteristics correlated with top
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found even-temperament, detail-oriented people who can
follow instructions well and have good people skills and good
communication skills were our top performers,'' said Karen
Czaplewski, MGE vice president-customer service.
</P>
<P>
   Now, when the utility screens call center applicants, it does
two rounds of interviewing and administers personality tests to
look for the same attributes.
</P>
<P>
   Talk to tenured call center employees long enough and the
requisite personality is apparent. Ask how they manage to stay
upbeat and on the job, and you'll hear two things:
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't take it personally.''
</P>
<P>
   And, ``I just try to put myself in the customer's shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just try to relate and never try to prejudge,'' said call
center veteran Aleasha Harris. ``I like people. I like working with
people, and that makes a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Well-run call centers run contests, give out frequent awards and
have various bonus programs to keep enthusiasm up. And to cut the
stress, some make a point to program in fun.
</P>
<P>
   At a Sprint call center in Lenexa, it's time for a fun break
when the lights go off, the mirrored ball starts flashing from the
ceiling and the music cranks up. That's when people get up from
their desks and do a chicken dance in the aisles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
