<SLUG> BC-CHINA-ADOPT-KAN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY AREA COUPLES IN CHINA TO ADOPT BABIES AMID
INTERNATIONAL CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GRAHAM  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A joyous journey to China took an uncertain
turn for two Kansas City area couples after errant NATO bombs
struck the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Scott and Kim Tucker of Leawood made the trip to adopt a baby
and enjoy some vacation time. So did Damon and Joyce Sickel of
Kearney, along with 12 other families adopting through Children's
Hope International, based in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   One-year-old babies _ Jasmine for the Sickels and Lili Gwynne
for the Tuckers _ are safely in their arms.
</P>
<P>
   But for three days, they have waited for the flight home while
confined to their hotel under police orders. Outside their windows,
protesters chant and burn American flags. The White Swan Hotel
adjoins the U.S. Embassy on a small island in the southern coastal
city of Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we heard about it (the bombing), we knew it would be a
problem,'' Joyce Sickel, 39, said in a telephone interview Monday.
``We were frightened because we didn't know what to expect.''
</P>
<P>
   The couples arrived in China on April 29, traveling together
like a tour group.
</P>
<P>
   Their day of joy was May 4, when babies from four orphanages
were presented to new parents in a town west of Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Late Friday night they arrived in Guangzhou to get visas for
their babies to enter the United States. Early Saturday, they just
had time to get medical checks and photos for visas at a building
near the hotel. Then busloads of protesters began arriving.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a little unsettling,'' Sickel said. ``I don't think
we're frightened or scared, because the hotel security and military
police are outside our doors. But it makes you feel uneasy, and you
just want to get home.''
</P>
<P>
   The White Swan is a luxury hotel with stores and restaurants.
Couples have been able to shop, dine and even swim at the pool.
</P>
<P>
   But some were looking forward to experiencing China outside the
hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the part of the trip where the vacation was supposed
to kick in,'' said Scott Tucker, 37.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he's been peeking out the window and videotaping the
protests. They appear to be well-orchestrated, he said, with neatly
dressed students carrying well-made signs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable that this happened to us,'' Tucker said.
``There's no way you could prepare for it. Of all the embassies to
be hit (by a bomb), it's very surprising.''
</P>
<P>
   Police in riot gear have kept the crowd under control without
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Embassy officials went to the hotel to finish the processing so
the couples could leave on schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The families plan to ride from the hotel to the airport today on
a tour bus, probably with the curtains drawn, Sickel said. They
expect to arrive in Kansas City late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker said they'll be happy to escape the protests.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little disturbing,'' he said. ``It's concerned us
greatly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
