<HEADER>
A2056 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCATTER-KAN-KAN &LR;      05-11 1352
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCATTER-KAN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY GIVING MIXED WELCOME TO SCATTERED-SITE PUBLIC HOUSING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RUTH E. IGOE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. - Donna Nagy knew it
was her dream home: bright gray paint, maroon shutters and a
spacious two-car garage. Not to mention the backyard deck.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Then there was the interior: three bedrooms, two bathrooms and
an airy living room.
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband now pay about one-fourth of their income for
rent. Their landlord is the Housing Authority of Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Their home is not the stereotypical picture of public housing.
Homes like Nagy's are dubbed scattered sites, in contrast to
old-style public housing projects.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Kansas City authority is in the midst of its biggest
expansion of scattered site housing.
</P>
<P>
   By 2001, the authority will use federal money to buy or build
nearly 300 homes. The $27-million effort will reshape Kansas City's
public housing landscape, placing duplexes, townhouses and homes in
many neighborhoods that have never seen public housing.
</P>
<P>
   That angers some current residents who think poor families could
ruin property values, increase crime and crowd school districts. On
Monday, one Northland neighborhood won a preliminary injunction
against a builder whom they have accused of erecting cheap
construction.
</P>
<P>
   Federal rules limit scattered sites' location. They can't go,
for example, in flood plains, noisy areas around airports or in
poor and minority neighborhoods. Those rules prevent clumping poor
people together in second-rate sites.
</P>
<P>
   National studies have shown that scattered site housing does not
harm neighborhoods, said Philip Olson, a sociologist who heads
University of Missouri-Kansas City's urban affairs program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It also helps those families moving from an assisted situation
toward independence.''
</P>
<P>
   Nagy is proud of her home.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it's provided a great deal of dignity,'' said Nagy.
``Most people in your neighborhood don't have a clue that you are
in a scattered site.''  &LR; brk:Magnet for trouble
</P>
<P>
   Like other cities, Kansas City had its troubled public housing
projects that became havens for crime and drugs. Today the city's
public housing stock is being whittled down, overhauled and
scattered.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, the authority toppled Wayne Miner's high-rise towers,
leaving low-rise townhouses. Where Pennway Plaza's walk-up
apartments once languished is Villa Del Sol, a mix of apartments
and townhouses catering to both public housing tenants and buyers.
Guinotte Manor is being redeveloped into brightly painted
townhouses and apartments.
</P>
<P>
   In each case, the authority pared down the number of dwellings
to create a more attractive environment and reduce the number of
residents. But that caused the authority's waiting list to
increase: 4,000 people are waiting for public housing and 9,000 are
in line for federal rent subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   As Kansas City replaced the projects, the federal government
provided the local agency with money for new scattered sites.
efforts misfired. ]
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, authority officials bought about 180 scattered
site homes. Many were dilapidated and located in poor central-city
areas. Some neighborhoods protested the authority's moves and, in
several cases, staved off similar purchases.
</P>
<P>
   The authority's new manager, TAG Associates Inc., razed 20 of
the worst properties. Renovations, including the removal of lead
paint and asbestos, continue on all others.
</P>
<P>
   TAG tapped a Chicago developer, The Habitat Co., to put the
languishing federal money to work.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Habitat has acquired 140 sites and has built 34 duplexes
in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; brk:Neighbors unhappy
</P>
<P>
   Some neighborhoods have concerns about public housing in their
communities.
</P>
<P>
   In the Northland's Maple Park, the authority is planning one of
its largest developments, a total of 30 single-family duplexes and
townhouses. The authority also is building two other duplexes in
the area.
</P>
<P>
   During Habitat's first community meeting with 50 residents, some
had harsh words. Others walked out.
</P>
<P>
   Maple Park President Pat Hosler wonders why her neighborhood
will include about 15 percent of the city's new scattered sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not fair,'' she said, noting that about 30 percent of
the 1,200 Maple Park homes are already rental. ``People are
generally concerned about crime going up with that many more
rentals in one area.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Northland neighborhood, Coves North, won a temporary
restraining order against a builder who is constructing six
prefabricated modular duplexes. In court Thursday, neighbors
protested the duplex construction plan in an area where home prices
start about $160,000. Neighborhood leaders said the builder had
misrepresented his plans.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, a Platte County Circuit Court judge issued a
preliminary injunction against the builder. That case will either
be settled or go to trial before the builder can continue.
</P>
<P>
   City Councilman Ed Ford, who heads the city planning committee,
shares some concerns. In cases like Maple Park and Coves North,
Ford thinks Habitat is locating too many low-income families
together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scattered site housing should be just that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He is helping neighborhoods like Maple Park work on compromises
such as reducing the number of public housing tenants and mixing
them with paying residents. Another of Ford's concerns is that
Habitat, in its search for quality, is limiting itself only to new
homes, which reduces areas for scattered site homes.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Lines, president of TAG Associates, Inc., said the
authority is working with neighborhoods by placing houses and
duplexes in areas already zoned for them, something the law does
not require it to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be a good neighbor,'' Lines said.
</P>
<P>
   The authority hired political consultant Jim Bergfalk to mediate
with concerned neighborhoods. Many fears are exaggerated, he said,
or spring from a NIMBY _ Not In My Back Yard _ attitude. He said
he's trying to ``take the fuel out of the fire.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, the housing authority is working with the midtown
Coleman Highlands neighborhood to build two houses on an empty
tract at 33rd Street and Southwest Trafficway. Local activists tout
their 95 percent owner-occupancy rates among the stone-accented
houses that make up their 16-block neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly embrace the concept of diversity _ socio-economic
diversity and racial diversity _ but there are concerns,'' said
Mimi Moffat, a resident attorney who represents the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people in the last 15 years have spent time and money
fixing their houses,'' Moffat said. That's an effort they are not
sure public housing tenants could match, she said.  &LR; brk:Question of
design
</P>
<P>
   Because Coleman Highlands is a historic area, the Landmarks
Commission has to approve Habitat's designs..MDNM/ During the past
year, Habitat officials, architects and neighborhood leaders have
worked together on home designs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've redrawn their plans several times,'' said neighborhood
president Joyce Williams. ``Everything they are coming up with is
drawn off another home.''
</P>
<P>
   Moffat said neighbors are warming to public housing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cooperating with a project would be good for what a lot of us
like to yak on about, that: `Westport is good for diversity,' ''
Moffat said. ``It would be hypocritical when it comes down to the
crunch to say: `NIMBY, NIMBY, NIMBY.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In the Northland, Nagy is planning a vegetable garden in her
back yard, a flower bed out front. She thinks complaints about
public housing tenants represent unfair stereotypes of the poor. To
qualify for her home, Nagy must pass annual reviews that show she
is an ambitious tenant who properly cares for her home.
</P>
<P>
   Someday soon, Nagy hopes she and her husband can pay their own
mortgage. For now, her children focus on getting good grades. Her
husband, Paul, continues to look for a permanent teaching job.
Nagy, who works at one of TWA's ticket counters, hopes for a
promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Said Nagy: ``I have my whole future ahead of me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
