<HEADER>
A2057 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FACE-KAN-KAN &LR;      05-11 0287
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FACE-KAN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY AWARDS $9 MILLION TO MAN; FACE DESTROYED BY DUMBWAITER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE LAMBE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo _ A Jackson County jury on Monday awarded more
than $9 million to a former Kansas City man whose face and one eye
wre torn off by a falling dumbwaiter.
</P>
<P>
   The dumbwaiter fell on Johnnie Lay, 50, as the elevator
repairman worked on it Sept. 30, 1992. Jurors on Monday found
Schindler Elevator Corp. of St. Louis liable for not installing a
safety device with the dumbwaiter at the Hyde Park Nursing Home,
401 E. 36th St.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors awarded $15 million in damages but found Lay one-third at
fault. That third and settlements from two other companies were
subtracted, leaving a verdict of about $9.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Helling, a doctor at St. Luke's Hospital, testified that Lay
did not bleed to death because he stayed conscious, sat upright and
held his face on. Helling said it was among the greatest acts of
courage he had ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   Lay's attorney, James D. Walker Jr., reminded jurors in closing
arguments Monday of that testimony. He also told them to remember a
plastic surgeon who said Lay's facial injuries were the worst he'd
seen on a living human being.
</P>
<P>
   Lay's rebuilt face now includes about 30 titanium plates and
more than 100 screws, Walker said, and he suffers frequent
infections. The disabled man lost one eye and has equilibrium
problems but not brain damage, his lawyer said. Lay now lives in
Queen City, near Kirksville, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas L. Caradonna, lawyer for the elevator company, told
jurors that the accident was Lay's fault because he did not block
the dumbwaiter before beginning to work on it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-99 0121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
