<SLUG> BC-SAVINGS-KAN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW MISSOURI PROGRAM ALLOWS FAMILIES TAX BREAKS FOR COLLEGE
SAVINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNN FRANEY  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Starting in August, a Missouri program will
allow residents of any state to set aside up to $8,000 a year for
college expenses, with state and federal tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Money invested in the Missouri Higher Education Savings Program
would be exempt from state taxes. Federal taxes would be deferred
until it was time to pay college bills _ and even then, the money
would be taxed at a lower student rate, said Missouri Treasurer Bob
Holden, speaking at Penn Valley Community College on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Advanced education beyond high school is a resource we should
want to make more available to our young people,'' said Holden.
``Missouri must make the 13th and 14th years of education
commonplace for young Missourians to build the skills they need to
compete in the next century.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the program will be based in Missouri, residents of any
state can participate. They just need $25 to open an account.
</P>
<P>
   Holden announced Monday that a nationally known
financial-services company would manage the fund _ the Teachers
Insurance and Annuity Association College Retirement Equities Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri's fund, which legislators approved last year, follows
the lead of other states that wanted to encourage families to begin
saving for college when their children are young.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri's Higher Education Savings Program allows the money to
be used for tuition, room and board, books, and other educational
costs at any college or university in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The money can be spent on a different student than the one for
whom it initially was intended. It also can be refunded without
penalty if a child receives a scholarship, dies or becomes
disabled. Spending the money on anything other than educational
expenses would result in a tax bill and a 10 percent IRS penalty.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on the savings program, see the state
treasurer's Web site at www.sto.state.mo.us. A toll-free telephone
number for the program will be set up in the next few days, Holden
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
