<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 01:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2062 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-PIRATES-ASTROS-HN     05-11 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PIRATES-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
No lefthanded starting pitcher has shut down the Astros all season,
but manager Larry Dierker concedes his club would have trouble if
forced to face Mike Hampton.
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Monday night, it paid to have the crafty lefthander on the
Astros' side.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton pitched a five-hit shutout, helping the Astros snap a
two-game losing streak with a 6-0 victory over the Pittsburgh
Pirates at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton (4-1) struck out seven and walked none to win his fourth
consecutive decision. The Astros provided plenty of offense,
breaking open a one-run game with five runs off former Astro Pete
Schourek in the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Hampton would have been pitching against us, we would have
had trouble scoring the way he was pitching,'' Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates surely agree. All five of Pittsburgh's hits were
singles, and they had two in the same inning just once.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until the fifth that the Pirates hit a ball in the air
out of the infield. Hampton retired 19 of the final 23 batters he
faced and seemed to get stronger as the game went on, striking out
four of the last six batters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt pretty comfortable out there, and the team was scoring
some runs behind me, which is always a key,'' said Hampton, whose
last shutout was in April 1998 against the New York Mets. ``I'm in
a groove. The good thing is getting ahead in the count and getting
them to hit my pitch. I didn't make too many mistakes over the
middle of the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton, who notched his fifth career shutout, has allowed just
three earned runs in his last 24 innings (1.13 ERA).
</P>
<P>
   And what better timing than with the Astros having just lost two
in a row to the Montreal Expos? Hampton has been the Astros'
streak-buster this season, with the club winning six of his seven
starts _ all in games following a loss.
</P>
<P>
   The complete game was the Astros' third this season. Hampton
also went 1-for-3 with a double to raise his average to .286.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always good,'' Pirates manager Gene Lamont said. ``He had
a real good cutter. He knows what he's doing and changed speeds
real well. He does everything _ an overpowering pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   Hampton benefited from three double plays and forced the Pirates
into 14 groundouts.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to Monday, Pittsburgh had won seven of its last nine
games, including three of four over the weekend in St. Louis. In
those nine games, the Pirates hit .320 with 21 doubles and 12 home
runs while averaging 7.5 runs.
</P>
<P>
   Schourek, who pitched for the Astros last season before being
traded to Boston, became the latest lefthander to have trouble
against the Astros, who are a National League-best 8-2 against
lefthanded starters.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no explanation,'' Dierker said. ``I remember two years
ago, everybody was wondering what was wrong with us that we
couldn't hit lefthanders. We had a lot of good righthanded hitters
(then) and weren't hitting them very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Schourek (1-3), celebrating his 30th birthday, held the Astros
to one run in the first four innings before unraveling in the
fifth, when the Astros sent 10 batters to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Schourek allowed six runs, nine hits and five walks in four
innings, tying his shortest outing of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Ahead 1-0, the Astros got five hits, five runs and three walks
in the fifth inning off Schourek and reliever Brad Clontz.
</P>
<P>
   After a leadoff walk to Jeff Bagwell, the Astros reeled off five
consecutive hits to chase Schourek. Ken Caminiti, who went 3-for-5,
doubled, and Richard Hidalgo, Tony Eusebio and Tim Bogar followed
with RBI singles.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Barker, who celebrated his 28th birthday Monday with two
hits and his first start in center field, singled off Clontz to
load the bases. Craig Biggio and Derek Bll drew consecutive walks
to force in two more runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game can be very humbling, so I'll take what I can get,''
said Caminiti. ``I'll take my hits, and hopefully I'll get some
power numbers pretty quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell's sixth homer of the year put the Astros ahead 1-0 in the
third. He is a lifetime .464 hitter (11-for-24) against Schourek.
</P>
<P>
   While the Astros were providing Hampton with plenty of offense,
Schourek continued to starve.
</P>
<P>
   For the seventh time this season, the Pirates failed to score
more than four runs for him. Pittsburgh has scored 19 runs total in
Schourek's seven starts and just seven runs with him in the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
