<SLUG> BC-CAR-TRACKS-PIR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISC, PENSKE MOTORSPORTS MERGE HOLDINGS  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - International Speedway Corporation, which purchased
Phoenix International Raceway nearly two years ago, added to its
growing empire on Monday by reaching a merger agreement with Penske
Motorsports Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Penske holdings include Michigan Speedway, California Speedway,
Nazareth (Pa.) Speedway, North Carolina Motor Speedway and a 45
percent interest in Miami-Homestead Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Upon completion of the transaction, ISC, which already owns 12
percent of Penske Motorsports, will acquire the remaining 88
percent, giving it 14 of 34 races on the NASCAR Winston Cup
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ISC also owns or operates Daytona (Fla.) International Speedway,
Talladega (Ala.) Superspeedway, Darlington (S.C.) Raceway, Watkins
Glen (N.Y.) International and Tucson Raceway Park.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, ISC is building racetracks in Kansas City and near
Chicago and is looking at the New York and Denver markets as
potential sites for construction of ovals.
</P>
<P>
   No Winston Cup races are held at Tucson or Nazareth. Nazareth,
however, does have a Championship Auto Racing Teams event on its
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``This merger will create the premier company in the country's
fastest-growing spectator sport and will provide benefits to
America's racing fans, and ISC and Penske Motorsports
shareholders,'' ISC Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Bill
France said. France also is president of NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   The projected merger also will move ISC ahead of Speedway
Motorsports Inc. in the number of races on the NASCAR Winston Cup
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   SMI, whose chairman is Bruton Smith, owns six racetracks hosting
nine Cup races.
</P>
<P>
   Only racetracks located in Martinsville, Va., Richmond, Va.,
Dover, Del., Pocono, Pa., Loudon, N.H., and Indianapolis are not
owned by ISC or SMI.
</P>
<P>
   The merger's total transaction value is believed to be worth
about $705 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are ecstatic about the merger,'' PIR General Manager and
Executive Vice President Robin Braig. ``(Penske Motorsports) is a
first-class organization, and we feel with the addition of their
knowledge and expertise of the racing entertainment business
combined with that of ISC, it benefits (everyone).'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-99 0137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
