<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 01:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2068 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      05-11 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARCIAPARRA BURIES M'S WITH THREE HOMERS, 10 RBI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ As Nomar Garciaparra's second grand slam and third home
run sailed into the Boston sky Monday night, Mariners left fielder
Brian Hunter motioned with his arm to the foul line.
</P>
<P>
   He was trying to convince umpires the drive was foul, just as
Carlton Fisk tried to will his ball fair in the 12th inning of the
sixth game of the 1975 World Series. Fisk's effort succeeded.
Hunter's did not. He knew better, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was flipping through the channels (Sunday) night, and one of
the reporters said he was getting hot,'' Hunter said of
Garciaparra. ``I thought, he's not the guy you want to be getting
hot, because he can do that at any time.''
</P>
<P>
   But what Garciaparra did at Fenway Park in the Mariners' 12-4
loss to the Boston Red Sox has few historical precedents. The
shortstop became only the 11th player in baseball history to hit
two grand slams in the same game. His 10 runs batted in were one
shy of the American League record, and the most in any game since
Mark Whiten's record-tying 12 RBI on Sept. 7, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   And it was the first three-homer game in Garciaparra's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad I waited to the big leagues to do it,'' he said. ``I
never did it, not even in Little League.''
</P>
<P>
   As extraordinary as the performance was, the Mariners have seen
another like it. Last month, they allowed nine RBIs to Ivan
Rodriguez of the Texas Rangers in a 15-6 loss.
</P>
<P>
   This loss was Seattle's fourth in six games on an eight-game
road trip against three of the AL's playoff teams from last year.
It prompted manager Lou Piniella to refuse post-game interview
requests for the first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Ken Griffey Jr., however, said something Piniella
likely was thinking.
</P>
<P>
   What was most amazing to him about Garciaparra's night?
</P>
<P>
   ``All the people that were on for him,'' Griffey said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners walked eight Red Sox last night. In their past five
games they have walked 38, and never less than seven. Over that
span, 15 walks _ an average of three a game _ have turned into
runs.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra victimized two of the five rookies on Seattle's
staff. Brett Hinchliffe (0-2) allowed the first two homers, Eric
Weaver the third. Hinchliffe, recalled from Class AAA Tacoma to
make his third big league start, allowed singles to the first two
batters of the game. He got ahead of designated hitter Brian
Daubach, 1-and-2, then hit him with a pitch.
</P>
<P>
   That brought up Garciaparra, who drilled a high fastball into
the right-field bullpen for his first grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   In the third, Daubach hit a leadoff double and Garciaparra lined
a hanging slider down the right-field line. Fenway's 302-foot right
field is the shortest distance in baseball, but Garciaparra had it
by 8 feet for his second blast. Troy O'Leary followed with a homer,
and Hinchliffe allowed two walks and a single before departing.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this league or any league, you can't make bad pitches, and
they hit them hard,'' said Hinchliffe. ``We scored in the first,
and I need to go out there and throw a shutout inning. The way I'm
throwing, I don't deserve to pitch in this or any league.
</P>
<P>
   `` ... You say it can only get better, but it keeps getting
worse. I have too good stuff to give up runs like that. I believe
in my ability, but I've got to make pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Hinchliffe and Freddy Garcia were the most impressive Mariner
pitchers in spring training, lending hope that the Mariners'
pitching staff, while young, might turn out all right. Seattle now
has a 6.54 ERA, the highest in baseball, and Hinchliffe has
surrendered eight home runs in 152/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spring training's a different story _ players aren't in shape
yet, and you can't let spring training (performance) fool you,''
said pitching coach Stan Williams. ``He got the ball up, and if you
pitch that way, you're going to get hit. I thought he had a good
warm-up, his attitude was real good, all-business. But he got the
ball up; these are professional hitters, and they hurt him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox couldn't do much with Ken Cloude _ 42/3 innings, one
hit _ but they hurt Weaver, too. With one on and one out, he walked
Valentin and Daubach to get to Garciaparra. Williams came to the
mound for a conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked on the mound, and he said, `Listen, start him with a
slider and then bust him in,''' Weaver said. ``Then I threw him a
spinner right there. I'm sure the guy's swinging great right now,
and if you give him a gift like that, I'm sure he's not going to
miss it. It doesn't matter if he already had two home runs or not _
he's not going to miss a pitch like that.''
</P>
<P>
   If only Weaver had known Garciaparra's game plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably would have swung at anything, if it was 10 feet
over my head or in the dirt,'' said Garciaparra, who has five
homers in his past 22 at-bats after starting the season homerless.
``There was a lot of energy going on. It was kind of neat. I just
wanted something good to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Very little good was happening for the M's, who now have lost
consecutive games started by a reliever, the Yankees' Mike Stanton,
and a pitcher with an 8.06 ERA, Boston's Pat Rapp. Rapp was lifted
with the bases loaded and nobody out in the third, and John Mabry
cut Boston's lead to 4-2 with an RBI force out. But Russ Davis
struck out and Mabry was caught stealing in a rundown, ending the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Three innings later, off winner John Wasdin, Dan Wilson flied to
shallow right with Davis on first. Darren Lewis caught it, then
looked shocked to see Davis well off the bag. He threw to first for
the double play as Davis scrambled back, too late.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
