<HEADLINE>
CZECH JOB AWAITING REICHEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX -  &UR; Robert Reichel apparently has a standing offer to
join the Czech Republic national team as a player/coach, with a
chance eventually to run the elite program in his native country.
</P>
<P>
   According to his agent, it's a position the upcoming free-agent
center might decide to accept regardless of how much money the
Coyotes offer him.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Coyotes announced that right wing  &UR; Shane Doan
will play for Team Canada in the World Championships in Norway.
Doan, 22, who scored two game-winning goals for Phoenix during its
first-round playoff loss to St. Louis, will be available for
semifinal games Wednesday and Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   As for Reichel, Coyotes General Manager  &UR; Bobby Smith said Monday
he was willing to send a lucrative, multiyear contract offer to the
27-year-old Reichel, whose 69 points were second-most on the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Robert makes up his mind he's going to play in the Czech
Republic next year, well, he's playing in the Czech Republic next
year,'' Smith said. ``If he wants to play in the NHL, we will make
him an offer and see if we can get a deal done. If he says to me,
`Look, Bob, this isn't about money, it's about family and I'm going
back home,' then that's the risk we took when we acquired him, and
we'll go on from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Reichel, obtained from the New York Islanders prior to the NHL
trading deadline, is vacationing in Mexico and could not be reached
for comment. If he listens to Smith's offer, though, he probably
can expect an offer worth $2.5 million to $3 million annually after
earning $1.7 million in base pay this past season.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it necessarily matters, according to his Edmonton-based
agent,  &UR; Paul Kraus.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people (chose not to report) as a threat, but in this
case, it isn't a threat, it's a fact,'' Kraus said. ``Look, I'm
sure (Reichel's) mind could be swayed. Everybody has a price. . . .
But he's a frugal guy, a sensible guy, and he's provided well for
his family. If he stopped playing in the NHL right now, he and his
family wouldn't be hurting at all.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Kraus, Reichel has been approached several times in
the past few years by Czech national team leader  &UR; Ivan Hlinka about
someday replacing him in Reichel's native Litvinov, the city where
the national team is based.
</P>
<P>
   Reichel has played for Hlinka on numerous occasions and was a
member of the Czech gold-medal-winning team in the 1998 Winter
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ivan wants to move on,'' Kraus said, ``and he wants Robert to
step into his shoes as the future. He's been tagged. Obviously,
(Hlinka) would want him to play for a few years before he goes off
into management and coaching, but the opportunity is there for him.
It's been there for a couple years already.'' &QL; 
Briefly &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian national team also extended an invitation to
Coyotes forward  &UR; Dallas Drake, but the veteran wing had to decline
after having a broken nose suffered in Game 7 against the St. Louis
Blues repaired last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bit of a tough decision for Dallas, but it's nice
that Shane is there,'' Smith said. ``He lost an opportunity to play
in the World Junior Championships when the Winnipeg Jets did not
let him go.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman  &UR; Jyrki Lumme is scheduled to undergo surgery to
repair his injured left shoulder either today or Friday in
Vancouver, Smith said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
