<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MICH-AFFIRM (Ann Arbor, Mich.) _ The University of Michigan's
affirmative action program has produced the most racially eclectic
student body of any Midwestern university _ and lawsuits charging
it with reverse discrimination. University officials now hope the
very diversity spawned by the policy will be its best defense in
court. By Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-FINANCE (Seattle) _ In the fund-raising sweepstakes
that are, in effect, the first round of the presidential campaign,
nearly every candidate has made serious pitches to the technology
industry. It is all but certain that computer industry donations
will be a bigger factor in the 2000 elections than in any previous
campaign. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-RADAR (Undated) _ For two decades the Pentagon has tried
to monopolize a space radar that can expose submerged submarines.
When the radar made its debut in 1978, military officials blocked
public release of satellite photos that showed normally invisible
wakes of speeding craft. Last year, the military had the federal
government set strict limits on the visual powers of proposed
commercial radar satellites, and this year, the Pentagon is
fighting a Canadian plan to launch a radar satellite that would
break the new U.S. rules. By William J. Broad.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DIET-DRUG (Undated) _ Some promoters are already treating it as
the next magic potion for fighting obesity. And though orlistat, a
diet pill approved for sale in this country two weeks ago and
marketed under the brand name Xenical, is available only by
prescription, it is being made easily available. That worries many
health specialists, who say the drug might produce bad reactions or
other problems if misused. By Dana Canedy.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic has
been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
