   &UR; SCIENCE TIMES (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-TORNADOES (Undated) _ Most of the process leading up to the
critical moment of tornado genesis is well understood, but unless
and until meteorologists can solve the puzzle of the last crucial
step, they will be at a loss to predict whether a garden variety
tornado is on the way, or one so puny it will fall apart at the
first obstacle it hits _ or a monster like one that struck the
outskirts of Oklahoma City. By William K. Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DRUG-REVIEW (Washington) _ Criticized for having to pull
back medication it had allowed on the market, the Food and Drug
Administration issues a review of its drug-approval process and
finds it adequate. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SPY-SAFEHOUSE (Undated) _ New research suggests that among
the adobe walls and Indian curios of the Santa Fe plaza was a drug
store whose spare rooms served as a safe house some 50 years ago
when thousands of scientists were working on the bomb nearby. In
this refuge, Los Alamos experts are said to have given Moscow the
intellectual heart of the bomb. By William J. Broad.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LIE-DETECTION (Undated) _ Researchers have demonstrated that
most people perform miserably on a test to determine who on a
videotape is lying and who is telling the truth, scoring at chance
levels or only slightly higher, although for each liar on the tape
a variety of clues were present that might have revealed the lies.
By Erica Goode.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MATH-BRAIN (Undated) _ The ability to do mathematics _
everything from simple arithmetic to thinking up equations that
explain an expanding universe _ may stem from the interaction of
two brain circuits that handle numbers differently, two scientists
have found. During human evolution, the researchers suggest, these
two brain areas combined forces and gave rise to the remarkable
human capacity for manipulating numbers arithmetically. Their
interaction may also underlie many kinds of advanced mathematics.
By Sandra Blakeslee.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BEETLES-FIRE (Undated) _ Researchers are studying the
biology of the beetles that flock to smoke and fire and promptly
move to plant their eggs in the damaged terrain. One goal is to
understand the fire-detection function and replicate it in a new
generation of fire alarms. By Warren E. Leary.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GALAPAGOS-FINCHES (Undated) _ The finches of the Galapagos
Islands have become a foremost example of evolution at work. They
display what biologists call adaptive radiation, the evolution of a
founding population into an array of different species, each
adapted to its own ecological niche. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MUSIC-SCIENCE (Undated) _ The connections between music and
science are subtle and uncertain, and all too often we are asked to
accept on faith the supposed links between the concert hall and the
laboratory. A seemingly endless debate persists between those who
regard music as a branch of physics and those who see it as the
artistic product of inspired but inexplicable minds. The latest
attempt to bridge the chasm was offered last week at the Guggenheim
by the Emerson String Quartet and a Columbia University physics
professor, whose words-and-music performance was not exactly a
recital and not exactly a lecture; it was something like what
people in the 1960s called a ``happening.'' By Malcolm W. Browne.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SAUNDERS-HOSPICE (Undated) _ Conversation With Dame Cicely
Saunders, 80, whom some consider the world's foremost expert on the
care of the dying. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ The Personal Health column: Phase 3
in the battle against breast cancer involves a five-year regimen of
the drug tamoxifen, which helps prevent a recurrence. Now other
drugs are being tried that show beneficial effects as well. By Jane
E. Brody.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-REYES-SYNDROME (Undated) _ It took two decades for
researchers to link Reye's syndrome to children's use of aspirin
for illnesses like flu or chickenpox. But since that discovery, the
syndrome has been virtually eliminated in the United States. By
Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-INTERNET-MEDICINE (Undated) _ More and more hospitals and
medical establishments are making vast troves of medical
information available on the Internet, and some are even
maintaining large staffs to do it. By Lisa Napoli.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GROUP-MARATHON (Undated) _ Judging from the growing numbers
of people running in groups, it looks like the loneliness of the
long distance runner could be a thing of the past. Group marathon
training is expanding across the country and running groups, health
clubs, coaches and personal trainers are becoming instrumental in
providing safe and successful venues for long distance training. By
William K. Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-TUNA-RISK (Undated) _ Preschool children should eat no more
than one tunafish sandwich a week and pregnant women should avoid
it altogether to protect against dangerous levels of mercury, a
group of environmental and health groups have warned. By Nancy Beth
Jackson.
</P>
