<SLUG> BC-BBN-EXPOS-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALOU ADDS CLASS, CREDIBILITY TO MONEY-STARVED EXPOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Sad as it is to say, the Montreal Expos may be on the
shakiest ground of any of the 30 major-league clubs.
</P>
<P>
   One season after Major League Baseball enjoyed what can arguably
be called its greatest season ever, the game remains
disproportionately unfair to clubs like the Expos, who have the
smallest payroll in the game and are forced to use ingenuity in
trying to compete with the big-money boys.
</P>
<P>
   It should come as no surprise that the Expos have won just one
out of every three games they've played.
</P>
<P>
   But one area where the Expos are set beyond their means is with
Felipe Alou, who remains one of the most respected managers in the
game. Alou, who turns 64 Wednesday, is someone who has
traditionally squeezed the most out of his players.
</P>
<P>
   Simply speaking, Felipe Alou ``is'' the Montreal Expos. Within
this organization, from top to bottom, he is the one person that
gives this now 31-year-old ballclub credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Think not? Try and name three members of the Expos. It's not
easy, is it?
</P>
<P>
   Take Alou out of the Expos picture and it's a bleak-looking
portrait. But with Alou holding the reins, the Expos have a hope of
meriting their standing as a major league franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's someone I place on another pedestal,'' Diamondbacks
Manager Buck Showalter said before Monday night's game against
Montreal. ``He's on higher ground. I don't think I've ever heard
anything bad said about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is precisely the point when it comes to Alou. He's a man
who stands above most, even though he might be managing in the
worst situation in the game.
</P>
<P>
   It's hardly a secret that the Expos could very well be playing
their final season in Montreal, their home since their inception in
1969. A group of investors in the northern Virginia area are trying
to wedge themselves into position to buy and move the club to just
outside the Washington, D.C, area.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal's management was so worried last fall about losing
Alou, it tore up the final season of his contract (which would have
been this season) and the following year's personal services
contract and rewarded him with a three-year, $6 million deal, tying
him with Colorado's Jim Leyland as the highest-paid manager in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   The mere thought of what might arguably be the smallest of the
small-market franchises paying their manager $2 million per season
underscores his importance to the club.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Dominican native insists the almighty dollar was not the
reason he spurned Los Angeles and the opportunity to seriously
compete for a divisional title with the Dodgers, who offered Alou
their managerial post before settling on Davey Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money is not what makes me happy,'' Alou said. ``One has to
have principles in life. Loyalty is very important, and one must be
true to his own word. I don't think about happiness. I think I'm
happy because I've never thought about being happy. There is no
barometer in life that says if you make a certain amount of money
you will then be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Alou remembers being paid $22,000 a year to manage the Class A
West Palm Beach Expos for six straight years before the big-league
club called on him to take over early in the 1992 season.
</P>
<P>
   His top salary as a player was $58,000 when he was an outfielder
alongside Hank Aaron for the Atlanta Braves in the late 1960s. He
knows full well that there are more important aspects in life, like
lending himself to a greater cause.
</P>
<P>
   But Alou alone does not appear to have enough to salvage the SS
Expos from sinking in their Quebec Province.
</P>
<P>
   When it's all said and done, though, Alou will be able to look
himself in the mirror and believe he has made a difference. How
many major league managers can say the same? &QL; 
Pedro Gomez can be reached at (602) 444-2364 or at
pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
