<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS NEED GUTS TO A MAKE BOLD MOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It was a beautiful day here Monday. One of the first
sunny ones we've had in awhile. One of the last, too. So say the
meteorologists, who along with the weather must be predicting the
Mariners' forecast.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Boston, by the bottom of the first inning, Mariner
broadcaster Dave Niehaus was telling the increasingly restless
citizens of Marinerville everything we need to know about where the
1999 season was heading.
</P>
<P>
   Way back. To the wall. Over the Green Monster. Home run. For the
other guys.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours before Monday's loss to the Red Sox, the M's recalled
a rookie pitcher named Brett Hinchliffe from Tacoma. And just as
one could have predicted, the kid pitched like a Rainier, loading
the bases in the first inning and then topping it with a grand slam
pitch to Red Sox clean-up hitter Nomar Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might have one of those days,'' Niehaus bellowed into his
microphone.
</P>
<P>
   In Mariner-speak, ``one of those days'' means one of those days
when the Triple-A pitching staff parading as Seattle's major league
club might give up a slew of walks and longballs.
</P>
<P>
   How right was Niehaus' call. It was one of those days, all
right.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Lou Piniella mercifully lifted Hinchliffe in the
third, he had given up seven runs on three homers _ two to
Garciaparra _ and everyone back home was left to ponder the
never-ending, unanswered question:
</P>
<P>
   Where can the Mariners get some live arms to stop this exercise
in self-immolation?
</P>
<P>
   That was even before reliever Eric Weaver let Garciaparra belt
his second grand salami of the night to give the Sox a 12-4 win.
</P>
<P>
   Before we go any further, let's remember one thing: The Mariners
got rid of Randy Johnson because they could not afford to keep all
three of their marquee players in the new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   So Johnson was dangled for nine torturous months while the
Mariners staked out a position _ a people-pleasing public relations
stance _ that Ken Griffey Jr. and Alex Rodriguez were priorities to
re-sign to long-term contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, with more than a year and half left on the deals of
both Mariner superstars, it appears a foregone conclusion that the
Mariners can't keep both Rodriguez and Griffey anyway, so it is
time to shop their shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez's value holds the key to pitching health and
well-being.
</P>
<P>
   Only there is one problem. The Mariners already let go of one
ace, since Johnson's $13 million a year salary was to steep for the
red-ink engulfed Mariners. So who is a legitimate front-line
starter who is not going to present the M's with a similar
financial puzzle?
</P>
<P>
   A second problem. Jose Cruz Jr.'s trade value was the key to the
Mariners' bolstering their bullpen in 1997, and look what's left of
that deal now. Nothing, which calls into question the Mariners'
ability to trade for value.
</P>
<P>
   In dealing the beloved A-Rod, the kind of deal citizens of
Marinerville are expecting would be a blockbuster. What if the
Diamondbacks offered Johnson in a trade for Rodriguez? Isn't that
the same as hoping the Braves give up John Smoltz? Rodriguez is
still a major bargain this season.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, the ever-hopeful citizens of Marinerville refuse to
lose the notion that the M's are a top-tier team in baseball.
They're not.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners are scaling back, not bravely building. That is why
the out-for-the-season Mark Leiter and Butch Henry were two-fifths
of the Mariners starting rotation to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   Some of us are trying to learn to lower our expectations of the
Mariners brass. Why? Because since the second half of '95, when
what the M's did started to matter, the club has done nothing but
make stop-gap deals when the pressure is on or when the trading
deadline is staring Woody Woodward in the face.
</P>
<P>
   Trading Rodriguez right now is a different sort of animal than
anything attempted in Mariners history. Trading A-Rod is a
proposition of such proportion that it would require incredible
vision _ the kind the M's sorely lacked during the Johnson debacle.
</P>
<P>
   Trading Rodriguez would takes guts. It would take leadership and
determination. It would take tough-minded, poker-faced negotiating
skill.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, it would take just about everything the Mariners
have failed to demonstrate in four years of spiraling out of
control, out of contention.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the fiscal horizon of baseball in general is a
disaster. The Mariners have psychically handcuffed themselves
because of their tremendous debt and fear of the future, both
locally and industry-wide.
</P>
<P>
   But if Safeco Field is a new beginning for the franchise, the
M's certainly seem satisfied to move to that field of dying dreams
in neutral. They are deer frozen in the headlights because of so
many unknown costs and unsure revenues _ even as minor-leaguers
like Hinchliffe and Weaver are asked to do what clearly they're
incapable of doing at this point in time.
</P>
<P>
   These are not the conditions for this tentative franchise to
make bold, sweeping deals such as trading a Hall of Fame candidate
like Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Unless, of course, the Mariners are finally ready to do
something drastic, which they should. It is time to stem the swift,
rising tide of disillusionment that is eating away at the
benevolent feelings Seattle baseball fans still have for their
not-so-mightyM's, but may not have long.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
