<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-SANDERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGENT: COWBOYS ASK ABOUT CORNER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Could the Cowboys be contemplating life without
cornerback Deion Sanders?
</P>
<P>
   With Sanders' status for 1999 in limbo following toe surgery
last month, it seems that the Cowboys are thinking about such a
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   So much so that they contacted the agent for Bengals free-agent
cornerback Ashley Ambrose last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to see where Ashley was as far as signing with
other teams,'' Kenard McGuire said.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys owner Jerry Jones was unavailable to comment.
</P>
<P>
   McGuire said Ambrose has received three offers, but has yet to
sign. He also said his client would be very interested in the
Cowboys because he wants to be a part of a contending team.
</P>
<P>
   McGuire, however, said he didn't know how serious the Cowboys
are about his client and understands that the team has salary-cap
issues. He said the Cowboys also didn't mention whether they were
interested in his client replacing Sanders or playing alongside
him.
</P>
<P>
   What's certain is that the salary-cap-strapped Cowboys won't be
able to make any moves until after June 1, when they are expected
to release some players under contract. That money is expected to
give the Cowboys room to sign their rookies.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys would likely need more room to sign a premier
cornerback such as Ambrose or unrestricted free-agent Ryan McNeil,
who played last season for St. Louis. Cutting Sanders, who is not
guaranteed to return this season and could be out four to six
months, might be the Cowboys' only option.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who has said there is a chance Sanders might not miss any
games, has said that they would wait to see how Sanders'
rehabilitation progresses before making a decision on bringing in
another cornerback. Sanders counts $8.2 million against the salary
cap next season. If Sanders were to be released, the Cowboys would
save $6.5 million in base salary for next season and be charged
$3.4 million against the cap in 2000 for remaining two years of
bonus charges.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Cowboys could opt for their original plan and
give Sanders a contract extension to create room. However, it's
unlikely they would do that until Sanders' injury status for next
season and beyond is cleared up.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
