<DOCNO> NYT19990511.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2077 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BBA-WHITESIDECOLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-11 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
SOMEWHAT OF A '75 THREE-PEAT 
</HEADLINE>
 BBA-WHITESIDE COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By Larry Whiteside  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   From time to time, people will tell you they get tired of the
hype surrounding Red Sox shortstop Nomar Garciaparra. Nobody can be
that good, they say. Sooner or later he'll become just another
ballplayer.
</P>
<P>
   Well, if you still feel that way after Monday night's historic
performance at Fenway Park, then perhaps it is you who needs a
reality check. Garciaparra hit three home runs _ two of them grand
slams _ and drove in 10 runs. The last time a Boston player had a
similar night was Fred Lynn on June 18, 1975.
</P>
<P>
   ``Days like this are for you to enjoy,'' he was saying in the
postgame press conference, which included only a few Boston media
members who were also on hand for Lynn's Night Out in Tiger
Stadium. ``I don't take them for granted. They're nice. The way
this game is, anything can happen tomorrow. So you have to enjoy
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Garciaparra's explosion, which fueled a 12-4 rout of the
Seattle Mariners, he will insist that he is not a home run hitter.
His first blast, a grand slam in the first inning, was a line drive
into the visitors' bullpen off Brett Hinchliffe. The second went to
right also, but this one, with Brian Daubach on base in the third
inning, snaked around the Pesky Pole. All Garciaparra was trying to
do was advance the runner.
</P>
<P>
   The last one was the stuff of legends. Few of the 21,660 people
who were in Fenway Park will recall the name of Eric Weaver, the
Seattle reliever who gave up the second grand slam, in the eighth
inning. But it is worth noting that the homer came on the first
pitch to Garciaparra after a long chat by Seattle pitching coach
Stan Williams with his young pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't like it,'' said Williams, who just happened to be the
Red Sox pitching coach in 1975 and thus an eyewitness to Lynn's
heroics. ``It's the second time in my career that I saw 10 RBIs in
a game, in 46 years. This year, I've already seen a guy (Pudge
Rodriguez of Texas) get nine against us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't forgotten the Lynn night. He hit three home runs to
right and then he drove one to left that could have been a fourth
home run. The last time at bat he had an infield single. It was
quite a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra sent people scurrying to the record books. He is the
second player this season to hit two grand slams in a game _
Fernando Tatis of St. Louis hit them in the same inning April 23 _
and the first Red Sox player to do it since Rudy York on July 27,
1946. He is the fourth Red Sox player to drive in 10 runs in a
game, joining York, Lynn, and Norm Zauchin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was amazing,'' said Garciaparra. ``I never in my life had
hit three home runs in a game, let alone two grand slams. As I
crossed home plate, I looked at all the guys and I was speechless.
I didn't know what to say. All I could do was put a little smile on
my face. The crowd, the curtain call, all the emotion, all the
adrenaline flowing . . . it was really nice. The fans were great. I
love playing here.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Rice, Boston's hitting coach, was another who was there in
1975, as a teammate of Lynn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't try to explain the differences between Freddie and
Nomar,'' said Rice. ``Ten RBIs are 10 RBIs. As long as you win,
that's a good day. In fact, for some people it's a good week.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can also hit three home runs for your team and lose a
game. I know a guy who did that. I hit three home runs against
Oakland once. Mitchell Page hit two home runs and we lost the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nomar earned his home runs. He hit the ball hard. If you do
that, you've got a chance. He didn't get cheated on any of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sox manager Jimy Williams was as impressed as anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen three home runs before but not 10 RBIs,'' said
Williams. ``How about the guys who got on before him? That's
special, too. It means a lot when other guys are on base.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a night Garciaparra will never forget.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day turned out to be pretty special,'' he said. ``I wasn't
looking for anything that last time. I just swung. Maybe it went
out just because of the adrenaline. Just try to make contact and
maybe some good thing will happen. This time, it did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
