<HEADER>
A2080 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-11 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ You think this Rockets team has problems?
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time, there were back-to-back storybook seasons in
Rocketland. You think they really were storybook?
</P>
<P>
   They were anything but. It only seems that way now because those
teams knew when it was time to play and when it was time to shut
up.
</P>
<P>
   As for this 1999 Rockets team, particularly in the case of the
guy who blew into town from Chicago and likes to blow off a little
steam when things don't go right, it can learn from those bygone
glory days.
</P>
<P>
   Today, it's easy to gleefully point to the Rockets' 1994 and
1995 NBA championships and remember only the fairy-tale endings.
It's easy to be blinded by the glitter of the title rings, to think
those teams bounced into the sunset hand-in-hand, humming
Zip-a-dee-doo-dah and skipping through a field of flowers in full
bloom.
</P>
<P>
   But memories can be tinted in sweet shades of color, like pages
out of a children's book, when everything works out and everyone
lives happily ever after.
</P>
<P>
   You think Scottie Pippen's very public and very ill-timed
finger-pointing escapade after Sunday's 101-100 Game 1 playoff loss
to the Lakers was the first time dissension sneaked into the
Rockets' locker room?
</P>
<P>
   Two words: Vernon Maxwell. Two more: Clyde Drexler. Two more:
Robert Horry.
</P>
<P>
   We can go on. But suffice it to say that once upon a time, there
were several occasions during the glory years when coach Rudy
Tomjanovich walked into the locker room only to find the fairy tale
unraveling before his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   There was Maxwell, griping about something or other or
challenging a teammate to a fight. There was Horry, being flaky.
There was Kenny Smith, telling people how his 1-for-13 night was
not as bad as it seemed.
</P>
<P>
   There was Otis Thorpe, questioning anything worth questioning.
There was Drexler, perusing a statistics sheet to check his minutes
and points.
</P>
<P>
   All those moments now seem inconsequential, because now they
are. Those teams won. They knew when, where and how to lodge
complaints, lobby for minutes, soothe bad feelings and find a way
to make it all better.
</P>
<P>
   This one needs to learn what those teams knew, as brittle as
they sometimes seemed: Shut up and play.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen indeed pointed fingers after Game 1, although he said
Monday, ``I wasn't pointing at one or two guys. I just didn't think
we were doing the smart thing at the end of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen indeed dropped the ball in more ways than one in the
critical moments of the loss. He indeed stuck a wedge further into
the fragile chemistry of a team that has had trouble finding its
way all year.
</P>
<P>
   Tomjanovich didn't want to talk about Pippen's finger-pointing
Monday, because Rudy T knows it's not something you do publicly
when you're in the playoffs and two losses away from the season
evaporating.
</P>
<P>
   But clearly, Tomjanovich was miffed at Pippen for dumping the
blame on teammates when it was Pippen who committed the critical
late turnover. And it was Pippen who got smoked by the Lakers' Glen
Rice to the tune of 29 points on 12-of-17 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Said Hakeem Olajuwon of Pippen's outburst against his teammates:
``You don't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon knows how a championship team overcomes problems.
Tomjanovich knows. Pippen should have known.
</P>
<P>
   You deal with problems and rifts in team meetings, which the
Rockets had before Monday's practice, and within the walls of the
locker room. Then you just play.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Pippen again questioned the makeup of this Rockets team
Monday, saying, ``It's still a challenge for us right now. There
are a lot of things you can point your finger at. We're still not
there yet. We're still not jelling.''
</P>
<P>
   It was just one loss. There remain several opportunities and
several ways the Rockets can make it all better and still make a
run for the ring.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen can play better defense against Rice. The rookies,
Michael Dickerson and Cuttino Mobley, should find a way to stay out
of foul trouble and create more on the fast break. Silly turnovers
should be eliminated. The defense should find a way to correct its
season-long problem of not rotating to the open man on the
perimeter _ Sunday's 37-point second quarter by the Lakers was
inexcusable.
</P>
<P>
   You think the Rockets never have had to overcome so much in the
midst of the playoffs? Of course they have.
</P>
<P>
   But those were fairy-tale seasons. This one has been a nightmare
considering the great deeds it promised when Pippen arrived from
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   If ultimately it doesn't all work out and the season indeed
crumbles away, there will be no storybook tale this time. There
will be only more finger-pointing. And maybe the first person we
all should point at is Pippen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
