<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2090 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LA-VANGOGH-LADN     05-11 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-VANGOGH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAN GOGH TO DRAW MIDNIGHT CROWDS IN L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
 
  
BY DOUGLAS HABERMAN 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Vincent's paintings are Goghing, Goghing but not
gone until midnight Sunday, and people desperate to see the
exhibition at the Los Angeles County Museum of Art still can get
tickets _ in the wee small hours of the morning.
</P>
<P>
   With the museum staying open overnight during the weekend for
the climax of the Van Gogh exhibition, tickets remain available
Saturday between 3 a.m. and 6 a.m. and Sunday from 2 a.m. to 6 a.m.
and from 10 p.m. to 11 p.m. Tickets are available through
Ticketmaster and at the museum for $20 from 9 a.m. to midnight, $10
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Despite criticism of the crammed exhibit space at the former May
Co. store, the exhibition was LACMA's biggest hit since the
``Treasures of Tutankhamen'' exhibit in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just decided I really didn't want to miss it,'' said Amy
Howard of Woodland Hills, who viewed the French impressionist's
works Monday on her first visit to LACMA since Tutankhamen.
</P>
<P>
   With about 750,000 tickets sold and the show in its final week,
LACMA's ``Van Gogh's Van Goghs'' exhibition is among the most
heavily attended in the United States in the past 20 years, said
spokesman Adam Coyne.
</P>
<P>
   About 1.2million people thronged to ``Treasures of
Tutankhamen,'' LACMA's biggest show ever, but only 240,000 saw its
recent Picasso show.
</P>
<P>
   Since its Jan. 17 opening, the exhibition has been drawing
crowds to LACMA West on Wilshire Boulevard and Fairfax Avenue.
Also, the closing was extended, from the original date of April 4
to Sunday and will be open 9 a.m. Friday to midnight Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The final weekend's around-the-clock schedule is a first for an
American museum, although London's Royal Academy did it recently
for a Claude Monet exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   ``There really was just a lot of demand for this show,'' Coyne
said.
</P>
<P>
   Since last July, membership has more than doubled from 64,000 to
more than 130,000, Coyne said. Membership begins at $65 a year for
two adults and their children under 18.
</P>
<P>
   Enjoying ``A Pair of Shoes'' and other works Monday was Gunnar
Anderson of Santa Ana who had seen the paintings once before in
Amsterdam. A Southern California resident for three years, he was
making his first visit to LACMA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came because this stuff is never going to leave Holland
again,'' he said, citing what he understood to be the high cost of
insuring the works.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, said Coyne, the Van Gogh Museum in Amsterdam _ which
during renovations sent the paintings to the National Gallery in
Washington, D.C., and to LACMA _ is unlikely to release them again
as a group for many, many years to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is truly a once-in-a-lifetime exhibition,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Coyne said there were few scalping problems.
</P>
<P>
   He also said the main lesson learned from the large response was
to ``overprepare,'' which he said they did. The museum opened LACMA
West in October to make sure the building was ready for the
exhibit, conducted staff rehearsals and installed a special queuing
tent and a food tent just for the Van Gogh crowd.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
