<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 02:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2111 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-NUDODGER-LADN-(SL     05-11 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NUDODGER-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONDESI LIFTS DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 WRITETHROUGH (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Raul Mondesi has heard it time and again. From his
teammates, others in baseball and just about anyone who knows he
and Chicago Cubs slugger Sammy Sosa are both from the Dominican
Republic.
</P>
<P>
   However, after Mondesi hit a pair of two-run homers to lift the
Los Angeles Dodgers to a 4-3 win against the Cubs at Dodger Stadium
on Monday, he did all he could to squash the nonsensical Sosa
comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   For clarification, Mondesi wasn't inspired that Sosa was in the
building.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't show up opening day and I hit two,'' Mondesi said.
``If he was here, it doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Also unimportant to Mondesi was the fact that Steve Trachsel
(1-4) was the Cubs pitcher, despite the fact that Mondesi has owned
the right-hander.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi had no idea he's 12 of 34 (.353) against Trachsel. Nor
did he know he has seven homers and 13 RBI against Trachsel.
</P>
<P>
   What was paramount was Mondesi's ability to deliver in the
clutch again. Eight of his 11 homers have either tied games or put
the Dodgers ahead. The latest two home runs also came after the
Dodgers held a players-only meeting to discuss the direction of the
team _ suddenly a big concern after losing two of three games to
the lowly Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Mondesi's) more patient at the plate this year,'' said
Dodgers left fielder Gary Sheffield, pointing to Mondesi's
team-high 21 walks. ``That's all it takes . . . when you're as
deadly as he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi's first homer gave the Dodgers a 2-1 lead in the fourth
when he hit a fastball to right-center. Sosa barely moved when the
ball was hit.
</P>
<P>
   He put the Dodgers ahead 4-1 in the sixth when he smashed a
Trachsel fastball over the left-field fence. Ahead in the count
1-2, Trachsel tried to throw a fastball low and away. Instead, he
threw one belt-high and inside, and Mondesi hit his second homer,
the 10th time in his career and first time since opening day.
</P>
<P>
   ``That second one wasn't a strike, but he's got enough strength
to hit that kind of pitch out of the park,'' said Trachsel, who
allowed two homers in his previous 43 innings. ``You could throw
him a knee-high strike and split the plate and he'll miss it. Next
time you could throw a pitch over his head and he'll hit it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi's 10th and 11th homers of the season were enough to give
right-hander Ismael Valdes (4-1) the win. He labored through six
innings, throwing 121 pitches but allowing only one run. Valdes
allowed nine hits and walked three.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs had a pair of base runners in four of Valdes' six
innings and even had three hits in the fourth inning but could not
score. The only run the Cubs scored off Valdes came via Tyler
Houston's leadoff home run in the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a lot of batting, from the first pitch to the last
out,'' Valdes said. ``It's easy to pitch a ball game when you have
your best stuff. When you don't have your good stuff, you have to
figure out how to get batters out. You have to fight all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' ninth win in their last 13 games wasn't without
excitement, though.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs chipped away for a run in the seventh off reliever Alan
Mills and pulled within 4-3 when Henry Rodriguez's two-out single
off closer Jeff Shaw scored Mark Grace.
</P>
<P>
   But Shaw, in his first save opportunity since April 30, struck
out Benito Santiago for his eighth save. Shaw has converted 18
straight save opportunities dating back to last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like we're trying to build some momentum,'' Dodgers
manager Davey Johnson said, ``but we haven't been able to get over
the hump.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
