<SLUG> BC-PASS-THE-HAT-KOSOVO-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO'S REPAIR BILLS TO COST 3.5 BILLION  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This 325-word ``separate buy'' article is from The Independent
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By STEPHEN CASTLE  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS _ Europe has put a price of up to $3.5 billion on
rebuilding Kosovo, and highlighted the need for immediate
preparations so that reconstruction can start as soon as there is a
cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   The European Commission has also estimated that the cost of
catering for the 700,000 refugees in the region will range from
$340 million to $780 million, depending on the length of the
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said they expected Europe to provide 50-60 percent of
the funds, a figure in line with the aid given to Bosnia after the
1992-95 war.
</P>
<P>
   At Monday's meeting of finance ministers several governments,
including that of Holland, argued that the money should come from
within existing spending plans _ the first indications of the
political sensitivities surrounding the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The Commission's analysis points to one central difficulty in
channelling aid to Kosovo and to the republic of Montenegro, which
has taken in about 70,000 refugees from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since neither is a sovereign country, neither is eligible for
membership of the International Monetary Fund and hence not for
membership of the World Bank,'' the report says.
</P>
<P>
   The document puts the estimated costs of reconstruction in
Kosovo at ``$2-3.5 billion over perhaps three years.''
</P>
<P>
   It warns: ``Since Kosovo is likely to enjoy a significant degree
of political and administrative autonomy, significant resources
will have to be directed to rehabilitate or create from scratch the
necessary institutions within the territory.''
</P>
<P>
   The report says economic assistance may need to extend to
countries, such as Romania and Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
   It adds: ``Preparations should begin immediately so that, as
soon as there is cease-fire the EU and the rest of the
international community is able to put in place within a short
space of time a priority reconstruction programme with financing
assured for at least the first three months and committed for the
first year.''
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 325-word article, it must be purchased from the
New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
