<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBANIA-SEARCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN REFUGEE CAMPS, SLEUTHING LOST RELATIVES IS A MUST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ She was allowed one call, one minute, and she
knew by heart the number to dial. Deep in a line of refugees
grasping slips of paper and old address books, Xhemile Goqaj hoped
that her mother and father had the same number with them, too.
</P>
<P>
   But Goqaj found out she was the first, so far the only, one of
her family to telephone a brother who works in Switzerland. In
those precious 60 seconds, she learned that a cousin had been
killed in Kosovo, but not whether her parents and another brother
were alive. She hung up, not knowing when or how she might be able
to call again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called to say I am alive and I am here and I don't know
where anyone else is,'' said Goqaj, who, together with her husband
and mother-in-law, had fled their home on a moment's notice.
``Maybe they killed them. I don't know. Maybe they are looking for
me. I need to find them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sent running from their Kosovo villages in opposite directions,
separated at international borders, divided in Macedonian refugee
camps, tens of thousands of refugees are now searching for each
other as well as hoping to be found.
</P>
<P>
   Their tools can be as old-fashioned as word of mouth and as
sophisticated as the satellite phones provided by the International
Red Cross and a Washington-based company called Iridium. Some are
relying on luck, others on determination. But with more than
400,000 refugees in Albania alone, and who knows how many on the
move inside Kosovo, the tearful reunions tend to require a bit of
both. Relief workers also say the odds worsen each time a sibling
or uncle relocates by choice or by force.
</P>
<P>
   Forced overnight to become amateur sleuths, some have set out by
foot and by bus, going camp to camp, tent to tent, mattress to
mattress. Like Xhevdet Kajtazi, who had expected to spend the
spring preparing for his high school graduation, they ask the same
question again and again: Have you seen my family? Until the sixth
town he reached, no one could tell the 17-year-old what he wanted
to hear. Then an aquaintance from home pointed to a tent in Kukes,
just inside Albania near the Kosovo border.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could not believe they were there. I had hoped, but _'' said
Kajtazi, who only the other day got word in Tirana that one missing
brother had been killed, but that another was in hiding in Kosovo
safe and _ so far. ``In the beginning, I thought for sure they were
all dead from grenades. So I asked and asked for them everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Many more Kosovars, however, appear to be staying put. The ones
who know where to register have had their names and locations
broadcast on local and international radio programs and printed in
Albanian newspapers. With so many Albanians working in Switzerland
and Germany, most everyone also wants a chance to try one of the
fancy international phones.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Red Cross has helped place more than 6,500
one-minute calls. An Iridium executive temporarily staying in
Tirana said the company's 50 phones are being used day and night
for three-minute calls. Other ethnic Albanians are buying calling
cards and lining up at pay phones.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people have been stripped of their identity, but
everyone comes out with a little piece of paper with a phone number
on it,'' said Red Cross spokeswoman Daloni Carlisle. ``Or they've
written it on an arm or on their belly.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlisle sees the 65 parents who had registered with the Red
Cross as having lost their children, and the 51 children officially
looking for their parents, as ``the very small tip of a very large
iceberg.'' More than 3,500 have had their names broadcast on radio,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   But anecdotal happy endings aside, those are brief, one-shot
attempts. If no one picks up the phone on the other end, if no one
hears the broadcast, many refugees fear they will never find their
way back to each other, now that their homes have been destroyed.
Entire villages have vanished, making it all but impossible to
return quickly even if peace is achieved.
</P>
<P>
   Huddled in the bleachers of a Tirana sports arena, converted
into a human warehouse filled with wall-to-wall mattresses and the
odor of desperation, Bademe Thaqi kept close the young daughter she
still has. Her older daughter, 17 and seven months pregnant, is
somewhere else, and Thaqi has no idea where that might be. All she
can do, she said, is hope that her daughter thinks to call
Switzerland, where Thaqi's husband works and where she has already
checked in by pay phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope maybe she and her husband will find out to come to
Albania,'' said Thaqi, 36, who managed to stay together with her
parents, sister and 13-year-old son all the way from Postasel,
Kosovo, to Tirana. ``But there is no phone in the village, maybe no
village anymore, so how will she find out?''
</P>
<P>
   Rimi, a 16-year-old from the Kosovo capital of Pristina, has
given up on the idea of ever finding anyone related to him. The
sports arena has been home since April 1, and he has registered
everywhere he can. His name and location have been aired on radio.
He thinks they were in the newspaper. With the faraway look of the
lonely, he noted that some of the aid workers at the nearby Red
Cross office now know him by his first name.
</P>
<P>
   Rimi, who did not want his full name used, had expected to end
up with his parents. He was in one car in a 70-car convoy leaving
Pristina, they were in another. But Serbian soldiers in black masks
stopped the caravan and began issuing arbitrary commands: this car
to Macedonia, that to Montenegro, those to Albania. Rimi has not
seen his family since.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just started crying right there and one Serb police says to
me, `If you don't stop crying I will kill you,' '' Rimi said. ``I
am too scared of spending the rest of my life alone. Before this I
have great hopes, but now I am hopeless. I have tried everything
and it's still just me.''
</P>
<P>
   At Mullet, a tent city on the outskirts of Tirana with about
1,300 refugees, a line of people in tattered clothes snaked its way
around a Red Cross vehicle. On their faces they wore hope. The
relief agency had brought a satellite phone to the camp for the
first time _ the first time most of the ethnic Albanians had a
chance to call out, since the camp phone is for incoming calls
only.
</P>
<P>
   Within two hours, perhaps 10 refugees had connected with
relatives, said aid worker Ellen Verluyt. Many more got busy
signals, or no answers, or the wrong answers. The number to Germany
that one man had carried so many miles belonged to a woman who said
she did not know any Albanians of any kind. In the second it took
Verluyt to explain, the hope on his face vanished and was replaced
by panic. Later Carlisle said the Red Cross will try to track down
correct numbers on the spot if there is time and no crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it's not so easy,'' Verluyt said. ``But if you've
got family abroad, you've got at least a chance at your connection.
. . I don't think you can just go looking for someone, but I think
they're doing whatever they can.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
