<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 10:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2274 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-HISTORIC-PHOTOS &LR;      05-11 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-HISTORIC-PHOTOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOTO EXHIBIT CAPTURES AMERICA'S CENTURY, WITH A TWIST 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  _
 By DAVID BERNARD  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Monica didn't make the cut. Neither did the sailor
kissing the nurse in Times Square. Or the South Vietnamese general
executing a Viet Cong operative during Tet. Or the astronaut
standing on the moon.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, ``Picturing the Century: One Hundred Years of
Photography from the National Archives,'' which opened here in
March, includes surprisingly few of the pictures that a visitor
with a head full of best-of-the-century lists would expect to see.
</P>
<P>
   What it does include is 200 images of America during its first
fully angle than you're used to. Which is exactly what curator
Bruce Bustard had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certain images become icons beyond just capturing a moment,''
said Bustard, a federal archivist. ``They're part of our collective
memory.'' The problem with these greatest hits is, they're so
familiar that we no longer really see them.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Bustard avoided the century's most famous
fractions-of-seconds as he selected photos from the eight
million-plus in the National Archives and Records Administration's
collection.
</P>
<P>
   As he began preparing the exhibition in 1997, he had already
decided on many of the images that would represent events and
photographers. While he admitted his list was limited, he also said
it was the only option.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way you can go through eight million pictures,''
Bustard said. ``You wouldn't want to'' _ especially since many of
the archives' photos are purely informational, depicting machinery,
land surveys, agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing only from this federal library also afforded him
different perspectives. Unlike the news media's more publicized
images, the archives' photos were taken by government photographers
to document the work of agencies, social programs, the military,
and official ceremonies, depicting America in its everyday moments.
</P>
<P>
   Arranged chronologically along the archives' Circular Gallery _
which curves behind the hall where the Declaration of Independence,
Constitution and Bill of Rights are displayed _ the photographs are
mostly sharp black-and-white until the exhibition's last quarter,
when the standardization of color film processing in the mid-1960s
becomes apparent.
</P>
<P>
   The photos range from turn-of-the-century panoramas of bustling
street scenes and sprawling farm landscapes, to President George
Bush among American troops in Saudi Arabia during Thanksgiving
1990, to President Bill Clinton playing a saxophone, to a beaming
President Boris Yeltsin of Russia at a 1994 summit.
</P>
<P>
   Often the scene is familiar history from a unique angle, since
the government photographer was not among the rest of the press.
American soldiers wade into the surf and German gunfire at Normandy
beach, as seen from the Coast Guard landing boat they have just
left. President Richard Nixon bids the White House farewell, as
seen from inside the helicopter he is boarding.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it's an unfamiliar photo that connects the familiar
ones. A 1913 assembly line. A 1965 portrait of a young Marine
standing by during a troop arrival at Da Nang shows his uncertainty
weighing as heavily as the duffel he carries.
</P>
<P>
   Other times a renowned photographer puts a signature style to
work for Uncle Sam. Dorothea Lange's pictures of Depression
breadlines and children peeking out of shanties extend an influence
felt by anyone who's ever seen a ``Save the Children'' television
commercial, and Ansel Adams's landscapes of the American West are
echoed in the best nature and travel magazines.
</P>
<P>
   In photography, government work often means undistinguished
``grip-and-grin'' handshakes. ``For a government photographer, it's
harder to have a point of view,'' Bustard said. These photographs
contain a surprising range of emotion, though. There's fairy-tale
wonder in the shot of a mother and daughter in a sparkling white
1950s kitchen, an image that ran in a propaganda magazine sent to
the Soviet Union. There's the vaguely sinister inner-city teen-ager
leaning against an alley wall, from a study on urban renewal. Or
the sublime view of the Statue of Liberty's back, seen through a
clutch of telephone poles on the flats of Hoboken, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition does include, of course, some images you may have
seen before: Lyndon B. Johnson taking the presidential oath of
office next to a shock-scarred Jacqueline Kennedy, or President
Richard Nixon's 1970 meeting with Elvis Presley. ``I wanted some
markers, to remind people of the time period,'' Bustard said. In
this fresh context, however, they are hardly cliche.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure my collection could be absolutely
comprehensive,'' he said, ``but I hope this covers some of the
major events of the 20th century.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Picturing the Century'' is a small, simply presented
exhibition. It possesses the energy of an anthem or a march,
though, a tune that reminds a nation who it is, and what's defined
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Picturing the Century: One Hundred Years of Photography from
the National Archives'' continues to July 4, 2001 at the National
Archives Building, Constitution Avenue at 7th Street NW,
Washington, D.C. Open every day except December 25. Hours: April 1
to Labor Day, 10 a.m. to 9 p.m. Sept. to March 31, 10 a.m. to 5:30
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: David Bernard is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC; _
</P>
</TEXT>
