<HEADLINE>
THE QUEST FOR FAME: THE PATH FROM THE DOGHOUSE TO THE PENTHOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By ERIK LINDEN  
 c.1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was their first trip to Manhattan. Like so many
young and aspiring actors, Reba and Sondra King were innocent and
starry-eyed, filled with dreams of hitting the big time. Their
acting careers might start with a dog food commercial or two, then
maybe Broadway or a debut on the silver screen.
</P>
<P>
   Overwhelmed by the behemoth skyscrapers and the yellow cabs
crawling like ants down 34th Street, the suburban damsels wrestled
their leashes and panted anxiously.
</P>
<P>
   Two rotweillers from Staten Island can feel a bit out of place
in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe this wasn't the best idea,'' Heather King, 23, the proud
mother, said to her husband. ``This was your idea. They're not used
to this.''
</P>
<P>
   King and her husband, Kevin, and their two dogs ventured into
the city to attend a seminar called ``How to Make Your Pet a
Star.'' Taught by seasoned animal trainer Barbara Weir, the
one-time class shows people the tricks of the trade for launching
their pets into careers in advertisements, on stage and screen.
</P>
<P>
   While many pet owners think their animals are cut out for
stardom, getting a pet into the acting business is no walk through
the park. Becoming Eddie from the TV sitcom ``Frasier'' or Morris
from the Nine Lives cat-food commercials is a rare feat. More
often, pets from New York City land relatively anonymous jobs in
print advertisements, photographs on greeting cards, or in theater
and opera.
</P>
<P>
   In the tiny room on 34th Street where the $40 seminar was held,
Reba and Sondra were the first to arrive; eventually, 16 other
owners and their pets trickled in. Two Jack Russell terriers, a
handful of poodles and a Bichon Frise arrived. Then a woman from
Queens named Maureen Kelley came in and unzipped a black duffel bag
with breathing vents. Out crawled Piper _ a 13-pound Turkish Angora
cat with style.
</P>
<P>
   Named after the pricey Champagne, Piper Heidsieck, the lone
feline sat patiently on Kelley's lap, while the drooling dogs faced
her down.
</P>
<P>
   Class began with the bad news. Weir, a tall, thin 66-year-old
who lives in New Jersey on a horse farm, told participants: ``Your
pets will not make you famous, nor will they make you rich.'' She
went on to say that, first and foremost, when considering the
acting business what every pet should be able to do is, well,
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   If a pet can't sit or stay in one place for five minutes, Weir
says, forget about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Animals are basically props,'' said Weir, who has been in the
animal training and agent business for 10 years. ``That means no
sniffing or socializing, and complete calm.'' Directors of
commercials, theater and film look for placid animals who obey
orders, she said. ``One growl and a director will throw you out and
get another dog.''
</P>
<P>
   Weir's animals have impressive resumes. Her two greyhounds
performed in ``Don Giovanni'' at the Metropolitan Opera, and her
mutt named Fancy appeared regularly on ``The Cosby Show'' in the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Weir brought along a veteran performer and her master to the
seminar: Carolyn ``Cookie'' Baker and her Yorkshire terrier named
Tiger Lily. The miniature, sandy-colored terrier appeared recently
in the Lillian Vernon catalog, and on a Valentine's Day greeting
card in which she held a long-stemmed rose in her tiny jaws.
</P>
<P>
   Showing off her stuff, Tiger Lily rolled over on command, as
other participants looked with admiration. Baker then placed a pink
rubber bone in Tiger Lily's mouth and stepped back to the rear of
the room. The redheaded Baker then instructed the dog to ``drop
it,'' and obediently, she did.
</P>
<P>
   Baker says that she enjoys doing different acting jobs with
Tiger Lily, and more for the novelty than for the money. ``I've
been doing this for a while,'' Baker said. ``And I'm not rich
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Income from commercials or theater, Weir told her audience, is
usually around $150 per hour. But they can earn more if their
particular breed is in demand, or if a project lasts for several
days.
</P>
<P>
   Most pets that land parts in movies live in Hollywood. Their
owners usually have several dogs of the same breed who look
identical. ``Some of them have eight of the same dog,'' Weir said.
``It's their living, and it's their business.'' In the movie
``Beethoven,'' she said, directors used eight different Saint
Bernards on the set.
</P>
<P>
   The first step for getting into the business, Weir told
participants, is to have a pet obedience-trained. Then, shoot some
simple 5-x-7 photographs of the animal against a flat background.
And finally, send the photos to a talent agency such as All-Tame
Animals or Dawn Animal Agency, both based in New York.
</P>
<P>
   After Tiger Lily did her pink bone routine, Piper, the calm cat,
went to the head of the class and _ despite facing 16 dogs _
remained mellow. Piper sat on a tattered black chair and withstood
several growls and swipes from Reba and Sondra, the two
rotweillers.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Maureen Kelley said Piper has always been a looker. That's
why she brought him today. ``Everybody keeps telling me how cute he
is,'' Kelley said. ``I think he'll be happy if he can get some
work.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Reba and Sondra, the rotweillers won't be getting work
anytime soon. The two dogs left early with their owners after
Sondra lunged at Piper. ``I'm not sure it's for her,'' King said,
smiling. ``I don't think she really cares about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Piper, on the other hand, might have what it takes. Kelley said
she plans to shoot some glossy photos of Piper, send them to an
agency, and hope for the best. As Kelley zipped Piper back into the
breathable duffel, the two headed toward the Empire State Building
and into the New York night.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Erik Linden is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
