<HEADLINE>
CALL IT NETIQUETTE: E-MAIL INTRODUCES A NEW ERA OF ETIQUETTE 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  _
 By HANNAH MITCHELL  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was just another e-mail message. ``Hi, sweetie,
how are you?'' Audrey Le wrote the message to her kid sister and
sent it on its way. No problem.
</P>
<P>
   Except that she entered the wrong address. The e-mail went to
the male teacher's assistant in her economics class.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have the right address?'' he asked her gingerly the
next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said 'Oh, my God,' '' recalled the 20-year-old Columbia
University student, laughing and adding, ``It wasn't funny at the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Electronic messaging makes communication easier than ever
before, but with its speed, affordability and accessibility come
downsides, sometimes major ones. Send the wrong message and a
friend can be permanently deleted from your address book. Send to
the wrong mailbox, and you could lose your job.
</P>
<P>
   Given these new hazards, someone has to outline the dos and
don'ts.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the etiquette experts, who have recently turned their
discriminating eyes to e-mail. These arbiters of good taste and
manners are warning of the dangers of sending the wrong message.
Even the queen of etiquette herself, Emily Post, posthumously
includes an e-mail section in her latest edition, written by her
daughter, Peggy Post. And entire Web sites are devoted to what's
commonly known as ``netiquette.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, Barbara Pachter, president of a New Jersey-based
business etiquette and communications company, added e-mail
etiquette to her traditional staples such as business dining and
letter writing. Companies pay for most of the seminars, though
Pachter has also advised civic clubs and taught for Rutgers
University's M.B.A. program.
</P>
<P>
   Pachter says the biggest mistake most people make is to treat
electronic messages like casual phone calls between old friends.
E-mail should be used with care, she says. ``It's a word document
and it will come back to haunt you'' is the recurring theme of
Pachter's e-mail sessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, people laughed when I said that,'' she said. ``But
there are consequences to the quality of the writing. People print
them out and people circulate them. E-mail is not private. Your
company has access to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Two executives at Salomon Smith Barney lost their jobs in 1998
for transmitting pornography electronically. At Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter, two former employees who are black sued the company after
receiving racist jokes by e-mail. The case was dismissed in 1997.
The e-mail was sent from outside the office and circulated among a
few employees, who the employer disciplined.
</P>
<P>
   While e-mail is speedy, it can have long-term consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Sternberg has written her doctoral dissertation on
Internet misbehavior, from electronic crime like e-mail viruses, to
gaffes like Li's. People send electronic messages to the wrong
addresses all the time, said Sternberg, who recalled one example
that left someone in a shaky spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was trying to put together a panel and was inviting
participants,'' said Sternberg, a doctoral degree candidate in
media ecology at New York University. ``Someone on the list, who
was more famous, wanted money to be on the panel.'' The panel
organizer obliged, but did not compensate the other panelists. He
received a thank-you e-mail from the celebrity, who mistakenly sent
it to the unpaid participants.
</P>
<P>
   Pachter advises that when sending an e-mail message to a
prospective employer or client, you should make sure your spelling
and grammar are perfect. E-mail is technically in memorandum form,
but senders should still include a salutation and ``sign'' their
name. If you don't know whether to call or e-mail, follow the other
person's lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they call you, chances are you should call them,'' Pachter
said.
</P>
<P>
   Common sense may still be the best guide. ``E-mail erupted so
quickly that the guidelines and how to handle it are still
evolving,'' Pachter said.
</P>
<P>
   Sternberg agreed: ``We've only had e-mail for about 15 years,
for most people less than 10 years. It will take time, in the same
way it took us time to develop codes of conduct for the phone.''
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, the rules of the game are being disseminated through the
e-mail grapevine. Bruno Pelletier, a San Francisco jazz musician,
uses e-mail to send his clients invoices.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks better than a hand-written note,'' said Pelletier,
39. ``It means you're established.'' But he is careful with his
newfound business device. ``I had friends that kind of showed me.
Apparently, you're not supposed to use all caps, because it looks
like you're shouting.''
</P>
<P>
   The rule on capital letters happens to be one of Pachter's eight
``ways to mind your electronic manners.'' The others are: don't
contribute to e-mail overload; keep messages short, one screen or
25 lines maximum; use short paragraphs, they are easier to read;
fill in subject lines to help the reader focus; limit each message
to one subject; proofread messages, and remember e-mail isn't
always private.
</P>
<P>
   Pachter also advises e-mailers never to send a message when they
are angry. ``It's too quick, too easy to push the button and it's
gone,'' she said. ``If you're writing a letter, at least you've got
to print it out, address the envelope and send it. And usually by
then you've come to your senses.''
</P>
<P>
   Mindy Bennett, a 28-year-old computer graphics artist, likes
communicating with pen pals by e-mail, but acknowledges it has its
shortcomings. She recalls one regrettable message.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said something, not realizing this person doesn't know me,
and they took it the wrong way,'' said Bennett, smoking Marlboros
and sending e-mails at Internet Cafe in Greenwich Village. ``That's
kind of hard, too, going in and saying, 'I'm sorry.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Had she had the benefit of italicizing or underlining some of
her words, Bennett said, her dry humor might have been understood.
``It's hard to express actual emotion'' by e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   The Emily Post etiquette guidebook addresses that lesson. ``The
fact that the recipient cannot see you and you cannot see him or
her imposes certain limitations,'' it reads. ``The recipient can't
hear the tone of your voice, so it is especially important not to
offend people.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Riffe, 34, manager of the Internet Cafe, says he has
never knowingly committed an e-mail etiquette blunder, but he has a
friend who has done so. ``They thought he had an attitude,'' he
said. ``Somebody can read anything into anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem may be that people are out of practice. Back
in the 1800s, for instance, Riffe said, people wrote many letters.
But these days, virtually everyone has given up the pen.
</P>
<P>
   Sternberg said : ``There's probably a whole generation of people
who simply never did much letter writing. E-mail is bringing them
back to the written word. But I don't think people can assume that
e-mail is like written letters.''
</P>
<P>
   Pachter added, ``E-mail doesn't replace face-to-face
communication.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Hannah Mitchell is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC; _
</P>
</TEXT>
