<HEADER>
A2281 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-PARTY-PROMOTERS &LR;      05-11 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-PARTY-PROMOTERS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTIES DON'T JUST HAPPEN: PROMOTERS INFUSE THEM WITH LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By MONICA LEWIS   
 c.1999 Columbia News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's shortly after 10 p.m. on a clear April evening
as A.J. Calloway struts through Justin's, a popular lower Manhattan
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   His shoulder-length dreadlocks pulled back to show off his
chiseled features, Calloway stops to chat with a group of young
men, giving handshakes as he moves on to another group. With a
drink in hand, he looks as if he's unwinding from a long day's
work. Actually, his workday has just begun.
</P>
<P>
   His place of operation is in clubs such as this one, filled with
young, good-looking people, dancing and drinking the night away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody parties,'' said Calloway, a member of Black Diamonds
Entertainment, one of New York's most active event promotion teams.
``It's all about making sure everybody is having a great time. It's
not all fun and games, trying to throw parties in New York, but
somebody's got to do it, right?''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, more and more young entrepreneurs think so. Black
Diamonds Entertainment and other events groups, like ProLinks Inc.,
Net2 and Partners in Soul, hold parties several nights throughout
the week at New York clubs like NV, the Metronome, Vivid, Cream and
Nell's, to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   Calloway said he believed people spend a lot of energy figuring
out what to do after work or over the weekend. Wayne Shields,
one-fifth of ProLinks, agreed. Like Black Diamonds Entertainment,
ProLinks has been on the party scene since 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York is a large town, but there's not many places to party
and network for professionals,'' said Shields, a senior investment
specialist at T.I.A. Kraft by day. ``I wanted to set the type of
ambiance and environment where you could meet your peers,
especially if you're a professional or corporate type.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Shields and Calloway said they went after a ``professional,
25 and older'' crowd. While making sure their clients have a good
time, the promoters say they are also concerned with matters such
as contracts with club owners, security and disc jockeys.
</P>
<P>
   But, for Calloway, there's one major downside to the business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sleep deprivation,'' he laughed. ``You're up at events during
the day, booking venues, going after sponsors. Then, at night,
you're at the parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Shields, Calloway, a 1997 graduate of Howard University,
does not have a day job. Still, he and his partners are doing well
financially, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he wouldn't get specific about revenues. ``Let's just say
that we're making more than the average young doctor coming out of
school,'' he said. ``The money depends on the venue you choose and
the agreement you have with the owner.''
</P>
<P>
   Some expenses Black Diamonds incurs come from providing
security, which Calloway said, can cost up to $700 a night. But
sponsors, such as FUBU Clothing, Johnnie Walker or Philip Morris
can offset this.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Black Diamonds, ProLinks is steering clear of the typical
club scene, opting to hold events at private lofts in the Flatiron
District that normally are used for magazine photo shoots.
</P>
<P>
   ``People get tired of that club atmosphere or environment,''
said Shields, adding that his group pays up to $6,000 for eight
hours at a venue like Nancy's Loft at 20th Street and Fifth Avenue.
The only club ProLinks deals with is Vivid Bar and Lounge at
Madison Avenue and 31st Street. There, the group holds its ``First
Fridays After-Work Mixer'', which is an ``invitation-only'' event,
Shields said.
</P>
<P>
   Shields said the Internet has been a big help to the business.
Gone are the days where promoters are handing out fliers on street
corners. Sending e-mails messages, Shields said, is the best way to
assure a safe, fun party environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got 10,000 people on our e-mail list,'' Shields said.
``By sending out these e-mails, it maintains a certain quality of
people. Instead of putting up posters and having street teams,
you're able to be a little discerning as to who comes in.''
</P>
<P>
   Calloway agreed, adding that Black Diamonds' motto, ``We reserve
the right to be selective,'' is placed at the end of every
promotion that appears on Web sites like Socialstep.com, a popular
Internet destination where parties and other entertainment events
are listed.
</P>
<P>
   Calloway says holding a party at Justin's, which is owned by
rapper and record producer Sean ``Puffy'' Combs, is a great way to
draw people in.
</P>
<P>
   ``People know Puffy and other celebrities often frequent
Justin's, so they may come out with the hope that they might run
into someone,'' he said. ``We never guarantee it, but it almost
always happens that someone big comes through.''
</P>
<P>
   Shields doesn't see the logic in such advertisements because,
``Puffy and Jay-Z aren't going to announce what parties they go
to.''
</P>
<P>
   Anika Warren, a 27-year-old student at Columbia University's
Teachers College, said she chooses parties based on the promoter's
reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If my girls and I are looking for a hot party and there are a
lot of things going on, we'll decide by what type of crowd we think
the promoters will attract,'' said Warren, who frequents Black
Diamond parties at Aubette and NV.
</P>
<P>
   Shields said this has been the trend for most of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The social scene has changed a lot. There was a time,
particularly in the Studio 54 days, when clubs were in,'' Shields
said, referring to a popular nightspot in the days of disco.
``Then, violence happened and clubs fell out of favor. That's when
promoters came into the picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Shields said promoters became as popular as the clubs
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, it was all about the venue, but as the '90s started,
it was who was throwing the party,'' Shields said. ``Clubs didn't
need promoters, but now, people follow the promoter.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Monica Lewis is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
