<SLUG> BC-CNS-24-HOUR-GYMS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL-NIGHT GYMS WORK OUT FOR MANY 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  _
 By LULADEY B. TADESSE  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Physical conditioning is for daytime. Night is for
sleep.
</P>
<P>
   That is, unless one is a sanitation worker, theater manager, cop
or cab driver. For folks whose work may not fit a 9-to-5 pattern,
getting buffed can mean late hours and someone like Gil Flores.
</P>
<P>
   Flores, who studies film in his off time, works in one of a
handful of gyms in the city open 24 hours a day, seven days a week.
The 30-year-old is the night manager at one, Crunch Fitness, an
international chain. Most of the city's more than 250 gyms operate
somewhere between the hours of 6 a.m. and 11 p.m., the peak times
for gyms-goers. But they miss potential customers seeking the
flexibility of an around-the-clock fitness facility.
</P>
<P>
   Flores says Crunch's night and day clients differ. ``The people
that come at night are more lively than the ones that come in the
morning,'' he said. ``In the morning, they don't want to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision to work out when the rest of the city sleeps can be
job-related. ``Twenty-four hours is a very important factor because
we have the airport, Rikers Island, police precincts and Yellow Cab
people,'' said Peter Sarkissian, managing owner of BQE gym in
Woodside, Queens, one of the largest and oldest 24-hour gyms in the
city. ``Our parking lot looks like a TLC lot after midnight,''
Sarkissian said, referring to the Taxi and Limousine Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Velasquez and his fiancee, Vivian Bargas, both 30,
joined BQE two weeks ago. ``I live down in Corona,'' Velasquez
said. ``She lives in Brooklyn. We got very different schedules at
work,'' but they want to exercise together. Both work at the
airport and their schedules can vary from month to month.
</P>
<P>
   But clientele is not always limited to those who have irregular
schedules.
</P>
<P>
   Igor, who would not to give his last name, a manager at Hardcore
Muscle &AMP; Fitness in downtown Manhattan, says some of his clients
like the quietness of the gym at night. About 75 percent of his
clients are men, mostly ``serious body builders,'' who prefer a
less crowded environment that allows them to concentrate.
</P>
<P>
   Crunch's Flores said: ``The people that come at night, they put
more in their workout, they have more enthusiasm. They are a lot
faster, more energetic on the machines than the morning ones.'' He
said he could not explain it, but guessed that they were coming
from work and were more focused on getting a good workout before
going home to crash.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason more gyms are not open all the time is
financial. ``The 24-hour upkeep becomes a big problem because there
is no down time for this equipment,'' said Sarkissian, who also
owns two other gyms, in Harlem and the Bronx, neither of which is
open 24 hours. ``You don't want to have yellow ribbons on your
equipment, he said, referring to indicators that the machinery is
out of order. BQE's biggest expense is payroll for its 40 to 50
employees. Utilities, which ``go up to $2 million a year,'' and
insurance are its next highest expenditures, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``To stay competitive you have to diversify,'' he said. ``We
have to offer more than any gym is offering. Our biggest thing is
our price. You have two years for $149 a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Convenience is at the heart of most people's choice of a gym.
With that in mind, BQE has a free parking lot, a juice bar, a
restaurant, a pro shop, separate kids' and ladies' gyms, daycare
and other amenities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of gyms better than this but this is open 24
hours,'' said Ali Bazzi, 24, a three-year member of BQE. Bazzi, who
is about 6 feet tall with crisply defined muscles, said he works
out every day. A salesman in Connecticut who commutes from his home
in Inwood, Queens, Bazzi goes to the gym whenever his unpredictable
schedule permits.
</P>
<P>
   The main competition to BQE are smaller ``localized,''
neighborhood gyms in Queens that are also open 24 hours, Sarkissian
said. Cynthia, who would not give her last name, is the manager of
Platinum, a small 24-hour gym in Rego Park. Platinum, which looks
much like the neighborhood stores lining Queens Boulevard, offers
many of the same perks as BQE, including a juice bar, parking lot,
babysitting facilities and exercise classes, she said.
</P>
<P>
   For Igor, who now is daytime manager at Hardcore, having a gym
that was open at night was good for his health in more ways than
one. ``I was on dialysis,'' he said. ``I needed to go to the
hospital practically every second day.'' He said he no longer needs
dialysis and can now work when he pleases.
</P>
<P>
   Although Crunch's all-night policy allows Flores to spend his
days studying film, working the graveyard shift can take a personal
toll. ``I don't have any relationships at all. Period,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His weekends are devoted to making short films. ``Even on the
two days I have, I don't go out,'' Flores said. ``It has to be that
way.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Luladey B. Tadesse is a master's degree candidate at
the Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is
no charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to
Prof. Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC; _
</P>
</TEXT>
