u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAXTER-COLUMN12-COX     05-11 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Expect education board with more edge
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Gov. Roy Barnes has been taking his sweet time making
a slew of major board appointments he's had on the table since the
end of the legislative session, submitting his applicants to
thorough background checks and trying the patience of various
interest groups, as he laps the state signing all the laws he got
passed.
</P>
<P>
   Given the general anticipation this has created, it was a little
curious that when Barnes announced his appointments for eight of
the 11 state Board of Education seats, he did so by fax and not
with a photo-op press conference.
</P>
<P>
   No matter, though: With the governor moving education to the top
of his priority list for the next year, the board members should
have plenty of time under the lights.
</P>
<P>
   The new board is likely to have more edge than its predecessor,
which was chaired by newly elected U.S. Rep. Johnny Isakson and
tailor-made to get along with the state's Republican school
superintendent, Linda Schrenko.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't be interpreted as a shot across anybody's bow if a
governor in another state nominated a PTA official from his home
county to the school board, but after Schrenko's differences with
the group, the appointment of state PTA president Cathy Henson sent
a message that this board will have its own voice. No one who saw
another appointee, Gloria Bromell-Tinubu, debate winner Bill
Campbell and Marvin Arrington in the last mayoral race will expect
her to be a shrinking violet, either.
</P>
<P>
   It's a more Democratic board, but the strongest characteristic
seems to be a strong identification with public schools. Atlanta
lawyer Harry Bruce Jackson, for instance, spoke of his father, who
was on the Coweta School Board, and his daughter, a first-grader in
DeKalb County. ``I'm a product of public schools, and so is my
wife,'' he said, echoing a sentiment expressed by several new
members.
</P>
<P>
   And they are ambitious: ``We really need to beginning planning
for 50 or 100 years hence,'' Bromell-Tinubu said.
</P>
<P>
   But much of the edge may simply come from the urgency of the
education issues facing the state, more than the personalities of
the board members.
</P>
<P>
   Marietta, Ga. publisher Otis Brumby, suggested by Barnes to
chair the board, spoke of his concern over the growing number of
parents in his area taking their children out of the public school
system. One of the major reasons, he noted, was classroom
discipline, an issue Barnes has highlighted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm all for choice, but public schools do need to be aware
they are going to have competition,'' Brumby said.
</P>
<P>
   Much of what the board deals with in the next few years will
depend on the education reform commission, to be made up of five
members each from the House and Senate and anyone else Barnes
chooses to name, which will meet for a year to study new public
school policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the key to the future of education in Georgia is going
to be in the results of the commission,'' said Rep. Jeannette
Jamieson, chair of the House Education Committee. ``If we just
rubber-stamp recommendations, we'll get nowhere. But I do not
expect this to be a rubber-stamp governor.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes hasn't announced his appointments to that commission,
either, but he'll have to hurry. By law, it holds its first meeting
June 7.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Baxter writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
