<TEXT>
<P>
   DISPATCHES FROM DREAMSVILLE: A school where we were loved
</P>
<P>
   (''Dispatches from Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in
which readers share with Cox Newspapers senior writer Joe Murray
their memories of growing up in small-town America. Back then, or
at least the way we remember it, life was like a dream.)
</P>
<P>
   By Mae Hardman
</P>
<P>
   Special to Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   One by one each morning the neighborhood kids joined the brigade
traipsing off to our Porterdale School in that Georgia mill town.
</P>
<P>
   Doris usually hid her sweater behind a tree and retrieved it on
her way home.
</P>
<P>
   Emily usually came home without hers, having left it wherever
she took it off.
</P>
<P>
   I hated galoshes and vowed I'd never wear them again. I haven't!
</P>
<P>
   At morning recess, some paid 3 cents a day for a half pint of
rich, whole milk and a sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   Because our mother made us eat a good breakfast, my brother
James and I never had that luxury.
</P>
<P>
   However, there were days when our peanut butter or egg salad
sandwiches got mighty soggy stuffed in our desks until lunchtime.
</P>
<P>
   Our teaches loved us and believed in us. We respected and loved
them also.
</P>
<P>
   I can remember something important from first through 11th
grades.
</P>
<P>
   Begonias, geraniums and-or sultanas always beautified the window
shelves of our classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   I can still smell the oil of cloves in Miss Jordan's gallon of
homemade paste.
</P>
<P>
   I learned scores of Bible verses in Miss Stanley's fifth grade.
</P>
<P>
   Our eighth-grade teacher, Miss Kite, chose a starlit night on a
ball field to teach the constellations to our biology class.
</P>
<P>
   I never ceased to hate maypole dances and physical education.
</P>
<P>
   I liked spelling and good grades.
</P>
<P>
   We grew. Our class graduated in 1942. Most of the boys went to
protect our heritage in the South Pacific, North Africa, Europe and
India during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, I kept in touch with almost every classmate.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, we were grown before we realized that people thought
``cotton mill village children'' were different. Actually, we had
more opportunities _ in clubs, sports, churches, school band, plays
and the library.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, when the time arrived for me to sell the family home
we had occupied for 70 years, I sorted out treasures for the three
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   The last thing I did was kneel to thank God for all the
memories, and then walked out the door, locked it and gave the keys
to the new owner.
</P>
<P>
   Bone-weary, I went immediately to spend the night at a friend's
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   When I turned back the gold chenille spread, there were purple
sheets _ my school colors.
</P>
<P>
   That had to be God's way of telling me I had begun a new phase
of my life.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Mae Hardman makes her home in Dillard, Ga.)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a story to share, send it to ``Dispatches from
Dreamsville,'' c/o Joe Murray, Cox Newspapers, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915. A photo of the writer is optional. If your
article is used, you will receive $25. For other Dreamsville
stories, visit http://www.geocities.com/SoHo/Bistro/7147.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
