A2315 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES1     05-11 0230
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHORTTAKES: Because he's there
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   George Leigh Mallory was in fairly good shape, considering, when
they found him a few days ago sealed in ice to the face of Mount
Everest since 1924. Mallory left behind two of the century's
enduring mysteries: whether he and his young companion, Andrew
Irvine, had reached the top and why people do things like that in
the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Mallory had a flip answer. Because, he said, it is there. Had he
survived, Mallory might have regretted coining the cliche, the way
Maurice Ravel came to regret writing the Bolero. Mallory was still
pluckily clinging to the rock face, dispatches from Everest
indicate, trying to arrest his fall. Irvine has not yet been found.
</P>
<P>
   One mystery has been solved. Mallory and Irvine were apparently
descending when they fell. Whether they reached the summit is not
known. Mallory and Irvine were last seen headed for the top, when
they were lost in a cloud.
</P>
<P>
   There is still no answer to the question of why humans do such
things, no answer even as to why they look for bodies at 27,000
feet. I once knew, but I forgot.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
