<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990511.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 10:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2316 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN12-COX     05-11 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Walk tall and carry a loud tune
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Each spring I seriously consider moving. Not
that I don't love my old home _ I do, but budding tulips and
unfolding maple leaves mean just one thing to me _ it's time to go
into the attic.
</P>
<P>
   Once a year I screw up my courage to go through the door inside
my office closet _ the one that leads to the attic stairs _ but
before I ever open it, the psyching up begins. First, I picture
myself brave, tall, virtually fearless, and then, just in case that
doesn't work, I begin singing a loud song like, ``CALEDONIA! What
makes your big head so hard?'' That way, whatever unknown,
unrecognizable, and yet unnamed presence might be up there waiting
to pounce, will hear me coming and get out while the getting's
good.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong, I'm not a hard-line attic hater. Attics are
really good things to have _ and the bigger the better because
everybody needs a place to shove stuff that's just too ugly to live
downstairs with the family but impossible to throw out because your
mother-in-law gave it to you and you'll need it for her next visit.
Without an attic, where would we keep the seascape Aunt Sookie
painted from memory right after Uncle Bert ran off with the lady
from the Western Union office? And where else could we store our
40-year collections of National Geographics and unfinished pieces
of needlework?
</P>
<P>
   Attics also come in handy during hard rains when the roof starts
leaking and we need a place to put buckets so the drips don't come
through the bedroom ceilings. Attics can be a veritable treasure
trove, holding everything from two empty 40-gallon tanks left there
by college-age sons who changed apartments so often their tropical
fish were in an ongoing state of shock, to hand-painted cribs
carefully covered and stored in anticipation of the first
grandchild.
</P>
<P>
   The big problem with my attic is that I don't go up there
enough. I put it off for a variety of totally logical reasons (too
hot, too cold, too dark, too Tuesday) and so by the time I drag the
old Mighty Mite up for a spring vacuum, there's no telling what
might be there waiting for me.
</P>
<P>
   When I was a kid, the attic in our old house filled me with
mixed emotions. In the daylight it was a place to search for musty
treasures, but after dark it became an imagined chamber of horrors
to be avoided at all costs.
</P>
<P>
   On rainy afternoons, or when my best playmates and I were out of
sorts with one another, I'd slip into the attic to explore. One day
I found my mother's wedding dress in the bottom of an old cedar
chest _ a discovery that led to many enchanted hours of
make-believe.
</P>
<P>
   When the weather was right, and nothing was shaking outside, I'd
head for the attic to play ``wedding.'' Gingerly, I'd slip the
age-spotted satin gown over my playclothes and carefully situate
the ring of orange blossoms that held the veil atop my straggly
hair. Humming the ``Bridal Chorus'' from Lohengrin, I'd begin a
slow march the length of the attic to a dusty mirror propped near a
front window. The dress sagged and the veil soon turned tacky from
one too many snags on the rough floorboards of my ``bridal aisle,''
but enthusiasm for the game never dimmed. Until it began to get
dark.
</P>
<P>
   Come nightfall, I gave the attic door in the upstairs hall wide
berth, and after Tootie told me there was an escaped prisoner of
war hiding out in old Mrs. Collister's attic across the street, I
began carefully locking ours and taking the key to bed with me _
just in case.
</P>
<P>
   Now that I'm all grown up, none of this kid stuff bothers me
anymore. I'm just waiting for a sunny day when the temperature's
right, to head up those stairs and clean that attic. Here I come,
attic. Ready or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``CALEDONIA! CALEDONIA! WHAT MAKES YOUR BIG HEAD SO HARD?''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or email: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
