<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 10:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2317 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-WILDFIRES12-COX     05-11 2549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-WILDFIRES12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Life in the aftermath of Florida wildfires
 &HT;    By Teresa Lane
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ Les Rarrieck no longer sprinkles raw
peanuts in his staghorn fern to summon hungry squirrels and owls,
and June Holcomb will not soon enjoy her grandson's aerial
acrobatics on the backyard trampoline.
</P>
<P>
   Clifford Newland has stopped tending the 70 varieties of
tropical fruits and vegetables from his South American homeland,
and Martha Brann's flowering shrubs have lost their fragrant
blooms.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly four weeks after a most unwelcome visitor arrived, a dead
calm remains settled over Franklin Street.
</P>
<P>
   The mercurial wildfires that thrust Port St. Lucie into national
headlines last month pounded Franklin Street, reducing five homes
to molten rubble and damaging two others before forestry crews cut
a 20-foot swath in the woods and ended the inferno's easterly
rampage.
</P>
<P>
   Acres of pine- and palmetto-studded forests turned to kindling
as the blaze, whipped by 30-mph winds, blackened more than 700
acres between Florida's Turnpike and Interstate 95 and caused some
$4.5 million in damages.
</P>
<P>
   Although at least 42 homes were destroyed citywide, few streets
were hit as hard as Franklin _ a once-bustling verdant corridor now
flecked with barren cement slabs, denuded forests and Dumpsters
filled with broken bits of lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen Kosovo, but I can imagine what the place looks
like after this,'' said David Keirs, whose large home on Franklin
was one of nine spared. ``We built here because of the lush trees
and the wildlife. Now I hate to open the blinds in the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   The superheated flames turned Keirs' surroundings into a winter
landscape, tall ashen stubs surrounded by blackened clusters of saw
palmetto whose curling fingers resemble Medusa's writhing hair.
</P>
<P>
   Green leaves on oaks and maples turned to a crackly brown, and
from a distance Franklin Street looks like a Virginia neighborhood
in the height of autumn.
</P>
<P>
   Despite signs of green rebirth among the slash pines and
palmettoes, the firestorm changed Franklin Street's landscape
forever. Two of the five homes destroyed will not be rebuilt, and
owners of two others say it's unlikely they'll return.
</P>
<P>
   The daily pain of remembering April 15 would be too sharp,
Rarrieck says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't usually cry, but I've been crying a lot lately,'' says
Rarrieck, 50, an American Legion baseball coach and owner of a
sprinkler business. ``I saw a lot of Napalm dropped in Vietnam _
they called our unit the walking dead _ and that's what my
neighborhood looks like now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I could go back there.''
</P>
<P>
   It was 7 a.m. on tax day, and Rarrieck savored his morning
coffee and newspaper a little longer than usual. Within an hour,
workers would arrive to install cream-colored carpeting and vinyl
tile throughout the house, and a year's preparation for Rarrieck's
new bride would be complete.
</P>
<P>
   Four houses away, Brann was making a list of building materials
she'd need to have a carport built for her lawn tractor. For no
particular reason, the 59-year-old Brann baked a 10-pound turkey
that had been in her freezer for months, and she later drove to
Home Depot for shingles and plywood.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere on the quarter-mile street in southwest Port St.
Lucie, residents were having breakfast or checking e-mail or
heading to work.
</P>
<P>
   It would be eight hours until the monster made its house calls.
</P>
<P>
   Rarrieck left work early that day, eager to get home and see his
new floors. He'd spent a year replacing appliances and remodeling
the wood-frame home he bought on S.W. Franklin 18 years ago, and
Rarrieck wondered how his bride-to-be would like the changes.
</P>
<P>
   She never got a chance to decide.
</P>
<P>
   It was 4:30 p.m. when he got past the roadblocks, and Rarrieck's
neighbors were outside their homes in the wrenching heat, stuffing
valuables into the trunks of cars and praying for a wind change as
an 80-foot wall of flames careened in their direction.
</P>
<P>
   Retiree Keirs and nurse Newland, who worked the midnight shift
at Lawnwood Regional Medical Center Thursday night, were still
asleep when the madness erupted. Others, like Rarrieck and Brann,
arrived home in time to see the approaching firestorm but do little
else.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after arriving with her lumber and shingles, Brann spied
flames snaking up her to shed and ran inside the house to grab some
important papers, jewelry and a substantial amount of cash she had
locked in a fireproof safe in her bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   She emptied the safe and made it to her pickup with one armload
of papers before being ordered to evacuate. Her jewelry and cash
lay on the bed, outside the protective walls of the fireproof safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had left it inside I'd still have it today,'' Brann said
dismally, sitting inside the Holiday Inn suite that has been her
home since the fire. When she combed the ashes later looking for
any shard of memories, Brann found the safe; undamaged on the
inside.
</P>
<P>
   A Red Cross worker found Brann's diamond-studded cross, a gift
from her son, now sooty and gray. All else was lost.
</P>
<P>
   Although Rarrieck installed sprinkler systems for a living, he
was helpless in the face of the fires. Fearing firefighters could
be injured by falling electric lines, Florida Power &AMP; Light shut
off electricity to much of southwest Port St. Lucie. Private wells
_ powered by electric pumps _ were useless.
</P>
<P>
   He remembered his gas-powered generator in the shed beside his
pool. Maybe he still could stave off the fiery beast.
</P>
<P>
   When the generator would not crank, he discovered the awful
truth. He had no gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   With flames engulfing the house across the street and policemen
ordering him to leave, Rarrieck ran to his front door to retrieve
E.T., his cat of 13 years. When he threw open the door, he spied
his new carpet and tile for the first _ and last _ time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked beautiful,'' he recalls tearfully. ``We had just
repainted inside and out and bought all new appliances. It was like
a whole new house inside.'' Within 30 minutes, everything was
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   John Flaksa, who had rented his home on S.W. Franklin for five
years, was repairing a microwave in Jensen Beach when he got the
call over his Nextel radio: your neighborhood's in flames.
</P>
<P>
   Flaksa was thwarted by roadblocks at two intersections but
finally found an unguarded street. He drove past three burning
houses on Franklin before he reached his own smoldering ruins.
</P>
<P>
   Turned down for renter's insurance shortly after Hurricane
Andrew, Flaksa had no coverage. His sister reached his house in
time to grab some items, but couldn't remember where Flaksa hid his
house key. She saved nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last picture of my house I have is flames coming out of
the Whirlpool refrigerator,'' said Flaksa, who repairs Whirlpools
and other appliances. ``The only things I could save were a few
cast iron fry pans. They need to be re-seasoned now,'' he said with
a grim smile.
</P>
<P>
   When Flaksa arrived home about 7 p.m., firefighters were
spraying water on Edwin Scott's home across the street at.
Ironically, Scott was hoping his house would burn so he could use
the proceeds from a $75,000 insurance policy to move his family to
Montana.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it would have went, it would have been a blessing,'' said
Scott, who has been without water since the fire because the flames
baked his water pump. ``We'd have had plenty of gas money, and I
don't need pictures to remember what my kids looked like when they
were little.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Port St. Lucie's population of 82,005, the city's
beginnings are ill-rooted in a developer's greed. The now-bankrupt
General Development Corp. carved Port St. Lucie out of 80 square
miles of pine forest in 1961 but failed to provide municipal water
and sewer lines or fire hydrants to 80 percent of the lots.
</P>
<P>
   Although recent city councils have taken steps to extend
utilities citywide, the process has been slow given the city's size
and opposition from some property owners reluctant to pay per-lot
assessment fees of roughly $2,500.
</P>
<P>
   The 749 acres that burned April 15 holds 1,600 homes but nary a
fire hydrant. Homeowners who tried to use their own well water and
hoses were left high and dry because private well pumps operate on
electricity.
</P>
<P>
   The direction of the wind, coupled with some houses' proximity
to woody lots heavy with pine needles, palmetto bushes and 50-foot
pines trees, combined to carve the fire's checkerboard path of
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Franklin Street residents witnessed three separate fires on
April 15, but the final one that blazed a northeasterly trail from
Gatlin and Rosser boulevards proved the most destructive.
</P>
<P>
   As dazed homeowners watched the orange flames creep closer to
their withered lawns, police and firefighters went door to door
giving residents two minutes to evacuate. Newland, whose house at
the corner of Franklin and California Boulevard was one of the last
to catch fire, was threatened with arrest when he tried to dart
inside his bedroom to grab photographs from his childhood in
Guyana.
</P>
<P>
   Less than an hour earlier, Newland had helped a neighbor save
his pool home from destruction when a smaller fire whipped through
another part of the parched landscape. The two men carried 5-gallon
of buckets of pool water to hot spots on the ground and roof but
Newland, a former firefighter in Guyana, had no pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fire was just running as if someone was driving it,'' said
Newland, 49. ``When the fire was 20 feet from my house, a guy with
a tanker truck of water and hose were across the street and I said,
'Man, my house is going to catch fire,' so he came over to help,''
said Newland.
</P>
<P>
   The tanker truck ran out of water after five minutes but was
winning the battle and went across the street to refill with pool
water.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came back with a full tank, but then he got a call on his
radio and he was out of here,'' Newland said. ``He just vanished. I
never saw him again.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his three-bedroom home, Newland's family lost a
car, truck and 1 1/2 acres of South American fruit trees, vines and
vegetable plants he had cultivated for nine years using primitive
tools.
</P>
<P>
   Newland has vowed to rebuild. And this time, he'll make sure his
home is protected against the forces of nature that swept away a
lifetime of memories April 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going for wood this time,'' said Newland, noting that
four of the five Franklin homes destroyed were built of wood. ``I
watched my house burn for 45 minutes before I was forced to leave,
and I learned a lot of things. Nice cured wood burns like mad.''
</P>
<P>
   June Holcomb's house was the only concrete block house
destroyed, and its concrete and stucco walls remained intact, along
with some kitchen plates and a ceramic fish on the front porch
patio table.
</P>
<P>
   Items like those ``disintegrated'' next door in the house Flaksa
rented. Like most residents of Franklin Street, Flaksa worried
about hurricanes but never imagined a raging wildfire would consume
the treasures he's collected for 52 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a lot of silver coins that my father started collecting
in 1921, and they just vaporized,'' said Flaksa, who found traces
of nickel and copper coins but no signs of the silver mint. ``All
the things you have turn into fuel for the fire.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent divorcee, Brann had read newspaper accounts of the
county's desert-like drought and hired men to clear underbrush from
wooded lots surrounding her home.
</P>
<P>
   No amount of clearing could have saved Brann's house, she now
says soberly. The flames were too high, the wind too strong, the
trees too dry.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in her hotel suite, Brann admits she feels scared and
alone without the possessions that have served her since childhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the sentimental one in the family,'' says Brann, a
mother of three who displayed her family's heirlooms and
photographs prominently throughout her modest three-bedroom home.
``I had three of my mother's afghans that she crocheted and
whenever I looked at them they reminded me of Mama.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most Port St. Lucie neighborhoods, Franklin Street folks
are friendly but not overly sociable, preferring to chat at the
mailbox or front doorstep before retreating into their own homes
and lives.
</P>
<P>
   Since the fire, neighbors have gone out of their way to comfort
one another. John Flaksa and Kelly Flinn lived three doors away
from one another for more than a year but never met until April 16,
when Flinn offered Flaksa whatever help he needed.
</P>
<P>
   Two children who often passed Newland laboring over his fields
of guava, passion fruits and gooseberry trees sat outside a Publix
supermarket one day and collected $200 for his family.
</P>
<P>
   A child who rode her bicycle past Brann's house walked up and
hugged the disabled custodian from Jensen Beach Elementary School
and asked if she was rebuilding the sky blue house that had been a
landmark on the corner of Franklin and John MacCormack Terrace for
13 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't decided,'' came the answer, trembling. ``I don't
know where I'm going from here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Here,'' as all of Port St. Lucie's fire victims will tell you,
is limbo, a sort of ethereal waiting room in between the dizzying
world of insurance claims, condolences and a final resting place to
call home.
</P>
<P>
   The community has reached out. A church collected $2,810 for
fire victims, and everybody from car dealers to Little League clubs
have collected money.
</P>
<P>
   And although fire victims have been offered everything from
rent-free homes to free furniture and food, most will tell you
they're simply eager to get their insurance check and rebuild or
move on.
</P>
<P>
   Most people with claims were given $5,000 for living expenses
within hours of the devastation, and a few were presented with
checks for the replacement value of their homes within a day or
two.
</P>
<P>
   Although nine homes on Franklin suffered little or no damages,
occupants of those did not escape unscathed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was crying as we drove back into the neighborhood, past all
those burned houses, because I was sure we didn't have a home any
more,'' said Rose Bamonte, 79. ``When I saw our home still standing
I made the sign of the cross and said, 'Thank God.' Our
neighborhood looked like a war zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Keirs had the opposite experience. He was told by police
dispatchers that his home was engulfed in flames when he called to
check on it that night.
</P>
<P>
   When he, his wife and daughter drove down the scorched street a
day later, they passed a pile of debris and were astounded find
their spacious home on Franklin untouched.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pulled in the driveway and dropped to our knees,'' Keirs
said. ``It didn't have a mark on it.''
</P>
<P>
   For those less fortunate, Mother Nature's healing has just
begun.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I drove down the road and saw someone sifting through the
ashes I had to turn away because it broke my heart,'' said Bamonte,
who evacuated her home along with her husband, 36-year-old daughter
and two cats. ``It seems so strange that the cute little house with
the front porch is not there any more. Everything is ashes.''
</P>
<P>
   Teresa Lane writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
