<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-POORKIDS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Report doesn't bode well for children born into poverty
 &HT;    By Mike Wagner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Amanda was destined to be a school statistic.
Another example of how child poverty shoves students to the back of
the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Her mom is poor, unemployed and has moved the 4-year-old to
different low-income apartments around Dayton, Ohio three times in
the last eight months. Only the efforts of Dayton City Schools Head
Start program kept the girl from falling completely out of the
system.
</P>
<P>
   But Amanda is one of the lucky children, according to a report
issued Monday by the Children's Defense Fund in Ohio. The report,
Helping Children Learn, says 40 percent of Ohio newborns start life
likely to live in poverty and perform in the lower half of their
class at school. The report shows a strong connection between
reducing child poverty and improving school performance for
students or future students.
</P>
<P>
   Like Amanda.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept finding her and bringing her back,'' Gail Rowe,
director of Dayton's Head Start program, said of Amanda. ``She
would have fallen through the cracks like so many young children
who live in high-poverty areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Using the new 4th grade proficiency test standards for reading,
the study showed that students in high-poverty districts failed
more often to meet reading standards. The report found that fewer
than half _ 47 percent _ of Ohio fourth graders tested last year
would have passed 1999's tougher reading standards.
</P>
<P>
   And in Dayton the scores would have been much worse.
</P>
<P>
   Only one in five Dayton students would have passed the 4th grade
reading test under the tougher standards. That ranked Dayton last
in the report among Ohio's ``big eight'' urban school districts,
which include Akron, Canton, Cincinnati, Cleveland, Columbus,
Toledo and Youngstown.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons cited for lower tests scores in high-poverty
districts included poor children who:
</P>
<P>
   _ Move frequently
</P>
<P>
   _ Lacking regular nutritious food
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't have proper health care
</P>
<P>
   ``Johnny's just not going to read as well if he attends two or
three different classrooms during one school year,'' said Mark
Real, director of the Children's Defense Fund. ``That's why helping
parents out of poverty can provide something as simple as the same
address _ and the same teacher _ for the school year.
</P>
<P>
   ``With four in 10 newborns at risk, we must make sure that every
child is healthy and ready to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Certain risk factors at birth increase the odds of childhood
poverty and difficulties in school, according to the report. Those
risks include having:
</P>
<P>
   _ A mother who didn't finish high school.
</P>
<P>
   _ A mother who was a teen.
</P>
<P>
   _ Unmarried parents.
</P>
<P>
   About 17 percent of Ohio newborns start life with at least two
of these three risks, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   These problems plague kids all through their school years and
can set up a pattern for repetition, said Kathy Channell, a
sixth-grade teacher at Berry Middle School in Lebanon, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's possible for kids to break the pattern and not follow in
the footsteps of their parents,'' Channell said. ``If a child has a
good mentor, a parent, a grandparent who takes a strong interest in
them, they can overcome the risk factors.''
</P>
<P>
   Education experts say the report's findings are not new, but
expose the holes in the state's vastly different curriculums and
programs from district to district.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ohio has a totally non-aligned curriculum and everyone does
their own thing,'' said Tom Lasley, dean of the University of
Dayton's School of Education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mobility is a terrible problem in our schools,'' he said. ``A
kid who moves from one district to another doesn't get from a
teacher what they are missing at home and that's a major problem in
development.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the report's overall findings, some Ohio districts are
achieving better-than-expected school performance in high-poverty
areas.
</P>
<P>
   In East Ohio's Jefferson County, despite ranking 12th in state
for child poverty, nearly 60 percent of fourth-graders would have
passed the fourth-grade reading test under the tougher standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our community and schools have embraced the fact that we are a
very diverse district and have met the challenges of being a small
urban district,'' said Charles Joyce, superintendent of the
Steubenville City Schools in Jefferson County. ``Sixty percent
still isn't good enough, but you can longer use being a (poor)
district as an excuse to fail.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Wagner writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
