<HEADER>
A2319 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN12-COX     05-11 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Grandpappy Polluter: In 2001, he gets his 30-year pin for
dodging air laws
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Behold the bronze pillars of equality in the Texas
Legislature. The James Byrd Jr. Hate Crimes Act, which would add
penal severity for illegal acts aimed at classes of people, is
getting held up because critics say it would create a ``two-tiered,
unequal system of justice'' _ some crimes treated differently than
others. Can you feel the outrage?
</P>
<P>
   Texas lawmakers would never dispense preferential treatment to
anyone _ that is, anyone who is without a smokestack to his name.
If you have one, and if you planted it on the prairie before 1971,
we have a dirty deal: You'll be treated preferentially. Call it
compassionate conservatism for the elderly _ smokestacks, that is.
</P>
<P>
   Outrage, please. Or, maybe you think some pollution is more
equal than others.
</P>
<P>
   A tireless environmental band in Austin has placed facts before
the public that not even wholly owned subsidiaries of industry
(we're talking lawmakers) can deny. The loophole that allows
grandfathered plants to still evade the 1971 Texas Clean Air Act
must be addressed.
</P>
<P>
   It would appear that Texas is nosing up toward doing that with
all the fortitude of a house cat that can't stand getting its paws
wet.
</P>
<P>
   A bill before the Texas House this week is touted, too
generously, as a means of getting grandfathered polluters to clean
up their act. These are plants _ most notably utilities, refineries
and carbon-black plants _ that are operating outside of state law,
which requires newly permitted plants to have ``best available
control technology'' (BACT) to curb pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, grandfathered plants do have pollution-control devices
pursuant to less lenient federal requirements. Some have made major
improvements voluntarily. But as a group they're releasing roughly
50 percent more pollution than they should.
</P>
<P>
   Senate-passed S.B. 766, authorized by Sen. J.E. ``Buster'' Brown
(R-Lake City, Texas) and supported by Gov. Bush, would implement a
voluntary program under which grandfathered plants could install
cleaner-air technology.
</P>
<P>
   Implied in the legislation is that plants that didn't do so
might face requirements in 2001. ``Might'' is the key word there,
might as in maybe.
</P>
<P>
   What would happen if the plants didn't sign on to clean up? No
one knows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our biggest beef is that it doesn't say anything about (what
would happen) two years from now,'' said Ken Kramer of the Sierra
Club of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem with the bill is that plants signing on would
not need to meet current-day BACT requirements, like new plants do,
but those of standards roughly 10 years old. That would be a big
step, reducing pollution by up to 30 percent. But current standards
would cut their pollution by half.
</P>
<P>
   Polluters would be hedging their bets under this program. Do
they believe Texas legislators actually would come back in two
years and force their hands? Or don't they?
</P>
<P>
   Considering that grandfathered plants have won that wager for
almost 30 years now, why change their hand?
</P>
<P>
   Kramer remembers hearings back in the early 1980s during sunset
hearings for the Texas Air Control Board and the discussion over
what to do about grandfathered plants.
</P>
<P>
   The message then was, ``Don't do anything about these older
plants because they're nearing the end of their useful lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Now we're about to run out of '90s, and most of those
grandfathered plants are still chugging along.
</P>
<P>
   The Brown bill could be a big breakthrough if it really had
teeth in it, actually set a deadline. Then again, if it did it
wouldn't be voluntary, and it still would allow Texas to continue
to treat some polluters preferentially.
</P>
<P>
   That's unjust _ unless you own an old smokestack, or someone
with a smokestack owns you.
</P>
<P>
   John Young writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
