</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEPATITIS-EXPLAINER12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A on hepatitis C and other strains of the hepatitis virus
 &HT;    By Paul Lomartire
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHAT IS HEPATITIS C?
</P>
<P>
   It is a virus that causes inflammation of the liver. It is
transmitted through exposure to infected blood. Unlike hepatitis A
or B, there is no vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   WHY IS HEPATITIS C DANGEROUS?
</P>
<P>
   Many people infected with the virus may never know they have it.
The virus can take decades to show symptoms while killing liver
cells and causing scarring called cirrhosis in 20 percent of people
with chronic C virus. Cirrhosis can lead to liver cancer. Alcohol
speeds the damaging process. Hepatitis C is the most common reason
for liver transplant.
</P>
<P>
   WHY IS HEPATITIS C SO HARD TO TREAT?
</P>
<P>
   There are six strains of the C virus. Genotype 1 is the most
common and toughest to treat. Each strain responds differently to
medicines _ meaning that the success rate for clearing the virus
from the body is 40 percent or less.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER HEPATITIS VIRUSES
</P>
<P>
   Hepatitis A
</P>
<P>
   Estimated 180,000 new infections annually. Vaccine exists.
</P>
<P>
   Transmission: Through feces-contaminated food or water or raw
shellfish harvested from waters containing raw sewage.
</P>
<P>
   Symptoms: Children usually show no symptoms and commonly pass it
to adults. Adults have dark urine and light-colored stool, fever,
yellow skin and eyes (jaundice), fatigue, nausea, vomiting,
abdominal pain. Symptoms disappear over a six- to 12-month period
and you become immune.
</P>
<P>
   Hepatitis B
</P>
<P>
   Estimated 200,000 new infections annually. Vaccine exists.
</P>
<P>
   Transmission: Through sex or shared drug needles. It is 100
times more infectious than AIDS. Can also be transmitted (though
much less common) by contaminated sharp instruments carrying
infected blood that are used for body piercing or tattooing, shared
razors, nail files, toothbrushes.
</P>
<P>
   Symptoms: Loss of appetite, nausea, fatigue, muscle or joint
aches, mild fever. About a quarter of people may see dark
urine/light-colored stool, yellowing of skin and eyes. Some have no
symptoms. Less than 5 percent of cases are chronic.
</P>
<P>
   Hepatitis C
</P>
<P>
   Fewer than 30,000 new infections annually. No vaccine.
</P>
<P>
   Transmission: Through shared drug needles/straws or other
exposure to sharp objects with contaminated blood. Also, blood
transfusions before 1992. Rarely transmitted sexually.
</P>
<P>
   Symptoms: Same as hepatitis B. Symptoms can be dormant 20-years
plus and are frequently misdiagnosed as the flu or chronic fatigue
syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Treatment: Estimated 80 percent of cases are chronic. Combining
two drugs _ interferon and ribavirin _ for six months to a year is
the most successful treatment available with a virus-killing
success rate of 40 percent or less. This combination of medicines
is expensive _ $300 a week _ and produces serious side effects
including flu-like symptoms, headaches, depression, irritability
and lethargy.
</P>
<P>
   Hepatitis D
</P>
<P>
   A co-virus with hepatitis B. Only people with B get D. Vaccine
for B prevents D. Symptoms and transmission same as B.
</P>
<P>
   Hepatitis E
</P>
<P>
   Little is known about this third-world virus.
</P>
<P>
   Transmission: Thought to be similar to A: fecal/oral route.
Associated with contaminated water.
</P>
<P>
   _ Source: American Liver Foundation
</P>
<P>
   HEPATITIS B AND C FACTS
</P>
<P>
   A drop of HIV-infected blood can survive nine minutes outside
the body. Hepatitis B-infected blood, seven days. Hepatitis
C-infected blood, nine days.
</P>
<P>
   _ Each year, 9,000 to 10,000 doctors, nurses and other
health-care workers are infected with the B virus through contact
with contaminated blood.
</P>
<P>
   _ Of the estimated 4 million people infected with hepatitis C,
about 100,000 are being treated.
</P>
<P>
   _There are 4,100 liver transplants annually. Twice as many
people need a transplant, a number expected to triple in 20 years.
More than one-half of transplants are due to damage from long-term
C-virus infection. An estimated 300,000 people were infected with C
virus in the U.S. through blood transfusions before 1992.
</P>
<P>
   _Even a transplant won't rid you of C virus: It recurs in 100
percent of liver transplant recipients. Virus is present in the
body and attacks new liver. A transplant just buys time.
</P>
<P>
   _Increasingly popular herbal cures are not viewed by most
doctors as harmful but also not proven to help against the B or C
virus.
</P>
<P>
   _Scientists don't know why people infected with C virus before
age 40 move slower to cirrhosis than people infected after age 40
or why men move faster to cirrhosis than women. Due to homosexual
sex and homemade tattooing, B- and C-virus infection is estimated
at 50 percent in prisons. Home testing: The first at-home test for
hepatitis C was recently approved by the Food and Drug
Administration. Home Access Health Inc.'s Hepatitis C Check costs
under $70. For more information: www.homeaccess.com or call
1-888-888-4372.
</P>
<P>
   _ Source: Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, American
Liver Foundation
</P>
<P>
   The liver is the largest glandular organ in the body, weighing
about 3 pounds and roughly the size of a football. It's called your
garbage disposal and guardian angel because trillions of liver
cells filter toxins and poisons that you eat, breathe or absorb
through your skin. Among the 5,000 jobs the liver does: Removes
bacteria from blood, stores energy, creates bile for food
digestion, creates muscle and is crucial to clotting.
</P>
<P>
   The liver doesn't warn of trouble until damage is advanced. When
active liver cells are killed and replaced by scar tissue, it's
called cirrhosis.
</P>
<P>
   One liver can be cut in half for two transplants and within
three weeks it will regenerate and grow to full size in each
recipient.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Hepatitis Foundation International
</P>
<P>
   HEP C TIMELINE
</P>
<P>
   Mid-1940s: First non-A, non-B hepatitis discovered in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   Late '60s, early '70s: Shared drug needles spread virus not yet
identified
</P>
<P>
   1988 _ C virus identified by molecular cloning.
</P>
<P>
   1990 _ Routine testing of blood donors for C virus
</P>
<P>
   1992 _ Blood transfusion risk below 1 percent by improved donor
test
</P>
<P>
   1996 _ Centers for Disease Control and Prevention survey
estimates 3.9 million people infected with C virus
</P>
<P>
   1997 _ CDC begins awareness campaign for 250,000 physicians
</P>
<P>
   1998 _ CDC publishes recommendations for control/prevention of C
virus
</P>
<P>
   May 1999 _ CDC begins public awareness campaign
</P>
<P>
   Source: Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
</P>
<P>
   WHERE TO CALL FOR HELP
</P>
<P>
   _Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, Atlanta. Hepatitis
information line, 24 hours: 1-888-443-7232. Internet:
www.cdc.gov/ncidod/diseases/hepatitis
</P>
<P>
   _American Liver Foundation, Cedar Grove, N.J. Hepatitis/liver
disease help line, 9 a.m. to 6 p.m. (Eastern), Monday through
Friday, voicemail 24 hours: 1-800-223-0179 or 1-800-GO-LIVER.
Internet: www.liverfoundation.org
</P>
<P>
   _Hepatitis Foundation International, Cedar Grove, N.J. Hepatitis
information, 9 a.m. to 5 p.m., Monday through Friday, voicemail 24
hours: 1-800-891-0707. Internet: www.hepfi. org
</P>
<P>
   Paul Lomartire writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
