<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MATERNITY-CLOTHES12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Maternity fashions: Staying cool and looking cool
 &HT;    By Christi Mays
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Comfort. Comfort. Comfort.
</P>
<P>
   That one small word means the world to mothers-to-be when it
comes to surviving the warm-weather months of their pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Comfort is first and foremost,'' said June Holloway, manager
of Maternity Works in Hillsboro, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Any natural fibers in fabrics, like cottons and linens, are
comfy. Synthetic materials like rayon and anything with stretchy
spandex keep the body cool in warmer months.
</P>
<P>
   Lightly woven sleeveless tops and shorts lead the way in this
year's casual lines, as well as anything denim, including the
popular overall shorts.
</P>
<P>
   Loose-hanging dresses made with spandex are great for an
expanding tummy, as are summery sundresses with drawstrings and
ties.
</P>
<P>
   Attractive, yet keeping with the comfort theme, sheer dresses
and flowing, rayon pantsuits are ideal for women who attend lots of
spring and summer functions or who want something a little dressy
for church or work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pregnant women still want to feel in style and feminine,
because you feel like a circus tent is the only thing that would
really feel comfortable,'' said Linda Dizmon, sales manager for
women's apparel at Sears and mother of five. ``You feel so awful
when you waddle past the mirror. Pretty clothes help you feel
better about yourself when you're wondering, `What is happening to
my body?' Pregnant women who dress nicely feel better. It's
psychological.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only has the availability and variety of maternity clothes
increased over the last decade, they now follow the trends more
closely than in year's past.
</P>
<P>
   Women say feeling in style is important when it comes to picking
out maternity clothes. ``They don't want to stick out like sore
thumbs,'' said Lori Yearwood, senior merchandising assistant at JC
Penney's. ``They stick out already.''
</P>
<P>
   Black and white are colors of choice for many expecting moms,
since those are slimming colors. Navy blue is a hot color this
season, as are pink and anything with flowers on it _ from shirts
to sundresses. Shift dresses, shirt dresses and sleeveless dresses
coupled with crochet or spandex jackets are fashionable finds for
the mother-to-be.
</P>
<P>
   Rayon pantsuits and skirts with mix-and-match tops and bottoms
not only are comfy finds for the office, but also easier on the
pocketbook.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of jumper-type things you can put a different top under
and then use the same top with shorts or pants,'' Dizmon said.
</P>
<P>
   With a little strategic planning, said Linda Thompson,
merchandising assistant in women's casual at JC Penney,
mothers-to-be can get by with a handful of essential pieces this
summer _ a pair of jeans, a pair of dressy pants, three or four
dressy blouses, several pairs of knit or denim shorts and maybe a
dress or two.
</P>
<P>
   Holloway urges women to splurge a little on at least one item as
a pick-me-up outfit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Feeling good about yourself when you're pregnant makes all the
difference in the world,'' she said. ``They should always feel
beautiful about themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Christi Mays writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
