u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN12-CO     05-11 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MONEYTALK: Calculator compares mutual fund expenses
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's give a cheer for the Securities and Exchange Commission:
It has put together a gadget that will help individual investors
estimate, fairly closely, how much it actually costs to invest in a
particular mutual fund.
</P>
<P>
   That's no small thing. Most investors don't know that their
money pays the ongoing expenses of their mutual funds every year,
according to SEC research. It's a sure bet that most of us couldn't
say what percentage we pay each year, much less how many dollars
that comes to.
</P>
<P>
   Now we can find out, using an online calculator that makes it
possible to comparison shop in a very confusing area.
</P>
<P>
   To make it work, you type in the sales fees and annual expenses
of a particular mutual fund, the amount you have to invest, how
long you intend to leave it there and what return you expect to
make.
</P>
<P>
   The machine crunches those numbers and spits out a report of how
much it will cost and how much of your money will be left for you
at the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cost calculator takes some of the mystery out of mutual
funds,'' said SEC Chairman Arthur Levitt. ``And it lets investors
see how costs add up in dollars and cents over time.''
</P>
<P>
   The calculator is tucked into the SEC's Internet site at
www.sec.gov/mfcc/mfcc-int.htm. Many local libraries provide
Internet access for those who don't have it on a home or workplace
computer.
</P>
<P>
   You can't expect the calculator to make decisions for you.
Investors must consider many factors besides cost when they pick a
mutual fund. There are the basics of how much risk you can stand
and how long you can leave the money to grow. There are also
specifics, such as how long the fund manager has been around, what
kind of securities he buys, how well they have done and how well
the fund's goals match your own.
</P>
<P>
   But cost always matters. You can get fees and expenses from a
fund's prospectus, which is available to anyone who asks. The
prospectus also gives a standardized example of total costs, but it
is a low-ball figure based on a $1,000 investment and a 5 percent
annual return. With the SEC calculator, you can put in your own
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   There are two ways to compare costs among mutual funds. The
chart illustrates a standardized comparison _ assuming that each
fund gives you the same total return each year. It shows, of
course, that high expenses will bludgeon your total return over a
period of years.
</P>
<P>
   An equally interesting comparison can be made by using actual
past returns of the funds you are studying. The Vanguard Index 500
fund has returned 18.8 percent over the last 10 years. If that
continues for the next 10 years and costs remain the same, your
$10,000 investment would grow to $54,977, after expenses of $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   But the Janus Twenty fund recorded an average annual return of
27.2 percent. At that rate _ if you're willing to assume it will
continue _ you would have $101,197. You would come out ahead, even
though your costs are nearly $9,700, or nearly 10 times higher than
the bite at Vanguard.
</P>
<P>
   Which is better? That's an individual decision. The calculator
gives you valuable information, but it won't take you to a
conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   It has been drawing praise. The Investment Company Institute,
which is the largest trade association for mutual funds, calls it
``a useful tool'' for investors.
</P>
<P>
   Don Phillips, president of fund tracker Morningstar Inc., said
the calculator has the advantage of providing specific numbers for
individual situations. ``If you want to make fees hit home, they've
got to be personal,'' he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Mark J. DiGiovanni, a certified financial planner in Snellville,
Ga., noted that the calculator totes up not just the direct costs
but the impact of diverting some of your dollars from investment to
expenses. ``It's not just the front-end fee; it's the money you
would have made if you had invested that fee,'' DiGiovanni said.
</P>
<P>
   Some people argue that the SEC could do a lot more to protect
investors. Maybe so. But the calculator itself is a step in the
right direction.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Ezell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
