<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 11:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2324 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPIN-CITY12-COX     05-11 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPIN-CITY12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    My night in ``Spin City''
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ I'm cold. I-can't-feel-my-toes cold. It's 5:30 p.m. _
90 minutes before ``Spin City'' begins taping at Manhattan's
Chelsea Piers. I'm standing outside the studio doors with the rest
of tonight's gung-ho audience.
</P>
<P>
   One woman is slurping coffee. Another fur coat-clad lady sways
back and forth, as if that slight motion might warm her bones.
``Spin City's'' set is on the Hudson River. That means tundra-like
winds sting you in the face like invisible needles.
</P>
<P>
   But I don't care. I'm about to check out what's ultimately going
to be a raucous, Friday night taping of one of my favorite shows.
</P>
<P>
   In the episode, deputy mayor Mike (Michael J. Fox) offers to
help bumbling speech writer James (Alexander Chaplin) manage his
money. But Mike's stock market scheme backfires in hilarious ``Spin
City'' fashion. And since this episode will air during the
all-important May sweeps, there has to be a special guest star.
Enter talk show host Jon Stewart, who plays a smarmy stockbroker.
</P>
<P>
   Once inside, I look around. It's a mostly young crowd. I see a
lot of . . . pimples. Many of those young faces, I learn later, are
foreign exchange students from my alma mater, New York University.
There are students from Japan. Singapore. Russia.
</P>
<P>
   We'll be here for a while. ``Spin City'' is only a 30-minute
sitcom, but it'll take nearly five hours to tape. Translation: A
lot of long breaks and waiting around sandwiched between all the
yuks. Here are the more memorable moments:
</P>
<P>
   5:50 p.m.: The studio doors are finally opened. There's not much
relief inside, though. Those cursed air conditioners make it mighty
tough to thaw out.
</P>
<P>
   6:13 p.m.: I finally start to get sensation back in my hands and
toes. I'm relieved: New York City emergency rooms get pretty
crowded on Friday nights. Don't ask how I know this.
</P>
<P>
   6:20 p.m.: Patrick Preblick, ``Spin City's'' perky publicist,
stops over and gives me the 25-cent tour. I see real-life pictures
of Barry Bostwick, who plays dim-bulb Mayor Randall Winston, with
Gerald Ford. Mike's office is decorated with pictures of Napoleon,
former President Jimmy Carter and a New York Mets cap _ with an
upside down NY insignia! Since I'm the biggest Mets fans around, I
have to ask about (ital)that(end ital). ``That's funny,'' says
Preblick, chuckling. ``I'll have to ask someone about that.'' I bet
she never did.
</P>
<P>
   6:57 p.m.: For the people who have no idea what ``Spin City'''s
about, ABC shows a clip reel and brief interviews with the show's
stars.
</P>
<P>
   7:05 p.m.: Mike Royce, the show's warm-up comic, makes his
entrance. I like him immediately. He asks each foreign student to
stand up and tell the audience where they're from. A guy from
Denmark is one of the first to stand. He's big and has a deep
voice. Says Royce: ``You sound like the Danish Terminator and I'm
afraid of you.''
</P>
<P>
   7:25 p.m.: The cast is introduced. All of them run out like
college football players before a big bowl game. I must say, I'm
looking for the curvy Jennifer Esposito, who plays the curvy Stacy.
Afterward, Royce tells us what's going to happen next. ``The lights
are going to go down and we will all touch each other
inappropriately.'' I laugh hard _ and so does everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   7:32 p.m.: Mike, James, Carter (Michael Boatman) and Stu (Alan
Ruck) are playing poker at James' house. Boatman is the first to
flub a line. ``You suck,'' Fox yells to a smiling Boatman. ``He's
got guests in the audience. His mom is here, so there's no real
pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   8:32 p.m.: ABC passes out raisins and water. What a gyp! We all
growl. ``Hey,'' shouts Royce, ``there's no finer raisin than the
Shop-Rite raisin. Eat them slow.''
</P>
<P>
   8:38 p.m.: In one of the show's funnier scenes, Stu checks out
the new Randall Winston action figure, a rather well-endowed doll.
Mayor Winston to girlfriend Janelle (Victoria Dillard): ``Are we
still on for tonight?''
</P>
<P>
   Janelle, after checking out the well-endowed doll: ``You better
believe it!''
</P>
<P>
   8:50 p.m.: The crowd is getting restless. Too many breaks
between scenes. Some audience members are getting creative with
those raisin boxes. ``Don't turn those raisin boxes into make-shift
harmonicas,'' Royce warns.
</P>
<P>
   9:01 p.m.: Tom Hertz, a ``Spin City'' writer, takes his turn
entertaining the crowd with jokes about marriage, breast implants
and sex. ``You know that smacking sound you hear during sex? I
pretend I'm getting applause.''
</P>
<P>
   9:12 p.m.: Royce has too much time on his hands, so he starts
bad-mouthing talk show host Maury Povich, his former employer.
``He's the crankiest host in the business,'' Royce sniffs. ``I
don't want to say anything bad about the networks, though, because
I want to work for one. If someone's out there from PAX TV, I'll
change religions.'' I'd call Bud Paxson, but I don't have a cell
phone.
</P>
<P>
   9:43 p.m.: It's getting late. Royce senses this, so he asks
people to come down to do impressions and goofy acts. This is New
York, so people are more than happy to oblige. One high school kid
does a creepy Mister Rogers bit. We keep an eye on him the rest of
the night.
</P>
<P>
   9:57 p.m.: Stewart makes his entrance and gets a loud ovation.
Two minutes later, Fox forgets Stewart's character's name.
</P>
<P>
   10:07 p.m.: More down time. The Gong Show-like acts continue.
One man does a ventriloquist bit. Another performs a mean Donald
Duck impression. ``I'm both frightened and enlightened,'' cracks
Royce.
</P>
<P>
   10:13 p.m.: It's attack New York time. Someone wants to know if
New York has ATMs in the subways. ``Yeah, we have cash machines in
New York subways,'' Royce says. ``They're called tourists.''
</P>
<P>
   10:30 p.m.: Everyone's messing up their lines now. ``You're
horrible, Richard,'' yells Richard Kind, who plays the mayor's
press secretary, at himself after a goof. ``I suck,'' screams
Dillard after her flub.
</P>
<P>
   10:37 p.m.: Fox joins the audience _ it's the night's high
point. ``Save me a box of those raisins!'' The weary crowd is
thrilled. They ask Fox about Back to the Future, Teen Wolf and
supermodel Heidi Klum. ``Yeah, Heidi's doing a two-part episode,''
he says. ``My wife cut her vacation short.''
</P>
<P>
   10:42 p.m.: Fox continues to work the room like a skilled
politician. The Canada native remembers his first U.S. job. It was
Midnight Madness, a film with David Naughton. ``He was the Dr.
Pepper guy. It was like the Beatles, man.'' Fox then tells the
crowd about the great job he's got. ``I mean, there are guys in
Kentucky who go into the ground and take out bits of rock and bring
them out. I'd rather be here, than there. You look at New York, and
there are all kinds of folks with squeegees, and stuff, and you
just go, `Yeah, I'm doin' OK.' ''
</P>
<P>
   11:10 p.m.: A mugging Boatman joins the crowd and floors us with
his dead-on impression of William Shatner singing The Way We Were.
</P>
<P>
   11:24 p.m.: An audience member does her best imitation of a
siren _ with her neck! No, I can't explain.
</P>
<P>
   11:37 p.m.: It's finally over _ nearly five hours later. The
cast runs out to a thunderous applause. It was a fun night _
raisins, ventriloquism, strangeness.
</P>
<P>
   It was sort of like The Jerry Springer Show _ without the
fistfights.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin D. Thompson writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
