<P>
   These columns for release Wednesday, May 12, 1999 are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ An admired movie actor, aging but still a
commanding presence, addresses the annual meeting of the National
Poison Association, of which he is president. (Tom Teepen is
national correspondent for Cox Newspapers.) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ Cox News Service columnist Howard Kleinberg
is on vacation. His column will resume May 24 for publication May
26.
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ Dispatches from Dreamsville: One by one each
morning the neighborhood kids joined the brigade traipsing off to
our Porterdale School in that Georgia mill town. Our teachers loved
us and believed in us. We respected and loved them also. (Hardman,
Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES _ George Leigh Mallory was in fairly good
shape, considering, when they found him a few days ago sealed in
ice to the face of Mount Everest since 1924. There is still no
answer to the question of why humans do such things, no answer even
as to why they look for bodies at 27,000 feet. I once knew, but I
forgot. (Rosenfeld, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ When I was a kid, the attic
in our old house filled me with mixed emotions. In the daylight it
was a place to search for musty treasures, but after dark it became
an imagined chamber of horrors to be avoided at all costs. Don't
get me wrong, I'm not a hard-line attic hater. Attics are really
good things to have _ and the bigger the better because everybody
needs a place to shove stuff that's just too ugly to live
downstairs with the family but impossible to throw out because your
mother-in-law gave it to you and you'll need it for her next visit.
(Schuett, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ Texas lawmakers would never
dispense preferential treatment to anyone _ that is, anyone who is
without a smokestack to his name. If you have one, and if you
planted it on the prairie before 1971, you'll be treated
preferentially. Outrage, please. Or, maybe you think some pollution
is more equal than others. (Young, Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
