<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-HEPATITIS-C _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Acting as the
nation's ever-cautious school nurse, the CDC has labeled hepatitis
C ``an emerging chronic disease of great public health concern.''
This month's Redbook magazine calls it ``the next deadly
epidemic.'' Last month's New York magazine wondered if it was ``the
new AIDS.'' TV's ER and L.A. Doctors have climbed aboard with
hepatitis C storylines. But how worried should Baby Boomers really
be? Experts say hepatitis C is less an epidemic than ``an epidemic
of discovery,'' says Dr. Leonard B. Seeff of the National Health
Institute. People infected 20 or 30 years ago are now discovering
they may have a problem. And, With the hepatitis C hysteria comes
another similarity to the dark days of AIDS _ shame. (Lomartire,
Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   HEPATITIS-EXPLAINER _ Q &AMP; A on hepatitis C and other strains of
the hepatitis viruses. ALSO MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MATERNITY-CLOTHES _ WACO, Texas _ Comfort. Comfort. Comfort.
That one small word means the world to mothers-to-be when it comes
to surviving the warm-weather months of their pregnancy. (Mays,
Waco Tribune-Herald). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   PERSONAL FINANCE
</P>
<P>
   MONEYTALK _ Let's give a cheer for the Securities and Exchange
Commission: It has put together a gadget that will help individual
investors estimate, fairly closely, how much it actually costs to
invest in a particular mutual fund. That's no small thing. Most
investors don't know that their money pays the ongoing expenses of
their mutual funds every year, according to SEC research. It's a
sure bet that most of us couldn't say what percentage we pay each
year, much less how many dollars that comes to. Now we can find
out, using an online calculator that makes it possible to
comparison shop in a very confusing area. (Ezell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
