<HEADER>
A2366 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     05-11 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Tuesday, May 11, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Wednesday.
If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RURAL-AIDS (New Braunfels, Texas) _ Robert Konkel has seen both
sides of life as an AIDS patient in a small town. He's felt the
cold sting of discrimination and fear. He's also seen the good side
of small-town life, with strangers volunteering to drive him to
medical appointments and a church he'd never attended raising
$6,000 to help pay for his medication. By ROGER CROTEAU. (Photo
available on Wieck database.)
</P>
<P>
   LYME-DISEASE (Albany, N.Y.) _ LYMErix is the only pharmaceutical
defense to date against Lyme disease infection, and there's a lot
of confusion about who should get the vaccine. Specialists advise
those exposed to tick hot-spots in the Northeast may want to
consider the vaccine. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   DOMESTIC-PARTNERS (Sacramento, Calif.) _ The California state
Legislature has quietly granted domestic partnership health
benefits to employees who work in the Capitol and district offices
across the state, prompting Republican lawmakers to demand a
hearing on the matter. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   SPY-LAWSUIT (San Francisco) _ Ending a bizarre police spy
scandal, a lawsuit that charged San Francisco and the
Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith with illegally spying on
Arab Americans and a panoply of political protesters is near final
settlement. By SETH ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   PEDESTRIAN-SAFETY (San Francisco) _ Responding to a record high
number of pedestrian fatalities in the city last year, Supervisor
Mabel Teng wants to give people more time to cross the street. By
RACHEL GORDON.
</P>
<P>
   MOTHERS-GUNS (San Francisco) _ A soon-to-be-unveiled national
organization is aiming to do for gun control what Mothers Against
Drunk Driving did for alcohol policy: turn anguished victims into
fiery catalysts for change. By VICKI HADDOCK.
</P>
<P>
   PROSECUTOR-SENTENCED (Laredo, Texas) _ A federal judge scolded a
former state prosecutor here and sentenced him to five years in
prison for selling leniency to drug defendants in what the
government described as ``pervasive corruption'' in the Webb County
district attorney's office. By DANE SCHILLER.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DEATH-STUDIES (Albany, N.Y.) _ Should teachers study death to
help students cope in the age of video games? Two professors at the
College of Saint Rose in Albany so they should. Donna Burns and
colleague Donna Reittinger are combining their expertise in
education and psychology to teach the teachers of tomorrow about
death and loss, and how to cope with both in the classroom. By
ANDREW BROWNSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   PORCH-SWINGS (Albany, N.Y.) _ We just never seem to outgrow some
things, and one of them is porch swings. They are making a big
comeback, now that porches are back in style. By FRANCES INGRAHAM.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-SUMMER (Undated) _ A roundup of the summer's top 10
events in the United States, including the opening of Universal's
Islands of Adventure in Orlando, Fla; the Bumbershoot in Seattle;
Cuisines of the Sun in Hawaii; the Spoleto Festival in North
Carolina; Elvis Week in Memphis; the New Orleans Wine &AMP; Food
Experience; and the Rose Festival in Portland, Ore. By SYD KEARNY.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BBA-A'S-OWNERSHIP (Oakland, Calif.) _ The jockeying over who
will own the Oakland A's now moves to Major League Baseball
officials in New York, as city and county officials strongly back a
local group to take over the baseball team. By ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-RICKY-MARTIN (Undated) _ The only thing that's as hot as
``Star Wars'' right now is Latin music star Ricky Martin, whose
English-language CD hits stores this week. By JOEY GUERRA
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-MYSTERIES-REVIEW (Undated) _ Fans of Stephen Hunter's
series featuring sniper Bob Lee Swagger will not be disappointed by
``Time to Hunt.'' In the spring of 1971 as Vietnam War protesters
overrun Washington, D.C., Cpl. Donny Feen, 22, is stationed at the
Marine Barracks at 8th and I streets SE. With only 13 months left
to serve, Donny is a short-timer and unlikely to be sent back to
the Land of Bad Things, as the Marines call Nam. By BOBBIE HESS.
</P>
<P>
   JEDI-JUNKIE (San Francisco) _ As far back as I can remember,
I've always wanted to be a Jedi. To me, being a Jedi was better
than being Superman. Sure, he could fly, bend steel, see through
walls, and carry a tanker on his back. His body bulged out of his
blue jumpsuit and his red cape waved around him like an American
flag. But the Jedi were cooler. By JASON LLOREN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Rashad L. Williams, a 15-year-old
freshman at San Francisco's Archbishop Riordan High School, is
running the Bay to Breakers on Sunday to raise money for Lance
Kirklin, one of the students who was severely wounded in the
massacre at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (Las Vegas, Nev.) _ Although I tried very hard to
dislike the Bellagio Gallery of Fine Art _ I mean, really, van Gogh
and Picasso under the same roof with SLOT MACHINES? _ I failed.
Somewhere among the 20 paintings, perhaps in front of Jackson
Pollack's FRIEZE, I had to put down my snobby 'tude and admit that
I was having a good time. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   CHILD-SOLDIERS (Los Angeles) _ It would be comforting to think
that the horrifying combination of children, guns and violence in
Littleton, Colo., is an anomaly, but unfortunately, it is not. At
least 300,000 children under the age of 18 _ some as young as 8 _
serve in government armies or rebel groups in Afghanistan, Angola,
Colombia, Sierra Leone, Sri Lanka and other conflicts around the
world. By DANIEL WEISS AND EMMA CHERNIAVSKY.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
