A2402 &Cx1f; kan-z
r v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BC-KAN-BUDGET-KAN &LR;      05-11 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-KAN-BUDGET-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of
Wednesday, May 12. If you have any questions, please call The
Star's News Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   FUEL: More bad news for regional transportation planners who
pinned their hopes for improving Kansas City's air quality on
reformulated gasoline (RFG). First, it was revealed that RFG, when
it leaks, is a worse groundwater polluter than standard gasoline.
Now, a new federal study indicates that RFG fails in its primary
mission, reducing ozone pollution. We find out the impact of all
this on regional highway planning _ already in trouble over the RFG
issue. Michael Mansur. 25.
</P>
<P>
   CIG: Closing arguments likely today and perhaps a verdict in the
cigarette smoking trial. The family of a Vandalia man claim the
Kool cigarettes he smoked gave him cancer and killed him. They say
the Brown &AMP; Williamson Co. knew the dangers of their product. The
tobacco maker says yes, cigarettes are dangerous and the victim
accepted the risk by ignoring warnings. The family is asking for
$25 million. It's the first cigarette case in Kansas City in recent
memory. Mark Morris. 20.
</P>
<P>
   WATCH: A new program offers protection and peace of mind for
elderly or disabled Kansas City residents. The Senior Watch Program
started in January in the police department's East Patrol Division,
but could spread to the rest of the city. Program members provide
police with their phone number, medical history, family contacts
and the name of someone nearby who can let police into their home
in an emergency. The information is entered into a computer, and
accessed only by the police. Since January, 280 people have joined
the program. Malcolm Garcia. 16. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   MONTI. Verdict in the murder case of Rodney Wayne Henry, accused
in the death of Pennsylvania residents Claire-Marie Monti. Richard
Espinoza.
</P>
<P>
   ABORT: Infanticide bill gets final approval in the Missouri
Senate and heads to the governor's desk, where the governor has
said he'll veto it. Legislature has enough votes for override _ the
question is whether they'll do it this week or wait until a
September veto session. Will Sentell. 18 inches.
</P>
<P>
   MCARE: A federal panel meets Wednesday to set the benefits that
50,000 Kansas City area Medicare members will get from their health
maintenance organizations next year. The panel is guiding a pilot
project in Kansas City (the first in the nation) to have HMOs bid
competitively for Medicare business. We take an early look at the
proposed benefits package for 2000: It includes better vision,
hearing and dental coverage, but slightly higher costs for doctor
visits and brand-name prescription drugs. Alan Bavley. 35.
</P>
<P>
   SHERIFF. Judge rules in case that caused uproar in Shawnee
County Sheriff's Department, where the sheriff is under fire for
alleging coverup drug use by a deputy; judge finds that a defendant
should go free because of a massive conspiracy in the handling of
drug case evidence; there are 106 other drug defendants who could
file similar appeals. John L. Petterson.
</P>
<P>
   TEC _ The Executive Council is an organization for CEOs of
mid-sized businesses to get together once a month in small groups
and share lessons, advice and encouragement from the trenches.
Several Kansas City groups are active. By Diane Stafford. Photo
</P>
<P>
   UTIL _ UtiliCorp United, in its second big merger move in a
month, plans to buy Empire District Electric Co. for about $800
million. By Steve Everly. Graphic
</P>
<P>
   BAKE _ Interstate Bakeries didn't do everything it was supposed
to do when it acquired Continental Grain, Dept. of Justice says.
Jennifer Mann
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-99 1232EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
