<HEADER>
A2446 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILLENNIUM-WOMEN-ADVI     05-11 1474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-WOMEN-ADVISORY-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the last 1,000 years, the lives of men have changed somewhat
-- but it's clear that the real revolution has been in the lives of
women.
</P>
<P>
   Read all about it in the following articles from ``Women: A
1,000-Year Journey,'' the second of six special issues, to be
published by The New York Times Magazine. Available from The New
York Times Syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   These features, which are for release May 16 or thereafter, will
move on the wire starting Fri., May 14. Many feature LOCAL ANGLE
boxes. For rates on one-shots, ``partnerships'' and packages of
three or six articles per issue, please contact your New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, listed at the end of this advisory.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE FOLLOWING SPECIAL PACKAGE of three articles will move on
May 16 FREE to Centerpiece clients. To become a subscriber, please
contact your sales rep for details. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ---
 &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-WOMEN-GLACIER &LR;  -- Our great-great-grandmothers waited
a lifetime for the social glacier to creak forward an inch. But
today a woman can wake up one morning and find that yesterday's
social reality has vanished overnight. 2,300 words. By Gail
Collins, a member of The New York Times editorial board.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-WOMEN-BABIES &LR;  -- Every day technology offers more
choices to more people for how and where to bear children _ along
with a tormenting array of new moral dilemmas. 3,500 words. By
Natalie Angier, who writes about biology for The New York Times and
is the author of ``Woman: An Intimate Geography.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-WOMEN-FICTION &LR;  -- Perhaps it's about ``male
liberation.'' Perhaps it's about admiration for female relatives.
It's not easy for a man to write in the character of a woman, but
if he cares to try, the effort can be a key to terrific story
telling. 1,800 words. By Jim Harrison, who wrote ``Dalva,'' ``The
Road Home'' and other books.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE 3 FEATURES ABOVE, in addition to the following 4 pieces of
ARTWORK and 3 ARTICLES BELOW, may be published by special
Millennium Series package clients. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ----
 &UR; MAPPING the MILLENNIUM: ``Interior Territory'' &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Ranging from the 13th to the late 20th centuries, these images
of the interior of the female body display a century's advance in
technology. Yet in terms of truth, the recent digital cross-section
is as cold and inhuman and soulless as the medieval pre-dissection
diagram.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Artwork availability: 35mm color slides or electronic
transmission (via E-MAIL, NEWSCOM or WIECK photo database) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1.) ''Anatomical Diagram from an English medical text shows a
woman's reproductive system, circa 1292.''
 &UR; CREDIT: Courtesy of the Bodleian Library, Oxford, England.
</P>
<P>
   2.) Illustration by Giulio Casserio, 1627, from ``Tabulae
Anatomicae.''
 &UR; CREDIT: Courtesy of the New York Academy of Medicine Library.
</P>
<P>
   3.) Twin diagram of the female body, with pull-out flaps, from
the home reference book, ``The Science of Eugenics and Sex-Life,
Love, Marriage, Maternity,'' 1930.
 &UR; CREDIT: Courtesy of David Brown Collection, New York.
</P>
<P>
   4.) A cross-sectional view of the Visible Human Female, 1999.
This virtual 3-D map of the female body comprises 5,000 images of a
cadaver; creating it required a database of almost 40 gigabytes.
 &UR; CREDIT: Courtesy of the Center for Human Simulation, which is
located at the University of Colorado and operates under the
auspices of the National Library of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-WOMEN-TIMELINE &LR;  -- Written mostly by men, traditional
histories of the last 1,000 years all tend to sell women short.
This article tells the rest of the story. 3,400 words. By Natalie
Zemon Davis, a former history professor at Princeton University and
the author of ``The Return of Martin Guerre,'' and Jill Ker Conway,
a former Smith College president.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-WOMEN-FUTURE &LR;  -- Today's twenty- and thirtysomethings
were born after the ``bad old days.'' But without a historical
awareness, they are vulnerable to sliding back into that dreamy,
dependent state of Women's Time, when relying on cleavage and
astrology was a means to personal definition. 1,600 words. By Naomi
Wolf, author of ``The Beauty Myth'' and ``Promiscuities.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-WOMEN-SAINTS &LR;  -- To gain special favor and appeal in
the public eye, or to be regarded as a holy creature, why must a
woman be able to endure public humiliation, self-abuse, pain and
suffering? This is one thing that hasn't changed in a century.
3,600 words. By Jennifer Egan, a novelist and a regular contributor
to The New York Times Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The following articles are available for purchase as ONE-SHOT
features. They are FREE to subscribers to the Millennium Plus
partnership package. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ---
 &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-WOMEN-LUST &LR;  -- From St. Thomas Aquinas' 13th-century
pronouncement, ``Woman is defective and misbegotten,'' to Shere
Hite's 1976 eye-opener, ``Men make their own orgasms during sex;
women should be able to as well,'' views on female sexuality, from
the heinous to the weird, have reflected each era's own morality,
science and religious thought. 1,300 words. Quotations selected by
Camille Sweeney, a project editor for The New York Times Magazine's
millennium issues.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-WOMEN-CHINA &LR;  -- In the old China, women had their
feet bound; they often had no first names and they killed
themselves when their husbands died. It was only in the last
century that the women's revolution came to China. 2,400 words. By
Sheryl WuDunn, a Tokyo-based correspondent for The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-WOMEN-PROFILES &LR;  -- Sometimes a woman has to say
``no'' to make her mark. Here is a gallery of such troublemakers,
zealots and doers. They include Lady Godiva, Hildegard of Bingen,
Ida Tarbell, Margaret Thatcher and Daw Aung San Suu Kyi. 13
profiles of about 200 words each. By authors including James Atlas,
Margo Jefferson, Phillip Lopate and Linda Nochlin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-WOMEN-ETIQUETTE &LR;  -- Betty Crocker, Fannie Farmer,
Martha Stewart: All our kindly, bossy advice-givers, real and
invented, trace their lineage to Mrs. Isabella Beeton, whose
``Beeton's Book of Household Management'' very properly instructed
ladies on when to pay the servants, what color lace to wear and how
to pick a breed of pig. 900 words. By novelist Margaret Atwood.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-WOMEN-ART &LR;  -- Funny how men's pictures of women
differ from women's pictures of women. After centuries of
conforming to men's views and stereotypes, female artists are
taking control of their own images. 1,200 words. By Holland Cotter,
an art critic for The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-WOMEN-LANGUAGE &LR;  -- Ought one utter the pithy
phrase,``but the era of every man for himself must never begin,''
and risk insulting all the women in the audience? Or ought one
change it to the murkier ``but we cannot go back to the time when
our citizens were left to fend for themselves,'' and hold the ears
of both genders? 1,000 words. By veteran New York Times columnist
William Safire.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-WOMEN-ECONOMICS &LR;  -- A panel of experts looks at
women's economic power and concludes that, yes, men are doing a
lot, but women's economic progress may be the hottest news in the
global free market. 3,200 words. Moderated by economist Michael
Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-WOMEN-CYBERSPACE &LR;  -- It may take cyberspace, where a
string of words can arrive free of the sender's face or name or
gender, to create a climate in which men will listen when women
speak up. 1,100 words. By the Information Age guru, Esther Dyson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-WOMEN-KIDS &LR;  -- Today's kids voice their views on
subjects such as women in charge; women acting like men; the
possibilties of a woman president and of men having babies. 2,700
words. Conversations gathered and edited by New York free-lance
writer Kim France.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-WOMEN-LISTEN &LR;  -- In ``Beowulf,'' the 8th-century
Anglo-Saxon saga, the hero recounts his manly feats to win the love
of Wealhtheow, queen of Hrothgar, who is serving beer to a
gathering of men. Sound familiar? Walk through any restaurant today
and hear the chatter of boastful men striving to impress the
(silent) woman of the hour. 1,500 words. By linguistics professor
Deborah Tannen.
</P>
<P>
   ......................................................
</P>
<P>
   (--U.S. and Canada: BOB FARNELL at 1-800-535-4425; fax,
717-646-4850. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Thank you very much.
</P>
