string of words can arrive free of the sender's face or name or
gender, to create a climate in which men will listen when women
speak up. 1,100 words. By the Information Age guru, Esther Dyson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-WOMEN-KIDS &LR;  -- Today's kids voice their views on
subjects such as women in charge; women acting like men; the
possibilties of a woman president and of men having babies. 2,700
words. Conversations gathered and edited by New York free-lance
writer Kim France.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-MILLENNIUM-WOMEN-LISTEN &LR;  -- In ``Beowulf,'' the 8th-century
Anglo-Saxon saga, the hero recounts his manly feats to win the love
of Wealhtheow, queen of Hrothgar, who is serving beer to a
gathering of men. Sound familiar? Walk through any restaurant today
and hear the chatter of boastful men striving to impress the
(silent) woman of the hour. 1,500 words. By linguistics professor
Deborah Tannen.
</P>
