<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990511.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2470 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORGES-BATS-TEXAS-NYT     05-11 1395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORGES-BATS-TEXAS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 BORGES in AUSTIN, TEXAS  
 &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.)  By TOMAS ELOY MARTINEZ  
 c.1999 New York Times Special Features  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are men who are similar to cities; like Baudelaire and
Marcel Proust to Paris, or Charles Dickens to London; there are
cities that really do exist, but which are, above all, literary
cities such as the Dublin that James Joyce narrated in ``Ulysses.''
</P>
<P>
   And there are countries that can be reflected in cities which at
first sight have nothing to do with them. You place the city in
front of a mirror and suddenly the country just appears. That's
what happens with Austin, the capital of Texas. In a secret,
subliminal sort of way, that city is Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   The similarity probably began in September 1961, when Jorge Luis
Borges was invited by the University of Texas to give a poetry
seminar.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Buenos Aires in 1899, Borges found Austin in the
pre-high-tech industry days. The city had a pleasant atmosphere and
its most prominent architectural structure was probably the (now
restored) provincial Capitol Building dome. Borges was surprised by
the vast prairies that smelled of siestas and grilled meat, the
puddles, the stray dogs, all of which he thought inappropriate for
what he had imagined to be the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he thought it strange that butchers and trench diggers
knew how to speak English. ``I always,'' he tells us in his
autobiography, ``thought that English was a language denied to that
class of people.''
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoons, students would see him walking on Guadalupe
Street, arm in arm with a haughty woman, thought to be his wife:
``Mrs. Borges.'' Actually she was his widowed mother, Leonor
Acevedo, who at age 85 looked 60. As Borges became progressively
blind in his later years, she was frequently his travel companion
and read to him aloud.
</P>
<P>
   One employee at the Benson Library, amid the rare books, says
she still remembers them immersed in reading Alfonso Reyes' and
Atilio Chiappori's manuscripts. ``She,'' the librarian states,
``would help him with the reading, whispering at his ear in a very
hushed tone.''
</P>
<P>
   Borges' mom surpassed him in agility, energy and passion for
life. One morning they stopped at the library windows and observed
some original editions of Sor Juana Ines de la Cruz, the fiery
17th-century Mexican poet, along with her handwritten documents.
The mother stubbornly insisted on taking a closer look. Sor Juana,
revered as a feminist, had chosen for 30 years to be a nun, the
only station in which a woman then was allowed to read and write.
</P>
<P>
   The manuscript, partially blurred and discolored, was a page
torn out of a book of confessions of the Convent of San Jeronimo,
in which Sor Juana asks forgiveness for her sins and signs in
blood: ``I, the worst in this world.''
</P>
<P>
   Pointing out that the blood strokes had almost vanished with the
passage of time, while the rest of the writing remained intact,
Borges' mother later observed: ``This definitely proves what
`Georgie' always said. Blood is thinner than ink.''
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving Austin, Borges had managed to scandalize a group
of American admirers with an array of politically incorrect
opinions _ on blacks, Texas music (a mix of ``country'' and
``mariachi'') and the usurpation of Mexican lands by Texas and
California, which he considered a blessing.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't there for the arrival of the bats. Austin is traversed
by the lazy Colorado River, which flows southward into the Gulf of
Mexico. The swampy surrounding lands were perfect breeding grounds
for mosquitoes. About 100,000 bats had migrated from Mexico and
settled under the Congress Avenue Bridge, whose concrete rafters
formed recesses like the niches of a honeycomb. When the cold
season came, the bats left, but they returned the following May,
reaching more than 200,000-strong, and because the females were
impregnated, the population soon doubled.
</P>
<P>
   By now the bats have become Austin's symbol; each day they
devour tons of mosquitoes and keep the air clean. At night, when
one nears the bridge, the harsh smell of the bat colonies clustered
there and their incessant shrieks are enough to drill through your
senses and your brain.
</P>
<P>
   A local group, Friends of the Bats, recently tried with no luck
to acquire manuscripts in which Borges wrote about Austin to
anthologize for this year's celebration of the Borges' centennial.
</P>
<P>
   Recently I attended one of the university's anniversary
celebrations. I was escorted to the modest student residence where
Borges first roamed as well as to the proud Victorian hotel where
he lodged later. My guide was another survivor of those times,
Professor Carter Wheelock, whose Spanish was so clear and
unadulterated that nobody would guess he had learned it.
</P>
<P>
   Wheelock also has a Borgean memory: He can recite 3,183 verses
from Beowolf, the famous Anglo-Saxon poem, with the same courteous,
unassuming intonation that he picked up from Borges decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   The professor told me that Borges and his mother arrived in
Austin on Sept. 7, 1961, on a plane from Miami. Six or seven
colleagues had gone to meet him, but Borges was not there. Five
days later, when they were just about to file a police missing
person's report, Borges and his mother arrived at the university,
elated. They had decided to take a bus trip through the Deep South:
Tallahassee, Biloxi, New Orleans, Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Borges,'' Wheelock continued, ``wanted to smell what he
couldn't see.''
</P>
<P>
   In the prairies of Austin, where almost nothing ever occurs,
everything seemed to happen to Borges. In July 1966, a bit before
one of his trips, a mentally disturbed college junior named Charles
Whitman, 24, had killed his wife and mother and then secured
himself, with a cache of rifles and shotguns, in the 27-story
university clocktower. For an hour, he shot at passers-by.
</P>
<P>
   A precise, telescopic police sniper eventually took Whitman out,
but not before he had hit 46 people and killed 16. When Borges
returned the following spring, on his way from Harvard, he asked
Wheelock to take him to the tower and show him where Whitman had
died. They climbed 27 floors and came to the small wooden balcony,
where the shadow of blood still remained.
</P>
<P>
   Borges bent over, just like his character in ``The Aleph,'' and
remained silent for several long minutes, his imagination fixed on
some spot in the universe _ ``a point which only he could see,'' as
Wheelock puts it _ and then asked to be helped down.
</P>
<P>
   On the descent, which was slower than the climb up, Borges said
nothing. He didn't speak for the entire afternoon, night or the
next day _ Borges, whose fiction was so well able to encapsulate
tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   A country is not only its geography and history, or its everyday
tragedies and celebrations; a country is not only its politicians.
It is also (and sometimes above all), its memory. Santiago de Chile
was the Argentina of 1845, when Sarmiento was there and wrote
``Facundo''; and Paris was the Argentina of 1962, when Cortazar
wrote ``Facundo''; and Paris was the Argentina of 1962, when
Cortazar wrote ``Rayuela'' on the same sheets of paper that are now
in the Benson Library.
</P>
<P>
   Austin is also Argentina, yesterday and today; you can still see
Borges on Guadelupe Street, taking a stroll with his blind-man's
walking stick and reciting Beowulf, while the newly arrived
immigrants dig ditches, except that now they no longer speak
English. The language they speak is a Spanish that Borges may not
even understand.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Tomas Eloy Martinez is the distinguished author of ``The Peron
Novel'' and ``Santa Evita.'' He is chairman of the Latin American
studies department at Rutgers University and travels widely as an
editor and journalist.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ---------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
