<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS IT DOLLY OR IS IT ... ?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Has Dolly Parton ever had breast implant surgery?
</P>
<P>
   _ C.L., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: Parton, who told a Baltimore Sun reporter in 1994 that she
was ``totally artificial in looks,'' addresses the subject in her
autobiography, ``Dolly: My Life and Other Unfinished Business.''
</P>
<P>
   The 53-year-old singer thanks Dr. Frank Kramer for work done to
her face, Dr. John Grossman for her body, and four other doctors
for various Parton parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's just say that some of Dr. Grossman's work has been very
uplifting,'' Parton wrote.
</P>
<P>
   She told USA Today in 1994 that she wasn't concerned about
health issues regarding her implants. ``I've never had any
problems,'' she said. ``I've had mine done so long, I would have
known by now.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans can write to Parton in care of International Creative
Management, 8942 Wilshire Blvd., Beverly Hills, CA 90211.
</P>
<P>
   Q: There used to be a beverage out called Kickapoo Joy Juice.
Who bottled it, and is there any still around?
</P>
<P>
   _ J.R., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: Kickapoo Joy Juice is being sold today only in Malaysia,
Singapore, Thailand and other Asian countries, according to the
company that produces it.
</P>
<P>
   The Monarch Co. in Atlanta, which also makes Dad's Root Beer,
has not sold the citrus-flavored soda in the United States for many
years.
</P>
<P>
   Kickapoo Joy Juice is one of several products based on Al Capp's
comic strip Li'l Abner, which appeared in newspapers from 1934 to
1977.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, there's no way to special-order the drink. To contact
the company, write to Jim Harford, Monarch Co., 1100 Johnson Ferry
Road, Atlanta 30342.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I write to Leon Metz of the History Channel?
</P>
<P>
   _ J.D., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to Metz in care of Bill Newkirk, 15315 Fairwood Court,
El Paso 79927, or visit www.leonmetz.com.
</P>
<P>
   Metz, an El Paso historian, author and lecturer, has written 15
books about Texas and the Old West, including ``John Wesley Hardin:
Dark Angel of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   He has contributed to several historical shows on cable,
including ``Gunfighters of the West'' for The Learning Channel and
``Real West'' on A&AMP;E.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-99 1334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
