<DOCNO> NYT19990511.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2488 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHAPMAN-TEXASATLARGE-     05-11 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAPMAN-TEXASATLARGE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISTORIANS DIG FOR ARTIFACTS OF TEXAS INDIAN WARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the mid-1870s, long after Texas claimed its independence from
Mexico and the United States settled the Civil War, North Texans
were still brawling with the Plains Indians over exactly who owned
the land.
</P>
<P>
   The battles, probably more than 20 in all, were called the Red
River War, and they ranged from the summer of 1874 into early 1875.
</P>
<P>
   Now, because of more than $100,000 in new grants, the Texas
Historical Commission is setting out to detail that war by locating
the battle sites, generating site records and maps, nominating
sites to the National Register of Historic Places, and working with
area museums to exhibit findings.
</P>
<P>
   There won't be any Alamos discovered or monuments built. This
war was carried on out of sight of most Texans, and it took place
in wide open spaces where cattle still graze.
</P>
<P>
   That presents a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those old battle sites are on private land, ranches
where the owners aren't always fond of strangers digging around in
their pastures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing we're doing now is trying to provide the land
owners with assurances that their property rights are in no way
imperiled,'' said Pat Mercado-Allinger of the commission's
archaeology division.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are telling them we are simply interested in looking at
what is remaining from these battles. We want the land owners to
play a part in preserving this important history.''
</P>
<P>
   The battlegrounds range across the Texas Panhandle, including
Hutchinson, Armstrong, Briscoe, Gray and Hemphill counties. One
important goal of the study will be to increase tourism is those
areas. The commission is already receiving support from the
Panhandle Tourism and Marketing Council, a group including everyone
from the Panhandle Plains Historical Museum in Canyon, to several
area dude ranches.
</P>
<P>
   The plan includes splitting up any artifacts discovered among
many of the local museums, so each has something different to
offer. But there are a couple of hitches.
</P>
<P>
   The first is finding any artifacts; and the second is getting
the landowners' permission to remove them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The materials do belong to them,'' Mercado-Allinger said of
the property owners. ``We would assume custody on a temporary basis
_ for study _ but the artifacts do belong to them.''
</P>
<P>
   She also said the commission is deeply interested in getting the
American Indian take on the battles. That will require cooperation
from several tribes. The Red River War was waged against the
Comanche, Kiowa, Southern Cheyenne and Southern Arapaho.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be starting that shortly,'' she said of
collecting the American Indian perspective. ``I'll be going to
Oklahoma to meet with the various tribes.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercado-Allinger said she would also be looking for information
from the Tonkawa and Delawares, who served as scouts for the
federal troops. So did the Seminole and Lipan Apache.
</P>
<P>
   Military columns converged on the tribes from several locations.
They came from Fort Sill, Okla.; Fort Union, N.M.; Fort Dodge,
Kan., as well as Fort Concho and Fort Richardson in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly column on things Texan. You can
call him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail: Artc(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
