<HEADLINE>
LIME DISEASE VACCINE MAY NOT BE FOR EVERYONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ You're not a hunter or a fisherman but you mow
the lawn, hike occasionally and play in the back yard with the kids
and dog.
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean you should get the new vaccine against Lyme
disease, a potentially serious tick-borne illness that's spreading
throughout the Northeast, especially in New York and Connecticut?
</P>
<P>
   ``There really are no set guidelines,'' said Dr. Kris Saririan,
an allergist and immunologist in Latham, N.Y. ``You really should
individualize each case.''
</P>
<P>
   Health experts aren't dodging when they say they can't give a
one-size-fits all answer about LYMErix, the vaccine that went on
the market earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   It is the only pharmaceutical defense to date against Lyme
disease infection, and there's a lot of confusion about who should
get LYMErix.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very personal, individual decision people should
make,'' said Dr. Barbara Wallace, director of the Bureau of
Communicable Disease Control for the New York Health Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's somebody's activities, where they do those activities and
the type of precautions they'll be taking,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, if you're living in or planning to spend significant
time in a tick hot-spot, like Long Island or the lower Hudson
Valley, the decision is easier. Those areas accounted for most of
New York's 4,409 cases of Lyme disease last year.
</P>
<P>
   Some other factors are important, too. If you've already had
Lyme disease, experts say the vaccine might be appropriate because
you've already proven you're at risk and there's always the chance
of being reinfected.
</P>
<P>
   But if you have any chronic arthritic conditions, including
rheumatoid arthritis, then the vaccine isn't for you. LYMErix,
which is manufactured by SmithKline Beecham, may aggravate such
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Early symptoms of the disease may include a circular rash around
the tick bite, fever, headaches and nausea.
</P>
<P>
   When diagnosed early, the disease is easily treated with
antibiotics. Untreated, however, the disease can cause arthritis,
numbness, facial paralysis, an irregular heartbeat and death.
</P>
<P>
   As with any vaccine, there are potential side effects, including
swelling at the injection site and flu-like symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   Age also is a consideration. LYMErix is currently approved only
for adults and children over 15. Studies are under way to determine
if it's safe for younger children.
</P>
<P>
   Even with those caveats, people are still wondering what to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a gray zone,'' said Dr. Joel Kremer, a professor of
medicine and head of the division of rheumatology at the Albany
Medical Center. ``I don't think we need everyone to rush out and
get this vaccine.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who choose to get the vaccine, now is the ideal time:
``Lyme is really most prevalent in spring,'' Kremer said.
</P>
<P>
   The vaccine doesn't offer a 100 percent guarantee against the
disease. And it's not a one-shot deal, either.
</P>
<P>
   LYMErix must be given in three doses over the course of a year,
with the first two shots spaced about a month apart and the last
one given 11 months later. Even at that point, the vaccine offers
only 75 to 80 percent protection against Lyme infection and doesn't
protect against other tick-borne illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   There is also some question as to whether vaccine recipients
will need an annual booster to retain the protection. Finally,
there's the issue of cost. While many health plans are covering the
vaccine, out-of-pocket costs for LYMErix can range from $150 to
$250.
</P>
<P>
   That's why many specialists say the most important factor to
weigh when considering the vaccine is your level of personal
vigilance against ticks. Protective measures include wearing
light-colored clothing so you can spot a tick more easily; using
insect repellent that contains DEET; keeping your property clear of
leaf litter and brush, which provide good hiding places for ticks;
and checking your body daily for ticks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to tell people I've broken two full-length mirrors over
the past two years examining myself every night,'' said David Weld,
president of the American Lyme Disease Foundation in Somers, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Besides avoiding contact with infected ticks, Lyme disease can
be avoided by removing ticks from the body within 36 hours.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Sylvia Wood can be reached at 518-454-5445 or by electronic
mail at swood(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
