<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CANADA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADA'S CLOSE ENCOUNTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   People travel for four main reasons _ new destinations, new
experiences, foreign flavor, and good value. Canada, an old
destination, has it all.
</P>
<P>
   The question, though, might be, with Canada so close, why go
elsewhere? Because Canada is so close, so friendly, and so
welcoming, it tends to get overlooked by all those who think they
have to cross the Atlantic to have new experiences, especially with
a foreign flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps now that the American dollar is worth up to $1.50
Canadian, (on May 5 it was worth $1.44 Canadian), more vacationers
might get the idea to go north this year savoring the foreign
flavor along with some great values.
</P>
<P>
   Canada, however, is more than a money-saving destination, it's
packed with great cities, cultural experiences, outdoor adventures,
great scenery, and, yes, foreign flavor.
</P>
<P>
   While there is a lot happening throughout Canada, Nova Scotia
has a lot to interest New Englanders. From July 23 through July 25,
the Fortress of Louisbourg will celebrate the 250th anniversary of
its return to France. The fort, the largest historical
reconstruction in North America, will be the scene of battlefield
re-enactments, music, and other events. Halifax is marking its
250th anniversary with a series of events beginning June 26. On
July 1, Halifax will open Pier 21, Canada's Ellis Island. Between
1928 and 1971, more than 1.6 million immigrants arrived in Halifax,
many continuing on to America.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Canadians speak English _ mostly _ and, yes, they are not
only a lot like us but they also like us. So, why fly 3,000 miles
when you can experience a whole new world just a few hours drive
away _ even less by air?
</P>
<P>
   Canada is easy to reach. From Boston there is nonstop air
service to Toronto, Montreal, Quebec City, Ottawa, Vancouver, and
the Atlantic provinces. By ship one can travel overnight aboard the
Scotia Prince that offers daily service between Portland, Maine,
and Yarmouth, Nova Scotia. From Bar Harbor, Maine, a high-speed
ferry offers three-hour cruises to Yarmouth _ in July and August
the service is twice daily. By rail, Amtrak offers connections with
Via Rail in Canada. There is also a new rail pass that covers trips
in both countries.
</P>
<P>
   Crossing the border is also easy. While a passport is the best
identification, American citizens need neither a passport or visa
to cross into Canada. Travelers will need proof of citizenship such
as a birth certificate and an ID card _ driver's licence _ with
photo.
</P>
<P>
   US drivers' licenses are valid in Canada. Drivers should carry
proof of ownership of their vehicle, as well as proof of insurance.
Traffic laws and road signs are similar to the United States. One
exception, in Quebec right turns on red are prohibited.
</P>
<P>
   Canada is on the metric system and mileage and miles per hour
are listed in kilometers: 25 km equals 15 miles; 50 km is 30 miles;
60 km is 36 miles; 80 km is 50 miles; and 100 km is 60 miles. Fuel
is also sold in liters. One US gallon is the equal of 3.78 liters.
</P>
<P>
   While Canada has a GST or Goods and Services Tax (7 percent) on
most goods and accommodations, and many provinces have a HST or
Harmonized Sales Tax (15 percent), Americans can receive a refund
on most purchases taken out of the country. Keep a receipt for a
refund. A brochure, ``Tax Refund Application for Visitors'' can be
found in many stores, some hotels, border crossings, and other
locations.
</P>
<P>
   Even Canada's currency is similar to ours, except of course for
``loonies'' and ``toonies.'' Canada uses coins instead of paper for
one- and two-dollars. The ``loonie'' is one dollar, the ``toonie''
is two dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
