<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPILLARY ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new bit of sarcasm has been circling the cultural airport,
looking for permission to land, and last week _ after two flybys on
the same morning _ it finally buzzed into my consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   The putdown popped up first in Scott Shuger's daily newspaper
digest in Slate, the on-line magazine. Shuger noted that the New
York Times had buried an important detail about the Littleton,
Colo., shootings in paragraph 42 of a story, thus demonstrating ``a
real instinct for the capillaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Capillaries? It took a few seconds to decode the insult: An
instinct for the tiniest blood vessels, not the major ones? Aha _
he meant that the Times showed the opposite of ``an instinct for
the jugular.''
</P>
<P>
   Just hours later, on WBUR's ``The Connection,'' in Boston, host
Christopher Lydon quoted a description of Henry James as ``a man
with a great instinct for the capillaries.'' He explained to his
baffled guest, the writer Cynthia Ozick, that it meant ``as opposed
to the arteries'' _ that James was a writer of fine detail, not
great slashing strokes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going for the jugular'' has been around for a while, but it's
not clear when it made its debut. The HarperCollins slang
dictionary gives jugular, solo _ derived from go for the jugular _
as a '60s synonym for ``cutthroat, savage,'' or ``vital, life and
death.''
</P>
<P>
   But the killer strike to the throat doesn't have to involve the
jugular veins. Jugular, related to yoke, refers to the neck area,
not just the blood vessels. There's an old verb, jugulate, meaning
to kill by slashing the neck, but English translators also used
throttle _ another word for strangle _ as a translation for the
Latin jugulare. Whatever the actual damage, going for the jugular
means your victim is getting it in the neck.
</P>
<P>
   The capillaries joke, though more recent, has been around longer
than you might think. The oldest citation in the Lexis/Nexis
database comes from a 1983 Fortune magazine piece: `` `By getting
Tymshare, (McDonnell Douglas) is adding 4 percent to the revenue
stream. That's like going for the capillaries instead of the
jugular,' quips aerospace expert Wolfgang Demisch.''
</P>
<P>
   In the sprinkling of citations since then, the would-be
catchphrase doesn't seem to be catching on. Along the way,
Democrats (in the Clarence Thomas confirmation battle), Republicans
(in the Clinton impeachment trial), Congress as a whole, and a few
attorneys and pols are accused of lacking that killer instinct. But
nobody gives a clue to the expression's pedigree till 1993, when
Murray Kempton writes, ``One of the older lawyerly adages is that,
when the jugular is beyond your reach, you can only go for the
capillaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe lawyers do understand the phrase in its short form _ and
can tell us when it began to circulate _ but journalists usually
add instead of the jugular, acknowledging that most everyday
readers aren't going to get going for the capillaries as a
free-standing witticism.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if David E. Kelley starts making his TV lawyers say
it every week, going for the capillaries has a chance; ``Ally
McBeal'' surely beats Slate as a way to spread the word. But it
remains a fairly complicated joke, and English speakers seem
content, for now, to leave it in its holding pattern and see how
long its fuel lasts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
No speed limits
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone recently used the phrase driving below 30 mph,''
writes Liza Cassarino of Foxborough. ``That doesn't sound right. It
should be driving under 30 mph _ but why?''
</P>
<P>
   It's a great pleasure to report, for once, that nobody seems
eager to have this argument. It's true that among usagists and copy
editors, debates have raged about when to use over and more than
and above. And since most of the ``rules'' are based on the whims
and crotchets of 19th-century arbiters, it's no surprise that the
rationalizations are elaborate and the edicts widely ignored.
</P>
<P>
   But the below/under question has somehow escaped the legislative
fervor. The inimitable H.W. Fowler did devote an entry to below vs.
under in Modern English Usage (1926), noting that people were
starting to say ``under his breath'' when they ought to say below.
He lost that battle, and apparently nobody has taken up his
cudgels.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases like this, the preferred idiom comes naturally _
40 below zero, students under 18 _ and I suspect most people choose
to drive under 80 (and over 40). But I haven't yet found a language
cop who would ticket you for below 80 or above 40. Until you hear
the sirens, the word you choose is between you and your
speedometer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Write or e-mail Jan Freeman at The Boston Globe, PO Box 2378,
Boston, MA 02107-2378; freeman(at)globe.com. Please include a
hometown and phone number.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-99 1353EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
