<DOCNO> NYT19990511.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2513 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-11 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENT RUNNING FOR SOMEONE ELSE'S LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Kids today. They're OK. Some kids are more than
OK.
</P>
<P>
   Rashad L. Williams, a 15-year-old freshman at San Francisco's
Archbishop Riordan High School, is running the Bay to Breakers race
on Sunday to raise money for Lance Kirklin, one of the students who
was severely wounded in the massacre at Columbine High School in
Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   According to Williams' mother, Sheila Burton-Harrison, her son
said, ``You know what, mom, that could have been me. I'm going to
run the Bay to Breakers for him. He may be in a wheelchair the rest
of his life. All I have to give him are my two legs.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams runs track and cross-country for Riordan, and on Monday
we met on the school's athletic fields. He's a handsome, serious
young man who runs the 400 and 800 meters and has a liquid,
purposeful stride.
</P>
<P>
   I asked him why a teen-ager would want to raise money to help a
badly wounded teen-ager he'd never met, but only heard of on the
news.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw that travesty that happened out there, I had to do
something,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   I asked him if he could imagine losing the use of his legs. ``I
just think of the hurt,`` he said. ``Mental and physical.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the kind of kid Rashad Williams is. He came in fifth in
the 800 in the West Catholic Association League. I said that was
pretty good for a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was what my coach said,'' Williams said. ``I said,
`Naah.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't get many kids like this,'' said Frank Oross, who has
been a track coach and teacher at Riordan for 25 years. ``Not only
is he a good student and athlete, his heart's in the right place.
That's what we teach here.''
</P>
<P>
   Candy McDonald, secretary to the Rev. Timothy Kenney, principal
of Riordan, said, ``People always complain about teen-agers today.
But they're not all like that. Here they're taught to be a family.
When one hurts, they all hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Teen-agers hurt for others far away, too. The day of the
Colorado shootings, you could imagine a national family of
teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We prayed in the morning and in the afternoon for the kids in
Littleton,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Williams decided to run the 7 1/2-mile Bay to Breakers
race for one of the Littleton kids, accepting pledges for each
mile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sunday morning, I'll be there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He'll finish, too. Maybe even somewhere near the top.
</P>
<P>
   This is a nice little story, but when you get into it, you learn
some painful things.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ireland, 17, who suffered severe head injuries at
Columbine High School, is famous as ``the boy in the window,'' but
the rest of the injured kids aren't well-known beyond Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Denver Post listed three students as still
hospitalized at the Swedish Medical Center in Denver. (Ireland and
Sean Graves, 15, have been moved to Craig Hospital for
rehabilitation.)
</P>
<P>
   Anne Marie Hochalter, 17, is in serious condition in the
critical care unit with a gunshot wound to the chest. Richard
Castaldo, 17, is in fair condition with five gunshot wounds to the
chest, back and arm.
</P>
<P>
   Lance Kirklin, 16, for whom Williams will be raising money, is
in serious but stable condition with multiple gunshot wounds to the
chest, legs and face. Kirklin already has had numerous surgeries
from 30 surgeons, and reconstructive surgery on his jaw may take
two years to complete.
</P>
<P>
   These kids have received care in a ``multiple trauma unit.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes that seems to be what our country is.
</P>
<P>
   But then you meet Rashad Williams, his mom, Sheila
Burton-Harrison, and her 1-year-old boy, R.J. Burton.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago they moved from San Francisco to Antioch. ``It's
quiet there,'' Burton-Harrison said. The family enrolled Rashad in
Riordan and his 8-year-old sister Remi Burton in San Francisco's
Fellowship Academy.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of these private church schools is cheap. But
Burton-Harrison, an inspector for San Francisco public transit
system, and her husband, Anthony Harrison, who works for a bottled
water company, manage to pay the tuition and all the baby sitters,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Rashad, who hopes to become a veterinarian, gets up at 5:30
every morning to catch a train or a carpool to Riordan. He loves
it. ``I like the diversity here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's rough out there,'' his mother said. ``I'm trying to arm
him with the best tools.''
</P>
<P>
   He has some pretty good ones already.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
