<HEADER>
A2522 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-ROSENBLATT-ART-BO     05-11 1571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-ROSENBLATT-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANA ROSENBLATT FIGHTS TO KEEP HIS DREAM ALIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He was a dreamer once, Dana Rosenblatt was. But no more.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years as a prizefighter have changed wispy dreams into
harsh realities for the Malden middleweight. Broken hands.
Dehydration. Battles with weight. One brief duel with
unconsciousness. Broken promises. It adds up.
</P>
<P>
   These things all have been part of his athletic life, but none
of them are what transforms a boxer's dream into a professional's
skepticism. Such things follow with the choice you make the first
time you walk up the three short steps that separate civilians from
fistfighters and accept money for hand-to-hand combat. Soon enough
every fighter learns that.
</P>
<P>
   So, no, it was not those things that broke the dream. It was
other things, things you never knew about when you were 20 and full
of hope. Conniving promoters. World ratings not worth the paper
they're printed on. A career too long put on hold by people who
never have known how your lungs can burn after 12 rounds of
fighting for your life.
</P>
<P>
   That is what kills a dream. Or at least that's what can wound
it.
</P>
<P>
   So now, a week and a half before he journeys to his second home
at Foxwoods Casino to fight a kid from Baltimore named Lloyd Bryan
that he's never met in an ESPN2 main event, Dana Rosenblatt dreams
no more. He fights instead. Fights the reality and the dream.
Fights just to keep on fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to drop the idealism from your motivation to keep
getting out on the road in the morning and sparring at night,''
said Rosenblatt (34-1, 23 KOs). ``Seven years in boxing and my
ideals are about gone out the window.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports is not a level deal once you're off the playground. The
only place a fight is level is in the schoolyard. It's not that way
in the professional ranks anyway, so I have no ideals any more when
I look at boxing. I don't look at the sports arena and think
justice is served any more, no matter who wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on the cynical side at 20 but now my wife laughs that
all I say is `no, can't, won't, never will be.' There's no way this
life doesn't carry over into how you look at other things. It's
different to be in something where the goal is to win a world title
and never get a chance to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   For most prizefighters, that is their fate. The fighters fight
but not for the prize they dreamed of. Not for the title. They
fight to survive instead.
</P>
<P>
   In Rosenblatt's case, he was close four years ago, when he was
rated in the top 10 by the World Boxing Council and World Boxing
Association and reached No. 1 in the World Boxing Union only to be
knocked cold by an old warrior who had known many triumphs and just
as many tragedies. The night Vinny Pazienza overcame what was
becoming a savage beating with one crushing right to Rosenblatt's
temple, the dreamer began to become a professional himself.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the lesson he learned was not just a harsh one.
It was costly, and he has been paying for it ever since as his
career slowed to a crawl once a broken hand followed in his
comeback fight and a second one came right behind it the first week
he tried to spar again.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Rosenblatt has been fighting for a living but not
for a shot at the middleweight title. That is still his dream, and
dreams _ like professional fighters _ die hard. But Rosenblatt
dreams less these days about title belts because he cannot see them
on the horizon any more.
</P>
<P>
   Instead he fights for money. He is a professional now, a
professional still hoping his break will come but expecting little
more than a hard night's work to earn his living.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 10th or 11th in the WBA and 16th in the WBC and they've
both got a lot of obscure names in front of me but that's my lot
for now,'' Rosenblatt said, sounding like the philosophy student
he's become at UMass-Boston, where he is 15 classes short of a
bachelor's degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm reduced to going after titles that carry a lot less
recognition like the IBA for now, knowing that beating a Terry
Norris means more than winning one of those belts.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the night Rosenblatt beat Norris despite fading late with a
dehydration problem, he didn't get what he expected. Norris was a
world champion several times over and though well past his prime
still knew how to fight, still had to be contended with, still had
to be beaten down. Rosenblatt did all that. Yet he did not get the
credit from most corners because people said Norris was no longer
Norris and so Rosenblatt was diminished in victory simply because
he couldn't destroy him.
</P>
<P>
   It was a ludicrous position to take, as ludicrous as some of his
supporters trying to diminish what Pazienza had done to Rosenblatt
in his only loss just because he was losing badly until the moment
he knocked Rosenblatt out.
</P>
<P>
   A fighter deserves what he earns, at least in the ring, and that
night against Norris, Rosenblatt earned respect. Of course, he
didn't quite get it so now he fights on, this time against Bryan
(18-2, 8 KOs), knowing all he can hope for is to keep winning and
be ready if his phone rings unexpectedly one day because an injury
or boxing's politics have conspired against someone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Financially I've been on the right side of things in boxing,''
said Rosenblatt, who made more than $100,000 last year and figures
to do at least as well in 1999 after pulling in $50,000 May 21.
``I've been luckier than most fighters, so it's worked out for me
on that end and I'm thankful for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I wasn't white and didn't have Foxwoods to fight at, I know
things would be different. That's the other side of this sport. If
my name was Jose Rio or something, I wouldn't be on the right end
of either end.
</P>
<P>
   ``My promoter (Bob Arum) didn't disappear after I lost. He got
me right back in and I earned $30,000 to fight Glenwood Brown but I
busted my hand and was out a long time. Last year they got me
Norris for $70,000 so it's hard to say I've been forgotten. It's
just the politics.''
</P>
<P>
   The politics of the middleweight division are that promoter Don
King controls two-thirds of the title, with Keith Holmes and
William Joppy as WBC and WBA champions, while International Boxing
Federation champion Bernard Hopkins fights for America Presents,
with whom Arum has done business in the past. Unfortunately, that
organization doesn't have Rosenblatt rated, for reasons no one can
quite fathom, and so he cannot fight for its title.
</P>
<P>
   So he fights in limbo, like so many other boxers, a 27-year-old
who still carries a champion's dream but keeps it buried now. Well
buried under seven years of learning how harsh boxing can be to
those who love it most _ the prizefighters who bleed for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to make 154 for a while because Top Rank could get me
a title shot there but I couldn't make the weight,'' Rosenblatt
said. ``So I just keep moving along.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I get an opportunity to fight, I look at it for what it
is. I'm happy for what I have and I don't brood about what I don't
have. I get paid what I'm entitled to because of what I can
generate when I fight. I'm a hell of a lot busier than most
fighters and I probably make more than some of the champions. For
now, that's what I got.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only disadvantage is that if you win these kind of fights,
you don't get much credit, but if you don't look good, you get
crucified and if you lose, you're screwed.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I know what I need. I need some spectacular knockouts
because that's the sick sensationalism the whole country is gripped
by today. Nobody looks to see if there's any substance to what's
behind it. They just want to see something spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   ``I been on both sides of that. I got no credit for beating a
legitimate guy like Norris but I knocked out Chad Parker in 30
seconds four years ago and people are still talking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblatt's point is well taken. Norris had been world champion
several times and world ranked for years even though he was
admittedly past his prime. Parker had the phoniest 31-0 record ever
made and never fought again after Rosenblatt destroyed him. But
that's boxing . . . as he now understands.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't really know how to value achievements properly
but that's the way the boxing business goes,'' Rosenblatt said.
``So you take what you can get. If I hadn't lost to Vinny, I'd
probably be in a different position today. I know that. My career
suffered a mortal blow that night but I made a lot of money
($350,000) and I know I'm on the cusp of making that kind of money
again if I can just get a couple of breaks with the right kind of
wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not dreaming. The title is dreaming. Making money is
reality. It's being in the right place at the right moment and
being ready when you get there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boxing isn't a dream any more. It's a job. It's not like I'm a
mercenary. I still want to fight for the title, but the system
sucks the idealism out of you.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, after it does, you are a professional. You are a
prizefighter then, as Dana Rosenblatt now understands, and the
prizefighter fights for whatever prize they offer until the real
prize _ the dream long buried _ shows up.
</P>
<P>
   If it ever does.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
