<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOSTETTER'S WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A couple of years ago, not long after US West bought Boston's
Continental Cablevision, top executives of the Denver-based Baby
Bell telephone company stopped by The Boston Globe to tout the
deal, accompanied by the man who had sold them the company.
</P>
<P>
   US West had renamed the company MediaOne and put Chuck Lillis in
charge. Lillis had sold everything from Fuller brushes to Wharton
Econometric forecasting services. He was seated among a phalanx of
other US West executives that day. He took over and held forth.
</P>
<P>
   He touted the joys of ``broadband,'' meaning the superefficient
transmission of telephone, television and Internet through a single
``pipe'' that Continental Cablevision had pioneered.
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing to indicate that the man sitting quietly to
his right, Amos B. Hostetter, was widely regarded as dean of the
cable television industry. Nor that he was one of the dozen most
widely admired businessmen in Boston, second only to Fidelity's
Edward Johnson as a company-builder.
</P>
<P>
   Neither was there anything to suggest that the deal had made
Hostetter truly wealthy, one of a small circle of Boston
billionaires, including Johnson, Richard Smith of Harcourt General,
Sumner Redstone of Viacom, and private equity specialist Thomas H.
Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Hostetter sat easily off to the side. If he was restless at
having been eclipsed, he didn't show it _ at least not much. He sat
sideways in his seat, closest to the door. When it was time to go,
he didn't linger.
</P>
<P>
   So when US West later that year announced it would move
Continental's operations to Denver from its headquarters on Lewis
Wharf, it did not come entirely as a surprise that Hostetter quit
the MediaOne board in anger.
</P>
<P>
   Lillis had broken his word, Hostetter told friends. The move was
not only unnecessary, it was also counterproductive. All but 15 or
so of Hostetter's staff of 160 quit with their chief rather than
move.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Hostetter told the Globe's Steve Bailey, ``I was
cross-eyed I was so angry. I was totally duped, used.'' Revenge
wasn't high on his list, Hostetter said. But then he added, ``I
really believe in business, you get back a fair measure of what you
give. I think the way current management is doing business will
ultimately bring its own demise without any help from me.''
</P>
<P>
   He was half right.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, AT&AMP;T Corp. topped what had seemed a generous
offer by Comcast Corp. with a $58-billion bid. If Lillis isn't out
on the street already, he will be soon. The Denver management is in
deep demise.
</P>
<P>
   Hostetter, however, himself turned out to be a key sherpa for
the deal makers. When family-owned Comcast failed to offer
Hostetter voting shares for his 9.5 percent stake in MediaOne, he
called up AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Chief executive C. Michael Armstrong has made clear that his
company already was thinking about making a pass at MediaOne _ Why
not? A month earlier it had bought a still bigger cable firm _ but
that Hostetter had increased its enthusiasm for the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was able to give us a confirmation of the insights about
the value we could extract from the investment,'' said Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   So Hostetter will rejoin the industry from which he was briefly
sidelined as adviser (executive chairman) to Leo Hindery, chief of
AT&AMP;T's broadband and internet services unit. He will sit on AT&AMP;T's
board of directors as well, joining John C. Malone, who became
AT&AMP;T's single biggest shareholder in March when he sold his TCI
Corp. to the phone company for stock.
</P>
<P>
   Since the sale of Continental Cablevision two years ago,
Hostetter has put on a pretty good impression of retirement. He
serves as board chairman at Amherst College. He established, with
his wife, Barbara, a $500 million foundation dedicated to education
reform. He spends plenty of time on Nantucket.
</P>
<P>
   But the electronic convergence of telephone, television,
computer hardware, software, entertainment and Internet services is
just beginning in the United States, not ending. Hostetter has
regained his seat at the table.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
