<HEADLINE>
COMPANY HONES IN ON SELLING FURNITURE ON-LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How do you become a big winner in electronic retailing?
</P>
<P>
   Pick a category with huge sales, establish a presence before
anyone else does, spend heavily to promote your brand name, and
provide the consumer with a a combination of low prices and good
service that he couldn't get in a normal store.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com has done it with books. Furniture.com is trying to do
the same with _ what else _ furniture.
</P>
<P>
   The Worcester company has been around only since last June, but
it already has followed most of the steps on the Amazon path to
success. It has raised $13 million from some of the best names in
venture capital, including CMGI Inc., the Andover firm that backed
such winners as Lycos and GeoCities. It has a simple name that all
but guarantees it will attract Internet traffic. It has tied up
some of the best real estate on search engines like Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game is over; this company already owns the category,'' a
breathless analyst from Needham &AMP; Co. wrote after listening to a
presentation from Furniture.com at an investment conference last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Spend some time with Andrew Brooks, the company's chief
executive, and you too may come away with the impression that you
are in on the ground floor of something exciting. Brooks and his
staff of about 100 work out of an old brick building in Worcester,
Mass. that looks more 19th century than 21st century. Yet the
vision they have of furniture retailing is definitely futuristic.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine that you are sitting at home staring at a computer,
which has a picture of your house and and its current furnishings
on the screen. Want to see what a new couch might look like in your
living room? Just press some buttons and the couch drops into the
picture. Want to turn it green, move it across the room? All
possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be something the retail experience can't mimic,''
Brooks says. The key word here is ``will.'' The type of wizardry
Brooks is promising is at least two years away when greater
bandwidth is available to the average household.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Furniture.com is offering a Web site with
50,000 selections from more than 100 different manufacturers. The
Web site has been redesigned several times in the last few months
to make it more user-friendly. The company has 15 design
consultants who can provide help either on the phone or on line.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks is such a good salesman you can almost forget to ask the
most obvious question. Is anyone really going to buy furniture over
the Internet?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was initially skeptical,'' says Donald Bellomy, an analyst
with the Aberdeen Group in Boston. Unlike books, pieces of
furniture are expensive. And as Bellomy puts it, if you buy on
line, ``You can't bounce on the bed.''
</P>
<P>
   According to analysts, however, roughly 2 percent of furniture
sales already are made through catalogs or over the phone. As time
goes by, the betting is that more people will be willing to make
purchases without kicking the tires in a showroom.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Vroom, an analyst with Thomas Weisel Partners in San
Francisco, predicts that the Internet can capture 20 percent of the
sales in the $60 billion furniture industry over a period of years.
If home furnishings like rugs and lamps are added to the mix, the
potential annual sales could be much larger, says Vroom. On-line
furniture sales today are probably too small to measure.
Furniture.com, which is privately held, does not disclose sales
figures.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts believe the furniture industry is ripe for change. They
say the business is fragmented, management is weak, and service is
too often disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Furniture retailers are our friends,'' says Brooks, ``because
they have made the shopping experience so miserable.'' Brooks says
the average customer visits five stores before making a furniture
purchase. Once a purchase is made, delivery can take another two to
four months because almost all furniture is made to order.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks hopes to do better. He predicts that by gathering
national data on consumer preferences he can reshape the furniture
industry into something the customer will like better. He also
hopes to shrink delivery time dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   Separating the hype from reality is difficult in the Internet
world. While some already have declared Furniture.com a winner,
Donald Bellomy is probably closer to the mark when he describes the
company as a ``work in progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Will consumers flock to the Internet to buy furniture? If they
do, will they choose Furniture.com? Stay tuned.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
