<HEADLINE>
BLAZING WORKOUT BY SILVERBULLETDAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Silverbulletday is ready.
</P>
<P>
   The champion filly, winner of the Eclipse Award as a 2-year-old,
blazed 5 furlongs in :59, out 6 furlongs in 1:11 3/5, at Churchill
Downs Monday, as she prepares to take on males in the Preakness at
Pimlico Saturday. Trainer Bob Baffert held Silverbulletday, who is
slight of build, out of the Kentucky Derby May 1, and she easily
won the Kentucky Oaks the previous day. Since the Derby resembled
the Charge of the Light Brigade, and Silverbulletday almost
certainly would have been smacked arund, it appears Baffert made
the right decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the smartest move I made all week,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Silverbulletday, who has won 10 of 11 career starts, really
smoked Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured, after she worked, they'd have to put water on the
track to cool it down,'' said Baffert. ``It was the kind of work I
was looking to get out of her. She put in a nice stiff work,
galloped out strong, and came back great. That's what you want to
see coming into a race like the Preakness.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert also intends to run his other outstanding filly, the
bigger-framed Excellent Meeting, who will work Tuesday at
Churchill, in the Preakness. Excellent Meeting, the only one to
defeat Silverbulletday, finished fifth in the Derby, with a strong
late run, after being as far back as 18th. Monday, Baffert
cross-entered both fillies in Friday's Black-Eyed Susan, but the
Black-Eyed Susan is worth $200,000, while the Preakness, which will
be drawn Wednesday, has a purse of $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the luck of the draw now,'' he said. ``Fate will decide
whether we run in the Preakness or not. Everything looks good now,
and we'll wait to see what happens in the draw. These are two great
fillies and I'm not going to waste a start. I want to run to win.''
</P>
<P>
   As of now, Baffert intends to enter his best 3-year-old colt,
Prime Timber, in the Sir Barton, a $100,000 stake on the Preakness
undercard. Prime Timber was buffeted about while finishing fourth
in the Derby, and Baffert wants to get a race into him, while
pointing toward the Belmont Stakes June 5, without putting him
through the rigors of the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a rough trip in the Derby,'' said Baffert. ``If I'm
going to go to the Belmont with him, I just can't sit on him, then
ask him to go 1 1/2 miles.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sorting out the field
</P>
<P>
   First American, who was 16th in the Derby, was withdrawn from
Preakness consideration Monday, after it was discovered he had a
chip in his ankle. With K One King, eighth in the Derby, having
been withdrawn Saturday because of ankle and leg problems, and
assuming Baffert is serious about entering Prime Timber on the
undercard, there are 15 horses currently in training for 14 spots
in the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   Since entrance into the Preakness is based on overall earnings,
the Valhol situation may once again play a part in who starts.
Valhol won the Arkansas Derby April 10, earning $300,000, but his
jockey, Bill Patin, was accused of carrying an electrical device
during the race. The Oaklawn stewards held up Valhol's purse, but
the horse's owner, James Jackson, won a ruling from an Arkansas
district court that released the money. That allowed Valhol, who
would have been excluded because of lack of graded earnings, to
start in the Derby, in which he finished 15th.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Derby, the Oaklawn stewards have held a hearing and
officially disqualified Valhol, taking away his purse. Pimlico is
honoring the stewards' decision, meaning Valhol, with only $44,100
in earnings, would be the one excluded from the Preakness. However,
Jackson's lawyers have a hearing set for Wednesday with the
Arkansas Racing Commission, which oversees the Oaklawn stewards, at
which they hope to have the decision overturned. If not, they will
probably return to court to get an injunction.
</P>
<P>
   If Valhol gets in, Torrid Sand would be knocked out. Torrid
Sand, who was third under the wire in the Arkansas Derby, got
$50,000 for third, but was awarded $100,000 for second upon the
disqualification of Valhol. If Jackson wins his appeal, Torrid Sand
would be re-placed third, and would have $91,400 in earnings, the
least of the Preakness aspirants.
</P>
<P>
   The 13 assured of a spot in the Preakness, should their
connections so choose, are, in order of earnings: Silverbulletday;
Derby winner Charismatic; Excellent Meeting; Cat Thief, third in
the Derby; Vicar, 18th; Menifee, second; Kimberlite Pipe, sixth;
Stephen Got Even, 14th; Adonis, 17th; Worldly Manner, seventh;
Badge, fourth in the Wood Memorial; Patience Game, first in the
Kentucky Derby Trial; and Lead Em Home, fifth in the Derby Trial.
</P>
<P>
   One more scratch before would render this moot. Since the Daily
Racing Form lists Valhol at 50-1 for the Preakness, and Torrid Sand
at 99-1, it really doesn't make much difference.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fast worker
</P>
<P>
   Menifee, who made a big charge to gain the place in the Derby,
zipped a half-mile in :47 at Churchill Monday, galloping out 5
furlongs in :59 3/5, under the watchful eye of trainer Elliott
Walden. ``Good horses work fast,'' said Walden. ``He's feeling good
and we're ready to go. He worked super, and did it on his own. He
might not be as far back early as he was in the Derby.'' . . .
Vicar, who was ridden by Shane Sellers in the Derby, does not yet
have a rider for the Preakness. Sellers accepted the mount on
Kimberlite Pipe when Vicar's trainer, Carl Nafzger, was slow to
commit to the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Material from publicity departments at various racetracks was used
to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
