<HEADLINE>
POETIC TOUCHES LIFT JOURNAL OF RENEWAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PRAGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
UNDER THE DEVIL'S THUMB 
By David Gessner 
University of Arizona Press, 213 pp., $16.95 (paperback) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just as journalism is the first draft of history, journals are
the first draft of personal history. They make an excellent tool
for capturing moments, sorting emotions, and gaining new
understanding.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the rare writer who can start with his journal and end
up with literature. ``Under the Devil's Thumb,'' the new collection
of essays by David Gessner, opens the question of whether he is one
of those writers.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the foremost obstacle is that journals would be
pointless without the first person, and unless done deftly, all
that navel-gazing can quickly become tiresome, even annoying.
Gessner has clearly considered the problem:
</P>
<P>
   ``It is always a bold gamble to think anyone might actually be
interested in you,'' he writes. ``But, if I cut myself some slack,
I can see my song as a modest entry in a great, old tradition. `I
should not talk about myself so much if there were any body else
whom I knew as well,' wrote Thoreau. . . . It has been said before
but bears repeating: we are all the first person.''
</P>
<P>
   Other aspects of Gessner's craft _ what writing should be, how
it changes him, how it connects him to his brother and the earth _
course endlessly through ``Under the Devil's Thumb,'' just as
creeks course through the Western landscape that provides the
grounding for many of Gessner's stories.
</P>
<P>
   Gessner grew up in Worcester and spent summers at the Cape, but
five years ago, at a bit more than 30 years old, he contracted
cancer. He survived, but one of the cancer's casualties was his
past. He decided to go west and start anew, while he still could.
He went looking for ``renewal and regeneration.'' That hope did not
extend to his right testicle, which is where the cancer resided and
which was removed. Upon arrival in Colorado, he found his new
writing task: ``I tried to excavate the past. I worked like
Sisyphus rolling a giant testicle up a mountainside.''
</P>
<P>
   The contrast between the ``dull, gray sinkhole'' of Worcester
and Rocky Mountain freshness is the first of many opportunities to
reflect on how ``where'' affects ``who.'' Who Gessner becomes in
his new hometown of Eldorado Springs, Colo., is a convert, and a
zealous convert at that. He celebrates his re-creation of the
westward pioneer's spirit, and rues bitterly the despoiling of the
West begun with atom bomb tests in the '40s and continuing today at
Rocky Flats nuclear weapons site, just 10 miles down the road.
</P>
<P>
   He dives into learning about the native birds and flora. He
attacks mountain trails on his bicycle, grooving on the pain as a
way to be present in the moment. He is passionate about his wife,
his wife's cats, about wild cats. He cannot help but to analogize.
``I challenge anyone, no matter how scientific and unromantic, to
walk through this country without breaking into paroxysms of simile
and metaphor-making.''
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, Gessner's gung-ho gusto is leavened by a wealth of
fresh observations that may well spring from the same source. He
revels in the land, for example, but is ``worn down by the
relentless pessimism of knowing we are destroying what we worship.
. . . We are settlers . . . with all of that word's connotations of
accepting less than what once was.'' Part of that destruction is at
the hands of those who would own their piece of paradise, where
they can build their dream houses. Larger-scale destruction
emanates from Madison Avenue, as it covers every butte with some
four-wheeling beauty.
</P>
<P>
   For all his looking inward, Gessner is adept when looking
outward, too, and can describe what he sees gracefully, such as
when ``a thousand white hares dart in front of the truck'' while
he's driving through a snowstorm, and perceptively, as when a
cutting mountain wind ``at once numbed and woke us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the success of ``Under the Devil's Thumb'' is
decided more by these poetic touches than by Gessner's ``bold
gamble,'' which is really not too different from what all journal
writers do. We experience, we write and record, and sometimes we
share what we've felt and seen. And then we start anew.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
