<HEADLINE>
MONTREAL JAZZ FESTIVAL GOES CAJUN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The International Jazz Festival of Montreal celebrates its 20th
anniversary July 1 through 11 with some new features including the
sounds and tastes of Louisiana. The festival will be held noon to
midnight daily and featuring 400 events (300 free concerts) within
a four-block downtown area. Adding to the festival will be a daily
parade inspired by the popular marching bands of New Orleans.
Another innovation will be cruises aboard the riverboat
Nouvelle-Orleans June 30 through July 10. Two cruises will be
offered, the first includes a Louisiana-style feast and music, the
second is at midnight and features Cajun and zydeco music. Among
performers this year will be Miles Davis, Cassandra Wilson, and the
Dave Brubeck Quartet. Programming for the festival will be
announced May 11, and the free outdoor concerts will be announced
on June 17. Tickets for the festival are now on sale. For tickets
or information on the festival, call 888-515-0515. Complete tourist
packages are available. Information is also available at
www.montrealjazzfest.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Tulip time
</P>
<P>
   Each May, 3 million tulips blossom for the Canadian Tulip
Festival in Canada's scenic National Capital Region. The festival
celebrates friendship, and this year the May 14 through 24 festival
will mark the unique friendship between the United States and
Canada. The festival, now the world's largest tulip event, began in
1945 with the gift of 100,000 tulips from Princess Juliana of the
Netherlands as a token of gratitude for sheltering the Dutch royal
family during World War II. Among the spectacular floral sculptures
planned are one based on Van Gogh's ``Iris,'' and another
representing a floral map of the two countries with bouquets that
highlight the official flowers of the 63 states, provinces, and
territories.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Two country rail pass
</P>
<P>
   A rail pass that allows travelers to create a custom itinerary
throughout Canada and the United States for one fare is now being
discounted 10 percent for seniors, children, and students. The
Amtrak/VIA North American Rail Pass allows a trip of up to 30
consecutive days over 28,000 miles of railways and 900
destinations. One segment of the trip must be in both countries.
The discount applies to both peak and off-peak fares. Peak fare is
$645 June 1 through Oct. 15; off-peak fare is $450 Oct. 16 through
Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Heritage opens
</P>
<P>
   Heritage Plantation in Sandwich on Cape Cod opens for its 30th
season this week. The museum is an Americana theme park on 76
landscaped acres with magnificent rhododendrons and daylily
gardens. Opening day offers free admission for mothers, who also
receive a free ice cream cone at the Carousel Cafe. On display this
year will be ``Edge to Edge: Selections from Studio Art Quilt
Associates'' focusing on the diversity of creativity in textiles
made in the last decade. The Military Museum will feature ``A
Splendid Little War, The Spanish American War, 1898.'' In the J. K.
Lilly III Antique Automobile Museum's gallery will be an exhibit,
``The Lynn Beach Painters: Art Along the North Shore of
Massachusetts, 1880-1920.'' The museum is open daily 10 a.m. to 5
p.m. through Oct. 17. For recorded information, call 508-888-1212.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Queen lookalike?
</P>
<P>
   Do you know anyone who looks like Queen Victoria? New
Brunswick's newest luxury inn, Windsor House of St. Andrews, is
looking for a Queen Victoria lookalike for its grand opening on May
24. Since she reigned from 1837 to 1901, co-owner Jay Remer said
their Queen Victoria could reflect any of the years of her
lifetime. For information, call 506-529-3330 or on the Web at
www.townsearch.com/windsorhouse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
