<SLUG> BC-PORCH-SWINGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWINGS GLIDE BACK INTO POPULARITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ We just never seem to outgrow some things. One of
them is swings _ the porch swing in particular.
</P>
<P>
   These are making a big comeback, now that porches are back in
style.
</P>
<P>
   This gentle piece of furniture was where some of us planned our
futures, got engaged, settled in with a good book and glass of
lemonade, napped, listened to the peepers in the hot night air,
told ghost stories, sang songs, lolled babies to sleep, chatted
with family and neighbors or just tried to catch a cool breeze and
while away the hours.
</P>
<P>
   Swings as furniture fell from favor as people were lured inside
by television and air conditioning and houses sans porches.
</P>
<P>
   As we reflect on the last century, old wrought-iron, steel or
aluminum gliders from the 1930s through the 1950s can still be
found at yard sales and flea markets. They can look like new with a
coat of paint and cushions. Or buy a new one. Manufacturers are
making reproduction glider swings and modern-looking ones to fit
contemporary tastes.
</P>
<P>
   If you prefer a swing, you'll need strong porch beams to fasten
it to, or try a free-standing version, which comes with its own
stand of either metal or matching wood.
</P>
<P>
   When buying a metal swing, make sure it features a
rust-resistant coating. A good wood swing should be
insect-resistant and weatherproofed so it will hold up to the
elements. Cedar is self-preserved and hardwoods can be stained or
painted.
</P>
<P>
   Swings can be found at antiques shops, flea markets, garden
centers and where swimming pools and fencing are sold.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Ensslin, owner of Classic Sheds and Gazebos in Albany, N.Y.,
advised measuring your porch or patio before shopping for a swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want a swing too close to a window,'' Ensslin said.
``If you don't have the space on a porch for one, get a
free-standing swing for the patio or lawn that has a canopy to keep
you dry or protect you from the sun.''
</P>
<P>
   Free-standing swings and gliders cost from $198 to $640 and up,
depending on the material and size. Swings cost $99 to $200 and up.
You can save on costs by making it yourself.
</P>
<P>
   When choosing any swing, always use care when small children are
around, especially with gliders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
