<HEADLINE>
AN ANOMALY IN KEY BISCAYNE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KEY BISCAYNE, Fla. _ Tricky Dick and Bebe _ was that a sitcom
with the laugh on us? _ are gone. But that doesn't mean the island
has lost its appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that depends on what appeals to you. Federal
government employee Richard Nixon, the trickster, and his pal Bebe
Rebozo had Key Biscayne homes, and were the darlings of many. They
often communed in the presidential bunker for such vital affairs of
state as cheering the televised feats of Nixon's beloved Washington
Redskins _ whom he coached in his fantasy life _ or adding names to
his storied Enemies List. Most of those listed (such as the Globe's
storied writer, George Frazier) rejoiced in their guilt by
disassociation with the trickster's style.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon's home, once an attraction to be pointed out to gawkers,
has been razed, replaced by a more lavish dwelling. The place that
appeals to me, though, the Silver Sands Motel, was also destroyed,
in 1992 by a blowhard named Andrew. Namely the malevolent Hurricane
Andrew.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't much left. Rubble and sand,'' says Orlando
Garcia, the manager. ``You can see the concrete slab over there,
the floor, all that remains of our restaurant and bar. We hope to
rebuild that someday as we did the motel rooms. We look the same
now as we always did.''
</P>
<P>
   That's one appealing, comforting feature for long-time customers
and a rookie roomer like me. Amid the highly-risen Miami
Beachification of condos and hotels, and the opulent houses of Key
Biscayne's rich, sits the Sands, overwhelmed and nearly hidden, a
one-story sqatter on the beach. An anomaly, it seems an
anachronistic stranger in town, out of its time and level. But it's
the other architecture, come-lately stuff that doesn't fit the
feeling upheld by the Sands: the old, barefoot Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-six rooms with kitchenettes plus a couple of cottages open
onto a lush tropical garden and swimming pool at center. Not that
you need a pool. The Atlantic Ocean, soothingly murmuring, mumbling
_ though sometimes rambunctiously growling _ is so close you may
fall in getting out of bed. Probably too close. But the place was
built before ground-ruling codes, thus was grandfatherly permitted
to return to the original foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Actually the Sands isn't that old, except that 1956 is pretty
ancient on this island that is connected to Miami, three miles
distant, by a couple of bridges. An agreeable local taxi driver out
of Boston University, Michael Coppola, loves the plain-and-friendly
cinder block joint, especially the bygone barroom _ ``when I was
drinking.'' He says scenes from the marvelous Bogart movie, ``Key
Largo'' (with Lauren Bacall, Claire Trevor, Edward G. Robinson,
Lionel Barrymore), were shot in the bar.
</P>
<P>
   However, Pepe Bara, a desk clerk for years, smiles, and spoils a
good story with the facts. ``Michael's a romantic. That movie was
made before 1956.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' laughs Garcia. ``But a considerably less distinguished
film, `Porky's' did some scenes here. Sorry, no Bogart. But one of
the stars, Dan Monahan, who played Peewee, was a nice guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the restaurant is gone, two of the Key's favored
nosheries are within walking distance. You might bump into Gabriela
Sabatini, the Divine Argentine, breakfasting at personable Ben
Zambrano's Donut Gallery. But you won't find gladhanding Stefano at
the place he founded, Stefano's. Reportedly he is far from any
beach at a goverment installation. Something about taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Not a taxing tramp is the beach walk southward, becoming a
greater pleasure as soon as you move beyond man-made structures and
enter a preserve of dunes and mangrove mercifully and thoughtfully
given over to Bill Baggs Park, a natural defense against
developers. One structure does appear, though, majestic in its
towering loneliness at the southern tip: the 174-year-old Cape
Florida Lighthouse of whitewashed brick.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, depending on tides, aisles of sand will appear at
water level inviting you to walk well out to sea, appearing to
those back on shore like a divine doing an ocean stroll.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever the water is lazy and clear it will reveal all sorts of
creatures sidling up to your sandbar path. Rays flapping. Eels
slithering. Crabs that look like cops aching to make a pinch.
Crowds of finned schoolmates, perhaps taking swimming lessons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saw some barracuda. Beauties,'' said Alese Pechter whom we
encountered one morning. She and husband Mort, Florida natives from
Delray Beach, are astute professional photographers of life above
and below sea level.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we swim in this water?'' My friend, Aurelio, was maybe
having second and third thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Always have,'' Mort said. ``The creatures don't resent our
having a piece of their action. The ocean is big enough for all of
us.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Silver Sands isn't. I'd been advised to book a year in
advance to assure a room for the 14-year-old tennis tournament, The
Lipton. Probably the best of US tennis tournaments, it occurs each
spring at Crandon Park only a mile up the street, and has been
renamed for a new sponsor in 2000 as The Ericsson, an angel bearing
cell phone. A French journalist friend, getting the same tip,
delayed, and was shut out this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, that place may be nice in a modest way, but it doesn't
have a monopoly on Old Florida,'' a friend, Harry Kirsch, wanted me
to know. His wife, Chris, said, ``There's also Old Florida hotel
elegance, albeit pricier, that preceded all of us: The Biltmore in
Coral Gables, not far from the Key.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed _ and the Kirsch's showed us the way.
</P>
<P>
   Long before Miami Beachification and Ft. Lauderdaleizing crowded
Florida's East Coast with stacks of concrete, the Biltmore stood
proudly aloof and lofty, back in the Twenties, overseeing the
Gables while bathed in an F. Scott Fitzgeraldian aura. Not all the
monied guests were pedigreed. Al Capone, who may have done business
with Jay Gatsby, tenanted the exalted tower suite, and golfed on
the hotel course. Did his clubs share a golf bag with a tommy gun?
</P>
<P>
   Bankrupted by the Florida Crash of '26 (a precursor of the
national financial flop in 1929), the hotel went through a variety
of traumas and ownerships, served in World War II as a military
hospital, lost plenty of money but not its singular dignity,
stretching up to the 15 story tower.
</P>
<P>
   Soaring in a soft shade of sienna,the centerpiece of its
Mediterranean neighborhood as it makes yet another comeback, the
Biltmore is an experience in Continental flair, vaulted lobby, and
high Italiante ceilings. Drinks beside the vast, handsome pool,
guarded by reflected statuary, as dusk arrives was followed by
dinner beside a fountain in the tiled courtyard. A changing of the
guard as the sentinels were moon and stars.
</P>
<P>
   It was, well, elegant.
</P>
<P>
   ``And now back to your little motel?'' Chris and Harry bade us
goodnight.
</P>
<P>
   Well, I like to fall out of bed into the Atlantic. Besides, it's
historic. A president walked that beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nixon,'' said Aurelio, backing me up.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he did,'' said Chris, ``I'll bet he never took off his
wingtips and socks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
