<HEADLINE>
CLASS GIVES FUTURE TEACHERS LESSONS IN DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDREW BROWNSTEIN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ On that unforgettable morning, the professors sat
in the Camelot Room of the College of Saint Rose, plotting a new
course to show teachers how to handle death in the age of video
games.
</P>
<P>
   Almost as an omen, the news came of the massacre at Columbine
High School: 15 people killed, including the two gunmen, whose
underground fascination with computer ultraviolence and Nazism was
a living testament to the denial of death.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it was the exclamation point at the end of the
sentence,'' said Donna Burns. ``No sooner had we gotten the course
down on paper than we had this catastrophe.''
</P>
<P>
   Has it all come down this? Death Studies?
</P>
<P>
   Burns and colleague Donna Reittinger would say it has. They are
combining their expertise in education and psychology to teach the
teachers of tomorrow about death and loss, and how to cope with
both in the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   The professors found Columbine a perfect lesson. They saw in the
mass murder a society where death is alternately romanticized or
hushed up, but seldom understood.
</P>
<P>
   Just as sex education rocked the schools in the 1970s, the
professors see the turn of the millennium as a time to break down
taboos surrounding mortality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're beginning to discover that death happens,''
Reittinger said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the great equalizer,'' added Burns.
</P>
<P>
   The new course, scheduled to begin in the fall, is called
``Coping with Loss in Childhood and Adolescence'' and is designed
as part of the teacher-education curriculum at the College of Saint
Rose, an independent school of 4,000 students in Albany. It's a
more focused and timely look at a topic both professors have dealt
with for more than two decades: Developmental Thanatology. That
mouthful stems from Thanatos, the Greek god of death, and was
popularized with the 1969 publication of Elisabeth Kubler-Ross'
best-seller ``On Death and Dying.''
</P>
<P>
   While science has seen enormous advances in the knowledge of the
mind and body, Reittinger and Burns say the understanding of death
has actually moved backward.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1900s, when children grew up in large extended
families, it was not uncommon to have open-casket wakes in the
house. But as those communities broke down, death became sterilized
and increasingly removed from the day-to-day lives of children.
</P>
<P>
   ``For kids, it's Disney World, sugar and spice and everything
nice, Barbie,'' Reittinger said. ``Unfortunately, children live in
the world with adults and process everything. When adults try to
protect them, children often wind up developmentally arrested.''
</P>
<P>
   The denial of death can be as innocuous as using the euphemism
``passed away'' or as serious as a Web site irreverently urging
browsers to ``Kill 'em all!'' That's what one of the Colorado
gunmen posted about his favorite video game.
</P>
<P>
   Loss can be a death in the family or any of the ``little
deaths'' that come from upheavals like moving to another city,
divorce or the breakup of a romantic relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess is that if we were to construct the psychological
autopsies of the two boys who did the shooting in Colorado, we
would find major unresolved losses,'' Reittinger said. ``Their
extreme rage was a reaction to those losses.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns recalled a recent trip to an Albany school to speak to
sixth-graders about a girl with cancer who had missed many days of
class. Like so many others, the teacher was unable to handle
nagging questions about the empty desk the girl left behind. Burns
found that when she posed the subject directly, students peppered
her with questions and faced the topic without fear.
</P>
<P>
   The professors like to talk about such ``teachable moments,''
which can be as simple as a goldfish dying in the class aquarium.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can have a funeral, talk about pets that died and start
talking about what death is,'' Burns said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of doing what most teachers do,'' Reittinger added,
``which is to scoop the fish up, flush it down the toilet and go to
Wal-Mart and buy a new one. They will then try, unsuccessfully, to
convince the class that this is the same old fish.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those who took Reittinger's Thanatology course this spring _
many of them student-teachers _ said the class already has helped
them calm student fears following the violence at Columbine.
</P>
<P>
   Senior education major Ray Parker said he learned to be
reassuring but direct, and never to avoid the topic of death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before this class, I definitely wouldn't have known what to
say,'' he said. ``I might have blown everything off.''
</P>
<P>
   At a time when teachers are asked to know self-defense and
medications, and are ridiculed for not educating properly,
Reittinger and Burns acknowledge that the job of teaching is not as
easy as it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   But they also believe teachers can make a difference. They point
to studies showing that children who have endured horrible losses
can survive if they have one adult who understands them. More often
than not, that person is a teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a teacher around who can't tell that story,''
Reittinger said. ``I know we ask teachers to do an impossible job.
But we have to try.''
</P>
</TEXT>
