<SLUG> BC-TRAVELING-SAFELY-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHER'S LOSS LEADS TO SAFER TRAVEL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (l and t coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM A. DAVIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   She was in Kenya addressing an international conference of
surgeons who treat highway accident victims, Rochelle Sobel
remembers, when her eyes unexpectedly filled with tears. ``I
realized that if Aron hadn't been killed,'' she says, ``he would
probably have been one of those doctors.''
</P>
<P>
   Her son, Aron Sobel, died in a 1995 bus accident in Turkey that
also took the lives of 22 other people. He was 25.
</P>
<P>
   An honors graduate of the University of Maryland, Aron had just
finished his medical studies and was to begin a residency in
internal medicine at the Boston University Medical Center after his
Turkish vacation. ``He had everything going for him,'' says his
mother, ``except luck.''
</P>
<P>
   Luck, she says, is something you need a lot of when driving and
riding the highways of many countries. ``The leading cause of death
among healthy Americans traveling abroad is traffic and road
accidents,'' says Sobel, who has made publicizing that grim fact _
and trying to do something about it _ her life's work.
</P>
<P>
   After learning that her son's bus plunged over a cliff because
the driver was operating at a high speed at night on a twisting
mountain road where other fatal accidents had occurred, Sobel
researched Turkish highway accident statistics. She was appalled to
learn that Turkey has one of the highest road death rates in the
world _ almost 20 times that of the United States _ something that
Aron, like most travelers to Turkey, did not know.
</P>
<P>
   With the support of her husband, Dr. Solomon Sobel, she launched
a campaign to alert young Americans to the dangers of road travel
in Turkey. ``But we soon realized that the problem was much broader
and wasn't confined just to young people or to one country,'' she
says, ``and we wanted to try to save lives, not conduct a
vendetta.''
</P>
<P>
   She founded the Association for Safe International Road Travel
as a memorial to her son. The nonprofit group lobbies for highway
safety around the world and collects safety data on places where
the hazards are most serious.
</P>
<P>
   The association's publication ``Road Travel Reports'' includes
information on road conditions, driver behavior, seasonal hazards,
traffic safety statistics, and the most dangerous roads and regions
in 60 countries. The group's Web site, htpp://www.asirt.org,
contains travel tips and warnings, along with a sample road travel
report.
</P>
<P>
   A tiny woman _ less than 5 feet _ the 57-year-old Sobel exudes a
powerful sense of mission and a seemingly inexhaustible supply of
time and energy. ``I don't sleep much,'' she admits, ``not since
Aron died.''
</P>
<P>
   Sobel has waged an effective, essentially one-woman battle to
focus public and governmental attention on how the number of
traffic fatalities has reached epidemic proportions in many
developing countries. ``The president of Kenya supports my work,''
she says, ``because he has had two sons killed in road accidents.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not telling people not to travel,'' Sobel says, ``but you
should know before you go.'' As in every year, millions of
Americans will vacation overseas this summer, she notes, and most
will prepare for their trips by researching hotels, planning
itineraries, and checking to see whether they need shots or should
take other medical precautions. ``But they should also find out
what are the safe countries in which to drive _ or travel by public
transportation,'' Sobel adds.
</P>
<P>
   Although Third World countries usually have the worst highway
safety records, says Sobel, road travel can be dangerous in
developed regions, too. ``You expect Europe to be safe, and most of
it is,'' she says, ``but Portugal has the highest highway fatality
rate in Western Europe, much higher than in the US.''
</P>
<P>
   Largely because of Sobel's persistence, the US State Department
now includes information about driving conditions and hazards in
its advisories. The data is available on the department's travel
advisory line, at 202-647-5225, or downloaded from its Bureau of
Consular Affairs Web site: htpp://travel.state.gov.
</P>
<P>
   It's often difficult to determine just how dangerous it is to be
on the road when overseas, Sobel says, because many countries,
among them India, Pakistan, and Mexico, keep poor statistics and
furnish little information about accident rates to
statistics-gathering organizations such as the International Road
Federation. ``Aron's death certificate said that he died of
multiple injuries,'' notes Sobel. ``There was nothing about his
being in a bus accident, but that's what really killed him.''
</P>
<P>
   After a recent meeting with Sobel, the State Department
announced that, in order to get a better picture of the problem, US
consulates will begin compiling detailed statistics on the number
of Americans killed or injured in traffic accidents in their
jurisdictions. ``They told me it would cost money to do this, but
what could be more valuable than saving a life?'' she asks. ``I
slept better that night than I had in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Aron's camera was undamaged in the accident and was returned to
his parents with his effects. Among the photos on the roll of film
in it was the last one taken of him.
</P>
<P>
   He's smiling in the photo, a relaxed young man enjoying a
well-earned break. In his hand is the guidebook he used to plan his
trip: ``Let's Go: Greece and Turkey,'' one of the popular budget
travel guides published by the Harvard Student Agencies. The
``Let's Go'' guides, like virtually all others at the time,
contained no warnings about the danger of road travel.
</P>
<P>
   In response to Sobel's calls and letters to their writers and
publishers, most major guidebook series _ ``Let's Go'' among them _
added road safety information.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was impressed by the fact that she had suffered a terrible
tragedy and turned it into a cause to make her son's death means
something,'' says Tom Brosnahan of Concord, Mass., author of the
``Lonely Planet'' guide to Turkey, ``and she alerted me to a really
dire situation.'' His guide now warns: ``In the last decade, around
80,000 people have lost their lives and a million have been injured
in traffic accidents. Drive defensively. When traveling by bus give
preference to the better companies with newer equipment,
better-trained drivers and stricter policies about vehicular
safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Sobel runs her group from her home in Potomac, Md. The
association has a few corporate sponsors _ international companies
concerned with the safety of employees traveling overseas _ but
depends for support primarily on individual contributions and the
work of volunteers. Sobel estimates that she has spent about
$40,000 to further the cause, much of it to cover the cost of
attending international road safety conferences.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never really get over the death of a child,'' Sobel says,
``and I'll go anywhere and do anything to keep some other mother
from going through the hell I've been through.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(To obtain travel reports on various countries, available for a
suggested donation to the association of $5, call 301-983-5252, or
send e-mail to asirt(at)erols.com, or visit the Web site at
htpp://www.asirt.org)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
