<HEADLINE>
THE OPTIONS FOR MILOSEVIC 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and k coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- Imagine the poor boot-licker in the Serbian
government whose lot it is to tell Slobodan Milosevic that the
horrific error that sent US bombs into the Chinese embassy in
Belgrade may complicate diplomatic efforts to bring an end to the
butchery in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the guy saying that one result might be that the
Russians will pull back from their tentative brokering activity; or
that another might be Russian and/or Chinese decisions to use their
vetoes in the UN Security Council or simply to threaten to throw
sand in the peacemaking machinery's gears.
</P>
<P>
   Then imagine Milosevic going nuts with frustration at those
possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   From the all-important perspective of the person on whom all the
responsibility for what has happened in the Balkans for the past
decade rests, negotiations, shuttle diplomacy, and political
maneuvering are everything right now.
</P>
<P>
   There is only one way Milosevic can avoid the proper
consequences for his criminal actions _ his overthrow or his
incarceration for life _ and that is by arranging a deal that at
least enables him to claim to his complicit populace that Kosovo is
still Serbia's, if not that there is some remaining manifestation
of that control, preferably one that fudges the security guarantees
for returning Kosovar refugees just enough to keep many of them
from returning.
</P>
<P>
   For that to be possible, the dictator needs the Russians, the
Chinese, and the UN to help arrange such a deal as quickly as
possible, not pouting over a bombing mistake that took lives he
could give a hoot about.
</P>
<P>
   Without that diplomacy, all Milosevic has to look forward to is
a continuous, relentless assault from the air on his forces in
Kosovo and his strategic foundation in Serbia proper that has
already hurt him badly and can only hurt him far worse if it
continues to intensify.
</P>
<P>
   So far, it does not appear that Milosevic has much to fear from
the Russians. Another high-level US mission to Moscow to help them
in their work is still on for this week. Around here, Russians are
quietly passing the word that their business will go on.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese situation will remain clouded, however, at least
until the semi-hysteria directed at Americans there plays itself
out for better or worse. Some US officials suspect the Beijing
regime is trying to outflank its genuinely anti-US internal rivals;
others worry that the situation could get out of control. The State
Department's warning to Americans not to travel to China for the
moment was at least an ominous signal of how much is at stake.
</P>
<P>
   But the crisis in Kosovo does not appear to be involved. The
Chinese already have suffered a diplomatic black eye by
irresponsibly vetoing last January the UN resolution re-authorizing
its protective presence in continually threatened Macedonia. The
reason was Macedonia's recognition of Taiwan _ a classic example of
how relentlessly self-interested Chinese diplomacy can be; however,
Americans should be aware that had the mission retained its UN
character and not been taken over by NATO, those three American
soldiers would never have been kidnapped and beaten by the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   So far, however, Chinese diplomats have avoided any talk about
their UN responsibility in the venting that has followed the loss
of Chinese lives in Belgrade. Cautiously, US officials expect that
stance to continue.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic sure hopes so, and there's the irony. Negotiations are
his way out, and the danger is that they could lead to something
less than peace, and a lot less than justice.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the true hawks on this issue _ Democratic Senator Joe
Biden of Delaware, joined recently by Republican presidential
candidate John McCain _ disdain deals. They'd go to Belgrade, with
ground troops, to cut this cancer out of Europe once and for all.
</P>
<P>
   They have a point.
</P>
<P>
   The only justifiable counter is that the slaughter and mayhem
could end a lot sooner if the Russians behave responsibly and in
their own interest, and if they and the Chinese cooperate in the
establishment of an equally responsible UN role.
</P>
<P>
   The details, however, require negotiation, and that produces
Milosevic's last hope, and thus his fervent wish that the diplomacy
not be sidetracked.
</P>
<P>
   NATO obviously needs a good, up-to-date map of Belgrade. But it
also needs to stick to its basic aims, as well as to continue and
intensify the only pressure Milosevic understands.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
