<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HENNEKENS-HARASS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICAL RESEARCHER QUIT AMID SEXUAL HARASSMENT INQUIRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ARMSTRONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When world-renowned epidemiologist Dr. Charles H.
Hennekens resigned his appointments at Harvard Medical School and
Brigham and Women's Hospital in March, he cited ``personal and
family illness.''
</P>
<P>
   Hennekens, who led the study that determined that an aspirin a
day cuts the risk of some types of heart attacks, planned to move
to Florida to be with his ailing mother, his lawyer told reporters.
In a terse statement issued in response to press inquiries, the
Brigham and Harvard declined to comment about the departure because
of ``issues of employee confidentiality.''
</P>
<P>
   What neither Hennekens nor the institutions disclosed was that
the doctor's resignation followed allegations that he sexually
harassed more than a dozen women who worked under his supervision,
according to three sources familiar with the complaints.
</P>
<P>
   The sources said the complaints were investigated by lawyers
from both the hospital and Harvard. All three sources worked with
Hennekens at the hospital's Division of Preventive Medicine, and
one of them says she was victimized by him.
</P>
<P>
   Hennekens left his position at the hospital six weeks after the
women told their stories to the lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Contacted last week, both Harvard and the Brigham said they
would have nothing further to say about the resignation.
Hennekens's lawyer, Joel Kozol, would not answer questions, but
issued this statement from his client:
</P>
<P>
   ``In today's world, allegations of sexual harassment are easily
made and difficult to disprove. When they are made by people who
are unwilling to be identified, they are not worthy of response,
much less publication. Since the Globe has chosen to publish
anonymous allegations, I will state only that I have never in my
life sexually harassed anyone in the Division or anywhere else.
Those who know me know this to be true.''
</P>
<P>
   However, women who worked with Hennekens said that over a period
of several years, he subjected them to unwanted advances and other
inappropriate behavior, including questions about their personal
lives and in one instance, allegedly asking his secretary to order
specialized underwear for him.
</P>
<P>
   The sources said many of the women who worked with Hennekens
feared him and remained silent about the alleged sexual harassment
because they were concerned the doctor might hurt their careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was terrified of Charlie,'' said a female researcher who
asserted that her career was harmed after she spurned advances by
Hennekens. ``He is a very powerful man with a broad-based ability
to harm people. He is connected to all of the power brokers.''
</P>
<P>
   The sources agreed to discuss the allegations against Hennekens
only if their identities were protected. They said they were
convinced Hennekens would retaliate against them, even though he
has left Harvard and the Brigham. They said they wanted to discuss
what happened out of concern that Hennekens was considering
appointments at other universities and might behave in a similar
way there.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, officials at two medical schools, Oxford University in
England and the University of Miami in Florida, told the Globe they
were engaged in preliminary employment discussions with the doctor.
</P>
<P>
   The twice-divorced, 56-year-old Hennekens is widely considered a
superstar in the medical research field, and his cachet was such
that he was able to attract millions of dollars in grants for his
work.
</P>
<P>
   Findings from the three long-term studies he oversaw until March
resulted in international news coverage and changed the way some
diseases are treated and prevented. Along with the study that found
that the risk of men suffering a first heart attack was reduced by
taking an aspirin a day, Hennekens's team also found that birth
control pills don't raise the risk of heart attacks, coffee is not
a health hazard, and low-fat diets don't prevent breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   He also served as editor or co-editor at many of the leading
medical research journals, including the American Journal of
Preventive Medicine and the Annals of Epidemiology. At Harvard, he
was the Eugene Braunwald Professor of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, several of the 120 employees of the Division of
Preventive Medicine, began discussing Hennekens's especially harsh
treatment of a female researcher, the sources said. As the
discussion unfolded, some current and former employees began to
share stories of harassment and untoward sexual advances by
Hennekens, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Spurred by the ongoing treatment of the female staffer and the
realization that the alleged harassment was widespread, a group of
lab employees decided to inform hospital officials at the beginning
of this year of the allegations against Hennekens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a particularly egregious situation,'' said one of the
sources. ``It was very familiar to those of us who had been
involved with him and not surprising. That stimulated people to go
forward, partly in support of this other person, and also there
being a need for some justice.''
</P>
<P>
   After Harvard and Brigham lawyers interviewed many of the lab
employees, Hennekens was confronted with their allegations, the
sources said. At this point, he was only allowed to return to the
lab with an escort from the hospital administration, the sources
said. He returned once and was not seen at the lab again. Six weeks
after he was confronted, the news of Hennekens's resignation was
made public.
</P>
<P>
   The sources said some women alleged Hennekens retaliated against
them if they rejected his advances, and they suffered unfair and
unwarranted attacks on their work. In some cases, the sources said,
women complained they were subjected to criticisms of their
personal lives. Some women said their roles in major research
activities were minimized.
</P>
<P>
   Other women complained only of inappropriate sexual advances by
Hennekens, and said they did not suffer professionally. Some of the
complaints were made by former staffers who said the behavior dated
back several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would make a sexual advance to someone or in some cases,
like my situation, it was an explicit sexual proposition in which
the sexual nature of his request was completely clear,'' said the
woman who alleges she was victimized by Hennekens. She declined to
discuss specifics of his actions, concerned he would be able to
identify her. ``I was extremely fearful of the consequences of
rejecting him. From that point forward my work suffered. He blocked
whatever I tried to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Hennekens was so powerful _ and could literally make or
break a young researcher's career _ the sources said the women who
worked for him were reluctant to complain about his behavior.
</P>
<P>
   However, a secretary who worked for Hennekens obtained a
temporary restraining order against him and last year filed a
lawsuit in Suffolk Superior Court alleging he engaged in
inappropriate behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit was dismissed by a judge after a trial in which the
secretary represented herself. Hennekens, in an affidavit filed in
the case, denied all of the charges and his lawyer said the lawsuit
was baseless. His lawyer also said a judge refused to issue a
permanent restraining order in the case.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary, Wren M. Fournier, alleged Hennekens harassed her,
even driving by her home after work hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe Charles Hennekens to be dangerous and request
protection in every manner against him,'' she wrote in court
papers. In a separate document, she said, ``I am still afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   She said other women in the office also feared Hennekens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I observed inappropriate behavior . . . primarily leering at
other female staff members and their subsequent avoidance'' of
Hennekens, she wrote in her affidavit seeking the restraining
order.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1998, Fournier said she received an ``alarming
report'' that a female employee was being sexually harassed by
Hennekens. ``Hennekens will not take no for an answer,'' Fournier
said the other woman told her.
</P>
<P>
   Fournier also alleged Hennekens attempted to confide details of
his personal life to her, including information about his second
divorce. She also said he had personal items mailed to his office,
items she had to open as part of her duties. In one instance, she
was required to open a box that included specialized girdle-type
underwear he ordered. Later, he allegedly required her to fill out
an order form for Manshape brand underpants. ``I was humiliated,''
she said in court papers.
</P>
<P>
   Fournier declined to comment on her lawsuit or experience at the
lab.
</P>
<P>
   Since leaving his positions in Boston, Hennekens has talked to
at least two other institutions about jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Lawrence Gardner, chairman of the Department of Medicine at
the University of Miami Medical School, said he had had
``preliminary discussions'' with Hennekens, but added it was
``premature'' to say if he would accept a position at the school.
``He is obviously a giant in the field,'' Gardner said of
Hennekens. ``I would be thrilled.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Richard Peto, an Oxford professor and noted epidemiologist,
confirmed there has been discussion of Hennekens taking a position
at Oxford. He was unsure of the status of those talks. When asked
why he thought Hennekens resigned his positions in Boston, Peto
said, ``I still don't know what this whole thing is about.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Richard Saltus of the Globe staff contributed to this article.)
</P>
</TEXT>
