<HEADLINE>
HE'S THE CANADIAN ELVIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When you look at Martin Fontaine, with his short hair and
youthful appearance, the last person you might think of is Elvis
Presley. But that's before his two-hour makeup session that adds a
wig, sideburns, and a shading process that cleverly creates a
curling lip. Then when he steps on the stage at Le Capitole de
Quebec and starts to sing and shake, the crowd explodes because,
well, they're seeing Elvis.
</P>
<P>
   Fontaine has appeared on stage at the Quebec City hotel for four
summers now, attracting a total of 300,000 spectators with a
hip-swinging performance that includes 40 Elvis songs interspersed
with actual film footage and news clips and is accompanied by a
10-member chorus and band. The result is a re-creation of the
King's musical career, from the giddy beginning to the devastating
ending. This year, the show will run June 3 to Oct. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Don't call Fontaine an Elvis impersonator, though. ``Not a
chance,'' he says. ``I interpret, rather than imitate, his music,
which enables me to capture the feeling and, well, the frenzy that
he created.''
</P>
<P>
   The performer continues: ``After the show each night, though, I
go back to being Martin Fontaine.'' A good thing, too. A couple of
high-energy hours involving four changes of wigs and 16 switches of
costumes should be enough Elvis for any one man.
</P>
<P>
   (Ticket prices start at about $25 US. Dinner-and-show prices
start at about $40 US. A package including a dinner show, hotel
stay, and breakfast begins at about $95 US. For more information,
call 800-261-9903 or 418-694-4444.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
And speaking of songsters: A live and multimedia tribute show,
``Sinatra Remembered,'' makes its debut at the Casino de Montreal
later this month. For more information, call 800-665-2274. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel trivia: Close your eyes and try to visualize the Canadian
Mounted Police uniform. Now what color is the stripe? (Answer at
end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: Ottawa is derived from an Algonquin word meaning
``traders.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
They couldn't agree more: Nova Scotia and Massachusetts have the
same state/provincial flower: the mayflower, or trailing arbutus. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Fun, fun, fun: There is a theme park of sorts in Hokkaido, Japan,
called Canadian World. Its principal attraction revolves around the
fictional Anne of Green Gables of Prince Edward Island. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Language switch: Using 500 actors, Montreal studios each year
speedily dub 60-90 movies into French and sometimes English. Most
of the movies are from Hollywood. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Spacious: The field at Toronto's Skydome is big enough to hold 516
African elephants. Or 751 Indian elephants. Or eight Boeing 747s.
Or the Roman Colosseum. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Skinny: A Vancouver structure claims the title of world's thinnest
office building. It's a mere 6 feet wide. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Glub: All of New Brunswick was once under the sea. But that was 370
million years ago. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Freebie: Oh to be on Prince Edward Island on a sunny summer (or
fall, or spring) day. For a vacation planning kit that includes a
detailed visitors' guide and more than $275 in coupons, call
888-PEI-PLAY or visit www.peiplay.com/may. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? The stripe down a Mountie's pants is yellow. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
