<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(gm) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR WEDNESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, May 12:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 2 pages of stories, photos and graphics
on the crisis in Kosovo and the aftermath of the bombing of the
Chinese embassy in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ NATO sees no signs of Serb withdrawal
from Kosovo; fighting increases. And NATO says it gave no assurance
it won't bomb retreating troops until Yugoslavia accepts all its
demands. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA (Beijing) _ Viktor Chernomyrdin, the Russian envoy,
meets on Kosovo with Chinese officials, who stick to their demand
that NATO bombing must stop before the U.N. Security Council adopts
a peace plan. Demonstrations against the embassy bombing wane. By
Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA-STUDENTS (Beijing) _ Students at Beijing
University, who have been leading the anti-American protests, talk
about the U.S., China and Kosovo. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-EUROPE (Berlin) _ Europe's defense and foreign ministers,
spurred on by their inability to face conflicts in the Balkans with
a joint armed force, agree to build a common defense structure by
next year. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PRISTINA (Pristina) _ A feature on remaining ethnic
Albanians in Pristina, the Kosovo capital. By Steven Erlanger.
