<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2570 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RURAL-AIDS-HNS &LR;      05-11 1123
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RURAL-AIDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL-TOWN AIDS PATIENT FINDS MIXTURE OF FEAR AND KINDNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Photos available on the Wieck database)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROGER CROTEAU  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BRAUNFELS, Texas _ Robert Konkel has seen both sides of life
as an AIDS patient in a small town.
</P>
<P>
   He's felt the cold sting of discrimination and fear, like the
time a pharmacy worker brushed the pen he used into the trash
without touching it. He has endured hour-long ambulance rides to
another city because of the lack of specialized medical care and
other services in his home town.
</P>
<P>
   He's also seen the good side of small town life, with strangers
volunteering to drive him the 25 miles to San Antonio for medical
appointments and a church he'd never attended raising $6,000 to
help pay for his medication.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people I expected to accept it turned their back on me,
and people I never would have expected to embrace me have
wholeheartedly supported me,'' Konkel said.
</P>
<P>
   The stigma of AIDS as a disease to be ashamed of and hide lives
on in many small towns across Texas, as does the close knit
community life that can offer heartwarming support to people who
fall on hard times.
</P>
<P>
   It is a dichotomy that torments many HIV-positive people in
rural areas, driving some away from their homes, keeping others
desperate to hide their condition, while allowing others to live
openly and use their experience to educate others about AIDS
prevention.
</P>
<P>
   Konkel, 40, has chosen to work tirelessly to try to slow the
spread of the disease in New Braunfels and other towns, a deathbed
promise to his mother.
</P>
<P>
   A gay man who said he was once a drug user, Konkel has given
speeches on rural AIDS intervention at national AIDS conventions in
San Francisco, handed out literature and condoms at parks and truck
stops, and spoken to any group that will listen. Now he has been
nominated to the Ryan White Council, which makes decisions about
what anti-AIDS programs get funded.
</P>
<P>
   Konkel said he would bring the needs of rural AIDS patients to
the attention of national experts if his nomination is successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rural intervention is basically being ignored,'' said Konkel,
a long-time resident of this South Texas town of 33,000 people.
``That is my intent on trying to get on the council.''
</P>
<P>
   Comal County, of which New Braunfels is the seat, has had 4
reported AIDS cases and 23 AIDS-related deaths, with six new cases
in 1998, according to the Texas Department of Health.
</P>
<P>
   Texas ranks fourth _ behind California, New York and Florida _
in the number of AIDS cases reported. As the end of March, the
state had 49,636 known cases and 27,480 deaths resulting from AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS is an affliction in which the human immunodeficiency virus
weakens the immune system, subjecting the body to serious
infection. AIDS is most often spread through sexual contact,
sharing contaminated needles and infected blood products.
</P>
<P>
   Health professionals who work with HIV-positive people agree
that patients living in rural areas or small cities face special
challenges.
</P>
<P>
   The fear of the illness being exposed is often more acute than
that of AIDS patients in large cities. Small town gossip and the
stigma associated with AIDS makes the idea of living openly with
the disease unthinkable to many.
</P>
<P>
   Konkel said he has never regretted the night in 1995 he told the
City Council he had AIDS and begged the mayor to set up a Council
on AIDS, a step never taken.
</P>
<P>
   But he understands why others jealously guard their secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in rural areas with AIDS do anything to hide it,'' he
said. ``It never gets listed as a cause of death in obituaries.
People die of a disease that has no name. But the problem is out
here, that's why I make myself so visible.''
</P>
<P>
   Konkel said the support he has encountered, from the
fund-raisers to the network of friends and supporters who have
driven him to his frequent doctor's visits in San Antonio, can
largely be attributed to who he is. From a well-known local family,
Konkel had been active for years in several charities. He had a
deep well of goodwill built up.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Others are not so lucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went public in 1990 and as soon as that happened my son
became a target in the school system,'' said Laurie Lee, an AIDS
activist from the Corpus Christi area who asked that her last name
not be used. ``He was beaten. It ripped my heart out every time it
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   At age 7, Laurie Lee's son was taunted by classmates who changed
the words to the theme song from the Addams Family television show
to ``The AIDS Family.'' They called his mother a whore, and he
often came home bloody after the ensuing fights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so traumatic it made me run,'' said Laurie Lee, who
acquired the AIDS virus from her ex-husband. ``It made me teach my
children to lie and hide things.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she ran from Corpus Christi, a city of 275,000 people,
to New Braunfels to be near her family, but left after just a
couple of months. Although she said her children were beaten and
taunted in Corpus Christi, she still felt she could be more open
about her condition there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to the World AIDS Day service (in New Braunfels) and
everyone talked about the fear, not being able to talk about it. It
was the weirdest feeling. I felt so out of place because there was
so much fear and I had not felt it for so long,'' she said. ``The
whole atmosphere was different.''
</P>
<P>
   Confidentiality is so important in rural areas, AIDS patients'
identities are even kept from other AIDS patients, said Renee
Cantu. Cantu, an AIDS educator, used to work for a Rural AIDS
Services Program in the rural counties surrounding Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Cantu's job was taking AIDS patients to medical
appointments in Austin. Often she would pick up a patient and drive
right past another patient's house, only to return to later in the
day to drive the second patient to Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might think it would make sense to drive them together,''
she said. ``But you can't do that. They don't want someone from a
neighboring town to know they have AIDS, even another AIDS
patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Cantu said her rural patients were all-too-familiar with ``those
small town scandals that everyone talks about.''
</P>
<P>
   The desire for anonymity makes it more difficult to find clients
for the Rural Aids Service Program, said Assistant HIV Director
Stephanie Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are kind of in a Catch-22,'' Taylor said. ``We want to find
the people who need our services, but we don't want to be too
visible in these areas, because we don't want discrimination to
occur. We keep a low profile.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
