<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO CONFLICT
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-STRIKES _ WASHINGTON _ Forging a powerful union, Russia
and China called Tuesday for an immediate halt to NATO air strikes
against Yugoslavia, in a move that threatened to scuttle U.S.
efforts to win United Nations support for sending military
peacekeepers to the embattled province of Kosovo. NATO dismissed
the pleas of Beijing and Moscow and forged ahead with an
intensifying and escalating air campaign that winds up its seventh
inconclusive week on Wednesday. (Deans, Cox News Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move by 7:30 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES _ KUKES, Albania _ As the tide of refugees
continues to flow into here from neighboring Kosovo province,
frustrated humanitarian aid officials struggled Tuesday to increase
its ebb by asking for volunteers to move to southern Albania.
Meanwhile, their counterparts in Macedonia appeared to meet with
some success as Kosovo refugees from crowded camps in Macedonia
began to move to a new camp near the southern Albanian town of
Korca. Developing. (Holmes, Cox News Service). 20. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 5 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   GORE _ WASHINGTON _ Former Rep. Tony Coelho, a prominent
Democratic strategist, is named general chairman for Gore's
presidential campaign. (Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE _ The chairman of the failed Medicare reform commission
Tuesday lashed out at his fellow Democrats, charging that many of
them want a campaign issue more than real reform. ``There are
clearly those who don't want to do anything on this and use this as
a political issue,'' said Sen. John Breaux, D-La., who chaired the
recent Bipartisan Commission on the Future of Medicare. (Lipman,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WASTE-HUD _ If the third time wasn't a charm, perhaps the fourth
will be for the federal government in its attempt to unload one of
its longest-running housing disasters. Clifton Towers, just a short
drive from the U.S. Capitol and a symbol of subsidized housing gone
awry, is being offered to private developers for $1 plus a federal
promise of $8.2 million for renovations . Over the last 30 years,
three landlords allowed it to deteriorate into a crime and rat
infested neighborhood hazard. (Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS-CONGRESS _ WASHINGTON _ Congress on Tuesday begins
taking steps to respond to the Colorado school shootings. The
principal vehicle is a Senate juvenile crime bill that Democrats
hope to amend with gun-control measures. (Mollison, Cox News
Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   LINDER _ Rep. John Linder talks about how members of Congress
use the Internet aand about potential legislation to regulate its
use. (Sherman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MAIN _ ATLANTA _ President Clinton visits the Sweet
Auburn Curb Market today to unveil the administration's new market
strategies to encourage growth in underserved communities. Clinton
likely will call on private corporations to help small businesses
get established, grow and thrive in these communities. Atlanta was
chosen because it has a reasonably successful Empowerment Zone and
is home to some of the nation's richest corporations. (Campos,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SIDE _ ATLANTA _ Who will greet the president at the
airport? Will there be protesters? If this cannot stand as a
separate story, we will fold into the main. (Judd/Hendricks/Gibson,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MLK-DREAM _ ATLANTA _ The 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals on
Tuesday hears oral arguments in the case filed by the estate of the
Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. against CBS over King's ``I Have A
Dream'' speech. The estate is appealing U.S. District Judge William
O'Kelley's ruling last summer that the speech is in the public
domain and unprotected by copyright laws. (Rankin, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   MLK-DREAM-BOX _ ATLANTA _ Summary of parts of King's speech that
are the most quoted but were not in the original text. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 6.
</P>
<P>
   VALUJET _ Since last November, Lee Sawyer, a graduate of Emory
University in Atlanta, whose parents died in the 1996 ValuJet
crash, has returned to the Everglades to chronicle the slow rise of
a monument designed and built by volunteers to honor those killed.
A dedication and memorial ceremony coinciding with the third
anniversary of the crash was to be held Tuesday. (MWilliams, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   MUMMIES _ A brite on the new mummies that are coming to the
Carlos Museum at Emory University in Atlanta. Museum officials
arrive in Niagara Falls, Canada to begin preparations to ship the
artifacts south. Quotes from Carlos team and the Toronto art dealer
who sold Carlos the mummies. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-LOTTERY _ Texas Lottery Commission meets. Discussion
scheduled on efforts to make emergency purchase of scratchoff
tickets to avoid potential shortage created by snafus in signing
contract with firm to provide tickers. (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   ATTN: Texas editors.
</P>
<P>
   OHIO-POORKIDS _ COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Amanda was destined to be a
school statistic. Another example of how child poverty shoves
students to the back of the classroom. Her mom is poor, unemployed
and has moved the 4-year-old to different low-income apartments
around Dayton, Ohio three times in the last eight months. Only the
efforts of Dayton City Schools Head Start program kept the girl
from falling completely out of the system. But Amanda is one of the
lucky children, according to a report issued Monday by the
Children's Defense Fund in Ohio. The report, Helping Children
Learn, says 40 percent of Ohio newborns start life likely to live
in poverty and perform in the lower half of their class at school.
(Wagner, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-WILDFIRES _ PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ Nearly four weeks after a
most unwelcome visitor arrived, a dead calm remains settled over
Franklin Street. Acres of pine- and palmetto-studded forests turned
to kindling as the blaze, whipped by 30-mph winds, blackened more
than 700 acres between Florida's Turnpike and Interstate 95 and
caused some $4.5 million in damages. Although at least 42 homes
were destroyed citywide, few streets were hit as hard as Franklin _
a once-bustling verdant corridor now flecked with barren cement
slabs, denuded forests and Dumpsters filled with broken bits of
lives. ``I've never seen Kosovo, but I can imagine what the place
looks like after this,'' said David Keirs, whose large home on
Franklin was one of nine spared. ``We built here because of the
lush trees and the wildlife. Now I hate to open the blinds in the
morning.'' (Lane, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BAXTER-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ Georgia Gov. Roy Barnes has been
taking his sweet time making a slew of major board appointments
he's had on the table since the end of the legislative session,
submitting his applicants to thorough background checks and trying
the patience of various interest groups, as he laps the state
signing all the laws he got passed. Given the general anticipation
this has created, it was a little curious that when Barnes
announced his appointments for eight of the 11 state Board of
Education seats, he did so by fax and not with a photo-op press
conference. No matter, though: With the governor moving education
to the top of his priority list for the next year, the board
members should have plenty of time under the lights. (Baxter,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-SECURITY _ JERUSALEM _ Try as he might, Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has not been able to get any momentum
this election season behind his hardline stand on security and
confrontation against the Arabs. In a biting setback Tuesday, the
Israeli supreme court(CQ) squashed an order by Netanyahu to close
offices of the PLO in Jerusalem. Netanyahu's aides say the issue
had nothing to do with the elections or Netanyahu's slide in the
polls. But, he has allowed the office to function during his three
years in office until this week, when opponents said he was looking
to score points on his defense of Jerusalem. In 1996, a series of
suicide bombings were key in turning voters to the hard-line
Netanyahu. This year, there have been no major attacks. The prime
minister has resorted to showing video of the old bus bombings in
his campaign commercials. (Kaplow, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
