<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 14:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2600 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-HOUSTON-3TAKES     05-11 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-HOUSTON-3TAKES-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOWNTOWN HOUSTON GETS A MAKEOVER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 16) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By RICK LYMAN 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Five years ago, or even two, taking visitors for a night on the
town would have been to court absurdity, unless your goal was to
get them home early. Downtown Houston was a place where
well-dressed people worked in their tunnel--connected,
air-conditioned cocoons until about 5:30 p.m. and then beat feet
back to the suburbs, leaving behind a dark, empty grid of glass
canyons. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But downtown Houston _ at least the north end of it, spreading
out from the Bayou Place development and its adjacent Theater
District toward the renovated Rice Hotel and easing onward toward
the baseball stadium that will replace the Astrodome next season _
is a very different place now. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's practically, almost ... well why not say it? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's cool. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the people who haven't been downtown for a year almost
don't recognize it,'' said Rasheed Rafaey, owner of Tasca, one of
the popular new restaurants in the northern end of downtown, which
is known, inevitably, as NoDo. ``You had zero street traffic a year
and a half ago after 6 p.m.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The amazingly rapid resurgence of downtown is only one of the
major changes that have overtaken the nation's fourth-largest city
and perhaps its unlikeliest tourist destination. Kemah Boardwalk, a
new waterfront development on Galveston Bay about a half-hour's
drive southeast of downtown, has provided another fresh
destination, especially for families.
</P>
<P>
   And the city's justly celebrated cultural scene continues to
grow, with recent additions to the Menil Collection and several
other Houston museums, as well as a major wing about to be finished
at the Museum of Fine Arts. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Menil, one of the most beguiling private collections in the
United States, has opened a new exhibition space called Richmond
Hall, two blocks south of the original galleries, where a permanent
exhibition by Dan Flavin of blue, green, pink and yellow
fluorescent tubes runs along 125 feet of wall space in a former
grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, the Byzantine Fresco Chapel, completed in 1997, is home
to 13th-century frescoes from Cyprus; the chapel, a modern
structure of gray limestone and concrete, won an award for
outstanding architecture this year from the American Institute of
Architects. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Museum of Fine Arts' Audrey Jones Beck Building is set to
open in March, 2000, during the museum's centennial year,
stretching across two city blocks with 85,400 square feet of
additional gallery space. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the biggest beneficiary of the city's downtown
revival was the Theater District, the half-dozen blocks around
Jones Plaza at the corner of Texas and Louisiana Avenues. The urban
square is itself scheduled to be renovated and relandscaped soon.
The plaza is surrounded on three sides by the city's premier
performing arts centers: Jesse Jones Hall for the Performing Arts,
home of the Houston Symphony, the concrete castle of the Alley
Theater Company, the city's most prominent theatrical group, and
the towering, red brick Wortham Center, home to the Houston Opera,
the Houston Ballet and other companies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before downtown's renaissance, it was not uncommon for people to
come here for performances, then get out immediately. But after
Bayou Place, a combination of movie theaters, restaurants and
sidewalk cafes, was opened in the former convention center on Jones
Plaza a couple of years ago, more and more theatergoers began to
arrive early for a drink or dinner, or stay after the show, and the
whole plaza area shifted into a nighttime bustle. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Angelika Film Center and Cafe anchors the southeast corner
of Bayou Place, with an eight-screen movie complex offering art
films and high-end commercial fare (an offshoot of the Angelika in
lower Manhattan, in New York) and a popular lobby cafe offering
pastas, sandwiches, a particularly delicious curried chicken salad
and numerous wines by the glass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Bayou Place's northeast corner is the Sake Lounge, an almost
instant hit when it opened a couple of years ago, with its
combination of high-tech decor, sidewalk cafe tables and whimsical
Japanese fare (the spider roll is a sushi-style hand roll made with
soft-shell crabs). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And there are others. Mingalone's Italian Bar and Grill is on
Bayou Place's northern side, Slick Willie's pool parlor is
upstairs, and it was announced recently that the Hard Rock Cafe was
thinking of moving from southwest Houston to Bayou Place.
</P>
<P>
   Those looking for something more casual can try another popular
downtown spot, the Cabo Mix Mex Grill, just a couple of blocks east
of Jones Plaza, which offers a lot of the usual grilled meats and
Tex Mex fare to a sometimes overly convivial crowd. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The appearance in the last year or so of dozens of new housing
units, many of them New York-style lofts in previously empty
vintage buildings, as well as luxury condominium projects like the
renovation of the former Rice Hotel on Texas Avenue three blocks
east of Jones Plaza, added something that downtown Houston has been
missing for generations _ a stable residential base to help support
the restaurants and shops. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   More are on the way. Six new downtown condo and loft projects
with nearly 400 units are expected to open in the next year or so.
Within a few blocks of the Theater District, where once was
darkness, are about a dozen restaurants and bars, including the
Hogg Grill, a stately cafe serving traditional steak-and-chops
fare, and Sambucca, a Mediterranean restaurant and jazz club in the
former Rice Hotel. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Downtown Management District counts 29 restaurants
and nightclubs that have opened in the last couple of years in
downtown Houston and 16 more set to open in the next few months.
Only a handful of these offer fast-food fare, and an astonishing
number are stylish, high-end restaurants, like Tasca. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rafaey, who is also chairman of the Retail and Club Subcommittee
of the downtown historical district, remembers how difficult it was
for him to find investors in his planned downtown restaurant in
early 1997. Bayou Place was in the works, along with the renovation
of the Rice Hotel, but the announcement had not yet been made that
the Houston Astros would move to a new downtown stadium for the
2000 season. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a hard sell for the first six to eight months,'' he
said. ``People thought I was crazy..'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tasca, offering a combination of tapas and New American cooking,
opened in June of 1998. By that fall, he said, downtown had really
begun to take off. With its high ceilings, brick walls and large
pieces of contemporary art, Tasca resembles a Manhattan cafe more
than a Houston restaurant. On one recent evening, a throng of
smartly dressed young people clustered around the long bar while
vivacious waiters served and entertained those seated in the room's
booths and tables. Live jazz played in the background. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The late-night side of downtown's resurgence has been the
seemingly overnight influx of the city's cutting-edge nightclub
scene from the Montrose District, about a mile to the southwest,
and the so-called Richmond Avenue Strip, several miles further to
the west. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Typical, at least for one of the upscale places, is the Spy
Club, two levels of DJ-driven disco music and lavishly decorated
bars and dance floors that draws an overflowing crowd of
20-somethings most weekend nights. One recent evening the throng
included well-dressed young businessmen chattering into cell phones
(in the few quiet corners where the thumping music made that
possible) and young women in abbreviated dresses or astonishingly
ornate costumes (one group wore skin-hugging black body suits and
bright red wigs).
</P>
<P>
   There's even a tobacco-funky upstairs cigar room. Spy is also
almost alone in that it betrays nary a whiff of
country-and-western, still the mainstay of many Houston night
spots. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other popular downtown dance clubs include Club Some, Oz, and
the 804 Underground Lounge and Disco, all with multiple levels of
dancing and head-throbbing music. Rich's Night Club offers a
similar multi-level experience with an emphasis on Houston's
sizable gay population, except for regular ``hedonism nights''
aimed at a hetero crowd. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kemah _ from a Karankawa Indian word meaning ``wind in the
face'' _ sits on the southwest shore of Galveston Bay, a
thumb-shaped body of water fed by the Trinity and San Jacinto
Rivers that connects the Gulf of Mexico to the heavily
industrialized, man-made Houston Ship Channel.
</P>
<P>
   The Lyndon B. Johnson Space Center, home of NASA, is not far
away, and the area is a combination of aerospace, middle-class
suburban sprawl and weekend getaways for Houston's boating crowd. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The uninspiring, 20-mile drive from downtown Houston is
something to be endured rather than enjoyed, but the eventual
approach into the small village of Kemah provides some refreshing
gusts of gulf air and a sense of welcome remove from Houston
congestion and strip-mall hegemony. The boardwalk development
itself, approached under one of two archways, is a pleasingly
atmospheric jumble of ship masts, carnival rides and ersatz seafood
shacks.
</P>
<P>
   The 14-acre complex opened in February 1998, was badly battered
by a tropical storm the following summer and quickly put back in
order, with no storm scars in evidence. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Landry's Seafood Restaurants developed the project, home to the
largest Landry's in the chain, a casual seafood place with a bent
toward Cajun spicing, as well as to outposts of the company's other
restaurants, including Joe's Crab Shack, the Crab House and
Cadillac Bar, a Tequila-shooting Tex Mex sort of place. There is
also a 52-room Boardwalk Inn overlooking a splash fountain for
children, a train ride that winds entertainingly in, through and
around the development, a carousel, a 65-foot Ferris wheel and
several other kiddie rides.
</P>
<P>
   But the undisputed centerpiece of the development since its
opening early this year has been the Aquarium Restaurant, a
three-story affair on the boardwalk's western edge that draws in
almost as many tourist-gawkers as it does diners. Described by
developers as an ``underwater dining adventure,'' the Aquarium is
built along theme-park lines, offering a sensory as well as a
culinary experience that begins with an entrance that resembles an
underwater cavern out of ``The Little Mermaid'' and a staircase
that wraps around a dazzling tube of water at least six-feet
across, glowing bright blue and filled with fish. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The third floor is reserved for special buffets and private
functions, but the second floor is the complex's show-stopper, a
bar and restaurant with stunning views of the water and a
wrap-around assortment of aquarium tanks, including a 55,000-gallon
one that feeds views of dozens of sea creatures into the cavelike
dining area and the outdoor patio. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The place is run a bit like a military operation; waits can be
long and, while there was no sign of hurry in the pace, tables are
turned over with amazing rapidity. But for a place with such an
emphasis on decor and sensory experience, the kitchen is terrific,
with a flair for all manner of gulf seafood, especially shrimp, and
a tendency to smother fresh flounder and haddock in mountains of
delicious crab meat, scallops and other fruits of the sea. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Still, most night-life expansion in Houston continues to be
downtown _ which is something of a godsend to residents playing
host to out-of-town visitors. The pleasures of life in Houston _
and they are many _ tend to revolve more around its neighborhoods
and rich restaurant and night-life scene.
</P>
<P>
   Houston has no Liberty Bell, no Statue of Liberty, not even an
Alamo, so it used to be a bit of a chore to figure out what to do
with visitors. The monolithic and crenelated glass towers have
always been a strong lure, but until recently they offered only an
empty promise. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No longer. Now, a morning in the lush gardens at Bayou Bend or a
visit to the Space Center can be followed by a lunch of barbecue or
Tex Mex, an afternoon at the Menil and an evening downtown _ drinks
at a sidewalk cafe overlooking Jones Plaza, a play or a concert,
and a wonderful dinner at any one of a dozen nearby restaurants. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We're not talking New Orleans here. It's not even San Antonio,
with its beautiful River Walk, or even the funkier night life
stretches on Sixth Street and the Warehouse District in Austin. But
it's a start: people on the streets, music filtering from smoky
rooms, neon and bustle, the crackle of cosmopolitan life. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With downtown resurgent, Houston has begun to feel _ both for
residents and for visitors _ more like a city in the round. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A guide to finding the hot spots &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
