<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL NOTES AND NEWS 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 16) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
AT THE FIELD MUSEUM, A WORM'S-EYE VIEW 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Field Museum in Chicago has just completed a
15,000-square-foot permanent exhibition that will, through the
illusory magic of a curator's wand, shrink visitors to
one-hundredth of their normal size and set them loose in a
subterranean wonderland. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Guests begin their visit to Underground Adventure at the
Scientist's Base Camp, where they are briefed on the remarkable
``technology'' that is going to shrink them to half an inch,
enabling them to see eye to eye some of the Earth's least well
known and most prolific organisms. Visitors then file into the
Shrink Chamber, which optically downsizes them.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 4,000-square-foot total immersion portion of the exhibition
teems with soil-packed jungles of gargantuan dangling roots,
burrowing worms and ravenous wolf spiders. Visitors can crawl
through vacant worm holes and discarded exoskeletons and observe a
moving four-foot centipede or 11-foot crayfish. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After visitors have toured the Micro Soil Lab and its 3,000
organism replicas and 6 animatronic, or moving, displays, they will
pass through the Reverse Shrink Chamber and be restored to
``original'' size.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other areas in the exhibition include the Mud Room, where
visitors can examine real soil and organisms. There are also
interactive computer stations where agrarian enthusiasts can try
their hands at solving modern soil challenges and manage a
1,000-acre virtual farm.
</P>
<P>
   The Field Museum, which is open daily, is on the Museum Campus
on Lake Shore Drive and Roosevelt Road. Admission is $7; $4 for
children ages 3 to 17. Admission is free on Wednesdays. Underground
Adventure costs an additional $4; $2 for children. Information:
(312) 922-9410. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CELEBRATING 75 YEARS OF VERMONT'S PARKS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vermont will mark the 75th anniversary of its state park system
this summer with programs on crafts, wildlife and history. Aside
from campsites, swimming areas and hiking trails, many of Vermont's
50-plus state parks contain remains of logging camps, iron
smelters, early settlements, mills, railroad beds, mines and
quarries.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Little River State Park in Waterbury, for example, is
crisscrossed with old roads and stone walls dating from the early
1800s. The foundations of houses and barns, the remains of farming
equipment, a sawmill and sugarhouse are all visible in the hills
above the campground. Along the river are reminders of the massive
Civilian Conservation Corps project that built the 835-acre
Waterbury Reservoir in the 1930s. A printed guide is available for
a ``history hike'' through the area. During the summer season, the
park offers evening pontoon-boat cruises on the reservoir.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 14 and 15 have been designated History Weekend at the state
parks, with such events as ``Walk Back in Time'' at Quechee State
Park, Indian programs at Grand Isle and North Hero parks and a
history cruise of Lake Champlain from the Burton Island State Park
The folk singer Margaret Mac-Arthur will perform at Emerald Lake
State Park in Dorset on Aug. 14 at 7:30 p.m. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other events include fishing clinics on June 12 (at Bomoseen
State Park in Fair Haven, Brighton State Park in Island Pond and
Lake Carmi State Park in Enosburg Falls); a Wood Carvers Week July
25 to 30 at Grand Isle State Park; a Crafts Weekend June 26 and 27,
and an Understanding Nature Weekend, July 31 and Aug. 1.
Information: (800) 837-6668 (select 2 on the voice-mail options),
or www.vtstateparks-.com. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
IN ALASKA, ECO-TOURS START WITH A COPTER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You've heard of heli-skiing. Why not heli-hiking? Outdoor
enthusiasts will be able to drop into southeast Alaska this summer
on Alpine Excursions Heli-hiking Tours, offered by Cape Fox Tours
of Ketchikan, Alaska. Cape Fox's tours focus on history, native
heritage and wilderness ecosystems. The heli-hiking expeditions,
which will run through Sept. 30, will allow visitors to experience
and learn about the diverse Alaskan ecosystem that thrives above
the timberline, at 3,200 feet. Participants are flown 20 minutes by
helicopter from George Inlet, 13 miles from Ketchikan, then led on
a 90-minute hike through the alpine environment where wolves, black
bears and three species of ptarmigans reside. Back at George Inlet,
visitors tour an old cannery and take a short walk through the rain
forest there. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tours are geared to cruise passengers, groups and the general
public; about $230 a person. Information: (907) 225-4846, extension
317 or 310. In summer, you can book in person at the Ketchikan
Visitors Bureau, (907) 247-6605. &QL; 
 &QL; 
REPASTS OF THE PAST AT HISTORIC HOUSES IN BRITAIN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Several National Trust sites in Britain will offer visitors a
chance to sample a taste of history this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Sara Paston-Williams, an expert on historic recipes, has trained
National Trust chefs to recreate a range of dishes appropriate to
the age and location of each property. Wherever possible,
ingredients are grown on site or are locally produced. Chefs are
encouraged to research family records and diaries to find recipes
used by the residents of each house or characteristic of the area. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Properties in Devon, Cornwall and Wessex (Bristol-Bath, Dorset,
Somerset and Wiltshire), Uppark in West Sussex, Ham House in
Richmond, Knole in Kent, and Hidcote Manor Garden and Snowshill
Manor in Gloucestershire are among the places that will be serving
historic food. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For example, at Petworth House in Sussex, the food will be from
the medieval period and will include baked salmon with wine sauce
($9.90) or potted butter beans and fresh herbs ($5.80); at Cliveden
in Buckinghamshire, Victorian-Edwardian dishes will include George
Bernard Shaw's nut roast ($8.65) or spinach and Stilton flan with a
nutmeg crust ($8.65), and for dessert gooseberry and elderflower
fool ($4.40); at Ham House in Richmond, Stuart and Restoration
dishes include local pork, lemon and ginger sausages in an
applesauce casserole ($9.90), or spiced onion tart ($9.60). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meals will be served at the properties' on-site restaurants. In
most cases it is not possible to make reservations, so visitors are
advised to call in advance and arrive early. Most properties are
open through October, and some reopen during Christmas to serve
traditional seasonal fare.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The National Trust Handbook and the Historic Dishes at National
Trust Properties pamphlet are available from the National Trust
Membership Department, Post Office Box 39, Bromley, Kent BR1 3BR;
telephone (44-181) 315 1111. The handbook is also available from
bookshops in England; $7.50. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CORRECTIONS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An entry in the International Datebook listing on May 2 for Maya
folklore festivals in Guatemala misstated the dates. They are July
22 to July 25, not June 28 to July 4.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Practical Traveler column on May 2, about code sharing _ the
sale of tickets by one airline on another line's flight, but under
its own flight number _ cited one example erroneously. Delta is not
seeking government approval to put its code on Finnair flights to
Moscow and St. Petersburg, Russia.
</P>
