<HEADLINE>
EGYPT: THE CONVOY ROUTE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 16) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By NANCY R. NEWHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   While I wasn't obsessed with security on my first visit to Egypt
in late February and early March, I certainly had it in mind. And I
wondered to what degree tourism had recovered from its
near-collapse after the tragic massacre of 58 tourists by Islamic
militants at the temple of Hatshepsut near Luxor in November 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The short answer is that a huge security operation is in place
at tourist sites in Egypt, and tourism is definitely back, if not
to 1997 levels. According to the Egyptian Ministry of Tourism,
visits dropped from a record high of almost 4 million in 1997 to
under 3.5 million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   After a brief stop in Cairo, my husband and I flew to Luxor
ahead of our Nile cruise departure and took a day trip to the
temples of Abydos and Dendera, about three hours north of Luxor by
car. Our guide set an early departure time of 7:30 the next
morning, and we soon understood why. For trips out into the
countryside, tourists must now go in convoy, with a truckload of
soldiers armed with submachine guns front and back. The convoys
left Luxor daily at 8 a.m., 2 p.m. and 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   When we arrived at the departure point, there was a cheerful
hubbub as vans, enormous buses, taxis and cars congregated and
soft-drink vendors worked the crowd; not too long after the
appointed hour, we steamed off in single file. Passing through
villages was something of an event, given the long convoy, with
friendly Egyptian children waving and jumping up and down as we
passed. At every major crossroads, armed soldiers were highly
visible.
</P>
<P>
   After about half an hour on the road, the convoy split into
three, with the largest group by far going to Hurghada for a day's
outing on the Red Sea. Again, each of the three smaller convoys had
soldiers front and back. The escort stayed with our group of four
or five vehicles for the whole trip.
</P>
<P>
   Outside every temple and tomb in the Nile Valley that we visited
on our own and as part of the cruise, soldiers were posted at the
entrances and dotted around in strategic spots. In Abydos, behind
the temple, I gazed at two robed figures sitting on camels on a
bluff, romantically profiled against the sky. It took a few minutes
to see that they too were carrying submachine guns.
</P>
<P>
   Temple and tomb sites on the principal tourist artery of the
Nile between Luxor and Aswan were clean and orderly, unless you
count desert dust. But in Abydos, which is somewhat outside that
circuit, we were sorry to see the bleak square in front of the
temple, with an appallingly filthy restroom and a forlorn cafe
(closed at the time).
</P>
<P>
   It seemed particularly dreary in contrast to the richly green
farmland of the Nile Valley that we'd driven through, where farmers
cut sugar cane and impossibly small white donkeys ridden by large
men trotted alongside irrigation canals _ the harvest page from an
Egyptian Book of Hours.
</P>
<P>
   Given the setting at Abydos, I prepared myself for
disappointment, particularly because from the outside, the mortuary
temple of Seti I (1294-1279 B.C.), constructed by him and his son
Ramses II, looks somewhat unimpressive. But the interior of this
temple, with its glorious painted wall reliefs, is a marvel that
rivaled anything we saw in Egypt. In fact, when I later mentioned
Abydos to Yassin Yassin, our superbly well-informed guide on the
Abercrombie &AMP; Kent Sunboat IV, he remarked: ``Oh, but you saw the
best first! You should have seen it last.''
</P>
<P>
   Passing through the later and less fine First Hypostyle Hall
into the Second, you enter a shadowy forest of heavy columns, with
exquisitely decorated limestone walls. (We regretted not having a
small flashlight. for the darker areas.) In places the paint has
faded, so that many scenes, incised in elegant high relief, are
alabaster pale, which only accentuates their perfection.
</P>
<P>
   The color in others is still remarkably intact. A row of seven
small chapels opening off this hall is also beautifully adorned
with scenes of Seti and various deities. There were just a handful
of tourists at Abydos (unlike the crowds at Karnak and the temple
of Hatshepsut), signs of deterioration on some walls, and one lone
guardian for the whole temple _ the price, perhaps, of being off
the main Nile Valley tourist circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Prosperous turn-of-the-century travelers went in style, a fact
confirmed by two famous grand hotels along the Nile, the Old Winter
Palace in Luxor (built in 1886 by Thomas Cook) and the Old Cataract
in Aswan (built in 1899), both recently spiffed up to their earlier
luster. We spent two nights in the Old Winter Palace, and rejoiced
in the high-ceilinged rooms, the wide hallways, and the general air
of slightly faded grandeur.
</P>
<P>
   Although Nile-view rooms are the most sought after, we took the
somewhat less expensive garden view on the theory that we would see
plenty of the Nile on the cruise. Then we congratulated ourselves,
because our balcony overlooked the oasislike palm garden, a riot of
greenery and birds. (The original old section of the hotel is kept
separate from the unattractive large new wing, although both share
the garden and enormous pool.)
</P>
<P>
   For a splurge, we reserved a day ahead for dinner in the 1886
Restaurant, a small luxury restaurant that is separate from the
main dining room; the food and service were good, and we had a nice
bottle of Chablis for $35 _ memorable because imported wine was
prohibitively expensive elsewhere in Egypt, including on the cruise
ship, and Egyptian wine is only for the determined.
</P>
<P>
   Although we didn't stay at the Old Cataract Hotel in Aswan,
where our cruise ended, we skipped a shipboard event to take the
ferry across the river to see it. Grandly situated above the Nile
in a spacious garden, the hotel lives up to its Agatha
Christie-enhanced reputation and then some, the fabulous Moroccan-
and Middle East-eclectic decor an exotic melange of dark red walls,
filigreed wooden screens, wondrous light fixtures and arabesque
arches.
</P>
<P>
   The dining room alone, a cavernous domed space with an
atmosphere of Arabian Nights gloom, was worth the visit.
Gratifyingly, some of the guests looked either like older English
country gentlemen or cast members from ``The English Patient.''
</P>
<P>
   When we returned to traffic-crazed Cairo, among many small
random pleasures we encountered was the marvelous puffy bread,
baladi, baked to order in beehive ovens by two costumed women just
outside Kebabgy, a pleasant kebab restaurant situated right on the
Nile in the El Gezirah Sheraton.
</P>
<P>
   Another hotel with marvelous views of the river, in this case
elevated well above it, is the Meridien-Le Caire. It is on the
north end of the island of Roda. Nonguests can have tea or drinks
on the breezy terrace if they meet a hefty minimum; the hotel's
24-hour restaurant and coffee shop, La Brasserie (there is also a
more upscale restaurant), with a jaunty yellow and blue decor,
offers the same view, glassed in.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   An easy walk from the Meridien brings you to the Manial Palace,
built in 1903 by King Farouk's cousin. Although in his excellent
guide, ``Egypt,'' for Cadogan, Michael Haag describes Manial as
``bizarre kitsch,'' lovers of period decor will enjoy the sumptuous
turn-of-the-century tile work and the palace's atmosphere of kooky
luxe (bypassing two other buildings, the hideous, mostly
faux-French ``throne room'' and the depressing little hunting
museum).
</P>
<P>
   And in the lovely palm-shaded garden is a small, dusty museum
displaying, along with various oddities, a fine collection of
Islamic calligraphy and Oriental rugs.
</P>
<P>
   We were intrigued to see women, some in Muslim-style head
scarves, smoking water pipes both at Kebabgy and at the Abou Aly
cafe in the Nile Hilton, a popular spot with Cairenes. We assumed
water-pipe-smoking was strictly a male affair. It seems that some
free-spirited Egyptian women have taken it up in the last few
years. One of our male guides grumbled wryly that this recent trend
boded ill for Egyptian men.
</P>
<P>
   There is a distinct pattern to an exploration of Cairo's
medieval quarter (confusingly called Islamic Cairo), from bustle to
tranquillity and back again. Making your way through the narrow,
dusty streets teeming with hawkers and hurried pedestrians and men
balancing trays of bread on their heads, past small shops and down
crooked passageways, you arrive at one of the many ancient mosques,
some of which are not easy to find.
</P>
<P>
   Yet stepping inside, you are suddenly in a place of utmost quiet
and repose, generally with just a few other visitors or a guardian
who will request a small baksheesh. Since Cairo's mosques are built
on an open plan _ the four interior sides open onto a courtyard _
they feel airy and accessible.
</P>
<P>
   A few trees or even an interior garden sometimes add to the
sense of calm. I was amazed at the cool air that seemed to waft
naturally through the arcades in these mosques, a sign of the early
architects' skills.
</P>
<P>
   In the vast interior of Ibn Tulun, built in the 9th century and
restored in the 13th, birds flit through the deeply shadowed
arcades, and it is hard to imagine the mosque's enormous courtyard
filled with the thousands of worshippers it was built to
accommodate. Because we were saving our energy for a many-mosque
day, we didn't climb the minaret, but later wished we had for the
view. Unlike any other minaret in Cairo, it has a spiral walkway
winding around the exterior, giving it a surprising, Oz-like
quirkiness in the otherwise austere structure.
</P>
<P>
   On a completely different, intimate scale, yet again a place of
complete peace, is the lovely mausoleum of Qaytbey. It is in a
decrepit section of the Islamic quarter not far from the City of
the Dead, an area our driver disapproved of and that we might have
spent a good while finding without our guide. (We hired a guide and
car one day to tour the old quarter; a second day we walked on our
own, once we had the lay of the land.)
</P>
<P>
   This 15th-century Mameluke mausoleum is as warm and colorful as
an Oriental carpet, with its original jewellike stained glass
windows set in typical deep stucco frames, its elaborate floor
paving and dome of dizzying carved complexity. There were only two
other visitors in the echoing interior, a far cry from what must
have been its brilliant heyday. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hotels
</P>
<P>
   ASWAN Sofitel Old Cataract Hotel, Abtal El Tahrir Street; (20)
97 31 60 00, fax (20) 97 31 60 11; double rooms from $165 in the
old building, $116 in the new one, including buffet breakfast for
two; the Agatha Christie Suite, $655 with breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   CAIRO Meridien-Le Caire, northern tip of Roda Island; (20-2)
362-1717, fax (20-2) 362-1927; La Brasserie restaurant and coffee
shop, open 24 hours; terrace overlooking the Nile, open from 9 a.m.
to 10 or 11 p.m., with a minimum charge for nonguests of about $6 a
person, at $3.25 to the Egyptian pound. Doubles start at $190.
</P>
<P>
   LUXOR Sofitel Winter Palace, Corniche el-Nil Street; (20-95)
380-422, fax (20-95) 374-087; doubles start at $160 in the old
section, $80 in the new. In the 1886 Restaurant, dinner for two
with wine costs around $90; open daily. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Museum
</P>
<P>
   Manial Palace Museum, northern Roda Island, Cairo; (20-2)
368-7495. Open 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. daily (last entry at 4); admission
$3. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants
</P>
<P>
   Kebabgy, El Gezirah Sheraton Hotel on Gezirah Island in Cairo;
(20-2) 341-1333. Restaurant with terrace on the Nile and indoor
seating. Lunch and dinner every day. Dinner for two with beer,
around $48.
</P>
<P>
   The Abou Aly cafe at the Nile Hilton, on Tahrir Square in
central Cairo, (20-2) 578-0444, is open daily, 10 a.m. to 2 a.m.,
serving meals, drinks and tea; the minimum charge is $7.70 a person
for nonguests.
</P>
</TEXT>
