<HEADER>
A2627 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-MYSTERIES-REVIE     05-11 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MYSTERIES-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEPHEN HUNTER RETURNS WITH A TERRIFIC THRILLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BOBBIE HESS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fans of Stephen Hunter's series featuring sniper Bob Lee Swagger
will not be disappointed by ``Time to Hunt'' (Island Books, $7.95,
paperback, 592 pages).
</P>
<P>
   In the spring of 1971 as Vietnam War protesters overrun
Washington, Cpl. Donny Feen, 22, is stationed at the Marine
Barracks in the capital. With only 13 months left to serve, Donny
is a short-timer and unlikely to be sent back to the Land of Bad
Things, as the Marines call Nam. But things go south when two
officers in the Naval Investigative Service ask him to spy on Pfc.
Edgar Crowe, who is believed to be leaking information to the peace
protesters.
</P>
<P>
   Donny reluctantly agrees to do so and meets one of the big
leaders of the movement, Trig Carter. At one of Trig's parties,
Donny runs into his fiancee Julie, a nursing student in from
Arizona for the big peace march. When the naval investigators
arrest Crowe, Donny refuses to testify and is shipped off to
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Donny becomes Swagger's spotter and the two take on a battalion
of Viet Cong to save a Marine outpost from being overrun. Donny
gets a leave, goes to Hawaii and marries Julie.
</P>
<P>
   When he gets back, Swagger has gotten Donny assigned to a desk
job for the remainder of his tour. But Donny refuses the job, and
returns to spot for Swagger. Word gets out that a Russian sniper is
in the area and Swagger sets out to trap him.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, Swagger is still haunted by his memories of
Vietnam. He now lives on a ranch in the Sawtooth Mountains of
Idaho, with his wife and their 8-year- old daughter, Nikki. On a
morning ride, a sniper kills a neighbor and wounds Swagger's wife.
Now Swagger must dig deep into the past to discover why someone is
trying to kill him and his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time to Kill'' starts out slowly and I began to think the
first half should have been edited down drastically. But as Hunter
develops his engrossing tale, I realized how well he laid the
groundwork for Swagger's hunt for the sniper. ``Time to Kill''
really exposes some of the demons of Swagger's past.
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't read Hunter, start with ``Black Light,'' ``Dirty
White Boys'' and ``Point of Impact.'' If you are already a Hunter
fan, rush out and get a copy of ``Time to Hunt.'' It's terrific.
</P>
<P>
   (``The Sands of Sakkara.'' By Glenn Meade. St. Martin's Press.
</P>
<P>
   $29.95. 400 pages.)
</P>
<P>
   One of my fondest travel memories is of a brisk November morning
outside Cairo. As I was pulling into the parking lot at the Step
Pyramid of Sakkara, a tour bus was pulling out. For one hour, I was
the only tourist exploring this wondrous structure.
</P>
<P>
   When Glenn Meade's World War II spy thriller came across my desk
it went to the top of the pile.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sands of Sakkara'' begins when the body of an elderly
white man washes up on the banks of the Nile in Cairo. New York
Times reporter Frank Carney believes it is the remains of Johann
Halder, whose German father's priceless Egyptian artifact
collection disappeared during the war. The elder Halder was killed
during the bombing of Hamburg in 1943 and the son was believed
killed during a secret mission the same year.
</P>
<P>
   Carney goes to the dead man's apartment. There he runs into Col.
Harry Weaver, who for more than 40 years was an adviser on American
presidential security. And Weaver gives Carney a great story, with
a stipulation: He can't print it until after Weaver's death.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Halder was the son of an American mother and a wealthy
German industrialist. Harry Weaver's father worked on the Halders'
New York estate and the two boys became the best of friends. In the
summer of 1939, the two join an archaeological dig at Sakkara.
There they meet Rachel Stern, the daughter of the dig's German
leader. Both fall in love with the beautiful Jewish woman.
</P>
<P>
   When war is declared, Halder heads for Germany to enlist.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Weaver returns to the States and enlists. Rachel and
her family were believed killed when their ship bound for Istanbul
exploded.
</P>
<P>
   In 1943, Weaver is assigned to the Cairo Embassy as an
intelligence officer. When embassy security is breached prior to
the secret summit meeting of Winston Churchill and Franklin D.
Roosevelt at Mena House near the pyramids, Weaver and British
intelligence officer Alfred Samson are assigned to hunt down German
operatives in Egypt. In Berlin, Halder is ordered to lead a mission
to Egypt to kill FDR. One of his operatives will be Rachel Stern,
who has been interned at Ravensbruck concentration camp.
</P>
<P>
   Meade weaves well-developed characters into a complex plot that
moves with a brisk pace. His vivid descriptions of the sights and
sounds of Egypt made me feel like I was back at Sakkara.
</P>
<P>
   (``The Alternate.'' By John Martel. Dutton. $24.95. 417 pages.)
</P>
<P>
   John Martel puts an unusual spin on the legal thriller _ and it
works.
</P>
<P>
   Lara Ashford, a former beauty queen married to former Rep.
Elliot Ashford, had been unfaithful. When she is brutally murdered
in their Pacific Heights mansion in San Francisco, Elliot is the
only suspect the District Attorney's Office is willing to consider.
</P>
<P>
   Ashford hires a big-name attorney from Los Angeles to defend
him. But he needs someone local and well-respected to help at the
bail hearing, so Barrett Dickson is brought in. Once the best
litigator in San Francisco, Dickson is now on the skids. But the
search for justice helps him dry out as he sees a rush to judgment
against his client _ for everyone involved has a hidden agenda.
</P>
<P>
   The client has a real alibi he can't reveal because he was
meeting with a Illinois gangster on parole. If the judge finds out
the gangster left the state, he'll go back to prison for a long
time.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Earl Field wants to use the case as his
springboard to the governor's mansion.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant District Attorney Grace Harris begins to have doubts
about how Field is handling the case when a crucial piece of DNA
evidence disappears.
</P>
<P>
   Alternate juror Amanda Keller, a former soap opera star now
working as head file clerk, will do anything to get Ashford
convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Martel's legal thriller is a smart look at the politics and
legal maneuvering of a front-page murder case. His characters are
well-developed as the story moves along at a sturdy pace. I would
hope that a juror could never get away with Amanda Keller's
actions, but it sure makes for a fascinating twist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
