<HEADER>
A2631 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JEDI-JUNKIE-HNS &LR;      05-11 1338
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEDI-JUNKIE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFESSIONS OF A JEDI JUNKIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JASON LLOREN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As far back as I can remember, I've always
wanted to be a Jedi.
</P>
<P>
   To me, being a Jedi was better than being Superman. Sure,
Superman could fly, bend steel, see through walls, and carry a
tanker on his back. His body bulged out of his blue jumpsuit and
his red cape waved around him like an American flag.
</P>
<P>
   But the Jedi were cooler. They wore samurai robes and tapped
into the Force to mind-trick opponents and move objects. They flew
fancy ships in space like they were doing laps at the Indy 500.
</P>
<P>
   And they carried the coolest weapon ever dreamed up: the light
saber, a glowing, humming blade of energy that could cut through
flesh and steel like butter.
</P>
<P>
   Face it, a Jedi could kick the Kryptonite out of Kal-El. Any kid
who saw ``Star Wars'' when it first burst onto the big screen in
1977 knew that.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 16 years after ``Return of the Jedi'' played in movie
houses, my friends and I are busily arranging our vacation time
around the May 19 opening of ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom
Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because we still remember the tragedy that befell Jedi
master Obi-Wan Kenobi, the menace inspired by Darth Vader's
presence and the excitement of the dogfight-like Death Star battle.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the new movie is half of that experience, it'll be worth
the effort.
</P>
<P>
   I first saw ``Star Wars'' when I was 7, the perfect age for this
sci-fi space saga to make an impression. My dad drove me all the
way from our suburban Pittsburg home to San Francisco's Alexandria
Theater to see it.
</P>
<P>
   We didn't even see it opening day; we waited as it gained more
attention _ and drew longer lines of moviegoers. Back then it was
not the phenomenon it is today. At first, it was just some sci-fi
flick, just a curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to see what the big deal was about this space film,''
my dad said recently, almost dismissively.
</P>
<P>
   The film opened up a whole new world to me. ``Star Wars'' was
more than a movie _ it was a journey I shared with my friends and
family, that spurred my imagination.
</P>
<P>
   It gave me a love of science fiction, of films and ultimately of
heroes.
</P>
<P>
   The movie introduced us to Luke Skywalker, still just a kid, who
hung out with these cool droids, a giant rug called a Wookie, a
space cowboy named Han and a gorgeous chick named Leia (a princess,
at that). They hopped around in sleek spaceships and used blasters
to fight off the bad guys.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, even Darth Vader, frightening as he was, became part of
the fun. He was a cool villain.
</P>
<P>
   The Cantina scene introduced us to these weird creatures and
aliens. The Death Star represented this menacing globe. The final
X-Wing battle scene turned out to be a wild ride, and we were there
in the backseat like R2D2.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Kenobi and the mysterious Force he talked about
at length. I grew fascinated with this omnipresent ``energy field''
he spoke of, one that surrounds us, penetrates us and binds the
galaxy together. It was something more than magic but short of
being God. It was heady stuff for a kid to comprehend but that
didn't matter. What the Jedi had, I wanted: to learn the Force and
to wield my own light saber.
</P>
<P>
   My friends and I settled for the toys and our own imagination to
recreate the magic of the film. My dad used to buy me stacks of
``Star Wars'' collector cards, so many that the shoe box that I
stored them in bulged on the sides. Buying those packets of bubble
gum and cards became a ritual for us; we'd drop by the gas station,
he'd pick me up four or five packs at a time, like they were
cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   For my circle of friends, ``Star Wars'' was a way of life aside
from family and school. We'd grab sticks and have make-believe
saber duels in our back yards. My friend Ben and I would gobble up
the action figures, space vehicles, whatever; as soon as they hit
the toy shelves we'd somehow convince our parents they were
necessities.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, we seemed to be competing. I bought a Leia and Luke,
Ben got the TIE Fighter. I got the rolling Landspeeder, he snagged
an X-Wing. I blew him away by getting the multilevel Death Star
playset with working elevator, exploding cannon, extending bridge
and garbage compactor with crushing wall.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it was a marketer's dream that fed the toy companies'
profits. But it also fed our imagination.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My love of ``Star Wars'' went beyond the toys and the cards.
</P>
<P>
   Using my action figures, vehicles and my dad's black-and-white
video camera, I recreated scenes from the film. I'd stage light
saber fights between Vader and Kenobi using crude animation. It was
pretty pathetic, but I was consumed by the Force. There was no
Blockbuster Video then and ``Star Wars'' wasn't on VHS until the
mid-'80s, so I'd try anything to relive the movie in whichever way
I could.
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Wars'' became a part of our culture, a part of our
consciousness. And it keeps coming back. When ``The Empire Strikes
Back'' was released in 1980, it fed our hunger. It was another
journey into fantasy, another roller-coaster ride.
</P>
<P>
   The images left an indelible impression: Elephant-like AT-Ats
walked the snowy plains of planet Hoth. Luke first met Jedi master
Yoda on a gray swampy planet. A giant asteroid worm nearly
swallowed the Millennium Falcon. Han and Leia visited a city that
floated among the clouds. Luke and Vader engaged in a saber duel
filled with fury and suspense.
</P>
<P>
   Swamps, snow planets, asteroid fields? Again, George Lucas
painted a strange yet wondrous world _ and the movie was even
better than the first ``Star Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   Heck, I can't even remember where and when I first saw
``Empire'' _ aside from the movie itself, all I recall are even
longer lines at the box office and more booty in my toy chest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Return of the Jedi'' brought the Force back three years later.
</P>
<P>
   Even though I had outgrown the toys (temporarily), I was hyped
on the film. I remember the day after it opened, a bunch of kids in
school kept bragging about how good the film was. One kid had
boldly predicted, ``It's gonna beat `E.T.''' at the box office (it
didn't; ``E.T.'' made $704 million internationally versus
``Jedi's'' $471 million).
</P>
<P>
   From 1977 to 1983, ``Star Wars'' captured the imaginations of an
entire generation. There was always talk about Lucas making
``prequels'' (movies set before the events in ``Episode IV''), but
it always seemed like Hollywood rumor fodder. ``Star Wars'' slowly
receded into our collective subconscious.
</P>
<P>
   Even though I still longed for the return of the Jedi, by the
mid-'80s I had given up. There would be no more, I told myself.
</P>
<P>
   Then came a rebirth. In 1997, Lucasfilm released the ``Star Wars
Trilogy: Special Edition.'' The classic was back, freshened with
new scenes and enhanced special effects. My friends and I waited
hours in line at the cinema for all three of the reissued films;
joining us were a whole new legion of fans just discovering the
trilogy.
</P>
<P>
   The new effects weren't what made the films so special. The
reason ``Star Wars'' never escaped my imagination was because it
generated such enthusiasm on a basic narrative level: It was modern
mythology for my generation. It was a galaxy-spanning tale of
bravery, faith and redemption. It was an incredible story when I
saw it in 1977; it remains one today.
</P>
<P>
   The gods of Greek, Norse or Roman mythology have remained with
us for a long time. For me, so has Luke Skywalker.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly I find myself 7 again. I've been buying the toys. My
roommate and I _ both of us thirtyish _ were dueling with toy light
sabers in the living room the other day (we broke one) the way two
guys would toss a football.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen years after ``Jedi,'' Lucas now brings us ``The Phantom
Menace.'' I honestly never thought I'd live to see the prequels.
</P>
<P>
   I guess the Force has been with us all along.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
