<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW THE WILD WEST LOOKS TO A REFUGEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - It's the first time you've been on a commercial
airplane, or maybe any airplane, and you've been inside it for so
long that day and night have overlapped, leaving you trapped in a
haze of dawn _ or dusk _ where the sun never quite rises or sets.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't what you wanted.
</P>
<P>
   You didn't want to leave your home in Kosovo, which is all
you've ever known, all you ever wanted to know.
</P>
<P>
   You didn't want to leave the refugee camp, where at least the
landscape and some of the faces were familiar.
</P>
<P>
   You didn't want to get on this airplane and fly across the ocean
and then across the North American continent to this place called
Arizona, which you couldn't find on a map if your life depended on
it.
</P>
<P>
   And now your life depends on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I think of these people,'' says Maureen Webster, director
of the Phoenix area Catholic Social Service, ``I think of courage.
We act sometimes as if it would be so easy to come to the United
States, that everybody wants to come here. But imagine what that
would be like if you were one of these refugees.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Land of palms and pools &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The plane descends and you look down at the land, which isn't
green and hilly like the place you were born, but brown and flat,
like a plank sticking out from the edge of the Earth.
</P>
<P>
   The words on the signs in the airplane mean nothing. The crew's
English is noise in your ears, like crickets on a summer night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We first meet the refugees we're assisting at the airport,''
Webster says. ``We'll have someone there who speaks their language,
to translate for the social worker. We'll pick up whatever baggage
they have _ often very little _ then we'll drive them to the
apartment we've rented for them. Usually, it's a place not too far
from our offices (at 19th and Northern avenues), so we can keep in
close contact.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone in the airport is in a hurry. Outside it is too warm
for May, and even on the ground you can see to the ends of the
Earth.
</P>
<P>
   The road you drive on is unbelievably wide and filled with too
many cars. In spots it lifts up over other roads with even more
cars. To the west of the airport are the towers of downtown, set
like chess pieces on an enormous playing board.
</P>
<P>
   The radio music you don't like, and the radio voices you can't
understand. Everywhere are squares of houses bordered by palm trees
_ (begin ital) palm (end ital) trees _ and tiny pools in the yards,
which you saw from the airplane and asked about and couldn't
believe it.
</P>
<P>
   But it's true.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
New home, new life &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a large Albanian population here,'' Webster says,
``so I don't know how many refugees from this conflict we'll get.
But we'll get some. We've had many wonderful people offering to
help. And the refugees will need it. They all do, whether they come
from Eastern Europe or Asia or Africa. We get them every year,
about 1,700, from all those places, and it's tough on them all.''
</P>
<P>
   The apartment you arrive at is small and clean, but where is it?
You couldn't find it again if you wandered off. You couldn't ask
directions. The social worker says if there's trouble you can dial
911. But what trouble? It was trouble that put you here.
</P>
<P>
   You are told you must get a Social Security number, whatever
that is, which you'll need to get a job.
</P>
<P>
   You may be a doctor or a lawyer or a college professor. It
doesn't matter in this strange place, where every few feet there
seems to be a restaurant from which the smell of cooking hamburger
drifts onto the road like fog.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us have no idea what a transition like this is like,
or how scary it is for these people,'' Webster says.
</P>
<P>
   Or, maybe you do.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe your first trip to Arizona was like a trip to the moon.
Maybe you couldn't relate to the landscape and thought the people
here dressed funny and acted funny and talked funny. Maybe you
believed at first there was no way you could live and work here.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe, like me, you'd only flown in from Pennsylvania. &QL; 
 &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
