<HEADER>
A2640 &Cx1f; tdt-z
b x &Cx13;  &Cx11;   &LR; FRIDAY May7 1999 05-11 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 FRIDAY, May 7, 1999
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aliza Marcus
</P>
<P>
   ISRAELI POLITICIANS WOO THE RUSSIAN VOTE
</P>
<P>
   TEL AVIV -- With a bit more than a week left before Israelis go
to the polls to elect a new prime minister, the two leading
candidates have turned the campaign into a race for the crucial
Russian immigrant vote.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has unveiled a package of
benefits for World War II veterans from the former Soviet Union,
and has strongly hinted that if he were reelected, the powerful
Interior Ministry portfolio would be given to a party representing
Russian immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, the Labor party leader, Ehud Barak, suggested
making a national Israeli holiday of May 9 -- the date Russia
celebrates its victory in the war. And, he said, he would provide
special social benefits for veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a very aggressive campaign on the street for the
Russian vote,'' said Boris Yentin, an editor at the
Russian-language daily newspaper Vesti.
</P>
<P>
   Polls have found that Netanyahu is losing support among voters
from the former Soviet Union, who make up almost 15 percent of the
electorate and in 1996 were key to bringing the Likud leader to
power.
</P>
<P>
   Backing for Barak has risen to almost 40 percent among what is
called ``the Russian vote,'' a big jump from the 25 percent of a
few months ago, according to a poll yesterday in Vesti. Netanyahu's
support dropped to 55 percent from 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been some disappointment in Netanyahu's policies and
Barak is making a good showing, representing himself as a man who
struggle for Israel and promising many things if he takes office,''
Yentin said.
</P>
<P>
   But Netanyahu may have scored some points yesterday when he
persuaded the strictly observant Orthodox Shas party, one of the
key members of his outgoing coalition, to apologize for derogatory
comments made about the Russian immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   In its campaign advertisements, Shas has called Russians
``counterfeiters, con men and call girls.'' This has led to a
crisis because another main Netanyahu coalition partner is a
Russian immigrant party, Yisrael B'Aliyah. Barak and Netanyahu have
been trying to attract support of Yisrael B'Aliyah, which is headed
by the former Soviet dissident Natan Sharansky.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sharansky was a minister under Netanyahu, he has
refused to give public support to Netanyahu's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Backing from Sharansky, whose party is a favorite among Russian
voters, would be a boost to either candidate, and both are playing
to him.
</P>
<P>
   When asked by Israeli newspapers how he felt about the
attention, the short, balding Sharansky said: ``They've finally
come to realize that I'm a handsome, tall man with thick curly hair
-- let me enjoy myself.''
</P>
<P>
   But the issues that Sharansky is promoting for his Russian
constituents go to the heart of many of Israel's internal
conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   About 800,000 people from the former Soviet Union have emigrated
to Israel in the past decade, helping to increase Israel's
population to 6 million, and providing a wealth of talent in
science, medicine and high-technology fields.
</P>
<P>
   This immigration has also brought problems. Israel's economy has
been unable to absorb everyone, leaving some immigrants stuck doing
poorly paid jobs far below their skills. Overall, Israel's
unemployment rate is almost 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   At least a third of the new immigrants are not considered
Jewish, according to religious law, under which the mother must be
Jewish. The issue is delicate, because marriage, burial and divorce
are controlled by the religious authorities, and those whose
Judaism is in question may face obstacles for all three. Because
the Interior Ministry registers citizenship, Russian immigrants
have many complaints about the Shas party, which under Netanyahu
has controlled the ministry. This has put Netanyahu in a difficult
position, because he is trying to woo both the strictly Orthodox
Jews and the Russians at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   In another arena dealing with the Russians, Netanyahu may have
received an unexpected present from Barak, although the origin of
the gift is clouded. Barak printed up Russian translations of his
published biography, which details his life as one of the country's
top military officers. And this week, it was found that the
Russian-language version had been doctored to make it sound as if
Barak was willing to divide Jerusalem and hand over part of it to
the Arabs.
</P>
<P>
   This does not go over well with Russian voters, who generally
take a more hard-line position on negotiations with the
Palestinians and the return of occupied land.
</P>
<P>
   The writers of the biography said the original had made it clear
that Barak had never said anything about giving up part of
Jerusalem, while his Russian translator said her version was also
true to the Hebrew original.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu has not waited for the mystery to be solved. His
political campaign ads have highlighted the disputed statements as
proof that Barak is ``soft'' on the Arabs.
</P>
</TEXT>
