<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-GOLAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELECTION NEAR, ISRAELIS DEBATE GOLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALIZA MARCUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KATZRIN, Golan Heights -- As far as Yoav Tsur is concerned,
living on the Golan Heights is the closest thing to heaven on earth
-- or maybe it is heaven itself.
</P>
<P>
   He owns a house in a quiet town where people leave their doors
unlocked, he drives to work on empty roads lined with flowers, and
he runs his own company on a hilltop with breathtaking views all
around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here because I loved this area and I still do. Somehow,
I must be crazy to be willing to give this all up,'' said Tsur.
</P>
<P>
   More than 30 years after Israel captured the Golan Heights from
Syria, the 44-year-old engineer stands on the front line of a new
battle for the strategic plateau.
</P>
<P>
   This time, though, the fight is among Israelis: between those
who would keep the Golan forever and those who believe it should be
returned to Syria as part of a comprehensive peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
   With national elections set for May 17, the two camps are
digging in on the heights, where some 17,000 Jews have set up home
since the 1967 war. Posters and bumper stickers are the weapons of
choice, as politicians and residents here push their platforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure my kids understand why I am willing to leave our
home,'' said Tsur, whose three children were born on the Golan.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if giving up the Golan means peace with Syria, then how
can I stand against that, even if it means abandoning my house and
my life?'' asked Tsur, a founding member of ``Way to Peace,'' a
group of Golan residents who support trading land for peace with
Syria.
</P>
<P>
   But another group, the Golan Residents Committee, argues that
the land must never be returned to Syria. Until Israel occupied the
plateau, Syria used it to attack Israeli towns in the Galilee
below.
</P>
<P>
   ``Syria has a terrible reputation. They may want the Golan but
they are not interested in peace,'' said spokeswoman Marla Van
Meter.
</P>
<P>
   Some politicians think the latter position wins votes.
</P>
<P>
   The Third Way, a centrist party that is part of Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu's Likud-led coalition government, has taken to
the campaign trail with a slogan that promises the Golan Heights
will always remain in Israel's hands.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu, meanwhile, has chastised the previous Labor
government for what he said was its willingness to hand over all of
the Golan Heights to Syria. At a recent Cabinet meeting, Netanyahu
accused Labor of planning to ``retreat to the banks'' of the Sea of
Galilee.
</P>
<P>
   According to a new study for the Jaffee Center for Strategic
Studies in Tel Aviv, more than 70 percent of Israelis polled either
do not want to return the Golan or would support only a partial
return.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the West Bank, which has religious significance for Jews,
ties to the Golan Heights are based on its strategic importance.
Rising nearly 1,300 feet above the Jordan Valley and comprising
about 485 square miles, the heights not only provide a direct line
of fire into Israel or Syria, but they also sit on top of important
water reserves. It is easy for Israel to maintain control on the
Golan, which was annexed in 1981, because most of the 100,000 Arabs
who lived there fled during the war.
</P>
<P>
   Labor leader Ehud Barak, Netanyahu's main rival for prime
minister, has not specified what he would give up for peace with
Syria, but he has promised to bring any agreement to a referendum.
Negotiations with Syria have stalled since Netanyahu took office
three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   A Barak adviser said Israelis tend to be hesitant on giving up
land until faced with the real possibility of a peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order for the Israeli public to be willing to give back the
whole Golan Heights they need to see and touch and look at a
package and that's not there now,'' said Alon Pinkas, Barak's
foreign policy adviser.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that might change people's minds is a growing sense
that Israeli soldiers should not have to die in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Syria has 35,000 troops stationed in Lebanon and there are some
who say the road to peace in Lebanon runs through Damascus.
</P>
<P>
   And for engineer Yoav Tsur, the way to peace with Syria runs
through the Golan and he wants to make sure politicians hear this.
</P>
<P>
   ``People love the Golan and want to keep the Golan, but I
believe in the end the majority of Israelis will go for peace even
if the price is giving back the Golan,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
