<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-OCALAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGER AT KURD MILITANT EXTENDS TO HIS TURKISH LAWYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALIZA MARCUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL -- Ahmet Zeki Okcuoglu no longer frequents his favorite
restaurants and rarely walks down the street alone. Public
transportation is out, as is any activity that requires him to mix
with strangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am simply afraid,'' said the bespectacled 51-year-old
Okcuoglu, one of the lead lawyers for Kurdish rebel leader Abdullah
Ocalan, whose trial begins later this month on charges of treason
and separatism.
</P>
<P>
   Ankara says nearly 10,000 soldiers and civilians have died in
his Kurdish rebel war for self-rule in southeast Turkey, making
public hatred of Ocalan so high that his lawyers are coming under
attack for defending a man dubbed ``baby killer'' by the press.
Some have received death threats.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, lawyers said they were beaten by police who were
escorting them away from the courthouse in an armored vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to be lawyers, not heroes,'' Okcuoglu said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   The capture in February of Ocalan is celebrated by Turks, who
say Ocalan and his Kurdistan Workers Party (PKK) are terrorists out
to destabilize Turkey. Since Ocalan's arrest, Kurdish suicide
bombers have staged attacks, only increasing anger at Ocalan.
</P>
<P>
   Ocalan is specifically charged with ordering killings of
children, teachers and other civilians in his fight for Kurdish
self-rule.
</P>
<P>
   There appears to be little question that Ocalan, who is the sole
inmate on an island prison, will be found guilty. There is no
disputing that he founded the PKK and that since 1984 the rebel
group has been waging a war in southeast Turkey that continues to
this day.
</P>
<P>
   Okcuoglu said he and his team of 20 lawyers will use the trial
to argue that Turkey represses its Kurdish minority and that
repression underlies the rebel war. ``I hope this court case will
be an opportunity for Kurds to explain the problems they face and
what rights they want to have,'' said Okcuoglu.
</P>
<P>
   Okcuoglu said he will argue that Kurds have long been denied
basic ethnic rights by the Turkish state and that those who have
chosen nonviolent methods of protest have been punished as much as
those who have taken up arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the start the state only gave Kurds the chance to fight
for their rights by resorting to guns and violence,'' said
Okcuoglu, himself jailed three times in the past 10 years for
speeches and articles in which he criticized Turkey's policies
toward Kurds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both sides should be judged, Turks and Kurds,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kurdish complaints focus on laws that restrict expression of
Kurdish identity. The Kurdish language is not allowed to be taught
in schools nor used in TV broadcasts. Books on Kurdish culture are
often banned as ``propaganda'' while people have been jailed for
interviewing Ocalan or calling for changes in Turkey's policies
toward the Kurds.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey argues such restrictions are necessary to protect against
separatist movements. In the past Turkish politicians have said
that it was impossible to consider changing the laws while the
country was fighting what it calls terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest of Ocalan is seen by some Kurdish and Turkish
intellectuals as a chance for Ankara to reevaluate its treatment of
the Kurdish minority, which makes up an estimated 20 percent of
Turkey's 65 million people. ``This is definitely an important
opportunity for Turkey, now they can say they have the violence
under control and it's a chance for the state to make some changes
in its policies,'' said Akin Birdal, chairman of the independent
Human Rights Association.
</P>
<P>
   Birdal and others argue that restrictions on Kurdish identity
and abuses committed by soldiers fighting the rebels have helped
fuel the rebel movement.
</P>
<P>
   Some 3,000 Kurdish villages in the southeast have been emptied
in the course of the war, and human rights activists said many
villagers were forced out by Turkish soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A country that closes down democratic routes for dealing with
problems ends up strengthening violence,'' said Serafettin Elci, a
61-year-old Kurdish politician and well-known opponent of Ocalan
and the guerrilla war. His party was closed down by the high court
earlier this year because the platform advocated Kurdish ethnic
rights, which the court said constituted ``separatism.''
</P>
<P>
   But Turkey's position has hardened since the capture of Ocalan,
who for years had been based in Syria until Ankara pressured
Damascus to kick him out last year.
</P>
<P>
   Caretaker Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit has said there is no
Kurdish problem in Turkey, only an economic problem stemming from
lack of investment and job opportunities in the poverty-stricken
southeast.
</P>
<P>
   The second largest party in parliament, after Ecevit's party, is
the far-right Nationalist Action Party, which also denies existence
of a Kurdish problem. The expected coalition government is not
expected to make any concessions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
