<SLUG> BC-PROSECUTOR-SENTENCED-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER TEXAS PROSECUTOR TO DO PRISON TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ A federal judge sentenced a former state
prosecutor to five years in prison for selling leniency to drug
defendants in what the government described as ``pervasive
corruption'' in the Webb County district attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public is concerned about this type of conduct, and I
think the city of Laredo would want to purge itself of people that
bring it shame,'' U.S. District Judge John Rainey said Monday in
sentencing Ramon Villafranca, the former Webb County assistant
district attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Villafranca, 59, stood silently as he was ordered to prison for
63 months and fined $10,000. Villafranca, who was an elementary
school principal in Laredo before becoming a lawyer, was allowed to
remain free on bond pending an order to report to prison.
</P>
<P>
   Rainey said Villafranca's actions eroded public trust in the
Webb County district attorney's office, but the judge rejected a
bid by prosecutors for a sentence of up to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am concerned about the loss of public confidence in this
matter,'' Rainey told the defendant. ``I hope this does send a
message we cannot tolerate this in a civilized society.''
</P>
<P>
   Rainey predicted other public officials were watching Monday's
sentencing and would be influenced by its outcome. Villafranca's
two-week trial in January included witnesses Jesse Salas, a bounty
hunter who secretly worked for the FBI, and Ruben Garcia, a former
state district judge who testified the he had split bribes with
Villafranca.
</P>
<P>
   Octavio Salinas, the lawyer representing the former prosecutor,
said the federal government brought shame to Laredo.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could have prosecuted him without making the circus that
this case has become,'' Salinas told the judge. Salinas criticized
the investigation and the May 1998 federal raid on the offices of
Joe Rubio, the Webb County district attorney, and other officials.
</P>
<P>
   More than 5,000 criminal case files were seized, as well as
financial and other documents, during the federal investigation of
Villafranca.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Don DeGabrielle said the sentence
satisfied him. ``It sends a message that corruption will not be
tolerated,'' DeGabrielle said outside court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
