<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SUMMER-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMER'S HOT SPOTS: 10 U.S. EVENTS THAT REALLY SIZZLE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By SYD KEARNEY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The living may be easy in the summertime, but selecting a place
to spend your vacation can be downright tough. There simply are too
many appealing destinations, attractions and events from which to
choose.
</P>
<P>
   Here are 10 U.S. events or attractions that may be the best of
the last summer of the 1900s:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ISLANDS OF ADVENTURE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dinosaurs and Dr. Seuss take center stage at Universal Studios'
Islands of Adventure, which will have its grand opening later this
month in Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The 100-acre park is part of a $2.8 billion expansion that
Universal execs hope will level the playing field with Disney as a
destination resort. The new expansion includes CityWalk, an
entertainment and retail district, and Portofino Bay, a luxury
hotel. The additions and the existing movie-themed park are being
touted as Universal Studios Escape.
</P>
<P>
   With two major roller coasters, high-tech motion simulators,
splashy water rides and a painstakingly reproduced Jurassic Park,
Islands of Adventure provides central Florida its first real thrill
park. Universal adds family appeal with Seuss Landing, where the
Cat in the Hat comes alive and guests ride sofas into the whimsical
storybooks of Theodore Geisel.
</P>
<P>
   One-day tickets for Islands of Adventure are $42 ($34 for
children). Travel packages that include park admission, lodging and
car rental are available. Call 407-363-8000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SPOLETO FESTIVAL &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For 17 days, Charleston, S.C., will be the arts capital of
America. The 1999 edition of the Spoleto Festival runs May 28
through June 13 and boasts more than 120 performances.
</P>
<P>
   Among the highlights for 1999 are ``Songs and Stories from Moby
Dick'' by performance artist Laurie Anderson, the Charleston
premiere of ``Mamba's Daughters'' by Dorothy and DuBose Heyward,
and a new production of Giacomo Puccini's ``Il Trittico.''
</P>
<P>
   Other featured performances include the Ballet Flamenco de
Antonio Canales, Kurt Weill's opera ``Die Burgschaft'' and
sleight-of-hand artist Ricky Jay.
</P>
<P>
   In its 22 years, the Spoleto Festival has presented 91 world
premieres and more than 80 U.S. premieres. Each year more than
100,000 people enjoy opera, theater, chamber and symphonic concerts
and dance performances.
</P>
<P>
   For a schedule of events, call 843-722-2764 or access
www.spoletousa.org. Ticket prices vary by event. Call 843-723-0402
for tickets.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
PORTLAND ROSE FESTIVAL &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stop and smell the roses _ hundreds of thousands of them _ at
the Portland Rose Festival in Oregon. The 25-day extravaganza kicks
off June 3 with the coronation of the Rose Queen and runs through
June 27.
</P>
<P>
   Now in its 91st year, the Rose Festival expects to draw more
than 500,000 guests with its more than 80 events. Highlights of the
schedule are the Grand Floral Parade (one of three festival
parades), a juried art show, a symphony concert with guest artist
Ray Charles, boat and car races, flower shows and a ferret fair.
</P>
<P>
   The theme of this year's Rose Festival is ``Set Sail for Fun.''
One of the spotlight events is Fleet Week, when dozens of ships
from all over the world dock on the Westside Seawall of the
Willamette River to welcome visitors. Festivalgoers can tour
vessels of the U.S. Navy, the Coast Guard and the Royal Canadian
Navy.
</P>
<P>
   For a schedule of events, contact the Portland Rose Festival
Association at 503-227-2681 or access www.rosefestival.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TELLURIDE BLUEGRASS FESTIVAL &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For four days each year, the town of Telluride, Colo., and its
symbiotic neighbor, Mountain Village, swells from a community of
1,500 to more than 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Telluride Bluegrass Festival is an EVENT as thousands pack
Town Park to hear music artists ranging from folk to traditional
bluegrass and blues. This year's festival, which will be June
17-20, will feature Willie Nelson, Leo Kottke, Bela Fleck &AMP; the
Flecktones, Earl Scruggs and Friends, Shawn Colvin, Steve Earle and
Mary Chapin Carpenter.
</P>
<P>
   Held in conjunction with the festival, the Telluride Bluegrass
Academy presents music workshops, songwriter competitions,
performances and family activities such as clown acts and a petting
zoo.
</P>
<P>
   The ``festivarians,'' most of whom camp just outside of town,
are as entertaining as the performers. The permit-required camps
become satellite cities filled with campfire jams and communal
kitchens.
</P>
<P>
   Telluride limits vehicular traffic in town for the festival's
run. Only residents and guests staying in the in-town lodging are
permitted to park. The rest of the crowds are shuttled in by bus,
or they bike or hike into town.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you are not a bluegrass fan, festival time can be fun.
The people-watching is outstanding, and while the campgrounds may
be packed, you'll never need a reservation at the town's many fine
restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   If you tire of crowds, just take a free gondola ride up to the
Mountain Village and blissfully empty hiking trails.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets to the Telluride Bluegrass Festival are sold out this
year, but it is never too early to start planning for next year's
festival. No date has been set for the 2000 event, but you can get
on a mailing list to receive ticket and lodging information. Call
Planet Bluegrass at 800-624-2422 or access www.bluegrass.com.
</P>
<P>
   For Telluride visitor information, call 888-827-8050 or access
www.telluride.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SMITHSONIAN FOLKLIFE FESTIVAL &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More than 1 million visitors are expected to take part in the
Smithsonian Folklife Festival, which will stretch along the Mall in
Washington, D.C., June 23-27 and June 30-July 4.
</P>
<P>
   Co-sponsored by the National Park Service, the festival
celebrates America's cultural traditions in concerts,
demonstrations, workshops and panel discussions. This year's event
will spotlight New Hampshire, Romania and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Paying tribute to New Hampshire, craftsmen and artists will
demonstrate canning and preserving, boot making and boat building.
The event also will feature Yankee fiddling and the raising of a
post-and-beam barn.
</P>
<P>
   Music and dance groups from Moldova, Transylvania and Wallachia
will perform as part of the Romanian program, while a Swazi house
will be constructed on the Mall in a demonstration of South African
crafts.
</P>
<P>
   Festival hours are 11 a.m.-5:30 p.m. each day. In addition,
dance concerts will be 5:30-7 p.m. daily. Special evening events
are offered 7-9 p.m. except July 4. All events are free.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Smithsonian visitor information is available by calling
202-357-2700 or accessing www.si.edu. During the festival, a hot
line (202-357-4574) will provide descriptions of daily events.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NEW ORLEANS &QL; 
WINE &AMP; FOOD EXPERIENCE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One lament commonly heard last week in New Orleans during a Jazz
&AMP; Heritage Show weekend: ``The locals don't go anymore. Too many
tourists. Too big. Too crowded.''
</P>
<P>
   That's too bad for the 30-year-old festival, which draws tens of
thousands of music lovers from around the world. One of the joys of
the Crescent City is its colorful characters and the gracious
hospitality of its citizens.
</P>
<P>
   But there is another festival where you can get a taste of the
city's rich cultural heritage and fine cuisine, and chances are
you'll be rubbing elbows primarily with New Orleans natives.
</P>
<P>
   It is the New Orleans Wine and Food Experience. Only 8 years
old, the June 23-27 event is quickly becoming one of the premiere
food and wine events in the country.
</P>
<P>
   That is no surprise when you have the great restaurants of New
Orleans from which to draw your culinary talent. Among the nearly
100 restaurants participating in the festival are Alex Patout's
Louisiana Restaurant, Arnaud's, Brennan's, Broussard's, G&AMP;E
Courtyard Grill, Galatoire's, Gumbo Shop, K-Paul's Louisiana
Kitchen, Kelsey's, Ralph &AMP; Kacoo's, Semolina and the Upperline.
</P>
<P>
   More than 500 wines from 100 wineries worldwide will be
showcased during tastings, vintner dinners and seminars.
</P>
<P>
   The premiere event of the festival is the Royal Street
Experience on June 24. Dozens of galleries on Royal Street in the
historical French Quarter open their doors for an evening of wine,
food, antiques and live jazz. Armed with a souvenir glass, guests
are encouraged to visit each shop for a wine and food sample.
</P>
<P>
   Other Wine &AMP; Food Experience events include two grand tastings,
a Sunday champagne brunch and special prix fixe vintner dinners at
26 top restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   A complete package that includes the Royal Street Experience,
both grand tastings, Sunday brunch and five seminars is $375. The
vintner dinners are priced separately at $75 per person. Other
event tickets also are offered a la carte.
</P>
<P>
   For information, call 504-529-9463 or access
www.travelneworleans.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
HEMINGWAY DAYS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's quite a love story. Ernest Hemingway loved Florida's Key
West, and today the city still celebrates its fondness for the
Nobel Prize-winning author.
</P>
<P>
   The Hemingway Days Festival, which runs July 16-25, will mark
the 100th anniversary of the birth of Hemingway, who wrote his
classics ``For Whom the Bell Tolls'' and ``A Farewell to Arms''
while residing on the island.
</P>
<P>
   The Papa Hemingway Look-Alike Contest, a festival favorite, will
be held at one of the writer's old watering holes, Sloppy Joe's.
The look-alike event is expected to draw more than 100
white-bearded contestants who will be judged by past winners and
Hemingway family members.
</P>
<P>
   A festival highlight is the Hemingway Days Writers Workshop and
Conference, where seminars by authors, scholars and those who knew
the writer will be presented. Book signings and readings also are
planned. Other Hemingway Days events include a street fair, sailing
regatta and arm-wrestling competition.
</P>
<P>
   For a schedule of events, call 800-527-8539 or access
www.fla-keys.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CUISINES OF THE SUN &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Head to Hawaii for sun, sand and superlative food and wine.
</P>
<P>
   Cuisines of the Sun, hosted by the Mauna Lani Bay Hotel and
Bungalows on Hawaii's Big Island, is four days of culinary magic
with cooking classes with celebrity chefs, tastings with winemakers
and meals made all the more memorable by their oceanside setting.
</P>
<P>
   The gastronomic festival, now in its 10th year, kicks off July
24. The theme of the event is ``As Good As It Gets: Culinary
Marvels for the New Millennium.'' Among the chefs whisking their
way to Hawaii are Lidia Matticchio Bastianich (Felidia in New
York); Francois Payard (Payard Patisserie &AMP; Bistro in New York);
Ming Tsai (Blue Ginger in Wellesley, Mass.); Jeremiah Tower (Stars
in San Francisco), Lee Hefter (Spago in Verleyu Hills, Calif.);
Michael Mina (Aqua in Las Vegas), Todd English (Olives in Boston);
Roy Yamaguchi (Roy's restaurants worldwide) and Al Wong (Alan
Wong's in Honolulu).
</P>
<P>
   Classes focus on a variety of topics, including fruit and
vegetable juice drinks; chocolate desserts; organic meats and
produce; and fusing Asian flavors with other ethnic recipes.
</P>
<P>
   The gala event _ a feast under the stars with wine and dancing _
closes the festival July 27.
</P>
<P>
   An all-inclusive package that includes ocean-view accommodations
as well as all events is $2,215, or $3,204 per couple. Tickets to
events can be purchased a la carte. For reservations, call
888-424-1977 or access www.maunalani.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ELVIS WEEK &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The faithful flock to Memphis each August to remember their
King. Elvis Week, Aug. 8-16, draws fans worldwide to a celebration
of the pop singer's life and music.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of events are planned around the city and at the late
singer's home, Graceland. Highlights of the week, which coincides
with the anniversary of Elvis' death in 1977 at age 42, include a
gospel brunch on Memphis' legendary Beale Street, a tribute
concert, a candlelight vigil at Elvis' grave site at Graceland and
a fan club festival.
</P>
<P>
   Elvis fans won't want to miss the new Elvis Presley's Heartbreak
Hotel, which is located just across the street from Graceland, and
Elvis Presley's Memphis, where contemporary southern cuisine is
accompanied by live entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   For a festival schedule or information, call 800-238-2000 or
access www.elvis-presley.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BUMBERSHOOT &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seattle Center is transformed into a colorful and cacophonous
bazaar each Labor Day as the city celebrates Bumbershoot.
</P>
<P>
   The four-day, multi-arts festival features music, dance,
theater, film, comedy, literary arts and comedy. This year, more
than 2,000 artists will be performing at the Sept. 3-6 event.
</P>
<P>
   Galleries, exhibit halls and other unlikely venues augment the
traditional outdoor stages. Some of the festival's more unusual
offerings: the West Coast's largest independent and small press
book fair; eating contests as performance art; and a showcase of
international circus acts.
</P>
<P>
   A Bumbershoot schedule is not yet available, and tickets have
not gone on sale. For information, write to One Reel, P.O. Box
9750, Seattle, Wash. 98109 or fax 206-281-7799 or access
www.bumbershoot.org. More Seattle tourism information is available
by calling 206-461-5840; www.seeseattle.org/home/skccvb.htm
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
