<HEADER>
A2660 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICARE-0512-COX     05-11 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-0512-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BREAUX CRITICIZES FELLOW DEMOCRATS ON MEDICARE REFORM
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (a) general news categories
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _The chairman of the failed Medicare reform
commission Tuesday lashed out at his fellow Democrats, charging
that many of them want a campaign issue more than real reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are clearly those who don't want to do anything on this,
and use this as a political issue,'' said Sen. John Breaux, D-La.,
who chaired the Bipartisan Commission on the Future of Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The 17-member commission fell one vote short in March of the
super-majority required by law for it to make a recommendation to
Congress on reforms. Breaux and Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., were the
only Democrats who voted for Breaux's proposal. It would have had
managed care plans compete for customers, with the federal
government subsidizing up to 88 percent of the cost of the average
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that setback, Breaux and Rep. Bill Thomas, R-Calif., the
panel's vice-chairman, plan to introduce legislation later this
month along the lines advocated by a majority of the commission.
</P>
<P>
   At a breakfast Tuesday at the National Press Club, Breaux was
particularly harsh in his assessment of the motives of fellow
Democrats. He said more Democrats don't want reform than do want it
because they can then attack GOP efforts to tinker with the popular
program that covers 39 million elderly and disabled Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Breaux rejected the suggestion that this year would not be ripe
for Medicare reform because it is too close to the 2000 election.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will always be an election,'' he said, noting that House
members have to run for office every other year. ``If the politics
of it becomes the guiding principle, then we will never do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Breaux said he was hopeful President Clinton would keep his
promise to offer an administration proposal to reform Medicare,.
But the senator said the White House will need to go further than
it has in order to offer substantial reform.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has suggested using 15 percent of the projected federal
budget surplus -- about $700 billion over the next 15 years -- to
extend the financial viability of the Medicare Part A trust fund.
Without reform, that fund -- which pays hospital bills -- is
expected to run out of money in 2015.
</P>
<P>
   Breaux said he was concerned that Clinton was receiving
conflicting advice: some urging an incremental approach that
tinkers with the current system; other pushing for more fundamental
reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it (the White House reform proposal) is
comprehensive,'' Breaux said. ``If it is status quo, just with more
field testing or pilot projects, that's not real reform. I don't
mind putting more money into the program. I think it needs more
money, but it needs to be a different program.''
</P>
<P>
   Breaux said his bill would differ slightly from the plan
considered by the commission in that it would offer prescription
drug coverage to all Medicare beneficiaries as an additional
option. The price of that option has not been determined.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
