A2670 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r n &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEGISLATURE-TEENS-TEX     05-11 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEGISLATURE-TEENS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPOSED BILLS IN TEXAS LEGISLATURE WOULD RESTRICT RIGHTS OF TEENS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN BROOKS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It seems that a teen-ager's life is one big
government-created paradox.
</P>
<P>
   A 15-year-old is old enough to get a job, yet too young to vote
for the people who set the minimum wage. Old enough to drive a
vehicle, but too young to be out alone at night. Old enough to be
punished like an adult, but too young to be treated like one.
</P>
<P>
   And if the Texas Legislature this session doesn't add a few more
caveats to a teen-ager's rights _ such that they are _ it's not for
lack of trying.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 bills filed this session would limit teen-agers in
some way, from raising the driving age and limiting body piercing,
to lengthening the list of offenses that require automatic
detention and criminalizing sex between teens.
</P>
<P>
   Although many of the proposals appear to be going nowhere in the
waning weeks of the session, it does say a lot about the opinion of
the lawmakers when it comes to the younger generation in this day
and age, researchers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just happen to be at a time in our history where I think
teen-agers are the object of a lot of antipathy, and are feared
much more than they have been in the past,'' said Laurence
Steinberg, professor of psychology at Temple University. ``And the
people now who are trying to restrict all these freedoms that kids
have were baby boomers in the 1960s, out there marching for those
very same freedoms.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the major pieces of legislation that are showing
potential for becoming laws this session include requiring minors
to tell their parents before they have an abortion; to have
parents' consent for body piercing; and to have adult supervision
during the first year of driving, with graduated driver licenses.
</P>
<P>
   Others that are pending in committees offer an example of the
mind-set of lawmakers in terms of governing teen-agers:
</P>
<P>
   One bill would mandate automatic criminal detention for fighting
on a school bus. Another, filed in reaction to a spate of heroin
overdoses among young people in suburban communities of North
Texas, would make it a crime for a minor to ask someone for drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Another would raise the age that a teen can check themselves out
of a treatment center from 16 to 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the message from adults on these laws is two-fold,''
said Steinberg, who wrote the acclaimed parenting book, You and
Your Adolescent. ``On the one hand, we're trying to protect you
from something dangerous. On the other hand, we're trying to
protect ourselves from you.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers take a more moderate stance on that, saying the laws
are in place to empower parents in raising their children right _
along with protecting the youths.
</P>
<P>
   There are more restrictions on teens now than ever before, they
acknowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Already, teen-agers can lose their driver's license if they are
caught with a pack of cigarettes. They can be thrown out of school
for making a menacing remark.
</P>
<P>
   Congregate at some malls without an adult, and they get busted
by juvenile authorities. In some communities, it is illegal for a
child to be out on the street during school hours.
</P>
<P>
   As teen-agers watch the laws and restrictions piling up with
each legislative session, they point out that most of them obey the
law and their parents. And, they say, enough already.
</P>
<P>
   ``More teen-agers might start to rebel'' if more restrictions
are imposed, Jared Silpa, 16, of Bedford. ``I'm not rebellious, but
I might rebel if I lost certain freedoms.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because times are changing, and the laws have to keep up,
said Rep. Toby Goodman, R-Arlington, who sponsored the massive
rewrite of the juvenile justice code last session. He also
acknowledged that ``99 percent of the kids out there are good
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But when I was growing up, you weren't reading in the
newspaper about 15-year-olds wearing gang colors going around in a
car shooting up houses, killing people ... (and) committing
suicide,'' Goodman said. ``When I was growing up, society was a
whole lot different than society is today. And if my children tell
me one thing, it's, `Dad, you know, you grew up in a different
time. It's a different world.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It's a different world, but one that deserves fewer
restrictions, not more, said 28-year-old New York resident Dave
Doctor, director of Libertarian Rock, a Web-based activist group.
</P>
<P>
   ``People under 18 are more mature than they used to be,'' said
Doctor, who has organized protests against a curfew in San
Francisco. ``And politically, they're becoming more aware of the
impact on politics in their lives. It used to be the laws never
really affected them much.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, now, the 14-year-olds' mothers are on Valium, their
little brothers are on Ritalin, and they can't even have a smoke.''
</P>
<P>
   There is yet another class of anti-curfew, anti-graduated
driver's license advocates who say the battle over restricting
teen-agers is not a question of kids' rights.
</P>
<P>
   It's a question of parents' rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am concerned that we do not give government the
responsibility of raising our children,'' said Sen. Jane Nelson,
R-Flower Mound, who wrote one of more than 10 parental notification
or consent bills this session. ``Government isn't the solution to
all of our problems.''
</P>
<P>
   A popular opinion is that teen-agers don't have any rights,
outside the rights to basic education and protection from abuse and
neglect.
</P>
<P>
   While schools or government can't restrict free speech or
freedom of religion, parents can, said Daniel Koller, a parental
rights attorney in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no such thing as freedom as a child. That's an absurd
thought to me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson agreed to a lesser extent, saying that if a teen-ager has
a bill of rights, it is one that is written by his or her parents.
</P>
<P>
   But teen-agers say the government and their parents can only
offer guidance: Part of growing up is testing the limits,
experimenting, experiencing and making mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   And whatever law gets passed, they will find a way around it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to stop teen-agers from doing something if they want
to,'' said Josh Gearn, 18, of Watauga. ``Your parents can only
watch you at certain times.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
