<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENDER SPINACH WITH CRISP SHALLOTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   My guess is that many people eat greens because they think they
should more than because they actually like them. This is a
circular problem: if you expect to dislike greens and put little or
no effort into their preparation, the results are inevitably dull.
</P>
<P>
   But there are a number of ways to make simple dishes of greens
more tantalizing. First and foremost is not overcooking them,
although I have friends from the South who disagree. The best
technique is not to steam greens but to simmer them in plenty of
water. They cook more evenly, it's easier to keep an eye on them,
and you will never burn the pot.
</P>
<P>
   Spinach takes about a minute, and collard leaves take a good 10
minutes (thick stems should be cooked a little longer). When
they're done, they can be drained and seasoned to serve
immediately, or refrigerated to reheat later. A quick toss in hot
olive oil scented with garlic, followed by a squeeze of lemon, is
enough to make any dish of greens appealing.
</P>
<P>
   The next level is still a minimalist preparation: make a topping
of crisp-fried shallots for the greens. By themselves, these
crunchy slices are irresistible; combined with tender greens, they
create an alluring contrast in flavor and texture. Even better, the
oil in which the shallots have been fried is a great addition to
the greens and, in the days following, many other dishes.
</P>
<P>
   The shallots must be thinly sliced. Use a mandoline if you have
one. Otherwise, lay the shallots on their flat sides, and then
slice as thin as you can using a sharp knife. Like the greens
themselves, the shallots can be cooked well in advance. When you're
ready to eat, just reheat the greens and sprinkle them with the
shallots.
</P>
<P>
   This preparation also serves as a good introduction to
deep-frying, because you can readily and infallibly detect when the
shallots are ready: they turn brown. At that moment, they must be
removed from the heat immediately, or else they will burn. The
flavored oil not added to the greens should be strained and stored
in the refrigerator; it can be used in vinaigrettes or for
sauteeing.
</P>
<P>
   TENDER SPINACH WITH CRISP SHALLOTS &QL; 
Time: 30 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 cup or more neutral oil, like grape-seed, canola or corn
</P>
<P>
   6 to 8 large shallots (about 6 ounces), peeled and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 pound spinach, washed and trimmed
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh lemon juice. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Place oil to depth of at least an inch in a small to medium
saucepan or narrow, deep skillet. Turn heat to high, and wait a few
minutes, until the oil reaches 350 degrees. (If you do not have a
frying thermometer, put a couple slices of shallot in the oil; when
the oil bubbles vigorously around them, it's ready.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2. Add shallots, and cook, adjusting heat so that the bubbling
is vigorous but not explosive. Cook, stirring, until shallots begin
to darken, 8 to 12 minutes. As soon as they turn golden brown,
remove them with a slotted spoon; be careful, because overcooking
will burn them. Drain the shallots on paper towels, and sprinkle
with salt and pepper; they will keep for a couple hours this way.
Reserve oil. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3. Meanwhile, bring a large pot of water to a boil. Salt the
water, and add spinach. Cook it until spinach wilts, about 1
minute. Remove spinach with a strainer or slotted spoon, and plunge
it into a large bowl that has been filled with ice water to stop
the cooking. When spinach is cool, drain and chop it. (You can
store the spinach, covered and refrigerated, for as long as two
days, if you like.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4. Place 1 tablespoon of the shallot oil in a skillet, and turn
heat to medium-high. Add spinach, and cook, stirring frequently and
breaking up any clumps, until it is hot, about 5 minutes. Season
with salt and pepper, and add lemon juice. Serve topped with crisp
shallots. &QL; 
Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
