<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KITCHEN-WARES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPIN DOCTORS FOR YOUR SALAD GREENS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Next to having fresh greens, the most important thing when
making a salad is that the greens are crisp yet dry. If you wash
lettuce and let it dry at room temperature, it will turn limp. If
you wash lettuce and pat it dry in dish towels, you will never get
all the water out of the crevices in the leaves, and the extra
water will ruin the vinaigrette.
</P>
<P>
   The solution is the salad spinner, a hand-operated device that
works like the spin cycle in a washing machine. The wet lettuce is
whirled in a cylindrical basket and centrifugal force pulls the
water off of the lettuce leaves.
</P>
<P>
   In the dark ages of salad spinners, the base was simply a
plastic basket in a solid plastic bowl and a mechanism in the lid _
a crank or a pull string _ propelled the basket. Now, there are
more mechanisms and more features _ there are even salad spinners
that claim to do the full cycle, from wash to spin dry. But all
rely on the same simple principle: the faster the spin, the dryer
the lettuce.
</P>
<P>
   The classic crank design has a handle on top. The basket spins
at the speed at which you turn the crank. Many crank models are
poorly designed. They often do not connect with the basket well, so
when spinning, the mechanism skips or the basket gets off balance,
causing the lettuce to move to one side and slow the spinning. Of
three crank spinners, the best was made by Copco, $8.98 at Zabar's,
2245 Broadway, New York, N.Y., (212) 787-2000. It held a great deal
of lettuce, and both the base and turning mechanism were sturdy,
making it easy to turn the crank quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Copco also makes a crank that is operated as a lever on the top
that you move back and forth. I didn't have much hope for it, but
was impressed with its performance. The crank was smooth and held
on to the basket without getting off track. It's $18.95 at Broadway
Panhandler, 477 Broome St., New York, N.Y., (212) 966-3434.
</P>
<P>
   The Moulinex crank model has a spinner made to collapse like a
camping cup. It's a good idea _ salad spinners do take up a lot of
room _ but it is poorly executed. The basket holds very little and
once expanded, the spinner is as unstable as a top. It's $24.99 at
Gracious Home, 1220 Third Ave., New York, N.Y. (212) 517-6300.
</P>
<P>
   A new mechanism among salad spinners is the pump by Oxo. Rather
than a crank, it has a large button on the top of the spinner that
you press to turn the basket. The spinner is well constructed, and
the pump does work, but it fails to build up great momentum. Which
is too bad, because it has a great little feature _ a button break
for slowing down the basket, so you don't have to wait for it to
stop before opening. It's $24.95 at a Cook's Companion, 152
Atlantic Ave., Brooklyn, N.Y. (718) 852-6901.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite salad spinners turned out to be those operated with
a pull string. As with a yo-yo, you pull the cord, which is then
drawn back in. This lets you develop a rhythm, so that the basket
spins without any jarring. One drawback is that over time, the cord
often wears out and breaks or becomes hopelessly tangled.
</P>
<P>
   The Jet salad spinner definitely does the job, and it has an
opening on top for letting water from a faucet pour in as you spin.
You can wash the lettuce as you spin, then turn off the faucet and
continue spinning to dry it. Unfortunately, this feature doesn't
really work. Some lettuces can be very dirty and need to be swished
around in a sink full of water. The Jet is $19.99 at Gracious Home.
</P>
<P>
   The Zyliss was far superior to all of the spinners I tested. Its
cord pulled smoothly. The container was large and did not move out
of place, even during a fast spin. The lettuce leaves were bone dry
and crisp when they emerged _ ready for a touch of vinaigrette, a
toss and a fork to skewer them. The Zyliss spinner is $24.95 at
Zabar's.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-99 1543EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
