<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 15:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2679 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT &LR;      05-11 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASTER-CHEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TARTE TATIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: This is the seventh of eight columns by Claudia Fleming,
the pastry chef at Gramercy Tavern in Manhattan. Her collaborator
on these columns is Melissa Clark.) 
(jt) 
 By CLAUDIA FLEMING and MELISSA CLARK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some people crave a small bite of something sweet to end a meal;
others like to savor a rich, salty morsel of cheese, especially if
they haven't finished all of their wine with dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Since I'm always looking for new themes to base my desserts on,
I decided to create one incorporating the elements of a cheese
course: fresh and dried fruit and the cheese, itself. Its
centerpiece is a tarte Tatin _ a caramel-glazed, upside-down apple
tart anchored in a crisp puff-pastry crust. While baking, the
apples release their juice, and it mingles with the caramel to form
an intense, buttery sauce.
</P>
<P>
   It was more difficult to come up with a way to fit in the
cheese. I wanted something simple to complement the tart, rather
than compete with it. At the same time, it needed to be more
elegant than, say, the traditional plain wedge of cheddar served on
a slab of apple pie. I opted for a deliciously mild, creamy goat
cheese from Coach Farm, because it can be beaten to cloudlike
lightness with cream to add a fluffy contrast to the tart. On the
plate, it looks like an innocently mild dollop of whipped cream.
But there is no mistaking its tangy flavor, a cool piquancy against
the caramel-coated apples.
</P>
<P>
   For the third element, the dried fruit, I turned to golden
raisins, which I plump in a hot bath of apple juice and verjus. If
you've never used verjus, you're in for a pleasant surprise. It's
grape juice made from unripe grapes, which makes it much more
complex and less sweet than regular grape juice. Verjus brings out
the inherent grape flavor of the raisins without making them
cloying. (It's also a terrific poaching liquid for other kinds of
fruit, if you have any left over.)
</P>
<P>
   For all this dish's success as a hybrid of cheese and dessert
courses, I wouldn't necessarily recommend pairing it with leftover
wine from dinner. But it is beautifully enhanced by dessert wine
like Muscat de Beaumes-de-Venise.
</P>
<P>
   One last note: Since apple season is coming to a close, feel
free to substitute peeled peaches in the tart and omit the raisins
in verjus. With vanilla ice cream substituting for the goat cheese
cream, it's perfect for those warm summer nights, which are only a
few weeks away.
</P>
<P>
   TARTE TATIN WITH GOAT CHEESE CREAM
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour, plus 1 hour to cool
</P>
<P>
   { cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   { cup (1 stick) unsalted butter, softened and cut into 1-inch
pieces
</P>
<P>
   4 medium Granny Smith apples, peeled, halved and cored
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces puff pastry, thawed
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces mild goat cheese, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   } cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   Golden raisin verjus (see recipe).
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 450 degrees. In 10-inch ovenproof skillet
over low heat, combine sugar with 3 tablespoons water, and cook,
stirring constantly, until sugar dissolves. Increase heat to high,
and cook until mixture is golden brown and caramelized. Remove
skillet from heat, and whisk in butter until melted and smooth.
Arrange apple halves, cut sides up, over caramel.
</P>
<P>
   2. Roll puff pastry to an 11-inch circle, trimming if necessary.
Drape it directly over apples, tucking edges.
</P>
<P>
   3. Place skillet in oven, and bake for about 25 to 30 minutes,
or until pastry is puffed and golden brown. Allow tart to rest
until cooled, at least 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   4. Using electric mixer, beat goat cheese until creamy. Add
cream, and beat until well combined. To serve, invert tart onto
baking sheet, and reheat it in 400-degree oven for about 10
minutes. Serve warm tart garnished with goat cheese cream and
golden raisin verjus.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDEN RAISIN VERJUS
</P>
<P>
   Time: 35 minutes, plus 15 minutes to cool  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 cup golden raisins
</P>
<P>
   } cup white verjus
</P>
<P>
   { cup apple juice
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   Seeds scraped from a 1-inch piece of vanilla bean.
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients in medium saucepan, and bring to simmer,
stirring occasionally. Immediately reduce heat to low. Let mixture
slowly cook, stirring occasionally and making sure it doesn't
return to simmer, until liquid is reduced by half, about 25
minutes. Let cool for at least 15 minutes before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 1 cup.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
