<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990511.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2689 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSEMARY-BUSH-ART-2TA     05-11 1269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSEMARY-BUSH-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROSEMARY ADDS A SUBTLE MAGIC TO COOKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By MOLLY O'NEILL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nearly 17 springs ago, I was given a spindly little rosemary
tree. Observed at a distance, it looked like bonsai; up close, it
resembled the sort of brown stick topped with green cloud that a
child might draw and call a tree. But unlike the naivete of a
child's artwork, my rosemary tree never became more refined or
precise. It grew taller and thicker and wild.
</P>
<P>
   And for reasons that may be more sentimental than culinary, I
get a bad case of rosemary chauvinism in the spring. My motivation
could not be culinary; I pinch little sprigs from the bush all year
round and, traditionally, rosemary is teamed with fall and wintery
dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when I cart new basil and chervil, oregano, parsley and
thyme onto the terrace every spring, I fuss with them briefly and
then dote on my rosemary. Next to the fragile baby annuals, the
perennial rosemary is so valiant, thriving in the perpetual fumes
of trucks and cars and forgiving my erratic attentions.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, I did not maintain the plant as a botanical
sculpture. I trimmed it erratically when I wanted branches for
grilling or making kebabs, pinched back its needlelike leaves when
I needed a fresh herb. It grew from plant to shrub on the terrace.
</P>
<P>
   The little pot eventually became a bushel basket, a two-person
moving operation, a counter space glutton, and sometimes, a
disturbing mirror.
</P>
<P>
   When the bush is parched, so am I, in ways that the frenzy of
modern life would rather I ignore. It reminds me to slow down, and
tend to the little things.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, I've resented my rosemary. It's big and it won't go away.
But I've never considered a serious pruning or a separation. The
herb is too central to my cooking, its aroma too closely tied to
the smell of coming home, its folk cures too automatic in our
household to deem dispensable.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, I've rejected the traditional role of rosemary _
the dominatrix of grilled food and heavy winter dishes. There's a
delicacy and a need to merge with other aromatics in the herb, a
perfume that's never fully realized when rosemary is allowed to
rampage alone in a dish.
</P>
<P>
   Used judiciously, rosemary performs a subtle magic to cooking.
The herb brings a hint forest and briny sea air, camphorlike and
breezy, to anything from wild game to delicate seafood, from pasta
and potatoes to custards and sorbet.
</P>
<P>
   But when the fresh herb is deployed with abandon, or when the
dried herb is used at all, rosemary is bad news: like a dark urge,
unrestrained. For this reason, the late Elizabeth David hated
rosemary.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Spices, Salt and Aromatics in the English Kitchen,'' she
wrote that ``rosemary figures in my kitchen as a decoration only,''
complaining of the lavish manner in which rosemary is used by some
Italians in marinades or stews: ``The meat is drowned in the acrid
taste of the herb, and the spiky little leaves get stuck between
your teeth.''
</P>
<P>
   But even Mrs. David swooned for fresh fish basted with a branch
of green rosemary dipped in olive oil as it grilled. And therein
lies the difference between the dried herb and the fresh one: used
carefully, the fresh herb is neither acrid nor a dental nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   I've learned to restrain my rosemary impulse, dish by dish. But
the more I've learned about rosemary, the more dishes I seem to
crave with its piney, turpentine scent.
</P>
<P>
   Rosmarinus officinalis figured prominently in literature,
folklore and sacred texts long before 1390, when it was first
mentioned in ``The Forme of Cury,'' the earliest surviving culinary
text, as an essential element to salad.
</P>
<P>
   The herb's name was derived of two Latin words _ ros and marinus
_ meaning, respectively, dew and sea, perhaps because the plant
thrives under the harsh sun and in the sandy soil of the
Mediterranean. The climate in California and even along the Eastern
Seaboard also suits the herb, which seems to prefer its water
misted all over its leaves rather than drenched in the soil.
</P>
<P>
   For this reason, my rosemary bush is happiest near the stove in
the winter, when soups and pasta water provide moist hot heat.
</P>
<P>
   Along with bay, thyme, savory, sage, marjoram, oregano and
lavender, rosemary is a among the plants some cooks call turpentine
herbs. Some botanists say that the herbs shared soil and climate
with seaside pines for so many millennia that they acquired a faint
piney flavor.
</P>
<P>
   If this speculation is true, the genetic imprint is very strong
indeed. On my terrace, my bush may be treated to nascent breezes
from the Hudson, but it is mainly exposed to exhaust fumes. Still,
its leaves continue to impart a sense of sea-meeting-woodland, a
whiff of Provence, of Italy and of the first time I ate in Chez
Panisse more than 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The aroma of rosemary is so potent that ancient texts referred
to it as incense, though perhaps this association has to do with
religious myths.
</P>
<P>
   In one, it is said that the Blessed Virgin laid the family's
laundry on rosemary shrubs to dry, lending a sacred aura to the
herb. Early Christian cults of the Virgin changed its name to Rose
(of) Mary. The church-and-herb connection may have fostered
rosemary's prominence in the herbal pharmacology practiced by
clerical healers.
</P>
<P>
   Even today, herbalists claim that rosemary promotes blood
circulation _ and when used in shampoos or, as in Curacao and
Spain, in a paste applied to a bald spot, encourages hair to grow.
Romans used rosemary pastes for nervous headaches and scholars wore
wreathes of fresh rosemary on their heads to improve memory.
</P>
<P>
   Memory, in fact, is the herb's attribute most celebrated in
poetry and old wive's tales. In medieval Europe, brides carried
rosemary branches in their wedding bouquets to remind their
husbands to be faithful. It is the herb most associated with
friendship and loyalty and, along with primrose and violets, was
used in bouquets carried by courting gentlemen, as well as in the
nosegays that women exchanged.
</P>
<P>
   It is said that scattering rosemary's tiny blue flowers in a bed
protects sleepers from bad dreams. And, in Cuba, a poultice of
rosemary and ginger is applied to the forehead to cure insomnia. In
some ancient food-cure systems, rosemary liniment is used to treat
rheumatism and gout.
</P>
<P>
   My family sips rosemary tea when we feel low, adds rosemary oil
to our bath water, uses rosemary soap and rosemary shampoo.
</P>
<P>
   And apparently we are not alone. The shelves of health food
stores and luxury bath shops seem to sprout more and more
rosemary-scented products every day.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, unbridled use of the herb is just as distasteful
in cosmetics as it is in cuisine. Rosemary needs to be melded, to
become a base note in an aromatic melange _ and kept on a very
tight leash.
</P>
<P>
   The herb provides an illusive bite, for instance, when used with
other aromatics to make soda (it is rumored to be an ingredient in
cola), snacks like chips with barbecue or ranch flavors, some
Belgian pilsners and even Chartreuse, the green liquor that
Carthusian monks have made since 1607.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the cook should use half as much rosemary as any
other spice or herb in a dish. Minced with thyme, and even
lavender, rosemary does wonderful things for lamb, veal, sausage
meat, game or beef. Using the herbs is like bringing the perfume of
grazing land back to the meat.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Most commonly, rosemary is found, along with garlic and onion or
lemon, tucked into the cavity of chicken, with additional leaves
pushed between the bird's flesh and skin. It is delicious. And so
are roasted potatoes tossed with rosemary, olive oil, salt and
pepper; the same combination can be worked into dough for pizza,
focaccia or pasta.
</P>
<P>
   Rosemary seems to make tomato sauces sunnier and gives a lemony,
piney nuance to soups and stews.
</P>
<P>
   After years of living with rosemary, I finally began using it in
custards and sorbets and the result defied my general distrust of
using savory things in sweets. Used sparingly in milky desserts,
rosemary can function like pepper, nutmeg, cinnamon or allspice to
provide a sharp contrast to the sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Even more recently, I was surprised to detect rosemary among the
Asian aromatics in a vinaigrette served with a lobster and daikon
roll at the Vong restaurant in Manhattan. Soy and ginger seems to
coax a sweet hint of helioptrope from the herb.
</P>
<P>
   Modern cooks would not automatically think of consigning
rosemary to a bit part in a dish; parsimony in rosemary defies the
current more-is-better mindset in American cuisine. But living with
rosemary, I've found that the less you notice the bush, the more
powerful it is.
</P>
<P>
   My rosemary was, last fall, given an acid-bath by the
construction crew that was re-pointing our building. She had a
tough winter, and eventually I gave her to a friend for
safekeeping.
</P>
<P>
   Upon entering her temporary digs the other day, I was buffeted
with a sense of endurance and well-being and an urge to cook, to
bathe, to arrange flowers. If I knew how to sew, I would probably
have considered making cachets.
</P>
<P>
   Rosemary, you see, abides like memories. And like the unnamed
sources of joy and sadness in any person's life, rosemary is best
as an unnoticed thread in the intricate and complicated fabric of a
life.
</P>
<P>
   SLOW-BRAISED TUNA IN ROSEMARY OIL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 2 hours, 10 minutes, plus 4 to 24 hours' resting time
</P>
<P>
   1 quart olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch rosemary
</P>
<P>
   1 2-pound center cut piece of fresh tuna.
</P>
<P>
   1. Place olive oil in a saucepan over low heat. Wash rosemary
and pluck leaves from the stems (reserve the stems for grilling or
making kebabs). Dry the leaves in paper towels; you should have one
to one and a half cups.
</P>
<P>
   2. Place rosemary in the warming oil and continue to cook over
lowest possible heat until warm to the touch, about 15 minutes.
Remove from heat and allow to cool. Ladle half the oil into a very
clean glass container, leaving the rosemary behind.
</P>
<P>
   3. Place the second half of the oil in a blender with the
rosemary leaves and blend very well. Add this mixture to the glass
container and shake to combine. Place in the refrigerator for at
least 4 hours and up to 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   4. Bring the oil to room temperature. Place the tuna in a small
but deep pan and pour the oil over to cover completely. Place over
low heat and cook 90 minutes. Remove from heat and allow to sit for
30 minutes. Drain tuna, discard the oil and cut the fish into six
steaks. Serve warm with boiled, parsley potatoes or use in nicoise
or tuna salad. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   ROSEMARY-SCENTED ASIAN LOBSTER SALAD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Vong &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   For the vinaigrette:
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons honey
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons sherry vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 half-inch piece ginger, peeled and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 stalk rosemary
</P>
<P>
   1 mild fresh chili, seeded, deveined and coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups grape seed or other light, mild-tasting vegetable oil &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the salad:
</P>
<P>
   4 lobsters, cooked and shucked
</P>
<P>
   \ cup pickled ginger slices, patted dry and julienned
</P>
<P>
   8 radishes, sliced wafer thin
</P>
<P>
   1 cup daikon sprouts
</P>
<P>
   4 cups watercress, arugula or other bitter greens, rinsed, dried
and &QL;
</P>
<P>
   coarsely chopped.
</P>
<P>
   1. To make the vinaigrette, place all the ingredients but the
oil in a blender or food processor and puree. While still
processing, slowly drizzle a steady stream of oil into the mixture
to make a thick vinaigrette.
</P>
<P>
   2. Cut the lobster meat into one-inch chunks. In a large bowl,
toss the lobster with the ginger, radish and sprouts and enough
vinaigrette to barely moisten the mixture (half to three-quarters
of a cup). Divide the bitter greens among four plates, place the
lobster mixture on top and top with the sprouts. Drizzle a little
additional vinaigrette over the greens and around them on the plate
and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Note: Leftover vinaigrette makes a marvelous marinade for
chicken or pork.
</P>
<P>
   ROSEMARY AND LEMON SORBET &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``La Varenne Pratique'' (Crown Publishing, 1989) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes, plus up to half an hour to freeze
</P>
<P>
   1\ cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   Grated zest and juice of 2 lemons, plus additional for garnish
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 tablespoons fresh rosemary leaves, plus additional leaves
for garnish.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a medium saucepan over medium heat, heat 5 cups water with
sugar. When the sugar has dissolved, raise the heat to high and
boil 3 minutes. Pour half the syrup into a second saucepan and set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add lemon zest to the remaining syrup, return to low heat and
simmer about 10 minutes. Add lemon juice, remove syrup from heat
and set aside to cool.
</P>
<P>
   3. Immerse rosemary in the other half of the syrup, place over
high heat and bring to a boil. Reduce heat to very low and simmer
10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   4. Remove from heat and allow to cool. Strain rosemary syrup
into the lemon syrup. Taste, adding more lemon or sugar to suit.
Cool in the refrigerator and then freeze until firm according to
the directions of your ice cream maker. Serve garnished with lemon
slices and sprigs of fresh rosemary.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 to 8 servings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
