<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2696 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0512-     05-11 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0512-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AID OFFICIALS WANT REFUGEES ON THE MOVE FROM BORDER AREA
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-STRIKES-0512.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ After losing everything he owns, evading Serb
patrols for a month, seeing his eight-year-old cousin wounded by
shrapnel, and finally escaping Kosovo on Monday, excuse Mursel
Murseli if he does not wish to move yet again.
</P>
<P>
   But Murseli and more than 100,000 other refugees in this
northern region are being asked to travel deeper into Albania and
away from the potentially dangerous border with Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations refugee organization, UNHCR and private aid
agencies began a tent-to-tent campaign Tuesday to persuade the
refugees to leave an area they fear could be targeted by Serb
artillery several miles away. They hope to send the first convoys
of refugees south on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   It is a logistical nightmare for international relief workers,
who acknowledge that their efforts at persuasion are likely to
fail. They face widespread resistance from the ethnic Albanians,
who wish to remain close to the border and to their homes they
eventually hope to return to inside Kosovo province.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've given us good reasons to stay. It is a hard sell, but
we must try because we fear they are targets here,'' said Ray
Wilkinson, spokesman for UNHCR in Kukes.
</P>
<P>
   For the past two weeks, relief officials have sought to
transport newly arriving refugees to the south with the help of
trucks supplied by NATO, not allowing them to get settled in the
makeshift camps along the border region. On average, some 4,000 to
5,000 refugees a day have been using NATO transportation on???
their own vehicles to leave Kukes.
</P>
<P>
   But resettling the 100,000 refugees living in camps or with host
families is another matter. Problems coordinating transportation to
new camps still under construction in the south mean that aid
officials cannot now specifically tell the refugees where they
would go and how they would get there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to do. Where will they send us? I don't know
if it is safe,'' said Murseli, 32, a medical technician from the
Kosovo city of Prizren.
</P>
<P>
   UNHCR and humanitarian relief agencies cannot force the refugees
to leave -- only the Albanian government has that authority -- and
they lack an adequate number of vehicles and supplies to move the
refugees 130 miles south to the capital, Tirana.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place simply is not sustainable for 100,000 refugees. As
the weather gets hotter, water is going to get scarce. Everyone
agrees that they must go. It's just a matter of how and when,''
said Pete Robinson of CARE International.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovar refugees also are being moved from neighboring Macedonia
to Albania. The first busloads of refugees arrived at Korce in
Albania from overcrowded camps in Macedonia. The new camp can
accommodate up to 6,000, but refugees in Macedonia also have been
reluctant to leave.
</P>
<P>
   More than 750,000 ethnic Albanians have fled Kosovo in the past
seven weeks. Struggling to cope with Europe's largest refugee
crisis since World War II, UNHCR head Sadako Ogata appealed Tuesday
for donor countries to provide more money to the effort. UNHCR is
seeking $143 million to sustain its operations through the end of
June, but has only $71 million.
</P>
<P>
   In Kukes, at a camp of 7,000 refugees operated by Doctors
Without Borders -- one of eight camps in the area - officials used
loudspeakers Tuesday morning to broadcast the suggestion in
Albanian that the refugees move, warning them that it could be
unsafe if they remain.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just begged people, 'Please go.' It's not going to work.
You can't ask people to go, you must tell people to go,'' said
Shpendi Reda, an Albanian doctor who helps to manage the camp.
</P>
<P>
   Some officials suggest that the Kosovo Liberation Army, the KLA,
is pressuring the refugees to remain near the border as a source of
recruits for the guerrilla army and as cover for their training and
supply operations inside Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring the danger looming just across the border in
Yugoslavia, NATO warplanes attacked Serb positions on Monday and
Tuesday within sight of the Morina border crossing.
</P>
<P>
   NATO jets high overhead pounded Serb military positions three
miles inside Kosovo just before noon, sending thick plumes of black
smoke rising above the green hills. Refugees fleeing Kosovo said
they believed a Yugoslav army base was hit.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
