<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Washington) _ White House spokesman Joe Lockhart
rejects China's appeal for a halt in the NATO bombing campaign.
China, upset about the attack on its embassy in Belgrade, wants the
air raids stopped before it will consider a framework for peace in
Yugoslavia that could be taken up by the United Nations Security
Council. By NANCY MATHIS.
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-APACHES (Washington) _ Wearing U.S. Army fatigues and
bunking down with the troops, two Boeing Co. technicians are out on
the front lines in Albania to help maintain the 22 Apache
helicopters poised for battle in Kosovo. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   HATE-CRIMES (Washington) _ Judy Shepard, urging Congress to
expand the federal hate crimes law to protect homosexuals from
violence, speculated Tuesday that her son Matthew may not have been
killed outside Laramie, Wyo., last year if there had been such a
law. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN. (Already filed; will update)
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-GUNS (Washington) _ The Senate is taking up a juvenile
justice bill that could become a vehicle for Congress to deal with
the Littleton, Colo., massacre. The bill contains several
gun-control measures, including an increase in the legal age for
purchasing a weapon and instant background checks at gun shows. By
BENNETT ROTH.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-POOR (Atlanta) _ President Clinton speaks to business
executives, prodding them to increase development in poor urban and
rural areas. By JOHN C. HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION-BUSH (Austin, Texas) _ The Texas House may vote on a
parental notification bill, an issue important to Gov. George W.
Bush. The bill is expected to face criticism from Republicans, some
of whom are unhappy that the legislation allows minor girls to
notify people other than parents before getting abortions. By POLLY
ROSS HUGHES.
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ A former top assistant to Dan
Morales says tobacco lawyer Marc Murr admitted to him in December
1997 that Murr did not have a contract to work on the state's
lawsuit against the tobacco industry. Murr is a friend of Morales,
the former state attorney general whose case against cigarette
makers ended in a settlement. By CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ First Lady Hillary Clinton is
acknowledging to friends that she really wants to run for the
Senate in New York. She has already been campaigning there but she
hasn't quite made a final decision about it. There are a lot of
complications to consider. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
