A2718 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN13-CO     05-11 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Draggin' and braggin'
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ Here's a story I heard in men's Sunday school
last week. It was told by the teacher to illustrate a passage from
the Book of Psalms that warns against boastfulness.
</P>
<P>
   This happened back in the 1950s. He was a young man in from
college.
</P>
<P>
   He had borrowed his family car and made a run down the main
drag, Timberland Drive, and then stopped off at a drive-in root
beer stand, a route so predictable that the car likely could have
driven itself.
</P>
<P>
   He stood around awhile with his buddies, and then they piled
into one of the other cars for a spin downtown to see if anything
was going on there.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen or 20 minutes later _ it doesn't take long to make the
rounds in a square town _ he was back at the root beer stand to
pick up his dad's car.
</P>
<P>
   Only thing was, the police had beat him to it.
</P>
<P>
   There they were, with the car hooked up to a wrecker and about
to tow it off when he intervened, asking what was the trouble,
Officer.
</P>
<P>
   Only to be told, you know doggone well what the trouble was,
that the car was going to be impounded and he was going to jail.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't make the mistake of asking what the charge was. He'd
already been told he already knew.
</P>
<P>
   Instead he asked if he could use a phone to call his dad.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the cop said, you can use the phone _ you can use the
phone in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Almost before he knew it, he was in jail, still wondering what
he did and what was going to happen next.
</P>
<P>
   One of his buddies from the root beer stand showed up a short
time later, asking to see him.
</P>
<P>
   The cops said no, but the buddy yelled his name back down the
hall toward the cells, asking him if he wanted him to call his dad.
</P>
<P>
   He said, yeah, you better, not knowing what else to do.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the buddy had found out what he was charged with _
dragging on Timberland Drive.
</P>
<P>
   Supposedly, he and another car had taken off from a red light,
tires squealing, right under the nose of a patrol car, which took
off after them.
</P>
<P>
   One fugitive went one way, and the other went the other way,
both managing to lose the cop, who doubled back around checking the
usual hangouts for the usual suspects, and that's when he spotted
the car he was sure was one of the draggers.
</P>
<P>
   So it was the buddy phoned the father.
</P>
<P>
   ``What'd they arrest him for?'' his daddy asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dragging,'' the buddy said.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long for the daddy to show up at the jail. He
managed to get the car and his boy, too, out on bail. He was angry,
and the boy was scared.
</P>
<P>
   Surprising enough _ since this was a law-and-order, no-nonsense
kind of father who well knew his son's many failings _ in this case
the father was angry with the police and not with the boy.
</P>
<P>
   Doggonedest thing he'd ever heard of, he sputtered. Arresting a
boy for bragging.
</P>
<P>
   The mistake was understandable.
</P>
<P>
   1. His dad couldn't hear well on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   2. His dad had never heard of dragging.
</P>
<P>
   The moral is: Even when it's something else, boastfulness can
get you in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. He still says he wasn't dragging.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)lcc.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.; web page,
http://www.geocities.com/SoHo/Bistro/7147.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
