<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2727 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TALK-NYT &LR;      05-11 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO. 2 WINE OF GREAT BORDEAUX CHATEAUX MADE WITH ALL THE CARE OF THE
FIRST 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can't afford Chateau Margaux any more? Or Chateau Latour, or
Chateau Any-Other-Famous-Bordeaux? Have you thought of trying your
favorite chateau's second wine?
</P>
<P>
   The principal wine of any Bordeaux chateau is the one that bears
its name. But every vineyard produces some grapes that are better
than others. Some chateaus mix all their grapes together and
ferment them into a single wine. But that practice is dying out.
</P>
<P>
   The result is the growing class of second wines, which may not
be made from the best of grapes, but do come from the finest
houses. They are worth knowing about because for a relatively low
price _ $50 compared with $240 in one example _ you are buying the
expertise of the great winemakers of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Second labels are mostly a Bordeaux phenomenon, closely
associated with the chateau system, although winemakers around the
world have resorted to separate names for lesser wines from their
principal vineyards. The difference is that outside Bordeaux, the
second label doesn't have a consistent meaning.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in most places _ Italy, Spain, Latin America and
California _ the second wine can be the better wine. For example,
the very best cabernet sauvignon from Robert Mondavi Winery is
designated a ``reserve'' wine to set it apart from the regular
bottlings.
</P>
<P>
   But to confuse matters, many more California wineries use terms
like reserve, proprietor's reserve or winemaker's reserve as
meaningless designations on inexpensive, commercial wines they buy
in bulk. Mostly, they are just dressing up the label.
</P>
<P>
   But in Bordeaux, the meaning of a second label is very specific.
Few Bordeaux vineyards are a single entity surrounding the chateau
whose name they bear. Many family-owned vineyards have been cut up
over the years to satisfy the demands of France's draconian
inheritance laws.
</P>
<P>
   Some chateaus have as many as 40 separate parcels of vines
spread around the commune in which they are located. A map of most
chateaus' vineyard holdings will look like a patchwork quilt.
</P>
<P>
   Because these parcels often have different soil, different
irrigation, even different microclimates, they are harvested and
vinified separately. What's more, within each parcel of vines, the
different grape varieties also will be picked and vinified
separately.
</P>
<P>
   The result is many different vats of wine. The best go into the
principal wine, called the grand vin; the rest go into the second
wine, also known as the second label. Thirty years ago, when Edmund
Penning-Rowsell wrote ``The Wines of Bordeaux,'' the first
important book on the subject in English, he barely mentioned
second wines. The sixth edition of his book (Penguin, 1989), lists
dozens of them.
</P>
<P>
   Some second wines are well known. Les Forts de Latour, the
second wine of Chateau Latour, is better known than the first wines
of many other chateaus. So is Bahans-Haut-Brion of Chateau
Haut-Brion, Pavillon Rouge of Chateau Margaux, Amiral de
Beychevelle of Chateau Beychevelle and Carruades de Lafite of
Chateau Lafite-Rothschild.
</P>
<P>
   In Bordeaux, second wines are usually, but not always, the
product of young vines. A good grapevine maintains its vigor for 35
to 40 years before it is replaced. Almost every Bordeaux chateau
has sections of new or young vines whose fruit is no match for that
produced by mature vines.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, different portions of a vineyard produce different
quality fruit. Some parts could have been damaged by hail, for
example, while others remained untouched. Then, too, the grapes
mature at different times: merlot is usually first, followed by
cabernet sauvignon and, even later, cabernet franc and petit
verdot. Each variety is picked separately and fermented
individually.
</P>
<P>
   Even a moderate size modern chateau may have as many as 30
fermentation vats to accommodate the different batches of grapes.
The blending process, called the assemblage, determines how much
wine will go into the first wine and how much into the second.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, economics steps in. At a great property, owned by
a Parisian banker or an insurance company, prestige will always
outweigh profit. If half the year's production is deemed even
slightly inferior, it will go into the second wine or will be sold
off in bulk. There have been years when some chateaus deemed none
of their wine good enough for the grand vin.
</P>
<P>
   A lesser property, whose owner makes his living from his wine,
may not be able to afford the luxury of such severe selection.
Consequently, his wine is not as good as it might be were he able
to reject some of his lesser vats.
</P>
<P>
   Alexis Lichine, the late wine writer and owner of Chateau
Prieure'-Lichine in Margaux, once observed: ``Rigorous selection is
what really permits the large properties in Bordeaux to be very
discriminating, thus enabling them to make the top wines. Selling
part of your production at half-price is a discipline demanding a
sacrifice that not many chateaus are willing, or can afford, to
make.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Bordeaux-loving consumer, buying a second label is a
question of perceived value. The 1995 Chateau Lafite-Rothschild
currently sells in New York for about $240 a bottle. The chateau's
second wine, Carruades de Lafite, sells for about $50 _ not a bad
price for a wine from Lafite-Rothschild in today's overheated
market.
</P>
<P>
   But is the Carruades better than, say, Chateau Pichon-Baron, a
grand vin also from the commune of Pauillac, and also about $50?
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the price spread between a chateau's first and second
wine is not so great. While a 1994 Chateau Haut-Brion will cost
around $135 and the Bahans-Haut-Brion of the same vintage about
$33, the Chateau Lagrange 1995, from St. Julien, sells for about
$40 and the second wine, Les Fiefs de Lagrange, from the same year,
is priced at about $25.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the second wine of a famous chateau will have been
made with all the care and skill of the first wine. Some second
wines develop a passionate following of their own. But most live in
the reflected glory of their famous siblings; good wines, yes, but
not necessarily better than lesser-known chateaus whose first wines
sell for the same prices.
</P>
<P>
   Some of my own favorites among the seconds would include the
Fiefs de Lagrange, mentioned above; two St. Estephes _ Frank
Phelan, the second of Chateau Phelan Segur, and Les Pagodes de Cos,
the second of Chateau Cos d'Estournel _ and Clos de Marquis, the
second of Chateau Leoville Las Cases.
</P>
<P>
   The second wine of Chateau Mouton-Rothschild can be delicious,
too, but it is made in tiny quantities and is rarely seen. It's
called Le Petit Mouton, but there is nothing petit about it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
