<SLUG> BC-WINE-TASTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICH CHILEAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Errazuriz Chardonnay Reserva 1996, Casablanca Valley, Chile.
About $15.
</P>
<P>
   The Casablanca Valley is only a few miles from the Pacific
Ocean, which has the same moderating effect on the vines that it
does on California vineyards. But the climate and the soil, sandy
loam, produce a different style chardonnay from that of California
vines.
</P>
<P>
   The wine is intense and rich but displays less of the buttery,
over-oaked quality of California chardonnays.
</P>
<P>
   The weather in these Chilean vineyards was cooler than normal in
1996 and produced wines with higher acidity, a decided asset. It
is, as it should be, a wine for food and not an aperitif.
</P>
<P>
   The style is restrained, and while it retains its own character,
it should appeal to devotees of white Burgundy.
</P>
</TEXT>
