<SLUG> BC-PEDESTRIAN-SAFETY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO CONSIDERS LONGER WALK TIMES FOR PEDESTRIAN SIGNALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RACHEL GORDON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Citing the record number of pedestrian
fatalities in San Francisco last year, a city official wants to
give people more time to cross the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rash of pedestrian fatalities and serious injuries over
the past year is of grave concern to me,'' Supervisor Mabel Teng
said Monday. ``Extending pedestrian walking times citywide will
save lives. It's that simple.''
</P>
<P>
   She has introduced legislation urging the Department of Parking
and Traffic to reset the timing of traffic signals to give
pedestrians a walking speed of 2.5 feet per second, rather than the
standard 4 feet per second suggested by federal guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   On a typical 50-foot-wide San Francisco street, a pedestrian
under Teng's plan would get nearly 21 seconds to cross, rather than
12.5 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Between July 1, 1997, and June 30, 1998, a record 41 pedestrians
were hit and killed by vehicles on the streets of San Francisco,
compared with 23 pedestrian deaths during the previous 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the fatalities were the fault of drivers, according
to police records. In 18 of the fatalities, pedestrians were found
at fault because they jaywalked or disregarded red lights.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Sunshine, chief of the Department of Parking and Traffic,
said Teng wouldn't have to do much urging to get longer crossing
times for pedestrians.
</P>
<P>
   Sunshine's agency already has been working on the effort to
increase crossing times at intersections. He said some signals
already had been altered near senior residential complexes in parts
of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Implementing the program citywide, Sunshine said, ``is doable.''
</P>
<P>
   But with every upside, there's a downside. In this case,
motorists would have longer waits and that could mean more traffic
congestion, Sunshine said.
</P>
<P>
   Under Teng's legislation, some signals would be exempted if the
longer cross times would cause more vehicular congestion.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for senior citizens and disabled people have lobbied
for years to get more time to cross the street at intersections
with signals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-99 1626EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
