<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NANNY12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Nanny' pre-empted by `Raymond' reruns
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   What could be more pleasantly soothing than Fran Drescher's
normal speaking voice?
</P>
<P>
   Why, Fran Drescher screaming in labor pains, of course. Either
that, or rubbing a cheese grater on a bad sunburn.
</P>
<P>
   The final episode of ``The Nanny'' gives us only the first, even
though it frequently feels like the second.
</P>
<P>
   Has there ever been a more unlikely star than Drescher, with her
nasal bray, her annoying laugh, her whining-as-humor, her penchant
for wearing lacy peekaboo dresses in public and then complaining
about the paparazzi? She's like the Zsa Zsa of the '90s _ famous,
but why?
</P>
<P>
   Several seasons ago in its six-year run, ``The Nanny'' served
CBS well enough, gathering a fairly loyal fan base. But that base
had deserted it of late, and CBS slapped the show by pre-empting
the last five episodes for reruns of ``Everybody Loves Raymond.''
Now, with what seems to be a sigh of relief, comes a one-hour
finale, and then it's finally over.
</P>
<P>
   So Fran Fine, as Drescher is called on the show, is pregnant
with twins. Naturally, this is cause for whining, about her size,
her hunger, waiting for the birth. ``Just try to get a Jewish kid
to leave his mother,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   In time-honored sitcom tradition, she goes into labor on a stuck
elevator. The twins are born, one girl, one boy, and then it's time
to cue the final montage of clips from six seasons of ``The
Nanny,'' set to ``The Way We Were.'' Some approaches can be simply
breathtaking in their obviousness.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, some people are fans of Drescher. In today's vast pop
culture hyper-mart, anything or anybody can pick up some kind of
fan base, the way black pants pick up lint: Howard Stern, Adam
Sandler movies, the Spice Girls, Pauly Shore.
</P>
<P>
   But there's also a place waiting for the Zsa Zsas of the '90s:
Old Navy commercials. Here's hoping that when Drescher gets cast,
she's in one of those where the celebs barely speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Nanny.''
</P>
<P>
   8 tonight on CBS
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D-
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
