<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2744 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WASTE-HUD-0512-Cox     05-11 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WASTE-HUD-0512-Cox </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOUSING DEPARTMENT TO SELL PROJECT AGAIN
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington category
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If the third time wasn't a charm, then perhaps the
fourth will be. That's what the U.S. Department of Housing and
Urban Development promised in announcing plans to unload Clifton
Terrace, one of its oldest white elephants.
</P>
<P>
   The decaying apartment complex, an example of low-income housing
policy gone awry, is being sold for $1 plus a government promise to
give the new owners $8.2 million for renovations. Housing Secretary
Andrew Cuomo predicted in late April that the transfer would be ``a
new beginning for the families of Clifton Terrace and the
surrounding neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Just a short drive from the U.S. Capitol, the project typifies
problems in the federal housing law's ``Section 8'' program, which
provides subsidized rents for the poor in privately owned
properties. With lax oversight from housing authorities, landlords
have had little incentive to maintain buildings. Federal auditors
surveying the 8,600 such properties nationwide have found $10
billion in needed repairs.
</P>
<P>
   Clifton Terrace has been among the worst cases. Since 1968, the
federal government has financed three different purchasers, only to
retake the property because the landlords took millions of dollars
in federal rent subsidies and allowed the apartments to
deteriorate. The most recent owner collected $31 million in rent
subsidies over 13 years before declaring the property to be
bankrupt, leaving undone nearly $4 million in maintenance work.
</P>
<P>
   Housing department officials in late April chose Michaels
Development Co. of Malton, N.J., and the non-profit Community
Preservation and Development Corp. of Bethesda, Md., to overhaul
the project.
</P>
<P>
   The designated new co-owners have agreed to make $16 million
worth of improvements, reduce the density from 289 units to 232
units for low- and moderate-income housing and develop 76
condominium units. They are scrambling to complete the deal within
the next two months. The government will not guarantee the
financing.
</P>
<P>
   The developers would need about 24 months to renovate Clifton
Terrace.
</P>
<P>
   (optional trim follows)
</P>
<P>
   By the mid 1990s, the three-tower project was a rat-invested
magnet for crime and a nightly echo chamber for gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the neighborhood is undergoing a renaissance, but the
three-acre project continues to be a detriment and a drain on
public funds that for more than a year have been used to operate
nearly vacant buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a negative, negative history,'' said Lessie Powell
Evans, vice president for Community Preservation. ``Some people
just say tear it down.''
</P>
<P>
   However, she insists that the three high rises, once fashionable
residences that have extraordinary vistas of the city, are worth
saving.
</P>
<P>
   Community Preservation has promised to provide services that
include child care, computer literacy programs and job training.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
