<HEADER>
A2750 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-URBAN-HERBS-ART-NYT &LR;      05-11 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-URBAN-HERBS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN HERB GARDEN SUITABLE FOR ANY SILL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By RICHARD W. LANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Every spring, when the urge to grow sets in, New
Yorkers carry home pots of herbs, imagining a garden on the
windowsill where fresh basil and dill can be plucked with abandon.
And every summer both hopes and herbs wither and die. The
inclination is always to blame a black thumb. But herbs are like
people: Not all thrive in an urban environment.
</P>
<P>
   It is undeniably worth the effort to grow herbs on your
windowsill. A Tiny Tim tomato plant or a pot of lettuce in a sunny
kitchen window is easy enough to nurture, but one small salad and
the season's over. Herbs, on the other hand, with their
concentrated flavor and minimal measurements, offer a harvest of
some duration, and they can add fragrance to a room as well.
</P>
<P>
   With fresh herbs on your windowsill, the whole approach to
cooking changes. If chives are growing right there in front of you,
it's so easy to snip a few right into an omelet. If cilantro is
growing out where you can see it, it can't be wilting and turning
slimy in the bottom of the vegetable crisper.
</P>
<P>
   Not all herbs will grow well indoors, and not all indoors are
suitable for growing herbs. The two primary limitations are light
and heat _ not enough of the former and far too much of the latter.
Most herbs are of a temperate nature, and New York's dry,
superheated apartments easily overwhelm them. Herbs like it cool.
At the very least they need to cool off at night, preferring
temperatures in the low 70s or below.
</P>
<P>
   Light is a less crucial factor, because you can always
supplement with special grow lights. This no longer means klutzy
fluorescent fixtures dangling over your pots. These days you can
get special broad-spectrum grow bulbs for track lights (only you
and your decorator will know). Any good hardware store will also
carry normal-looking clip-on or hanging lamps that can be fitted
with plant bulbs, either reflectors that can be angled directly
onto herbs or the glow type that shed light over a wide area.
</P>
<P>
   As for the plants themselves, forget about basil, no matter how
tempting the new varieties like lemon and Thai might be, unless you
can offer a full day of sunlight or are willing to leave the lights
on 12 hours a day. Even then, basil grown indoors is prone to
spider mites unless you mist it as frequently as you brush your
teeth. On the other hand, if you happen to be one of those New
Yorkers in the highly unusual position of having a sunny bathroom,
this would be absolutely the best indoor environment you could
offer this herb, because of the high humidity usually found there.
</P>
<P>
   Lovage and chervil do well in rather poor light but are not the
most versatile herbs for cooking. Lovage is prized primarily for
its strong celerylike flavor, and chervil, which has a very subtle
flavor, is one of the fines herbes in classic French omelets. The
windowsill offers limited acreage, so herbs with more demand from
the resident chef probably make better use of the territory.
</P>
<P>
   The easy six for a windowsill herb garden are rosemary, bay,
mint, parsley, thyme and chives. The first three need only moderate
light, say two hours of direct sunlight a day; the second three are
a little more demanding, needing at least three to four hours of
direct sunlight. Cilantro can be grown like parsley, but dill and
sage need more light than a windowsill can provide.
</P>
<P>
   Most herbs can be started from seed, but you will have better
luck with chives already prestarted in a pot. Buying herbs in pots
is always easiest, especially now that even supermarkets carry
them. For pot size, obviously you can't grow a 3-foot thyme plant
in a 3-inch pot. You need about an inch in diameter for each three
inches of plant. Herbs should be fertilized regularly with a dilute
solution.
</P>
<P>
   Rosemary is particularly attractive as a windowsill herb because
it can be trained into a miniature orb. I once bought rosemary
spears at the supermarket with kebabs in mind and stuck them in a
glass of water to keep them fresh. A week later, Kebab Saturday
having been rained out, the unused stems had rooted. Our son,
Revell, planted them in a pot, bent the stems over into arches and
tied the tips together with green florist's wire. Rosemary's new
growth proceeds vertically, but I trim these tips off to season
chicken or lamb or fish, and Revell's topiary ball just gets fuller
and richer with every season.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet bay, like rosemary, is a perennial, so once you have an
established pot plant it becomes part of your eternal spice shelf.
A fresh bay leaf can be used in soups and stews and more. This is a
hardy plant, resistant to most pests, except scale, which can
readily be removed with soapy water. Bay will outgrow the
windowsill, though: It can become a small tree, up to 4 feet tall
indoors. Harvest the leaves from the top if you want to keep the
herb down to bush size, or from the sides if you want the more
treelike configuration.
</P>
<P>
   Mint is nice to have around just for the pleasure of pinching
off a leaf every now and then and inhaling, though, of course, it's
great for mint juleps and as a garnish for lamb or strawberries.
For best results, use a very loose soil mixture. A seed-starting
mix is excellent, because it holds moisture well, and mints do not
take well to dry soil. There's a reason they tend to grow near
water meters and dripping faucets.
</P>
<P>
   Parsley, unlike the other five of the easy six, is a biennial,
and so you should either start new seeds every year or buy a new
plant. The trick to growing parsley as a pot plant is always to
pinch the outermost stems from around the crown. This will force
continuous fresh growth from the center.
</P>
<P>
   Lemon thyme makes for a special flavor not readily bought at a
store, although the common thyme, Thymus vulgaris, is more readily
available as a plant and easier to grow to boot. Your window will
really smell like an herb garden when the sun shines on thyme, no
matter which variety you grow. The soil for thyme should be
slightly alkaline (crush some eggshells into your potting mixture)
and allowed to become rather dry, though not bone-dry, between
waterings.
</P>
<P>
   Chives like a rich, constantly moist soil. Given these
conditions and a reasonable amount of light, they will reward you
with an abundant harvest. But you must keep trimming back the
plants, or the young spears will become tough as they mature. If
the plant gets away from you and matures, it will send out pretty
little balls of purple flowers. The flowers look striking, and
these living Koosh balls are great in salads.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
