<HEADER>
A2751 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HATE-CRIMES-1STLD-WRI     05-11 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HATE-CRIMES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. SHEPARD URGES CONGRESS TO PROTECT GAYS IN HATE CRIME LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: New material throughout.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Judy Shepard, urging Congress to expand the federal
hate crimes law to protect homosexuals from violence, speculated
Tuesday that her son Matthew may not have been killed outside
Laramie, Wyo., last year if there had been such a law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I would not have to be here today, talking about how my
son was savagely beaten, tied to a fence and left to die in
freezing temperatures,'' Mrs. Shepard said. ``Matt is no longer
with us today because the men who killed him learned to hate.''
</P>
<P>
   She told the Senate Judiciary Committee how her son Matthew, who
was a 21-year-old student at the University of Wyoming, was beaten
last October simply because he was gay. She urged the panel to
approve legislation that would broaden the federal hate crimes law
to protect gays.
</P>
<P>
   The current hate crimes law, which was passed in 1969, allows
the federal government to prosecute crimes against people based on
race, color, religion or national origin. The law also requires
that any victim must have been participating in at least one of six
``federally protected activities'' such as attending a public
school, serving as a juror or being present in a public space such
as a park.
</P>
<P>
   A bipartisan group of senators, including Sens. Edward Kennedy,
D-Mass., and Arlen Specter, R-Pa., recently introduced legislation
that would expand the federal hate crimes law to include gender,
disability and sexual orientation. It would also eliminate the
federal protected activities language from the current law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly Congress needs to do more to address the issue of hate
crimes,'' Kennedy said. ``Few crimes tear more deeply at the fabric
of our society than hate crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Shepard said she realizes that a new law may not have
prevented Matthew's death, but ``perhaps these murders would have
gotten the message that this country does not tolerate
hate-motivated violence.''
</P>
<P>
   She told lawmakers that enactment of the law would be worth it
``if even one family can avoid getting that phone call in the
middle of the night.''
</P>
<P>
   Most hate crimes are prosecuted at the state and local level but
U.S. Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder said the federal hate
crimes statue allows the federal government to give state and local
officials assistance. Such assistance includes using the Federal
Bureau of Investigation to investigate such crimes and provide
technical assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Holder said that only about six hate crimes per year are
prosecuted at the federal level. He also said local law enforcement
agencies reported 8,049 hate crimes in 1997, or about one per hour.
</P>
<P>
   In the Shepard case, Wyoming authorities charged Russell
Henderson and Aaron McKinney, both 21, with murder and kidnapping
under state law. Henderson pleaded guilty to murder last month and
is currently serving two life sentences in prison. McKinney is
awaiting trial, which is set to begin Aug. 9.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson and McKinney met Shepard in a bar on Oct. 7 and lured
him outside, kidnapped and pistol-whipped him. They left Shepard
tied to a fence outside of town in freezing temperatures. Shepard
was found the next day and hospitalized but died five days later.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Matt's room at the hospital what we found was a motionless,
unaware young man with his head swathed in bandages, his face
covered with stitches, and tubes everywhere,'' Mrs. Shepard said.
``One of his eyes was partially open, but the twinkle of life
wasn't there anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, chairman of the Senate Judiciary
Committee, said he was concerned that the legislation was too
broadly written and could allow rape cases to be prosecuted at the
federal level under the proposed gender provisions of hate crimes
bill.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ``I am very concerned that we are not doing
everything we should do'' and promised to craft a more
narrowly-targeted bill.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy countered that states would still continue to take the
lead role in prosecuting hate crimes, but ``the full power of the
federal government should also be available to investigate,
prosecute and punish these crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Shepard said, at a minimum, the legislation would ``make a
powerful statement and help create a climate of a more tolerant
America.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jennifer Corbett Dooren can be reached at (202) 298-6920 and at
jennifer (at) hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
