<HEADER>
A2755 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BROWN-SUGAR-ART-2TAKE     05-11 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROWN-SUGAR-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THAT ELUSIVE FLAVOR? SUGAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Va.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By POLLY FROST   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This may seem a little odd for a sugar lover to say, but I don't
like my sugar to be too sweet. Sugar connoisseurs, who appreciate
the many qualities a great sugar can bring to a dish, know exactly
what I mean.
</P>
<P>
   Too much sweetness can destroy all that is good in sugar,
overpowering the subtleties of its many flavors and perfumes.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, there is much more to reap from a sugar than sweetness,
like richness of texture, a molasses bouquet and an old-fashioned
aroma. These are qualities only brown sugar can provide.
</P>
<P>
   Brown sugar links me to my baking ancestors. I remember the
creamy brown sugar frosting my great-grandmother Daisy Pearce
smoothed onto her devil's-food cake, and the moist brown sugar
hermits and chess pies of other relatives.
</P>
<P>
   While older cookbooks, like the original ``Joy of Cooking,''
have numerous recipes for brown sugar dishes, there is a dearth of
recipes featuring this homey ingredient in recent cookbooks. But
that does not mean the passion and inventiveness of brown sugar's
partisans have waned.
</P>
<P>
   Marcel Desaulniers, the author of ``Death by Chocolate,'' uses
brown sugar in a number of the recipes, including the Chocolate
Phantasmagoria, a rich dessert. Shirley Corriher, a food writer,
sprinkles it on cooked carrots to give them a sweet-potato flavor.
</P>
<P>
   What exactly is the object of such affection? Brown sugar is
simply white sugar from sugar beets or sugar cane that has been
refined and coated with molasses. At least, that is the type that
is commonly found on supermarket shelves. But there are also
sugars, new to most Americans, that are so good they just might
revive interest in cooking with brown sugar.
</P>
<P>
   These sugars _ muscovado, Demerara and golden baker's _ come
primarily from the island of Mauritius in the Indian Ocean. Made
from cane sugar grown in volcanic ash, they are not refined down to
white sugar, so they retain much of their natural molasses. These
sugars have a depth and complexity of flavor the supermarket brands
can't touch.
</P>
<P>
   Muscovado comes in light and dark, and has a consistency similar
to store-bought brown sugar. The light version has a velvety,
lingering molasses flavor and is so versatile it can be used as a
replacement for both light and dark commercial brown sugar.
</P>
<P>
   The dark muscovado is a pungent treat that tastes of rum. It is
a trickier sugar to use _ its intensity might take some getting
used to _ but it can add a nicely decadent touch to barbecue sauces
and cocoa.
</P>
<P>
   Demerara is a brown crystallized sugar that is both light in its
texture and deep in its hints of molasses. It is especially good as
a topping _ sprinkled on a creme brulee, for example _ and can add
a bit of crunch to pie or tart dough.
</P>
<P>
   Golden baker's sugar has a lush granulated texture and a soft
and subtle, almost floral, flavor that makes it ideal as an
all-purpose sugar. Of the three, it is the most easily used as a
replacement for white sugar.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a length of flavor in these sugars,'' said Nancy
Pollard, the owner of La Cuisine, a cooks' supply store in
Alexandria, Va. She uses muscovado when she makes chocolate ice
cream.
</P>
<P>
   Rose Levy Beranbaum, the author of ``The Cake Bible,'' now uses
golden baker's sugar in dessert recipes, except for things like
meringue, where it would darken the color. When she discovered it
in Britain years ago, she said, she was struck by its ``purity of
flavor.''
</P>
<P>
   I make the simplest of cookies using muscovado or golden
baker's. I do not add spices or even vanilla, preferring to let the
flavor of these sugars stand on their own and give the cookies an
elusive, deep, lingering flavor.
</P>
<P>
   These sugars are increasingly available in specialty shops, for
about $5 for a one-pound bag. In New York, Dean &AMP; DeLuca, the
Vinegar Factory and Eli's Manhattan carry Mauritius sugars imported
by the India Tree Co., a Seattle wholesaler (800-369-4848).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Simpson &AMP; Vail, a tea company in Connecticut, sells its own
brand of these sugars by mail order (800-282-8327), and also
supplies it to stores, including Zabar's and Balducci's. La Cuisine
sells India Tree sugars by mail order (800-521-1176). Demerara in
cube form, made by Gilway, is available in some markets.
</P>
<P>
   Golden baker's and Demerara sugar can be kept in the same way
that refined sugars can, but the muscovado can clump and grow hard
just as commercial brown sugar does. There are various techniques
for keeping sugar moist, but you can simply keep the sugar in an
airtight container and when ready to use, pour it into a bowl and
place a damp towel over it.
</P>
<P>
   Once you have tasted what brown sugar can be, it may be
difficult to go back to the commercial brands. These Mauritius
sugars could be the new stars of the kitchen. Pastry chefs, are you
ready?
</P>
<P>
   BELGIAN SUGAR TART &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Everybody Eats Well in Belgium Cookbook'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   by Ruth Van Waerebeek (Workman Publishing, 1996) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   Flemish yeast dough (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   } cup golden baker's sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons finely ground almonds
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   { cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons unsalted butter, cut into small pieces.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 450 degrees.Grease and flour a 10-inch tart
pan with a removable bottom. On a lightly floured surface, roll out
dough to form a disk about 11 inches in diameter and \-inch thick.
Press dough into pan and trim edges. Prick holes in bottom with a
fork. Cover with a towel, and place in a warm spot to rise for 20
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Combine sugar and almonds in a small bowl. In a medium bowl,
whisk together the eggs, cream and vanilla.
</P>
<P>
   3. When dough has risen, sprinkle two-thirds of the almond
mixture evenly over surface. Cover with egg mixture, and sprinkle
with remaining almond mixture. Dot surface with butter.
</P>
<P>
   4. Bake tart in lower third of oven for 8 minutes. Reduce heat
to 300 degrees, and bake until custard is set, about 12 to 15
minutes. Serve while slightly warm.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: One 10-inch tart (8 to 10 servings).
</P>
<P>
   FLEMISH YEAST DOUGH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 15 minutes, plus 1 hour rising time
</P>
<P>
   1 package active dry yeast
</P>
<P>
   \ cup lukewarm (100 to 110 degrees) milk
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   \ cup Demerara sugar
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of salt
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg, lightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   2{ tablespoons unsalted butter, melted.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a bowl, combine yeast and milk. Let sit until foamy, about
5 minutes. Stir well.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a large mixing bowl, combine flour, sugar and salt. Make a
well in the center and pour in the egg, yeast mixture and butter.
Gradually work flour into liquid ingredients until dough is smooth,
soft, and no longer sticky; do not knead or overwork dough.
</P>
<P>
   3. Form dough into a ball and place in a lightly oiled mixing
bowl. Cover with a towel and allow to rise in a warm spot until
doubled in volume, about 1 hour. Punch down dough and roll out as
desired.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: One 10- to 12-inch tart crust.
</P>
</TEXT>
