<HEADLINE>
ZAGAT INVITES WEB SURFERS IN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SHELLEY BELZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Zagat Survey went online Tuesday at www.zagat.com with every
morsel of information that appears in the restaurant guide series,
and more, all of it free for now. Users can electronically rate
restaurants anywhere, whether Zagat has a guide to that locale or
not. The site is also looking for input on a Diners' Bill of
Rights, which will cover subjects like service and tipping, to give
restaurateurs something to chew on.
</P>
<P>
   In design, the site resembles the Zagat CD-ROM. Restaurants in
cities across the country, plus Toronto, Paris and London, can be
found by category (like cuisine, neighborhood, view), with their
ratings from the Zagat guide for food, decor, service and cost.
Clicking on the top of any column will reorder the list. Click on
``F'' (for food), and the restaurants will appear from most to
least delectable in the opinion of diners. All this works quickly
and easily.
</P>
<P>
   An oddity of the site, however, is that you might find the area
a restaurant is in (like Greenwich Village or Soho for New York),
but not one iota more of information. For the address or anything
more, you have to click on the restaurant name, which brings up a
log-in screen to register, an increasingly common practice on the
Net, unfortunately.
</P>
<P>
   The registration, Tim and Nina Zagat explained by telephone last
week, is for a future club or membership. The site states that
membership is free until Sept. 1 (and may be continued beyond
then), that there is no commitment, and no credit card information
is required.
</P>
<P>
   Registering does require giving name, address, phone number,
e-mail address and a little too-personal information, like place of
birth or mother's maiden name that no impostor would know and that
you might not feel comfortable divulging, considering how it can be
used. (Occupation and income are optional.) Registering makes sense
if you are going to shop by credit card on the site (members get a
25 percent discount on Zagat guides and products like sweatshirts),
or if you are going to vote for a restaurant (to eliminate the risk
of ballot-box stuffing).
</P>
<P>
   But you must register to get what you would from a printed Zagat
guide, like the address of that clicked-on restaurant and a review
of it, as well as a little more: a map and driving directions to
it. The maps are only for U.S. cities. In cases like New York,
driving directions might not be what the prospective diner needs
most.
</P>
<P>
   Exotic Produce
</P>
<P>
   Fanciers of exotic fruits, vegetables and seasonings will be
glad to know that Frieda's, the country's leading specialty produce
distributor, based in Los Alamitos, Calif., is on line, at
www.friedas.com. The company was founded in 1962 by Frieda Caplan,
who first made her mark on America's food tastes by persuading
stores to sell fresh mushrooms instead of canned ones. Another coup
was renaming the Chinese gooseberry to create a world kiwi
industry.
</P>
<P>
   For retail customers, Frieda's has a collection of baskets
(click on Frieda's by Mail). An exotic fruit basket includes the
signature kiwis, Asian pears, horned melons, tamarillos and
cherimoyas (five pounds, $72; eight pounds, $87). A basket of
seasonings popular with cooks includes elephant garlic, dried hot
chilies, dried exotic mushrooms and shallots (eight pounds, $57).
The site also has photos and explanations of exotic fruits and
vegetables, along with dozens of recipes detailing what to do with
a tamarillo or a cherimoya.
</P>
<P>
   Orders by e-mail or by calling (800) 241-1771.
</P>
<P>
   Gourmet Books at Discount  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers for cookbooks on the Internet might want to add Gourmet
Guides (www.gourmetguides.com), a mom and daughter business in
Seattle, to their list. Jean Bullock began the business in the
early 1970s, but these days Sarah Bullock does most of the work.
All the books are new, including out-of-print remainders, and are
usually sold, Sarah Bullock writes by e-mail, at a discount of 50
percent or more. Through the Net, they have customers in Japan,
Israel, Turkey and Peru.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to stock unusual titles that the big chains aren't
interested in but many foodies and cookbook lovers are,'' she adds.
These include ``The Khwan Niamut,'' a facsimile of a 1939 cookbook
with recipes for royal Persian feasts at home ($11), and the
``Prairie Avenue Cookbook'' by Carol Callahan, recipes and
recollections from 19th-century Chicago families ($11).
</P>
</TEXT>
