<SLUG> BC-MOTHERS-GUNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORGANIZERS PLAN A MADD-LIKE ASSAULT ON GUNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VICKI HADDOCK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A nascent national organization is aiming to do
for gun control what Mothers Against Drunk Driving did for alcohol
policy: turn anguished victims into catalysts for change.
</P>
<P>
   The Bell Campaign is being created by some of the same people
who turned MADD into a national force, with hundreds of local
chapters.
</P>
<P>
   Funded by a $4.3 million grant from the Goldman Fund, the
nonprofit group has been quietly organizing under the auspices of
the Trauma Foundation at San Francisco General Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers plan to launch the Bell Campaign on May 25 with an
appeal for stricter gun control. The organization plans offices in
Atlanta, Honolulu, Laguna Hills, Calif., New York, San Francisco
and Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   While the mass killings at Columbine High School in Littleton,
Colo., have prompted the government to take a new look at the
availability of weapons, particularly to minors, organizations like
the National Rifle Association remain an omnipotent force rooted in
the constitutional right to bear arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The void has been that the only big grass-roots movement on
guns in this country is the NRA,'' said Andrew McGuire, executive
director of the Trauma Foundation and the creative force behind the
Bell Campaign. ``That is about to change _ and it's going to shake
up the whole debate about guns in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   McGuire has a lifetime of picking fights with formidable
Goliaths. Burned in an Oakland fire as a child, he campaigned for
fire-retardant children's pajamas, then emerged as a key advocate
for a motorcycle helmet law and an array of gun-control laws and
ordinances.
</P>
<P>
   He also was an acting executive director of MADD.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, we will prevail,'' McGuire said, ``because in the
words of one victim, we love our children more than they love their
guns.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Helsley, California liaison for the NRA, said gun-control
measures in California ``haven't done a thing to protect children.
They're certainly not any safer than the children of Vermont, which
has virtually no gun laws at all.
</P>
<P>
   Helsley predicted the Bell Campaign would fail.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Campaign organizers recall the early days of MADD, when
drinking and driving was routinely excused and critics dismissed
MADD as a simplistic fly-by-night group of overwrought moms.
</P>
<P>
   Today, with nearly 4 million supporters in hundreds of chapters,
MADD has been instrumental in pushing for enacting tougher
penalties for drunken drivers, lowering the blood-alcohol limit,
raising the drinking age and transforming public attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people first underestimated about MADD, and now about the
Bell Campaign, is that we are driven,'' said Beckie Brown of New
Port Richey, Fla. ``An organization like this is made up of people
like me _ parents and loved ones who couldn't stop fighting to stop
senseless tragedy. We do it as a memorial to our slain loved
ones.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss of her son, Marc, to a drunken driver in 1979 led to
Brown's involvement in MADD, and she went on to become the
organization's national president. Another son, Michael, died of a
self-inflicted gunshot wound.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is a board member of the Bell Campaign.
</P>
<P>
   She acknowledged that she didn't know what if any changes in
public policy could have saved Michael. ``But that's the discussion
America needs to have. What will make the difference, what would
have saved my son's life, what would have saved those wonderful
kids in Littleton that my heart is so broken for?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-99 1652EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
