<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-WOMEN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE BUSY, BUSY MONTH OF MAY... 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILIAN MINCER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's good that Mother's Day comes in May.
</P>
<P>
   In our house, it's a day for long-distance phone calls,
breakfast in bed and heartwarming cards. It's a day to catch your
breath before the May marathon.
</P>
<P>
   My mother-in-law, a retired teacher, warned me years ago about
May madness. She told me this time of year was busier than
December.
</P>
<P>
   But back then, I didn't appreciate the wisdom of her words. I
didn't know how many baseball games, field trips or work
assignments you could fit into one month.
</P>
<P>
   Now that I have children, I know better. Now, when I call my
mother-in-law on Mother's Day, our conversation always begins with
me explaining that her gift will be late because I haven't had time
to move it from the front seat of my car to the post office scale.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, now that more is being offered to children and more
is being asked of parents, more women are in the work force. Today,
63 percent of mothers of small children and 78 percent of mothers
of school-age children work outside the home.
</P>
<P>
   A generation ago, I left my elementary school with a Popsicle in
one hand and a report card in the other. My parents weren't asked
to attend any graduations until I walked several years later across
my high school dais.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, my daughter will spend her last week of sixth grade
showered with attention. There will be an awards ceremony, a DARE
graduation and a sixth-grade breakfast, all events I'm expected to
attend.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are optional events parents can go to, such as
field trips, spring concerts and, of course, ball games.
</P>
<P>
   This is also the time when the work load piles up at the office
because everyone's beginning to realize those projects still in the
to-do file need to get done before summer vacation.
</P>
<P>
   It's also busier than usual because so many of us are arriving a
bit late or leaving a bit early to attend one of our many
family-related activities.
</P>
<P>
   This flurry of activity always makes me feel guilty and
grateful. Guilty because even if I doubled myself I couldn't
possibly attend all these activities, but also grateful for the
opportunities our schools provide.
</P>
<P>
   We need to recognize that at times like this it doesn't matter
if the house is messier than usual or the meals at McDonald's are
more frequent.
</P>
<P>
   We need to support our children and their schools as much as
possible. But we must put aside the guilt and recognize that while
the thanks we receive on Mother's Day comes only once a year, the
work we do as parents occurs over a lifetime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
