<SLUG> BC-BOEING-APACHES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING TECHNICIANS HELP KEEP APACHE CHOPPERS FLYING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Wearing U.S. Army fatigues and bunking down with
the troops, two Boeing Co. technicians are in northern Albania to
help maintain the 22 Apache attack helicopters poised for battle in
Kosovo, a company spokesman said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Jensen, of Boeing's helicopter division in Mesa, Ariz., said
the two technicians are assisting Army mechanics at the Tirana,
Albania, who maintain the helicopters preparing for tank-killing
missions against Yugoslav forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Army does all the actual work, and the technical reps are
there to give special advice, counsel or guidance _ whatever they
are needed to do,'' Jensen said, adding that the two technicians
live with the troops and don Army uniforms minus the Army insignia.
</P>
<P>
   If the Army dispatches additional Apaches to the region, more
Boeing personnel might be called in, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Albania, rain and mud could pose problems for the
helicopters' mechanical systems, but Jensen said the company
technicians have not reported any serious maintenance woes thus
far.
</P>
<P>
   The Boeing civilians in the war theater are an example of the
increasingly prominent role played by defense contractors in
advising the U.S. military on technical matters affecting complex
weapons systems.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1997 military exercise conducted at Fort Irwin Calif.,
designed to test new digital weaponry, 1,200 defense contractor
workers _ one for every five soldiers involved in the experiment _
were present to make sure everything worked as advertised.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1991 Gulf War, civilian workers for McDonnell Douglas
Corp. and Grumman Corp. were stationed aboard Navy carriers to help
maintain aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Also during the war, nine advisers from McDonnell Douglas _
which has since been purchased by Seattle-based Boeing _ helped
keep 274 Apaches flying missions. The company officials were called
on to advise the Army on how to remedy serious maintenance problems
caused by desert sand that clogged aircraft parts and weaponry.
</P>
<P>
   The Apache is considered the most technically advanced
tank-killing helicopter in the world. The two-member crew can fire
16 tank-killing Hellfire missiles, 70mm rockets and a 30mm cannon
that can shoot 625 rounds per minute. The aircraft can hover just a
few feet off the ground, pop up and pounce on an enemy tank and fly
away at speeds approaching 200 mph.
</P>
<P>
   But the gunships have gotten off to an inauspicious start in the
Kosovo conflict. Two of the helicopters crashed and two crew
members have been killed since 24 of the choppers arrived at a base
in Albania near the Kosovo border. None of the sleek craft has been
sent into action and both crashes involved training missions.
</P>
<P>
   NATO commanders had to wait more than three weeks for the
Apaches _ designed to fight in bad weather and at night _ to arrive
from bases in Germany. The delay was partially attributed to the
Army's insistence that it have a force of 5,000 support troops to
protect and maintain the helicopters in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 and at the email
address eric(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-99 1716EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
