</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AWARDS FOR THE UNSUNG JOURNALIST
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Wednesday, May 12)  
(mk) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Journalism awards ceremonies tend to be rather dull affairs
because they recognize only good journalism, which represents only
a small part of what we do.
</P>
<P>
   I occasionally do a column on wacky headlines, headlines like
``Red Tape Holds Up Bridge'' or ``Crack in Toilet Leads to Arrest''
or ``Prostitutes Appeal to Pope.'' The sad truth is that I could do
a column of that sort three times a week for the rest of my life
and never run out of material, given the fevered,
near-hallucinatory imaginations of headline writers on deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Headlines like these can be quite clever, in their own
Alice-in-Wonderland way, yet you never hear of their writers
receiving any awards for their efforts. This is too bad, because I
feel certain that the general public would be much more interested
in following this competition than one in which a 12-part series on
sorghum subsidies goes up against a 25-part series on browser wars.
</P>
<P>
   Another journalism category that isn't considered for awards,
but should be, is the category of creative corrections, otherwise
known as the Oops! Awards.
</P>
<P>
   Time/CNN was a strong contender last year when it corrected
itself by saying the United States didn't really use nerve gas
against its own troops in Laos, though it's possible that somebody,
somewhere may have thought about it. Time/CNN could go up against
the Cincinnati Enquirer, which had to retract its 18-page special
supplement accusing Chiquita Banana of playing truth-or-dare with
Satan, or something like that. (Like most people, I didn't read the
original story; just the groveling retraction.)
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers do a lot of hand-wringing, yet there is no trophy or
plaque given to the paper that does it best. When the Starr Report
came out last year, editors somberly apologized to readers as if
they had mistakenly sprayed the pages with botulism toxin, then
proceeded to run the report in its 3-million-word entirety,
complete with explanatory editorials, columns and, if they could
get away with it, anatomically correct diagrams. Some readers,
unfortunately, didn't find the Starr Report to be all that big a
deal, causing some papers to run it twice.
</P>
<P>
   After the shootings in Colorado, a certain paper with which I
have a passing familiarity asked readers if it was giving too much
coverage to ``copy-cat'' false alarms at local schools right
underneath a front-page story about ``copy-cat'' false alarms at
local schools. The strategy seemed to work: The majority of readers
said they had had enough.
</P>
<P>
   But these are the major omitted categories; there should also be
prizes for the things that constitute the day-to-day grind of
newspaper journalism. For example, an award might be given to the
writer of the Story That Made the Least Sense Because It Was
Chopped in Half to Make Space for a Promotional Advertisement.
There would be lots of nominees for this award, and it might need
to be shared by several people.
</P>
<P>
   Another award could be given to the writer of the Story That
Jumps to Nowhere, also known as The Parallel Universe Award. This
happens when a story is supposed to be continued on an inside page,
but for one reason or another, possibly solar flares or residual
shock waves from the Big Bang, isn't. Readers should be invited to
select the first-place winner based on how many minutes or hours
they flipped through the paper, looking for the continuation or
``jump'' of the story. (We in the newspaper business call it the
``jump'' because of the way readers jump out of their chairs and
hurl their paper to the floor when they can't find the promised
continuation.)
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there should be an award for the writer of the Most
Misleading Headline, a category in which the competition would be
fierce if not positively lethal. I'm thinking in terms of a
headline like ``Woman Gives Birth to Septuplets'' above a story
having to do with the dangers of air bags or maybe a restaurant
review. Again, readers may want to judge this category,
particularly if they spent the greater part of a morning searching
for a story that had anything remotely to do with a woman, birth or
septuplets.
</P>
<P>
   To keep the awards ceremony from running on too long, there
will, unfortunately, be no categories for misspellings or
grammatical errors, unless they are committed by someone other than
me. Or possibly I.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota, Fla., Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-99 1718EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
