<SLUG> BC-DOMESTIC-PARTNERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA QUIETLY APPROVES BENEFITS FOR UNMARRIED PARTNERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ The California Legislature has quietly
granted health benefits to the unmarried partners of employees who
work in the Capitol and district offices across the state,
prompting Republican lawmakers to demand a hearing on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   The new policy allows Blue Shield health coverage, dental and
vision care to unmarried couples who live at the same address and
who are ``in a close and exclusive relationship in which each is
responsible for their common welfare,'' according to a memorandum.
</P>
<P>
   The City of San Francisco and many major California companies
already offer benefits to employees who have unmarried partners.
</P>
<P>
   And the Legislature is considering three bills that would allow
domestic partnership benefits at most private businesses, and among
tens of thousands of state, city and county employees. San
Francisco goes further than any of the bills by requiring companies
that contract with the city to provide domestic partner benefits to
their employees, although that ordinance is being challenged in
court.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows how many of the Legislature's 2,000 employees would
want the new expanded benefits, but it would apply to any
homosexual or heterosexual couple. The Legislature would pay $170
to $340 to sign up the covered partner and any dependents.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something that puts us on a fair and competitive basis
with the private sector, and it's the right thing to do,'' said
Assemblyman Bob Hertzberg, D-Sherman Oaks, chairman of the Assembly
Rules Committee, whose members recently approved the new rules.
</P>
<P>
   The Rules Committee acts as a sort of board of directors and
personnel department for Capitol employees. At the direction of top
Democratic leaders, a memo was sent to all 12 members of the Senate
and Assembly rules committees asking them to vote on the matter by
checking ``aye'' or ``nay'' on the memo.
</P>
<P>
   The new policy was approved on a party-line vote and went into
effect immediately. There was little public notice of the policy
and no formal public hearing to discuss the matter, which miffed
Republicans on the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Assemblyman Bill Leonard, R-Uplands, demanded the Joint
Assembly-Senate Rules Committee hold a public hearing on the
matter, even though it appears to be a done deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The central objection is a morality issue,'' Leonard said.
``This is discouraging family units by marriage and encouraging
other relationships ... Clearly it's a bad message that it sends,
an anti-family, anti-marriage message.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a benefit that is not of a traditional nature,'' said
state Sen. John Lewis, R-Orange, a Senate Rules Committee member.
``It's one I don't think we should be asking taxpayers to
subsidize.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Legislature has been run by Democrats for several
decades, this was the first major effort to offer domestic
partnership benefits to Capitol employees. Assembly Speaker Antonio
Villaraigosa, D-Los Angeles, and Senate President pro tem John
Burton, D-San Francisco, support domestic partnership benefits.
</P>
<P>
   And Gov. Gray Davis had fought for domestic partnership benefits
while he was a University of California regent. Davis said he would
not sign a bill legalizing gay marriage, but would sign measures
expanding domestic partnership benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even for progressives, the issue of homosexuality still raises
concerns about what the reaction from the rest of the legislators
or the public will be,'' said Rand Martin, chief of staff to Sen.
John Vasconcellos, D-San Jose. ``Until recently, there haven't been
enough people like the Burtons of the world who say, `Reaction be
damned, it's the right thing to do.' The leadership had just not
been there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-99 1722EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
