<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2844 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WYOMING-BOOK-REVIEW-N     05-11 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WYOMING-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CLOSE RANGE: WYOMING STORIES': LECHERY AND LONELINESS OUT WEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds, please note explicit language)  
(Eds: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there is any blood left in our romance with the West, Annie
Proulx (``Postcards,'' ``The Shipping News,'' ``Accordion Crimes'')
wrings it dry in her powerful new collection, ``Close Range:
Wyoming Stories.'' The people in these 11 fictions lead hard lives,
working livestock, raising sheep, riding the rodeo circuit, selling
trinkets to tourists, trying to wrest a living from the gritty
hardpan of their failing farms. No one is successful here except
the bar owners, the dude ranchers and the cattle traders, and they
are always just offstage, counting their money.
</P>
<P>
   Few here are ennobled by love; what drives Ms. Proulx's people
mainly is lust and lechery, itch and obsession. Ottaline Touhey,
the eldest daughter of the ranch family in ``The Bunchgrass Edge of
the World,'' is ``distinguished by a physique approaching the size
of a hundred-gallon propane tank.'' In conversation, ``a listener
would look back and forth between the pillowy, dimpled mouth and
crystal-crack blue eyes and think it a pity she was so big.''
Ottaline is so lonely that she hears her father's wreck of a John
Deere 4030 tractor talking to her _ ``Sweetheart, lady-girl'' _
begging her to restore it.
</P>
<P>
   Rasmussen Tinsley, in ``People in Hell Just Want a Drink of
Water,'' comes home to his family after five years of silent
absence. Left monstrously disfigured and speechless by an auto
accident, he takes to riding around neighboring farms and exposing
himself, until one outraged rancher fixes him with a dirty knife.
</P>
<P>
   What awaits most of the characters in these stories is the
hazards counted by Mrs. Freeze in ``Pair a Spurs,'' when she traces
a four-mile distance in her mind: ``Rattlesnake, gopher hole,
spooked horse, heatstroke, heart attack, lightning bolt.'' Or the
fate of Mero, the old ex-cowboy in ``The Half-Skinned Steer,'' who
drives across the country to his brother's funeral, only to get
lost and stuck in the snow and to look into a red eye of ``pure
teetotal hate'' pronouncing him ``done for.''
</P>
<P>
   Why should you read these stories, then, if their characters'
lives are so mean and their fates so inevitable? You read them for
their absolute authenticity, the sense they convey that you are
beyond fact or fiction in a world that could not be any other way.
And you read them for their language, not lyrical but a wry poetry
of loneliness and pain. After the castration of Ras Tinsley: ``The
morning light flooded the rim of the world, poured through the
window glass, colored the wall and floor, laid its yellow blanket
on the reeking bed, the kitchen table and the cups of cold coffee.
There was no cloud in the sky. Grasshoppers hit against the east
wall in their black and yellow thousands.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the names of the characters evoke the stinted world of
these stories: Tick Corn, Como Bewd, Hondo Gunsch, Pake Bitts, Dirt
Sheets, Wauneta Hipsag, Dig Yant, Car Scrope, John Wrench, Hulse
Birch and, a sly joke, Dunny Scotus from Whipup, Texas, suggesting
Duns Scotus, the 13th-century Scottish theologian who disputed
Aquinas' harmony of faith and reason and whose name eventually gave
rise to the word dunce.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, you have little choice about reading the stories once
you've begun them. At the opening of ``The Mud Below,'' Diamond
Felts is mounted on a bull called Kisses, ``rank and salty, big as
a boxcar of coal.'' Will his long rodeo slump finally end? Will he
feel once again ``the dark lightning in his gut, a feeling of
blazing real existence''?
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Governors of Wyoming,'' Wade Walls shows up at Shy
Hamp's ranch on a mission to fight ``these subsidized ranchers and
their gas-bag cows destroying public range, riparian habitat,
wiping out rare plants, trampling stream banks, creating
ozone-destroying methane gas, ruining the National Forests that
belong to the people, to all of us, stinking, polluting, stupid,
world-destroying cows ...'' When he spoke, ``his stiff face jerked
as though moved with hooks and wires.''
</P>
<P>
   At the start of ``Brokeback Mountain,'' the volume's strongest
story, Ennis del Mar and Jack Twist, two ``high school dropout
country boys with no prospects,'' find themselves passionately
attracted to each other sexually one summer while looking after
sheep on Brokeback Mountain. But they know that in Wyoming ``them
guys you see around sometimes'' have had their heads beaten in with
tire irons. So they try marrying women and living normal lives, and
seeing each other only on annual so-called fishing trips.
</P>
<P>
   ``Years on years they worked their way through the high meadows
and mountain drainages, horse-packing into the Big Horns, Medicine
Bows, south end of the Gallatins, Absarokas, Granites, Owl Creeks,
the Bridger-Teton Range, the Freezeouts and the Shirleys, Ferrises
and the Rattlesnakes, Salt River Range, into the Wind Rivers over
and over again, the Sierra Madres, Gros Ventres, the Washakies,
Laramies, but never returning to Brokeback.'' Two cowboys making
love.
</P>
<P>
   As the narrator of ``A Lonely Coast'' says, ``Wyos are touchers,
hotblooded and quick, and physically yearning.''
</P>
<P>
   A lonely coast. If you've ever been there, ``you've seen how the
shore rock drops off into the black water and how the light on the
point is final. Beyond are the old rollers coming in for millions
of years. It is like that'' in Wyoming ``at night but instead of
the rollers it's wind. But the water was here once. You think about
the sea that covered this place hundreds of millions of years ago,
the slow evaporation, mud turned to stone. There's nothing calm in
those thoughts. It isn't finished, it can still tear apart. Nothing
is finished. You take your chances.''
</P>
<P>
   In Ms. Proulx's bleak but expressive stories, the stone turns
back to mud again. People take their chances and lose.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `CLOSE RANGE: Wyoming Stories'
</P>
<P>
   By Annie Proulx
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated by William Matthews. 283 pages. Scribner. $25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
