<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2846 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOREA-ARTS-ART-NYT &LR;      05-11 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-ARTS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOREANS, LONG COPIERS, TRY A NEW ROAD TO CREATIVITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ She may or may not become a great artist,
but Ji Hyun-eun has the makings of a great photocopier.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Ji spends four hours a day, six days a week, in
after-school art classes, as do most Korean high school students
who aspire to become artists. And the centerpiece of those classes
is copying: the laborious sketching of the same classical
sculptures, over and over, until she can sketch them in her dreams.
</P>
<P>
   This is the fourth year that Miss Ji has been doing this in her
after-school hours, and she seems only slightly frustrated that she
has spent her time copying other people's works rather than
producing her own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like creativity, but to be creative I have to do this
first,'' she said as she sketched a classical bust, surrounded by
other art students doing exactly the same thing. ``If I can sketch
this well, then I can do well in my entrance exams and then I can
get into art school and become an artist.''
</P>
<P>
   South Korea has an ancient and dazzling artistic tradition, and
it would be difficult to find a society that treats art more
respectfully, but these days there is a growing sense in South
Korea that the system of nurturing young artists is
catastrophically flawed. The problem is that many art departments
admit students largely based on their ability to copy classical
busts, so that is what artistically inclined children spend years
learning to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's terrible,'' Kim Heung-sou, one of Korea's greatest modern
artists, said of the education system for training artists. ``It's
copying. It's not art.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to be a good artist, you must draw what you
like,'' said Kim, whose work hangs in museums around the world
under his pen name, Kimsou. ``You need creative work.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim, 80, says the education system is stunting not just art but
the economy as well. When South Korea was hit in the fall of 1997
by the Asian economic crisis, he and many other Asians decided that
an underlying reason was that society was too regimented and not
creative enough. Kim reasons that as long as countries like South
Korea are simply expert at manufacturing other people's products,
they will always risk losing production to countries with lower
wages.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I decided we needed more creativity in society, and we
needed to bring it in with the children,'' Kim said as he relaxed
on a couch in an apartment overflowing with books and magnificent
canvases. Kim started his own program to train artists, choosing 80
elementary school pupils from 3,000 who applied. He meets with them
weekly for three hours and has them draw what they want so long as
it has some meaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at this,'' he said, clutching a childlike sketch. ``This
is by a 6-year-old girl! This part is her dream of getting married
some day, so she is in a wedding dress, and this is her groom.
Isn't it wonderful!''
</P>
<P>
   The search for ways to inject creativity into education is
evident elsewhere in East Asia, from Japan to Taiwan to China, and
the issue is particularly relevant in the arts, which are supposed
to be society's creative frontier. Young artists in the region have
traditionally learned their trade by meticulously copying the work
of their teachers for years or decades. Respect for the teacher was
so great that it might have been seen as disrespectful to draw
things differently.
</P>
<P>
   The seriousness with which art is taken in South Korea is
evident on Picasso Street, as the street with the art schools is
nicknamed. It has scores of art institutes and art supply stores.
In Korea there are eight applicants for every place in a university
art program, and an applicant has almost no chance of being
admitted without a few years of study every evening in a private
art institute.
</P>
<P>
   One result is that South Korea is one of the few countries where
ordinary artists drive sports cars and dine in the flashiest French
restaurants. The artists get rich not selling their work but
tutoring high school students who want to get into university art
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Picasso Street may have plenty of art, but it somehow lacks the
creative impulse that inspired Picasso. ``I often tell my students
that if Picasso, Dali or van Gogh took lessons here, using this old
method of sketching busts, they would not make it into art
university,'' said Chung Chung-sik, the 42-year-old owner of the
Dae Sang Art Institute on the street.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even the critics acknowledge that the system has some
advantages. Korean artists have outstanding technical skills, and
all that copying of classical statues gives students a foundation
of facial expressions and shading that serves them throughout their
careers.
</P>
<P>
   Some Korean artists acknowledge that their own system
shortchanges creativity but argue that the American system has
precisely the opposite problem. American artists, some suggest, are
full of wild ideas but lack rigorous artistic skills, so they
produce works that are sometimes more creative than artistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worry about American art schools,'' Kim fretted. ``They
don't teach the foundation; they just do the ideas. So you get
post-modern art that is just like graffiti.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case Korean art schools are beginning to change the
admission process, and the ability to copy classical busts is
steadily becoming less important.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the universities seem to feel great pressure to change,''
said Joung Ki-jun, owner of the Hwal Joo Ro Art Institute.
``Because, to be frank, the contradictions in the system are such
that art students here are not able to realize their full artistic
potential.''
</P>
<P>
   Some artists are optimistic that the changes will breathe new
life into Korean art, grafting new creative outlets onto a system
that has brilliant technical training.
</P>
<P>
   ``Korean art used to be very stuffy,'' said Chung, the institute
owner. ``But now all that is changing, and because of those changes
I think Korean art has a very bright future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
