A2856 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-ADVISORY-NYT &LR;      05-11 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-ADVISORY-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service commends to your attention a
feature package with photos and graphics from  &UR; The Seattle
Post-Intelligencer &LR; . The stories will be filed on Wednesday for
immediate release or for weekend use.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIFE AND DEATH IN IRAQ: A nation sagging under the weight of
sanctions &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Larry Johnson, foreign editor of The Seattle Post-Intelligencer,
accompanied by photographer Larry Johnson, recently spent two weeks
in Iraq to report on the effect U.N. sanctions have had on Iraq's
people, most notably its children.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and DeLong traveled with a delegation called Washington
Physicians for Social Responsibility. They returned with a
compelling story of how the fabric of family life has been torn as
children are forced to drop out of school and find work and how
thousands of malnourished children are dying every month because of
a lack of medicine and food.
</P>
<P>
   Also contributing to the package was Michael Paulson, the
Post-Intelligencer's Washington correspondent.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ (Baghdad) _ At Al Mansour Pediatric Hospital, malnourished
children lay on stained mattresses. The hospital is dark;
electrical power is cut periodically each day to conserve
resources. Moving from bed to bed, Dr. Tarig Al-Shujairi lists the
illnesses: typhoid fever, pneumonia, leukemia, tuberculosis,
cholera. A nurse runs by carrying a small bottle of oxygen. Nemya,
a blond 2-year-old with meningitis is unable to breathe through the
fluid clogging her bronchial tubes. Her father and mother stand at
the side of her bed while the nurse covers Nemya's face with the
small oxygen mask. It is too late. Nemya's chest heaves, her body
shakes, and she dies. Her mother pulls her scarf close about her
face and cries silently. Her father looks at a visitor and touches
his chest over his heart. A fifty-cent tube could have saved her
life, but the hospital has none. Impossible to obtain under the
sanctions, Al-Shujairi says. Such is life _ and death _ in Iraq
under the sanctions imposed by the United Nations in the wake of
the 1991 Gulf War. By Larry Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-VIGNETTES (Undated) _ Star-dash anecdotes on daily life in
Baghdad: a visit to an orphanage, at a wedding, an evening at the
tea house on the banks of the Tigris River (smoking flavored
tobacco from a water pipe), visiting a mosque during prayers, and a
military preparedness and training session for members of the
ruling Baath Party, including women. By Larry Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-FIXES (Washington) _ In Congress, the critics of sanctions
are pushing several pieces of legislation that would exempt food
and medicine from sanctions, or that would require congressional
approval and impose sunsets. From politicians to grass roots
activists, there are more and more calls to get rid of a program
that critics say does more harm to innocent people than achieves
its stated goals. With 1 picture. By Michael Paulson.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-SANCTIONS (Washington) _ Since the end of the Cold War, the
U.S. and the U.N. have increasingly resorted to embargoes and trade
restrictions as a way of attempting to force change in countries
whose policies they don't like. The breadth of sanctions is
staggering: 42 percent of the world's population now lives in
sanctioned countries. Now, sanctions are coming under assault by
the business community and from those who argue sanctions hurt
civilians, not political leaders. By Michael Paulson.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-DOCTORS (Undated) _ Capsules on the 22-member delegation to
Baghdad, which included doctors, a veteran, a peace activist, a
writer, an artist and a medical student.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-TRIP (Undated) _ An short explainer outlining the
circumstances of the trip, how it came about.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-TIMELINE (Undated) _ A timeline of key events in Iraq since
it invaded Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-FACTS (Undated) _ Quick facts on its people, geography,
government.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions about the package, call Veronica
Villarreal in Seattle at (206) 448-8342, after Monday. Other
questions, call the N.Y. Times News Service at (212) 556-1927.
</P>
</TEXT>
