<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-EATING-WELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EATING WELL: DO-IT-YOURSELF AIRLINE MEALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: recipes at end of article)  
 (bl)  
 By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not so long ago, when I passed through the gate to board a Delta
dinner flight from New York to Atlanta, I spied a stack of filled
brown paper bags and assumed they contained leftover bagels from a
breakfast flight.
</P>
<P>
   It was not until it was too late that I learned those bags were
not discards but dinner. Because no sign or person had advised me
to pick one up, I flew the whole way on an empty stomach. Not that
I missed much, but at 30,000 feet you have no other options for
feeding yourself.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called act of dining aboard an airplane, at least on
domestic flights, has sunk to such depths that airports are doing a
land-office business in carry-on food, and things should only get
busier with the summer flying season setting in.
</P>
<P>
   There are flights that promise to serve a meal but deliver only
pretzels or, at best, mystery meat laminated to a squishy roll;
there are lunchtime flights with nothing at all, as airlines
tighten their belts to save money on food service. (Why don't they
put that extra money into the space between the seats?)
</P>
<P>
   One friend jokes that the only way to get lunch while traveling
cross-country is to board between 11:05 and 11:07 and be over a
certain state at a certain time.
</P>
<P>
   Choices at the airport are generally better than those on the
plane _ particularly in the wake of the recall reported in February
of 78,000 burritos made for American Airlines by Culinary Foods of
Chicago, a subsidiary of Tyson Foods. They were found to be
contaminated with listeria.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even airport fare is not necessarily what you might
choose to eat if you were looking for something that tasted good
and was good for you.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, make something at home, preferably the night before
travel. Cooking the day of a flight is not what most people want to
fit into a harried day of departure.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few rules for what you take on board. The food
should be easily portable and easy to cut or in bite-size bits,
because of the shortage of elbow room. It should not be too
aromatic: that's not fair to fellow passengers (especially if
they're hungry).
</P>
<P>
   You don't need fancy cutlery; plastic disposables will do. Do
take plenty of napkins. And while flying is dehydrating, the
airlines are still generous with liquids.
</P>
<P>
   But stay away from the very salty foods like peanuts, pretzels
and pizza: the salt just adds to the dehydration.
</P>
<P>
   One way to make cooking for a trip relatively painless is to
make twice as much for dinner of a dish that would also make an
appropriate cold meal on the flight the next day. And it takes very
little additional time to cook extra.
</P>
<P>
   The leftover food will also have time to chill in the
refrigerator. Food can be kept at room temperature for as long as
two hours; if you wait longer than that to eat your on-board meal,
it should be packed with a re-usable chill pack in an insulated
soft-side bag.
</P>
<P>
   Use old plastic containers for carrying the food, preferably
some that you can toss out rather than pack for the return flight.
</P>
<P>
   The recipes suggested here were chosen because they taste as
good the second day as the first and can be prepared quickly. The
pork and potato-arugula salad is ready in 20 minutes; the tuna
salad sandwich in 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, certain leftover cooked vegetables are delicious
chilled: steamed asparagus, broccoli florets, green beans, boiled
potatoes. They are especially good with a dipping sauce like salsa.
Cherry tomatoes on the stem are also perfect finger food.
</P>
<P>
   Fruit is a good choice because it is a hydrating low-calorie
snack that requires no cutlery; any apple you bring from home will
taste better than what the flight attendant hands out. Pick
whatever is in season and will not squash easily like berries.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the selection, keep it light. But if all else fails, a
2-ounce tin of caviar, a hard-cooked egg and some toast rounds
would hold most people, at least during meal service.
</P>
<P>
   BARBECUED PORK
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons coarsely grated fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sherry vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons reduced-sodium soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 pound pork tenderloin, washed and trimmed
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil pan spray.
</P>
<P>
   1. Combine ginger, vinegar and soy sauce. Cut pork into 3
pieces, making the thin end longer than the middle and the other
end. Coat with ginger mixture and allow to marinate for 15 minutes
or overnight if you like (refrigerated).
</P>
<P>
   2. Preheat a broiler or stovetop grill. Cover the broiler pan
with a double thickness of aluminum foil and spray with pan spray.
</P>
<P>
   3. Broil or grill the meat, turning once, until slightly pink at
the center. Allow about 10 minutes for the thin tail end and about
15 minutes for the rest. Watch carefully: it goes from pink to
overdone in a flash.
</P>
<P>
   4. Thinly slice and serve half the pork for dinner and
refrigerate the remaining portion in a a couple of layers of
aluminum foil. Place in a small insulated bag for the flight. Serve
with potato arugula salad.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   POTATO AND ARUGULA SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1{ pounds tiny new potatoes
</P>
<P>
   1\ bunches arugula
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1. Scrub potatoes but do not peel. Cook in water to cover in
covered pot for 15 to 20 minutes, depending on size. Drain and cut
in halves or quarters, depending on size.
</P>
<P>
   2. Thoroughly wash arugula under running water and cut off tough
stems. Drain and dry; break into bite-size pieces.
</P>
<P>
   3. Whisk together oil, vinegar and mustard in a bowl large
enough to hold all the ingredients in the recipe. Add potatoes and
arugula, toss and season with pepper. Serve half for dinner and
place the remaining half in a small plastic container with a
tight-fitting cover. Refrigerate. Place in small insulated bag for
the flight.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Note: You can also make a main dish of this by adding cooked
chicken strips or chunks. If cooking for one, halve the recipe.
</P>
<P>
   TUNA SALAD SANDWICH
</P>
<P>
   Time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 6- or 7-ounce can water-packed tuna, drained and rinsed
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon reduced-fat mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon bottled salsa
</P>
<P>
   { roasted red pepper, minced
</P>
<P>
   Cherry tomatoes, washed and dried
</P>
<P>
   4 thick slices whole wheat or multi-grain bread.
</P>
<P>
   1. Place tuna, mayonnaise and salsa in a food processor and
process almost to a paste.
</P>
<P>
   2. Stir in the red pepper and spread half the mixture on each of
two slices of bread. Top with remaining bread and cut in halves or
quarters. Wrap tightly in aluminum foil and refrigerate. Carry to
plane in an insulated bag with cherry tomatoes or other raw
vegetables like baby carrots.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
