<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, May 12, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A record 2.4 inches of snow fell at Williston, N.D., on Monday
as a cold upper-level low pressure system drifted overhead.
Wednesday, the cold, lofty low will stall over Saskatchewan,
Canada. In turn, an associated front at the surface will stall over
the upper Middle West, setting the stage for broken areas of rain,
some accented by thunder. Moderately heavy rain is possible over
portions of the upper Mississippi Valley and western Great Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of showers and thunderstorms will develop from the Gulf
states to the middle Mississippi Valley as moist air streaming
inland from the Gulf of Mexico is lifted by an upper-level trough
of low pressure arriving from the Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Isolated, potent thunderstorms will erupt across parts of west
Texas as humid winds from the southeast gliding up the westward
sloping terrain are further lifted by a jet stream disturbance. A
few storms could become severe. In the Southeast, showers and
thunderstorms will sprout across eastern sections of the Carolinas
and Georgia as an upper-level low pressure system stalled off the
coast destabilizes the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, hit-or-miss thunderstorms will bubble up over inland
areas of the Southeast. In Florida, isolated thunderstorms will
form in conjunction with sea-breeze fronts moving inland from the
Gulf and Atlantic coasts.
</P>
<P>
   Widely separated, gusty thunderstorms will flare Wednesday
afternoon near the Mason-Dixon Line as a cool front arrives from
the north at a time of maximum afternoon heating and greatest
instability.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Changing Sites
</P>
<P>
   The place with the longest continuous weather records in
California, which date back to 1849, has been moved to a new
location, in the Sacramento area. The sensors have been moved
several times during the last 150 years, but this is the first
change since 1933. The new location for the thermometer and
rainfall data was chosen with great care, since sites with reliable
long-term weather records are very important in studies of climate
change. In particular, the Sacramento data will be used to study
the effects of urbanization on climate since the city has grown
substantially since 1933. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
