<HEADLINE>
HOLD YOUR NOSE! RARE FLOWER TO BLOOM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By LAURA HIGGINS   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ An enormous and smelly flower has begun to
bloom here at Marie Selby Botanical Gardens.
</P>
<P>
   The plant is a Titan arum, which officials at Selby Gardens
describe as a ``bizarre behemoth of the plant world.'' A second
Titan Arum at Selby is also expected to bloom this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Horticulturalists say there is no way to predict when this rare
event might occur again. Selby has gone so far as to set up a
telephone hotline at (941) 366-2815 to give daily updates as the
blooms unfurl.
</P>
<P>
   So rare is this massive flowering that it has occurred only
seven times this century in the United States. Blooms can reach
heights of 7 feet or more. The crimson flower emits an odor of epic
proportions, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It smells really bad _ like dead meat,'' said George Weich,
Selby's director of horticulture, ``but only when it's in full
flower.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the plant blooms so infrequently, the titan's intense
smell is needed to ``carry some distance'' to attract pollinator
beetles, Weich said.
</P>
<P>
   The plant is found in the rain forests of Indonesia. Selby
acquired seeds seven years ago from a horticulturalist who visited
Sumatra. Each year, the titan, or Amorphophallus titanum, sends up
a single leaf or a flower. Until now, the two plants have sent up
only leaves.
</P>
<P>
   This year is different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up until today, you couldn't tell what was going on,'' Weich
said Monday about the larger bloom. ``It just looked like a bullet
coming out of the ground. Now it's unfurling a little bit. It's
beginning to look like a flower.''
</P>
<P>
   ``From here on,'' he added, ``it almost explodes.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the larger bloom was 36 1/2 inches tall and the
smaller was 24 inches. The blooms will grow at a rate of three to
four inches a day before reaching a peak of approximately 6 1/2
feet high by 3 feet wide. The full flowering lasts about 48 hours
before collapsing from its own weight.
</P>
<P>
   Selby plans to cross-pollinate the plants. If successful it
would be a botanical first, since a titan has never yielded seeds
in cultivation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no particular season for it,'' Weich said of the
blooming. ``You just never know. It has its own timetable, but we
don't know what that is.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota, Fla., Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
