<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-LAWMAKER-ART-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MUSLIM SCARF SPARKS A DEBATE ON DEMOCRACY IN TURKEY
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Texas)  (ART ADV: Photo of Ms. Kavakci is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ Sitting demurely behind her desk dressed in
immaculate white, Merve Kavakci does not look like someone who
could send a nation of 65 million into turmoil. But because of what
she wears, she has done exactly that.
</P>
<P>
   It is not Ms. Kavakci's chic white suit with gold buttons that
caused the problem. It is the white scarf that covers her head,
coupled with ideas of freedom she developed while living in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kavakci was elected to Parliament last month, but when she
entered the parliamentary chamber in Ankara to take her oath of
office, pandemonium broke out. More than 100 legislators stood and
jeered, failing to break her composure but setting off a political
earthquake that is still shaking Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   In the end Ms. Kavakci, 30, left the chamber without taking her
oath. It was decided that the parliamentary chamber, considered the
cathedral of the secular republic, is no place for a woman with a
Muslim scarf.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, perhaps fearing that she would set off a near riot if
she ventured into a restaurant or cafe, Ms. Kavakci invited a guest
to her office at the headquarters of her religious-oriented
political party, Virtue, in an outlying section of Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was expecting a reaction, but a democratic reaction,'' she
said of her memorable day in Parliament. ``I believe I had a right
to be there. I had been elected like the other 549 members. I am a
person like each of them. I campaigned like them, I eat like them,
I sleep like them. Because of my personal choice, I don't dress
like them. What they said was, `You are not like me so you can't
exist.'
</P>
<P>
   ``These were the same politicians who campaigned for more
democracy, who said they wanted democracy for everyone in this
country, freedom of speech, freedom of religion and blah blah blah.
If they really wanted democracy they would have supported me in
Parliament even if they didn't like the way I dress. But they have
a very elastic definition of democracy: democracy for me, but not
for you because you're different.''
</P>
<P>
   In the days since Ms. Kavakci burst onto the front pages,
secular politicians and commentators have been denouncing her as a
radical fundamentalist, a subversive bent on destroying Turkish
democracy, and an agent of Iran and Libya.
</P>
<P>
   President Suleyman Demirel called her an ``agent provocateur''
and said he had documents proving her ties to foreign powers. An
association that promotes women in Turkish politics condemned her
as ``a pawn in the hands of fanatical politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior prosecutor has announced that he is preparing a case
against Ms. Kavakci for ``fomenting hatred.'' Another prosecutor
said he would seek to ban her party on the grounds that it is ``a
vampire sucking the blood of the secular state.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Ms. Kavakci has received piles of
congratulatory messages from traditional Turks, many of them women,
who consider her an exciting new symbol of piety and political
defiance. There are more than a few cities in Turkey where she
could probably be elected mayor if elections were held now.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of Ms. Kavakci and her party assert that their long-term
goal is to impose a radical form of religious rule that will
ultimately destroy freedom in Turkey. They consider her embrace of
the language of democracy deeply cynical and mendacious.
</P>
<P>
   Cigdem Kagitcibasi, a professor of social psychology at Koc
University in Istanbul, said the wearing of head scarves created
social pressure on women who did not wear them, and warned that
this pressure could ultimately lead to the imposition of
``religious terror'' in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   ``At every point in the development of society,'' Ms.
Kagitcibasi asserted, ``religion has been used as a cover to block
and roll back progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in front of a Turkish flag in her office, however, Ms.
Kavakci asserted that her goal was not to subvert democracy, but to
implant it in a country that does not yet fully enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   If there is still a stereotype that women who wear Muslim head
scarves are meek and submissive, Ms. Kavakci destroys it as soon as
she begins to speak. She is intensely focused and highly
articulate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turkey has to sit down and decide whether we want to be a
democracy or not,'' she said, speaking in rapid-fire English. ``If
we want to be Communist or fascist, then I have no place here. But
in a democracy, my scarf would not be such a huge issue.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The roots of her militancy, Ms. Kavakci said, lie partly in
Turkey but also in the United States. After her mother quit her
post as a professor of German literature because of a conflict over
her head scarf, her father, a professor of Islamic law, decided to
start a new life. He became director of the Islamic Association of
North Texas, and moved to Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kavakci stayed behind, but she too had trouble at school
because of the head scarf she began wearing when she was 17. After
visiting her family for a vacation, she shocked them by announcing
that she was going to stay. She entered the University of Texas at
Dallas, graduating in 1994 with a degree in computer science.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the United States I was accepted, not discriminated
against,'' she said. ``People in America smile at everything and
tolerate everything. They accept you even if you have a different
background or culture or religion. They take it easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are different here. In our Parliament, if you think, if
you're smart, that's trouble. I am what I am, and they don't like
that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
