<HEADER>
A2877 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GMA-TEXAS-COX     05-11 0506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GMA-TEXAS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Charles Gibson tapes a segment on Texas barbecue
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The ``big hair'' mystery guest never showed up,
but about a hundred loud protesters did during the ``Good Morning
America'' telecast from the University of Texas campus on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   During an interview by Charles Gibson with Austin computer mogul
Michael Dell, a group protesting the delay in appointing an Asian
American studies program chairman revved up to fever pitch, nearly
drowning out the two men. The rowdy students continued to chant
during another interview with actors Brian Benben and Madeleine
Stowe, who live on a ranch near Fredericksburg.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd began gathering on the South Mall at 3 a.m., and
despite weathering a wild thunderstorm, they were mostly cheerful.
A few happy onlookers carried signs welcoming the ABC morning show
and a couple of men carried signs asking Diane Sawyer to marry
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good Morning America'' came to Austin for the first stop on
the program's ``Great American Gulf States Bus Tour.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week, executive producer Shelley Ross said
the Austin telecast would feature a ``mystery guest with big
hair,'' but that never materialized. An ABC publicist said a
shorter segment on Texas beauty shops that specialize in big hair
did air during a local news break, but nobody here saw it. No
mystery guest.
</P>
<P>
   Austinites who may have worried that the ABC program would make
us look like bumpkins breathed easily after the first few minutes,
when Gibson glowingly referred to the economic, political and
cultural influences of our fair area. We came off as smart and
sophisticated, not goofy.
</P>
<P>
   There were the expected features on barbecue (during which
Gibson donned a battered old cowboy hat and drooled over samples),
UT cheerleaders, an appearance by Bevo and his trusty Silver Spurs
and a performance by Shawn Colvin. There was one glaring error,
when Gibson referred to Walter Cronkite as one of UT's famous
grads. Uncle Walter attended but never graduated from UT.
</P>
<P>
   After greeting viewers, Sawyer sped off to the Governor's
Mansion, where she interviewed Gov. George W. Bush and his wife
Laura. Bush, who still claims he's not an official candidate for
president, was charming if evasive. Regarding renewed interest in
gun control in the wake of the Columbine High School massacre, Bush
said we should ``renew our efforts to be good moms and dads.''
</P>
<P>
   The highlight of the show was a tape of Sawyer's impromptu visit
to the Bowie High School prom, which took place Saturday night at
the Marriott, where the ``Good Morning America'' crew was staying.
Remember Elaine's awkward dancing on ``Seinfeld''? That pretty much
sums up Sawyer, and she must have known it. There were lots of
laughs as she made her way around the dance floor.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Holloway writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
