<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO CONFLICT
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-STRIKES _ WASHINGTON _ Forging a powerful union, Russia
and China called Tuesday for an immediate halt to NATO air strikes
against Yugoslavia, in a move that threatened to scuttle U.S.
efforts to win United Nations support for sending military
peacekeepers to the embattled province of Kosovo. NATO dismissed
the pleas of Beijing and Moscow and forged ahead with an
intensifying and escalating air campaign that winds up its seventh
inconclusive week on Wednesday. (Deans, Cox News Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move by 7:30 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES _ KUKES, Albania _ As the tide of refugees
continues to flow into here from neighboring Kosovo province,
frustrated humanitarian aid officials struggled Tuesday to increase
its ebb by asking for volunteers to move to southern Albania.
Meanwhile, their counterparts in Macedonia appeared to meet with
some success as Kosovo refugees from crowded camps in Macedonia
began to move to a new camp near the southern Albanian town of
Korca. Developing. (Holmes, Cox News Service). 20. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 5 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE _ The chairman of the failed Medicare reform commission
Tuesday lashed out at his fellow Democrats, charging that many of
them want a campaign issue more than real reform. ``There are
clearly those who don't want to do anything on this and use this as
a political issue,'' said Sen. John Breaux, D-La., who chaired the
recent Bipartisan Commission on the Future of Medicare. (Lipman,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WASTE-HUD _ If the third time wasn't a charm, perhaps the fourth
will be for the federal government in its attempt to unload one of
its longest-running housing disasters. Clifton Towers, just a short
drive from the U.S. Capitol and a symbol of subsidized housing gone
awry, is being offered to private developers for $1 plus a federal
promise of $8.2 million for renovations . Over the last 30 years,
three landlords allowed it to deteriorate into a crime and rat
infested neighborhood hazard. (Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS-CONGRESS _ WASHINGTON _ Congress on Tuesday begins
taking steps to respond to the Colorado school shootings. The
principal vehicle is a Senate juvenile crime bill that Democrats
hope to amend with gun-control measures. (Mollison, Cox News
Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   LINDER _ Rep. John Linder talks about how members of Congress
use the Internet aand about potential legislation to regulate its
use. (Sherman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BARR-WEBSITE _ Bob Barr's website is declared the best on
Capitiol Hill. (Sherman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   CHUNG _ WASHINGTON _ Appearing before Rep. Bob Barr and others
on the Burton committee, campaign fund-raising figure Johnny Chung
is testifying in public for the first time, alleging that the head
of Chinese military intelligence provided $300,000 intended to help
re-elect President Clinton. (Carr, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   HAITIAN _ WASHINGTON _ Some 50,000 Haitian refugees eligible to
become permanent residents of the United States can apply to change
their status beginning next month under regulations being published
today by the Immigration and Naturalization Service. (Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MAIN _ ATLANTA _ President Clinton visits the Sweet
Auburn Curb Market today to unveil the administration's new market
strategies to encourage growth in underserved communities. Clinton
likely will call on private corporations to help small businesses
get established, grow and thrive in these communities. Atlanta was
chosen because it has a reasonably successful Empowerment Zone and
is home to some of the nation's richest corporations. (Campos,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
