<HEADER>
A2881 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARCHEFS-SFCHRON &LR;      05-11 3059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARCHEFS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
(Editors Note: In this package, the Chronicle profiles six rising
stars among Bay Area chefs. The package will move in three parts.
Profiles of three of the stars are included below. Each profile is
followed by a recipe from the chef. Also look for  STAR CHEFS2, 
profiles of the three other stars, and  STARS SIDE , which tells
where to find this year's stars and what became of previous stars.) &HT;     &HT;     HERE COME THE STARS: Young Bay Area Chefs on the Rise  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Who are the people who will make a splash in the
Bay Area in 2000 and beyond? The Food staff dusted off its crystal
ball and came up with half a dozen likely candidates.
 &HT;    Truth be told, we didn't really need any supernatural tools. We
were guided by our taste buds. The chefs highlighted here have
wowed us with their savory courses or their miraculous desserts and
pastries.
 &HT;    All of our chefs have one thing in common _ they take a classic
approach to food. You won't find wild cross-cultural cooking in any
of their repertoire. Five are grounded in classic French and one in
rustic Italian.
 &HT;    The future never tasted so good.
 &HT;     
 PROFILES: HEATHER HO, SARAH LAMBERT, CRAIG STOLL  
   
   
 PROFILE: HEATHER HO  
 
 By Karola Saekel   
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
Majoring in hotel and food management at Boston University, Heather
Ho and her family expected that she would become a manager, an
executive. So when she so loved the program's food/cooking
component that she decided to become ``just a cook,'' the family
was nonplussed.
<P>
   They've gotten over the shock. After graduating from the
prestigious Culinary Institute of America at Hyde Park, N.Y., and
an internship at San Francisco's then-brand-new Aqua, where her
nascent love affair with pastry came into full bloom, the
Honolulu-born chef secured jobs at such prestigious Manhattan
restaurants as JoJo, Gramercy Tavern, Screening Room and
Clementine.
</P>
<P>
   When she was offered the position of pastry chef at Boulevard
last fall, she didn't think long before accepting. For one thing,
she says, ``I always wanted to come to San Francisco'' (where her
mother now lives). For another, her style and philosophy are in
perfect sync with Boulevard chef/owner Nancy Oakes. ``I've never
worked in a more congenial place,'' Ho says.
</P>
<P>
   She also finds Boulevard's clientele receptive to her style of
dessert-making. ``I like American classics,'' she says _ with a bit
of tweaking.
</P>
<P>
   That tweaking often takes the form of deconstructing a
traditional recipe, then reassembling it in a fresh way. Example:
that old standby, fruit crisp. Ho starts with a shortbread crust,
tops it with stewed fruit, then caps it with a separately baked
crumb topping. With this treatment, the bottom retains its
integrity, the fruit is cooked just to the right degree and the
topping is crisp and crunchy rather than soggy _ a drawback to most
standard crisps.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, Ho says, it's still a comfortingly familiar dessert.
</P>
<P>
   She has found that diners may be adventurous when choosing an
entree or appetizer, but they tread more traditional ground when it
comes to desserts. Strawberries will outrank mango or pineapple any
day of the week, she says. Anything with raspberries sells, and if
a pastry chef wants to play it really safe, nothing beats creme
brulee.
</P>
<P>
   The trick in creating successful restaurant desserts, Ho says,
is to come up with something that's familiar yet sports an element
of surprise. To make this work, Ho plays with intriguing shapes,
adds an herb or pairs fruit and/or pastry with an unusual ice cream
flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurant desserts should be neat and tidy and not too big _
``no doggie bags for dessert,'' she quips.
</P>
<P>
   Comparing her East and West Coast experiences, Ho says New
Yorkers have a penchant for chocolate and expect dressier desserts.
San Franciscans appreciate a more straightforward approach _ and
they know and love fruit: ``You don't have to explain what a quince
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Ho believes that a chef _ pastry or otherwise _ should balance
personal creativity and customer expectations. No matter how
imaginative a dish might be, if it scares diners it's a failure.
</P>
<P>
   She hasn't found San Francisco diners overly conservative, but,
thankfully, they also aren't likely to make the kind of wacky
requests that sometimes confound New York chefs. ``No chocolate
sauce on tarte Tatin,'' she says, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DEVIL'S FOOD CAKE WITH CARAMELIZED BANANAS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Heather Ho &LR; , pastry chef at Boulevard, &LR;  offsets the intense
chocolate flavor of this cake with whipped cream, or vanilla or
caramel ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Cake &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cocoa
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup boiling water
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   11/3 cups light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 egg + 1 egg white, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup pecans, toasted
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 cup + 2 tablespoons cake flour
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   Pinch salt
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Caramel Pecan Topping &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup water
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons cream
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups pecans, toasted and finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Banana Topping &LR;
</P>
<P>
   4 or 5 firm-ripe bananas
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Lightly grease and flour a 10-inch
springform pan.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the cake:  &LR; Whisk together the cocoa and boiling water
until smooth. Cover with plastic wrap and let cool to room
temperature. Whisk in half of the buttermilk, mixing until smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the mayonnaise, brown sugar, egg, egg white and vanilla.
Beat with an electric mixer until very light and nearly doubled in
volume, about 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the pecans, the 2 flours, baking powder, baking soda and
the salt in a food processor and pulse until the mixture achieves a
powdery consistency. Add to the beaten egg mixture in thirds,
alternating with the remaining buttermilk. Fold in the chocolate
mixture until just combined.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the batter into the prepared pan and bake in the lower
third of the oven for 25 to 30 minutes, until a cake tester
inserted in the center comes out clean. Place on a rack and let
cool to room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   The cake may be made up to 8 hours in advance to this point.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the topping:  &LR; Combine the sugar, corn syrup and water
in a small, heavy-bottom saucepan. Place over medium heat and cook
until the mixture turns amber, washing down any sugar crystals
clinging to the sides of the pan using a pastry brush dipped in
water. Remove from heat and slowly add the cream. If lumps form,
return to heat briefly, stirring constantly, until smooth. Whisk in
the butter and fold in the pecans.
</P>
<P>
   The filling may be made up to 1 week in advance. Cover tightly
and keep refrigerated. Reheat in a double boiler or microwave until
quite warm (but not hot) and softened. Mixture will remain stiff.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To assemble:  &LR; Dot the top of the cake with the caramel, then
spread over the cake. This will be textured; do not expect a smooth
topping.
</P>
<P>
   Just before serving, preheat the broiler.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the bananas diagonally into thin slices, discarding ends.
Pat slices to flatten, then arrange on the cake in concentric
circles, starting from the perimeter. Try to cover the top as
completely as possible. Sprinkle with sugar and broil 3 to 5 inches
from the heat source, until the sugar melts and turns golden. Watch
carefully so it doesn't burn.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the rim of the springform; transfer the cake to a plate
and serve immediately, topped with whipped cream or ice cream if
desired.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 490 calories, &LR;   &LR; 6 g protein, 67 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 25 g fat (5 g saturated), 34 mg cholesterol, 187 mg sodium, 4 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; PROFILE: SARAH LAMBERT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By Kim Severson &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
Pastry chef Sarah Lambert walks into her Mill Valley patisserie by
3:30 a.m. six days a week. She heads home at 7 p.m., often so tired
she barely has energy to talk to her boyfriend or walk her two
dogs.
</P>
<P>
   She often spends hours searching for the right ingredients, like
organic rose petals, candy or perfect golden raspberries to top a
tart. And she gets personal with her customers _ during the wedding
season, she'll sit with three or four couples a week, patiently
helping them select their cakes.
</P>
<P>
   At 27, the bright young chef from New Jersey who owns the sleek
Patisserie Lambert finds herself with a heavy workload. Despite the
pressure, she's an incredibly nice person. At least, that's what
her staff of 10 will tell you. Lambert certainly won't. She's more
interested in discussing the finer points of patissiere, a culinary
territory she approaches with the intensity of a chemist and the
eye of an artist.
</P>
<P>
   In the 16 months Patisserie Lambert has been open, it has gained
the affections of Marin residents, picky French ex-patriots and San
Franciscans who appreciate her authentically French baked goods.
</P>
<P>
   Lambert's shop is functionally designed with contemporary black
snake lights, a processed cement floor with a copperlike patina and
stainless steel cases that contain some savory items, like
caramelized onion, bacon and Gorgonzola quiche. But her focus is
sweet French pastry.
</P>
<P>
   In high school, Lambert spent her spare time in the kitchen. She
prepped food in an Italian restaurant and learned the basics at
home from her grandfather and mother. She left the East Coast and
took up studies at the California Culinary Academy because
California seemed like the best place to learn about food. Although
she trained in every aspect of cooking, she kept drifting back to
the pastry kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Lambert calls on her training in cooking and her delight in
dining out to inspire her pastry work. For example, a
saffron-perfumed chicken dish she ate out led to a honey-saffron
Bavarian mousse with sliced peaches.
</P>
<P>
   She brainstorms with head pastry chef Shawn Brennan, a former
chef at Charles Nob Hill in San Francisco who also uses flavors
found in entrees to enhance pastry, like a gingered white-pepper
shortbread.
</P>
<P>
   But twists on tradition aren't Lambert's trademark. Tradition
itself is. An apprenticeship under a German chef at the San
Francisco Hilton cemented her appreciation for the formal
constructs of European baking. Further training at Le Cordon Bleu
in Paris and work under master French pastry chefs at Le Cirque in
New York and La Folie in San Francisco sharpened her skills.
</P>
<P>
   Authenticity matters to Lambert. She often offers pate a choux
filled with hazelnut praline cream flavored with rum and vanilla.
The traditional but obscure French pastry is shaped like a bicycle
tire and called a ``Paris Brest,'' named after a bike race from
Paris to Brest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get a lot of French customers who ... say, `This is just
like home.'''
</P>
<P>
   American-born customers are fond of her perfect petit four
glace, almond tarts and Vahlrona truffles, which show up by the
dozen at parties in Marin County.
</P>
<P>
   Lambert strives to find the balance between pleasing customers
and producing pastries true to their origins. For example, she has
had to pull customers around to her way of thinking about cakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are surprised by the lack of sweetness. But my cakes
aren't as sweet. I don't want everything to taste of sugar.''
</P>
<P>
   Lambert's challenge remains running her shop, although at the
urging of some of her New Jersey investors, she is considering
expanding to the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, finding some time to relax is high on her list.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SARAH LAMBERT'S MERINGUE KISSES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Though simple to make, these cookies are incredibly satisfying.
The light meringue provides contrast for the large amount of
chocolate. Use the best quality chips you can find.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   10 egg whites
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   5 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   5 cups chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons vanilla
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Instructions: &LR;  Preheat the oven to 250 degrees. Line a baking
sheet with parchment paper.
</P>
<P>
   Using an electric mixer on low speed, Beat the egg whites until
frothy. Add the salt and beat on medium speed until the whites
begin to stiffen. Increase the mixer speed to high and beat until
the whites hold firm peaks.
</P>
<P>
   Reduce mixer speed to medium and slowly add the sugar, a couple
tablespoons at a time. When all the sugar has been added, increase
mixer speed and beat until the ingredients are incorporated and the
sugar crystals have dissolved (rub a little of the meringue between
your fingers; you'll be able to feel any sugar grains).
</P>
<P>
   Using a large spatula, fold in half of the chocolate chips and
half of the vanilla. Repeat with remaining chips and vanilla.
</P>
<P>
   Using a large ice cream scoop, portion into well rounded mounds
on the baking sheet. Bake for about 30 minutes, or until just
lightly colored.
</P>
<P>
   Cool and store in an airtight container.
</P>
<P>
   Yields 25 cookies.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER COOKIE: &LR;   &LR; 335 calories, &LR;   &LR; 3 g protein, 59 g carbohydrate,
12 &LR;   &LR; g fat (7 g saturated), 0 mg cholesterol, 68 mg sodium, 0 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; PROFILE: CRAIG STOLL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By Robin Davis &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   At the bottom of the menu at Delfina is a statement that reads,
``Don't be afraid of your food.'' Chef/owner Craig Stoll is so
passionate about the subject, he hates hearing people say a certain
food is good for you or bad for you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stop with the food allergy du jour,'' he says. ``People should
enjoy food, enjoy life. That's what it's about.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoll is nothing if not opinionated, especially when it comes to
cooking. The 34-year-old worked his way through a number of Bay
area restaurants before opening his wildly popular Mission district
restaurant last &UR;  &LR; November.
</P>
<P>
   When he arrived in San Francisco after earning degrees from the
Culinary Institute of America in Hyde Park, N.Y., and Florida
International University, he landed at Campton Place in San
Francisco. A self-described punk (``I would have fired me,'' he
says), Stoll says working with people like former Campton Place
chefs Bradley Ogden and Jan Birnbaum made him realize how little he
knew.
</P>
<P>
   He also gained experience in restaurants such as Hawthorne Lane
and Splendido but attributes much of his cooking style to a
six-month internship in Italy. He spent half the time in cooking
classes in Piedmont and the other working at a restaurant called Da
Delfina outside Florence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned what ingredients, what food could really taste
like,'' Stoll remembers. ``I learned about simplicity, purity and
directness of flavors.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, his food at Delfina emphasizes seasonality.
``I try to focus on the flavors that are there instead of trying to
combine a lot of flavors,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The simple approach works. His spaghetti sauce is nothing more
than canned tomatoes, garlic, olive oil and basil, but the finished
dish is a revelation. Equally as good are his fluffy salt cod
brandade, roast chicken and flatiron steak next to a pile of crispy
fries.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, his restaurant is not Italian but is his take on
California cuisine or, as he says, ``what California cuisine should
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Stoll graciously credits his partner, Anne Spencer, with much of
Delfina's success. ``Annie is incredible with people,'' he
explains. ``When I met her, I met the front-of-the-house partner
I've always wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Plans for the restaurant include doubling the space by taking
over an antique shop next door and adding a wood-fired oven and an
outdoor patio. In terms of food, Stoll would like to continue to
expand his repertoire throughout each season.
</P>
<P>
   But despite some national attention, Stoll still considers
Delfina a neighborhood restaurant and says the people who come in
are the best customers he's ever had.
</P>
<P>
   ``People love the menu and they're not afraid of the food,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   And that makes this rising star very happy.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; DELFINA'S SPAGHETTI &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The secret to this simple and delicious recipe is partially
cooking the pasta in water then finishing the cooking in the pasta
sauce. This recipe yields enough sauce for 8 servings (it's easier
to make in a larger quantity). You will need only half of it for
this recipe. Ladle the remaining sauce into an airtight container
and freeze for another day. It freezes well for up to 2 months.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4 garlic cloves
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   2 (28-ounce) cans peeled whole tomatoes (such as Di Napoli)
</P>
<P>
   3 cups water
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Hot red pepper flakes to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 bunch fresh basil (leaves only), torn into small pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 pound spaghetti
</P>
<P>
   Freshly grated Parmigiano-Reggiano cheese
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Heat the oil in a large heavy saucepan over medium-low heat.
Smash the garlic with the side of a chef's knife; sprinkle with
salt. Add to the oil. Cover and cook slowly until tender but not
browned, about 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, remove the seeds from the tomatoes, breaking up
tomatoes slightly with your hands. Add the tomatoes and their
juices, along with the water to the saucepan. Increase heat to
medium-high. Season lightly with salt, pepper and chile flakes.
Bring to a boil. Skim the foam that rises to the top, being careful
not to skim the oil. Reduce heat to medium-low and simmer for about
2 hours, stirring occasionally, until the sauce is reduced by about
two thirds and the oil is emulsified in the sauce. Remove from
heat.
</P>
<P>
   Pass two thirds of the sauce through a food mill fitted with the
medium blade. Stir this puree into the remaining sauce, then stir
in the basil.
</P>
<P>
   Cook the pasta in a large pot of boiling salted water for 6
minutes. Drain, reserving 11/2 cups of the cooking water.
</P>
<P>
   Choose 2 large, heavy skillets. Place a generous 1/2 cup of the
sauce in each. Place over medium-high heat. Add 1/4 cup of the
reserved cooking water to each skillet. Divide the pasta between
the skillets. Cook, stirring frequently, until the pasta is cooked
through and sauce clings to the pasta, adding more cooking water if
necessary. Adjust seasonings.
</P>
<P>
   Divide pasta among serving plates. Sprinkle with Parmesan.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4, with leftover sauce.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 580 calories, &LR;   &LR; 16 g protein, 94 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 15 g fat (2 g saturated), 0 mg cholesterol, 325 mg
sodium, 2 g &LR;   &LR; fiber.  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
