<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2882 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOURCE-GREEN-SFCHRON &LR;      05-11 1666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOURCE-GREEN-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: This column profiles Northern California growers,
anglers and artisans who make the region such a culinary
wonderland. Over the next few months, we'll take you from field to
forest to factory to look at the wealth of ingredients stocking our
larders. As a bonus, Georgeanne Brennan will offer tips for using
the bounty in fresh, innovative ways.  AT THE SOURCE: Grower Finds Market for Specialty Greens  
 
 By Karola Saekel  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 CALISTOGA, Calif. _  You would think that when it comes to salad
greens, one size fits all.
 &HT;    You would be wrong.
 &HT;    At Forni Brown Vegetables, a Calistoga grower of organic salad
greens, herbs, tomatoes and baby vegetables, such celebrated Napa
Valley chefs as Thomas Keller of French Laundry and Hiro Sone of
Terra get greens grown to the size they prefer. Keller reportedly
likes 1/4-inch leaves; Sone opts for a somewhat larger size.
 &HT;    As well as meeting size preferences, Forni Brown plants
requested crops, sometimes from seeds the chefs bring to them from
Europe or Asia. ``Hiro,'' says gardener Lynn Brown, ``has to have
his shiso.'' Other chefs may want a particular European green, a
certain kind of mint or such delicacies as blanched frisee _
created by placing an upside-down flower pot over the plant.
 &HT;    The week of May 2 saw the first '99 harvest of this tender salad
green. This, says Brown, is the time when the year's first
plantings reach perfection. At his nursery, a five-minute walk from
Calistoga's main drag, Brown and partners plant every week, 10
months a year, supplying virtually all the major local restaurants
and a few beyond the valley.
 &HT;    Forni Brown concentrates on its chef customers, occasionally
selling to the public at a few seasonal farmers markets and
supplying the Palisades Market, a small, upscale deli in Calistoga.
But Brown says the methods his company has developed over the past
18 years are equally applicable to home gardens.
 &HT;    Most greens, he says, grow well in Northern California. To fill
your salad bowl fresh from the garden most of the year, he suggests
putting out seed every 10 days to two weeks, planting only as much
as your household will consume in two weeks.
 &HT;    Forni Brown's 41/2 acres in Calistoga keep as many as 30
restaurants in greens. But just recently the partners _ Brown,
Peter Forni and Barney Welsh _ acquired 170 acres administered by
the Sonoma Land Trust in nearby Knights Valley. Some of the land is
forested, but the partners are formulating plans for growing a lot
of organic vegetables on the historic farm site (complete with a
120-year-old barn).
 &HT;    Gardener Brown is passionate about his crops. His voice
practically shudders when he talks of some mass-marketed so-called
mesclun salad mixes that contain cut-up large romaine and spinach
leaves, with ornamental kale thrown in for color (see Food in the
News elsewhere in this section). ``That stuff (the kale) is
virtually inedible,'' he says, adding that the only ingredient that
should be torn is radicchio.
 &HT;    He admits that the definition of mesclun is a little vague. Some
purists insist that it should be based on dandelion greens, but he
likes to define it as ``small _ fork-size _ greens at their best.''
 &HT;    Almost as important as growing and harvesting correctly is the
way greens are handled after they have been picked. Brown says to
mix the greens for mesclun _ he uses up to 14 varieties, including
some Asian greens _ in a large bowl of water. If you mix them dry,
you are going to bend some leaves, he cautions, ``and in a couple
hours, you'll have brown streaks.''
 &HT;    After washing and mixing, the greens need to be dried. At home,
salad spinners are fine, but if you are fixing salad for a crowd,
you might do what Forni Brown does: Place the greens in mesh bags
(the kind used for machine washing lingerie) and put them in the
washing machine's spin cycle _ no water, no heat. Just make sure
there are no residues of detergent or bleach in the machine.
 &HT;    Many chefs, of course, buy different greens separately, but the
convenience of the precleaned mix has a lot of adherents. Industry
estimates predict that in a few years these mixes will account for
25 percent of salad greens sold in the United States, Brown says.
 &HT;    Brown has favorites among the 30 or so greens his company grows:
tatsoi, also known as Chinese spinach, is equally good picked small
or large and, although related to bok choy, has no cabbage flavor.
His favorite mustard green is Chinese red mustard, with a flavor
like Dijon mustard.
 &HT;    But his all-time pick is Little Gem, also known by its French
name, sucrine. It's a semi-romaine developed in France about 150
years ago, ``long before Luther Burbank.'' It's the preferred
lettuce in England, he says, and for good reason: Its
romaine-shaped heads carry smooth, flat leaves that are succulent
and possess none of the leathery quality often found in true
romaine.
 &HT;    Brown thinks Little Gem is a good green for proselytizing:
``Even people who say they don't like salad, including kids, love
this stuff.''
 &HT;     
 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) 
 
 SOME GREENS NEED NO DRESSING  
 
When you make a salad with assertive greens, such as tatsoi,
frisee, radicchio, arugula, mache, chicory, lolla rossa or Chinese
red mustard, you don't need to pile on a lot of extra flavors with
dressings. &HT;    In fact, says Lynn Brown, one of the three partners in Forni
Brown Vegetables of Calistoga, you shouldn't. Brown cites Chinese
red mustard _ one of his favorites _ as an example. This mustard
green, he says, has a flavor that evokes Dijon mustard, so the
simplest of dressings is the best: salt and pepper, olive oil and a
dash of balsamic vinegar.
 &HT;    If the mustard leaves are more than 5 or 6 inches tall, they're
best used for wraps.
 &HT;    Tatsoi can substitute for spinach in a salad. In fact, Brown
points out, it is sometimes called Chinese spinach. He says in
addition to making a fine salad, these greens are sturdy enough to
go into a stir-fry.
 &HT;    The preferred salad green in the Brown family kitchen is
sucrine, also known as Little Gem, dressed with salt, pepper, olive
oil, vinegar and a generous grating of fresh Parmesan.
 &HT;    Arugula, says Brown, takes well to a slightly more elaborate
treatment _ salt, pepper, oil, vinegar, Gorgonzola and toasted
walnuts.
 &HT;    Although salad ingredients account for nearly 90 percent of
Forni Brown's business, the company also grows tomatoes, eggplant,
edible flowers and herbs, including perennial favorite rosemary.
 &HT;    Brown has a suggestion for cooks who think they don't like the
flavor of rosemary: Chances are you are using the wrong kind of
rosemary. If the plant produces dark purple blossoms, it's the
ornamental kind. The paler the blossom, the better the taste, Brown
says. ``Dark-flowering rosemary may look pretty, but it tastes
soapy.``
 &HT;     
 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) 
 
 
 GEORGEANNE'S KITCHEN: Get Variety From Your Greens  
   
 By Georgeanne Brennan  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;  Young, tender springtime salad greens can be used
in more than just salads.
<P>
   &UR; Pizza of Bay Scallops, Goat Cheese and Young Salad Greens.
 &LR; Make a favorite pizza dough and roll it into thin 6- to 8-inch
rounds. Drizzle each round with a little olive oil; then add a
sprinkling of scallops, dollops of goat cheese and a sprinkling of
fresh thyme. Bake until the crust is crisp, the cheese melting and
the scallops cooked through. To serve, top with a mixture of baby
greens or baby arugula.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Quesadillas With Young Salad Greens and Teleme Cheese.  &LR; Cut
slices of teleme cheese and layer them over half a large flour
tortilla. Fold the other half over the cheese. Lightly oil a frying
pan and heat it over medium-high heat. Cook the folded tortilla on
each side until it is golden in spots and the cheese has melted.
Remove, open the tortilla and add a handful of greens.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pan-Seared Salmon on a Bed of Young Salad Greens.  &LR; Melt a
little butter in a frying pan over medium heat. Add a salmon fillet
skin side down and cook about 2 minutes. Turn and cook the other
side just until the meat is opaque and flakes. Sprinkle with salt
and pepper, and squeeze the juice of 1/2 to 1 lemon over the
salmon. Remove it to a plate of young greens, putting it on top of
the greens. Add a little white wine and a little chicken broth to
the frying pan, and reduce the juices to about 1 to 11/2
tablespoons. Pour them over the salmon and the greens.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Captain's Platter.  &LR; Arrange slices of smoked salmon, smoked
trout, brined herring and calamari salad on an individual plate or
small platter. Add peeled green grapes. Make a dressing of olive
oil, a little honey and raspberry vinegar. Toss baby greens in the
dressing and add them to the platter.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Fried Fish Sandwich with Young Salad Greens.  &LR; Roll a red
snapper fillet in seasoned flour, and fry it in hot olive oil a
minute or two on each side until the flesh is opaque and flakes
easily. Remove it to a toasted bun spread with tartar sauce. Top
with a handful of young greens.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Roasted Garlic-Walnut Chicken and Young Salad Greens.  &LR; Slip
lots of slivers of garlic beneath the skin of a 3- to 31/2-pound
chicken, season with salt and pepper and put in a roasting pan.
Roast at 350 degrees about 11/2 hours, basting from time to time,
until the skin is crispy and the juices of the inner thigh run
clear when pierced with the tines of a fork. Toast some walnut
pieces and set them aside. Make a dressing with walnut oil, salt,
pepper, a little red wine vinegar and a little of the pan juices of
the chicken. Toss the greens in the dressing, then arrange them on
a platter. Slice the chicken and arrange it on top of the greens,
being sure to include the garlic slivers. Serve warm.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR; Georgeanne Brennan, a food and garden writer who lives in Yolo &LR; 
 &LR; County, Calif., is the author of ``Aperitif'' and ``The Food &LR;   &LR; and
Flavors of Haute Provence.'' &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
