<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOODNEWS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Food, nutrition and health studies bombard us, but
the seemingly endless information is often as confusing as it is
enlightening. With Food in the News, The Chronicle's Food staff
aims to change that. This regular round-up column will make
practical sense of the latest nutrition-related studies _ as well
as offering offbeat but tantalizing snippets of other food news to
put on your plate. &HT;        FOOD IN THE NEWS: Is Ready-to-Eat Salad Safe to Eat?  
 &HT;     By Kim Severson  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; So how safe is that bag of pre-packaged salad in
the 'fridge?
<P>
   If you're relatively healthy, it's fine. But some government
researchers want to make ready-to-eat salad safer for the elderly,
some pregnant women and people with compromised immune systems.
</P>
<P>
   Their proposed &UR;  &LR; tool is irradiation, a process that shoots low
levels of ionized radiation through food to kill microbes and
retard spoilage. The controversial food treatment is being examined
largely as a way to reduce salmonella and other disease-causing
bacteria in beef and poultry, but some fruits and vegetables are
getting the rays.
</P>
<P>
   Although rare, irradiated strawberries, oranges, tomatoes and
mushrooms have appeared in some of the nation's produce bins.
Federal regulations require food treated with radiation be clearly
marked as such.
</P>
<P>
   Bags of ready-to-eat salad might one day be part of that mix.
Recent experiments at a U.S. Department of Agriculture laboratory
in Florida have shown that zapping packaged iceberg lettuce reduced
yeast and microbe populations significantly and only slightly
affected crispness. But how safe is too safe? That's the question
some food-science researchers and people in the $1.2 billion
bagged-salad industry are asking.
</P>
<P>
   Before it goes into oxygen-controlled bags, ready-to-eat lettuce
is washed in a chlorine solution and then in clean water. The
result is a product that has never been associated with a
food-borne illness, USDA officials say.
</P>
<P>
   That should be proof enough that a zap of radiation isn't
needed, says Larry Bell, vice president for science and technology
at Fresh Express, the pioneer in bagged salads, in Salinas, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Further, irradiating lettuce could actually make it less safe,
says Trevor Suslow, a post-harvest specialist at the University of
California at Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Irradiating food kills bad bacteria along with friendly
organisms that help keep it fresh, Suslow and Bell explain. The
process also extends shelf life, but by doing that disarms nature's
alarm: the spoilage process. Food that is rotted looks so
unappetizing that consumers don't buy _ or eat _ it, thus avoiding
potentially dangerous bacteria. But if the spoilage process is
interrupted, potentially unsafe pathogens can continue to grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time food has produced a toxin or that toxin has grown
to a high-enough level to make you sick, the produce is already
rotted. Irradiation might change that,'' Suslow says.
</P>
<P>
   Makers of prepacked salads, along with organic farmers, are
looking at ways other than radiation to supplement the chlorine
wash process, which can be hard on workers and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Pumping rinse water full of ozone, an environmentally safe
process which kills organic material and then becomes oxygen, is
one option. And the Environmental Protection Agency recently
approved some new disinfectants based on safer, alternative forms
of chlorine and other compounds.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Suslow says, don't worry about your salad's
safety. ``I wouldn't do any extra washing. It's a very clean
product already.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
