<SLUG> BC-TASTE-POTSTI-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel of
professional tasters tries a different product available in
supermarkets.  
 
 TASTER'S CHOICE: Top Frozen Potsticker Comes From Trader Joe's   By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  With all the convenience products in the freezer
case, making hors d'oeuvres for a party or an after-school snack
can be a breeze. Of course, it's no surprise that there are many
Asian offerings in this category like egg rolls and, more recently,
potstickers.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's panel tasted four different frozen potstickers, all with
vegetable fillings. Overall, the panel was disappointed with what's
in the market, saying that much better potstickers can be picked up
from most neighborhood Chinese restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Prices varied dramatically, but some were only slightly less
expensive than what you can buy at restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Potstickers were cooked according to package directions.
</P>
<P>
   Top honors went to  &UR; Trader Joe's &LR;  (16 ounces, $1.99). Two
panelists thought the filling was mushy, while two others found it
too sweet. But one panelist described this potsticker as ``thin and
delicate.'' Two would buy it, one might buy it, and two would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ling Ling &LR;  (15 ounces, $3.89 at many supermarkets) came in
second. One panelist thought this brand looked the most like
restaurant versions. One liked the noodles in the filling, but
another did not. Another liked the vegetable filling but found the
seasoning peppery. One would buy it, three might buy it, and one
would not.
</P>
<P>
   Scores dropped dramatically to third place, which went to
 &UR; Health is Wealth Vegetable  &LR; (6.4 ounces, $3.19 at Whole Foods).
Four panelists did not like the appearance _ a little like
traditional potstickers _ but one liked the crispy exterior. One
panelist described the filling as fishy tasting; another thought it
was bland. None would buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Scoring just six points below was  &UR; Health is Wealth Meatless &LR; 
(6.4 ounces, $4.39 at Whole Foods), which the package describes as
pork-free but with a ``delicious pork taste.'' Panelists didn't
agree, characterizing the tofu faux pork filling as unpleasant.
None would buy it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Panelists were Dan Bowe, associate culinary director, Center for
Culinary Development; John P. Carroll, cookbook author; Patricia
Hart, dietitian and consultant; Donna Katzl, chef-owner, Cafe For
All Seasons, San Francisco; and Kirk Webber, chef-owner, Cafe Kati,
San Francisco. All products are tasted blind.  &QL;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
