 WHERE TO SPOT RISING STARS
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
(Editors Note: This is the third part of a three-part package
profiling six rising stars among Bay Area chefs. Look for
 STAR  CHEFS  and  STAR CHEFS2  for profiles of and recipes from
each chef.) &HT;     SAN FRANCISCO _  Here is where you can feast on food created by
this year's Rising Star chefs.
 &HT;     Chad Callahan.  Masa's, 648 Bush St. (at Powell), San
Francisco, Calif.; (415) 989-7154. Dinner Tuesday-Saturday. Closed
Sunday-Monday.
 &HT;     Heather Ho.  Boulevard, 1 Mission St. (corner of Steuart
Street), San Francisco, Calif.; (415) 543-6084; Lunch weekdays,
dinner nightly.
 &HT;     Sarah Lambert.  Patisserie Lambert, 457 Miller Ave. (at Valley
Circle), Mill Valley. Calif.; (415) 389-1977. Open 7 a.m.-2 p.m.
Monday-Tuesday, until 6 p.m. Wednesday-Saturday. Closed Sunday.
 &HT;     Richard Reddington.  Chapeau, 1408 Clement St. (at 15th Ave.),
San Francisco, Calif.; (415) 750-9787. Dinner Tuesday-Sunday;
brunch Sunday. Closed Monday.
 &HT;     Ron Siegel.  Charles Nob Hill, 1250 Jones St. (at Clay), San
Francisco, Calif.; (415) 771-5400. Dinner Tuesday-Sunday.
 &HT;     Craig Stoll . Delfina, 3621 18th St. (between Dolores and
Guerrero), San Francisco, Calif.; (415) 552-4055. Dinner nightly.
 &HT;    
 WHERE ARE THEY NOW? 
 &HT;    
 &HT;     By Tara Duggan  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; The Chronicle didn't name Rising Stars last year,
but here's what's happened to the 1997 group.
<P>
   &UR; Christopher Fernandez.  &LR; Fernandez was executive chef of
Crescent Park Grill in Palo Alto, which closed last year. Fernandez
is now catering while he waits for the right restaurant
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; David Fickes &LR; . Fickes left Infusion Bar and Restaurant in San
Francisco for Manhattan Beach, where he was chef at Anacapa
Restaurant. Last October, he helped open the Canal Club in Venice.
He is currently looking for a chef's position in Southern
California.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Mourad Lahlou. &LR;  Lahlou is still chef/owner of Kasbah in San
Rafael. Ultimately, he says, he would like to open a restaurant in
San Francisco with his brother Khalid, who runs the front of the
house at Kasbah.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Julia McClaskey &LR; . McClaskey remains head chef of Universal Cafe
in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Charles Phan.  &LR; Phan is still executive chef at Slanted Door in
San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Nicole Plue &LR; . Last August, Plue left Hawthorne Lane to become
pastry chef at Eleven Madison Park in Manhattan. She plans to stay
in New York for a while, although she says she misses the Bay Area.
</P>
</TEXT>
