<HEADER>
A2889 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARCHEFS2-SFCHRON &LR;      05-11 3050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARCHEFS2-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RON SIEGEL, RICHARD REDDINGTON, CHAD CALLAHAN 
 &HT;    
 &HT;     
 PROFILE: RON SIEGEL 
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
(Editors Note: This is the second part of a three- part package
profiling six rising stars among Bay Area chefs. Profiles of three
of the stars are included below. Each profile is followed by a
recipe from the chef. Also look for  STAR CHEFS2,  profiles of the
other three stars, and  STARS SIDE,  which tell where to find this
year's stars and what became of previous stars.) &HT;     
 HERE COME THE STARS: Young Bay Area Chefs on the Rise   &HT;     By Miriam Morgan  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ron Siegel seems like an unlikely candidate for a
French-inspired chef. The child of vagabonds, he and his family
moved so many times that he wound up living in the same Palo Alto
house twice.
</P>
<P>
   Yet sometime during those itinerant growing-up years, the
talented 32-year-old chef of Charles Nob Hill, the jewellike
40-seat restaurant at Jones and Clay streets in San Francisco,
found that cooking gave him the satisfaction no other career did.
</P>
<P>
   It began in a butcher shop. When he was 16, Siegel took a job
with John's Town and Country Market in Palo Alto and learned how to
cut up chicken, meat and fish. ``I liked working with my hands and
was into it. I liked the atmosphere. Plus it was a lot of money at
the time,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next several years, Siegel worked in everything from
construction to maintenance. ``But I kept coming back to
restaurants,'' he says. ``I like how kitchens are organized in a
certain way and how your workday is broken up doing different
things.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was when he moved to San Francisco, enrolled in the
California Culinary Academy and landed a job at Aqua that he really
saw what the restaurant world was like. He found his first mentor
in George Morrone, Aqua's opening chef, who in turn landed him a
job at the four-star Daniel in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a European-style kitchen where they spoke French and
there were about 30 cooks. I wasn't sure I made the right
decision,'' he says. But it was there he met renowned chef Thomas
Keller, and when Keller moved to Napa to open French Laundry, he
brought Siegel with him as sous chef.
</P>
<P>
   With just a half-dozen chefs in the Laundry's kitchen, ``you had
to set everything up yourself,'' Siegel says. But the French style
was similar to Restaurant Daniel _ and that's what he likes.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at Charles Nob Hill, again working for Aqua owner Charles
Condy, Siegel fuses his skills and his passion for French-inspired
food, creating his own a la carte and prix fixe menus and serving
them on lovely china in an elegant setting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like making things look beautiful but simple,'' says the
one-time construction worker. ``I don't have things flying off the
plate or things like fried herbs. I take the classical French
technique and update the impression of what the dish should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Those ``impressions'' include serving snails with spring garlic
right now and spring onions sliced paper thin and sweated in butter
to go under a perfect morsel of lobster.
</P>
<P>
   Lobster, it would seem, would be one of his favorite ingredients
(he claims it isn't), having been the basis for his highly
publicized Iron Chef television show last January. In the popular
Japanese show, seen here on some cable stations, he became the
first American chef to best the reigning Japanese ``champion'' in a
one-hour cook-off. His dishes of lobster ravioli and lobster with
seared foie gras, braised artichokes and wild mushrooms won an
unprecedented unanimous decision from the judges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business at the restaurant doubled after that, but that's not
really me _ `bringing home the gold.' You have to ask yourself,
`Are you a chef or a celebrity?' I'm a chef. I just like to cook.
You'll never see me in Las Vegas, I'll guarantee you that.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PAN-SEARED SQUAB BREASTS WITH ENGLISH PEA RAVIOLI, MORELS &AMP; PEA &LR; 
 &UR; TENDRILS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   4 squabs (see note)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup + 1 tablespoon olive oil, or as needed
</P>
<P>
   4 tomatoes, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch thyme
</P>
<P>
   1 pound morel mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   2 shallots, minced
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Ravioli &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup salt + salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds English peas, shelled
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup mascarpone cheese
</P>
<P>
   Pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   16 round wonton wrappers (see note)
</P>
<P>
   1 egg, lightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Garnish &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1 cup pea shoots, optional (available at Whole Foods or Asian
markets)
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For the squab jus (stock) and morels: &LR;  Take the reserved bird
bodies (including legs) and remove and discard any skin and fat.
Using a large knife or cleaver, cut the bodies through the bone
into small pieces. Heat a heavy-bottom stock pot; add 1/4 cup of
the olive oil. When the oil is hot, add the cut-up bones and brown
for about 10 minutes, stirring occasionally. Once the bones have
browned, discard the oil. Add 1/4 cup water to the pot, stirring to
incorporate all the browned bits. Boil down until the water
``crackles.'' Add 8 cups water, along with the tomatoes and thyme.
Bring to a boil, reduce heat and simmer for 2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Trim the stems from the morels. Place the trimmings into the
stock for additional flavor. Slice the mushrooms into rounds and
soak in warm water to clean for about 10 minutes. Dry mushrooms and
set aside.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the ravioli: &LR;  Bring 2 quarts water to a boil in a large
saucepan. Add 1/4 cup salt (it should taste like saltwater). Add
the peas and simmer for 3 to 5 minutes, until tender. Drain and
drop peas into a bowl of ice water. When cool, drain and puree
them; strain through a fine-mesh sieve. Mix in the mascarpone _ it
should bind and flavor the puree. Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To assemble the ravioli:  &LR; Brush 1 wonton wrapper very lightly
with beaten egg. Place a scant tablespoon of the pea puree in the
center of the wrapper, leaving a 1/2-inch border around the
perimeter. Place another wrapper on top, carefully aligning it with
the bottom wrapper. Press the edges together while pushing the
puree toward the center, and smooth down the seal. Make sure the
seal is clear of puree and that there are no air pockets in the
ravioli, or they will burst open while cooking. Cover the finished
ravioli loosely with plastic wrap or parchment paper to keep it
from drying out.
</P>
<P>
   Repeat this procedure, forming 7 more ravioli (you may have
leftover filling).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To finish the dish:  &LR; Clean the pea shoots by plucking the
leaves from the stems. Toss the shoots in a drizzle of olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   After the squab stock has finished cooking, strain it through a
fine-mesh sieve into a saucepan. Boil over high heat until reduced
to 1/2 cup (this takes about 15 minutes). Whisk in 3 tablespoons of
the butter; set aside and keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate pan, saute the shallots in the remaining 1
tablespoon butter for 5 minutes. Add the reserved morels and saute
for a few minutes until soft. Add to the squab stock; keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Season the squab breasts and liver with salt and pepper. Place a
skillet over medium-high heat, then add 1 tablespoon olive oil.
When the oil is hot, add the squab breasts and saute quickly, no
more than 2 or 3 minutes per side (the breasts should be on the
rare side). Remove the breasts from the pan and keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Add more oil to the pan if necessary, then saute the livers
quickly, for about 1 minute. Keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, bring a large pot of water to a boil. Add the ravioli
and cook for 3 to 5 minutes, until the pasta is al dente and the
filling heated through. You may have to cook the ravioli in batches
to prevent them from sticking to each other.
</P>
<P>
   For each serving, place a spoonful or two of squab jus (with
morels) on a warm plate, add 2 ravioli, top with 2 squab breasts,
then a portion of liver. Garnish with pea shoots.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note:  &LR; When purchasing the squabs, ask the butcher to remove
the breasts (ask for skinless airline breasts) and to reserve the
body for you, including the livers.
</P>
<P>
   For the ravioli, Siegel uses fresh pasta cut into 4-inch rounds
instead of wonton wrappers, and serves 1 per plate.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 725 calories, &LR;   &LR; 68 g protein, 38 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 34 g fat (14 g saturated), 485 mg cholesterol, 204
mg sodium, 7 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; PROFILE: RICHARD REDDINGTON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By Michael Bauer &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Lots of chefs want to cook, but few follow the trail as doggedly
as Richard Reddington.
</P>
<P>
   Equipped with a business degree from Miami University in Ohio,
Reddington went to work selling Hallmark cards in Indiana. After
three years, he decided he wanted to make a career in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he had absolutely no training, he wasn't deterred.
He wrote Roland Passot of La Folie, and when he didn't hear back,
he simply showed up at the door.
</P>
<P>
   Passot agreed to let the then 25-year-old wannabe chef hang
around with him for the day. Reddington asked to stay on as a
non-paid kitchen helper, and Passot agreed. After several months of
working 12 hours a day six days a week, Reddington told Passot he
needed an income, so Passot put him on the payroll. Reddington
stayed about two years before spreading his wings at Fran Gage's
now-shuttered bakery and at Postrio as a line cook.
</P>
<P>
   He zigged to New York and cooked at Park Avenue Cafe, then
zagged back to San Francisco to work for Traci Des Jardins at
Rubicon. From there he took off for a seven-month training stint in
France, where he talked his way into several three-star
restaurants, including Arpege in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Chef/owner Alain Passart let him take over the meat station
after a one-day, sink-or-swim tryout. Not speaking much French
became an advantage because, Reddington explains, ``I didn't know
why he was yelling at me.''
</P>
<P>
   On his return to the United States, Reddington donned chefs'
whites at Daniel in New York for about seven months and then moved
to Southern California to open Spago Beverly Hills. Then back to
San Francisco, where he became chef de cuisine at Jardiniere under
Des Jardins.
</P>
<P>
   Reddington decided to take a break and was riding his bike past
Chapeau, on Geary Boulevard near 22nd Avenue, when he saw owner
Philippe Gardelle, who had worked with him at La Folie. Gardelle
needed a chef, and Reddington decided to help out. He's been there
five months.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the places he has worked have been more intense and
expensive than at Chapeau, where entree prices are around $15. But
Reddington sees this type of cooking as a way to learn more. It has
taken him five months to learn to make a cassoulet that meets his
own standards, and crafting bistro food has perfected his ability
to make terrines and sauces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always felt that I matured quickly, but still I have a lot
to learn,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   His style, he says, is to coax the most flavor out of each
ingredient and to combine flavors so they support each other.
Achieving this marriage of flavors can be learned, he acknowledges,
but ``some cooks get it and some cooks don't.''
</P>
<P>
   He does. His combinations are fresh and vibrant, but the flavors
are never jarring. He makes a chestnut leek soup, for example,
that's perfectly balanced with the tart-sweet addition of apples.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Chapeau is not the last stop on his culinary journey.
``What I'll do is play off some of the things I've learned. I'll
take those skills with me, but I probably won't do a cassoulet.''
</P>
<P>
   He says he will stay at Chapeau long enough to train a chef to
carry on. His next goal is to open a restaurant where he can have
three or four other chefs to help him put out his style of
contemporary French cooking.
</P>
<P>
   His parents at first didn't understand his passion for cooking,
but they're learning by tasting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love going home and just cooking for my family,'' he says.
``This is what I am, this is what I'm doing.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; CREAMY BRANDADE OF SALT COD &AMP; POTATOES WITH GARLIC CROUTONS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 pound boned salt cod
</P>
<P>
   2 heads garlic
</P>
<P>
   10 ounces olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 bunch thyme
</P>
<P>
   1 pound russet potatoes, peeled and cut into eighths
</P>
<P>
   About 1/2 gallon milk
</P>
<P>
   Salt, if needed and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil + oil for baguette slices
</P>
<P>
   1 baguette
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Soak the salt cod in water to cover for 48 hours, changing the
water several times.
</P>
<P>
   Break the heads of garlic into individual cloves, gently
smashing the cloves, then peel them. Save 1 clove for the croutons.
Cover the remaining cloves with olive oil and simmer gently for 20
minutes, or until the garlic turns golden brown. Remove from heat
and throw in the thyme.
</P>
<P>
   Place the potatoes in a saucepan and pour in water to cover.
Bring to a boil, then reduce heat and simmer until tender; drain.
Rice the potatoes and keep them warm.
</P>
<P>
   Drain the salt cod and place in a saucepan. Pour in enough milk
just to cover. Bring to a boil, reduce heat and simmer gently for 8
to 10 minutes. Drain. Add another 1 cup milk and bring to a boil.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the potatoes, the cod and 3/4 cup of the boiling milk,
and the garlic and its cooking oil (discard the thyme) in a food
processor. Process until smooth (don't overwork or it will become
gummy). Add remaining 1/4 cup milk if the brandade is too thick.
Season with salt, if necessary and pepper. Finish with the extra
virgin olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the baguette on the bias into croutons. Toss or brush with a
little olive oil, season with salt and pepper and toast until
golden in a 400 degree oven. Rub with the reserved garlic clove
(cut in half, if desired).
</P>
<P>
   Portion the brandade onto heated plates and surround with
croutons.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8 to 10.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 505 calories, &LR;   &LR; 15 g protein, 36 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 33 g fat (5 g saturated), 23 mg cholesterol, 719 mg
sodium, 1 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; PROFILE: CHAD CALLAHAN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By Michael Bauer &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; For eight years, Chad Callahan worked in the shadow of Julian
Serrano at Masa's. When the respected four-star chef left last year
to open Picasso in the Bellagio Hotel and Resort in Las Vegas,
Callahan stepped into the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   For most people in the food world, he was an unknown, just as
Serrano was when he took over the restaurant nearly a decade
earlier. Few people, save for the chef and the kitchen crew, know
the sous chef of the major restaurants, even though they do most of
the hands-on work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The minute I walked in the door, I felt very natural and I
knew I wanted to rise up in the ranks,'' Callahan says.
</P>
<P>
   The 33-year-old chef has had a passion for food as long as he
can remember. His father was one of the founders of the Chart House
steak-and-seafood restaurant, and his mother was French and loved
to cook. Callahan remembers first working in the restaurant when he
was 10 years old.
</P>
<P>
   He loved it so much that he wanted to start cooking right out of
high school, but his father convinced him go to college for at
least two years. Callahan went to California State University at
Chico on a football scholarship and after he did his time, he
enrolled at the Culinary Institute of America in Hyde Park, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   He worked at several places before landing at Masa's, but the
bulk of his training has been there. Slowly Callahan is changing
the menu to include such dishes as the Black Striped Bass Gratinee
(see recipe).
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my flavors will be a little bolder,'' he says.
''Julian was really into texture.''
</P>
<P>
   One of his favorite foods is a bowl of steamed clams, but when
he first took over he didn't see how he could put something that
simple on the menu. Now he's reconsidering.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel as if the rules have really changed now about what
people are deeming four-star food. I think they want things that
are approachable.''
</P>
<P>
   Still he knows he can't stray radically from the Masa's
tradition, and he really doesn't want to. He has worked so long
under Serrano that he's just beginning to get a feel for his own
style.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm still working on that myself, to be completely
honest.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; BLACK BASS WITH PINE NUT GRATINEE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Beurre Blanc &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup + 2 tablespoons dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   1 shallot, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 small bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces sweet butter, cut into small pieces
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon crushed saffron
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons water
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Vinaigrette &LR;
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons aged balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Spinach &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; 4 tablespoons sweet butter
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces toasted pine nuts
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces golden raisins
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound baby spinach
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Fish &LR;
</P>
<P>
   4 black bass fillets, boned
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons sweet butter
</P>
<P>
   5 ounces pine nuts, toasted and finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces plain breadcrumbs
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Beurre Blanc:  &LR; Combine 1/2 cup wine, the shallot and bay
leaf in a saucepan and reduce until almost dry. Add the cream, then
whisk in the butter; set aside and keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the saffron, water and 2 tablespoons wine in a saucepan;
boil until reduced by half. Pour into the beurre blanc, whisk, then
strain through a chinois. Keep the sauce warm.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Vinaigrette:  &LR; Mix the extra virgin olive oil with the
balsamic vinegar and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Spinach:  &LR; Melt the butter in a saucepan; add the pine nuts
and raisins and cook until the butter browns. Add the spinach, salt
and pepper and saute until wilted. Transfer to a warm plate.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Fish:  &LR; Preheat the broiler. Season the flesh-side of the
fillets with salt and pepper. Heat the olive oil in a nonstick
saute pan. Add the fish and saute over medium heat until crisp.
Turn and cook for 30 seconds longer. Transfer to a heat-proof
platter.
</P>
<P>
   Melt the butter in a small skillet. Add the chopped pine nuts
and breadcrumbs, and cook until foaming. Spoon over the fish. Broil
until golden brown.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To Serve:  &LR; Arrange the fish on the spinach. Pour the saffron
beurre blanc around the fish, then spoon a little of the
vinaigrette around and on the beurre blanc, and over the fish, if
you like.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 1155 calories, &LR;   &LR; 57 g protein, 31 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 95 g fat (37 g saturated), 220 mg cholesterol, 308
mg sodium, 4 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
