<HEADER>
A2891 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NASDAQ-SETTLE-650&AMP;ADD     05-11 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASDAQ-SETTLE-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SETTLEMENT MONEY TO BE WEIGHTED TOWARD INDIVIDUAL INVESTORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y.)  (rk) 
 By DIANA B. HENRIQUES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Individual investors will be given an edge over
institutional investors in the distribution of about $1 billion
that Nasdaq dealers paid to settle a landmark 1994 antitrust
class-action case accusing them of fixing prices on Nasdaq shares.
</P>
<P>
   Under a plan that lawyers expect to mail to Nasdaq investors
next month, all investors will share in the settlement fund based
on how many Nasdaq trades they made during the seven-year period
covered by the settlement, which was the largest in antitrust
history.
</P>
<P>
   But under the plan, each trade by an individual investor will be
give 50 percent more weight in the calculations than a trade by an
institutional investor.
</P>
<P>
   The typical institutional investors will still collect far more
than an individual, of course, because the volume of an
institution's Nasdaq trades is so much larger than that of a
typical individual investor. But the arrangement means that
individual investors will get more of the settlement fund than they
otherwise would have, class-action lawyers agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Grundfest, a Stanford University law professor and former
member of the Securities and Exchange Commission, said he believed
the distinction made between individuals and institutions ``may be
the first of its kind.''
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement was first reported by James M. Newman, the
publisher and editor of Securities Class-Action Alert, a newsletter
that monitors securities litigation. Newman, too, called the
preferential treatment for individual investors surprising.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not another example of it that I can think of,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Lovell, a member of the legal team that pursued the
novel antitrust class-action case, said the unusual formula was
simply the result of the routine practice of trying to distribute a
settlement in ways that reflect the reality of the harm that was
done.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, institutional investors were able to trade Nasdaq
stocks on private trading networks, such as Instinet, where they
could routinely get better prices than those available to
individual investors. As a consequence, institutions suffered less
from the price-fixing activity charged in the antitrust litigation
than individual investors did, Lovell said.
</P>
<P>
   The unusual distribution formula was part of an overall
distribution plan that received preliminary approval from federal
Judge Robert W. Sweet in Manhattan on March 9. Objections to the
plan will be heard by Sweet in October, and all investors' claims
must be filed by December.
</P>
<P>
   Lovell said the settlement administrators hope to distribute the
money to investors late next year, but Newman said he thought that
target was ``very optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   The formula favoring individual investors was devised with help
from a group of deputy attorneys general from various states. ``We
felt that they could be neutral because their constituents include
both citizens, as individual investors, and their own state pension
funds, as institutions,'' Lovell said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Perino, a law professor at St. John's University in New
York who studies class-action litigation, agreed that the formula
is unusual. But he said he doubted it would be copied in future
securities class-action cases because such cases typically hinged
on the decline in the stock's price, which affects all investors in
the same way.
</P>
<P>
   The distribution plan is the latest step in a journey that began
in May 1994, when a team of class-action lawyers accused 37 major
brokerage companies, including Merrill Lynch; Lehman Brothers;
Goldman, Sachs; Salomon Smith Barney _ now part of Citigroup _ and
Morgan Stanley, Dean Witter, of artificially fixing prices on
Nasdaq stock they traded between May 1989 and mid-July 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the Nasdaq dealers were accused of conspiring to
inflate their own profits by artificially widening the gap between
the price at which investors could buy a Nasdaq stock and the price
at which they could sell it.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The lawsuit, which experts considered to be a long shot,
prompted the Justice Department and the SEC to undertake their own
investigations of the Nasdaq market. Those inquiries, in turn, led
to far-reaching changes aimed at making the market fairer for all
investors.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, most of the defendants settled price-collusion charges
filed by the Justice Department. Earlier this year, the SEC
collected more than $26 million in fines from 28 Wall Street firms
involved in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Sweet awarded the class-action lawyers a
record-setting fee of $144 million for their work on the case,
about 14 percent of the settlement award, plus $4.4 million in
expenses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
