<HEADER>
A2894 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELLIS-WATER-SKI-ART-N     05-11 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-WATER-SKI-ART-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP WATER-SKI JUMPER CAN THANK HIS STUBBORNNESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DURWARD BUCK   
 The (Lakeland, Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKELAND, Fla. _ Scot Ellis confesses he has a stubborn streak.
If you want to bring it out, just tell him he can't do something.
</P>
<P>
   The world's top-ranked jumper in the sport of water skiing, the
Lakeland resident was told after a spectacular crash in July 1995
that he would never walk again without a limp. Don't even think
about skiing, the doctors said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admit that did motivate me a little bit,'' Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
   A year after the injury, he was named to the U.S. Water Ski
team.
</P>
<P>
   Two years after the crash, he finished second in jumping on the
pro water skiing tour.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at 27, he is ranked first in the world, based on 1998
performances in which he jumped more than 200 feet 50 times. No one
else has accomplished that in one year.
</P>
<P>
   His personal best is 220 feet, two feet under the world record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gone 230 in practice,'' he said. ``But it doesn't count
unless you do it in a record-capability tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis was born on June 14, 1971, in Laurel, Miss., but grew up
in Lakeland. When he was 4 or 5, he saw a Lakeland Water Ski Club
show on Lake Hollingsworth. He liked what he saw. By age 8, he was
competing in tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came to us very young,'' said Chuck Dees of Lakeland, who
was Ellis' first coach. ``We taught him to jump and to jump
properly. You have to learn it properly or I won't let you jump.
Scot learned very easily.
</P>
<P>
   ``He listened and then was able to go out there and do what you
had told him,'' Dees said. ``He was a three-event skier for a long
time before he specialized in jumping.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved skiing,'' Ellis said. ``I could go skiing every
weekend and get a trophy every time. By the time I was 10, I had a
room full.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis competed in national events as a junior skier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of in the middle of the pack until 1988 or '89,''
he said. ``Then I sort of took off.''
</P>
<P>
   At 5-foot-7 and 175 pounds, Ellis is smaller than most skiers
who compete at the top level, but he beat the big guys
consistently.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, he won the boys' world, national and Junior Olympics
championships. At age 17, he set two Men 1 (ages 17-24) national
jump records at 177 and 179 feet. He made the U.S. Water Ski team
at 20 and placed second in the world championships.
</P>
<P>
   His greatest success came in Australia at the Moomba Masters,
the water ski event that attracts the largest crowds in the world _
up to 200,000 spectators. Ellis placed second in 1993, first in
1994 with a site record of 203 feet, first in 1997 with a site
record of 216, first in 1998 and first in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, he set the Men 2 (ages 25-34) jump record at 199 feet.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the pro water ski circuit in 1990 and placed first on
the tour in his rookie season. Since then, except for the injury
year, he's ranked in the top four.
</P>
<P>
   He is constantly making minor adjustments in the style that
earned him the nickname ``Rocketman'' on the tour. He is one of the
most popular skiers on the tour, and the only one with his own
poster.
</P>
<P>
   His injury in 1995 occurred at an Indianapolis tournament when
an arm binder broke. Binders are designed to keep his position
aligned on the jump ramp where skiers reach speeds of more than 75
mph. He dislocated his hip and suffered nerve damage that made him
lose feeling in his right leg.
</P>
<P>
   Two doctors gave gloomy predictions, so he went to a third.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once he figured out exactly what the problems were, we had a
place to start,'' Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
   A neurologist found the dislocation. A chiropractor started him
on a long and ongoing rehabilitation process.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling in his leg and foot are slowly returning, but he wears
braces and tapes his ankles when he jumps. After his accident, he
hung out at his parent's home on Lake Tennessee in Auburndale and
watched other skiers train. He coached some of them and listened to
their words of encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   Six months after the rehabilitation process began, he went back
to Indianapolis for a tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I was almost dead last, maybe 14th out of 15,'' he
said. ``But I was so happy, I didn't care.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the 1996 season, he was jumping 200 feet again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still not skiing as well as I did when I was 18,'' he
said. ``But I'm improving.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis credits his parents, Roger and Janifer, and his sister,
Shelly, along with the unwavering support of his sponsors with
helping in his comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of my sponsors kept me,'' he said. ``I figured some of
them would drop me. I'll always be grateful.''
</P>
<P>
   His sister, a student at the University of Central Florida,
understands the long healing process after an injury. When she was
6, she fell out of a boat and was cut severely; she now uses an
artificial leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scot was always there; he never let me give up no matter how
much I was hurting,'' she said. ``No one realizes just how close we
are.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he was hurt, he told me he finally understood what I was
going through; I think it was a humbling experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Scot Ellis' goals are to win another pro jumping title and to
promote a new event called ``ski flying.''
</P>
<P>
   By lengthening the ski ramp, lengthening the tow rope and
increasing boat speeds, jumpers are making stunning distances.
</P>
<P>
   The ski flying was developed by five-time world champion Bruce
Neville, who is now 36. He and Ellis have pioneered a sport which
already has skiers going more than 270 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is only a matter of time until we reach 300,'' said
Neville, a frequent visitor to the Ellis home.
</P>
<P>
   It is not unusual to see four or five of the top jumpers in the
world train together. They take turns driving boats, spotting each
other and giving technical advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scot is a technician, and that may have held him back in years
past, but he's started to be more aggressive,'' Neville said. ``He
still has that tremendous style.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had some tough going, but he is definitely the best U.S.
skier.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota, Fla., Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
