<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2896 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LINDER12-COX     05-11 0395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LINDER12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Congressman seeks marriage of technology, privacy
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With Internet usage rising markedly among members
of Congress, elected officials are quickly learning about the power
and pitfalls of the on-line world.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Linder (R-Ga.) told a conference on lobbying and the
Internet Tuesday that the biggest challenge facing Congress in this
area is resisting legislation that threatens Americans' privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing that the Internet and computers have taken from
us is privacy,'' Linder said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he opposes administration efforts to expand the ability
of authorities to search and retrieve files on personal computers.
``If they can get a judge to issue a warrant, they'll have access
to snoop through your computer,'' Linder said. ``Just because they
have a warrant to search a closet doesn't give them the right to
look through your whole house.''
</P>
<P>
   Linder also applauded the decision of the Federal Deposit
Insurance Corporation to withdraw its controversial ``know your
customer'' regulation. The proposal would have required banks to
monitor customers' daily usage of their accounts in order to
identify potential drug dealers.
</P>
<P>
   American University's Center for Congressional Presidential
Studies sponsored the conference to take note of the Internet's
growing importance in the daily work of the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   All but 41 of the 534 members of the House and Senate (there is
one vacancy) now have Web sites, said James Thurber, the center's
director. ``There is a demand from the public,'' Thurber said.
``And members also are going to do anything they can to communicate
with constituents as part of their desire to get re-elected.''
</P>
<P>
   Linder said he receives an increasing amount of correspondence
by e-mail, which he said is much better than a telephone call.
``It's usually well thought out and they don't tend to ramble,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But he acknowledged that a lot of bad information also is
available on the Internet and that people sometimes cannot
distinguish.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find I have more conspiracy theorists in my district than
before the Internet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Sherman writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
