<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY ON HER OWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton joked at a recent White House
Correspondents' Association dinner that he and his wife Hillary
weren't scared of confronting the notoriously mean New York press;
it was the Manhattan co-op apartment boards they feared.
</P>
<P>
   He predicted that if the first lady does indeed run for the
Senate seat being vacated next year by Democrat Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, they will have trouble finding a place to live there.
(This blithely assumes that if she moves to New York, he will go
along. But, hey, never examine a joke too closely.)
</P>
<P>
   To laughter and applause, the president described an application
form unlikely to impress a finicky co-op board. Anticipated
employment? Unknown. Anticipated earnings? Unknown. Current
residence? Public housing. References? Nelson Mandela, the Dalai
Lama, Steven Spielberg. Outstanding debts? Williams &AMP; Connolly (his
defense lawyers).
</P>
<P>
   The first lady herself acknowledges to friends that she WANTS to
run, co-op boards or not. But she also insists she isn't fully
committed yet.
</P>
<P>
   She has recently made so many trips to New York and displayed so
much interest in arcane local issues, however, that she gives the
impression she is already campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   The New Yorker magazine wryly took note of her sudden
fascination with the state in a cartoon featuring a television
newscaster. The anchor announced, ``In a further effort to
ingratiate herself with New Yorkers, Hillary Clinton threw out the
first pitch at last night's Yankee game and went on to pitch three
scoreless innings.''
</P>
<P>
   In public at least, the president has been supportive. ``For 22
years now or more we've done what I wanted to do in terms of my
political career,'' he said in a television interview. ``So the
deal I made was she gets the next 22 years. ... I would be happy to
be the spouse of a senator.''
</P>
<P>
   New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, the most likely Republican
Senate nominee, is taking Hillary Clinton seriously as a potential
competitor. In recent hypothetical contests, they emerge as
virtually evenly matched.
</P>
<P>
   He ridicules her carpetbagger status and complains on his Web
site that she has no connection to the state that would enable her
to properly represent it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you think would happen if I got off a plane in
Arkansas and announced for the (U.S.) Senate?'' the mayor asks
appreciative Republican audiences. ``Where is Whitewater? Maybe I
could go to Whitewater ... '' He also accuses her of having no
sense of humor, although his own lack of that admirable quality has
often been noted.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, moving to New York while still technically occupying the
White House would be a tricky maneuver. She would not have to live
in the state while she campaigned. She is required only to have a
home address there by Election Day. But voters could come to resent
the fact that she is from out of state if she delays too long in
establishing residence there.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the question of what to do about Bill. Does he
move with her, or is this the perfect opportunity to set up
separate households? Her rocky marriage is bound to be a subtheme
in any campaign. Her current image as the long-suffering wronged
wife has reinforced her popularity. but it remains a delicate
subject.
</P>
<P>
   Recently she has begun to hint at the misery her husband's
roving eye has caused her but she continues to stand at his side
and praise his public policies.
</P>
<P>
   During a union-organized forum held at Buffalo State College
last week she gingerly ventured into that perilous personal
territory. The mostly female audience applauded her frankness.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a question about family values, she smiled and
said gently, ``Marriages are hard. They are hard work. I'd be the
first to tell you that.''
</P>
<P>
   The first lady is clearly more comfortable talking about public
policy issues than she is revealing her private feelings. If this
policy wonk does run, she will not be caught unprepared on any
major issue. She does her homework, and it's not the kind that
involves pots and pans. She has the kind of discipline that might
actually lead her to pitch three scoreless innings.
</P>
<P>
   Combining the roles of a Senate candidate immersed in grassroots
politics and a global celebrity representing the nation on grand
issues of war and peace may not be as awkward as some Republicans
are suggesting. She is already blending the two.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, for instance, she used a White House ceremony linked
to Mother's Day to call for congressional passage of new gun
control measures. The following day she was back in New York state
raising money for a Democratic congressman. Then at a U.S. airbase
in New Jersey she welcomed the first Kosovar Albanian refugees to
be given temporary shelter in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Monday she joined the president in a high-profile White House
conference on youth violence that proposed voluntary efforts to
identify and address possible causes. Then she flew to Ireland to
become the first woman to be granted the key to the city of Galway
and to receive an honorary degree from the university there.
</P>
<P>
   As a U.S. senator, she could have the best of both worlds. Why
does she want to run? Why not?
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at 202-298-6920 and
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
