<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-OAKLAND-A'S-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OWNERSHIP OF OAKLAND A'S NOW IN THE HANDS OF THE LEAGUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZACHARY COILE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ The jockeying over who will own the Oakland
A's now moves to Major League Baseball officials in New York, as
city and county officials strongly back a local group to take over
the baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   The Oakland City Council and the Oakland-Alameda County Coliseum
Authority voted Monday to support a group led by former A's
executive Andy Dolich, emphasizing that local ownership is the best
way to ensure the team stays in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland Mayor Jerry Brown, City Council President Ignacio De La
Fuente and Councilman John Russo will go to New York in the next
few weeks to lobby Commissioner Bud Selig on the sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to make sure that Major League Baseball, the owners
and the commissioner know that we are 100 percent behind this
group,'' De La Fuente said.
</P>
<P>
   Dolich, a former executive vice president for the A's who heads
a group of mostly East Bay investors, said he'll fly to New York
within the next 10 days to make his pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next step is essentially additional conversations with the
decision-makers at Major League Baseball: team owners, members of
the ownership committee,'' Dolich said. ``I will continue what I've
done for basically the last 18 years of my life: I'll be speaking
to people about why Oakland A's baseball has an opportunity to be
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   The recommendation of the City Council and the Coliseum
Authority was a victory for Dolich and his group, but they still
face several hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   The would-be owners will still need the approval of 75 percent
of the American League club owners and a majority of National
League owners.
</P>
<P>
   And they must complete the sale within just a few months, or
else current team owners Steve Schott and Ken Hofmann can sell to a
rival group.
</P>
<P>
   Under the non-negotiable terms of the proposed sale, the buyer
must pay $122.4 million (including $2.4 million in commissions) to
Schott and Hofmann, and agree to keep the A's in Oakland at least
through 2004. The city and Coliseum Authority hired Game Plan LLC,
Boston investment bankers, to find and scrutinize potential local
buyers.
</P>
<P>
   The group backed Monday is made up of Dolich, baseball Hall of
Famer Joe Morgan, Men's Wearhouse CEO George Zimmer, Modesto
supermarket mogul Robert Piccinini, the Alameda Newspaper
Group-owned Oakland Tribune and San Francisco advertising executive
Jeff Goodby.
</P>
<P>
   The rejected group is led by San Mateo lawyer and former bank
executive Michael Lazarus and includes Arizona banker Lyle
Campbell, former San Francisco Giants and Baltimore Orioles pitcher
Steve Stone, and Bob Watson, a former A's coach and New York
Yankees general manager.
</P>
<P>
   The Lazarus group could still be involved as an alternate buyer.
If the Dolich team can't complete the sale by Sept. 20, the current
owners could entertain the competing bid.
</P>
<P>
   Selig, baseball's commissioner, said last week that he wanted
Oakland and Alameda County officials to send both bids for
consideration to baseball's owners. But the council rebuffed the
commissioner, saying it deserves to help pick the A's new owners
because city taxpayers had invested millions in city money in the
Coliseum and provided favorable leasing arrangements with the team.
</P>
<P>
   The council voted 8-0 for the Dolich group, citing the bidders'
longstanding ties to Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question you have to ask is which group has a critical
self-interest in working with the city and county to make baseball
work in the long term here in Oakland,'' said Russo. ``When you
look at the groups in that filter, it becomes a very easy
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, who railed against city officials' deal to bring back
the Oakland Raiders football team, waded into the treacherous world
of professional sports in Oakland for the first time by supporting
the Dolich group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oakland is coming back,'' Brown said. ``It's in the midst of a
very powerful revitalization and this is another step in that
direction, with local people continuing to support their baseball
team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
