A2900 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      05-11 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACH YELTSIN? DUMP PRIMAKOV? RUSSIA FACES ANOTHER CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The parliament is priming itself for a vote to impeach
the president, on charges that he brought Russia to ruin. The
president's men talk darkly of dumping the prime minister, accusing
him of leading the country back to its Communist past.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Russia's latest political crisis, where rumors are
rife, and political intriguers have already unsheathed their knives
for a showdown Saturday, when the impeachment of President Boris
Yeltsin is due to come to a vote.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the fate of Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov's
eight-month-old government has also been thrown into the balance,
amid loud hints from the Kremlin that it has outlived its
usefulness as a guarantor of political stability.
</P>
<P>
   Like other Russian crises, this one, too, may pass. But for the
moment, all those involved are doing their best to keep the
country's nerves on edge _ at a time when Russia is deeply involved
in delicate diplomacy to end the war in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's own record of bizarre and unpredictable behavior has
added to the uneasy mood in Moscow. In recent appearances, he has
seemed unsteady on his feet, even incoherent, blurting out
incomplete sentences before television cameras and screwing up his
face in an unsightly scowl as he dressed down top aides in public.
</P>
<P>
   For several weeks, Yeltsin and his dwindling team of Kremlin
advisers have seemed bent on cutting back Primakov's authority _ by
firing one of his top ministers, by purposefully sidelining him at
public events and by privately painting him as an agent of the
Communist opposition, which has given him its support in
parliament.
</P>
<P>
   That support was the key to Primakov's nomination as a
compromise candidate to head the government last fall. It has been
the source of his own power, and independence from a resentful
Kremlin and his popularity as the man who saved Russia from the
brink of a full-blown crisis.
</P>
<P>
   But according to his critics, including those within the
presidential administration, it is also the reason for his
government's paralysis, particularly in the economic sphere.
</P>
<P>
   In a public rebuke Monday, Grigori Yavlinsky, the head of the
parliament's largest liberal party who first nominated Primakov
last fall, accused the government of do-nothing policies, which he
said were reminiscent of the ``era of stagnation'' under former
Soviet Communist party leader Leonid Brezhnev.
</P>
<P>
   As the impeachment vote nears, rumors of Primakov's pending
dismissal _ or forced resignation _ have again resurfaced, stirring
speculation that Yeltsin may be looking for an excuse to disband
the parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Even in his current weakened position, Yeltsin still has the
power to make such threats come true, which may be enough to give
his opposition pause. When, and whether, he chooses to exercise
that power has become a popular Moscow guessing game here, and one
that the Kremlin's master intriguer seems intent on manipulating to
his own advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Russian parliament's lower house was due to
take up a five-count impeachment charge against Yeltsin, its
members voted to postpone. Many analysts expect them to do the same
this time, in part because they are unlikely to collect the 300
votes necessary to make the impeachment charges stick.
</P>
<P>
   Of the five impeachment charges, only one _ accusing Yeltsin of
waging an illegal war in Chechnya from 1994 to 1996 _ has the
support of both liberals and Communists in the 450-member lower
house. The other charges involve the breakup of the Soviet Union,
the shelling of the parliament in 1993, the collapse of the Russian
military, and the ``genocide'' of the Russian people.
</P>
<P>
   Any charges approved by the lower house would then have to first
clear the Russian constitutional court, then the Supreme Court and
finally the parliament's upper house before Yeltsin could be
removed from office. The chances of clearing these hurdles before
Yeltsin's second presidential term expires in the summer of 2000
are very slight.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin has repeatedly urged the lower house to go ahead with
the impeachment vote, and remove it from the agenda. But
postponement of the vote has proved useful to his Communist-led
opposition, which has made the ouster of Yeltsin its chief
political slogan in the run up to December's parliamentary
elections.
</P>
<P>
   With the impeachment debate due to begin Thursday, Primakov on
Tuesday again came out publicly against any attempt to dislodge
Yeltsin, telling parliamentary leaders that he is ``categorically''
against an impeachment drive that he said threatens the country's
political stability.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's aides Tuesday also denied reports that they have
readied plans for a dismissal of the government. But according to
one of the participants, Primakov told parliamentary leaders
Tuesday that he himself would step down if the Kremlin tried to
force the resignation of his two top remaining Communist ministers,
Yuri Maslyukov and Gennady Kulik.
</P>
</TEXT>
