u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-INVEST-NYT &LR;      05-11 0426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-INVEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE STOCK TRADING FIRMS FORM KEY ALLIANCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DIANA B. HENRIQUES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The landscape of the stock-trading business continued to shift
Tuesday, as Instinet, the dominant private trading system, and its
scrappy rival, Island ECN Inc., announced potentially important
alliances with other players.
</P>
<P>
   Instinet, a unit of Reuters Group PLC, is paying $20 million for
an 11.4 percent stake in W.R. Hambrecht &AMP; Co., the brainchild of
Silicon Valley financier William Hambrecht. Hambrecht operates the
OpenIP0 system, an online auction-based system for underwriting
initial public stock offerings.
</P>
<P>
   Trading in initial public offerings has become a sore topic
among online investors. Almost weekly, small investors who cannot
have their orders filled watch in frustration as an initial
offering, initially priced in the teens for the few institutions
able to buy, soars.
</P>
<P>
   Instinet chief executive Douglas Atkin said the current
situation hurt both the companies and the individual investors. If
a stock is priced at $19 and the first trade is at $30, ``that is
money that's coming out of the company's coffers and being given to
a few big institutions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In his view, Hambrecht's auction system is fairer to individual
investors and allows the company to keep more of the money
investors are willing to pay for its shares.
</P>
<P>
   Atkin said Instinet would soon develop links to allow its
institutional members to submit their orders to Hambrecht's
auctions directly over Instinet. In addition, the two companies are
negotiating a joint venture that would allow Instinet to export the
initial-public-offering auction service to Europe and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   For Island, the news Tuesday was that Waterhouse Investor
Services Inc., a subsidiary of Toronto-Dominion Bank and a
substantial discount brokerage firm here and in Canada, would buy a
12.5 percent stake in Island for $25 million. An agreement in
principle has been reached, and final papers should be signed in
the next two months, the companies said.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at Island, a subsidiary of Datek Online Holdings
Corp., said the fresh capital would help Island build the
infrastructure it would need if it were granted stock-exchange
status by the Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   At present, Island runs a distant second to Instinet in the
proliferating field of electronic communications networks, or ECNs,
the computerized systems that match buy and sell orders that
brokers submit for their customers. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
