<SLUG> BC-GASOLINE-SMOG-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCHERS SAY GAS ADDITIVE DOESN'T CUT SMOG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE KAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ An ingredient added to gasoline to curb auto air
pollution, but blamed for increases in water pollution, does little
to reduce smog, according to a study released Tuesday by the
National Research Council.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the study credits tough air-quality regulations,
reformulated gasoline and vehicle improvements over the last few
decades for having ``substantially cut the emissions that help
create near-ground ozone.''
</P>
<P>
   In the study, designed to compare additives, the researchers
found that MTBE _ methyl tertiary butyl ether _ is more effective
than ethanol in reducing ozone, a major component of smog. But the
overall impact of either additive on reducing ozone is very small,
the study says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Motor-vehicle emissions of chemicals that form ozone pollution
have decreased in recent years,'' said committee Chairman William
Chameides, regents' professor of air and atmospheric sciences at
the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's largely because of better emissions control
equipment and components of reformulated gasolines _ other than
oxygen additives _ that improve air quality,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although additives reduce some pollutants from motor vehicles,
Chameides said, the oxygenates appear to have little impact on
lowering ozone levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moreover, it's not possible to attribute a significant portion
of past reductions in smog to the use of these gasoline
additives,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Robert Perciasepe, assistant administrator in the
U.S. Environmental Protection Agency's Office of Air and Radiation,
said the agency supports the technical findings of the independent
federal research council, an arm of the National Academy of
Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Perciasepe didn't agree with Chameides' statement that the
oxygenated reformulated gasoline does little to reduce smog.
</P>
<P>
   He credits a 20 percent reduction in smog-forming emission from
reformulated gasoline containing the additives. The presence of
oxygen also curbs toxic emissions, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA is investigating the environmental effects of oxygen
fuel additives, Perciasepe said. He expects the results in July.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA, the lead enforcement agency under the federal Clean Air
Act, which requires the additives in areas that violate ozone
standards, is the last remaining holdout in support of the
oxygenates, particularly MTBE.
</P>
<P>
   Touted as a clean-air savior a decade ago, MTBE has leaked from
underground fuel tanks into 10,000 wells in California, including
drinking water supplies in South Lake Tahoe, Santa Monica and in
Napa, Mendocino and Orange counties. In March, the governor
announced that MTBE would be banned in California by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   State regulators, oil refiners and environmentalists welcomed
the study, saying they believe MTBE is doing more harm than good.
</P>
<P>
   ``The air board has felt for some time that you can make the
reformulated gasoline without using the oxygenates,'' said Allan
Hirsch, a state Air Resources Board spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``This report helps bolster the argument that there should not
be a federal requirement for oxygenated gasoline in California.''
</P>
<P>
   Denny Larson, Northern California director of Communities for a
Better Environment, called MTBE a menace. His group, which sued the
oil companies last year alleging that the industry has long known
of MTBE's potential to leak to groundwater, supports efforts by
refineries to make the gasoline burn cleaner without the use of
additives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't believe it was ever proven that oxygenates were
necessary to make cleaner gasoline, and the recent studies,
including an earlier University of California study, bear this
out,'' Larson said. ``The oxygenates have allowed the oil companies
to make a higher profit by putting in other chemicals to dilute
gasoline.''
</P>
</TEXT>
