   CHAPMAN-TEXAS AT LARGE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ In the mid-1870s, long after Texas claimed its
independence from Mexico and the United States settled the Civil
War, North Texans were still brawling with the Plains Indians over
exactly who owned the land. The battles, probably more than 20 in
all, were called the Red River War, and they ranged from the summer
of 1874 into early 1875. Now, because of more than $100,000 in new
grants, the Texas Historical Commission is setting out to detail
that war by locating the battle sites, generating site records and
maps, nominating sites to the National Register of Historic Places,
and working with area museums to exhibit findings. By ART CHAPMAN.
Story has moved in ``a'' general news category. &QL; 
