<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHERWARNINGS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIALS SEEK WAYS TO ALERT NON-ENGLISH SPEAKERS TO DANGEROUS
WEATHER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DIANE SMITH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Emiliana Vega has an emergency plan in case a
tornado touches down near her Irving apartment: Hide in the closet
and stay out of the path of flying glass.
</P>
<P>
   The 35-year-old native of Guanajuato, Mexico, learned her simple
blueprint for safety from Spanish-language news broadcasts and her
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many times we see the images, but we don't know everything
they are saying,'' Vega said in Spanish, referring to the English
news stations.
</P>
<P>
   Vega is not alone. Across the Metroplex, there are tens of
thousands of non-English-speaking people who depend on
word-of-mouth and foreign language media to find out when severe
weather is looming.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, where the Hispanic population is projected to reach
more than 6.3 million by next year, National Weather Service
officials are talking about providing Spanish weather warnings on
the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration Weather Radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an issue that we are discussing at the highest level of
our agency. ... How can we get information to non-English-speaking
individuals?'' said Rick Dittman, NOAA Weather Radio and
dissemination meteorologist with the agency's Southern Region
Headquarters in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   In San Diego, Calif., the National Weather Service hopes to have
a Spanish NOAA system in place in two to three years, said Ed
Clark, warning coordination meteorologist.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can hope that at least the states that border Mexico will
do that,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration is the
federal agency that oversees the National Weather Service. NOAA's
nationwide network of radio stations broadcasts continual weather
information such as warnings, watches, forecasts and other hazards
24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   Known as the ``Voice of the National Weather Service,'' NOAA
Weather Radio is a public service found on radio frequencies,
television and weather scanners. The National Weather Service
provides Spanish forecasts and warnings via the Internet, and on
the NOAA Weather Radio in San Juan, Puerto Rico _ where English is
the second language.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the needs of changing demographics is important in
reaching as many people as possible, Dittman said.
</P>
<P>
   What has proved effective in capturing the Spanish-speaking
audience is the Emergency Alert System, a joint effort among the
National Weather Service, local media and emergency personnel that
sends out warnings of danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we issue a warning, if there's a Spanish station, they
receive the product and translate the warning for listeners,''
Dittman said. ``Your Spanish-speaking channel is no different than
Channel 8 or 5. It's just in Spanish.''
</P>
<P>
   Cesar Ramirez, a newscaster for radio station KESS/1270 AM this
week aired tornado tips such as keep calm, move away from windows
and don't attempt to outrun a twister in a vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people who don't speak English,'' Ramirez
said. ``What we do is important. We tell people how to protect
themselves in case there is a tornado.''
</P>
<P>
   Silvia Quijada, 32, of Irving, a native of El Salvador, learned
about the tornadoes that hit Oklahoma and Kansas last week through
the Spanish media. She said the tragedy made her wonder what to do
if a tornado hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worry about my children,'' she said. ``It is important to
take care of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Elvia Wallace-Martinez, host of a Spanish-language Christian
radio show in Irving, said the information gap is an issue with
first-generation Latino immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are at a higher level of assimilation they will know
English,'' Wallace-Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue isn't unique to Latinos. The Metroplex has a
potpourri of cultures and languages evidenced in the alternative
media and organizations aimed at helping immigrants start anew in
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas-based Radio Korea Christian Station, an independent
station that is not on the AM/FM radio bands, translates weather
reports from local English newspapers for its audience.
</P>
<P>
   Asli Parker, president of the Somali Outreach Center in Euless,
has soothed the weather fears of Somali refugees who have never
experienced a tornado.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were very scared,'' said Parker, who told them how to
prepare. ``They said, `We heard they have bad weather in Oklahoma.
Are we going to have the same weather?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Sing Boulom, a public service officer with the Haltom City
Police Department, said the the non-English-speaking Southeast
Asian community is largely shut out, and word-of-mouth is key to
finding safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``The information is not available so they don't know about it _
unless they know English or the tornado hits their roof,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
