r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILD-SOLDIERS-HNS &LR;      05-11 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILD-SOLDIERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILD SOLDIERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANIEL WEISS and EMMA CHERNIAVSKY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It would be comforting to think that the
horrifying combination of children, guns and violence in Littleton,
Colo., is an anomaly, but unfortunately, it is not.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Trenchcoat Mafia'' are not the only children using guns
and bombs. At least 300,000 children under the age of 18 _ some as
young as 8 _ serve in government armies or rebel groups in
Afghanistan, Angola, Colombia, Sierra Leone, Sri Lanka and other
conflicts around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Children are forcibly recruited or sometimes volunteer,
pressured by a culture of violence, or they are driven to join
because they are poor or orphaned. Boys and girls serve as
messengers, spies and cooks. Girls are turned into ``wives'' or
concubines forced to serve groups of soldiers. Children are also
used in combat to make and deploy mines, to ambush enemy patrols or
even to fight on the front lines.
</P>
<P>
   There are no international standards to protect children in
armed conflict. The primary international treaty, the Convention on
the Rights of the Child, contains a glaring inconsistency: It
articulates 18 as the age of majority to protect the rights of
children in all areas, with the sole exception of the provisions on
recruitment and participation in armed conflict, which define an
adult as 15 years old.
</P>
<P>
   The international community has begun to take steps to address
the lack of protection for these children. In 1995, under the
auspices of the U.N. Commission on Human Rights, negotiations began
to raise the age for military recruitment and service from 15 to
18.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the recruitment and use of children younger than 15 was
proposed as a war crime under the statute of the proposed
International Criminal Court. Many countries have indicated their
willingness to adopt or consider adopting the new standard,
including Australia, Canada and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, however, has refused to do so, and in fact
contributed to the collapse of negotiations on the new standard a
year ago. Worse, the U.S. Defense Department has since sought to
undermine international support on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon objects to raising the age to 18 because U.S.
military recruitment practices allow 17-year-olds to enlist with
parental permission. At a time when all branches of the U.S. armed
forces are facing a shortage of personnel, their fear of losing
some high school recruits is understandable, but misplaced.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, a very small number (less than one-half of 1
percent) of U.S. troops are below age 18. The shortages won't be
eliminated by recruiting more 17-year-olds; rather, they point to
the need for comprehensive reform in the financial benefits and
career opportunities offered to the men and women of our armed
forces.
</P>
<P>
   There is some support for the new standard in other parts of the
administration, but it is a far cry from the stand the United
States should be taking on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Appropriations Authorization Act, passed by Congress
and signed into law by the president in October 1998, includes a
provision encouraging the U.S. not to block the standard, which
would be implemented through an optional protocol to the Convention
on the Rights of the Child.
</P>
<P>
   One major problem is that the United States remains one of only
two countries _ along with Somalia _ that has failed to ratify the
Convention, now the most widely ratified international treaty in
history.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does this erode our credibility on international human
rights issues, it makes the United States ineligible to join the
proposed optional protocol.
</P>
<P>
   As the U.N. Commission on Human Rights meets in Geneva this
month, there is a window of opportunity for the United States to
join the international community in supporting stricter standards
on child soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who pledged in 1992 that protecting human
rights would be a pillar of our nation's foreign policy, should
take the lead in building support for ratification of the
Convention and the proposed optional protocol.
</P>
<P>
   Ending the practice of recruiting 17-year-olds into the military
is a small price to pay to help keep the world's children out of
war.
</P>
<P>
   (Daniel Weiss, a lawyer with O'Melveny &AMP; Myers in Los Angeles,
served as a fellow on the House Foreign Affairs Committee. Emma
Cherniavsky is a Los Angeles-based writer. Both are members of
Young Advocates of Human Rights Watch-California.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
