 May 11, 1999  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; OPENING REMARKS FROM THE ``LATE SHOW with DAVID LETTERMAN'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night down in Baltimore, the Cuban national team defeated
the Baltimore Orioles 12-to-6, p laying baseball. Castro was so
thrilled about the victory that he gave the winning pitcher for the
Cuban team a brand new 1954 Oldsmobile.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Castro was in such a good mood after the baseball team beat
the Orioles that he sent President Clinton a box of cigars -- and
also matches in case Clinton wanted to smoke them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesse Jackson's on the show. Jesse Jackson is a very busy man.
Earlier today, he was down in Washington and he successfully
negotiated the release of three interns from the Oval Office.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesse Jackson is on the program, and he's here tonight to make
an announcement -- that he had absolutely nothing to do with Amy
Fisher getting out of jail.''
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton is in Germany, and earlier today he
delivered his Eich Bein Ein Philanderer' speech.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday, Clinton met with the three former POWs that Jesse
Jackson got out of Yugoslavia, and they told him what it was like
to be a prisoner of war, and Clinton told them what it was like to
be married to Hillary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an historical biography now that says that President
Abraham Lincoln might have been gay. Apparently they make a pretty
good case. I think during his time in office he was always sending
roses to a very young Strom Thurmond.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This flight attendant for British Airways...They land the
airplane and the flight attendant takes off all her clothes and
puts on one of those yellow life vests and a pilot's cap, and this
flight attendant, this woman runs around the plane because she lost
a bet. And I'm thinking about it, no, wait a minute, this sounds
more like Air Force One.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you watch the Country Music Awards show last night?...The
high point of the big broadcast for me, I guess, was when New York
City Police Commissioner Howard Safir showed up at the Country
Music Awards with his date, the Dixie Chicks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're banning the sale of beer in the bleachers at Yankee
Stadium. And I'm thinking well, great, what fun is it going to the
Yankee games now if you can't get drunk and urinate on the
outfielders.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How many of you saw Noah's Ark?' I watched it. I think it's
kind of dull. Were you like me, were you rooting for the flood?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they took some liberties with the story of Noah's Ark.
It's an unbelievable story, but I think they took some liberties.
For example, Noah -- I don't believe his wife ever asked Issac to
make her a Margarita.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fascinating story, though, and the way Noah was able to
round up the animals -- here's how it happened. All of the animals
came running when they heard the can opener.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm no Biblical scholar, I'm no student of the Old Testament,
but I've seen Noah's Ark,' and I want to tell you something, this
is the single loosest interpretation of the Bible since President
Clinton's grand jury testimony.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Let's put the 'Fun' back into Dys-fun-ctional! &LR;
</P>
<P>
   If at first you don't succeed, destroy all evidence that you
tried.
</P>
<P>
   A conclusion is the place where you got tired of thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Experience is something you don't get until just after you need
it.
</P>
<P>
   For every action, there is an equal and opposite criticism.
</P>
<P>
   He who hesitates is probably right.
</P>
<P>
   Never do card tricks for the group you play poker with.
</P>
<P>
   No one is listening until you make a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Success always occurs in private, and failure in full view.
</P>
<P>
   The colder the X-ray table, the more of your body is required on
it.
</P>
<P>
   The hardness of the butter is proportional to the softness of
the bread.
</P>
<P>
   The severity of the itch is proportional to the reach.
</P>
<P>
   To steal ideas from one person is plagiarism; to steal from many
is research.
</P>
<P>
   To succeed in politics, it is often necessary to rise above your
principles.
</P>
<P>
   Two wrongs are only the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Work is accomplished by those employees who have not reached
their level of incompetence.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with the gene pool is that there is no lifeguard.
</P>
<P>
   Monday is an awful way to spend 1/7th of your life.
</P>
<P>
   The sooner you fall behind, the more time you'll have to catch
up.
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope the light at the end of the tunnel isn't the
headlight of an
</P>
<P>
   approaching train!!
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CITY STREETS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   As I watched my greengrocer in Greenwich Village carefully water
the plants he has for sale, I commented that he must love them. He
demurred. He really didn't like plants at all, he said. I asked him
why he gave them such good care and he replied matter-of-factly
that it was as Plato said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, the philosopher-king,'' he said, and then gave me
his version of Plato's remarks. ``The man who should be king is the
one who least wants the job because he'll do it the best,'' he
said. ``It's like that with me and the plants.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, I was left amazed by the city's always unexpected
combinations, this time the philosopher and the greengrocer.
</P>
<P>
   _ ALICE ELLIOTT
</P>
<P>
   A large family of tourists stood at the corner of Fifth Avenue
and 51st Street, transfixed at the sight of four uniformed police
officers on horseback. Judith Wolfe heard this exchange:
</P>
<P>
   ``See children, that is how they catch criminals in New York
City,'' the mother said. ``There is too much traffic to use police
cars.''
</P>
<P>
   A moment of silence and then one of the children piped up: ``Do
they use a lasso?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   An unknown gentleman was already in the elevator of the Upper
East Side apartment building when Lois Sherr Dubin, a resident, got
on. As the two descended she noticed the man's belt buckle and
having just written a book on North American Indian jewelry, she
asked if the buckle was made by Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' he said and proceeded to remove it to have a
look. Within moments they reached the lobby and as the doors
opened, a young woman who was waiting to enter stared as the man
casually replaced his belt. Without missing a beat, the man turned
to Ms. Dubin and said, ``Thanks very much.'' She smiled and said,
``You're welcome.'' Neither one enlightened the young woman.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dubin is still smiling. And the belt buckle? It was a
knockoff.
</P>
<P>
   The submission by Benjamin Bederson on April 12 about the eye
chart he memorized for his Army physical in 1942 reminded me of my
father, a doctor who examined recruits in the Bronx during World
War II. He used to say he could tell how the war was going by the
instructions he received from his commander. At one point in 1944,
he said, he knew the fighting was particularly rough when this
order arrived: ``Don't examine the recruits' eyes _ just count
them.''
</P>
<P>
   _HARRISON J. GOLDIN
</P>
<P>
   It was a sizzling summer day and when my husband, Allan, and I
first set foot in the cab, we were shocked _ pleasantly. The cab
was comfortably air-conditioned and the driver had his radio tuned
to relaxing classical music.
</P>
<P>
   As tourists, we were accustomed to stressful cab rides and New
Yorkers who seemed to care only about themselves. This cabby broke
the mold _ he apparently cared about others.
</P>
<P>
   Just to be sure, I checked him out. ``Do you put on classical
music for your passengers?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   He snapped his head around, his eyes pierced mine and he said:
``Lady, this is New York. I put on classical music for myself.''
</P>
<P>
   _LESLIE SALOMON
</P>
<P>
   An elderly couple came up from the Canal Street subway station
and walked west toward the Hudson, looking for a restaurant at
Watts and Washington Streets. The man had a map in hand when a
young woman passing by asked if she could help.
</P>
<P>
   She knew the restaurant, Capsouto Freres, and led the couple two
blocks to the entrance.
</P>
<P>
   The man thanked her profusely and the Samaritan responded,
``That's all right _ I'll be old myself someday.'' The couple
entered the restaurant laughing.
</P>
<P>
   _ROCKHILL GRAY
</P>
<P>
   A woman and her young daughter were crossing the street when a
cab turned into their path. They stopped. He slammed on the brakes.
They moved forward again. So did the cab. Finally the little girl
decided to take matters into her own hands. Yolanda Crous watched
as the child stood with her legs apart and hand thrust forward and
shouted with great authority, ``Stop in the name of the law.'' And
he did.
</P>
<P>
   The waitress at the diner on West 42d Street whisked by,
dropping her menus on the table. Robert Sarnoff ordered a tea, a
coffee and an apple pie a la mode, all of which arrived quickly.
Two men and a woman in the next booth, who said they were visitors
from Michigan, were astonished by the quick service. They had been
waiting a half-hour for their cheesecake and Sprites, they said,
and it was the second time they had received such poor service at
the diner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do you come back?'' Mr. Sarnoff asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be a lot thinner when I return home,'' the woman said.
</P>
<P>
   William Borden and his wife, Nancy Lee, live in Bemidji, Minn.,
but whenever they are in New York, they make what they call a
pilgrimage to Zabar's, where they stock up on items that they carry
home in a cloth tote emblazoned with the store name.
</P>
<P>
   Once, when they returned to their resort town, population
11,000, they went shopping at a local supermarket. As they emerged,
Zabar's bag filled with local groceries, a summer visitor rushed up
and asked hopefully, ``Is there a Zabar's in Bemidji?'' Hope turned
to disappointment at their answer, but the Bordens are still hoping
for a branch in northern Minnesota. Their bag is ready.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
