<HEADER>
A2926 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-HAWKS12-COX     05-11 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pistons try to deal with Mutombo
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ Dikembe Mutombo stands as an almost
unwitting symbol of the Hawks' domination over the Detroit Pistons
past, present and for the long-range future.
</P>
<P>
   After scoring 45 points and grabbing 32 rebounds in the first
two games of their best-of-five series, Mutombo is literally cause
and effect. Three years ago, as a free agent, he declined to play
in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with one more burst of energy tonight at the Palace, the
Hawks are in position to sweep the sagging Pistons out of the
playoffs after only three games.
</P>
<P>
   And the Hawks' prospects appear brighter for the next few
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Focusing on the present, Mutombo sat calmly after practice
Tuesday and spoke of his commitment to finishing off the Pistons.
``The prison is full,'' he said. ``We can take no more prisoners,
so now we must shoot the prisoners.''
</P>
<P>
   No question the Pistons are badly wounded. Because coach Alvin
Gentry considers Steve Smith the best shooting guard in the NBA, he
will not leave him open to double-team Mutombo. If the Pistons do
not double Mutombo, they pay the price that was exacted Monday
night. Thirteen of his 14 shots went in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if they will do that again,'' Mutombo said. ``I
can't count on it, but whatever they want, it's OK with me.''
</P>
<P>
   A rout in this series would further a trend that started in 1996
when Hawks general manager Pete Babcock made a chump out of his pal
Rick Sund, the Pistons GM who had been fired previously by Dallas
during that franchise's dark decline.
</P>
<P>
   That summer, the Pistons went after Mutombo and were told he
would not play for them. The Hawks were able to sign Mutombo to a
five-year, $55 million free agent's contract because the Pistons
agreed to help them by taking Grant Long and Stacey Augmon, along
with their contracts.
</P>
<P>
   That allowed the Hawks to clear salary-cap room for Mutombo. The
Hawks got two first-round picks in exchange _ one through
Sacramento, the other Detroit's.They are cashing in those picks in
next month's NBA draft.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Mutombo led the Hawks to a 3-2 first-round series
victory over the Pistons, scoring 26 in one game. The Pistons went
out and signed Bison Dele as a counter-move.
</P>
<P>
   Worse for the Pistons, neither Augmon nor Long worked out. They
shipped Augmon to Portland for the Blazers' 1999 first-rounder.
After Doug Collins resigned as coach, Long went to Gentry, then the
interim coach, to talk about his diminished role on the team.
Gentry said Long did not figure in the team's plans. After Detroit
exercised a clause that allowed them to pay Long on the cheap for
the 1998-99 season, he exercised his right to become a free agent.
He has played a pivotal role as a Hawks emergency starter in the
series.
</P>
<P>
   In late January, the Pistons needed big men. They signed free
agent Loy Vaught after he recovered from back surgery. They also
wanted Christian Laettner and proposed a sign-and-trade deal with
the Hawks. In return, the Hawks got the only other first-round pick
Detroit had this season, the one they had gotten for Augmon, plus a
$4.4 million salary-cap trade exception.
</P>
<P>
   So, the Hawks hold the upper hand now. They can stumble twice in
this series and still knock out the Pistons in a fifth game at
home.
</P>
<P>
   And they have a chance to be even more dominant over the next
several years, while the Pistons try to figure a way to counter
with $65 million worth of commitments to Laettner, Vaught and Dele
_ all brought on board the last two years because they couldn't get
the big guy himself.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Denberg writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
