<HEADER>
A2927 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-HAWKSNOTES-COX     05-11 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKSNOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hawks Notebook: Crawford shooting for Game 3
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ There is some hopeful news on the Hawks'
injury front. Chris Crawford might be able to play tonight and
would be likely for a Game 4 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Hawks trainer Chris Tucker said Tuesday that the second-year
starting forward has a first-degree shoulder separation, which he
likened to a sprained ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford, who fell three minutes into Monday's game, underwent
two rehab sessions Tuesday and is scheduled for another session
this morning. If he has sufficient range of motion, he will take a
flight here for tonight's game.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker ruled out strapping Crawford's shoulder with a device.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can do that with some guys, but Chris' game is above the
rim,'' he said. ``He plays with his arms extended. If we strap him
up, he can't do that. We're better off allowing him to fully
heal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks also decided that Alan Henderson will make the trip,
but it was questionable whether his vision problems would ease.
Henderson watched Monday's game from the bench wearing an eyepatch
after struggling for four minutes Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks are down to 10 healthy players and their front court
is thin. With Grant Long and Ty Corbin in the lineup, backup center
Mark West and small forward Roshown McLeod are the only healthy big
men on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Crowded house
</P>
<P>
   Tickets for a possible Game 5 Sunday at Georgia Tech go on sale
at noon today at Ticketmaster and the Georgia Dome box office. The
Dome is unavailable because it cannot be converted from a concert
set-up Saturday night in time for a Sunday afternoon tip-off to
accommodate NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Seats will be at a premium because capacity at Tech is 9,300.
The first two games at the Dome drew 20,884 and 16,377.
</P>
<P>
   Tired? Corbin says no
</P>
<P>
   Worried about fatigue at age 36?
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely not,'' Corbin said after going 41 minutes off the
bench Monday. Tuesday morning, Corbin said his legs are full of
life and he's ready for another long stint on the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was fresh coming into the series, and, as long as I got my
day off, I'm fine,'' Corbin said.
</P>
<P>
   As the man primarily responsible for containing Grant Hill, he
is under constant pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is, we help a lot (on defense), so I don't have to
try and hold him all by myself,'' Corbin said. ``Grant Long takes
him sometimes; the guards come over and help out. It's the team's
responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Corbin said the Hawks can work Hill until the Pistons guards
prove they can sink long open shots consistently.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they get it going, we'll have to make some adjustments.By
the numbers
</P>
<P>
   If there is a Game 4, it will be at 7 p.m. Friday on TBS. ...
The Hawks haven't swept a series since they knocked out Houston in
two games in 1979. The first round was best-of-three then. ... The
Pistons' total of 139 points is the second-worst two-game offensive
display in playoff history during the shot-clock era. Utah combined
for 136 points in Games 3 and 4 of the first round against Houston
last season.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Denberg writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
