<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2928 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-PISTONS12-COX     05-11 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PISTONS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NBA will lose 'ultimate professional' in Dumars
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN, HILLS, Mich. _ He was the good guy on the Bad Boys. None
of the talk of overly physical and borderline-dirty play about the
dominant Detroit Pistons in the late 1980s applied to Joe Dumars.
He was above it all, a beacon of decency and pride.
</P>
<P>
   And now, with the Pistons one defeat away from extinction, one
of the league's most respected players readies for retirement.
</P>
<P>
   The event won't be marked by an hourlong special on ESPN, as
happened for Michael Jordan, John Elway and Wayne Gretzky. But the
loss of Dumars, 36, is significant for the NBA, for the class and
character he exhibited over 14 years are often lacking in today's
athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the ultimate professional, the ultimate performer,''
said Maurice Cheeks, former NBA point guard and current 76ers
assistant coach. ``There aren't enough words to describe him. To
me, he's in a class with Julius Erving. I would think Grant Hill
came into the league looking at Joe the way I looked at Doc when I
was playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill learned how to comport himself as a pro from Dumars. At
most every opportunity, the veteran shooting guard would lend the
young forward the knowledge he attained over a career marked by
championships in 1989 and 1990 and six All-Star Games. Dumars
understood from the start what many high-paid, high-profile
athletes never get: It takes more energy to be a jerk than to be a
nice guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's one person who's influenced me the most since I
came to the NBA, it's been Joe,'' Hill said. ``He's just a great
person, a great player, a great pro. I was lucky to come to a team
with someone like him.''
</P>
<P>
   The path to the Hall of Fame is not a clear one for Dumars. His
career average of 16.1 points is not mind-blowing, but his
contributions as an all-around player and clutch performer over the
years cannot be ignored. In his prime, he was the best defensively
at his position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe was tough and smart and committed,'' said Isiah Thomas,
Dumars' former backcourt mate. ``When we stepped on the basketball
court, Joe Dumars was one player I did not have to worry about. He
came to play every night, no exceptions. You couldn't ask for a
better teammate.''
</P>
<P>
   Detroit got the better of the Chicago Bulls back then because
Dumars was attached to Michael Jordan like Velcro. Their battles
were physical and classic. The impression Dumars left on Jordan was
unmistakable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never talked to each other,'' Jordan said. ``We just both
played the game hard and with respect for the game and each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Dumars has taken an interest in Allen Iverson. He has
spoken to the 76ers young gun about the virtues of being
professional. Coincidence or not, Iverson has come off recently
less of a Generation X, selfish player.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people only see the negative,'' Iverson said, ``but
this was about a veteran player giving his advice on what to weed
out, what to take in. It means something coming from him. Why do
you think he's been so successful for so long? It's not just
because he's a great player.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Hawks complete the sweep tonight, Dumars will take off
his Pistons uniform for the last time. While he's ready to take on
a new life, he does not want to go out on a broom.
</P>
<P>
   The playoffs are ``very important to me, but it can't be just
important to me,'' he said. ``It has to be important to everybody
here. We have some guys for whom this is the first time in the
playoffs, and you have me on the other end of the spectrum. There
are guys here who have just as much motivation as I do, but for
different reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Dumars never played the role of self-absorbed player. During the
height of his career, he took courses in investment banking. He
established an annual charity tennis tournament for Detroit
children's hospital. He opened the Joe Dumars Recreational Center
for area kids. And he did normal things that most players would
never do, like attending a sportswriter's wedding, with gift in
hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never felt celebrity status automatically makes you a
role model,'' Dumars said. ``It's personal values, morals and
ethics. Not money and status. If it were that, then my parents
never would have been role models. For so many years, you try to
establish yourself as a player and a person, trying to be accepted
in the community. I'm at peace with myself as a player and a
person.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Bunn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
