</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-MERGER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ISC, Penske pact strengthens hold on racing world
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Speedway operators International Speedway Corp. and
Penske Motorsports have reached a $610 million merger agreement
that will bolster their already influential power in stock-car
racing.
</P>
<P>
   Under an agreement that should be completed later this year, the
new company, which will keep the ISC name, will control nine tracks
that host 14 of 34 events on this year's NASCAR Winston Cup
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ISC owns speedways in Daytona Beach, Fla.; Darlington, S.C.;
Phoenix; Talladega, Ala.; and Watkins Glen, N.Y. Under the merger,
ISC acquires Penske's tracks in Fontana, Calif.; Brooklyn, Mich.;
and Rockingham, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   The merging companies already co-owned a new speedway in
Homestead, Fla., and Penske also owned a track in Nazareth, Pa.,
which hosts Busch Grand National and other motorsports events.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR president Bill France Jr. will remain chairman and chief
executive officer of ISC, with Roger Penske serving as vice
chairman. ISC and Penske Motorsports had a combined $306 million in
revenues and $92 million in income in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   By 2002, ISC could own more than half of the tracks hosting
Winston Cup races. The sport's other track-operating giant,
Charlotte-based Speedway Motorsports Inc., owns six speedways,
including those in Atlanta; Concord, N.C.; Las Vegas; and Fort
Worth, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The merger was reached just a few months after NASCAR announced
it was taking television negotiating rights from speedway
operators. With the merger, which gives the new company a combined
800,000 seats and 400 luxury suites, ISC should have more leverage
in future scheduling. ISC also stands to take a large share of
television revenues when NASCAR agrees to a new network contract.
In addition to the 10 tracks already in place, the merged company
also is involved in planning or constructing new tracks near
Chicago, Denver, Kansas City and New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the deal, ISC will acquire 88 percent, or 12.2
million outstanding common shares, of Penske Motorsports stock it
does not already own at $50 per share.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
