</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLS-CONGRESS-0512-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SENATE OPENS DEBATE ON VIOLENCE AND KIDS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (a) general news categories
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - Senators from both parties scrambled Tuesday to
respond to the school shootings in Littleton, Colo., by offering a
flurry of anti-violence amendments to a bipartisan juvenile justice
bill.
</P>
<P>
   A Republican task force on violence and youth crime headed by
Sen. Wayne Allard, R-Colo., endorsed 15 amendments as the debate
began. Democratic leaders endorsed another eight.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP proposals included five to enhance the safety of
schools, four to discourage violent entertainment and four to
strengthen gun control laws. One would fund more enforcement of
existing gun control laws, and another would permit a monument with
religious prayer or symbols on public school grounds, if the
monument commemorates someone slain on that property.
</P>
<P>
   The eight Democratic amendments had a total of 11 provisions,
all of which would strengthen gun control laws.
</P>
<P>
   The debate on those amendments, and several others offered
without either party's endorsement, will extend through Thursday or
Friday, Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said.
</P>
<P>
   Only one proposal is sure to pass, because it was endorsed by
both parties. It would expand the existing ban on sales of handguns
to juveniles to include semi-automatic weapons.
</P>
<P>
   As many as half of the other amendments may be approved, because
many senators want to show they share their constituents' concern
over the safety of schoolchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., a former state attorney general,
commented, ``There are very good ideas on both the Republican and
Democratic sides to improve this bill.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Sen. Ben Nighthorse Campbell, R-Colo., an ex-policeman
and ex-teacher, sounded a more skeptical note.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly (the amendments) are all little pieces of some bigger
picture,'' Campbell said. ``But I know some people are saying all
we have to do is make changes to control guns...and others are
saying it's all Hollywood's fault.''
</P>
<P>
   The juvenile justice bill is co-sponsored by Judiciary Committee
Chairman Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, and the panel's ranking Democrat,
Joseph Biden of Delaware. It would authorize $1 billion a year for
five years in federal aid for juvenile justice programs of states
and localities.
</P>
<P>
   The bill splits the money fairly evenly between prevention
programs and punishment programs, funds better exchanges of
juvenile felony records between states, and places a lifetime ban
on gun purchases by any juvenile convicted of a violent felony.
</P>
<P>
   Several senators asked for restraint during this week's debate,
which comes on the heels of a wave of rumors and false bomb threats
that have emptied classrooms temporarily in several states.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope that everybody engaged in this debate would be
mindful that we not do anything that creates more anxiety among our
youngsters,'' cautioned Senate Republican Conference chairman Paul
Coverdell of Georgia, as he unveiled the 15 GOP proposals at a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember, there are 50 million students in 118,000 schools,
and, traditionally, that environment is the safest for children
except their own homes,'' Coverdell said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn., who is about as liberal as
Coverdell is conservative, issued a similar warning against
rhetorical grandstanding on the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been very careful in talking about Littleton not to
make any correlation between it and any agenda item I am for,''
Wellstone said. ``Some events are so dark, so evil, that they
cannot be flippantly explained.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
