</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARR-WEBSITE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia representative shares best website honors
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.) has the top-ranked House Web
site, according to an American University survey of congressional
sites.
</P>
<P>
   Barr's Internet address provides brief summaries of issues of
importance to 7th District residents, explanations of legislation
he has sponsored and links to dozens of other sites, including
major media outlets.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will never be a substitute for face to face meetings and
town hall discussions, but the Internet can play a valuable role in
enhancing those efforts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Barr shared first place among House members with Democrat Earl
Blumenauer of Oregon and Republican Brian Bilbray of California.
Republican Sen. Spencer Abraham of Michigan has the best Senate
site, according to the survey.
</P>
<P>
   Barr was the only Georgian in the top 10 in the House or Senate.
Every Georgian in Congress, except Rep. Johnny Isakson, has a Web
site. Isakson aides have said that the office that runs the House
Internet services has been slow in posting Isakson's home page.
</P>
<P>
   American University faculty and researchers who evaluated the
493 House and Senate member sites looked at content, constituent
service, visual appeal, user friendliness and use of technology.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being the overall leader, Barr topped the list in
the content rankings. Accused by Democrats of being inattentive to
his district, Barr placed third in the category of constituent
service provided on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Sherman writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
