A2936 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-BUSINESS-COX     05-11 0417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-BUSINESS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    President to business leaders: Share economic strength
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Bill Clinton appealed to the nation's
business leaders on Tuesday to invest in those rural and urban
communities that have been left behind by the recent economic boom.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, at a White House appearance before departing to
Atlanta, also called on Congress to enact his proposals for tax
credits and loans for companies that put up venture capital for
businesses in economically distressed communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should not be a partisan political issue,'' Clinton said.
``We want to provide the economic incentives necessary to create
jobs, keep growth going in America, keep inflation low, and go into
that new century with everyone _ everyone _ walking hand in hand,
together.''
</P>
<P>
   To bring more public focus to the problems of the nation's
distressed communities, Clinton said he planned to spend two or
three days in July visiting cities and towns in ``our most stubborn
pockets of poverty.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said 37 U.S. cities still have unemployment rates that
are twice the national average, despite the largest peace-time
expansion since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of smaller communities where children still
have to go past abandoned storefronts to get to a grocery store to
buy a carton of milk,'' Clinton said. ``We don't have to leave
anyone behind. And if we can't do this now, when in the wide world
will we ever get around to it?''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was joined at the White House by more than two-dozen
corporate CEOs, including BellSouth's F. Duane Ackerman, Delta
Airlines' Leo Mullin and AFLAC's Daniel P. Amos.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and the business leaders met to discuss the economic
problems facing rural and urban America for about 90 minutes before
flying to Atlanta aboard Air Force One.
</P>
<P>
   Amos, whose Columbus-based company is involved in helping former
welfare recipients learn job skills for work, said the session
helped him focus attention on potential markets in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially at our company, we spend so much time thinking
internationally,'' Amos said. ``We all of the sudden focused within
our own country ... It brought all of us back to a point where we
were considering the things that made our country great.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
