<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2965 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-SECURITY-0512-     05-11 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-SECURITY-0512-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SLIPPING IN POLLS, NETANYAHU HAS TROUBLE KEEPING SECURITY ON
VOTERS MINDS
 &HT;    400&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAMLA, Israel _ Trailing Labor Party challenger Ehud Barak in
opinion polls with just six days before the vote, Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu preached to his followers Tuesday night
in the familiar language of his right-wing Likud Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who is going to face Arafat? Barak or Likud? Who is going to
face (Syria's) Asad? Barak or Likud? Who is going to defend
Jerusalem?'' he shouted to a rowdy Likud crowd packed in a wedding
hall in this blue-collar city.
</P>
<P>
   But, try as he might, Netanyahu has been unable to focus the
upcoming elections on the hard stance against the Arabs that was
once his political strength.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Tuesday, Netanyahu suffered a setback when an Israeli
court postponed his ordered partial closing of Palestine Liberation
Organization (PLO) offices in east Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The court ruling said that any closure of offices at the Orient
House, an old mansion used as the PLO's unofficial Jerusalem
headquarters, would have to wait until after the May 17 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu's opponents noted that the building had been operating
throughout his three-year term and that the prime minister just
wanted to look tough against the Arabs or possibly stir up
Palestinian unrest.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling may have diffused a major crisis in the peace
process. Palestinians had threatened violence if, as was implied,
Israeli police stormed their building.
</P>
<P>
   But, the decision dulled an arrow in Netanyahu's political
quiver and increased the chances that security issues will not
decide this Israeli election as they have most others.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu has tried several times to move terrorism and peace
process issues to the forefront. Two weeks ago, he enraged some
Israelis when he featured 1996 video clips of bus bombings in his
political commercials.
</P>
<P>
   It was those bombings, in which more than 50 Israelis were
killed by Palestinian terrorists, that undermined the popularity of
then-Prime Minister Shimon Peres and may have handed the close
victory to Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   But, this election season has been free of terrorism --
something for which Netanyahu can, and often does, claim credit.
But, while security is clearly a major issue to most Israelis, many
of them have long decided their vote. The campaign has focused on
wooing Israel's small undecided vote, which seems to be concerned
with other issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we know his success in fighting terror is
counter-productive electorally,'' said Israeli political scientist
Efraim Inbar. ``Now, people take it for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Several other factors have made security and the peace process
less of an issue this year.
</P>
<P>
   First, other issues have taken the spotlight. A recent poll
showed that most Israelis believe that the bitter rift between
fundamentalist religious Jews and secular Jews is the country's
biggest problem -- larger than the split between hawks and doves on
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Secondly, Netanyahu's opponents have been successful in raising
questions about his integrity and competence.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the differences among the candidates on peace issues
appears to be narrow. Barak and the other major candidate, Yitzhak
Mordechai, are former generals with better military credentials
than Netanyahu. They also take hard lines on the peace process.
They might be a little more forthcoming than Netanyahu in dealing
with the Palestinians, but maybe not by much.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sting of the campaign, the Arabs, has been neutralized,''
said pollster Hanoch Smith. ``It's very hard to find any
differences among any one of the three main candidates as to what
they're saying about the main issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Israelis have reached a consensus on many important
peace process issues. Most, for example, seem grudgingly willing to
allow limited Palestinian statehood.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
