<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-ELECTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETANYAHU STRUGGLES IN BID FOR POLITICAL SURVIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ With five days before Israel's general election,
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's fight for political survival is
in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night Netanyahu released a new prime-time television ad
in which he pleaded with supporters to stick by him, a message
whose tone of desperation seemed a far cry from the confident,
telegenic conservative who came from behind to win in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never claimed that I am free of errors,'' Netanyahu
said. ``You who are partners in our principles, in our path, I
beseech you to put aside every other consideration _ I beseech you
to come back home.''
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts, even those who support him, said the ads
amounted to an admission that Netanyahu's campaign for reelection
had imploded in recent weeks with intense infighting within his
fractured government coalition and its diverse constituency.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent polls show Netanyahu steadily declining against
the more liberal Labor Party challenger Ehud Barak. Netayanhu is
now trailing in polls by an average of 8 percent, and polls
expected to be released Wednesday will, according to Israeli
television, put him even further behind.
</P>
<P>
   Amnon Lord, a weekly columist for the popular daily newspaper
Yediot Ahronot who supports Netanyahu, said, ``The polls are
worrisome; there is no avoiding that. But it is very difficult to
gauge the Israeli electorate in polls. So I think he will survive
this first round, and then it's a whole new ball game in the second
round.''
</P>
<P>
   But Daniel Ben-Simone, who is covering the campaign for the
leading daily newspaper Ha'aretz, said, ``These polls are very
real, and very clear. It is the end of Netanyahu's term.
</P>
<P>
   ``After driving miles and miles through Likud land, I can tell
you it looks like an earthquake. There is nothing left. The
offices, the activists are not there. At this time three years ago,
Jerusalem was in flames in terms of the Likud presence. But Bibi is
being abandoned by his party, especially the Russian community. It
is an expression of massive discontent.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, voters will cast ballots in a five-way race. But
Barak is not expected to win an absolute majority, so the two
leading contenders, almost certainly Barak and Netanyahu, will face
a run-off on June 1.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for Netanyahu's fraying campaign appears to be the
failure of what the Israeli media have dubbed his ``doomsday''
approach of trying to stir Israeli voters' fears over security
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, Netanyahu seized on the emotional issue of the
status of Jerusalem by threatening to close offices used by
Palestinian political leaders in historically Arab East Jerusalem.
On Monday, Netanyahu ordered the offices, known as Orient House,
closed, and violence was expected to erupt if Israeli forces
attempted to close the offices by force.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu heightened tensions by saying that Barak would allow
Jerusalem to be divided in ``final status'' peace talks with
Palestinians, which have been delayed by at least one year in the
deadlocked peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Israelis regard Jerusalem as its eternal and indivisible
capital. But Palestinians call East Jerusalem, which was captured
by Israel in the 1967 Six Day War, as the capital of its future
state.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Israel's High Court ordered Netanyahu's government to
delay closing the offices at Orient House for at least a week,
defusing the issue until after the election.
</P>
<P>
   The move to shut down Orient House, widely seen as politically
motivated, was sharply criticized even by one of Netanyahu's
long-time supporters in the Likud Party, Jerusalem Mayor Ehud
Olmert.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu has denied that he was using the issue as an election
ploy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
