</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-IMPEACH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUMA ANNOUNCES HEARINGS TO IMPEACH YELTSIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia edged toward a new political crisis Tuesday as
legislators set impeachment proceedings against President Boris N.
Yeltsin for this week amid growing speculation of a major
government shakeup.
</P>
<P>
   Ekho Moskvy radio, citing Kremlin sources, reported Tuesday that
Yeltsin was preparing to fire Prime Minister Yevgeny M. Primakov
and replace him with little-known Railways Minister Nikolai
Aksyonenko.
</P>
<P>
   It almost did not matter that the Kremlin later denied the
report: Rumors of a government shakeup have intensified as the
long-delayed impeachment proceedings against Yeltsin have moved
closer to conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, leaders of the State Duma, the opposition-dominated
lower house of parliament, announced that the chamber would hold
three days of impeachment debates starting Thursday and could vote
as early as Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Adding a touch of drama to the process, the Duma's Communist
speaker, Gennady Seleznyov, Tuesday ordered security increased at
the parliament building in central Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   The Communists and their allies, the driving force behind the
impeachment effort, have been predicting that Yeltsin could try to
close down parliament by force. Yeltsin has already done that once,
in 1993, causing a standoff that ended in a military assault
against the Legislature by pro-Kremlin troops and tanks that left
at least 140 dead.
</P>
<P>
   Few others are predicting such a violent outcome this time. The
impeachment process, as outlined in the Constitution Yeltsin
adopted after winning his battle with parliament in 1993, makes it
extremely difficult to remove the president.
</P>
<P>
   But Yeltsin has indicated he may fire Primakov, who is popular
in the Duma, to retaliate if the house votes for impeachment. The
president has a history of abruptly firing his senior lieutenants _
he sacked two prime ministers last year _ and has little patience
for aides who overshadow him, as Primakov has done in recent
months.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Gennady Zyuganov, head of the Communist bloc that is
the Duma's largest, raised the stakes more by warning that Russians
would take to the streets if Yeltsin dismissed Primakov, who rates
as the country's most popular politician in polls.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Yeltsin's deputy chief of staff, Oleg Sysuyev, denied
any changes were being planned. It was Sysuyev who only days
earlier fueled rumors of Primakov's ouster in an interview with
Vlast magazine, in which he criticized the government's economic
policies and remarked that ``no prime minister is irreplaceable,
including Yevgeny Maximovich'' Primakov.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov Tuesday defended his record, saying he had stabilized
the ruble and confounded pessimists who had predicted
hyperinflation for Russia. The 69-year-old premier, limping from a
back ailment, also appealed to the Duma to vote against
impeachment, saying it ``does absolutely nothing for the creation
of political stability in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   The Duma will consider five charges against Yeltsin: that he
broke the law when he brought about the collapse of the Soviet
Union in 1991, improperly used force to dissolve parliament in
1993, conducted policies that ruined the Russian army, waged
``genocide'' against the Russian people by pursuing economic
policies that impoverished the people, and illegally waged war from
1994 to 1996 against the rebel region of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Only one of these counts, on the Chechen conflict, which killed
tens of thousands of Russian citizens, is believed to have a chance
of receiving the 300 votes necessary in the 450-seat Duma to pass.
</P>
<P>
   If any of the charges are approved by the Duma, they would be
reviewed by Russia's Supreme Court and Constitutional Court before
going to a final vote in the Federation Council, the upper house of
parliament, which has twice defied Yeltsin in major votes this
year. But many observers, noting that the two courts are appointed
by Yeltsin, give little chance of the vote actually making it to
the upper house anytime before the president's term is set to end
in July 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, opposition lawmakers seem intent on drawing attention
to their positions before this December's parliamentary elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
