</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-ARMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LARGE STOCKPILE OF WEAPONS SEIZED BY SOUTH AFRICAN POLICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ The police announced Tuesday that
they had uncovered a vast cache of arms and ammunition in a bunker
in KwaZulu-Natal province, aggravating tensions as South Africa's
second post-apartheid elections approach on June 2.
</P>
<P>
   The stockpile, believed to be the biggest uncovered in South
Africa, were found in Nquthu, about 20 miles west of Ulundi, the
former headquarters of Mangosuthu Buthelezi, the head of the
Zulu-based Inkatha Freedom Party.
</P>
<P>
   The find was announced on a day when officials from Inkatha and
President Nelson Mandela's African National Congress gathered in
Pietermaritzburg to talk about ways to ease tensions between the
two parties, which have been locked in a struggle for dominance in
the province for more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials say the province is awash with
weapons, many of them left over from the most intense period of
fighting between the two groups, before the elections in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting continued even after the election, easing only in 1997
and 1998 after prolonged peace negotiations. But rights monitors
have warned of increasing violence as campaigning began this year.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials were led to the cache, which included more
than seven tons of arms, ammunition and explosives, by Phillip
Powell, a prominent member of Inkatha. In recent weeks there have
been numerous newspaper articles suggesting that the flamboyant
Powell, who is often seen heavily armed, was about to be arrested
for gun-running.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement to the South African Press Association, Powell
said the rumors of his impending arrest had led him to approach the
police with information about the bunker. He said he had negotiated
immunity for himself, though the director of public prosecutions,
Bulelani Ngcuka, later said no such deal had been struck.
</P>
<P>
   The arsenal _ which included several rocket launchers, 1,484
rifle grenades, 140 antipersonnel mines and more than 4,300
detonators _ was found buried in a bunker about 12 feet deep. The
police entered through a manhole.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Buthelezi said he welcomed any steps that would
foster peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not been informed about any aspects of this matter, and
I am not yet in a position to comment about it,'' he said. ``I can
merely state that I am pleased that any arms caches are
recovered.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell apparently told authorities that the weapons were
originally supplied to him by the former members of the police
force before the 1994 elections.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the province was racked by violence among blacks,
and some members of the white government were secretly promoting
the conflict by arming Inkatha. More than 12,000 people died in
what has often been referred to as a low-grade civil war in Natal.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few years, the conflict between Inkatha and the
African National Congress has eased, and Inkatha has served in the
coalition government. When both Mandela and his deputy, Thabo
Mbeki, have been out of the country, Buthelezi has served as acting
president, a role he reportedly enjoys.
</P>
<P>
   There has been much speculation that Buthelezi will be given a
prominent position in the next government as well, though the ANC,
which is expected to win the election easily, has no obligation to
do so.
</P>
<P>
   But recently the political language has turned harsher and
incidents of violence have been on the rise, though it is often
difficult to distinguish political violence from clan fighting and
disputes over control of certain business interests, such as taxi
routes.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen people have died in the last month in incidents linked
to political violence, far fewer than in the months before the 1994
elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
