<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICKYMARTIN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICKY MARTIN'S GOT THE GOODS, BUT DOES HE HAVE STAYING POWER?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like most overnight successes, Puerto Rican singer Ricky
Martin's didn't really come overnight. But you can pinpoint the
date _ and if you tried hard, the time _ that Martin became more
than just a success, when he became huge: Feb. 24, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   That night, Martin aroused a somnambulant Grammy Awards ceremony
with a flamboyant rendition of ``La Copa de la Vida (The Cup of
Life),'' a nearly year-old song most Grammy viewers probably had
never heard. Rising from beneath the stage, the handsome young
singer led a carnival-style production number, complete with
streamers, balloons, dancers on stilts, and percussionists charging
through the audience. His mesmerizing performance was rewarded with
the night's only spontaneous standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   Anglo America, say ``hola'' to a new superstar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever did that was a genius,'' says Dave Morales, music
director for Top 40 radio station KHKS/106.1 FM (KISS-FM), where
Martin's single ``Livin' La Vida Loca'' rocketed into the Top 5
less than a month after it debuted March 29. ``Everybody still
talks about that performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Everybody's talking about Martin, too. ``La Vida Loca'' was No.
1 on last week's Billboard Hot 100 singles chart, in only its
fourth week on the chart. People magazine put him on its latest 50
Most Beautiful People in the World list. At the Grammys, host Rosie
O'Donnell made lecherous remarks about the handsome 27-year-old
singer. Madonna quickly arranged to record a duet with him. Luciano
Pavarotti invited him to perform in a ``Pavarotti and Friends''
concert this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Martin _ unfamiliar to most Americans before Feb. 24,
even though he had already sold 13 million albums as a solo artist
_ had a lot of friends.
</P>
<P>
   And with Tuesday's release of ``Ricky Martin,'' the singer's
first English-language album, he'll have a lot more. Dan Lightner,
manager of the music store at Borders Books and Music on Hulen
Street in Fort Worth, says that interest in the album has been high
ever since the Grammys. And in Tejano-friendly Texas, it doesn't
seem to matter that Martin isn't a Tejano artist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny,'' Lightner says. ``People you wouldn't expect to
be buying Latin music are buying his albums, either kids or
middle-aged people buying it for kids.'' Lightner says that often,
when customers come in and ask for the not-yet-released new album,
they still buy one of Martin's Spanish-language releases such as
last year's ``Vuelve'' _ which has sold more than a million copies
in the States, and a reported 5 million worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   If you still haven't heard of Martin, don't worry _ you will.
For the rest of the year, there'll be no escaping him. He's already
magazine-cover material and a drool-worthy fixture on MTV and VH1.
Although Morales wouldn't give specifics, KISS plans to bring him
for an in-store appearance during the next few weeks (Martin drew
7,000 people at a similar appearance recently in LA). He appeared
on last week's ``Saturday Night Live'' and Tuesday was on MTV's
``Total Request Live.'' Soon, Martin's conquering of the United
States will be complete.
</P>
<P>
   Or will it? Although Martin is certainly talented _ ``Livin' La
Vida Loca'' is infernally catchy, lingering in your brain days
after you hear it _ there's a sense that his appeal is more visual
than aural. He's great-looking and approachably sexy _ but then, so
are a lot of pop stars; he's a great showman. But talent and looks
aside, is Martin _ the beneficiary of a massive publicity campaign
from Sony Music _ simply just one of the most glaring examples
we've ever seen of the star-maker machinery at work?
</P>
<P>
   Ramiro Burr, who covers Latin music for the San Antonio Express
News, doesn't think so. Although he wonders about Martin's staying
power, he believes that Martin's the real deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a skeptic, too,'' Burr says. ``Right place, right time,
right producer, right label. But I don't think there's any
publicity creation at work here. The guy has a decent voice. He's
broken his chops with Menudo.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yeah, Menudo. Martin was a founding member of the '80s
Latino boy band, a fact that Martin's publicist dismissed with,
``We don't even discuss Menudo.'' Still, his work with the group is
undeniably part of his appeal _ here's a teen singer made good,
much in the same way that former New Kids on the Block singers
Jordan Knight and Joey McEntire have broken through as
dance-friendly adult acts (Rolling Stone recently led its album
review section with a roundup of all three artists' most recent
discs).
</P>
<P>
   And Menudo's only one chapter in Martin's past. Even as he was
becoming a Latin-music superstar, Martin was making himself
familiar to Anglo audiences. He appeared on Broadway in ``Les
Miserables,'' and did a 1994-'96 stint on the ABC soap opera
``General Hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   These angles help give Martin multiple spin appeal, as does his
Latino heritage. Some observers are predicting that Latin music
will be the Next Big Thing, with Martin leading a musical
revolution that pulls along such contemporaries as longtime
heartthrob Luis Miguel, Enrique Iglesias (Julio's son), Elvis
Crespo and salsa singer Mark Anthony.
</P>
<P>
   But then, a couple of years ago, music critics predicted that
techno music was going to be the next big thing, and that didn't
happen. Latin music's previous breakthrough artists haven't led to
a full-scale explosion _ not Santana, not Miami Sound Machine, and
not Selena, although some believe that she would have led a
Latin-music boom had her life not been cut short.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crossover is more of a myth for Latin music than a reality,''
says Enrique Fernandez, a columnist for the Sun-Sentinel in Fort
Lauderdale, Fla. (where Martin owns a restaurant, Casa Salsa).
``Miami Sound Machine had to become Gloria Estefan to cross over.
They started doing more dance-oriented music and very quickly
became big.''
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez believes that Martin's appeal is largely visual. But
then, he says, that's the way it is with most pop music these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about being a great singer, but about being a great
entertainer,'' Fernandez says. ``There's a lot of raw talent in
Latin music, but people don't see it because it's not packaged.''
</P>
<P>
   Morales, the KISS music director, says the packaging wouldn't
matter, though, if Martin's music weren't grabbing people's ears.
</P>
<P>
   ``The song is great,'' Morales says. ``The record is one of our
top three most requested songs, and you can't see him on the
radio.''
</P>
<P>
   Borders' Lightner agrees that one thing will keep Martin in the
limelight for some time: His music just plain sounds good.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's perfect summer music,'' Lightner says. ``It's gonna be
booming out of everybody's stereos this summer.''
</P>
<P>
   -
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
