<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times plans 2{ pages of stories, photos and
graphics on the crisis in Kosovo and the aftermath of the bombing
of the Chinese embassy in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ Rebuffing Yugoslavia's announcement
that it had begun a partial troop withdrawal from Kosovo, NATO said
today that there were no indications that any Yugoslav forces were
leaving the province. NATO also warned that it would not guarantee
the safety of any Serbian units that did try to retreat unless
President Slobodan Milosevic agreed to remove all of his troops.
Other military developments. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PRISTINA (Pristina) _ She's seen too much, Meli said. She
wants a rest. She wants it to be over. She wants to leave, like her
friends, and go to Macedonia. But she wants to stay, because her
mother wants to stay, and it's her home and why should she leave
it? And it seems to be getting better, she says, in Pristina,
anyway. A feature on remaining ethnic Albanians in Pristina, the
Kosovo capital. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ A look at the National Imagery
and Mapping Agency, the Pentagon office that drew up the outdated
map that contributed to the accidental bombing of the Chinese
Embassy in Belgrade. The agency has been embroiled in two other
international incidents in the past year, including the fatal
accident in Italy in which a Marine Corps jet using faulty maps
struck a ski-lift cable. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA (Beijing) _ Viktor Chernomyrdin, the Russian envoy,
meets on Kosovo with Chinese officials, who stick to their demand
that NATO bombing must stop before the U.N. Security Council adopts
a peace plan. Demonstrations against the embassy bombing wane. By
Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CHINA-STUDENTS (Beijing) _ Students at Beijing
University, who have been leading the anti-American protests, talk
about the U.S., China and Kosovo. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-EUROPE (Berlin) _ Europe's defense and foreign ministers,
spurred on by their inability to face conflicts in the Balkans with
a joint armed force, agree to build a common defense structure by
next year. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TRIBUNAL (The Hague) _ International lawyers and
diplomats here believe that Yugoslavia has timed its announcement
to withdraw part of its troops from Kosovo to coincide with the
opening of its lawsuit against ten NATO nations before the
International Court of Justice. In this view, the Yugoslavs believe
that the move will bolster their case if the court calls for
cessation of hostilities. By Marlise Simons.
</P>
