<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2982 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-11 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN MEN WERE MEN AND PLAYERS RETALIATED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Pat Burns pines for the good old days, when men were
men and were allowed to do what righteous and honorable men had to
do when necessary _ beat the innards out of each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did we put rules in to protect the players?'' he inquires.
``That's what they say. But we have more hitting from behind now
than there's ever been. There's more stickwork, more two-handed
slashes that are wicked and vicious.''
</P>
<P>
   He was thinking specifically of the Alexei Zhitnik ramming of
Ray Bourque on Sunday when, as the Captain pointed out, ``My
numbers were showing,'' and he was making an oblique reference to
the fact that the mentality of the suits who govern the game is
completely different than it was a generation or two ago.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the game actually may have been safer when a
perp knew he would be answering to the proper authority before the
game was over.
</P>
<P>
   Take it from (itals)a real(unitals) policeman: The game may have
been safer overall when hockey gendarmes roamed the ice. People
didn't get away with things without paying a penalty, the way they
often do now. Woe be to he who retaliates.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be careful,'' says Ken Belanger, one Bruin who, it
seems to me, would have relished the old days. ``The refs call
(itals)everything.(unitals) They always seem to get the
retaliation. A big part of my game is finishing the check. I've had
times where I've finished the check and gotten called for
roughing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got two referees,'' Burns continues. ``They've got
supervisors. Guys are running down saying, `You missed that call,'
or `That wasn't a call.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But first you have the cheap shot, which may or may not merit a
penalty. If it does, fine. But if it doesn't, you now have to suck
it up, which would be an incomprehensible circumstance for a hockey
player of yore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can just see what would have happened 20 years ago,''
surmises Kyle McLaren, who was a 1-year-old 20 years ago. ``Five
guys would have been on top of him (Zhitnik), right after it,
pounding away. In this day and age, it's not like that. I'd rather
have the five-on-three.''
</P>
<P>
   Kids! What's the matter with kids today? Eddie Shore never
talked like that.
</P>
<P>
   We're not necessarily talking about Eddie Shore's day, either.
Think back to 1980 and a series with the Islanders, then in search
of their first championship. In Game 4, Terry O'Reilly, a warrior
if ever there was one, had two knock-down drag-outs with Clark
Gillies and one with Garry Howatt before drawing a game misconduct.
That makes one more fighting major than has been assessed in the
entirety of the 1999 playoffs, pending any fisticuffs in Tuesday
night's action.
</P>
<P>
   But that wasn't even the best part of the series. The game
before, there were four fights at the conclusion of the first
period. It all started with a Mike Milbury-Duane Sutter fracas, and
before order was restored some 20 minutes later, there were bouts
featuring Stan Jonathan vs. Bob Lorimer; Wayne Cashman vs. Howatt;
and Al Secord vs. Gordie Lane. And let's not forget the sight of
Islanders goalkeeper Bill Smith shedding equipment as he ambled
down the ice, only to find himself jumped en route by Bruins backup
netminder Yves Belanger. Got a lump in the throat and mist in the
eye yet?
</P>
<P>
   No one is calling for the resumption of mayhem when Game 3 gets
under way at the Marine Midland Arena Wednesday night, even though,
in that sense, the game they played was more fun. The NHL has
decided that it was in the general best interests of the league to
downplay thuggery, and that's that. But beware, as always, of the
famed Law of Unintended Consequences. You probably could kill all
the rattlers, but you might not like having an influx of rodents
and assorted other pests. Likewise, what Burns is saying is that in
eliminating the true policeman you are fostering the cheap-shot
element, oftentimes coming from people who never would be goaded
into a fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zhitnik isn't going to fight,'' sneers Burns. ``Now if that
were (the injured) Rob Ray, he'd do what he wanted and then say,
`what are you going to do about it?' ''
</P>
<P>
   This is a relevant topic matter since folks on both sides of
this Bruins-Sabres confrontation think a line has been crossed. The
Bruins think that Buffalo, which is hardly a team of bruisers, has
been waging sort of a guerilla war of cheap shots. The Sabres think
the Bruins whine too much. They are also suggesting that Boston's
hallowed captain floppeth too much. The nerve!
</P>
<P>
   There is a lot of gamesmanship going on here, and what else is
new? Burns says some things to get the attention of his team. He
says other things to get the attention of the officials. Lindy
Ruff, the Buffalo coach, made his own public appeal to the
officials following Game 1, when he suggested that the more
experienced Burns was better at manipulating the officials than he
was. This is all nothing new. It began, I think, with King Clancy.
Or perhaps King Henry VIII.
</P>
<P>
   Hockey is not a genteel sport. This isn't croquet. Hockey is a
hit-and-be-hit sport, and it has spent the better part of a century
defining itself in very manly terms. Like anything else, it can be
over-romanticized. Talk all you want about allowing burly men to
exact frontier justice by putting up their dukes, but it didn't
always end there. Who can forget the photo of Wayne Maki's stick
landing on the helmet-less head of (Terrible) Teddy Green? Is that
what we want?
</P>
<P>
   No, of course not. All Pat Burns wants is for manly men to keep
order in the time-honored way without worrying that every
extra-hard check following an uncalled charging becomes a power
play. He wants cowardly perps to skate around with a little fear.
Who could rightfully argue with that?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-99 1909EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
