<DOCNO> NYT19990511.0276 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2984 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-SABRES-ZHITNIK-BO     05-11 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SABRES-ZHITNIK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZHITNIK WILL BE ON BRUINS' MINDS IN GAME 3 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ While they are distributing wanted posters of
Alexei Zhitnik, the Bruins must at least concede his good points.
If nothing else, he is a most democratic health hazard.
</P>
<P>
   Showing no favoritism, the All-Star Sabres defenseman has
inflicted his worst playoff damage on one of his own. Miroslav
Satan's ankle got in the way of a Zhitnik slap shot during Game 3
of Buffalo's first-round sweep of Ottawa, and the Sabres haven't
seen the veteran winger _ or his team-high 40 goals _ since. The
only uniform Satan has worn in the past two weeks is a hospital
johnny, which he donned again for a bone scan Tuesday, and he won't
be available Wednesday night when Boston visits Marine Midland
Arena for the third round of this best-of-seven Eastern Conference
semifinal confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Zhitnik's wounding of Satan was purely accidental.
The Bruins maintain that his ambush of their captain and
indispensable cog, Ray Bourque, Sunday in Boston was premeditated
assault.
</P>
<P>
   While Bourque was able to resume his normal duties after being
checked from behind at 14:57 of the second period during Buffalo's
series-tying 3-1 victory, the Bruins contend that Zhitnik had no
right tampering with a civic treasure and that his transgression
merited far more than the two-minute penalty for boarding he was
assessed.
</P>
<P>
   Playoff stakes do not accommodate frontier justice. But the
Bruins _ even the normally placid Bourque _ have indicated that
prudent retribution may be in order against Zhitnik, who earlier in
Game 2 left Boston forward P.J. Axelsson in a brace following a
knee-on-knee collision and served up an appetizer for his infamous
hit on Bourque by charging the defenseman _ a hit Zhitnik admitted
(itals)was(unitals) dirty.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Zhitnik wore an angel face Tuesday and seemed
thoroughly unimpressed with his notoriety.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can take anything,'' he said after a light workout at the
Sabres' suburban practice arena in Amherst. ``The hit looked pretty
bad, but it wasn't intentional. It's playoff hockey, so we can
expect anything. I'm just going to go out and try to play hockey,
take some body. I play rough hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering that that's the nature of the playoffs, his
teammates couldn't understand what the fuss was about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not talk about the hit on Kruse?'' said disgusted Buffalo
captain Michael Peca, referring to Bruin muscleman Ken
Baumgartner's stickwork on Paul Kruse at 8:34 of the second period
Sunday that put the Buffalo left wing on the bench in a state of
suspended animation. ``Why don't they comment on that? Everybody
chooses to focus on what they want.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres readily acknowledge that their focus is on Bourque,
but it's hardly an original concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the focal point of every playoff series,'' said coach
Lindy Ruff. ``Every team wants to finish him. And he just keeps
going, seldom gets injured. But you've got to keep doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   While steadfastly championing Zhitnik's innocence _ echoing his
player's claim that Bourque turned in to the check and that the hit
from behind was unintentional _ Ruff was unconcerned that his top
defenseman has emerged as the major villain from the Bruins'
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll want to finish him off,'' said the coach, ``but I
don't expect they'll want to take any stupid penalties.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhitnik also doubted that a physical series would turn fistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a fighter,'' he said. ``There are no fights in the
playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   But there can be distractions, and Ruff hopes Zhitnik has become
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you see your name in the paper, that the other team's
talking about you,'' he said, ``that means you're doing your job.''
</P>
<P>
   In this regard, Zhitnik pleaded ignorance rather than innocence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really pay attention to TV talk or newspapers,'' said
the 26-year-old Ukrainian. ``I try to stay away from that stuff.
Nobody said anything about that.''
</P>
<P>
   He might get the message Wednesday. But the Sabres do not fear
for his safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he really cares,'' said Peca.
</P>
<P>
   And even if it reaches the point where he has no choice, said
Ruff, ``I'm not worried at all. Alexei gets fired up. He's got a
nasty side to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Really? The Bruins never would have guessed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
