<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2985 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VOUCHERS-BUSH-HNS &LR;      05-11 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOUCHERS-BUSH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH HAS DOUBTS ABOUT FATE OF HIS SCHOOL VOUCHER PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA TOLLEY  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush expressed some doubt Tuesday
that lawmakers would approve a school voucher program this session,
but he was optimistic that other key parts of his legislative
agenda would prevail.
</P>
<P>
   Bush called for the passage of a school voucher pilot program at
the beginning of the legislative session, and the proposal is
strongly supported by Lt. Gov. Rick Perry, a fellow Republican.
</P>
<P>
   But with fewer than three weeks to go in the session, Senate
Democrats said they had the votes to keep the bill from being heard
on the floor. The House has not yet approved a voucher plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I think there's still a chance that vouchers may have
some life in the Senate ... but I'm not nearly as hopeful about
that particular issue as I would have been at the beginning of the
session,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   The program would provide vouchers to parents of children in
poorly performing public schools. The vouchers could be used to
help pay tuition in private schools.
</P>
<P>
   Friday is the last day for the House to consider all bills on
third and final reading, but proponents say there may still be an
attempt to approve a limited voucher program. The legislative
session ends May 31.
</P>
<P>
   Although voucher proponents have lobbied hard for the proposal,
Bush said, opponents have been successful in presenting their side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are afraid that vouchers will hurt public
schools. I disagree,'' he said. ``I think vouchers will help
parents whose children get locked into failed schools. But the
opponents to vouchers have done a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Putting Children First, an organization that favors vouchers, is
still hopes for passage of some type of proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not over until it's over,'' said Chuck McDonald, a
spokesman for the group. ``Obviously, it would take some doing to
pass voucher legislation at this point. ... but there's always a
chance. It's still possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Bush was more optimistic that lawmakers would deliver
a school property tax cut he could support, even though the Senate
version calls for half the $2 billion in tax relief he is seeking
and the House hasn't even approved a tax-reduction plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like we're in good shape. I think we're going to have
both a teacher pay raise and tax cuts that will be substantial,''
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is considering a bid for the Republican presidential
nomination, and some political observers believe he wants to emerge
from the session with a sizable tax cut that he can tout on the
campaign trail. But the governor insisted he is only concerned
about Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what's important to Texas that matters to me. We'll worry
about all the (presidential) exploratory business later. Right now,
it's what's best for Texas,'' said Bush, who is expected to travel
to Iowa and New Hampshire next month after the legislative session
ends.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
