</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS STADIUM BILL PUT IN THE WORKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Governor Cellucci unveiled legislation Tuesday to help
the New England Patriots build a new home in Foxborough, and
pledged to work with town officials to expedite the permitting
process so the $225 million stadium could be ready by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The $70 million infrastructure plan is expected to pass with the
necessary two-thirds approval in the House and Senate. Both
branches are scheduled to begin debate on the measure next Tuesday,
one day after a public hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's pretty good news in terms of the progress of this
bill,'' Cellucci said.
</P>
<P>
   Foxborough residents must also sign off on the stadium
development at a special town meeting that has not yet been set.
The goal: speedy action so that the facility can be ready for play
by 2001, the date he initially targeted in team owner Robert
Kraft's Connecticut stadium deal, which collapsed last month when
the construction timetable appeared in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Thomas M. Finneran, Senate President Thomas F.
Birmingham, and Cellucci designed the legislation with input from
the NFL last month after years of political struggle that almost
drove the team to move out of state -- twice in as many years.
</P>
<P>
   Birmingham said Tuesday's announcement shows the divisiveness
between the House and Senate on the issue has finally been put to
rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have proved the naysayers wrong. We have proved we can work
together in a bipartisan way to get to `yes,' '' the Chelsea
Democrat said. ``Perhaps we should have won it in regulation. It's
fine to win it in overtime.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the political keloid -- the result of Kraft's
frustration and impatience with Beacon Hill and the Legislature's
polarization over him -- was still visible Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   None of the state's top leaders have spoken to Kraft about
whether the deal is acceptable to him, and the Patriots patriarch
was conspicuously absent from Tuesday's announcement, otherwise
dripping with mutual praise and sports metaphors.
</P>
<P>
   New England Patriots spokesman Stacey James said the team would
withhold comment until after the Legislature votes on the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Finneran, blamed for blocking a $72 million Senate stadium plan
last year, seemed anxious to put the saga behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems the endzone is in sight,'' said Finneran. ``And it's
a good story to tell.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cellucci stumbled when asked why no one on Beacon Hill has
spoken to Kraft directly since the franchise owner walked away from
a proposal to build a $374 million publicly financed stadium in
Hartford. Before Kraft's April 30 decision to pull out of the
Connecticut deal, he was not allowed to negotiate with another
state without penalty. He can now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did leave a message with him that I was very pleased,''
Cellucci said, referring to a call to Kraft 10 days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives from the NFL were included in the talks to
finalize this latest plan, but not even they were supposed to speak
with Kraft about the negotiations while he was still engaged to the
Hartford agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The league has since apprised Kraft of the details and the team
has publicly committed to staying in Foxborough. Part of the deal
would have the NFL financing a portion of the $225 million stadium,
to be built next door to the current facility.
</P>
<P>
   The town, which owns the footprint of land beneath Foxboro
Stadium, would give up that property, but become the new owner of
the footprint beneath the replacement structure, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Foxborough Industrial Development Corp., a quasi-public
agency, would issue the 25-year bonds backed by the state.
</P>
<P>
   The bill:
</P>
<P>
   -- Requires the team to pay the state $1 million a year, plus
taps satellite parking lots for another $400,000, for the life of
the $70 million in bonds for sewer, road, and utility service
upgrades along Route 1.
</P>
<P>
   -- Allows the team to decide just how to generate cash for $1
million of the yearly payment to the state. This point was
purposely left vague because Cellucci's anti-tax stance made him
skiddish about imposing a stadium-related tax or fee.
</P>
<P>
   -- Includes a ``recapture'' clause should the Patriots decide to
leave Foxborough after the public sector invests in the area. Under
this provision, Kraft would have to pay back all of the debt
service the state incurred up to the time he decides to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think there's some legitimate grounding of the franchise,''
Finneran said.
</P>
<P>
   The $1.4 million so-called revenue stream from the Patriots
would essentially cover the state's annual financing costs, an idea
the NFL did not like because they feared it would set a precedent
with other states contemplating new facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The league was never comfortable...until we made it clear this
was going to be the best deal they'd get,'' Finneran said.
</P>
<P>
   Finneran held up a Senate plan last year that would have
provided $52 million for infrastructure and $20 million for land
the state would purchase and lease back to Kraft. The speaker said
public investment in private land was against his principles.
</P>
<P>
   What changed?
</P>
<P>
   The introduction of a fresh idea Finneran was willing to accept
saying the team would grant the state an easement to make access
and sewer line improvements on their property.
</P>
<P>
   But the prospect of a second chance -- this time for being a
hero -- may have also played a part for the Mattapan Democrat, the
subject of much bashing on sports radio over the last 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Looking stern, Finneran later added, ``I don't get euphoric over
these things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-99 1912EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
