<DOCNO> NYT19990511.0279 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2988 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS &LR;      05-11 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS FOCUSED ON GETTING THE WIN, BELANGER SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The posturing is over, the strategy has been set.
Wednesday night, after much talk, it will be time to play. The
Bruins are planning to go after the Buffalo Sabres early and often
in Game 3 at Marine Midland Arena, but don't misunderstand.
</P>
<P>
   There will be no retaliation for Alexei Zhitnik's nasty hit on
Bruins captain Ray Bourque. There will be no vigilante antics, no
payback.
</P>
<P>
   With enforcer Ken Baumgartner sidelined, left wing Ken Belanger
said he in no way feels obligated to mix it up with any Sabres. He
and his teammates will finish their checks, keep their heads on
their shoulders, and do their best to gain the ulimate revenge _
win the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the media making a war out of it, it's not the
players,'' said Belanger. ``It's a game we play, it's a physical
game. Checks happen. Obviously, it wasn't a clean check. You don't
like to see it happen. We finish our hits just as hard. It's all
the newspapers making wars back and forth. We can't be focused on
that, we have to be focused on winning the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Belanger said if he were to go out there with an eye on settling
things with Zhitnik, it would be one-sided.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll get a five-minute major for fighting and he won't fight,
that's no secret,'' he said. ``It's one of those plays where maybe
next year you take a liberty and take a run at him. Right now, you
can't. It's not even an issue. They hit our good players, we have
to hit their good players. That's how it works. We're going in
there with a new attitude. We're going in there to win two games
and that's what our frame of mind is.''
</P>
<P>
   Right wing Rob DiMaio, another of the Bruins' more gritty
players, said they weren't given an edict by coach Pat Burns to not
retaliate. The coach didn't have to say that. With so much riding
on the next two games, DiMaio said it's a no-brainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to tell us to be smart, he's going to tell us to be
disciplined and sometimes you have to turn the other cheek but I've
never heard the word, `don't' come out of his mouth,'' said DiMaio.
``I think we're all knowledgeable enough to understand the
importance of games and the importance of taking a bad penalty and
how it can hurt your hockey team.''
</P>
<P>
   DiMaio said the good thing is they all have long memories, so if
they have to wait to send a message to Zhitnik about his style of
play, so be it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those things will take care of themselves when it's time to
take care of them,'' he said. ``Even if it's not this series, we've
got next year. These things aren't forgotten. Sometimes you have to
bite your tongue. As hard as that is to do, and it's very hard,
there's a right time of the game to do it and you don't.''
</P>
<P>
   If there's an area of concern for the Bruins, it's not the
physical play of the Sabres. It's the poor start the team had in
Game 2. Boston's play was awful and the Sabres jumped on the Bruins
right out of the gate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd better be ready,'' said DiMaio. ``They're going to be
coming out very hard and we have to match that. We have to be
prepared ourselves. There's physical and there's stupidity and we
have to be smart. We're going in there with the idea we have to
win. We have to start well and I think we have a good opportunity
if we play the style we know we can play. We know what to expect
from them. I don't think they're sure what to expect from us right
now, which could be to our advantage. We really have to come out
with a lot of intensity.''
</P>
<P>
   Goaltender Byron Dafoe said the team desperately wants to avoid
a repeat of Game 2's first period and that they're going to have to
play with a sense of urgency.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to take it to them, we want to turn this series
around,'' said Dafoe. ``Throughout the season, they pretty much
dominated us. They don't know what we can really play like as we
played in the first round or even at the end of the season. There's
going to be extra emotion obviously because of what happened in
Game 2. We just have to keep in control and play our game.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns said he thought it was actually good for the Bruins to go
out on the road, where the club has played well except, of course,
in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything I've heard the last couple of days has been
negative,'' said Burns. ``I think we'll probably take a lot of
emotion into that. We've got a good challenge on the table right
now and I think the players will take it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-99 1913EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
