<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2993 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-SWEENEY-BO     05-11 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-SWEENEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEENEY DEFENSIVE MINDED, DESPITE GOALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN VELLANTE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- He went five years between Stanley Cup playoff goals
and now he has two in five games.
</P>
<P>
   And that's as many as he had in 81 games during the regular
season.
</P>
<P>
   But don't get excited, folks.
</P>
<P>
   Don Sweeney isn't.
</P>
<P>
   He knows his role, and knows, too, that if he's going to help
carry the Bruins deep into the playoffs, it's going to be because
of his defense, not his offense.
</P>
<P>
   That's what he does best and that's what he did very well in the
six-game conquest of Carolina and in the first two games against
Buffalo. He couldn't have picked a better time to step it up a
notch.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to Tim Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's (Sweeney) playing some great hockey right now and we
really need that, especially at playoff time. That's what you need
from a defenseman and he's brought that to the table. Not just in a
couple of games, but in every game. The goals have been a bonus.''
</P>
<P>
   And listen to Hal Gill.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been playing unreal. I haven't seen him play this well in
a long time. He's been an impact player for us in the playoffs.
He's picked his spots. He's been huge.''
</P>
<P>
   And listen, too, to coach Pat Burns.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the most part he goes unnoticed, but he's doing the job
and when you need him to step up and make the big play, he's
there.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been a solid postseason for the 11-year veteran, now 32,
who in eight games has logged an average of 23-plus minutes and has
delivered his share of thundering hits. And let's not forget the
two goals, in Game 4 against Carolina and Game 2 against Buffalo.
Both were big.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney, though, prefers not to dwell on his play.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point in time, I mean, you can sit back at the end of
the year and look in the mirror and analyze all you want how you
played, but let's be honest. It takes four wins to win a series and
everybody's involved in that and everybody has to play their roles
in order to accomplish that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take 20 guys each and every night. You have
injuries and you have to look at your depth. You have to bring to
the table what you bring as an individual and collectively and hope
that it's good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney says he has no illusions about what's expected of him.
He knows it isn't for him to score goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you take more chances during the regular season, you can
probably score more goals,'' he said. ``Raymond (Bourque) could
have more points. It's hard to believe that, but he could if he
didn't take care of his own end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what my role is on this hockey club. I'm not a
power-play guy. We're a team that's a transition team. We're not a
team that scores a lot of end-to-end goals. I'm going to provide
what I need to provide for this hockey club to be successful.
That's to be steady and to contribute every night.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney, along with some of his veteran teammates, has preached
to the youngsters about what it's like to be playing hockey in
mid-May.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what it's all about,'' he said. ``I hadn't even played
in the playoffs the last two years, due to injuries last year, and
we missed them the year before. I was very eager to get going
against Carolina. It doesn't get any better than the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had guys in here that tasted a first-round victory and
that's something they hadn't done before. We have to let them know
that it only gets harder from here on in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked to them and told them that you don't always have
opportunities, that they slide by. When they present themselves,
you have to grab hold of them like they're the most precious thing
going. Take advantage of the situation that's in front of you.
Don't wait because you're 19 or 21 years old and say, `Well, maybe
next year, I'm going to get better next year.' It just doesn't work
that way. You need to realize what's in front of you and grab that
brass ring while you can.''
</P>
<P>
   And, he adds, ``Now is as good a time as any.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
