<DOCNO> NYT19990511.0283 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2997 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-JERUSALEM-NYT &LR;      05-11 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-JERUSALEM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI COURT LETS PALESTINIAN OFFICES REMAIN OPEN UNTIL AFTER
ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also ISRAEL-POLITICS) 
(rk) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The Israeli Supreme Court on Tuesday barred the
government from closing three offices at the Palestinian political
headquarters in East Jerusalem, easing a crisis that had threatened
to erupt in violence less than a week before the Israeli election.
</P>
<P>
   The court order was a political blow to Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu, who pressed for the closing as part of a re-election
campaign in which he has made Israel's control of Jerusalem a
rallying cry.
</P>
<P>
   Faisal al-Husseini, the top Palestinian leader in East
Jerusalem, emerged strengthened, riding a wave of popular support
as Palestinians rallied around the headquarters, known as Orient
House, which they consider a symbol of their claims to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The court's ruling removed a looming threat of violence after
the police served orders to close the three offices on Monday night
and Palestinians gathered there to block entry by the security
forces.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu's Cabinet authorized the closings, asserting that the
offices _ a maps department that monitors Israeli settlement
activity, a liaison office with foreign diplomats, and Husseini's
office _ were linked to the Palestinian Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Israeli-Palestinian interim self-rule accords, the
authority cannot operate in Jerusalem. The city's future is to be
decided in talks on a final peace agreement _ talks that were
supposed to have been completed by May 4, but have barely begun.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian officials and Israeli intelligence chiefs warned
that a forcible police entry to Orient House, the Jerusalem
headquarters of the Palestine Liberation Organization, was likely
to cause bloodshed and set off riots. American diplomats tried to
mediate the dispute, and the State Department urged restraint.
</P>
<P>
   Confrontation was averted Tuesday by Israeli peace advocates
from Jerusalem. They petitioned the Supreme Court, arguing that
Netanyahu's decision to close the offices was tainted with
``electoral considerations.'' They asked for an order barring the
closing until after the May 17 elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prime minister is creating an event,'' said Daniel
Seidemann, the lawyer who filed the petition, ``a photo opportunity
that on the following day will appear in his television ads, and
this affects the lives and deaths of individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Dalia Dorner ruled that the offices could not be closed
until a further court decision. She gave Husseini and his
colleagues a week to submit their response, deferring the case
until after the election on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu responded: ``We are determined to close these offices,
which challenge our sovereignty in Jerusalem, but we are determined
to do so in accordance with the directives of the judiciary system,
carefully and responsibly. We have no intention of inflaming the
area. I'm doing what a prime minister must do, ensuring our
sovereignty in Jerusalem.''
</P>
<P>
   At Orient House, Palestinians celebrated victory, shooting off
fireworks, dancing and chanting slogans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a victory over anyone,'' said Husseini, who was
given a hero's welcome by his supporters. ``This is a victory for
peace, for peace-loving people not only in Palestine, but in Israel
and all over the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-99 1917EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990511.0284 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2999 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0512-C     05-11 1409
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0512-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S., RUSSIA MEET TO STEP UP DIPLOMATIC EFFORTS TO HALT NATO
BOMBING, END KOSOVO CRISIS
 &HT;    1000&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0512.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Russia's envoy to the Balkans said he would propose
new ideas when he meets Wednesday in Moscow with U.S. diplomat
Strobe Talbott over ways to bring peace to Yugoslavia's embattled
province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In a potential stumbling block for the United States and its
allies, however, China locked arms with Russia in demanding an
immediate halt to the NATO air campaign against Yugoslavia, NATO
wound up its seventh inconclusive week with fresh attacks early
Wednesday.(CQ)
</P>
<P>
   In another troubling sign for the alliance, Chinese President
Jiang Zemin denounced NATO's mistaken attack on China's embassy in
Belgrade last Friday as ``a provocation to all 1.2 billion Chinese
people,'' as Beijing formally scratched a broad array of high-level
military and diplomatic meetings it had scheduled with U.S.
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang made the remarks hours before the remains of the three
Chinese killed in the bombing were scheduled to arrive in Beijing,
where anti-American protests were expected to roll into a fifth day
on Wednesday, rekindled by the emotion-wrought return of the
bodies.
</P>
<P>
   As President Clinton searched for ways to smooth the roiled
waters between the United States and the world's most populous
country, Jiang continued to snub the White House, refusing to speak
to Clinton over the telephone.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman James Rubin insisted that Clinton had
not yet tried to use a special hot line set up two years ago to
head off prickly problems between Washington and Beijing. The
issue, he said, is not finding a phone, but rather getting Jiang to
answer it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A hot line or a telephone has to have two people on both sides
of the phone,'' Rubin said. ``We're clearly indicating our
willingness to talk to them on the phone . . . They've chosen,
obviously, that they are not ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has apologized for the inadvertent attack twice in
public and once in a letter to Jiang. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright hand-carried a letter of apology to the Chinese Embassy in
Washington last Saturday, the morning after the ill-fated attack.
</P>
<P>
   China's state-run media didn't broadcast or publish news of the
apologies, however, until Tuesday, sparking some here to wonder
whether the Chinese government -- or some faction of it -- might be
feeding anti-American sentiment across a country that takes in
one-fifth of the world's population.
</P>
<P>
   China's Foreign Ministry spokesman, Zhu Bangzao, denied that,
calling the protests ``overreactions,'' and saying suggestions that
the demonstrators were backed by Beijing amounted to ``a
misunderstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   In his first public remarks on the issue, however, Jiang added
to the confusion, praising the demonstrators as the banner carriers
of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last few days, the Chinese people have used protests,
meetings, statements and all sorts of methods to express their
utmost indignation,'' Jiang told Russia's envoy to the Balkans,
Victor Chernomyrdin, during a meeting in Beijing Tuesday. ``It
shows the fervor, will and strength of the great patriotic spirit
of the Chinese people,'' Jiang said, according to state-run news
agencies in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   China formally notified the United States that it was suspending
a series of high-level meetings that had been scheduled for later
this month and next on subjects ranging from human rights and
nuclear weapons proliferation to security issues.
</P>
<P>
   Also in jeopardy are talks that have gone on for years aimed at
economic and trade reforms that would enable China to qualify for
membership in the World Trade Organization -- a step deemed
critical to the furtherance of U.S.-Chinese commercial ties.
</P>
<P>
   Also at risk was a planned trip next month to Beijing by Defense
Secretary William Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin, Russia's former premier, left Beijing for Moscow,
where he arrived late Tuesday in preparation for his meeting with
Talbott, deputy secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before everything else, it is essential that NATO stop its
strikes against Yugoslavia,'' Chernomyrdin told reporters, echoing
the view China has also expressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' Chernomyrdin said, ``is an important condition for
peace talks.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO ignored the plea, pressing its air campaign into its 50th
day with fresh attacks across Yugoslavia early Wednesday(CQ), and
U.S. and allied officials vowed the strikes would escalate further
in the days and weeks ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO's air campaign will continue until atrocities in Kosovo
have ceased, all Yugoslav security forces have left Kosovo, and
there is agreement on an international security presence that will
allow refugees to return to the region in safety,'' Albright said
in a message taped for release across Yugoslavia's main state of
Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   The address was to be beamed by radio into Serbia as part of a
larger U.S. effort to counter state-controlled media in Belgrade,
which has yet to notify the public of military repression that the
United States estimates has left more than 4,600 ethnic Albanians
dead and perhaps 1.5 million homeless.
</P>
<P>
   ``When this conflict is over, good and decent Serbs will be
appalled at what has been done in your name. You did not shoot sons
in front of their mothers, chase families into minefields, or
select out young women to be raped,'' Albright said. `` But the
world knows that your military,
</P>
<P>
   paramilitary and police forces are doing all of these things in
Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin insisted that the souring of Sino-American relations and
Beijing's growing link with Moscow over the issue would not affect
the air campaign nor impede the search for a diplomatic end to the
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not believe that this will have any significant effect
on the conduct of our military operation or the pace of the
diplomatic track,'' Rubin told reporters at the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   The striking union of Moscow and Beijing, however, raised the
geopolitical stakes in the Kosovo conflict. China and Russia are
among the five permanent members of the United Nations Security
Council, along with the United States, Britain and France.
</P>
<P>
   Each one has veto power that can block Security Council
resolutions, such as the one the United States and its NATO allies
are seeking to endorse a plan for setting up an international
protectorate in Kosovo and policing it with a NATO-led peacekeeping
force.
</P>
<P>
   Russia agreed, in a very general sense, to that plan last
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The Talbott-Chernomyrdin meeting on Wednesday is a day-long
working session aimed at putting flesh on the bones of that
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said it was unlikely that China would block any accord --
or the Security Council resolution endorsing it -- that might be
reached between Russia and NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe that China will at the end of the day stand
in the way of an agreement that could be struck by Russia based on
NATO's five conditions,'' said Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   Those conditions are:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  an end to hostilities inside Kosovo;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  the withdrawal of all Serb forces from Kosovo;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  the acceptance by Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic, president of
Yugoslavia, of an international peacekeeping force with NATO at its
core to police the peace in Kosovo;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  guaranteed safe return of ethnic Albanian refugees;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  and political autonomy -- but not independence -- for Kosovo's
ethnic Albanian majority.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin also raised the possibility that Finland's president,
Martti Ahtisaari, might soon travel on a diplomatic mission,
perhaps to Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't want to rule that out,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   Talbott is to fly to Helsinki Wednesday night for a Thursday
meeting with Ahtisaari, a former U.N. representative with extensive
experience in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he's prepared to play a role as appropriate, and we
want to discuss with him, as we discuss with others, various ways
in which to achieve our diplomatic objective,'' Rubin said. ``He's
someone who we have a lot of respect for and we want to stay in
close touch with and seek his advice on this subject.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
