<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Wednesday, May 12, and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Jeremy Bagott at the Daily News, (818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-BOMB (Los Angeles) _ Los Angeles Unified School District
contractors have been quietly building a room into the foundation
of the trouble-plagued Belmont Center that could be a bomb _
literally. A May 7 letter to the facilities department from state
toxic control officials says Turner/Kajima has been building an
unventilated electrical vault on a site that could emit enough
methane to actually blow up. By Greg Gittrich. (Will move in the
``n'' California and ``a'' national news files.)
</P>
<P>
   STARWARS-RIOT (Los Angeles) _ If Star Wars fans choose to see
George Lucas' much-anticipated ``prequel,'' the force will be with
them. Cities are taking precautions throughout the Los Angeles
region to prevent skirmishes and stampedes over tickets and seats.
LAPD will be monitoring the theaters. The Burbank Police Department
and traffic bureau have set up contingency plans to deal with the
expected chaos at the city's two downtown movie theaters, where
Star Wars will be showing on five screens on May 19. By Lee Condon.
(Will move in the ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   POT-KID (Los Angeles) _ Interviews with about 20 students at
Arroyo Seco Junior High School poked holes in a seventh-grade boy's
claim that he was wrongfully suspended for trying to do the right
thing in handing marijuana a friend had purchased over to his
parents. Sheriff's investigators said they will pursue juvenile
court charges against Tyler Hagen and three other schoolmates for
buying and possessing marijuana. By Patricia Aidem. (Will move in
the ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   LITTON-AVONDALE (Los Angeles) _ The board of directors of
Avondale Industries agreed Tuesday to begin discussions with Litton
Industries over the Los Angeles-based company's $38-per-share offer
for Avondale. The board acknowledged that Litton's offer is sweeter
than a previous offer from Newport News and worth pursuing. Last
week, Litton made separate, unexpected bids for Avondale and
Newport News that, if successful, would make Litton the preeminent
military ship contractor in the U.S. By Greg Wilcox. (Will move in
the ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-ENTREPRENEUR (Los Angeles) _ To Tom O'Malia, successful
entrepreneurship is all about recognizing and seizing the right
opportunity to launch a new venture. So it is with teaching, says
O'Malia, director of the Lloyd Greif Center for Entrepreneurial
Studies at the University of Southern California's Marshall School
of Business. By Enrique Rivero.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in the ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-JUDGMENT (Los Angeles) _ Warner Bros. received a $3.6
million judgment against Los Angeles-based company that was
counterfeiting the Burbank-based company's Looney Tunes and DC
Comics merchandise. The principals of the company were also found
by a U.S. Federal District Judge to have violated two previous
orders prohibiting them from engaging in the sale of counterfeit
products. By Ben Sullivan. (Will move in the ``f'' financial news
