<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: LAND OF THE RISING STOCK MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Japan's economy may be dead in the water, but the nation is once
again the land of the rising stock market. The question is, when
will the world's second- largest economy begin to justify
investors' increasingly high hopes?
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, the benchmark Nikkei 225 index is up 20.96
percent in yen terms, beating even the Dow Jones industrial
average. Anyone who invested in the Nikkei in dollars has a 13.58
percent gain for the year. Shares of small companies have jumped
along with the big blue chips.
</P>
<P>
   Pushing share prices higher is the consensus view among
economists that the worst is over for Japan. Last year, the
nation's gross domestic product declined 2.8 percent. Economists
expect output to shrink only 1.5 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Japan, responsible for 20 percent of the world's production of
goods, has been mired in its deepest recession since the end of
World War II. While some numbers and anecdotal information out of
Japan very recently have seemed positive _ consumer spending has
stopped dropping, automobile sales have risen a bit _ real evidence
of a rebound is scanty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The passage of the bank reform legislation last fall and the
extra fiscal stimulus gave people confidence,'' said Carl Weinberg,
chief economist at High Frequency Economics in Valhalla, N.Y. ``But
investors' expectations for the timetable are too optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   This optimism is evident in the buckets of money pouring into
Japanese stocks. According to Robert Adler, president of AMG Data
Services, money flowing into mutual funds that invest in Japanese
equities has exceeded that going into any foreign market in recent
weeks. On Feb. 24, assets in Japanese equity funds totaled $1.73
billion, but have since risen to $3.02 billion, a 75 percent
increase. Only a small portion of that increase comes from market
gains as the Nikkei 225 has risen 20.5 percent in the period.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past month, some $77 billion a week has gone into
Japanese equity funds. ``Japanese inflows are the heaviest they've
been since June 1997,'' Adler said. ``Then, a nine-consecutive-week
period with relatively heavy flows was brought to a screeching halt
by the Thai baht collapse. Outflows started and investor sentiment
hasn't recovered until now.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of those putting money into Japan are doing so in the
belief that the economy is about to turn up. Others are probably
trend-followers, jumping into whatever investment is the top
performer of late. Since Japanese equity funds topped the
performance lists for international mutual funds offered by U.S.
fund companies in the first quarter of 1999, they have attracted
even more attention. And now that interest rates on Japan's
government bonds have dropped to 1.32 percent, Japanese investors
appear to be edging into stocks as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stock markets can be wrong,'' said Robert Parks, professor of
finance at the Lubin Graduate School of Business at Pace
University. Parks believes that investors are mistaking low
interest rates in Japan _ money market rates are close to zero _ as
evidence of relatively easy monetary policy, an approach that would
turn the economy around. ``But low interest rates are not evidence
of fiscal monetary stimulation, they are evidence of a collapsing
economy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, through March 31, tax revenues were down 7.1 percent,
consumer prices had fallen 3.9 percent, and residential land values
in Tokyo had declined 1 percent. Weinberg expects corporate
earnings to disappoint and the nation's output for 1999 to be down
much more sharply than the 1.5 percent decline most economists are
projecting.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most closely watched figures out of Japan is the
so-called bank lending number, a report of lending activities from
19 city banks, due out late Thursday. A rise in lending, which has
been falling for almost two years, would be a harbinger of an
improved economy, Weinberg said. But he suspects lending is still
on the downswing. In March, bank lending fell 3.6 percent from a
year earlier; his forecast for April is a 4.1 percent drop from the
1998 period.
</P>
<P>
   Weinberg said that GDP growth doesn't usually show up until
three to four quarters after money and credit have begun to expand.
``That means that at the soonest it will be the first quarter of
2000 before meaningful economic expansion takes place,'' he said.
``And for that to happen everything has to be perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   To try to jumpstart their economy, Japanese policy-makers have
cut taxes and increased government spending on public works. But
the spending has been funded by the issuance of government bonds,
the wrong approach according to Parks, because it sops up private
funds that might otherwise go to investment or consumption.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Japan must increase the money supply by rolling the
printing presses, Parks said. Policy-makers are afraid to do this
for fear of pushing the yen down and inflation up. The recent 3.5
percent increase in the broad supply of money in Japan has simply
been the result of consumers shifting money around, not the
creation of new money, an economist said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned that Japan's sovereign debt will be downgraded
again if they don't shift their policies,'' Parks said. ``And if
yields on sovereign debt shoot up, what would that mean for credit
demands that have collapsed as it is? Once the economic decline
gains a self-reinforcing momentum, you go right into a
depression.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
