<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MTBE-STUDY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GASOLINE ADDITIVE ISN'T CURTAILING SMOG, STUDY SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Calif.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A controversial ingredient several states' gasoline, blamed for
widespread water contamination, does little to reduce summertime
smog as it was intended to, according to a National Research
Council study that may add momentum to growing efforts to eliminate
the additive.
</P>
<P>
   MTBE has been added in large quantities to gasoline since 1995
as part of a recipe change aimed at reducing air pollution in
vehicle exhaust. But, almost immediately, MTBE began seeping into
drinking water supplies, including 53 in Massachusetts so far and
more than 100 each in Maine and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the study by the National Research Council, research arm of
the National Academy of Sciences, suggests the public is getting
only modest air quality improvements from MTBE, called an
oxygenate, in exchange for the threat to water supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very very hard for us to see anything significant
coming out of the addition of oxygenates with the exception of a
reduction in carbon monoxides,'' said William Chameides, an
atmospheric scientist at the Georgia Institute of Technology who
chaired the study panel. He made no policy recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   But others cautioned against writing off MTBE, noting that it is
just one ingredient of a broader reformulated gasoline that has
been highly successful at reducing ozone and the other chemicals in
smog. Reducing or eliminating MTBE, which adds octane for vehicle
starting power, could prompt refiners to add other, more toxic
ingredients to compensate.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, they pointed out that the most readily available
substitute for MTBE, a corn-derivative called ethanol, may actually
increase smog, according to the same National Research Council
study.
</P>
<P>
   ``My take home message from this report is we have to be careful
about what we put in gasoline. There is no single magic solution,''
said Daniel Greenbaum, chairman of the US Environmental Protection
Agency's blue ribbon panel investigating oxygenates. ``We need to
get to a place where we continue to get the benefits of
reformulated gas.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Research Council study comes amid mounting concern
from coast to coast about MTBE, one of two oxygenates that the
federal Clean Air Act requires as an ingredient in reformulated
gas. MTBE, or methyl tertiary butyl ether, causes cancer in lab
animals and, though its threat to humans is hotly debated, its
paint thinner odor can render water undrinkable.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the state of Maine has ordered MTBE levels sharply
reduced in its gas this summer, while California Gov. Gray Davis
plans to eliminate MTBE entirely by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, state regulators have taken no steps to
curtail MTBE, but the Department of Environmental Protection is
ordering all 1,500 public water suppliers in the state to begin
monitoring for the chemical. At least traces of MTBE have reached
53 public water supplies, requiring the closure of three and
treatment of a fourth.
</P>
<P>
   DEP assistant commissioner Arleen O'Donnell said the state
probably would not decide on MTBE's fate until late this year after
Greenbaum's panel and a New England-wide study of the issue are
closer to completion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to avoid this being a water versus air issue and make
this a `what's best for the environment issue?' '' said O'Donnell.
``Over the next six months, we'll have a lot more information to
make an informed decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The doubts now contrast with the hopes in 1995, when
reformulated gas, containing 11 to 14 percent MTBE, was introduced
at gas pumps across southern New England as well as the southern
portions of Maine and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We view it as the alternative fuel of the future that is ready
now,'' said Robert Mathey of Mobil, calling reformulated gas ``the
most cost-effective as well as the most environmentally attractive
way to reduce emissions.''
</P>
<P>
   Reformulated gas as a whole has worked much better than
expected, reducing toxic chemicals from tailpipes by 37 percent in
Boston, compared to a predicted 15 to 20 percent reduction.
</P>
<P>
   But as the National Research Council researchers looked at the
smog-fighting value of reformulated gasoline, they found that
little credit goes to MTBE or to ethanol, the oxygenate of choice
in places such as Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Smog-causing emissions from motor vehicles are declining,
Chameides said, ``but that's largely because of better emissions
control equipment and components of reformulated gasolines, other
than (MTBE or ethanol) that improve air quality.''
</P>
<P>
   Chameides said MTBE does reduce the amount of toxic benzene in
gas, but he said that was partly offset by new toxic chemicals from
burning MTBE. Moreover, he said, refiners can probably produce a
clean-burning gas that doesn't contain either MTBE or significant
benzene.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does seem that there are no air quality benefits exclusive
to oxygenates,'' said Jason Grumet of the Northeast States for
Coordinated Air Use Management, a Boston-based group studying MTBE
for New England's governors. ``It is unquestionably possible to
achieve the ozone benefits, the toxic benefits'' without MTBE or
ethanol.
</P>
<P>
   But Grumet warned that gas prices could jump by 10 cents a
gallon if MTBE were abruptly banned. If regulators allow four or
five years for a transition, he predicted refiners could produce a
reformulated gas without the MTBE threat or a big price hike.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
