<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: GOLDEN BEAR COMES BACK AS A `SOLID 4'
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Ohio, Pa.)  (rk) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONROE, N.Y. _ Jack Nicklaus is golf's Golden Bear and Steve
Pedersen, a 37-year-old retired New York City police sergeant, is a
7 handicap, but as they met for the first time Tuesday, they had
something in common: a hip replacement.
</P>
<P>
   And when the Golden Bear was on his way to hitting a ceremonial
tee shot opening the Golf Club at Mansion Ridge here Tuesday, the 7
handicap approached him for an autograph.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks for answering my note,'' Pedersen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks for sending it,'' Nicklaus said, signing a Masters
souvenir flag. ``How are you doing?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still a few pounds over,'' Pedersen said, patting his
tummy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm four or five over,'' Nicklaus said, patting his own tummy.
</P>
<P>
   In about 20 practice rounds since returning from Jan. 27 surgery
on his degenerative left hip, the 59-year-old Jack Nicklaus has
also been four or five over par more often than not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a solid 4 now,'' he said with a smile, alluding to what
his golf handicap would be if he were an amateur.
</P>
<P>
   But when was the last time that the best golfer in history, the
winner of a record 20 major titles, actually had a 4 handicap?
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was 12,'' he said. ``The next year, I got down to a
plus 3.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than four months after his surgery, Nicklaus spoke of
returning to tournament golf May 20 at the Senior PGA Tour's Bell
Atlantic Classic outside Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   On June 3 he will rejoin the PGA Tour at his Memorial tournament
at Muirfield Village near Columbus, Ohio, and on June 17 in
Pinehurst, N.C., he will tee off in the U.S. Open Championships for
the 42nd consecutive year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to expect too much of myself,'' he said. ``If I
shoot a 78, I shoot a 78.''
</P>
<P>
   When last seen in a tournament, Nicklaus limped to a
five-under-par 67 in the final round of last year's U.S. Senior
Open at Riviera, but he had soared to a 79 the day before.
</P>
<P>
   Hobbled by his ailing hip, he didn't enter last year's British
Open, ending his streak of consecutive major tournament appearances
at 154. He also skipped last year's PGA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't do this operation for golf,'' he has said. ``I did it
for quality of life, so that my wife, Barbara, didn't have to put
up with me having my hip dominating my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend at the Muirfield Village course he designed,
Nicklaus shot 81 on Friday, but on Sunday he had 71, hitting 15
greens in regulation and reaching the fringe of a par 5 in two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like a pussycat off the tee and a gorilla around the
greens,'' he said, joking. ``I'm not quite there, but I'm not that
far away.''
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged being bored by his 10-month layoff from
competition, the longest of his career. After a dismal 1979 season
when he didn't win a tournament, he ``touched the clubs three
times'' from after that year's PGA Championship to January.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that next year,'' he remembered, ``I had one of the best
years I ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   That year he won both the U.S. Open at Baltusrol and the PGA at
Oak Hill outside Rochester, one of six years in which he won two
majors. Not that he intends to be a regular on the PGA Tour or the
Senior PGA Tour now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to turn around and be a golfer again just
because I had hip surgery,'' he said. ``I've got other things to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   What he mostly does now is design golf courses. And now, up on
the first tee at Mansion Ridge, a hilly 6,889-yard course here in
Orange County and the first Jack Nicklaus-signature layout in New
York state, he was about to formally open the 172nd course he has
designed, co-designed or redesigned in 26 countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we do here,'' he told the 100 people assembled, ``is hit
the first tee shot. Do I get a mulligan?''
</P>
<P>
   As he slipped his left hand into a white glove, he held a
persimmon driver that will be mounted in the Mansion Ridge
clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing this with loafers on,'' he said. ``I don't have my
contacts in. I might not see the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   He took a couple of practice swings, then stepped up and hit the
tee shot, but when the ball veered into a fairway bunker, he took
his mulligan. This time, the ball soared far down the middle of the
fairway.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a little bit better,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But at the Bell Atlantic Classic, the Memorial and the U.S.
Open, not even Jack Nicklaus gets a mulligan.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
