<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERE'S HOPING FOR A REAL BABE IN `PHANTOM' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - You don't normally think of Carrie Fisher as a babe.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing wrong with that. She's a good actress. She's a funny
writer (see ``Postcards From the Edge'' for proof). As a bonus, she
was married to Paul Simon for about five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But even in her younger days, she never graced the covers of
magazines with a come-hither look and not much else, like the
ubiquitous Pamela Anderson prior to the removal of her implants.
That just wasn't her role.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there was that one bright, shining, fleshy moment when, for
``Star Wars'' fans everywhere, Carrie Fisher became a certified,
card-carrying babe.
</P>
<P>
   You know what I'm talking about. Near the beginning of ``Return
of the Jedi,'' Fisher, as Princess Leia, traded in those stupid
cinnamon-roll hair buns for a swirling metal bikini.
</P>
<P>
   It was a striking sight and about time _ it was the first
instance in any of the ``Star Wars'' movies that a woman was seen
in anything other than a glorified bathrobe. Fisher made enough of
an impression that, nearly 20 years later, she found herself in a
``Friends'' plot, with Ross, Chandler and Joey all admitting they
had lusted after her. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Hanging around with Hutt &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But we'll never know if Fisher looked so babealicious only
because she spent most of her time sprawled next to Jabba the Hutt.
You remember Jabba, the enormous intergalactic gangster who looked
like something you might find in the business end of a dirty
handkerchief.
</P>
<P>
   Next to him, Monica Lewinsky would look like Cindy Crawford.
Context is everything.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of which, there is also the audience to think of. The
babe barometer wasn't set on ``stunning'' for these guys. Your
classic ``Star Wars'' disciple _ the one who quoted Darth Vader
incessantly every time the chess club met and grew up to put a
JEDINI TE vanity plate on his Pacer _ didn't need Farrah Fawcett or
Cheryl Tiegs to get excited. Carrie Fisher or Darla Sue in Spanish
class _ what did it matter? Just another in a string of fantasies
you knew you weren't going to the prom with.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, babes were never the point of the ``Star Wars''
movies. Pseudoreligious nattering fortified with the occasional
science-fiction sword fight was. Girls? Yuck. Dude, get a load of
that lightsaber. (Sorry, Dr. Freud.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Waiting game &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As you probably know _ it's getting more media coverage than the
past three presidential administrations combined _ ``Star Wars:
Episode I _ The Phantom Menance'' opens in a week. We still don't
know exactly what three-headed monsters and assorted other cr
eatures we'll see. But enough information is out there to make a
somewhat-educated guess as to whether we'll have to wait until the
third movie of this trilogy to see a babe.
</P>
<P>
   It looks as if we won't. Right off the bat there is Queen
Amidala, played by Natalie Portman. She's beautiful enough
certainly. And if you're going to entice the future Darth Vader,
you've got to have something going for you.
</P>
<P>
   On the downside, like Leia, she's royalty, with all the modesty
that implies. How many years did it take the ``National Enquirer''
to get shots of Princess Diana in a bathing suit? Plus, in the
publicity photos, Amidala sports a hair helmet that would make Burt
Reynolds wince.
</P>
<P>
   Sigh. Did Leia teach us nothing?
</P>
<P>
   Shmi Skywalker, played by Pernilla August, should be a
non-factor. August is an attractive actress, but she's dowdied up
for the movie as you would expect Darth Vader's mother to be.
</P>
<P>
   The smart money is on Oola, a Twi'lek dancer played by Femi
Taylor. According to ``Playboy,'' she appears on-screen for only a
minute or so but makes such an impression in her barely there
costume that she has her own action figure.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, Oola's hairdo includes what looks like a pair of wayward
intestines growing out of her head. Not an attractive feature, but
when you compare her look with the rest of the offerings in ``The
Phantom Menace,'' she looks like the best babe candidate.
</P>
<P>
   If not, Darth Maul carries a double-edged lightsaber. The
disciples need something to slobber over. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach Bill Goodykoontz at bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
