<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CHINA-STUDENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAGE OVER EMBASSY BOMBING ABRUPTLY TRANSFORMS CHINESE CAMPUSES 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-CHINA) 
(bl) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Exactly 10 years ago, as protesters demonstrated in
Tiananmen Square, a small grassy triangle in the center of Beijing
University became a shrine to democracy, plastered with tracts
about liberty and freedom. In recent years it had become a temple
for the professions, filled with notices about computers and law
examinations.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last four days, the plaza has been transformed anew,
into a museum of frenzied nationalism and anti-American sentiment.
Hundreds of handwritten letters and posters decorate the fence, the
trees and nearby billboards in a vitriolic reaction to the bombing
of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Support Yugoslavia and Resist America,'' one poster read.
``Adolph Clinton,'' another read. A letter suggested that students
should cover the U.S. Embassy with garbage.
</P>
<P>
   A poem read, in part: ``Resist America Beginning with Cola,
Attack McDonald's, Storm KFC.''
</P>
<P>
   University students here led the angry and sometimes violent
protests at the U.S. Embassy over the bombing. With the
authorities' permission, the students have vented a nation's fury.
</P>
<P>
   But even after four days of nearly continuous demonstrations, it
is clear that there remains an extremely deep wellspring of angry
emotion on college campuses that could percolate for months or
years. This emotion, seems to be crystalizing into a burst of angry
nationalism.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrations have quickly become a formative experience
for college students, who are in some cases making dramatic life
decisions like forgoing overseas study based on their new views.
</P>
<P>
   Many students who cheered Michael Jordan last year and welcomed
President Clinton on his recent visit are lashing out at all things
American.
</P>
<P>
   At People's University on Sunday, several American students were
surrounded by a group of Chinese students who were screaming,
``Blood must be repaid with blood!''
</P>
<P>
   Westerners who were walking on the Beijing University campus
were subject to hard stares and impromptu lectures on imperialism.
Occasional anti-American taunts are tossed out of dormitory
windows.
</P>
<P>
   The scene is a jarring about-face at universities where two
months ago the highest achievement was to obtain a place at an
American graduate school. In some departments at Beijing
University, more than half the students have gone to the United
States after graduation in the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   A generation raised on rock music and Coca-Cola is experiencing
a complicated shift. ``Many of my classmate have been going through
their things and planning to burn all American products, at least
those they can do without,'' said a 22-year-old marketing major at
Beijing University, who like many of those interviewed would not
give her full name.
</P>
<P>
   Some students said they worried that rash actions now could
haunt China for years. ``There's is a tone of irrational extremism,
and people aren't thinking clearly about what they think and
write,'' said Yu Jie, a popular liberal essayist who is a graduate
student at the university. ``I think this will have a very bad
effect on the economic, social and cultural development of China.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Saturday, the universities here have sent busloads of
students to the U.S. Embassy area. On campuses, students talk of
little else, and they have organized accompanying on-campus study
sessions and protest rallies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I protested because I'm extremely outraged at this trampling
on the dignity of the Chinese people,'' said Chen Wanyi, 20, who
marched last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Although many students opposed the rock throwing that has
battered the embassy, they said they understood why it had
occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the protest looked extreme,'' said Lin Yijin, a
trendily dressed 28-year-old journalism student at People's
University, who protested on Saturday and Sunday. ``But I think
compared to what we were responding to, it was pretty restrained,
just bottles and rocks and things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Students said they believed that the United States had
intentionally bombed the embassy in Belgrade, although few
explained why Washington might have wanted to do that.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike average Chinese, who can see only state-controlled media,
the elite university students generally have Internet access. They
read Clinton's expressions of regret and the NATO explanation, both
of which the students dismissed as unbelievable or inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   At the Beijing University triangle, students have posted a full
English transcript of the NATO news conference in which officials
first explained the bombing. It is covered with comments like
``pure lies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Chinese are furious, and although we've now heard the
apologies, we still feel that the response from NATO and the United
States has been superficial,'' a senior said. ``If you'd seen the
pictures of the three corpses, you'd understand why.''
</P>
<P>
   Although a number of students said they continued to feel
friendly toward the American people, they were keeping their
distance for now. Students said they were boycotting American
products. The usually bustling McDonald's and Pizza Hut restaurants
stood mostly empty Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give up the poison of American-style fast food and cultural
opium _ Coca-Cola, Pepsi, McDonald's, KFC,'' read a poster on the
triangle.
</P>
<P>
   A Dairy Queen store near the protests was closed, and a
Baskin-Robbins store was also closed, hiding its sign under red
cloth and placing banners that said ``Down With Imperialism'' on
its doors.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-American atmosphere is so intense that some students
said they were contemplating whether to continue English classes,
take jobs with U.S. companies or pursue hard-won acceptances to
Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   Many are clearly torn between the moment's anger and pragmatism.
Some said the protest groups were probably smaller than usual
Tuesday because students were busying cramming for a national
English test Wednesday and standardized tests this weekend that are
required for U.S. graduate schools.
</P>
<P>
   A group of students at the National Minorities University in
Beijing said it wanted to go to Yugoslavia to join the army, and it
has posted fliers on other campuses urging others to join.
</P>
<P>
   But a number of students who strongly support the protests said
the excesses frightened them. ``Are we still in the revolutionary
era?'' an essay posted on a wall at People's University asked.
``Must we answer barbarity with barbarity?''
</P>
<P>
   Jiao Li, 20, a student at the Beijing Transport Technology
College, said: ``I think this is a passing thing when students are
inflamed with patriotism and very emotional. So it's natural for
now to respond by not drinking Coke, for example. But I don't think
that refusing to work for an American firm will solve any
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Students said the anger would fade slowly and only if NATO and
the United States offered acceptable apologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the Chinese want is an explanation and an apology that
will restore our dignity'' Lin Yijin said. ``I wouldn't take the
stuff about `Blood for blood' and `Attack NATO' too seriously. For
us, this is about saving face.''
</P>
</TEXT>
