A3018 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-GOLF-REPORT-TEX     05-11 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLF-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUVAL-WOODS: MADE FOR TV, AND TROUBLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Disregard the dialogue, which could have been scripted by Don
King, and listen to the background noise.
</P>
<P>
   There it is, that persistent squeaking sound. The one that keeps
being drowned out by the voices of Tiger Woods, David Duval and ABC
officials trumpeting an Aug. 2 shootout between the world's
top-ranked golfers.
</P>
<P>
   Do you hear it?
</P>
<P>
   I do, even if PGA Tour officials choose to turn a deaf ear.
That's the sound of Pandora's box. The lid is creaking open, and
anything could come spilling out.
</P>
<P>
   Anything, it seems, except a meaningful meeting between Woods
and Duval at a real, live PGA Tour event.
</P>
<P>
   The two have not played in the same tournament since the Masters
and will not hook up in Fort Worth-Dallas over the next two weeks
despite a combined $5.8 million being laid on the table by
organizers of the GTE Byron Nelson Classic and MasterCard Colonial.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Woods will tee up tomorrow in the first round of the
Nelson. Duval will play next week at Colonial. But their paths may
not converge again until the season's next major championship, at
the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   Don't blame that on sheer happenstance or bad timing. Look,
instead, at the agency that represents both players: International
Management Group.
</P>
<P>
   It is IMG that is organizing the Aug. 2 exhibition match, the
first of its kind to be telecast live in prime time. It is IMG, in
conjunction with ABC, that stands to reap substantial profits if
this bit of creative programming outperforms summer reruns in its
appointed, Monday time slot.
</P>
<P>
   It is IMG, in short, that benefits by keeping Woods and Duval
apart as much as humanly possible to maximize suspense and ratings
for an IMG-arranged ``shootout.'' Hmmmmm. Ever think ``that'' may
be the reason Duval backed out of the Nelson and Woods will bolt
for Germany during Colonial week?
</P>
<P>
   The PGA Tour has given its blessing to this exhibition, in large
part, because $200,000 of the $1.5 million purse will be donated to
the tour's First Tee Project, which introduces golf to inner-city
youth. Yet in doing so, is the tour cutting its own throat in the
long run?
</P>
<P>
   After charitable contributions are deducted, the winner of the
Woods-Duval shootout will pocket $900,000. By comparison, a golfer
would have to win both the Nelson and Colonial to earn $900,000 at
PGA Tour events in Fort Worth-Dallas this season. And his chances
of doing so would be far less than 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Little wonder, then, that Woods already is pushing for more of
these cushy, IMG-sponsored exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to see it become a series, where we could have
more special events like this,'' Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   Such a series should make PGA Tour officials squirm. The game's
elite players need more incentive, not less, to play events like
the Nelson and Colonial.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Houseman, president of the Salesmanship Club and a
two-time Nelson tournament chairman, foresees the potential for a
day when players build their schedules around a handful of
high-dollar exhibitions, the four majors and the four World Golf
Championship events. Unless forced to do otherwise, elite players
won't have to compete more than 10 times a year at PGA Tour events.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that doesn't happen, but the concern is there,''
Houseman said.
</P>
<P>
   The Woods-Duval exhibition should heighten such concerns. The
lid to Pandora's box is open wider than ever.
</P>
<P>
   SPOTLIGHT ON ... Dennis' 3-year-old son already following Tiger
</P>
<P>
   With any luck, Fort Worth resident Clark Dennis will be paired
with Tiger Woods during one of the weekend rounds at the Nelson.
That way, Dennis can get a feel for how he's doing in attempts to
follow the golf advice of his son, Will.
</P>
<P>
   The two were watching a PGA Tour telecast this season when Will
Dennis, 3, asked his flu-stricken father if he had played in the
tournament being shown on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `Yeah, I played. But I wasn't feeling good and I
missed the cut,' '' Dennis said.
</P>
<P>
   Unmoved by his father's wheezing and sniffling, the toddler
offered an impromptu pep talk that Dennis has taken to heart
heading into consecutive starts at the Nelson and MasterCard
Colonial (May 20-23).
</P>
<P>
   ``Will stands up, puts his hands on his hips and says, `Dad,
you're supposed to put it in the hole, like Tiger do,' '' Dennis
said. ``I was floored. I didn't even know he knew who Tiger was.
But now, that's my goal for this year: to put it in the hole like
Tiger do.''
CHIP SHOTS
Back for seconds
</P>
<P>
   Paul Earnest, club pro at Four Seasons Resort and Club, is
competing in his second consecutive Nelson, this time by the grace
of a sponsor's exemption. He said lessons learned at the 1998
Nelson and 1998 PGA Championship should help this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having done this before, I think I'll have my emotions better
under control than last year,'' said Earnest, who missed the cut in
both 1998 events. ``That should help me more than anything. I know
I'll have to play well just to make the cut and that's my goal.''
Special exemption
</P>
<P>
   Esteban Toledo fell short of earning a berth in the MasterCard
Colonial by missing the cut at last week's Compaq Classic of New
Orleans and dropping to 92nd on the money list. The top 80 earn
automatic Colonial invitations.
</P>
<P>
   But the former boxer will be competing in Fort Worth because of
a sponsor's exemption, the first he has received at a PGA Tour
event in a career that began in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've written hundreds of letters, asking for them,'' said
Toledo, 36. ``To have someone finally say `yes' ... That tournament
is going to be so special for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo showed his gratitude by volunteering to be host of the
tournament's youth clinic at 4:15 p.m. Tuesday on the club's
driving range.
Colonial Shootout update
</P>
<P>
   MasterCard Colonial officials have received commitments from
seven of 12 golfers who are scheduled to compete in two-man teams
during Tuesday's Colonial Shootout.
</P>
<P>
   Confirmed competitors, said club officials, include Fort Worth
resident Mark Brooks, Davis Love III, Justin Leonard, Jeff Sluman,
Billy Andrade and Tom Watson, the defending Colonial champ. Six
two-man teams will compete on the course's back-nine holes,
beginning at 2 p.m.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
