<HEADER>
A3033 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSE-HASTERT-ART-2TA     05-11 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-HASTERT-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE REPUBLICANS PLEASED WITH HASTERT'S DELIBERATE, LOW-KEY
APPROACH
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo of Hastert is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Five months after he was tapped as the accidental
speaker, Dennis Hastert has turned out to be just what most House
Republicans want: nearly invisible.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of charging the ideological ramparts like his immediate
predecessor, the electric and polarizing Newt Gingrich, Hastert, a
57-year-old, bear-like former high school wrestling coach, limits
his public appearances mostly to business groups or schools, where
he is prone to bland comments like: ``What we need to do is we need
to listen to kids.''
</P>
<P>
   He is praised by House members for keeping his promises,
although they acknowledge that is because he rarely makes any. In a
telling touch Hastert has relegated to extinction the most obvious
symbol of Gingrich's quirky eccentricity _ the replica of a
Tyrannosaurus rex head that had dominated one of the speaker's
conference rooms. A set of portraits of Abraham Lincoln has gone up
in its place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to get back on track,'' Hastert, an Illinois
Republican, said in an interview. ``After the impeachment stuff we
needed to get America's house back to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Slumped in a chair, he spoke mordantly for a moment of the
``sobering influence'' on fractious House Republicans of last
November's election losses that allowed them to ``look over the
grave's edge and see their name on the casket.''
</P>
<P>
   So instead of bombarding Congress with sweeping new agendas like
Gingrich, Hastert, from Illinois, prefers to stick to the basics
like passing a budget and spending bills on time. He is also
seeking to limit the number of issues that could lead to
destructive divisions among Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   He is so self-effacing that Democrats in search of a new foil to
replace Gingrich charge that House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, of
Texas, really runs the House. Republicans maintain that DeLay, a
passionate conservative who fueled the impeachment drive against
President Clinton, has a strong influence through his long
friendship with Hastert, who had previously been DeLay's chief
deputy whip. But they say Hastert is charting his own course.
</P>
<P>
   The last American politician who tried to make a virtue out of
``normalcy'' was Warren G. Harding, who did not go down in history
as one of the nation's most notable presidents. It is a sign,
however, of just how chastened and wary the House Republicans are
this session that most praise their new leader precisely for his
low-key solidity.
</P>
<P>
   They call Hastert the right man for a year they describe as a
holding action as they await a presidential nominee to lead the
party. The goal, says Rep. Joe Scarborough, R-Fla., who was elected
in the Republican Revolution of 1994, is to ``do no harm.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Hastert is not a lightening rod like Gingrich.
``There's a general feeling in the Republican conference that the
Denny Hastert style is working,'' said Rep. Peter King, R-N.Y.
``Not trying to be showboating, not trying to be dramatic, just
being solid.''
</P>
<P>
   Some restless Republicans are starting to wonder whether their
new leader is too low key. They question whether Hastert is willing
to take any risks at all, as he tries to manage the House with one
of the smallest majorities this century. It is a question that
could have a significant bearing on how a host of issues play out,
from an overhaul of the Social Security and Medicare programs, to
tax cutting to revision of the campaign finance laws.
</P>
<P>
   And it was underscored by the way the speaker chose to handle a
recent House debate on the war in Yugoslavia, staying silent
through the day-long proceedings as DeLay worked the floor against
a resolution sponsored by Democrats to support the air war. The
measure failed on a 213-213 tie, with Hastert voting at the very
last moment on the losing side. Only 30 other Republicans voted
with him.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert has since told Republicans that he made a mistake and
should have voted early to signal his belief that the air war
should be supported.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Dick Gephart, who hopes to win back the
House in 2000, immediately charged that ``the extreme right wing of
the Republican Party remains in control of that party.''
</P>
<P>
   But many Republicans say they were pleased that Hastert allowed
them to vote as they wished. One House Republican who asked not to
be identified said that the intense dislike for Clinton within the
House GOP caucus had only intensified after the impeachment effort,
and that the majority of Republicans were determined to make Kosovo
``Clinton's war.'' He contended that if Hastert had tried to round
up support for the air war, he ``would have created a rebellion.''
</P>
<P>
   And rebellions are what House Republicans are trying to avoid.
``We have a five vote margin,'' Hastert said. ``Any time that you
move five moderates or five conservatives so you don't have them
any more, you can't get anything done.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Hastert still makes it clear that he never wanted to be speaker.
He calls December 19 _ the day he became the consensus replacement
for Robert L. Livingston of Louisiana, the speaker-designee who
resigned after the disclosure that he had had an extramarital
affair _ a ``day of infamy.'' Asked if he has come to like his
position of power, he said tartly, ``I'm reserving judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Because Hastert had served as DeLay's chief deputy before
becoming speaker, some questioned how independent he would be of
the hard-driving whip who helped push the impeachment effort. But
even moderate Republicans who dislike DeLay's politics say DeLay is
not in control.
</P>
<P>
   ``If DeLay has some vehement opposition, it slows the process
down and you have to work to convince the speaker,'' said one House
member who did not want to be identified. ``But he has gone his own
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert, for example, was the one who made the decision to go
ahead with the Kosovo debate. Senior Republican aides said DeLay
had thought the party would be better off avoiding a debate and
allowing Clinton alone to be responsible for how the war comes out.
Delay also would hold off any vote on campaign finance as long as
possible, whereas Hastert is listening to moderate Republicans who
want a quick vote.
</P>
<P>
   Of his relationship with DeLay, Hastert said, ``We've been
fairly close. My nature is different from him. Tom is kind of
energetic and knee-jerk on a lot of things, and I'm a little more
laid-back and at least outside, of a little calmer countenance.''
</P>
<P>
   He said they can be candid with each other and discuss issues,
``but you know, I'm going to do what I think is right.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides his staff and leadership team, Hastert also relies on a
kitchen cabinet of advisers. Among them, aides say, are Daniel J.
Matoon, a lobbyist for BellSouth; Bill Pitts, a lobbyist for Walt
Disney who was once a senior aide to Robert Michel of Illinois, the
Republican minority leader in the Bush administration; Rep. Thomas
W. Ewing , a fellow Illinois Republican; and Bill Paxon, a former
congressman from upstate New York now with the powerhouse
Washington law and lobbying firm, Akin, Gump, Strauss, Hauer &AMP;
Feld.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say Hastert is a listener. He often checks out the
House floor so that he is easily approachable. He goes to informal
gatherings of House members like the Thursday prayer breakfasts.
</P>
<P>
   When bills come to the floor, Hastert allows House members to
make far more attempts to amend them than was common under
Gingrich. That allows them to see if they really have any support
for their positions and to blow off steam. He has also tried to
keep the agenda as free as he can of anything that can split
Republicans _ such as a Social Security overhaul which he says he
will only consider if there is a bipartisan agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's going to do everything in his power to minimize
the number of bills that divide moderates from conservatives,''
said one House Republican who did not want to be identified. ``The
key is to get some solid _ but very few _ accomplishments to get us
beyond the label of a do-nothing Congress and keep us united.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert has focused most intensely on a few basics. For only the
second time in 20 years, the House and Senate enacted a budget on
time by April 15. Republicans also passed a bill to give states
more flexibility in using federal education funds, which they
believe will help them fend off Democratic attacks on education.
They hope to unify around a tax cut plan this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some Republicans _ and certainly the Democrats _ are
starting to bristle at the minimalist agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Moderate Republicans are weighing whether to go around the
speaker and work with Democrats to try to force a campaign finance
bill to the floor through a special discharge petition.
</P>
<P>
   And Rep. Mark Foley, R-Fla., said he would like to see his party
become more aggressive on Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think we have to fill the next 12 months before the
nominees are up and running with some substance,'' he said.
``Social Security and Medicare are the two primary issues most
American are anxious to have discussed.''
</P>
<P>
   Hastert continues to juggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is to return a Republican majority,'' he said. ``I'm
going to do the best job I can day in and day out and let the chips
fall.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
