<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3036 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CHINA-NYT &LR;      05-11 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CHINA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE LEADERS MEET WITH MOSCOW ENVOY; PROTESTS START TO SHRINK 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-CHINA-STUDENTS) 
(bl) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Russia's special envoy on the Kosovo crisis, Victor
Chernomyrdin, met with China's top leaders to discuss the issue
Tuesday as rage continued to boil here in response to the
accidental NATO attack on the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Russia and China have been the strongest international critics
of the NATO bombing campaign in Yugoslavia, and they are seeking to
develop closer ties overall.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief news conference Tuesday, Chernomyrdin said the two
countries agreed that talks in the United Nations to create an
international intervention force for Kosovo must be preceded by a
halt to the bombing _ a precondition that NATO has rejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear that first it is necessary to stop the bombing and
then to conduct negotiations,'' Chernomyrdin said.
</P>
<P>
   But Russia is also anxious to play the role of peacemaker, and
hopes to advance the proposal it worked out with the top seven
industrial nations last week in which an armed force under United
Nations auspices would enter Kosovo as Yugoslav troops withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   One goal of the Russian envoy, who met in Beijing with President
Jiang Zemin, Prime Minister Zhu Rongji and Deputy Prime Minister
Qian Qichen, appeared to be to gain China's support for the general
approach of the so-called Group of Eight plan. As a permanent
member of the Security Council, China will have to agree to the
creation of any U.N. force.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin hinted at progress toward at least this goal. ``The
Chinese side is studying the proposals of the Group of Eight,'' he
said. ``They agree that the decision by the Group of Eight could be
the basis for future negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   But Chinese accounts of the meetings did not mention the Group
of Eight plan by name, only emphasizing China's demand for an
immediate halt to the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   As the leaders met, noisy demonstrations in another part of
Beijing continued to paralyze the U.S. Embassy. By government order
to universities and other state-run institutions, affected people
say, the huge demonstrations of previous days have been greatly
scaled back.
</P>
<P>
   But still, every half hour or so during daylight hours Tuesday,
approved student groups, often joined by hangers-on, were being
guided by the police past the British and U.S. Embassies, where the
marchers chant slogans such as ``Down with Clinton'' and ``We Want
a Full Apology.''
</P>
<P>
   The television and newspapers finally reported Tuesday that
President Clinton, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and other
NATO leaders had apologized for the embassy bombing. But many
people here described the gestures as inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, National Security Council spokesman David Leavy
said Tuesday that the White House was preparing a letter for the
Chinese government explaining in detail how the United States
mistakenly hit the embassy in Belgrade. The document is expected to
be sent to Beijing within 48 hours, Leavy said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the letter would essentially restate the explanation
provided by the Pentagon on Monday that attributed the bombing to
``institutional error'' of those drawing up targeting maps for air
strikes _ as opposed to human error or mechanical failure. The
document will assure the Chinese that the attack was a mistake and
will not happen again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese certainly deserve to hear what happened, just as
the American people do,'' Leavy said.
</P>
<P>
   In Beijing on Tuesday, along the route to the U.S. Embassy,
plastic sheeting was used to protect the concrete blocks of the
sidewalk, which protesters had been cracking up to make their
projectiles. Tuesday afternoon, as a contingent of 300 from the
Medical University approached the embassy, police shouted, ``Throw
down your rocks'' and took several out of protester's hands.
</P>
<P>
   Many members of this and other groups still smuggled rocks by,
though, and the already shattered and paint-spattered facade of the
embassy was repeatedly pummeled.
</P>
<P>
   After dark, the time of the most violent protests in previous
days, the police did not allow any demonstrators to enter the
embassy district. When one impatient crowd tried to charge past the
police, a few leaders were detained, and witnesses saw at least one
of them being beaten and kicked by the police.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Ambassador James Sasser, along with two other diplomats,
eight marines and two security officers, remained holed up in the
embassy, where they have been since Saturday. Although conditions
appeared less dangerous, the ambassador has declared he will not
leave until it is clearly safe to come and go at will.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Embassy announced that it would lower its flags to half
staff for 24 hours beginning Wednesday morning, when the ashes of
the three people killed by the bomb attack on the Chinese Embassy
in Belgrade are scheduled to arrive in Beijing. This is intended
``as a sign of respect,'' said Bill Palmer, an embassy spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Funeral plans have not been announced for the three who were
killed _ Shao Yunhuan, a 48-year-old reporter from the official New
China News Agency; Xu Xinghu, 31, a reporter for the Guangming
Daily newspaper, and his wife Zhu Ying, who worked in the
advertising department of the same newspaper. Six Chinese who were
seriously injured and 20 more with light injuries will return on
the same plane Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting the wave of antipathy toward things American,
theaters throughout China have been ordered to stop showing
American films, according to press reports.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, there is evidence that Chinese leaders do not
want to jeopardize foreign trade and investment. The New China News
Agency reported on meetings Tuesday between the chairman of
Motorola Inc., a major investor in China, and the mayor and the
Communist Party chief of the city of Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
   The press account said the two officials reassured Motorola
chairman Gary Tooker that anger over the embassy attack ``would not
affect Tianjin's resolve and policies to open to the outside
world.'' The officials ``pledged to support an expansion of the
friendly ties with Motorola.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
