u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-MAIN12-COX     05-11 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MAIN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton's Atlanta visit showcases downtown market
 &HT;    By Carlos Campos
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For two hours Tuesday, President Bill Clinton acted
like head cheerleader for a pep rally in support of Atlanta's
efforts at urban renewal, while charming the vendors in the Sweet
Auburn Curb Market and praising their entrepreneurial spirit.
</P>
<P>
   The president heaped praise on the city's work to improve
inner-city neighborhoods suffering from years of blight and
neglect. He brought together a handful of local residents and
business people at the Curb Market to listen to their success
stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important that we try to take this example to the
whole nation,'' Clinton said of Atlanta's efforts. ``I believe we
ought not to leave anybody behind when we go into the 21st century.
I want people to see you and believe it can be done in their
neighborhoods.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton used the brief Atlanta trip to push his ``new markets''
initiative now before Congress, which he announced during his State
of the Union address in January.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton flew to Atlanta with a planeload of national executives
from American Airlines, Goldman Sachs, Aetna, AT&AMP;T Wireless,
Bankers Trust, Delta Airlines, AFLAC, BellSouth and others.
</P>
<P>
   Encouraging businesses and financial institutions to invest in
depressed communities during the current economic boom is part of
the president's new initiative.
</P>
<P>
   The downtown market was selected as the backdrop for the
president's visit because it has benefitted from $4.9 million in
federal loans which have helped refurbish the once-flagging
facility.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton held an informal chat session with local business
people, including Jason Slaughter, president and CEO of
International Food Specialties, Sallie Daniel, a vice-president
with NationsBank, Ken Blakely of the Centennial Olympic Park Area,
John Aderhold of Aderhold Properties, Sonya Jones and Vivian Reid,
shop owners in the Curb Market, and Tricia Donegan, a co-owner of
Eureka, a new restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sister and I and her husband started the business a year
and a half ago,'' Reid told the president. ``It's been growing
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton sipped from a cup of Cameroon Boyo coffee he was given
at the coffee shop where Reid works as he listened to each person's
story.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell, at Clinton's side throughout his
visit, said he was proud the president chose Atlanta as an example.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is a validation of the success that we've had,
not only in the Empowerment Zone, but also in revitalizing other
parts of our city that are not in the zone itself,'' Campbell said.
``Our unemployment is the lowest it's been in years, job creation's
the highest, construction building permits are a record, people are
moving back into the city, crime rates going down. I think it's a
city that's a great success story in large part because of the
partnership with this administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's Empowerment Zone was established under a 1994, $250
million Clinton administration program to seed economic growth in
disadvantaged neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell accepted a last minute invitation from Clinton to
return to Washington on Air Force One to help the president push
some anti-crime legislation pending before Congress, Campbell Press
Secretary Nick Gold said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's appearance at the Curb Market caused an exciting buzz
at the market among the vendors, many craning their necks over a
mob of reporters to get a view of the president.
</P>
<P>
   Jones delivered on her promise to send the president back to
Washington with a sweet potato cheesecake, one of her specialties.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also accepted a bite of cheesecake Jones offered while
he visited her Sweet Auburn Bread Company. ``Boy, that's great,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   At a produce stand, the Korean owners Joy Choi and Chung Park
said they were so excited to shake hands with the president, they
forgot to give him something.
</P>
<P>
   ``We prepared a fruit basket, but we forgot that one,'' Park
said. ``Too excited.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point during the tour, Clinton stopped before reporters
with a bag full of kaolin _ a clay that is mined heavily in Georgia
_ he was given at one booth.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys know what this is?'' the president said. ``This is
kaolin. It's the stuff Kaopectate is made of.''
</P>
<P>
   The president kidded with reporters about the unique regional
offerings at the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you guys see the cow's ears and pig's feet back there?''
he said. Clinton then told a story of how Russian President Boris
Yeltsin once cut the ear off of a roasted pig and said ``If I was a
real friend of Russia, I'd eat it.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Campos writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
