<SLUG> BC-MA-MCAS-HELP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE WANTS TO OFFER MCAS HELP BY NEXT YEAR, PEYSER SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOREEN IUDICA VIGUE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Board of Education chairman James A. Peyser hopes that
by next year the state panel will be able to help rescue school
districts that do poorly on the state's MCAS exam.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking Tuesday at a luncheon with Globe editors and reporters,
Peyser said the board is working on a way to inspect and evaluate
schools that fail the controversial competency test, with some
consequences attached.
</P>
<P>
   He said student data would be used to track improvements and
evaluate districts that are not performing well. An ``evaluation
team'' of rating specialists would examine why the students failed,
and how much the school was at fault.
</P>
<P>
   Once the team determines the root of the problem, then the board
would decide if the school or school district requires remedial or
punitive action.
</P>
<P>
   Peyser, who was appointed to the Board of Education by Governor
Paul Cellucci in March, also said he expects the failure rate for
the current round of MCAS testing _ which resumes with the
multiple-choice segment next week _ to be about 20 percent, the
same as last year.
</P>
<P>
   In an hourlong discussion that touched on a wide range of
education issues, Peyser reiterated his support of testing for
veteran teachers, noted he would like to see the cap lifted on
charter schools, and said he would be closely monitoring the
success or failure of the statewide school voucher system recently
approved in Florida. Peyser favors vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   Peyser said he would like to see the board approve charters that
``embody excellence'' and can prove in their charter proposals
precisely how that will be achieved.
</P>
<P>
   In discussing the Littleton, Colo., school tragedy, Peyser said
educators need to pay more attention to the cultures of schools and
to work to create school identities and mission statements that are
more inclusive. He said he does not think placing metal detectors
or police officers in schools are good ideas, unless they are a
last resort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schools should be communities and not institutions that you
pass through,'' said Peyser, executive director of the Pioneer
Institute, a conservative think tank. ``Knowing and establishing
the culture of a school seems to be one answer to the problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
