A3040 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SIDE-COX     05-11 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Supporters, critics of president line streets of AtlantaBy Alan
Judd
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ James Washington remembers when drug dealers and
prostitutes roamed his neighborhood and crowds gathered only when
the young victims of serial killer Wayne Williams were brought to
the nearby medical examiner's office.
</P>
<P>
   So Washington, 52, was especially gratified Tuesday not just by
President Clinton's visit to Sweet Auburn, but also by what it
signified _ the economic rebirth of a once-blighted part of
downtown Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really a bad area,'' Washington said, leaning on his
cane as he waited for a glimpse of the president leaving the Sweet
Auburn Curb Market at Butler Street and Edgewood Avenue. ``You
wouldn't see a police officer after 10 o'clock at night.... (But)
I'm really enjoying this. It shows some heart for him to come down
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington was among the several hundred people who waited in
the hot sun outside the market for two hours while Clinton was
inside extolling economic development in inner cities and rural
areas. Some pulled their children out of school to stand outside,
and one 17-year-old patient at Hughes Spalding Children's Hospital
who hoped to see Clinton came outside hooked to three IVs; neither
she nor her nurse would give their names.
</P>
<P>
   Most said they appreciated the president's visit. But many
complained that they were allowed to see little more than the
president's car speed past. A few people brought placards
protesting the NATO bombing of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Security was tight, with city dump trucks and MARTA buses
forming makeshift blockades at several intersections and police
officers and Secret Service agents keeping onlookers at least half
a block from the market. Because of security concerns, the closest
Clinton came to making a public appearance was on the tarmac at
Hartsfield International Airport, where he greeted 10 AmeriCorps
and VISTA volunteers, telling them, ``You folks remind me why I
want to be president.''
</P>
<P>
   But at Sweet Auburn, Clinton didn't even step outside to wave to
the crowd, and a white canvas tent shielded his limousine from view
as he entered and left the market's back door.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really horrible,'' Rogena Nealy said as she stretched
over a police barricade to peek at Clinton's motorcade from
Coca-Cola Place, almost a block away. ``But with them bombing the
Chinese embassy in Belgrade, I can understand the security for our
president. This is a very hostile time for the president of the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   A few in the crowd shared the hostility. Jack Jersawitz, a
socialist activist who ran for mayor of Atlanta in 1997, brought a
sign that read, ``Try and hang terrorist Clinton. Victory to
Yugoslavia.'' Another protestor, Diane Mathiowetz, carried a
bullhorn and several hand-lettered posters, including one that
identified NATO as ``New American Terrorist Organization.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody like to hold a sign against the war in Yugoslavia?''
Mathiowetz called out to the crowd, but few responded. Marialice
Haufe, a senior from Georgia State University who later identified
herself as a Clinton supporter, spotted the NATO poster and said,
``Oh, I like that one,'' and lifted it above her head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't come specifically to hold a sign,'' Haufe said. ``But
I like to follow political figures around whenever they show up. If
you're going to be out in the crowd, why not hold up a sign and
express your opinion?''
</P>
<P>
   It was unlikely, though, that Clinton saw much more of the
onlookers than they saw of him. The motorcade traveled over just a
few hundred yards of surface streets off the Downtown Connector,
and he was gone from Sweet Auburn in an instant.
</P>
<P>
   Just seeing the car, though, was enough for James Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw it move,'' he said moments after Clinton left. ``It was
the highlight of my day.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Judd writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga. Gary Hendricks contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
