<HEADER>
A3042 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VALUJET-COX     05-11 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VALUJET-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Families of ValuJet crash victims gather to dedicate site
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE EVERGLADES, Fla._They gathered near this lonely spot three
years ago, numb from shock and loss, trying to comprehend how their
loved ones could've perished aboard the doomed jetliner.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, they came back again to dedicate a memorial to the dead
from ValuJet Flight 592, quietly laying 110 roses at the base of a
solemn memorial overlooking the vast plain of sawgrass where the
jet went down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's peaceful,'' said Eunice Dowd of Douglasville, Ga., whose
sister, Angie Green of Nashville, Tenn., died aboard the plane.
``At first I thought the memorial looked kind of stark and lonely,
but as you walk through it, it's nice. The peace is nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Peace has not come easily to many of the victims' families.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-bound DC-9, flying on Mother's Day, 1996, filled
with smoke shortly after taking off from Miami International
Airport. The crew fought for several minutes to bring the crippled
aircraft back around for an emergency landing in Miami, but a
furious blaze from improperly-packed oxygen cannisters in the
forward cargo hold sent the plane plunging earthward at more than
400 mph.
</P>
<P>
   The victims' families were left with troubling questions about
the discount airline's safety record, as well as the work of
government inspectors and regulators who oversaw it. ValuJet has
since disappeared, transformed into AirTran, another discount
operation with a heavy presence in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the troubling questions, the families were left with
a terrible void in their grief_no bodies to cry over, visit and
bury.
</P>
<P>
   Teams of rescue workers combed through the watery muck for
weeks, but the impact of the crash was so great they found only
scattered remains of the 110 victims. There were only scattered
belongings, too_a tennis shoe here, a scrap of clothing there.
</P>
<P>
   The crash site is about 20 miles west of the Miami airport,
about eight miles north of U.S. 41, a two-lane asphalt strip that
splits the Everglades on its way west to Naples.
</P>
<P>
   Days after the crash, some of the stricken families were taken
in buses down a bumpy levee to within a few hundred yards of the
actual crash site, which is accessible only by boat.
</P>
<P>
   For many, that was as close as they came to having a physical
place to fix in their minds for memories of their lost loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   Until Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We finally have a place to come to,'' said Amanda Myers of
Albany, N.Y., whose parents, Conway and Anna Laurie Hamilton of
Miami, died on the plane as they flew to their granddaughter's
graduation from Atlanta's Emory University. ``This is where they
are.''
</P>
<P>
   The memorial sits atop a levee overlooking the distant crash
site. It consists of 110 cement columns topped by four-sided
pyramids, arranged in a triangle facing north toward the crash
site.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me the design is an allegory for the rise of the victims'
souls and the fall of the fateful plane,'' said Lee Sawyer, Myers'
sister.
</P>
<P>
   Architectural students from the University of Miami designed the
memorial, working with the families. Most of the materials and
labor were donated, with students helped by master craftsmen from
local unions. They spent most weekends for the past several months
completing their work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means no one will ever forget,'' said Jane Lathem of
Alpharetta, Ga., whose son, Ray, died aboard the plane with other
members of Mount Pisgah United Methodist Church as they returned
from a mission trip to Latin America. ``This will always be here to
remind people of what happened to our loved ones.''
</P>
<P>
   The family members have formed a group to lobby for safer
airlines, sometimes joining with relatives of victims from other
crashes. Many still have civil lawsuits pending, and many hope the
federal government will conduct a criminal investigation of the
crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an on-going issue with the families,'' said Richard
Kessler, an Atlanta lawyer who lost his wife, Kathleen. ``There is
legislation in Congress now called a `passenger's bill of rights,'
but nowhere in that is there a statement saying the first priority
is to get the passengers safely to their destination.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with those frustrations, the families struggle to cope
with their losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still the same anger and sorrow you felt the first day,''
said Patrice Bowman of Miami, who lost her fiance, Robert Woodus
Jr., in the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Eight months after the crash, Bowman gave birth to Woodus' son,
Robert III. On Tuesday, she fought back tears as the toddler
carried a peach-colored rose to the memorial in honor of the father
he never knew.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so hard,'' she said. ``But I look at it that I lost
something, but I was also left with a special gift, our son.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Williams writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
