<HEADER>
A3045 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CREDIT-ART-NYT &LR;      05-11 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FEAR AND NERVOUSNESS' IN BOND MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Thirty-year bond chart is being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Long-term interest rates, which have been rising
steadily since early April, jumped to their highest level in almost
a year Tuesday as investors continued to worry about inflation and
the next meeting of Federal Reserve policy-makers on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The failure of the U.S. economy to slow down significantly and a
reminder last week from Alan Greenspan, the Fed chairman, that
inflation could become a problem again, have spooked investors, at
least for the time being.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of fear and nervousness in the market at this
juncture,'' said Thomas Connor, head government trader at J.P.
Morgan Securities. This is not because investors expect a surge in
inflation this year or even that the Fed will raise interest rates
next week. Instead, they are nervous because they have to wait for
new inflation data and the Fed meeting before they can determine
whether the recent rise in long-term interest rates has been
overdone, in part because of Greenspan's warning, or will push on
toward 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The surge in the yield on the 30-year bond, which increased to
5.83 percent, also cooled the stock market a little, leaving the
Dow Jones industrial average up only 18.90 points, at 11,026.15.
</P>
<P>
   Also adding to the gloomy atmosphere was a lackluster auction of
five-year Treasury notes and negative comments about the bond
market from Stanley Druckenmiller, the manager of George Soros'
Quantum Fund. According to Bridge News, Druckenmiller told
investors at a conference in London that bonds were in a bear
market now and that the Fed would raise interest rates by the end
of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the uncertainty factor, traders and analysts said
that until the results of the Fed meeting were known, long-term
rates could edge higher. And the bond market could get a worse
shock if two inflation reports _ the Producer Price Index on
Thursday and the Consumer Price Index on Friday _ are
disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   Both reports are expected to reflect the recent rise in crude
oil prices, which saw the price of a barrel reach $18.98 last week.
The unknown is whether these two inflation barometers have positive
surprises _ as they did in March _ or negative ones. In March, the
consumer index rose only two-tenths of a percent despite a 1.6
percent jump in energy costs. For this month, Wall Street is
forecasting a five-tenths of a percent rise in the producer index
and a four-tenths of a percent rise in the consumer index.
</P>
<P>
   The government report on retail sales for April, which is due
Thursday, will also signal how fast the American consumer is still
spending. Consumers are the main reason that the economy has grown
at a brisk 5.25 percent pace over the last six months, far too fast
for Fed policy-makers to remain comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Fine, chief market analyst at Chase Securities, said he
was forecasting an increase of three-tenths of a percent in retail
sales for April. But he said investors would also keep their eyes
on the revision for the March data. An upward revision of that
number would add to fears that consumer spending will keep the
economy chugging along too quickly and eventually force the Fed to
raise interest rates, maybe by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   While the Fed is not expected to raise interest rates to slow
economic growth when the Federal Open Market Committee meets next
Tuesday, some analysts are wondering whether the Fed will send a
warning shot to the bond market. The central bank would do this by
indicating, with a formal directive, that it thought its next
interest rate move would most likely be an increase.
</P>
<P>
   But if the inflation news is not alarming and the Fed stands
pat, then there is a chance for interest rates to fall a little
until the next round of economic data provide a clearer picture of
how strong the economy is and how persistent price pressures might
become.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the 30-year bond fell 19/31, to 91 26/32, while the
yield, which moves in the opposite direction, rose to 5.83 percent
from 5.79 percent on Monday. That was the highest yield since 5.84
percent on May 27, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The new five-year Treasury notes yielded 5.367 percent and the
demand was weak, traders said. There is a 10-year note auction on
Wednesday. In when-issued trading on Tuesday, the yield on the
10-year note was 5.49 percent, up from 5.46 percent on Monday. The
yield on the current 10-year note rose to 5.57 percent, from 5.52
percent on Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
