<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3049 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      05-11 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORALES AIDE SAYS LAWYER IN TOBACCO-FEE CASE ADMITTED NOT HAVING
CONTRACT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A former key assistant to Dan Morales has told
investigators that Marc Murr, the mystery Houston lawyer in the
tobacco lawsuit, admitted only a few weeks before the case was
settled that Murr didn't have a contract to represent the state
against cigarette makers.
</P>
<P>
   Murr, assisted by Morales, the former Texas attorney general and
a longtime friend, attempted to claim as much as a half billion
dollars in legal fees after Morales negotiated a $17.3 billion
settlement with tobacco companies last year.
</P>
<P>
   Their efforts are now being investigated by the FBI and Texas
Attorney General John Cornyn, who succeeded Morales on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn turned over additional information on Morales' purported
contracts with Murr to federal investigators Friday in a meeting in
Austin, the attorney general's office reported.
</P>
<P>
   In a document filed in federal court a week ago, Cornyn accused
Morales and Murr of falsifying signatures and backdating two
contracts, dated Oct. 17, 1996, and Jan. 31, 1997. Cornyn called
the contracts ``fake'' and said they were part of an effort to
mislead a federal judge deciding on fees in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn said the purported 1996 contract wasn't created until
1998. Another source familiar with the investigation said the
second contract may have been created as long as a year after it
was dated.
</P>
<P>
   The day after Cornyn made his allegations, Murr abruptly
withdrew a claim against the state for about $260 million in legal
fees, which had been awarded by a state arbitration panel appointed
by himself and Morales. Murr still is to receive $1 million in fees
payable by the tobacco industry under a separate, national
arbitration award entered late last year.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Potter, Morales' top state lawyer on the tobacco suit, has
reported that Murr told him in December 1997, the month before the
case was settled, that Murr didn't have a state contract, a source
close to Cornyn's investigation said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Potter, who now teaches at the University of Texas Law School,
declined comment Tuesday about any discussions with Murr. But the
source said Potter told Cornyn's office that Murr made the
admission to him in a brief conversation the two had Dec. 18, 1997,
in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Potter and Murr were in Chicago for a negotiating session as
Morales and other state lawyers worked on hammering out the
settlement agreement with tobacco industry representatives that was
announced in January 1998. The agreement ended a state suit, filed
in 1996, over smoking-related health care costs and cigarette
marketing practices.
</P>
<P>
   Potter has been interviewed by the FBI and by Cornyn's office,
but he has declined to discuss details of his meetings with
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Potter said Tuesday that even before he took office Cornyn
requested a meeting to be brought up to date on tobacco issues.
Cornyn met with Potter and another Morales staffer, who now works
for Cornyn, during which ``a lot of our reservations'' about Murr
were discussed, Potter said.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn aides, who didn't want to be identified, said a third
former Morales assistant, who also now works for Cornyn, contacted
federal investigators about the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Morales and Murr have known each other since they worked
together at Bracewell &AMP; Patterson in Houston in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Morales has insisted that Murr played a crucial role in the
landmark tobacco case, often as a behind-the-scenes adviser. But
other lawyers have said that Murr did little work on the case. His
name didn't publicly surface until about the time the suit was
settled.
</P>
<P>
   Murr didn't return a phone call Tuesday from the Houston
Chronicle. And his lawyer, Roy Minton of Austin, declined comment
beyond saying Murr hadn't been contacted by the FBI or the U.S.
attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Morales nor his attorney, Sam Millsap of San Antonio,
returned phone calls Tuesday. Last week, Millsap said Morales
hadn't been contacted by federal investigators, and both he and
Morales heatedly denied Cornyn's accusations.
</P>
<P>
   Millsap said then that Cornyn, a Republican, was trying to
discredit Morales, a Democrat who didn't seek re-election last
year, so he will not run for governor in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The purported Oct. 17, 1996, contract between Murr and Morales
provided the Houston lawyer a 3 percent contingency. The Jan. 31,
1997, agreement, which purportedly replaced it, promised him a
``reasonable fee.''
</P>
<P>
   Before a state arbitration panel of three retired judges picked
by Murr and Morales last fall, Morales supported Murr's claim for 3
percent, or about $520 million. The state arbitrators awarded Murr
$260 million, which Murr moved to vacate in a brief hearing before
U.S. District Judge David Folsom of Texarkana last week.
</P>
<P>
   Folsom gave Murr 60 days to resubmit a claim before it is
formally dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Morales had a separate contract with five other private lawyers
who are sharing $3.3 billion in fees awarded by a national
arbitration panel. Tobacco companies have agreed to pay those fees.
</P>
<P>
   In a related development Tuesday, The Dallas Morning News
reported that two forensic experts hired by the newspaper had
determined that the purported Jan. 31, 1997, contract between Murr
and Morales had been doctored.
</P>
<P>
   The examiners told the newspaper that the signature pages of the
document are duplicates of a separate contract dated the same day.
The experts said the initial three-page contract was altered and
then photocopied as part of the second document.
</P>
<P>
   They said some signatures from a previously unknown agreement
that Morales had with Murr and Dallas attorney Will Pryor were
transferred to the new document, as Cornyn alleged last week.
</P>
<P>
   Pryor, a former top assistant to Morales, told the Houston
Chronicle that he and Murr signed a contract on Jan. 31, 1997, to
assist Morales in the tobacco suit. Pryor, who by then was a
mediator in private practice, said he quit the case several weeks
later because he felt uncomfortable with the arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   Pryor said he was worried that questions might be raised because
of his former close association with Morales.
</P>
<P>
   Minton, Murr's lawyer, has acknowledged that the Murr-only
contract dated Jan. 31, 1997, was ``put together sometime after
Jan. 31,'' but he said he didn't know when.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn has said he also will turn over his findings to the
Travis County District Attorney's office which prosecutes public
corruption cases involving state officials.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
