<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-GUNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE DEBATES YOUTH VIOLENCE LEGISLATION IN WAKE OF COLORADO
SHOOTINGS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For the first time since the Colorado high school
shootings, the Senate began debate Tuesday on youth violence
legislation that could lead to new gun control provisions as well
as tougher law enforcement measures aimed at young people.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, which had languished in the Senate for months,
was given sudden prominence as lawmakers rushed to register their
concern about the April 20 shooting at Columbine High School in
Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   The basic legislation would give federal officials greater
ability to prosecute juveniles as young as 14 as adults for serious
felonies and drug crimes. It would pump more than a $1 billion
annually into juvenile crime programs over five years and address
the problem of youth gangs.
</P>
<P>
   But lawmakers also made it clear that they hoped to use the
measure as a vehicle to address broader concerns, ranging from too
much media violence to too many guns, that may have led to the
tragedy in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day the senators paraded before the media to
announce a series of amendments, including making it harder to
purchase firearms at gun shows to barring film makers from using
public lands to make violent movies.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Republicans stressed the need to beef up
enforcement of gun laws and address cultural deficiencies that they
said lead to violence. Democrats talked more about funding after
school programs and cracking down on guns.
</P>
<P>
   And both sides acknowledged that the debate over guns was likely
to be the most vigorous and could overshadow other elements of the
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that ultimately it is going to devolve into a gun
fight,'' said Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, chief sponsor of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some Democrats made it clear that they were going to
attempt to force votes on a number of gun measures, including
background checks at gun shows and a three-day waiting period to
buy a handgun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without guns, families in Littleton, Colo., would not be
grieving, 15 people would be alive today,'' said Sen. Edward
Kennedy, D-Mass.
</P>
<P>
   However, Republicans argued that the problem is that current gun
control measures are not being enforced and proposed instead that
more money be spent on prosecution of violators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Passing a law sounds good, but to maximize our impact we've
got to prosecute the laws we've got,'' said Sen. Jeff Sessions,
R-Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the expected showdown, lawmakers of both parties
appeared to agree on two gun control provisions. One would bar
juveniles who committed felonies from purchasing guns even as
adults. The other would bar youths under 18 from purchasing
semiautomatic weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The congressional debate comes a day after President Clinton
hosted a conference on youth violence that focussed on a range of
issues involving entertainment images and access to weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has called on Congress to approve a package of gun
control measures, including raising the age of purchase of handguns
from 18 to 21 and holding adults responsible for youths who gain
access to guns that are used to kill people. The president has
called for a limit of one handgun purchase a month.
</P>
<P>
   But wary of the power of the National Rifle Association, which
opposes all of these measures, many lawmakers of both parties have
been reluctant to get too far out front on the gun issue.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, said that while she
supported instant background checks at gun shows, she was
noncommittal about the other proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison said she was worried about the federal government
stepping on state laws regarding guns. Furthermore, the Texas
Republican said she does not believe her constituents were
demanding more gun control, even in the wake of the Colorado
shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Texas we are a gun-owning state. We are a hunting state. It
is pretty strong for second amendment rights,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Other lawmakers acknowledged that there were no simple solutions
to the youth violence and they worried about solutions that could
step on people's rights.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ben Nighthorse Campbell, R-Colo., said he was worried that
``we don't erode the first amendment rights or second amendment
rights.''
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty in trying to regulate such rights was apparent
when a group of GOP senators unveiled proposals that included
barring the use of federal property for the filming of excessively
violent movies.
</P>
<P>
   The senators were asked if such a law would prevent the filming
on public lands of historic events such as Custer's last stand, the
1876 Battle of Little Bighorn, where Gen. George Custer and his
unit of 210 soldiers were massacred by Indians.
</P>
<P>
   None of the lawmakers could answer the question.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
