<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3053 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NRA-GOP-COX     05-11 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NRA-GOP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia GOP cools to reception of top NRA speaker
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Colorado school shootings fresh in their minds,
some Republicans are objecting to plans to have a top National
Rifle Association official address the Georgia GOP convention later
this month.
</P>
<P>
   These Republicans fear a public relations nightmare if the
Georgia party welcomes Wayne LaPierre, the NRA's executive
vice-president, to its Augusta, Ga. convention on May 22 at a time
when polls suggest Americans increasingly support gun control
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Since last month's killings at Columbine High School in
Littleton, Colo., the NRA has come under withering criticism for
its advocacy of measures that make it easier to own and carry guns.
And NRA president Charlton Heston and LaPierre signed a letter
following the massacre opposing new controls on guns.
</P>
<P>
   While Republicans have had a good relationship with the NRA,
some are now saying the organization should lower its profile for a
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's bad timing, to say the least,'' state Rep. Mark
Burkhalter (R-Alpharetta, Ga.) said of LaPierre's scheduled speech.
``The prudent thing to do would probably be to uninvite him.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. John Linder (R-Ga.) said Bob Barr, an NRA director, is
the only one of his Georgia colleagues in the House who ``doesn't
see a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Barr, in fact, said he ``heartily'' supports LaPierre's
appearance at the convention. ``These issues weigh heavily on the
minds of Georgia Republicans,'' he said. ``We need to address what
we can do about youth violence today.''
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Paul, the Georgia GOP chairman, said Tuesday that he finds
himself in a political jam because of the invitation he issued in
January.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an invitation that was extended before all this stuff
happened,'' Paul said. ``I told everybody I am not going to
withdraw the invitation.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul, whose successor will be chosen at the convention, said
that asking LaPierre to withdraw would amount to blaming the NRA
for the killings in Colorado, although he said he understands why
the invitation has become a sensitive topic.
</P>
<P>
   LaPierre did not return telephone calls Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   State Republicans find themselves in a dilemma. In spite of the
new energy for some gun control measures, revoking the invitation
would no doubt anger some NRA members and gun rights advocates in
Georgia. They are an important constituency in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Democratic Gov. Roy Barnes and Attorney General Thurbert
Baker were glad to have the NRA's endorsement in the last election.
</P>
<P>
   And Barnes signed into law a measure that prohibits Georgia
municipalities from suing gun manufacturers for damages related to
gun deaths. The NRA backed that legislation and Barr has introduced
a similar bill in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Paul noted that LaPierre sought the invitation, in part, to try
to ease relations with the Georgia GOP that were strained by the
Democratic endorsements.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Sherman writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
