<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPAQ-RANDO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMAQ SERVICES CHIEF TO STEP DOWN   IN JUNE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Texas)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The chief of Compaq Computer Corp.'s big services
business will step down July 1, continuing the management exodus
from the No. 1 personal computer maker and kicking off a search for
a new executive to head the operations bought from Digital
Equipment Corp last year.
</P>
<P>
   John Rando, the former Digital executive who now is senior vice
president and general manager of Compaq Services in Stow, will
leave ``to pursue personal interests,'' a Compaq spokesman said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Rando becomes the fourth senior executive to exit the
Houston-based computer maker in recent weeks as it tries to map out
a strategy to regain the profitability it enjoyed for much of the
decade.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Compaq ousted chief executive officer Eckhard
Pfeiffer. Compaq's chief financial officer also left, as did its
worldwide sales chief.
</P>
<P>
   Rando wasn't asked to resign, Compaq said, and wasn't available
Tuesday to elaborate on his reasons for leaving or his future
plans.
</P>
<P>
   But his departure adds to the uncertainty surrounding Compaq's
prospects, said Eric Rocco, principal analyst at Dataquest in
Lowell. Services remains key to Compaq's strategy to diversifying
beyond the personal computer business, he said. ``Anytime a
hands-on person like Rando steps down there's going to be some
issues,'' Rocco said. ``This only adds to their challenge going
forward, how they move from being just a (PC) box-pushing
company.''
</P>
<P>
   Rando came to Compaq last year along with 22,000 other Digital
service employees as part of a strategy by Pfeiffer to move away
from the fiercely competitive personal computer business.
</P>
<P>
   The units now known as Compaq Services employ 27,000 worldwide,
including the majority of Compaq's 11,000 employees in
Massachusetts and New Hampshire. Seven thousand of the 11,000 are
in the Bay State. Of Compaq's total 1998 revenue of $31.2 billion,
the services business contributed $3.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, new service businesses like networking analysis have
begun to offset declines in traditional service revenue from
maintaining large corporate computer networks, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   But those results weren't enough to offset broader problems at
Compaq, and analysts questioned whether the company had done enough
to capitalize on the former Digital assets.
</P>
<P>
   With the recent executive departures from Compaq, observers now
wonder how many more changes are in store. ``You've got a situation
where everything is fair game right now,'' said S.G. Cowen analyst
Richard Chu.
</P>
<P>
   Rando, 47, graduated from Boston College with a computer science
degree in 1974 and joined Digital two years later as a software
specialist. He rose through the ranks at Digital and was a central
figure in striking a partnership with Microsoft Corp. in 1995 under
which Digital trained thousands of engineers to support the
software giant's networking products.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq said it will begin a search for Rando's successor
immediately. In a statement, Compaq chairman Ben Rosen praised
Rando for building ``one of the most motivated and successful
service organizations in the computing world'' and called the
services group ``a vital element of Compaq's future success.''
</P>
<P>
   Until July 1, Rando will continue to oversee three divisions
reporting to him. They include a customer services group, headed by
Peter Mercury; the networking and systems integration division run
by Kannankote Srikanth and a group known as operations management
services, headed by Tim Leisman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
