<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3056 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-FUNDRAISING-ART     05-11 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-FUNDRAISING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATIC FUND-RAISER TELLS OF DEALINGS WITH CHINESE DONORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(rm) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Democratic fund-raiser who has pleaded guilty to
campaign-related bank and tax fraud told a House panel Tuesday that
he met in 1996 with a high-ranking Chinese intelligence official
who promised him $300,000 for use in the presidential election
saying, ``We really like your president.''
</P>
<P>
   Recounting mysterious meetings at restaurants, hotel lounges and
karaoke bars, the fund-raiser, Johnny Chung, provided his first
public account of his experiences, from 1994 to 1996, as he
traveled the Far East prospecting for business clients eager for
access to the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   In his testimony to the government Reform and Oversight
Committee, Chung said he met several times with the chief of
China's military intelligence agency, Gen. Ji Shengde, who directed
that the $300,000 be wired to Chung's bank account in Hong Kong for
use as contributions to President Clinton's re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Chung's appearance before the House committee came at a time of
serious tension between the United States and China, when the
relationship has been badly strained by the mistaken NATO bombing
of the Chinese embassy in Belgrade and an uproar in Congress over
the the possible Chinese theft of secret American nuclear data.
</P>
<P>
   Chung said that at their first meeting in August 1996, Ji used
the alias ``Xu'' and emerged as a shadowy figure from a kitchen
entrance of an abalone restaurant in Hong Kong. They spoke
obliquely about Clinton, Chung said. Ji told him, ``We hope to see
him re-elected. I will give you 300,000 U.S. dollars. You can give
it to the president and the Democratic Party,'' Chung said.
</P>
<P>
   Chung was introduced to Ji by Liu Chaoying, the daughter of
powerful Chinese general and an official in a Chinese aerospace
company. Chung said he never told Democratic Party officials that
he raised money in China, but believed that Democratic officials
were aware of his business activities there. Chung said he later
introduced Ms. Liu to Donald Fowler, who was then chairman of the
Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Chung said he felt uncomfortable about funneling the general's
money into the presidential campaign, and so he spent most of it
for personal and business expenses. Investigators have traced only
about $35,000 of the money to the campaign. Federal law does not
permit foreign nationals to contribute directly to American
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   After the fund-raising scandal erupted, Chung, who visited the
White House 50 times, came to personify the fund-raising abuses
committed during the president's re-election campaign. He was
responsible for nearly $400,000 in contributions to the Democratic
Party, all of which was returned after the election as tainted.
</P>
<P>
   But on Tuesday, in sometimes halting English, the California
businessman seemed less sinister than out of his depth in the
high-stakes world of presidential fund raising. In five hours of
testimony, he described himself as a ``first-generation immigrant''
who would never ``undermine the interests of my country'' and is
``as loyal to our country as any of you.''
</P>
<P>
   Chung pleaded guilty in March 1998 in a deal with the government
in which he agreed to cooperate fully with authorities. He was
sentenced to a suspended jail term and 3,000 hours of community
service. His testimony Tuesday under subpoena was approved by the
Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   Although he had never testified before, the broad outline of
Chung's account had been previously known from news reports. In his
testimony, he accepted responsibility for his misdeeds, but said
that the lawmakers who had summoned him to testify at the hearing
that they also were accountable for setting up the fund-raising
rules that he operated under. ``I didn't create the system,'' he
said. ``You did.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yet, more than two years after this controversy erupted you,
the Congress, have done nothing to change this system,'' Chung
said. ``Indeed within the last month I received an invitation to a
fund raiser where I might have yet another photo opportunity with
some politician _ although most of you would probably run away from
me at his point.''
</P>
<P>
   Chung's appearance at the hearing showed how his fortunes had
changed since he escorted select guests on private tours of Hillary
Rodham Clinton's office. Republicans on the committee warmly
greeted him as a fund raiser whose secret dealings with Chinese
espionage officials have powerfully buttressed Republican
accusations that China put into effect a plan to use money
influence the 1996 Presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Democrats from Chung's party who turned on Chung,
bitterly denouncing him as an untrustworthy witness. ``You've had
your 15 minutes, Chung,'' said Rep. Tom Lantos, D-Calif. ``You are
a very minor, insignificant puppet of the Communist regime.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Waxman, D-Calif., accused Chung of providing
authorities with misleading accounts of his dealings with Hazel
O'Leary, the former energy secretary and Margaret Williams, a
former White House aide, who were investigated before they were
cleared of wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Chung said that after investigators focused on him, he was
offered money to keep him from cooperating with federal authorities
and was introduced to a Los Angeles lawyer, David E. Brockway, who
Chung said would help him if he kept his silence. But after the
hearing, the lawyer denied Chung's account. ``He's a huckster and a
hustler, Brockway said in a telephone interview. ``It's a lie.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
