<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYCOS-DEAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LYCOS-USA NETWORKS DEAL DEAD, SOURCE SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The controversial merger between Lycos Inc. and operations of
USA Networks Inc. is expected to be declared dead Wednesday,
according to a source close to the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos, the third most popular portal on the Internet, and New
York media concern USA Networks announced in February that the
Waltham, Mass. company would be combined with a number of retail,
broadcast, and Net businesses run by USA Networks.
</P>
<P>
   But the two firms have had trouble selling their vision for a
hybrid Internet/electronic retailing company to Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos shareholders were outraged by the low value the deal
placed on their shares. Lycos investors were to get no more than 35
percent of the new company's stock, while USA Networks shareholders
were to receive as much as 61.5 percent. Furious shareholders sent
the value of Lycos stock plummeting.
</P>
<P>
   The deal has been teetering on the brink of collapse since
March, when David Wetherell, a member of the Lycos board who had
approved the deal, changed his mind and vowed to fight it. As chief
executive of Internet venture firm CMGI Inc., Wetherell controls
about 20 percent of Lycos stock.
</P>
<P>
   Given Wetherell's opposition and the skeptical reception among
other Lycos investors, the deal's prospects have been fading in
recent weeks. Tuesday, the merger still had a pulse, but just
barely.
</P>
<P>
   The source said Lycos and USA Networks, which is run by Barry
Diller, were engaged in last-minute negotiations to try to save the
proposed merger. But that would have required USA Networks to offer
a new, higher bid. The source described this outcome as very
unlikely and predicted a decision to abandon the deal would be made
in the wee hours of this morning.
</P>
<P>
   The failure of the ambitious deal would be a blow to Lycos chief
executive Bob Davis, but he may not walk away empty-handed.
According to terms of the agreement between Lycos and USA Networks,
the deal can only be scrapped by mutual agreement. The source said
Lycos was seeking to pull the plug on the merger on the most
beneficial terms possible.
</P>
<P>
   Even an unattached Lycos is still a formidable Internet force.
The company's Web sites are used by more than half of all
Internet-using Americans, and market analysts expect it to break
even in the current quarter and turn a profit in fiscal year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But Barry Parr, electronic commerce analyst for International
Data Corp. in Mountain View, Calif., insisted Lycos needs an
alliance with a major TV company to attract millions of people who
will be coming onto the Internet in future years.
</P>
<P>
   Davis had hoped to use USA Networks's cable channels, like USA
Network and the SciFi Channel, to promote Lycos. But Parr thinks
Lycos shareholders rejected the deal partly because they doubted
these channels had the audience size and prestige to benefit Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think really what the market was saying is if you don't have
the partner that builds your brand, you don't have the right
partner,'' said Parr.
</P>
<P>
   USA Networks didn't return a call late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos shares closed Tuesday at 98 1/4, down 7, while USA
Networks shares rose 5/8 to 35 7/8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-99 2007EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
