<HEADER>
A3059 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POWERTV-COX     05-11 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWERTV-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Scientific-Atlanta poised to profit from digital TV
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For Scientific-Atlanta, AT&AMP;T's $62 billion deal to buy
MediaOne is a big stamp of approval for its investment in digital
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see AT&AMP;T's purchase of MediaOne as an emphatic validation
of the benefits of an interactive broadband network,'' says Steve
Necessary, vice president of marketing at Scientific-Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for Scientific-Atlanta's enthusiasm is that AT&AMP;T has
said it intends to use MediaOne's digital networks to offer lots of
other services than television. Among them: local telephone service
and high-speed access to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T's strategy dovetails with that of Scientific-Atlanta, which
has launched a new equipment line that enables cable operators to
provide two-way digital television.
</P>
<P>
   The line is called Explorer 2000, and so far 90 cable systems
have signed up for it. Thirty-one have actually begun using
Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   In part, Explorer is dependent on the ability of cable operators
to rebuild their systems to handle digital traffic. That effort,
while picking up steam lately, has been slow and scattered. Only
about a quarter of all cable systems nationwide can handle digital
signals.
</P>
<P>
   But even those systems using Explorer are not taking full
advantage of the product. Most operators are using Explorer just to
provide the expanded channel capacity and sharper images of digital
technology.
</P>
<P>
   But Explorer is capable of doing so much more. It can, for
example, let viewers use their televisions to browse the Web, send
and receive e-mail, order movies on demand and shop online.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more useful the Explorer can be, the wider its appeal and
more cable operators will want to use it,'' said George Hunt, a
media analyst at Wachovia Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Scientific-Atlanta agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``If consumers like the things Explorer can do, then the cable
operators will sell more of them and we'll make more money,'' says
Necessary. ``It's a win-win-win deal for us, consumers and cable
operators.''
</P>
<P>
   Marketing campaign
</P>
<P>
   To promote the adoption of two-way television,
Scientific-Atlanta has organized a marketing effort called
``CreativEdge.''
</P>
<P>
   CreativEdge is a branding umbrella under which
Scientific-Atlanta is gathering as many different kinds of software
that make use of Explorer's two-way capacity. This software enables
Explorer to do things such as send e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Giving Scientific-Atlanta's longtime standing with cable
operators, the company is hoping its sponsorship will make
operators more likely to try new two-way software.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're nurturing applications big and small,'' says Necessary.
``And we're ensuring that these applications work fine, on any
cable system.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the applications are still in development, but most are
within months of commercial rollout. Last week, Scientific-Atlanta
sponsored a demonstration of many of these new two-way applications
for cable TV operators. It was the first time outside a national
trade show that the company had done a group presentation of
two-way software for operators.
</P>
<P>
   PC meets television
</P>
<P>
   What operators saw, for example, was Peach Network. An Israeli
company, Peach Network has developed software that uses Explorer to
run PC applications _ from games to word processors _ on television
screens.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of more months of work and we'll be ready for the
market,'' says Peach Network President Ofir Paz.
</P>
<P>
   Another application nearly ready for prime time is TV Navigator.
Developed by a company called NCI, navigator is based on software
that shrinks a Web page to fit comfortably on a TV screen. This
software also enhances the look of a Web page so that can be easily
read from a distance, such as that between a television and a
couch.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can also watch TV at any time while you're surfing the
Web,'' says Rajesh Amin, business development manager for
Scientific-Atlanta's digital subscriber networks unit. NCI
Navigator does so, Amin explains, by leaving a little box for
television, which users can move around the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Many of Scientific-Atlanta's CreativEdge developers are small
start-ups _ but not all. Its members also include giants such as
IBM.
</P>
<P>
   IBM is selling a collection of software tools, branded as
business, through CreativEdge. These tools enable cable operators
to team up with merchants to create virtual online stores capable
of letting viewers use their televisions to browse product catalogs
and buy merchandise. Viewers can also e-mail stores to ask
questions, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to IBM, Scientific-Atlanta has been working with
software giant Microsoft. Scientific-Atlanta is trying to ensure
that Explorer is compatible with both Microsoft's Windows operating
systems and its software.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the two companies announced last December a joint
initiative to develop a next generation set-top box that supported
simultaneously both Scientific-Atlanta and Microsoft operating
systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to provide operators with products that give them
the most value and utility,'' says Necessary. ``In some ways, it's
that simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
