<DOCNO> NYT19990511.0319 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3062 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-ART-TRIMS-NYT     05-11 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ART-TRIMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TRIES TO SELL EXECUTIVES ON INNER-CITY ECONOMICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of Clinton is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Eager to keep his domestic agenda going, President
Clinton flew here Tuesday to call for corporate investment in
inner-city America and said he would tour some of the nation's
pockets of poverty, which he characterized as great economic
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   The July tour is to be modeled on the overseas missions that
Cabinet secretaries and corporate officers frequently make to help
American businesses take advantage of emerging markets. Clinton
said that some of America's neglected rural and urban areas
constituted such emerging markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our greatest untapped markets are here at home,'' the
president said at the White House Tuesday morning after a
closed-door session with 15 chief executives of major corporations.
Clinton later brought the executives here for a tour of local
businesses that have profited from federal investment.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said Clinton's tour was to take him to Appalachia, the
Mississippi Delta, Indian reservations and aging industrial cities
like Gary, Ind. The aides said he would try to get the executives
to see the tour sites as sources of customers and make substantial
investments in them.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The president's schedule was intended to highlight a portion of
the domestic agenda he laid out when he first campaigned for
president, when he said repeatedly that ``no one should be left
behind.''
</P>
<P>
   With the war in Kosovo, the school shootings in Littleton,
Colo., and other issues now dominating his time in Washington,
Clinton is eager to revive this aspect of his presidency,
particularly as former Sen. Bill Bradley challenges Clinton's
designated heir, Vice President Al Gore, on broad questions of race
and economic equality. Gore spoke extensively with the executives
Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Much of the United States is enjoying the biggest economic
expansion in more than three decades. And Clinton noted that in
particular, African-American and Hispanic residents were enjoying
the lowest rates of unemployment since the government began keeping
those statistics. But he said that parts of the country had had no
new investment, no new business and no new jobs, and that 37 cities
had unemployment rates that were double the national average.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the midst of all our prosperity,'' the president said here,
he wanted to point out ``both the obligation and the opportunity we
have to do better.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's support for investment at home was inspired by
the Rev. Jesse Jackson's pleadings in the last year to Wall Street
to encourage private investors, said Gene Sperling, Clinton's
economic adviser. Jackson was not with Clinton on Tuesday but is
supposed to be part of the July tour.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spent his day emphasizing that people in poor areas
could succeed if someone invested in those areas, and if they are
aided by federally sponsored tax credits, loan guarantees and
technical support. He is also proposing $1 billion in tax credits
for businesses in poor areas.
</P>
<P>
   He brought the executives with him here on Air Force One for a
round-table discussion staged between stalls at a historic farmers'
market and talked about tax incentives for the so-called
empowerment zones _ areas in the inner city earmarked for economic
initiatives _ but not before cruising for munchies and coming up
with some coffee and sweet potato cheesecake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have lifted things from almost every entrepreneur here,''
the president said with a laugh. He said that the woman who gave
him the cheesecake ``destroyed my diet today _ and I loved every
bite of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The market, the Sweet Auburn Curb Street Market, is in Southeast
Atlanta's first black commercial district, not far from the home of
the Rev. Dr Martin Luther King Jr. In operation since 1923, the
market has fallen on hard times over the years and has been aided
with more than $8 million in federal financing.
</P>
<P>
   The market now employs about 800 people in 24 shops. The
president was intrigued by a bin of cows feet and pig ears,
recalling that when Russian President Boris Yeltsin visited him in
Washington, he presented Clinton with a roasted pig and cut off the
ear, telling Clinton he would eat it if he were a true Russian.
</P>
<P>
   Many shop owners said business was slow, and it was not clear
whether the tour inspired any of the executives to want to invest
in the nation's poorer outposts. The executives included
representatives from Bell South, American Airlines, Goldman Sachs,
the Rite Aid Corp., AT&AMP;T Wireless, Delta Airlines, Bankers Trust
and New York Life.
</P>
<P>
   Like the president, Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell, told the
executives that there was profit to be made in places like this but
only with investment up front.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe, when you look at the inner city, the opportunities
are apparent,'' Campbell said. ``It's access to capital that we
think has been the biggest impediment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
