u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARKET-NYT &LR;      05-11 0498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET, TECHNOLOGY SHARES LEAD STOCK MARKET HIGHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also AOL-TV, CREDIT) 
(mk) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks were buffeted by a further selloff in the bond
market Tuesday but recovered and moved higher, led by technology
and Internet shares.
</P>
<P>
   Bond prices fell and long-term interest rates rose to their
highest level in nearly a year after an auction of new five-year
notes was poorly received. Major stock market averages dipped after
the auction results were announced in the afternoon but then
regained some of their footing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still a lot of concern in the bond market about an
overheated economy and what that means for inflation,'' said Ned
Riley Jr., chief investment officer at BankBoston Corp. ``But that
concern seems to be less of an issue in the stock market.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 18.90 points, or
two-tenths of a percent, to 11,026.15. But broader market measures
did appreciably better.
</P>
<P>
   Buttressed by sharp gains in America Online, Wal-Mart and Cisco
Systems, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index gained 15.31 points,
or 1.14 percent, to 1,355.61. Meanwhile, the NASDAQ composite index
rose 40.29 points, or 1.6 percent, to 2,566.68. The Russell 2000
index of smaller-company stocks increased 4.96 points, or 1.12
percent, to 446.81.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks sensitive to the business cycle, which have moved sharply
higher over the last month on signs of vigorous economic growth,
surrendered their leadership role Tuesday to the well-known, big
capitalization growth stocks that have been the market's standard
bearers for a number of years.
</P>
<P>
   International Paper, a Dow component, fell 2 1/4, to 53 7/8.
Allied Signal, another Dow stock, fell 1 3/8, to 63 9/16. And
Georgia-Pacific fell 4 3/16, to 56 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Internet stocks, which have been under selling
pressure over the last few weeks, did much better Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The group was led higher by America Online, which surged after
Mary Meeker, Morgan Stanley Dean Witter's influential Internet
analyst, upgraded the company to ``strong buy'' from
``outperform.'' Later in the session, the company announced that it
would develop an Internet television service with several partners.
</P>
<P>
   America Online, which was the most actively traded issue on the
New York Stock Exchange, rose 11 5/16, to 139 5/8.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems, another big company with important ties to the
Internet, gained 2 5/8, to 111 7/8. After the market closed, the
company posted earnings that were slightly above expectations and
announced a 2-for-1 stock split. Riley and other analysts said the
Cisco earnings report could get technology stocks additional
momentum Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Strong earnings helped lift the price of Wal-Mart Stores, a
component of both the Dow and the S&AMP;P 500. Wal-Mart gained 2 1/8,
to 47 5/16.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the rise in interest rates, a number of financial
service stocks did well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
