<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3065 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HERSANT-FIGARO-NYT &LR;      05-11 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERSANT-FIGARO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERSANT GROUP SEEKS TO SELL PART OF LE FIGARO 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ The Hersant Group, a heavily indebted French newspaper
company, is seeking bids for up to 49 percent of its flagship
paper, Le Figaro.
</P>
<P>
   The effort to divest itself of part of Le Figaro by Hersant,
which controls about 30 percent of French newspaper circulation,
follows the April sale of Hersant's Paris evening paper,
France-Soir, to financier Georges Ghosn, for a symbolic one franc,
about 17 cents. France-Soir had been losing about $1.6 million a
month, and in exchange for the sale Hersant agreed to assume $13.5
million of France-Soir's debt.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Hersant's owners, the family of French press baron
Robert Hersant, who died in 1996, voted to transform Le Figaro into
an independent company with an eye to selling a stake to investors.
</P>
<P>
   French press reports have named as possible buyers Francois
Pinault of Pinault-Printemps-Redoute, who recently bid for a large
stake of the Gucci fashion house and already owns a small share of
the leading daily Le Monde, and Bernard Arnault, the chairman of
the luxury goods maker LVMH.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, The Financial Times of London reported that the Carlyle
Group, a Washington-based takeover firm, was also a potential
investor. Officials at Le Figaro and Carlyle would not comment.
</P>
<P>
   Socpresse SA, the Hersant family unit that controls Le Figaro,
is reported to have about $367 million of debt, and has come under
increasing pressure from French banks that are its principal
creditors. Critics often accused Hersant of using easy credit from
what was at the time a state-owned French banking system for his
acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   To reduce the group's debt, Socpresse's chairman, Yves de
Chaise-martin, has been merging some of the group's more than 15
regional newspapers and seeking to shed all or part of the control
of others.
</P>
<P>
   The Hersant Group has been hurt by France's sluggish economy and
the inroads of competing media. Circulation of Le Figaro, France's
leading conservative paper, has dropped to about 360,000 copies,
from 430,000 in 1985, and is reportedly losing about $20 million a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Hersant's idea behind carving Le Figaro into a separate
subsidiary was to increase the paper's capital base and then
reintroduce it as a major competitor to Le Monde, a liberal daily
part-owned by its journalists and the market leader. That project
is a favorite of French conservatives, who value Le Figaro's
potential role in the run-up to presidential elections in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The privately owned Hersant Group began facing financial trouble
even before the death of Hersant _ a secretive, driven man who
built the group up over four decades starting with a motor
magazine. He acquired Le Figaro in 1975 and ran its daily
operations until his death.
</P>
<P>
   A sale of Figaro assets to a non-French investor like Carlyle
would be certain to create intense unhappiness in France, where
newspaper unions are influential and foreign control of more than
20 percent of a news business requires government approval.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-99 2015EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
