<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALIVATING OVER HOT WINGS COULD HAVE STARS SINGING BLUES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The Stars are playing St. Louis, but are they
thinking Detroit? Give it a week, and ``Red Wingitis'' could be
both rampant and useful. But if it's happening now, then that's a
dangerous disease.
</P>
<P>
   Quizzed on that point yesterday, the Stars' players, to the man,
responded as expected. As in, there has not been, nor will be, any
peeping past St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   But general manager Bob Gainey, an old soldier who fought many a
Stanley Cup war, didn't exactly dismiss the possibility as pivotal
Game 4 of this second-round series approached Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's there, it's logical, the thought is floating around, and
it has to be dealt with individually and collectively among our
group,'' he said when asked about any concern over premature ``Red
Wingitis.''
</P>
<P>
   And after the Blues had rescued Game 3 here Monday night,
cutting the Stars' series lead to two games to one, some of the St.
Louis players seemed puzzled. There were indications they didn't
think they had yet seen the Stars' best game, which again hints of
a Detroit thing.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, no one from the Stars' side disagrees, starting with
coach Ken Hitchcock. To most of us, it's been inevitable that the
Stars and Red Wings would meet in the Western Conference finals,
and decide the Stanley Cup winner then and there. But Hitch began
verbally banging on his team after the Game 3 loss. And that theme
continued yesterday. Plus, the soft-spoken Gainey also joined in.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this time of year, it's a daily and constant exercise to
keep the focus in the right area,'' Gainey said. ``But for us,
that's not anything new. From Day One of this season, the
expectations for our team have always been different from where we
are, or where we were.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, a team built with Tom Hicks' money, Gainey's
expertise and Hitchcock's coaching is expected to bring home the
Stanley Cup, or else.
</P>
<P>
   In winning the first six playoff games, various warts were easy
to cover. But the Stars' loss Monday night quickly brought the
spotlight down on such areas as the folly of the power-play unit,
or the latest lack of production from the Mike Modano line. And
then there has also been the Detroit phobia to consider.
</P>
<P>
   Without question, the Red Wings have been the most impressive
team in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, that's been noticed,'' Gainey said of the Red Wings'
playoff run. ``And at the same time, everyone needs to recognize
we've got a tiger by the tail in St. Louis. When it's December or
January, and you're talking about the playoffs, the importance
doesn't mean much. But once you are here, it comes down to a
step-by-step process. Our step right now is the semifinals. A very
good and competitive series is happening with St. Louis.''
</P>
<P>
   A random poll of club officials and NHL scouts indicated the
Stars played well enough in the Edmonton series to defeat Detroit.
But the kicker is no one who was asked yesterday felt any of the
performances against St. Louis thus far were up to Red Wings'
standards.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, the second period against St. Louis in Game 3 was an
absolute embarrassment. The Blues scored only once in that
20-minute barrage but still changed the course of the game.
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side for the Stars, they've been strong in the third
period in all seven postseason contests; have bounced back to tie
the score in five of them; and Jere Lehtinen will return for Game
4, as might Guy Carbonneau.
</P>
<P>
   Lehtinen was injured early in the second period Monday night and
missed the remainder of the game. Carbonneau has yet to play in
this series because of injury.
</P>
<P>
   But overall, the third-period composure over seven playoff games
is a healthy trend. What Game 4 will reveal is what kind of
jump-start, if any, did losing Monday night provide for the Stars.
If there was ``Red Wingitis,'' has it now been cured?
</P>
<P>
   And in taking note of Detroit's postseason roll, Gainey recalled
when the Soviet National team made its first visit to North America
in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were playing that series against them, we used to
practice in the same arenas,'' Gainey said. ``To watch them skate
in practice, the first thought was we can't beat them. They were
that skilled.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then you get on the ice against them and provide
resistance against that skill, and it wasn't as difficult as it had
looked watching them in practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Detroit has been mighty, but first things first. The Blues
are gaining momentum in this series. For the Stars, what happens
next doesn't matter. This is all about what happens now. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
