A3082 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAMRADIO-COX     05-11 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAMRADIO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Family will Ham it up at convention
 &HT;    By Laura A. Bischoff
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Dick Miller used to be the only amateur radio
operator in his family, but then the Ham bug bit his wife, then his
son-in-law and his daughter, then the other daughter and her
husband and it kept going from there. Now 14 family members are
licensed ham radio operators.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just sort of spreading down the family tree. It's kind of
unusual because a lot of other hams ask me how I got my kids to be
hams. I don't know. I didn't bug them,'' said Miller, general
chairman of Hamvention '99, the amateur radio show at Hara Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day my wife came out to my ham shack and said, 'If you
die, what am I going to do with all this stuff?' And I said 'You
have two choices: sell it or get your license.' She got her
license,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Then about 13 years ago, Miller took his son-in-law, Mark
Denlinger, to Hamvention and next thing he knew nearly everyone in
the family was getting his or her ham license.
</P>
<P>
   The Miller Family will be at Hamvention 99 Friday through Sunday
in full force, along with 28,000 other ham radio enthusiasts from
across the United States and from 50 foreign countries. The 48th
annual Hamvention features 1,500 vendors sprawled across Hara's
parking lots in an open air flea market where shoppers can get the
latest gizmos, hard-to-find parts and other items. Indoors, another
250 manufacturers display their wares and seminars and forums are
held.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the market and seminars at Hara Arena, Hamvention
will hold a banquet and concert at the Nutter Center on Saturday.
Joe Walsh, 51, best known from his work as a guitarist with The
Eagles and The James Gang, will perform beginning around 8:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a an amateur radio operator _ a very avid one. He was
glad to do it to support amateur radio,'' Miller said of Walsh.
</P>
<P>
   Banquet-concert tickets are $40 while the 6,000 general
admission concert tickets are $20 apiece. Tickets are available at
the Hara and Nutter box offices and Ticketmaster outlets.
</P>
<P>
   Hamvention, which is sponsored by the Dayton Amateur Radio
Association Inc., is expected to have a $3.4 million economic
impact on Montgomery County, officials estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hamvention's attendance figures have been trailing in
recent years, Miller said previous crowd counts may have been
inaccurate. But new tracking systems will provide accurate counts
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Ham radio may be taking a side seat to the Internet where people
connect through web pages and e-mail messages. But Miller said the
Internet just doesn't have the same thrill as talking live to
people around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to be a techie to get your (ham) license or to
enjoy it. You can be from any walk of life,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Hamvention '99 Days: Friday through May 16.
</P>
<P>
   Where: Hara Arena, 1001 Shiloh Springs Road, Trotwood, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets: $16 in advance for a three-day pass (no single-day
tickets available); $20 at the door.
</P>
<P>
   Parking: Free parking at Dayton Mall and Salem Mall with free
shuttle buses to Hara. Limited parking in lots on Wolf Road at $5
to $10 a day.
</P>
<P>
   More info: (937) 276-6930 or www.hamvention.org
</P>
<P>
   Laura A. Bischoff writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
