<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRONICLE-PUBLISHING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRONICLE PUBLISHING MAY BE PLANNING TO SELL ASSETS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Ill., Calif., Neb., Kan.)  (bl) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The family that owns Chronicle Publishing Co. in San Francisco
has called in the investment bank of Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette
to evaluate its assets and advise it on possible financial
strategies.
</P>
<P>
   Many observers, though not all, say this means that the company
is preparing to sell The San Francisco Chronicle, the country's
11th-largest newspaper, and KRON, the NBC affiliate in the
country's fifth-largest television market, along with two other
television stations, two publishing companies and two smaller
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When an announcement like this is made, it generally ends up
in a sale,'' said P. Anthony Ridder, the chairman and chief
executive of Knight Ridder, whose San Jose Mercury News competes
with The Chronicle in the Silicon Valley area south of San
Francisco Bay, and whose Contra Costa newspapers are battling The
Chronicle for suburban readers east of San Francisco Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The future of The Chronicle, a morning paper with a circulation
of about 475,000, and its afternoon rival, The San Francisco
Examiner, which has a circulation of about 111,000, has been a
subject of speculation for years. The two newspapers are part of a
joint operating agreement that started in 1965 and is scheduled to
run until 2005.
</P>
<P>
   But since that agreement took effect, both newspapers have found
themselves gradually losing suburban readership in the sprawling
Bay area. Aside from the Knight Ridder papers, the Alameda
Newspaper Group east of the Bay is owned by one of the industry's
most aggressive competitors, William Dean Singleton, the chief
executive of Media News Group Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Ridder said any buyer would find the various assets
of Chronicle Publishing ``very attractive properties.'' Various
industry observers valued the company's total assets at well over
$1 billion. It is not clear, however, if one company could buy both
The Chronicle and KRON. Chronicle Publishing has a waiver from the
Federal Communications Commission rule that prohibits
cross-ownership of a major newspaper and television station in the
same market, but a buyer might not get the same waiver.
</P>
<P>
   The most likely suitor for all or part of Chronicle Publishing's
assets would be its rival, Hearst Corp., which owns The Examiner.
Under the terms of their joint operating agreement, the two
newspapers share business operations but run separate, and highly
competitive, newsrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Newspaper Agency, which runs the shared
advertising and production operations of the two newspapers, has
about 3,200 employees, about 1,000 of whom are represented by at
least 10 separate unions. Despite its status as the junior member
of the operation, by size, the owners of The Examiner have always
taken an aggressive public stance, declaring that they have no
intention of shutting the operation at which William Randolph
Hearst first tried his hand as a newspaper publisher in the late
19th century.
</P>
<P>
   George Irish, the president and group head of Hearst Newspapers,
declined Tuesday to comment on the Chronicle announcement, which
was made by Chronicle Publishing chief executive John Sias in a
news release Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Sias is not a member of the extended family that owns the paper
and has had internecine battles for two decades. The descendants of
the two DeYoung brothers, who started The Daily Dramatic Chronicle
in San Francisco in 1865, have publicly wrangled over control of
the newspaper and the company's board several times in the last
decade.
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle Publishing is privately held. It owns the Chronicle,
the Bloomington Pantagraph in Illinois and the Worcester Telegram
in Massachusetts.
</P>
</TEXT>
