</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TRIBUNAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAVIA ASKS WORLD COURT TO ORDER A HALT TO NATO BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-NATO) 
(nk) 
 By MARLISE SIMONS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE HAGUE, Netherlands _ A parallel fight to the war in Kosovo
is taking place here at the International Court of Justice, where
Yugoslavia is asking for a legal order against 10 NATO nations to
halt the bombing, and the NATO members are responding with scorn.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the suit has coincided with Yugoslavia's assertion
that it is withdrawing part of its forces from Kosovo, and some
international lawyers and diplomats suggest that the troop
announcement may have been intended to help bolster Belgrade's case
in court.
</P>
<P>
   In the grandiose Hall of Justice of the Peace Palace here,
Yugoslavia told a panel of 20 judges that the NATO bombings of its
territory over the last seven weeks had violated the U.N. charter,
the Geneva Conventions and several human rights treaties and that
the attacks constituted genocide.
</P>
<P>
   Belgrade demands that the international court, the highest
judicial body of the United Nations, issue an injunction telling
the NATO countries to end their attacks immediately and ordering
them to pay compensation for all the damage done. Belgrade has
filed separate complaints against each of the 10 countries involved
in the NATO attacks. It cannot sue NATO because this court deals
only with disputes between nations.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav government seems to give enormous importance to its
lawsuit. Belgrade has included eight professors of international
law in its delegation, six of them non-Serbs from Western
universities.
</P>
<P>
   The British government, so far the most outspoken champion of
NATO's actions, has also underscored that it takes the lawsuit
seriously by sending Attorney General John Morris to argue its
case.
</P>
<P>
   The hearings in Yugoslavia's lawsuit against the 10 NATO nations
began on Monday morning, just hours before Belgrade announced that
it would pull back part of its forces. The sessions continued
Tuesday when several NATO countries responded.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 NATO countries in their replies have all mocked
Yugoslavia's claim, calling it cynical and absurd, while denouncing
its crimes in Kosovo. The United States said Tuesday that
Belgrade's suit was ``a feat of hypocrisy and cynicism of Orwellian
proportions.''
</P>
<P>
   The 10 NATO countries have also argued that the International
Court of Justice has no jurisdiction in this case for various
reasons, one of them being that Yugoslavia is not a member of the
United Nations. After the breakup of Yugoslavia, the United Nations
told the various parts to re-apply for membership, but Serbia and
Montenegro have refused to do so.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the United States and Britain, the other eight
countries involved in the lawsuit are Belgium, Canada, France,
Germany, Italy, the Netherlands, Portugal and Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the NATO governments dismissed Yugoslavia's case, some
international law experts gathered here have argued that Belgrade
is at least partly on solid legal ground. They say NATO has indeed
sought no U.N. approval for its attack on Yugoslavia while the
``humanitarian intervention'' that NATO says it is carrying out is
still at best a very tenuous concept in international law.
</P>
<P>
   But legal scholars here have also remarked that Yugoslavia is
bringing its case to the Peace Palace, which is less than half a
mile from another U.N. court, the Yugoslav war crimes tribunal,
which Belgrade refuses to recognize. It has consistently scoffed at
the indictments and arrest warrants issued by the tribunal and of
late it has even refused to accept tribunal documents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
