u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SONY-MUSIC-ONLINE-NYT     05-11 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SONY-MUSIC-ONLINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONY, FOLLOWING UNIVERSAL, TO SELL DIGITAL MUSIC ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sony Music Entertainment says it will begin selling songs online
in digital form using Microsoft technology, accelerating the rush
of record companies to the Internet even before the industry
settles on a common standard.
</P>
<P>
   Sony's plan, being announced Wednesday, follows an announcement
last week by the largest record company, Universal Music, that it
would distribute music online in digital form by the end of the
year. The moves indicate the companies' eagerness to take advantage
of the growing electronic commerce market.
</P>
<P>
   Sony said that as early as midsummer it plans to begin selling
singles from its artists, who include Mariah Carey, Celine Dionne
and Will Smith. Prices will be comparable to those of singles
purchased in retail stores, said Fred Ehrlich, general manager for
new technology and business development for Sony.
</P>
<P>
   Sony said it would use Microsoft's Windows Media 4.0, a
technology to compress music into digital form, store it and make
it available for download. It is among a handful of alternatives to
MP3, a format widely used on the Internet to download music but
loathed by the music industry because it lacks safeguards against
piracy.
</P>
<P>
   The Windows Media 4.0 technology will permit songs to be
downloaded through the Internet and stored or copied to a computer
hard disk, compact disk or floppy disk. But the software will
prevent songs from being played unless the user pays for them or
meets other licensing agreements, said Will Poole, senior director
of marketing and business development for Microsoft's streaming
media division.
</P>
<P>
   The music industry has created a consortium called the Secure
Digital Music Initiative to create standards by June 30 for
distributing music digitally _ standards that electronics makers
can then use for portable digital music devices.
</P>
<P>
   Ehrlich said Sony was not seeking to break ranks with the
consortium and would wait until the June standards are released
before beginning to sell music digitally. ``It doesn't hurt the
record industry to try to establish relationships in anticipation''
of the standards, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Sony would sell only singles at the outset because most
consumers do not yet have the high-speed connections that would
make downloading an album practical.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Nathanson, an international media analyst for Sanford C.
Bernstein &AMP; Co., a New York-based investment research and
management company, said the agreement provided a major boost for
Microsoft's technology, which record companies had been slow to
embrace.
</P>
<P>
   Universal Music, for example, is using competing software from
Intertrust Technologies Corp. of Sunnyvale, Calif. Microsoft
unveiled its software last month and plans a final version by
summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
