A3089 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GROW-SFCHRON &LR;      05-11 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Making Web Searches Easier
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Peter Sinton &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  Hunting for information online about starting and
financing a business can be very frustrating. It is easy to get
lost or overwhelmed. Are there ways to narrow the search and get
more targeted information?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer:  &LR; You have identified one of the common problems of Web
searches. It's sometimes like finding something in the dark. You
know it's there but it's hard putting your fingers on it.
</P>
<P>
   However, there are increasingly smart online search services. In
fact, two of them are local companies that got financing in the
past quarter and are planning public stock offerings.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's Looksmart.com ( &LR; www.looksmart.com &LR; ) has 140
editorial staff who review hundreds of thousands of Web sites and
list them by neat categories. For example, you can hit the Business
&AMP; Finance tab and get a menu of everything from business
professions to U.S. regional businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Hit the Small Business tab and get another dozen categories such
as Advice &AMP; Guides, Home Business and Venture Capital. Click
Venture Capital and up pops a list of information sources with
two-line descriptions of the site as well as links to the home
pages of scores of alphabetically listed VC firms.
</P>
<P>
   Under Government &AMP; Law, there are links to the U.S. Small
Business Administration and most sites of interest to
entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   Berkeley's Ask Jeeves Inc. ( &LR; www.askjeeves.com &LR; ) answers more
than 1 million questions a day from Internet users who can pose
their queries in plain English rather than typing in single words
or setting them apart with instructions parameters AND or NOT.
</P>
<P>
   For example, ask ``Where can I find venture capital?'' and Ask
Jeeves responds with five related questions that you can click to
get more information: These include ``Where can I find a list of
venture capitalists?'' and ``Where can I find advice on how to
obtain venture capital?''
</P>
<P>
   However, ask a complicated question like ``What venture capital
firms specialize in Internet startups?'' and Ask Jeeves is often
stumped.
</P>
<P>
   Registration a Business
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have an Internet consulting business that is planning to
incorporate and I wonder if I need a city business license to do
something as mundane as open a business bank/checking account?
People want to give us checks made out to the business and we have
not set this up.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; A: Get thee to City Hall. It sounds like you are operating a
business and getting paid for services without registering with the
city.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco requires that all businesses located within the
city and county file for a Business Tax Registration Certificate
within 15 days of starting business. The annual charge is just $25
if gross receipts are below $15,000 and you have no employees. For
businesses with employees, the fee runs from $150 to $500 depending
on how much they pay in taxes. The certificate must be renewed by
October 31 for the following calendar year.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco taxpayer assistance officer Peter Chou suggests
that you go to San Francisco City Hall, 1 Dr. Carlton B. Goodlett
Place. Check in with the county clerk's office in Room 168 to see
if the fictitious business name you plan to use is available.
</P>
<P>
   Then go to the tax collector's office, Room 140, and fill out
the application, register the name and pay the fee. The business
license is mailed out approximately 10 days after the payment is
received.
</P>
<P>
   For more information call (415) 554-4400 or visit the Web site
 &LR; www.ci.sf.ca.us/tax &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   You should also verify that the area in which you wish to do
business is zoned for that purpose. Zoning information can be
obtained from the Zoning and Planning Department at 1660 Mission
St. Their phone number is (415) 558-6377.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send small-business questions to  &LR; entrepreneurs(at &LR; 
 &LR; sign)sfgate.com &LR;  or to Peter Sinton, Grow a Business column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
