<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3092 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS &LR;      05-11 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA, RUSSIA SEE BOMBING HALT NECESSARY STEP TO PEACE TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Chinese and Russian leaders agreed Tuesday that
NATO's bombing of Yugoslavia must stop before peace negotiations
can be held, but NATO and US officials insisted there would be no
pause in the air campaign until all their conditions are met for
halting persecution of ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   While protests outside the US Embassy in Beijing and other
American facilities in China abated substantially, official anger
at last Friday's bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade
remained white-hot.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan refused to speak with US Secretary
of State Madeleine K. Albright. President Jiang Zemin called the
bombing a provocation to 1.2 billion Chinese people. The leading
government-controlled newspaper, People's Daily, dismissed as a lie
the US claim that the bombing, which killed three people and
injured 20, was accidental.
</P>
<P>
   Viktor Chernomyrdin, Russia's special envoy on the Kosovo
crisis, said after meeting with Jiang in Beijing that despite NATO
rejection of Russian and Chinese demands that the bombing stop,
work should continue on a plan worked out by Russia and the seven
richest industrial nations last week to get Yugoslavian forces out
of Kosovo and deploy international peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   NATO says it launched the bombing campaign, entering its 50th
day Wednesday, to stop Yugoslavian forces, which are dominated by
the Serbian ethnic group, from abusing ethnic Albanians who make up
90 percent of the population in Yugoslavia's Kosovo province. More
than 700,000 people have fled Kosovo, often in the face of armed
threats from Serbs, since the campaign began.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin met with Jiang in an attempt to keep China from
blocking UN Security Council approval of the peacekeeping scheme.
He then returned to Moscow, where he is to meet Wednesday with US
Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott. The Russian envoy said he
had new proposals to discuss with Talbott but provided no
specifics.
</P>
<P>
   US State Department spokesman James P. Rubin said the bombing of
the Chinese Embassy would not have ``any effect whatsoever on the
pace of diplomacy or the military campaign'' because China would
not block a proposal that would end the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   In other major Kosovo news Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
   -- NATO and US officials said there are no indications that the
withdrawal of forces announced by Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic on Sunday actually is occurring, and added there is clear
evidence that fighting between the Kosovo Liberation Army and
Yugoslavian forces continues. Yugoslavia had said it was beginning
a partial withdrawal because the KLA was defeated and dispersed.
</P>
<P>
   -- NATO launched some of its heaviest air raids to date,
striking airfields, petroleum storage and production facilities,
tanks, artillery, and military command posts throughout Serbia in
attacks described as ``very successful'' by German Major General
Walter Jertz, who gave the alliance's daily military report. NATO
also said it would begin flying missions against Yugoslavia from
Hungary and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   -- The United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees said it was
running out of funds to deal with the crisis and warned that
tensions were rising in Macedonia, where refugee camps are
overcrowded and and the ethnically Slavic, Christian majority is
uncomfortable with the influx of more than 200,000 ethnic
Albanians, who are Muslim. But Macedonian Foreign Minister
Aleksandar Dimitrov said some of the problems could be attributed
to excessive bureaucracy and insensitivity on the part of the UN
agency.
</P>
<P>
   -- China, which already had suspended a variety of military,
arms control and human rights contacts with the United States,
canceled a planned visit next week by Gen. Charles Krulak,
commandant of the Marine Corps. Pentagon officials said it also
appeared unlikely that Defense Secretary William S. Cohen would be
able to visit China as planned in June.
</P>
<P>
   -- Legal representatives of the 19 NATO countries participating
in the bombing, appearing before the International Court of Justice
in The Hague, concluded their defense against charges made to the
court by Yugoslavia that NATO was committing genocide in the
Balkans. The NATO representatives said the campaign is a legally
justified intervention aimed at ending a humanitarian catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   China is making four demands related to the bombing of its
embassy _ an open and official apology to the government and people
of China, a thorough investigation, public disclosure of the
results, and severe punishment of those responsible.
</P>
<P>
   US officials stressed that President Clinton, Albright, and
other NATO leaders have apologized and expressed regret repeatedly,
but only Tuesday were these apologies conveyed to the Chinese
public by the government-controlled media _ implying that
withholding the apologies whipped up the protesters who stoned and
assaulted the US Embassy in Beijing over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin, from the State Department, said the bombing is being
thoroughly investigated ``to see how this mistake could have
occurred and to ensure that it does not happen again.'' He said the
investigation is in a preliminary stage, and that the US ``will
consider appropriate action'' when it is completed. He made no
commitment either to reveal the full results of the investigation
or to punish those responsible for the error.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu dismissed explanations that the
bombing resulted from misinformation by CIA target planners.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could the joint intelligence source of the most powerful
military alliance in the world mistakenly identify the location of
a large diplomatic mission with a big courtyard, a plate on the
front door and flying the national flag?'' Zhu said to reporters at
a briefing.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the sniping between the UN refugee agency and the
Macedonian government, there were other ominous signs Tuesday from
that former Yugoslav republic, whose stability is vital to
containing the fighting in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   UN personnel said trains loaded with refugees were arriving at
Blace, on the Macedonia-Kosovo border, letting a few hundred people
off and returning into Kosovo still almost full. It appeared the
Serbs would be able to unleash a new flood of refugees on the
over-stressed Macedonian camps and government virtually on a
moment's notice.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to relieve the pressure on Macedonia by transferring
some of the refugees to neighboring Albania are faltering, the UN
said, because refugees are resisting relocation out of fear they
will not be able to leave from Albania for Europe or North America.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees being evacuated from the region have come largely from
Macedonia to relieve ethnic and political tension there. Relief
agencies had planned to move 6,000 refugees from Macedonia between
last Thursday and Sunday but could find only 650 volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   In the biggest day of evacuations yet, 2,242 refugees left
Macedonia Monday, most to the United States, Canada, Turkey, or
Ireland. About 38,400 people have been evacuated from the region so
far.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
