<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3094 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSALYNN-CARTER-ART-N     05-11 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSALYNN-CARTER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO FIRST LADIES, SO ALIKE AND SO DIFFERENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ark., Ga., Kent.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ She was the prelude to Hillary Rodham Clinton, a
quietly rebellious first lady of the late 1970s who sat in on
Cabinet meetings, pushed Congress to pass mental health legislation
_ and was asked by her party to run for U.S. senator from Georgia
after her husband left the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even consider it,'' Rosalynn Carter said last week in
a 39th-floor suite of the Waldorf-Astoria Hotel, where she was
ensconced with her Secret Service agents during a visit to New
York. ``What would I have done in Washington with Jimmy at home?''
</P>
<P>
   Home was Plains, Ga., population 700 or so. But what about
taking the defeated president to Washington as a Senate spouse?
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Carter smiled at the thought: ``I think the question
answers itself.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Mrs. Clinton, Mrs. Carter said she hadn't had a real
conversation with her since 1992. ``I've seen her at maybe two
events,'' Mrs. Carter said, squirming. ``This is embarrassing.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's office said Tuesday that one event was former
President Nixon's funeral and another was a 1997 Habitat for
Humanity house-building in Kentucky, where Mrs. Clinton and Mrs.
Carter installed vinyl siding.)
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Carter did manage to say that she has ``a lot of respect''
for Mrs. Clinton, although she did not exactly endorse the first
lady's potential Senate campaign from New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's up to her, if she wants to do it,'' Mrs. Carter
said. ``She's so well educated, and so capable. I think she
probably would really like to continue to use her knowledge and
influence. I can understand why she wants to run for the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   The club of living former First Ladies has a membership of five:
Mrs. Carter, Betty Ford, Barbara Bush, Nancy Reagan and Lady Bird
Johnson. As a wife of a former Southern governor and a close
political partner of her husband, Mrs. Carter is by far the most
like Mrs. Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But there has been bad blood between the Clintons and Carters
for nearly two decades, ever since Jimmy Carter sent several
hundred Cuban refugees from the Mariel boatlift to Arkansas,
creating a political crisis for then Gov. Bill Clinton, who in part
blamed Carter for his gubernatorial re-election defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, Carter said he felt ignored by the Clinton White
House, while the Clintons complained that the former president was
meddling in foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us back to Rosalynn Carter, the political wife who
has always kept the names and carried the slights. ``When they
first went to Washington, he was a Southern governor,'' she said of
Clinton. ``And Jimmy had not been re-elected. And I think they
wanted to detach themselves a little from that. And I can
understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Carter was in town to receive an award and to promote a
paperback edition of ``Helping Someone With Mental Illness,'' her
book on mental health. She is 71, fit, shy and self-contained,
although she warmed up toward the end of an hourlong talk.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Mrs. Clinton, who is 20 years younger, Mrs. Carter never
seemed frustrated as the political spouse, although she has a
clear-eyed view of what people demand of the president's wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they want to hurt the president, they can jump on the first
lady,'' Mrs. Carter said. ``But what happened to Hillary is really
interesting to me. Because when she was working on policy she was
criticized. But as soon as she stood by her man, everyone loved
her.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Mrs. Clinton, Mrs. Carter lobbied to pass legislation, in
her case the Mental Health Systems Act of 1980, although the
financing died under President Reagan. But unlike Mrs. Clinton, who
testified before Congress and then failed in her efforts for health
care reform, Mrs. Carter worked with less fireworks. ``They
probably would have treated me the same way if I'd gone to Congress
and said, `This is my bill and I want you to pass this,''' Mrs.
Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Mrs. Carter did testify about the mental health
legislation before a Senate committee, as she recounts in ``First
Lady From Plains,'' her autobiography. ``We could find a record of
only one other first lady who had testified before Congress _
Eleanor Roosevelt on behalf of the coal miners,'' Mrs. Carter
proudly wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Carter said she spends a third of her time traveling, a
third at the Carter Center in Atlanta and a third at home in
Plains. ``It's a great life,'' she said. ``What you learn when you
get out of the White House is that you still have the resources.''
Of course, ``if a first lady goes anywhere, she gets a lot more
attention than a former first lady does. But a former first lady
gets enough.''
</P>
<P>
   One of her good friends these days is Betty Ford. The husbands,
antagonists after the 1976 presidential election, have long since
patched things up.) Mrs. Carter and Mrs. Ford have taken a trip to
Washington together, where they stayed at the Hay-Adams Hotel and
lobbied Congress on Mrs. Clinton's health care bill _ Mrs. Carter
to ensure that it covered mental health, Mrs. Ford to see that it
included substance abuse. ``It didn't have what any of us wanted,''
she said. Mrs. Ford ``got together the Republicans, and I got
together the Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Carter said she has long got over her bitterness from her
husband's loss to Ronald Reagan. Even so, ``my biggest regret in
life was that Jimmy was defeated.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-99 2035EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
