u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-1STLD-WRI     05-11 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. REJECTS CALL TO STOP YUGOSLAV ATTACK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Sub for minor editing) 
 
By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ China and Russia called on NATO Tuesday to halt its
air campaign against Yugoslavia in the wake of the mistaken bombing
of the Chinese Embassy, but the United States rejected the demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to continue with prosecuting the air campaign
until the NATO conditions are met, and that alone will be the cause
of any suspension of the bombing,'' said White House spokesman Joe
Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   In Beijing, Chinese President Jiang Zemin met with Russian envoy
Viktor Chernomyrdin and they agreed that the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization must stop its attacks against Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic's forces before peace talks begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main principle is to stop the bombing,'' Chernomyrdin
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Chernomyrdin also urged the Chinese not to block a U.N.
Security Council resolution that Russia and the seven world
economic powers crafted last week that would demand Milosevic
remove his troops and allow an international security force into
Kosovo to protect the ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang, in his first comments about the embassy bombing, called
it a ``provocation'' against the people of China. Jiang has not
responded to a letter sent by President Clinton on Sunday that
apologized and offered to discuss the incident by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has demonstrated the enthusiasm, will and power of the
great patriotism of the Chinese people,'' the media reported Jiang
as telling Chernomyrdin. ``The whole country is now determined to
study and work harder, so as to develop the national economy
continuously, enhance national strength, and fight back with
concrete deeds against the barbaric act of U.S.-led NATO.''
</P>
<P>
   Chinese media reported for the first time about the apology made
by President Clinton and NATO. The protests that have made
Ambassador James Sasser a hostage in the embassy appeared to ebb.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview with NBC-TV's ``Today'' show, Sasser
said there were only a few hundred protesters compared to 10,000
Sunday. ``We're not getting nearly as many rocks thrown at us, and
the crowds are much smaller,'' Sasser said.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese police escorted only small numbers of protesters to the
embassy and prevented them from carrying rocks. Sasser said the
front of the embassy looks ``like a war zone'' after three days of
peltings by rocks. Sasser also said he and staff members so feared
the embassy would be overrun Sunday that they began destroying
sensitive information and disabling machinery.
</P>
<P>
   The roiling of Sino-American relations began Friday when a B-2
Stealth bomber attacked the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade based on
faulty information. The Central Intelligence Agency conceded using
an old map of Belgrade that did not include the location of the
Chinese Embassy, which moved to a newer facility in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen, appearing before a Senate
appropriations subcommittee, said the Chinese government inflamed
passions by suggesting the embassy bombing was deliberate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a difference between righteous indignation and
calculated exploitation,'' Cohen said of China's actions. Cohen
again explained the bombing resulted from an ``intelligence
failure.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen also disputed Belgrade's claim that some Yugoslavian
troops are being withdrawn after completing their mission to rid
Kosovo of rebels. Troops stormed into the Serbian province in March
and uprooted nearly 1.3 million of the 1.7 million ethnic Albanians
that make up the majority. More than 700,000 have fled to Albanian
and Macedonian refugee camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Number one, we have seen no evidence of any partial pullout,
and number two, a partial pullout would mean a total victory for
him,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   The defense chief repeated NATO demands that Milosevic withdraw
all his forces. NATO wants Yugoslavia to allow the return of the
Kosovar refugees and allow an international security force into the
province.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen appeared before the Senate panel as Congress prepares to
vote on Clinton's request for $6 billion to fund the United States'
cost of the NATO operation.
</P>
<P>
   The House nearly doubled the president's request as it offered
the Pentagon more money while the Senate also had added a series of
pork-barrel projects. Clinton has threatened to veto the bill.
</P>
<P>
   NATO operations have intensified in recent days as warplanes
aimed at nearly two dozen targets in Serbia and Kosovo. NATO also
reported Yugoslavian forces appeared to be continuing firefights
with Kosovar rebels.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear that there is no pause in NATO's operation Allied
Force, which now enters its 49th day,'' said NATO spokesman Jamie
Shea.
</P>
<P>
   Shea also said he hoped China would ``work constructively with
Russia'' to pass a U.N. resolution calling on Milosevic to accept
the conditions reached by NATO, Russia and seven world economic
powers.
</P>
<P>
   At the State Department, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
made her fourth direct appeal to Serbs, the ethnic majority in the
Yugoslav federation.
</P>
<P>
   ``When this conflict is over, good and decent Serbs will be
appalled at what has been done in your name,'' Albright said. She
also dismissed the comments of one Yugoslavian government official
who said the ethnic Albanians were paid actors in a NATO-directed
film.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to see a democratic Serbia enter modern Europe and
join the community of Euro-Atlantic democracies. That is where you
truly belong. But first, you must put the ugly specter of `ethnic
cleansing,' this dark chapter from Europe's past, behind you once
and for all,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
