<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3096 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENATE-JUVENILE-BOS &LR;      05-11 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATE-JUVENILE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE DEBATES JUVENILE CRIME BILL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHNGTON _ The Senate took up a $1 billion juvenile crime bill
Tuesday, three weeks after the Littleton, Colo., shooting tragedy,
giving both parties new ammunition for old positions on how to cope
with violent crime.
</P>
<P>
   In an emotional opening day of debate, Republicans were
galvanized to crack down on youth crime with tougher laws, while
Democrats pushed for more crime prevention programs and stricter
gun-control laws.
</P>
<P>
   Although the two parties appear to have reached a compromise on
some key provisions, the battlelines were drawn immediately, with
the Democratic leadership unveiling three amendments to the
tough-on-crime Republican bill as soon as debate began.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican bill, which has languished in different forms in
the Senate for two years, would give prosecutors rather than judges
the power to try children as young as 14 years of age in adult
courts. It also would enhance penalties for a variety of violent
offenses and target gang-related crime in particular.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are few issues that will come before the Senate this
Congress that touch the lives of more of our fellow Americans than
our national response to juvenile crime,'' said Senator Orrin G.
Hatch, the Utah Republican and chairman of the Judiciary Committee.
``Crime and delinquency among our young people is a problem that
troubles us in our neighborhoods, schools and parks.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch and his Democratic counterpart, Senator Joseph Biden of
Delaware, hammered out a compromise Tuesday that would set aside
roughly $513 million in federal funds for drug treatment, school
counseling and crime prevention programs.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise also would provide $50 million to hire
prosecutors to target juvenile offenders and bring them into
federal courts.
</P>
<P>
   But agreement appeared to end there.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are emphasizing measures that would require the
entertainment industry to take responsibility for marketing violent
images to children and to encourage the government to enforce laws
already on the books.
</P>
<P>
   ``Passing a law sounds good, but to really maximize our impact
... we've got to prosecute the laws we've got,'' said Senator Jeff
Sessions, Republican of Alabama. He said there has been a dramatic
drop in the number of juveniles prosecuted in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are pushing crime prevention and treatment strategies,
and some lawmakers want to add to the bill the most significant
gun-control legislation since the 1993 Brady law.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire nation will be watching the Senate this week,''
said Senator Charles E. Schumer, Democrat of New York. ``They will
be watching to see if we have the will to stand with the American
people, or if we will buckle to the few remaining extremists in the
gun lobby who want gridlock.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have agreed to include in the bill a ``juvenile
Brady'' provision that would forbid juveniles with a felony record
from ever buying a gun, and they might go along with changes in the
way gun shows are regulated.
</P>
<P>
   But few have said they will support Democratic proposals to
reimpose a three-day waiting period on buying a handgun, to require
background checks and a paper trail on gun-show purchases, or to
mandate that guns be sold with trigger locks.
</P>
<P>
   Gun-control forces, however, might get a boost in the wake of
the Colorado shootings, according to Republican aides. How
Republicans will respond to Democratic amendments proposed by the
minority leadership, including one crafted by Senator Edward M.
Kennedy, is also unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's initiative is modeled on Boston's successful effort to
link parents, schools, mental health and law enforcement resources
in the fight to prevent and respond to youth violence.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, the Senate chambers echoed with dramatic
calls by members to uncover the roots of youth violence.
</P>
<P>
   Senators Joseph I. Lieberman, Democrat of Connecticut, and John
McCain, Republican of Arizona, proposed establishing a national
commission on youth violence to formalize the process of exploring
the problem and a solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most basic and profound responsibility that our culture _
any culture _ has is raising its children,'' said McCain. ``We are
failing that responsibility and the extent of our failure is being
measured in the deaths and injuries of kids in the schoolyard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
