<HEADLINE>
A GOVERNOR IS CANDID ABOUT HIS U-TURN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Questions posed to Minnesota Governor  &UR; Jesse Ventura  &LR; by the gay
and lesbian magazine the Advocate focus on gay and lesbian issues _
he's sympathetic _ but the most surprising part of the interview is
the governor's honesty about a post-election change of heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you support the death penalty?'' the Advocate asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to,'' answered Ventura, ``until I became governor,
because I wouldn't want that burden put on my shoulders. I wouldn't
want to have to make the choice of whether one lives or dies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately, we don't have the death penalty in Minnesota.
Government shouldn't have the right to take a life. But life in
prison should be life, without parole.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLOSE LISTENING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The M &LR; ay 14  &LR; installment of ``Lost &AMP; Found Sound,'' NPR's
series featuring sounds recorded in the past 100 years, focuses on
the tradition of the lector, a person hired to read aloud to
workers making cigars in Florida in the early part of this century.
Spanish-language newspapers would be read in the mornings;
afternoon readings were from classics by  &UR; Miguel &LR; 
 &UR; Cervantes &LR; , &UR; Emile Zola  &LR; and  &UR; Jules Verne &LR; , among others.
</P>
<P>
   When the lectors were thrown out of work by the advent of
automated cigar-making equipment, many became Spanish-language
radio announcers. The show is produced by  &UR; Nikki Silva  &LR; and  &UR; Davia &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Nelson. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; George Leonard &LR; , a man who reads reviews, says that the word
``quirky'' has become passe, and it's amazing today ``how many
movies, plays, television dramas and novels are either `nuanced' or
`edgy' or both.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Reading a recent issue of the Spanish-language newspaper El
Mundo,  &UR; Andrew Demcak &LR;  noticed an apparent example of Spanish
spell-check at work. A photograph of  &UR; Cameron Diaz  &LR; was captioned
``Camaron Dias,'' which he says means ``shrimp days.''
</P>
