</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMEY PROPOSES JULY DEBATE ON CAMPAIGN FINANCE REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a new sign of flexibility by the Republican
leadership, the House majority leader said Tuesday that he thought
the House should consider legislation by the end of July to
overhaul campaign finance laws.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dick Armey, R-Texas, the minority leader, has steadily
opposed the bipartisan legislation to ban the unlimited,
unregulated donations to political parties known as soft money.
House leaders have talked about a debate by the end of September,
but Armey said Tuesday that he thought the House should get the
debate over with. Last year the bill passed the House handily
despite the opposition of the Republican leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``My own view is that we should move it by the end of July,''
Armey said at his weekly news conference. ``I think a lot of
activists will be more comfortable with that. It will just be a
more pleasant experience to take it up. We have a lot of good
people with a lot of good ideas. Give them a fair shot on the floor
and walk though it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear whether Armey was signaling a change of heart
by Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., as well. Hastert has said he
will schedule the debate by the end of September. But he also told
several dozen Republican moderates last week that he would consider
their plea for an earlier vote.
</P>
<P>
   Michele Davis, a spokeswoman for Armey, said the majority leader
was simply stating his longstanding position. Senior Republicans
said Hastert could be leaning Armey's way.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Calif., the chief sponsor of the main
bipartisan bill to restrict soft money and some forms of issue
advertising, said Tuesday: ``July is certainly better than saying
we will deal with it in September. But now is better than July. I
think we should do it now and get it over with.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a July date for the debate could pose a tactical
quandary for the bipartisan coalition working to pass the
legislation, whose Democratic sponsor is Rep. Martin T. Meehan of
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The group has been fighting for a vote before Memorial Day or
before the July 4 congressional recess to put pressure on the
Senate, where the bill died last year in a filibuster. And 192
Democrats have signed a special discharge petition in an effort to
go around the Republican leadership and force the measure to the
House floor for a vote. They need 218 signers to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans are reluctant to challenge Hastert, and many of
those who support an overhaul of the campaign finance laws would be
unlikely to sign the petition if their speaker were willing to meet
them halfway and hold a vote in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``My own preference, I say this very definitely, would be to do
this before the July 4 recess,'' said Rep. Marge Roukema, R-N.J.
``But there are a whole number of people who thought that before
the August recess would be satisfactory.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Democrats said that a vote by the end of July would still
leave the Senate dealing with the issue after its August recess,
when Congress is usually consumed with trying to pass spending
bills before the Oct. 1 start of the new federal fiscal year.
Meehan said this would make it harder for Senate sponsors of the
bill to use every tactic at their disposal to pass campaign finance
legislation, because they would not want to risk a government
shutdown by holding up spending bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Armey's announcement today that late July would be a
reasonable time seems like just another attempt to kill meaningful
reform by delay,'' Meehan said. ``Reformers in the Senate know that
if they receive the House reform bill any later than the beginning
of July, they won't have enough time to navigate the Senate bill to
legislative success.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Republicans oppose the Shays-Meehan measure, in part
because their party raises more money than the Democratic Party and
in part because they say the measure imposes unconstitutional
limits on free speech. Besides banning soft money, it would limit
the ability of outside advocacy groups to run thinly disguised
campaign advertisements in the period before elections.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., who has led the Senate fight
against the bill, says he will do so again, vowing to kill it one
more time. He recently compared the bill to a character played by
Glenn Close, taking one last stab at the man she was stalking in
the movie ``Fatal Attraction.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This issue springs back,'' McConnell said. ``You think you've
killed it and it's back again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
