A3106 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-TRIPPIN'-SPI &LR;      05-11 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-TRIPPIN'-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TRIPPIN' A NASTY, DULL, PREDICTABLE TAKE ON THE SAME OLD THEME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Seattle) _ There's an old Marvin Gaye song that asks, ``How
long can this keep goin' on?'' Hopefully, not very much longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trippin''' is another in a line of recent movies that are dull
variations on the theme of high school boy/girl wants girl/boy,
gets boy/girl through subversive method, then loses girl/boy and
ends up making up with boy/girl at the senior prom. They're an
insult to everyone.
</P>
<P>
   The groove worn by movies like ``Can't Hardly Wait'' and ``10
Things I Hate About You'' is woefully thin. How long can it be
before kids get tired of such sexist and denigrating fare?
</P>
<P>
   ``Trippin''' which is about yet another trio of high school boys
who fool girls into sleeping with them by promising them a prom
date, is on the lowest rung of the ladder yet.
</P>
<P>
   The teenagers in Gary Hardwick's script are typical high school
kids concerned with the usual woes: Where do I go to college and
how can I get a date for the prom?
</P>
<P>
   For Greg Reed (Deon Richmond), college is a non-event and the
girl of his dreams is unattainable. He retreats into his fantasy
life _ trippin', his friends and family call it. There he's a rock
star, a computer whiz, a lover beyond compare _ in short,
everything the real Greg is not.
</P>
<P>
   Greg has a huge crush on Cinny Hawkins (Maia Campbell), the best
looking and smartest girl in school. She's sure to be prom queen
but her cling-on boyfriend hardly lets Greg get close. But Cinny is
no snob. She befriends Greg and believes him when he lies to her
and tells her he's been accepted at UCLA. She thinks he has a
future. Only Greg, his two loser best friends and forgiving family
know the truth.
</P>
<P>
   So when Cinny breaks up with her beau and accepts Greg's offer
to go to the prom, how long can the charade go on before Cinny
realizes Greg is just another confused flake who doesn't know who
he is or what he wants?
</P>
<P>
   The filmmakers have the same problem. After making Greg out to
be a sincere guy, they slather the closing credits with sexist,
crude remarks about Greg's ``scoring'' with Cinny. It's a cheap
shot designed to titillate the lowest of the low.
</P>
<P>
   The script holds no surprises. It's a nasty, dull, predictable
take on the same old theme. It doesn't matter if the cast is black,
white, gay or straight, Hollywood is stuck in a rut. Hopefully, the
tired old story will soon wear itself out at the box office and the
studios will be forced to re-examine what teenagers are _ as well
as what they want to see.
</P>
<P>
   Trippin'. Directed by David Raynr. Written by Gary Hardwick.
Cast: Deon Richmond, Maia Campbell, Donald Adeosun Faison, Guy
Torry. Rogue Pictures. 92 minutes. Rated R for sexual content,
language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-99 2042EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990511.0347 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3108 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHUNG-COX     05-11 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHUNG-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chung offers own story to House committee
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Former Democratic fund-raiser Johnny Chung finally
got the chance Tuesday to give his side of the story, telling a
congressional panel that he received $300,000 from a high-ranking
Chinese official and was offered more to keep quiet about it.
</P>
<P>
   But Chung told members of the House Government Reform and
Oversight Committee that the $300,000 wire transfer from the head
of China's military intelligence agency was a ``business
investment,'' not an attempt by the Chinese to influence American
elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my opinion that much of what these people wanted from me
had less to do with influencing any election as it was to gain what
most Americans want from our system _influence and the ability to
develop relationships with important people,'' Chung said.
</P>
<P>
   Chung, an immigrant who worked his way from being a busboy at a
Holiday Inn to a successful blast fax business owner, viewed
campaign donations as his ticket to the upper echelons of power.
</P>
<P>
   ``I began to realize that I could also get a little something
back for giving money,'' said Chung, who once compared donations to
subway tokens in the access they bought at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   From 1994 to 1996, Chung said, he received more than $2 million
from his business contacts in China. Less than 20 percent went to
political campaigns, Chung said, none of it directly.
</P>
<P>
   Chung testified that he often took Chinese businessmen and
officials to political events, paying their way since it is illegal
for foreigners to donate to a campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for being a big donor, Chung said, he was allowed to
visit the White House more than 50 times. He gave $366,000 from
1994 to 1996 to the Democratic National Committee, all of which has
since been returned.
</P>
<P>
   Access to the White House impressed Chung's foreign business
contacts. Pictures with politicians are ``worth their weight in
gold'' in China, Chung said.
</P>
<P>
   Chung also made several new accusations during his five-hour
testimony claiming, among other things, that:
</P>
<P>
   _ Mark Middleton, a former senior White House aide, allegedly
accepted $500,000 from Asia Pulp and Paper in September 1996.
</P>
<P>
   _ Former Arkansas restaurateur and longtime Clinton friend
Charlie Trie asked the Chinese government for $1 million to support
President Clinton and the Democrats. Trie in 1996 offered more than
$600,000 from questionable sources to Clinton's legal defense fund,
which rejected the donations. Trie goes on trial Monday in Little
Rock, charged with obstructing a U.S. Senate investigation into
campaign fund-raising abuses by ordering the concealment of
subpoenaed documents in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   _ After pleading guilty to making illegal campaign contributions
to the Clinton campaign, Chung was threatened and offered money
from Beijing ``to take care of'' his legal expenses and family if
he refused to cooperate with the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Barr (R-Ga.), a member of the panel, said Chung's
testimony shows there ``was a plan by the Chinese government to
funnel money into the president's re-election efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   Barr said he is equally concerned about recent reports of
alleged espionage by the Chinese government at several U.S. nuclear
weapons laboratories and by Clinton's approval, announced Tuesday,
of a commercial satellite launch next month in China for the
Iridium global paging and telephone network.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're seeing is a breakdown of any barriers between our
government and China,'' Barr said. ``This administration has
transferred highly sensitive technology that far eclipses the
Rosenberg trial.''
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats scoffed at such claims, saying Chung's testimony
shows the Democratic National Committee had no idea that he was
receiving money from China.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Waxman (D-Calif.) asked how the committee could
believe anything Chung said when he has contradicted himself
several times and made allegations that, once investigated, turned
out to be false.
</P>
<P>
   Chung became a cooperating witness in the federal campaign
fund-raising investigation after pleading guilty to making illegal
contributions to Clinton and other Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Chung now has mixed feelings about the political system where he
won so much influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is your system,'' Chung told the lawmakers. ``I didn't
create it. If you guys don't like it, change it. Don't shout at me,
change it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Carr writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
