</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Column: Scheid Vineyards Wants to Pour Some Life Into
Annual  Meetings 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Mark Veverka &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Annual shareholder meetings suck.
</P>
<P>
   OK, there, I said it. Please excuse the graphic descriptor. But
after struggling to find a less abrasive adjective, I can think of
no other word that adequately expresses the unrelenting disdain I
hold for these horrendously rote rituals of corporate boredom.
</P>
<P>
   I strongly believe that I've earned the right to feel this way.
After nearly 15 years of covering public companies, I've easily
been to more than a hundred of these dreaded excuses for democratic
discourse.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, at Crain's Chicago Business, where I once was an
eager-to-please intern and later a jaded reporter, the
award-winning business weekly made it a practice to cover the
annual meetings of every public company in the greater Chicago
metropolitan area. The thinking was, a fight could always break
out, or at least it was assured that almost every public company
would grace the publication's pages at least once a year.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, while spring is a celebrated event for most
Chicagoans _ offering a welcome respite from yet another brutal
Midwestern winter _ it means weeks upon weeks of gosh-awful annual
meetings for the staffers at CCB.
</P>
<P>
   I drag out my annual meeting baggage to raise a point, however.
One publicly held company actually is attempting to change our
perception of these moribund affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Scheid Vineyards of Marina del Rey (Los Angeles County) is
daring to make its annual meeting this afternoon in San Francisco
easier to swallow _ so to speak. In this, Scheid's second year as a
public company, the grape grower is turning its annual meeting into
a big ol' wine tasting.
</P>
<P>
   Well, sort of. Contending that Wall Street may not yet fully
understand its industry, Scheid is using its shareholder meeting as
a platform for a wine industry symposium.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of holding a routine meeting at Scheid's corporate
headquarters in Southern California, the company opted to invite
some of the wine industry's top economists and financial experts,
hoping to demystify investing in publicly held vineyards, says
Chief Financial Officer Heidi Scheid.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our effort to educate the investment community. We're
trying to attract several groups (including) financial analysts,
money managers and individual investors,'' Scheid says.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the company chose to move its meeting from Los
Angeles to San Francisco's Ferry Building, bringing its story
closer to California's investing and wine-making centers.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Scheid isn't the first wine company to pour a glass
of wine at an annual meeting. Other publicly held vintners do that.
In fact, some vineyards, such as Chalone, throw elaborate
wine-tasting dinners for its shareholders. But because Scheid is
less a winemaker, per say (it makes only 5,000 cases of its
high-end wine a year), and more a producer of wine grapes, the
company aims to use the forum of its annual meeting to explain its
specialized niche in the industry, Scheid says.
</P>
<P>
   Scheid grows premium varietal wine grapes on about 6,000 acres
located mostly on the Central Coast in Monterey County. While it
provides grapes to such big-scale producers as Canadaigua and
Beringer (which both are publicly held), Scheid also supplies
smaller, upscale vineyards such as Hess Collection, Chalone and
Joseph Phelps.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Scheid has some explaining to do. Its stock is
trading at about $5 a share, down about 44 percent for the past 12
months, according to Bloomberg. Scheid's grape production declined
about 30 percent in 1998 due to lousy weather, reports financial
analyst Anton J. Brenner of Cruttendon Roth, which rates this
micro-cap a ``strong buy.'' Brenner argues that the stock is cheap
given that it is trading only five times its projected earnings for
1999.
</P>
<P>
   The bullish bet is that grape prices will rebound and the
premium wine market (brands between $7 and $12 a bottle) will
continue to grow. Overall, wine consumption is relatively flat in
the United States, but those who buy wine are drinking more bottles
of the premium stuff with fatter margins, says wine economist Jon
Fredrikson of Gomberg-Fredrikson of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby Boomers with some extra money in their pocket are going
crazy for these wines,'' Fredrikson says. ``That's where the action
is.''
</P>
<P>
   No ... the action very well could be, dare I say, at the Scheid
shareholders meeting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
