u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANADA-GOLD-FRAUD-NYT     05-11 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-GOLD-FRAUD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXECUTIVE IN BIG GOLD SCANDAL FACES INSIDER TRADING CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By TIMOTHY PRITCHARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ The vice-chairman of Bre-X Minerals Ltd. was charged
with insider trading and other securities law violations Tuesday in
connection with the company's fraudulent reports of a huge
Indonesian gold discovery three years ago, one of the biggest
financial scandals in Canada's history.
</P>
<P>
   The eight counts filed by the Ontario Securities Commission
against John Felderhof mark the first serious charges in the
scandal, which erased billions of dollars in shareholder value from
the company overnight when the gold discovery was found to be a
fake.
</P>
<P>
   Felderhof, who is also under investigation by the Royal Canadian
Mounted Police, could face two years in prison and millions of
dollars of fines and restitution if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Long considered a central figure in the scandal, Felderhof moved
to the Cayman Islands when suspicions about the legitimacy of gold
discovery at the Busang site in Indonesia came to light in 1996. It
is widely believed that he still resides in the Cayman Islands.
</P>
<P>
   Felderhof has been named a defendant in several class-action
lawsuits filed on behalf of investors who saw their shares, which
once traded at more than $200, plunge to pennies. He has said he
knew nothing about the fraud.
</P>
<P>
   The Ontario commission, Canada's chief market regulator, said in
a complaint filed with the Ontario Court of Justice that from April
24, 1996, to Sept. 10, 1996, Felderhof sold more than 2.7 million
shares of Bre-X for almost $84 million (Canadian), or about $58
million (U.S.) at current exchange rates, ``with knowledge of a
material fact pertaining to rights of Bre-X in relation to the
Busang properties that had not been generally disclosed.''
</P>
<P>
   The complaint also said that between June 20, 1996, and Feb. 17,
1997, Felderhof authorized or permitted news releases by Bre-X that
contained misleading or untrue estimates of gold reserves.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Groia, Felderhof's lawyer in Toronto, said the complaint
``came as a great surprise to us.'' Felderhof or his lawyer was
ordered to appear June 15.
</P>
<P>
   Bre-X, once a penny stock based in Calgary, Alberta, became one
of the greatest stock market sensations ever in Canada's mining
industry, historically known for speculative claims of riches.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bre-X's managers had no mining experience and the
company had no revenue or profit, the company's shares soared as it
promoted the Busang site as the biggest gold discovery in history,
containing more than 70 million ounces. Placed among listings in
the Toronto Stock Exchange's elite 300 index, its market
capitalization grew to more than $4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The company collapsed in bankruptcy, and its shares were
delisted in 1997 when an investigation found that the Indonesian
property was a fraud, fabricated by a Bre-X geologist, Michael de
Guzman. He later died in what the authorities called a suicide by
jumping out of a helicopter over the Indonesian jungle.
</P>
<P>
   David Walsh, Bre-X's chairman and a heavy promoter of the
company's stock, died about a year ago of an aneurysm at his
Bahamas estate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-99 2053EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990511.0353 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3118 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      05-11 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOWA: A STRAW POLL RESERVED FOR IOWANS 
VIRGINIA: FORESHADOWING REDISTRICTING BATTLE 
MASSACHUSETTS: THAT RESIGNATION? JUST CALL IT PREMATURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES JR.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In presidential politics, Iowa is best known for its
first-in-the-nation February caucuses. But earlier still, usually
in August of the preceding year, the state's Republicans gather in
Ames to talk up the coming caucuses and tease candidates and voters
a bit by conducting a presidential straw poll.
</P>
<P>
   Straw polls are, in truth, little more than straws in the wind.
Many national party leaders say they should be outlawed because
they are unscientific, subject to mischievous manipulation by
candidates and, ultimately, misleading and even harmful.
</P>
<P>
   But state party leaders _ the Democratic leaders in
Massachusetts being the latest example _ tend to schedule more of
them, not fewer, saying they build excitement.
</P>
<P>
   Front-runners see them as possible sources of embarrassment and
often try to avoid them, a tricky political move in and of itself.
Also-rans see opportunity in them.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Ames gathering often attracts as many as 10,000
participants _ including most presidential hopefuls _ it is, in the
end, a measure mainly of name recognition and the ability of
candidate organizations to haul in supporters and, if necessary,
pay their $25 entrance fees to Hilton Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, political professionals and many White House
hopefuls argue that the event's rules are so loose and its results
so often off-the-wall that there is no reason to take it seriously.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, they note, former Gov. Lamar Alexander of Tennessee
chartered two 727s to fly in supporters from back home. He finished
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, former Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas, the
front-runner going into the gathering, chartered a fleet of buses
to haul in the faithful from all over the Midwest. He ended up in a
tie for first place with Sen. Phil Gramm of Texas _ though he
ultimately went on to win the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1987 poll, Pat Robertson, the religious broadcaster,
upset and embarrassed the presumed front-runner at that point, Vice
President George Bush. But Bush went on to win the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   What to do?
</P>
<P>
   This year's Iowa straw poll will be conducted in Ames on Aug.
14. But unlike polls of the past, only Iowans will be permitted to
vote _ and only after producing proof of residency.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to make it Iowans-only so that it is a
high-quality event and means something when someone wins or someone
doesn't,'' the state's Republican chairman, Kayne Robinson, said
recently in announcing the new rules.
</P>
<P>
   VIRGINIA FORESHADOWS REDISTRICTING BATTLE
</P>
<P>
   The focus during election year 2000 will be mainly on the
presidential race and congressional contests. But on the ballot too
will be the election of new governors and legislatures in most
states.
</P>
<P>
   These will not, however, be your usual state races. Rather, they
will take on special political import because the winners will get
to preside over the Congressional and state legislative
redistricting that will begin after the 2000 federal census.
</P>
<P>
   It is an opportunity that comes once every 10 years. A rough
rule of thumb holds that the political party that controls both the
governor's office and the legislature in a state at that point can
redraw district lines so that 1 of every 5 districts tilts in its
favor.
</P>
<P>
   No surprise, then, that in Virginia, which holds its legislative
election this year rather than next, the scramble for control is
well underway, a forerunner of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. James S. Gilmore 3rd, a Republican, will not be on the
ballot, having been elected just two years ago. But the entire
Legislature, or General Assembly, is up, with the outcome a real
cliffhanger since Republicans hold only a 21 to 19 edge over
Democrats in the state Senate, while the House of Delegates is
evenly split, with 50 Democrats on one side and 49 Republicans and
a Republican-leaning independent on the other.
</P>
<P>
   Gilmore considers the fall vote so crucial to Republican
redistricting hopes that he recently broke one of the cardinal
rules of politics. He took sides in two House primary contests.
</P>
<P>
   There was much mumbling in the party that he was more interested
in pushing conservative candidates and a conservative legislative
agenda than pushing redistricting. And one of his Republican
predecessors, A. Linwood Holton Jr., a moderate, publicly chided
the governor, accusing him of abandoning the ``politics of
inclusion'' and violating the 11th Commandment of Republicanism:
never hurt a fellow Republican.
</P>
<P>
   But Gilmore stuck with his endorsements, saying he was only
trying to ``shape the Republican Party in a little different way''
so that it could go into the millennium in full political control
of the state.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats took heart from the divisive endorsements, with Craig
Bieber, the executive director of the state party, calling them an
``uncharacteristic lack of political judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, party officials announced that a former
Democratic congressman from Virginia, L.F. Payne, would head a
political action committee that would raise money both in and out
of the state to support Democratic efforts this year to grab
control of the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   THAT RESIGNATION? JUST CALL IT PREMATURE
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Martin Meehan, D-Mass., has decided not to honor the pledge
he made back in 1995 to leave Congress in early 2001 when his
fourth term expires. Meehan says that he has concluded that the
concept of term limits has no political merit and that he can
better serve his constituents by seeking re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts Republicans have yet to put up a candidate to
oppose him. But they say they may try to force him to honor his
pledge by hauling him into court.
</P>
<P>
   On what grounds?
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, when Meehan made his pledge, they say, he backed it up
by sending an official letter to the House clerk that read:
``Should I be elected to serve more than two additional terms, I
hereby resign.''
</P>
<P>
   The executive director of the Massachusetts Republican Party,
John Brockelman, vows to ``aggressively pursue'' the legal
ramifications of the letter.
</P>
<P>
   Meehan's rejoinder, though a spokesman: ``You can't resign from
a future Congress.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
