<HEADLINE>
EMPOWERMENT ZONES TOUTED FOR AREAS OF PERSISTENT POVERTY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ President Clinton urged the nation's business leaders
to help spread the nation's economic growth to stubborn pockets of
poverty by investing more in poor urban neighborhoods and rural
communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we ought not leave anybody behind when we go into
the 21st century,'' the president said after touring Atlanta's
Sweet Auburn Curb Market, located in an inner-city neighborhood
revived over the past decade with public and private money.
</P>
<P>
   Despite record unemployment nationally, Clinton said, many areas
of the country remain economically stagnant, some with jobless
rates double the national average.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that every American who's willing to work ought to
have a chance to do it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With 15 corporate executives and financiers in tow, Clinton flew
to Atlanta for a tour of the market on the eastern edge of downtown
and a discussion with local leaders and small-business owners on
ways to boost private investment in similar, economically
distressed communities.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet Auburn Curb Market, located near the Martin Luther King
Jr. Historic District, opened in 1923 and went into economic
decline in the late 1980s. In 1992, Atlanta officials pumped $4.9
million into restoring the market, which now features 24 small
businesses, including flower shops, food vendors, a seafood market
and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Another $8.3 million in federal money was pumped into the market
under an Empowerment Zone program initiated by Clinton in 1994. In
addition to loan guarantees, businesses in the market receive tax
credits for creating jobs, most of which went to residents of
nearby neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, the Clinton administration has designated the Lower
Rio Grande Valley and El Paso as Empowerment Zones, which qualifies
them for similar federally guaranteed loans and job training grants
for new businesses.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Houston is awaiting word on whether a 19-square-mile area including
downtown and surrounding neighborhoods will qualify for the
program.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, Clinton spent almost a half-hour touring Sweet
Auburn Curb Market before joining the discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important that we try to take this example to the
whole nation,'' Clinton said after his tour. ``I want people to see
and believe it can be done in their communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving for Atlanta, Clinton summoned corporate leaders
to the White House to outline his program to help economically
deprived areas, which he characterized as ``new markets'' for
investors who traditionally look elsewhere to put their money,
often abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was astonished when we listened (to) some of the things that
they're already doing to bring opportunity to people,'' Clinton
said after the meeting. ``But we have to do more.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been given an opportunity now, because we've got the
strongest economy in at least a generation, to prove that we can
bring the benefits of free enterprise to every neighborhood in
America,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years our government has worked to give Americans
incentives to invest in emerging markets around the world,''
Clinton said. ``But now we know ... our greatest untapped markets
are here at home _ at the least, $85 billion in untapped markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Revisiting a proposal outlined in his State of the Union message
in January, Clinton touted his ``new markets initiative'' _ a
package of tax incentives and loan guarantees awaiting action in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals are designed to attract venture capital to areas
in need of economic stimulus, such as the Lower Rio Grande Valley,
the El Paso area and the Los Angeles barrios.
</P>
<P>
   The president announced plans for leading a delegation of CEOs
and members of Congress on a three-day tour of some of ``untapped
markets'' in the Mississippi Delta, Indian reservations and
Appalachian hamlets in early July.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going places not just to remind America of the plight of
the Americans who live there, but to highlight their enormous
economic potential,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said the trip was to be patterned after trade
missions that Cabinet secretaries make overseas to help identify
markets for American investors that, through trade and commercial
agreements, lead to new jobs and economic development abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's ``new markets'' program was developed by an
administration task force working with corporate executives,
members of Congress and pioneers in community development.
</P>
<P>
   It was first unveiled in January as part of the Rev. Jesse
Jackson's Wall Street Project, a coalition of executives seeking to
expand business opportunities for minorities and women.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal before Congress includes a 25 percent tax credit
for investors in targeted communities, which administration
officials said could lead to creation of small technology firms,
shopping centers, retail stories and small manufacturing plants.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
