<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3126 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALINGER-LETTERS-ART-     05-11 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALINGER-LETTERS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOVE LETTERS FROM A PRIVATE AFFAIR OF THE FAMOUSLY PRIVATE
SALINGER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By PETER APPLEBOME   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fourteen letters by J.D. Salinger, the most private
of literary figures, are about to be auctioned in the most public
of arenas _ Sotheby's New York _ in a move likely to raise vexing
questions about the private rights of public figures.
</P>
<P>
   The letters were written between April 25, 1972, and Aug. 17,
1973, to writer Joyce Maynard, with whom Salinger had a nine-month
romance. It began when she was an 18-year-old Yale University
freshman and he was a celebrated 53-year-old author who had
retreated from public life to an isolated cottage in Cornish, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Maynard left school to live with Salinger, who abruptly cut
off the relationship in March 1973. She refused to divulge anything
about their relationship for more than 25 years, before recounting
almost every bit of it _ from her sexual inadequacies to his
eccentric diet and fixation on homeopathic medicine, in her 1998
memoir, ``At Home in the World'' (Picador USA, 1998).
</P>
<P>
   Now she is selling the 14 letters, which are formal and
avuncular at the outset, turn to love-struck ardor and ultimately
become brusque, chilly and impersonal.
</P>
<P>
   The sale is the latest offshoot of what seems in retrospect a
romantic mismatch that would have made great literary satire: the
obsessively private Salinger and the compulsively confessional Ms.
Maynard.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, the letters, like a high-intensity flashlight
beamed into a musty attic, are a startlingly intimate glimpse of
the most private and reclusive of American authors. Because
Salinger, now 80, has so zealously guarded his private life and
last wrote for publication in 1965, the letters will surely
intrigue scholars and others interested in his work.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, they are as private as correspondence can be,
essentially love letters to someone he describes almost from the
start as a kindred soul. As such they will no doubt strike many as
a grievous invasion of Salinger's consistently and insistently
stated desire to maintain his privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Maynard, who is divorced with three children, said the
decision was simply financial. Sotheby's has estimated that the
letters, which are being sold as a unit, will bring $60,000 to
$80,000. ``I'd rather put my children through college than own a
box full of Salinger's letters,'' she said. ``They were a piece of
my past that I've finished with, and I'd rather use them to help
support my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Salinger's literary agent, Phyllis Westberg, and a lawyer who
has represented him, Marcia Paul, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Maynard has long been criticized by some writers as a
virtual caricature of the confessional bent in American letters.
And just as her memoir was criticized by some as an attempt to
traffic in Salinger's reclusive fame, the sale of the letters will
probably be seen by some in the same light.
</P>
<P>
   Author and critic Cynthia Ozick said of the case: ``What we have
is two celebrities, one who was once upon a time a real writer of
substance and an artist, and one who has never been an artist and
has no real substance and has attached herself to the real artist
in order to suck out his celebrity. It's really such a Jamesian
story, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than criticizing Ms. Maynard, novelist E.L. Doctorow said
he found it unfortunate that a personal relationship ``was being
commodified, as seems to happen with frequency in this country.''
He added, ``I think the word sad is appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all Salinger's brief incursions into the public realm
in recent years have been legal efforts to maintain his privacy. In
the most celebrated case, Salinger was successful in 1987 in
blocking the publication of a biography by Ian Hamilton that relied
heavily on unpublished letters Salinger wrote to his friend and
editor, Whit Burnett, and to others, between 1939 and 1961.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, Salinger copyrighted the letters, which had been
donated to university libraries, to frustrate Hamilton's plan to
quote extensively from them. Hamilton then radically revised his
book, paraphrasing rather than quoting the letters. But in a ruling
that shocked publishers and biographers, a federal appeals court in
New York ruled that Salinger had the right to protect the contents
of his unpublished writings even from extensive paraphrases that go
beyond the ill-defined ``fair use'' provisions for written
material, as in a review of a book.
</P>
<P>
   The book was again revised and finally published in a very
different form and with a new title, ``In Search of J.D.
Salinger,'' in 1988. Since then his legal and literary
representatives have successfully forced the Film Society of
Lincoln Center in New York to cancel a planned showing of an
Iranian film adapted from his 1961 book ``Franny and Zooey'' and
shut down a Web site about his work.
</P>
<P>
   The Hamilton case limits the ability of publications, authors
and scholars to quote from letters. But there is no apparent legal
question about Ms. Maynard's right to sell the 38 pages of letters,
which are neatly typed or scrawled in ink or pencil on typing
paper, yellow lined paper and, in one case, on a card from the New
York Public Library. Legal experts say the only apparent legal
challenge to the sale could be over issues of their public display.
</P>
<P>
   The letters begin on April 25, 1972, the day Ms. Maynard's
reminiscence, ``An 18-Year-Old Looks Back on Her Life,'' complete
with ingenue photograph, ran as the cover story of The New York
Times Magazine. In the article she presented herself as a character
who could have come from one of Salinger's books _ a true innocent,
part child, part adult, as wearied and put off in her own way by
much of what she sees around her as Salinger's Holden Caulfield is
in ``The Catcher in the Rye.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Among the hundreds of letters she received from admirers,
detractors, suitors, editors and producers was a double-spaced,
typewritten letter on a single piece of thin typing paper that came
in a hand-addressed envelope from Cornish, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   The writer said he was offering a few unsolicited thoughts ``in
strictest privacy, if you can bear it,'' from a kindred spirit. He
praised her writing, warned her against people who would exploit
her talent, said he was familiar with the perils of such
exploitation and wished her well. It was signed, ``Sincerely, J.D.
Salinger.''
</P>
<P>
   She wrote back and received a handwritten letter dated May 2 on
three sheets of lined yellow paper. Salinger thanked her effusively
for her reply, railed on at length about the costs and risks of a
public life and signed off, ``In friendship, partisanship, J.D.
Salinger.''
</P>
<P>
   As the relationship proceeded, the letters became more avid and
intimate. And just the way much of Salinger's fiction seemed a
search for one pure soul in a dirty world, he extravagantly praised
Ms. Maynard while lamenting almost everything around him:
relatives, letter writers and most of all anything having to do
with publishing, public life and the media. He did speak with
fondness of his two children, who shared their time between him and
their mother.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote of feeling deep doubts about virtually every value he
had witnessed in a voice that seemed very much like Holden
Caulfield at 53, now a cranky adult instead of a quirky adolescent.
And if Ms. Maynard is likely to be criticized in some quarters,
Salinger's voice in the letters _ and what will strike some as a
calculated attempt to seduce an 18-year-old girl _ may not seem
nearly as appealing as the voice of his fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Though the letters are written during the Vietnam War era, there
is little in them about politics or anything outside his own life,
aside from an overall distrust of what seems to him the fashion of
being unfashionable. Instead he writes of homeopathy, favored
actors and things he likes: Jane Austen, vaudeville, his daughter's
basketball playing, attending Dartmouth football games with his
son, ``The Andy Griffith Show,'' ``I Love Lucy,'' Alfred Hitchcock
movies. He writes with a New Yorker's sensibility of apartments on
the Upper West Side and said he wrote every day, though it is
apparent he had no thoughts of publishing again.
</P>
<P>
   He writes frequently on the writer's life and lot, but the only
direct reference to any of his published writing comes in response
to her question about how Holden Caulfield managed to cram so much
activity into a single night in ``The Catcher in the Rye.'' He said
he doesn't know, and suggests checking with a newspaper advice
columnist.
</P>
<P>
   In his fourth letter, he sends her his phone number, in the
fifth he proposes a meeting, and by the sixth he sounds like a
love-struck suitor contemplating meeting her parents. The letters
end when she leaves school to move in with him.
</P>
<P>
   The final letter, dated Aug. 17, 1973, after he had broken off
the relationship, ends the correspondence with a chilly thud.
</P>
<P>
   He responds clinically to her questions about ordering
homeopathic publications and how to treat distemper in dogs and
throws in a laundry list of favored remedies. Saying, ``it's late
kiddo,'' he complains that he is tired and has been answering
letters all day and signs off.
</P>
<P>
   The auction is scheduled for June 22, and the letters will be on
display from June 17 to 21.
</P>
<P>
   Marsha Malinowski, Sotheby's vice president for books and
manuscripts, said Sotheby's sells perhaps 400 lots of letters a
year, but she was hard pressed to think of any in her 13 years
likely to attract as much interest as Salinger's.
</P>
<P>
   She said she had no qualms about the sale despite Salinger's
desire to maintain his privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as the writer has his rights, so does the recipient of
the letters have the right to do what he or she feels is
appropriate with them,'' she said. ``And I think that Joyce Maynard
feels it is appropriate for these letters to be available to
scholars and the outside world for further knowledge and insight
into a great American writer.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Maynard, who said she planned to attend the auction, said
she had long since stopped worrying about her critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing I can say to those people, so I just don't try
anymore,'' she said. ``I take Salinger's advice: You'd better not
spend your life looking over your shoulder to see what people are
saying about you.''
</P>
<P>
   As is his custom, Salinger was not available for comment. But he
stated his position on his privacy quite clearly in depositions in
which he was asked what he hoped to gain from preventing Hamilton
from using his letters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll retain a very important sense of privacy, of property
that I really believe is mine,'' he said. ``Privacy is privacy.
Letters were meant for a certain pair of eyes and those eyes
alone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
