<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: BUSY TOURIST SEASON PREDICTED; 2 CITIES ADD
FLIGHTS; AIRLINE PERKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Also moving in `t' category) 
(bl) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Still haven't made reservations for summer vacation? Well, don't
wait any longer, because the AAA auto club predicted Tuesday that
from Memorial Day through Labor Day (the unofficial summer season)
Americans would make a record 271 million trips of at least 100
miles from home. Over Memorial Day weekend alone, a record 33.3
million people are expected to get away.
</P>
<P>
   The projections for both the summer and Memorial Day represent a
4 percent increase over the respective travel numbers for 1998, a
year in which overall summer travel figures jumped 7 percent from
the summer of 1997. If the projections hold, this Memorial Day will
be the fourth this decade to show an increase of more than 1
million in the number of people traveling at least 100 miles from
home.
</P>
<P>
   The projections are based on an AAA-commissioned national travel
survey of 1,500 adults by the Travel Industry Association of
America.
</P>
<P>
   The AAA also projects that summer travelers can expect increases
of slightly more than 1 percent this year in the costs of meals and
lodging, for an average total of $213 a day for a family of four.
By contrast, an analysis released Monday by Pricewaterhouse Coopers
and Bear, Stearns &AMP; Co. forecast that Americans would pay ``much
more'' for summer travel this year over last, because of higher
prices for hotels, fuel, car rentals and, possibly, domestic
leisure air fares.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the actual cost, all parties agree that within three
weeks, the roads and skies of the United States will begin filling
with summer travelers.
</P>
<P>
   2 Cities Add Flights
</P>
<P>
   Business travelers and city officials in New Orleans and
Cleveland expect to benefit mightily next month when Trans World
Airlines begins a new daily nonstop June 1 betweem New Orleans and
Mexico City that originates in New York, and when Continental
Airlines begins daily nonstop service on June 30 between Cleveland
and Gatwick Airport in London.
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans officials expect the TWA flight to increase
corporate and leisure travel to their city by millions of dollars a
year, and to position New Orleans as a hub for commerce with Latin
America.
</P>
<P>
   Projections for the Cleveland-London flight, the first nonstop
flight between Cleveland and Europe, are that it will add about
$200 million a year to the economy of northeastern Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   To attract the TWA flight, which will be the only daily nonstop
between New Orleans and Mexico City, several corporations _
including Harrah's Entertainment, which expects to open a New
Orleans casino this fall _ agreed to buy an undisclosed number of
tickets for an undisclosed price for a certain period. In addition,
New Orleans International Airport agreed to reduced TWA's landing
fees for that flight.
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland-London flight is symbolic of Continental's steady
expansion at Cleveland Hopkins International Airport _ to 268 daily
departures currently from 205 in 1995. But it did not hurt matters
that $120 million is being spent to expand the airport, including
$92 million for a concourse for Continental's regional carrier,
Express Jet, scheduled to begin service Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   With aircraft flying so full over the last couple of years, it
is tempting to conclude that passengers will automatically flock to
each new flight. Not so. Which is why airlines often start or
cancel routes, add or reduce frequencies, fly seasonal schedules
and change the size of the planes used on particular routes.
</P>
<P>
   Airline Perks
</P>
<P>
   Fly first class or business class to Japan before May 31 and
Japan Airlines will give you your choice of up to $300 in American
Express gift checks, two free nights at the Bellagio Hotel in Las
Vegas, or private car service from Narita Airport to your hotel in
Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Fly United Airlines and stay at a Hilton Hotel and you will earn
points in Hilton's HHonors program and also in United's
frequent-flier program, Mileage Plus. The offer is good through May
31, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Hotels
</P>
<P>
   U.S. hotels won 5 of the 10 spots in Gourmet magazine's ranking
of the best hotels in the world, and one of them _ the Halekulani
Honolulu _ came in first The others were the Ritz-Carlton, Naples,
Fla. (No. 6); the Boulders, Carefree, Ariz. (7); the Greenbrier,
White Sulphur Springs, W.Va. (8) and the Phoenician, Scottsdale,
Ariz. (9). The survey of the magazine's readers was conducted by
the Willard &AMP; Shullman market research firm in Greenwich, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   The renovated 210-room Sheraton Phoenix Airport Hotel has
reopened in Tempe, Ariz., with an executive club, conference center
and other amenities for business travelers. In Aurora, Colo., the
157-room Hilton Garden Inn Denver Airport is open for business,
with a 24-hour business center and three meeting rooms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-99 2102EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
