u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-NYT &LR;      05-11 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMBASSY BOMBING POINTS OUT PROBLEMS IN PENTAGON MAPPING AGENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md.)  (nk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Pentagon agency that drew up the outdated map
used in the bombing of the Chinese embassy in Belgrade has been
embroiled in at least two other international incidents in the last
18 months.
</P>
<P>
   The National Imagery and Mapping Agency prepared the maps for
the crew of the Marine Corps jet that struck a ski-lift cable in
February 1998 near Aviano, Italy, leaving 20 people dead. The cable
did not appear on the maps, agency officials said, because the
towers supporting it were under 100 feet tall, the minimum height
that was required to be shown on the map.
</P>
<P>
   The CIA was blindsided a year ago when India tested a nuclear
device, and many intelligence experts blamed the dearth of
experienced analysts in the new agency for its inability to detect
preparations for the explosion. Satellites and analysts alike
failed to focus on the nuclear test site, despite signs that a test
was coming.
</P>
<P>
   Formation of the National Imagery and Mapping Agency from parts
of the Pentagon and the CIA three years ago ignited an uproar among
intelligence officials. The primary goal was to provide battlefield
commanders with speedier intelligence, especially from
reconnaissance satellites and U-2 spy planes. By merging several
agencies, the government also expected to save money.
</P>
<P>
   But many senior CIA photographic analysts perceived their new
assignments to the mapping agency as drudge work, and they either
retired or sought transfers to other government jobs, continuing an
exodus that began in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Some influential lawmakers have decried the embassy bombing as a
sign that U.S. intelligence capabilities are stretched too thin and
as evidence that the new mapping agency is not working.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little premature to reach any conclusions about whether
this combined agency is working well or not, but the debate has
opened up again,'' Rep. Porter J. Goss, R-Fla., who heads the House
Intelligence Committee and who opposed the agency's creation, said
in an interview Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The accidental bombing has touched off a furious round of finger
pointing among various Pentagon and intelligence officials. There
is plenty of blame to go around, from the CIA analysts who picked
the target to the military data bases that had an old address for
the Chinese Embassy.
</P>
<P>
   This is important because the geographic coordinates of targets
are checked against the data bases in order to attempt to avoid
civilian casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Even though China moved its embassy in 1996 from Belgrade's old
quarter to a newer portion of the city, that information was never
transmitted to the agency's mapping experts or put into many of the
government's data bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had high-level officials who have visited the new Chinese
embassy, but they have not placed a call out to the agency or to
the department saying, `By the way, we're at the new embassy,' ''
Defense Secretary William Cohen told the Senate Appropriations
Committee on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   At ground zero in all this is the little-known, 7,000-member
organization tucked away in an old Army building in Bethesda, Md.
The agency is a hybrid of eight defense and intelligence agencies,
principally the Pentagon's Defense Mapping Agency and the CIA's
National Photographic Intelligence Center, which was spawned by
complaints from Gulf War commanders that they lacked up-to-date
intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   The new agency sought to break down barriers between military
mapmakers and intelligence analysts of airborne reconnaissance
photographs, with the aim of whisking a polished report to troops
in the field.
</P>
<P>
   But combining the two organizations has been a bumpy process,
despite upbeat reports from field commanders like Gen. Anthony
Zinni, whose Central Command has responsibility for the Persian
Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   The cadre of scientific and technical experts who analyzed the
satellite data dwindled through resignations and retirements,
intelligence experts said, and was gradually supplanted by a
younger work force steeped more in political science than
scientific testing.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the intelligence analysts responsible for
interpreting spy satellite photographs are less skilled and less
experienced than their predecessors of 10 years ago, at the end of
the Cold War, said some present and former intelligence officials,
including Gordon Oehler, who retired last year as director of the
CIA's Nonproliferation Center.
</P>
<P>
   NIMA officials insist the criticism is unfair and say that as
trouble spots erupt around the world, their analysts are being
asked to analyze more and faster, while Congress in recent years
has kept cutting the agency's budget, which is classified.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fallacy is, if you combine eight unfunded agencies into
one, they'll be fully funded,'' one agency official said Tuesday.
``Everyone's looking for savings.''
</P>
<P>
   The agency's director, Army Lt. Gen. James C. King, was
unavailable for comment Tuesday, a committee spokeswoman, Laura
Snow, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``NIMA is understaffed and underfunded,'' said Sen. Richard
Shelby, R-Ala., who heads the Senate Intelligence Committee. He
observed that the panel had increased the agency's funds one day
before the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Goss, while insisting that the agency is adequately financed,
acknowledged a crucial shortfall in intelligence analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have very definitely gotten into a situation with NIMA
where we literally have roomfuls of collected intelligence material
and not enough good analysts,'' he said. ``When you have that, it's
a catastrophe waiting to happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-99 2104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
