</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: ELECTRICITY IN THE GARDEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Good grief. After a dismal lockout and a dreary
season, the Knicks are still with us and, not only that, they have
a chance to be around for a while.
</P>
<P>
   For all their troubles, deficiencies, slumps, weaknesses, flaws,
gaps, you name it, they will play Miami Wednesday night in a
Madison Square Garden that will seek to muster all the energy of
the really good years.
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty of emotion stored up in the Garden after a tepid
and abbreviated season. The Garden has rarely come alive this year,
and when it did, it was often for the most electric player on the
Knicks, the anti-Frazier, the anti-Bradley, Latrell Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing I can do is have a big start,'' Sprewell said
Tuesday. ``A steal or a dunk early, connect with the crowd. That
will carry over to the rest of the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell does not exactly play like all the guys on the banners
hanging from the rafters. His on-court version of ``Hit the Open
Man'' _ the mantra of the Red Holzman years _ is to stage a
solitary fast break against two or three defenders.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Garden crowd loves him because he changes the
plodding tempo of the Knicks, as they gamely try to slow the game
down for their big-hearted but sore-ankled Patrick Ewing. Sprewell
has the same impact of the early John Starks, minus the
chest-thumping, but he is taller and more agile, and has come along
during the doldrums at the big barn on Seventh Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks haven't jelled for more than a game at a time, and
part of the fault is obviously Sprewell's. The crowd has been
forced to stifle its own elitist ``Dee-fense'' history and root for
the guy with the braids (to say nothing of his history of
coach-throttling.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the best fans in the world; they'll be pumped,''
Sprewell said Tuesday after practice. ``They make a lot of noise,
up on their feet. You can tell they want us to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Knicks fans like to think they are the hippest fans in all
creation, but Sprewell said they are also the noisiest. He would
like to ignite them early Wednesday night, in a totally crucial
game as the Knicks try to win two at home, to avoid a fifth and
deciding game in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   If Sprewell is going to perform any electrification, he will
have to do it off the bench. He has been the sixth man most of the
season, and chafed about it at one point, when his agent popped off
about starting next year or being traded.
</P>
<P>
   That has been the only disruptive sign from Sprewell this
season. His occasional wild romps on the court and his defensive
lapses are merely part of his game _ nothing personal, that is.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if you did not know any better, you would not take
Sprewell for the chap who locked his 10 large fingers around the
vulnerable throat of his coach, P.J. Carlesimo, during a Golden
State practice last season.
</P>
<P>
   Standing next to Sprewell during a group interview session, it
is hard to forget that he basically lost it in a very physical
manner, and paid a huge price for it _ suspended after 14 games
last season, at the cost of $6.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   However, his reputation for anger and menace does not show in
his daily demeanor. It is easy to see why Dave Checketts was
impressed enough after a personal interview to trade for Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   Not to exaggerate, but Sprewell is one of the more approachable
Knicks, at least from the standpoint of the working press, and he
seems quite rational.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell had said he was looking forward to his first playoff
experience since 1994, when the Warriors went out in three
straight. He and Allan Houston shot well to help the Knicks win the
first game in Miami, but both were somewhat out of control in the
second game, as the ball seemed to squirt away from them.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't so much that they were mishandling the ball, however,
as it was the Miami defenders getting their hands (and knees, and
elbows, and their entire trunks) in the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was more us than them,'' Sprewell said. ``We didn't play as
smart as we had been. In the playoffs, it's obviously more intense
than the regular season. Teams do more scouting and they have time
to prepare for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Off the court, Sprewell talks calmly about ``game plans,'' but
when he leaps off the bench, he seems oblivious to some of the
finer points. That is part of his charm, and Wednesday night the
Garden crowd will forget the ancient finesse and root for Sprewell
to turn on the juice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
