u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAB-SECURITY-NYT &LR;      05-11 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAB-SECURITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENERGY SECRETARY ANNOUNCES PROGRAM TO STRENGTHEN LAB SECURITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JAMES RISEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vowing to assert his direct control over the
government's fiercely independent nuclear weapons laboratories,
Energy Secretary Bill Richardson on Tuesday announced a
wide-ranging program to strengthen security after allegations that
China has repeatedly pried nuclear secrets out of the labs.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing that he plans to name a new Energy Department
``security czar,'' Richardson acknowledged that the move was part
of his effort to fundamentally alter the relationship between the
weapons labs and the Energy Department, which owns them. In the
past, Richardson conceded, the major labs have circumvented
dictates from energy secretaries, often with the help of friendly
and powerful allies in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   He said the independence of the labs, and their ability to
exploit informal political channels to get money from Congress
without going through the Energy Department, have allowed lab
officials to ignore recommendations from Washington to improve
security and counter-intelligence measures and to screen foreign
visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, who previously represented the New Mexico
congressional district that includes Los Alamos National
Laboratory, which is now at the center of the spy scandal, knows
that he will not be able to cut off the labs' ties to Congress. But
he insists that his reorganization will improve the labs' efforts
on security and counter-intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I run the labs now,'' Richardson said. ``This was not the case
in the past. Secretaries in the past did not tackle these things
because of the constituencies involved and because of politics.''
</P>
<P>
   The new security ``czar'' will be a senior official who will
report directly to Richardson and will oversee all security-related
functions, including offices handling computer security, nuclear
material control, and background checks on foreign visitors to the
labs.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, who came to the Energy Department last year, made it
clear that his actions were in response to his own frustrations
with the way lab officials have dealt with him. He complained that
he ``used to ask for information on foreign visitors to the labs,
and I couldn't get straight answers.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson also plans to consolidate security-related budgets
for various labs and other facilities into one $800 million budget.
</P>
<P>
   Confronting criticism on Capitol Hill for failing to prevent a
scientist already suspected of being a spy for China from
transferring huge amounts of secret data out of a classified
computer system at Los Alamos, Richardson also announced a $50
million increase over two years in funding for computer-related
security measures. That comes on top of an $8 million increase he
proposed in March, soon after the furor began.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson also said that the Energy Department will tighten
security controls over floppy disk drives and other devices that
could be used to remove or download files from classified computer
networks. That action comes after lawmakers expressed outrage last
week that new computersecurity measures imposed by the labs in
April still would not prevent downloads from classified computers
onto removable disks.
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Department will also require that electronic
``banners'' be posted on office computer networks throughout the
department and the labs that alert computer users that they are
working on a government system subject to search and review by
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   In the Los Alamos case, the office computer of the chief
suspect, Wen Ho Lee, was not searched until March, even though he
had been under investigation since 1996. Officials say that the FBI
was turned down by the Justice Department in 1997 when it requested
approval to seek a warrant that would have allowed FBI agents to
tap Lee's phone and covertly monitor his computer.
</P>
<P>
   While Lee had signed a standard Los Alamos waiver in 1995
acknowledging that the lab had the right to audit his computer use,
the FBI decided that waiver was not enough to make any evidence
they found in Lee's computer admissible in court. FBI attorneys
decided that since the Justice Department had rejected the bureau's
request for a search warrant, the standard waiver would not stand
up as legal justification for searching his computer.
</P>
<P>
   A banner on screens constantly warning users that their
computers were subject to search and examination would provide a
more solid legal foundation. Richardson also said that he is
placing an 18-month moratorium on the declassification of Cold
War-era Energy Department documents. A declassification of
weapons-related data begun in 1993 by former Energy Secretary Hazel
O'Leary has been widely criticized among intelligence officials who
say it compromised some American nuclear secrets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
