<HEADLINE>
FIELD FAVORABLE TO SILVERBULLETDAY ENTRY
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Mike Pegram was dead set against running his
3-year-old filly, Silverbulletday, against the boys in the Kentucky
Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Now the owner seems to believe running her Saturday in the
Preakness Stakes is the right thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   What's the difference?
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, there isn't a 20-horse field'' in the Preakness,
Pegram said. ``When I saw what happened at the Derby, I just looked
up at the sky and said, `Thank you for not having my filly in
there.' That was like a Roller Derby.''
</P>
<P>
   Pegram said Silverbulletday, who easily won the April 30
Kentucky Oaks the day before The Derby, will be entered Wednesday
for the 13/16-mile Preakness at Pimlico Race Course, the second leg
of thoroughbred racing's Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't necessarily mean she will run. She also was
entered in Friday's Black-Eyed Susan Stakes for fillies, the
Maryland equivalent of the Oaks.
</P>
<P>
   The decision will be made Wednesday, based in part on what post
position she draws.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's up to (trainer) Bobby (Baffert) and (jockey) Gary
(Stevens),'' Pegram said. ``But as it sits right now, she's going
in the Preakness.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert also is planning to enter his other filly, Excellent
Meeting, who finished fifth in the Kentucky Derby. She was entered
Tuesday in the Black-Eyed Susan and will be entered Wednesday in
the Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Pimlico track is narrower than Churchill Downs', the
Preakness field is limited to 14 starters.
</P>
<P>
   Silverbulletday and Excellent Meeting turned in strong workouts
Monday and Tuesday at Churchill Downs in Louisville, Ky. Each was
timed in 59 seconds for five furlongs. They are to be flown to
Baltimore Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Only four fillies have won the Preakness, the last being Nellie
Morse in 1924.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she continues to run like she's training, I think she can
beat the boys,'' Pegram said of Silverbulletday. ``That's why she's
in there right now.''
PRIME TIMBER TO SKIP PREAKNESS
</P>
<P>
   Baffert said Prime Timber, fourth in the Derby, will skip the
Preakness and start in the Sir Barton Stakes on the undercard.
After First American defected with an injury, that leaves 14 or 15
likely entrants, depending on the status of local long shot Lead Em
Home.
</P>
<P>
   Pimlico officials are almost certainly rooting for Lead Em Home
to stay in the barn. If Lead Em Home is entered, either Valhol or
Torrid Sand would be excluded based on career earnings. To decide
which one, the track would be forced to take a position on the
continuing Arkansas Derby controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Valhol's Arkansas Derby purse was ordered stripped last week by
the Arkansas State Racing Commission, which concluded that jockey
Billy Patin carried an illegal electrical device. Torrid Sand was
moved from third to second place.
</P>
<P>
   However, Valhol's owner, James Jackson of Rockport, obtained a
court order before the Kentucky Derby to force Oaklawn Park to
credit Valhol with the Arkansas Derby purse.
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas commission attorney Byron Freeland said he believes
that order remains in effect. Pimlico director of racing Lenny Hale
said Tuesday that if a decision has to be made at entry time
Wednesday, the court order probably will be honored.
</P>
<P>
   That would put Valhol into the race at $344,100 with local
riding star Edgar Prado aboard and force Torrid Sand _ also
excluded from the Kentucky Derby _ back to the sidelines at
$91,400.
</P>
<P>
   But if Pimlico should instead side with the Arkansas commission
verdict, Torrid Sand ($141,400) would get into the Preakness, and
Valhol ($44,100) would rank 15th behind Lead Em Home ($95,487) and
go instead in the Sir Barton Stakes.
TRAINING HARD
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday was a busy day for final workouts.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky Derby winner Charismatic went five furlongs in 1:01,
and D. Wayne Lukas stablemate Cat Thief went in 50 1/5 seconds for
a half-mile, both at Churchill Downs.
</P>
<P>
   Other five-furlong workouts at Churchill were recorded by
Patience Game (:58 3/5) and Worldly Manner (1:00 2/5). Also going a
half-mile, or four furlongs, was Torrid Sand (:48 1/5).
</P>
<P>
   Vicar topped the Pimlico work tab with his five furlongs in 59
3/5 seconds. The Nick Zito-trained duo of Adonis (1:01 3/5) and
Stephen Got Even (1:01 4/5) worked the same distance. Lead Em Home
went four furlongs in 49 seconds, and Valhol was timed in 50
seconds. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
