</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERFORMING-SPACE-THEATER-ART-3TAKES-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRYING TO BALANCE THE OLD GARDE WITH THE NEW  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 16) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis., Texas)  (af) 
 Steven Drukman is writing a history of avant-garde theater in
America.  
 By STEVEN DRUKMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Some changes come more easily than others. In 1979,
when a bunch of scrappy performance artists transformed an
abandoned public school in the East Village into a showcase for
experimental dance and theater, they didn't even have to change the
name. P.S. 122 (now Performance Space 122) stood as a vast
ready-made home for the city's burgeoning performance-art
community.
</P>
<P>
   Then another change occurred: through the 1980s and '90s, the
neighborhood surrounding the red brick building on First Avenue and
Ninth Street was gentrified. P.S. 122 was transformed from a rental
house with a $40,000 annual budget into a producing organization
with an $800,000 annual budget.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, it has presented more than 5,000 artists and
commissioned hundreds of new plays and dance works. Increased
financial support, critical accolades from the mainstream press,
and an audience that grew more discerning as it increased (the
mailing list now exceeds 13,000) all combined to turn P.S. 122 into
what its longtime executive director, Mark Russell, calls ``the
Carnegie Hall of performance art.''
</P>
<P>
   But now Russell, who programs more than 150 performances every
year, faces a new challenge: How to keep P.S. 122 cutting-edge by
presenting emerging talent while also providing space to the
established artists who came of age with some of the audience. And
how to do it in a climate of diminished state and federal support
as well as increased competition from younger theaters, like the
Here Arts Center in SoHo, theaters very much like P.S. 122 in its
infancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I have a new job this year,'' said the soft-spoken
Russell recently. ``We are now high enough on the food chain of
presenters so that I have to make difficult choices. I have to
worry about putting people in seats, but P.S. 122 must always be a
shelter for some bohemia. And still, I want to keep this a home for
our masters. The hardest part of my job is to say to artists who
have performed here for years, `That piece may work better
somewhere else.'''
</P>
<P>
   The roster of those who have appeared at P.S. 122 while
developing into major arts figures reads like a Who's Who of the
experimental dance and theater scene. Eric Bogosian, Meredith Monk
and Spalding Gray are a small sample of those who have presented
new work.
</P>
<P>
   Today, many of these artists, aging along with the institution,
are part of what would once have been a contradiction in terms: the
mainstream avant-garde. Gray, an original member of the
experimental Wooster Group, has become known to wider audiences
through his one-man shows and appearances in mainstream films.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he frequently returns to test new material at P.S. 122,
as he did last fall in his solo show ``Morning, Noon and Night.''
</P>
<P>
   Bogosian's 1982 ``Fun House'' was the first work of many that
went on from development at P.S. 122 to a full-scale commercial
run. ``P.S. 122 has never been and never will be a place that
exists only to move a production,'' Bogosian said. ``You can make
theater for show biz, for a paycheck, or, like at P.S. 122, for
love and joy.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, honestly, it can be a little ramshackle. But that's
part of the experience: it's casual and excited. Audiences don't
sit there, shoved in their seats by an angry usher, arms crossed,
thinking, `O.K., now show me something.' They want to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bogosian, who, like Russell, is 44, added: ``As far as
cutting edge, I actually think that idea has been abandoned over
the years, in a good way. Maybe I reflect their new audience, as
someone who goes out less because I have two small kids now, and so
I want to see something good. But Mark Russell knows that, and so
taste supersedes shock value.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing in the vast 3,000-square-foot space that makes up the
larger of his two theaters, Russell wears the downtown
establishment look: a goatee and earrings in both ears, but
conservative preppy clothing. ``Sometimes I feel like the hunchback
of P.S. 122,'' he confessed. ``Much of my job is telling newer
artists who consider this their P.S. 122 about the history,
teaching them what other artists here learned before them. Like,
yeah, I know, blood looks really good on naked bodies.''
</P>
<P>
   The history of P.S. 122 has also been recorded in two recent
books. ``Out of Character: Rants, Raves and Monologues From Today's
Top Performance Artists'' was edited by Russell, who has been
running P.S. 122 since 1983. It contains the texts of solo shows,
many performed at the former school by, among others, Karen Finley,
Penny Arcade, Ron Athey, David Cale and Deb Margolin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Caught in the Act'' is a collection of photographs, mostly of
P.S. 122 performances, by Dona Ann McAdams, whom Russell calls
``P.S. 122's house photographer.''
</P>
<P>
   The original founders were three performance artists _ Tim
Miller, Charles Dennis and Peter Rose _ and a choreographer,
Charles Moulton. ``For me,'' Miller recalled, ``it was the ultimate
treehouse. There was a real `I'll show you mine, if you show me
yours' buzz about the space.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller said that Russell had been ``immersed in the deep psychic
and creative juices of the enterprise'' from the beginning, and
seemed to be the most likely candidate to run the business side.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But Russell insisted otherwise: ``I was just hanging out!
Because I sold magazine ads to downtown arts organizations, people
assumed I had business know-how. So in March of '83, when they
asked me to become executive director, I just said yes. When I came
on the job, if a performer had 100 bucks for rent, we'd show him
where the clip lamps were, maybe make a poster and do a mailing,
and that was it.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, five separate groups formed the 122 Community Center
to take over the building. Russell sits on the board with his
group, Performance Space 122, along with Painting Space 122, the
Children's Liberation Day Care Center, Mabou Mines (the avant-garde
theater company) and the AIDS Service Center.
</P>
<P>
   The groups divide responsibilities for maintenance and pay $1 in
annual rent to the city. Russell supervises a full-time staff of
seven and several part-time box office assistants and ushers.
</P>
<P>
   He tends to draw distinctions between P.S. 122 and other similar
long-lived institutions like La Mama E.T.C. and the Kitchen with
care: ``I see us as not competing _ our audiences now often overlap
_ but having different ecologies. Dance Theater Workshop and
Danspace have more of a dance agenda. We started as a reaction to
places like the Kitchen and Franklin Furnace. Our guys couldn't get
gigs there.''
</P>
<P>
   Martha Wilson, the founder of Franklin Furnace in 1976, said she
considered the P.S. 122 crowd the next generation. In addition,
``They really came from a different tradition,'' she said.
``Whereas we were more of the European avant-garde _ we would
present an artist fasting for 40 days, for example _ P.S. 122 was
always more in the theater world, with a beginning, middle and end.
</P>
<P>
   ``While Franklin Furnace is concept-based and not overly
concerned with audience, P.S. 122 is solicitous of its audience.
And Mark Russell's success has been to broaden that audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell said he believed each generation had its own
avant-garde: ``There will always be artists who are trying things.
Sometimes they gravitate toward dance, or performance art, or
theater, or the installation world, or they combine those forms to
bring out what they want to say to their time. People who want to
make their statement are attracted to New York, so there is a
steady source. Sometimes it's hard to pick up what they're talking
about. But it usually becomes clear through one or two voices what
the new concerns are and where it's going.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have the luxury of the major transgressions of
theater in form and content that the past did. So we are down to
the fine-tuning of the avant-garde. It's hard to shock people or to
turn their eyes to something new, to take an experience like going
to the theater or a subject like sex and make it fresh for them.
And I think those are the concerns of the avant-garde: to find what
is real, to find the truth in the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell characterized the show ``Thwak,'' by David Collins and
Shane Dundas, two Australians who call themselves the Umbilical
Brothers and do physical and verbal comedy, as ``one that got
away.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad they are getting a commercial run at the Minetta Lane
Theater,'' he said. ``They are definitely the kind of show we might
have presented. I'm interested in works that push their genre and
are very original. These two guys are.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the best things I found recently,'' he continued, ``I
saw at 11:30 on a Tuesday night _ way past my bedtime _ at Baby
Jupiter, a bar and restaurant on Stanton Street. The artist's name
is Akim Funk Buddha, from Zimbabwe, and the show is called `Da
Fusion.'
</P>
<P>
   It involves tap-dancing, break-dancing, mask work, puppetry and
a 20-piece band that includes sitars, zithers, a theramin and kodo
drums.'' Russell said the show would be presented at P.S. 122 in
November.
</P>
<P>
   Remembering the last time he was at P.S. 122, Richard Schechner,
the experimental director and a professor of performance studies at
New York University, said: ``I saw Spalding Gray try out his new
piece there. It was an excellent evening and valuable to Gray, who
thinks of P.S. 122 as a supportive environment for developing new
materials.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask about the avant-garde. What avant-garde? In advance
of what garde? In today's multiplex performance world _ a zillion
channels from cable through the Internet and a few dozen places for
live performance _ P.S. 122 has its niche somewhere to the left of
the Kitchen. As for relevance, the question is: To whom, for what?
In general, the more that smaller spaces allow elbow room for
artists, the better.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell said he looked ``for a spark with new talent, but
sometimes it takes a few tries to throw something up against the
wall before anything sticks.'' Open year round, often with four
different events per evening, P.S. 122 offers an array of artistic
activity with widely varying artistic payoffs. With money from the
Jerome Foundation, the New York State Council on the Arts and the
Van Lier Fund, Russell commissions 10 to 20 new works a year and
said he begged foreign governments to fly him abroad to see
emerging international talent.
</P>
<P>
   First-timers may perform at P.S. 122 for one night as part of a
larger series, at no admission price. But last year's solo show by
Danny Hoch, ``Jails, Hospitals and Hip-Hop'' (produced commercially
at the building in association with P.S. 122) had such wide appeal
that it played to sold-out houses for 14 weeks, with tickets priced
up to the theater's limit of $25. (Hoch is making a return
appearance in the show from May 27 through June 7.)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-99 2116EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
