<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3150 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PACIFIC-SFCHRON &LR;      05-11 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PACIFIC-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Exchange After Tech Alliance
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Sam Zuckerman &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
The Pacific Exchange is close to inking a joint-venture deal with
New York broker Cantor Fitzgerald to start a computer-based stock
options trading system, people familiar with the matter said.
</P>
<P>
   The venture is key to the exchange's strategy for staying
competitive as the options business goes electronic. An agreement
could be announced within a few weeks, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Cantor approached Pacific, the No. 3 U.S. options exchange, in
January shortly after the Chicago Board Options Exchange, the
nation's largest options exchange, pulled out of its deal to merge
with San Francisco's bourse.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific and Cantor confirmed talks have taken place, but they
declined to provide details.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had discussions with Cantor about a potential
strategic alliance,'' said Pacific spokesman Dale Carlson. ``We've
had lots of discussions with lots of parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Pacific previously approached the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, a
technologically advanced options exchange, about a possible
alliance but chose to focus on Cantor, sources said. A CME
spokesman declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Options are contracts that give holders the right to buy or sell
stocks at preset prices before a fixed date. Exchanges trade
options wholesale for brokers who in turn buy or sell them for
retail or institutional customers.
</P>
<P>
   A possible Pacific-Cantor deal comes as traditional options
exchanges around the world rush out electronic trading systems to
replace or operate alongside their old-fashioned trading floors.
Under the traditional system, called open outcry, options contracts
are traded by frantic brokers shouting out offers to buy or sell.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional exchanges are threatened by computer-based
competitors, including the soon-to-be-launched International
Securities Exchange backed by Palo Alto online broker E-Trade.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific is especially vulnerable following the collapse of its
CBOE merger since it lacks the funds to buy an advanced computer
trading system. Exchange officials have said a joint venture is the
best way to get access to the technology they need.
</P>
<P>
   The plan Cantor and the San Francisco exchange are negotiating
would allocate some options to their joint electronic system while
keeping others on Pacific's trading floor in the Mills Building on
Montgomery Street, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe there is a future for both open outcry and
screen-based trading,'' Carlson said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, observers said, if customers find that electronic trading
is cheaper and more efficient, all exchanges, including Pacific,
could eventually be forced to close their options trading floors.
Pacific has already said it plans to adopt an all-electronic system
in its stock exchange business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been predicting the end of open outcry for 10 years,
though the change has been slower than I thought,'' said Steven
Manaster, director of Virginia Tech University's Financial Risk
Management Center.
</P>
<P>
   One person familiar with Pacific's operations estimated there is
just a 10 percent chance the exchange's options floor will still be
open in five years.
</P>
<P>
   Cantor operates the world's largest electronic brokerage system
for bonds and other debt securities.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, it formed a partnership with the New York Board of
Trade, a commodities exchange, to start an all-electronic exchange
for specialized trading vehicles called financial futures.
</P>
<P>
   The Cantor Exchange, as the joint venture is known, was the
first federally regulated exchange operated by a private brokerage.
Most exchanges, including Pacific, are membership associations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most significant thing we bring to any potential alliance
is the ability for an electronic business to be up and running
instantly,'' said Cantor managing director Debra Walton.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Cantor would get a large flow of business
channeled to its exchange. Last year, Pacific traded about 275,000
options contracts a day.
</P>
<P>
   Choosing which options would be traded electronically and which
would stay on Pacific's trading floor is a key issue in talks.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the Cantor Exchange often trades less than 1,000
futures contracts a day because it hasn't achieved the critical
mass to make it competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific's Carlson declined to comment on whether an alliance
would have to be approved by the exchange's members.
</P>
<P>
   ``If by embracing new technology, the exchange injures the
careers of its members, they have a problem,'' said Virginia Tech's
Manaster. ``The members are unlikely to support the plan unless
they are compensated with some piece of the action.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
