<HEADER>
A3151 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PERFORMING-SPACE-THEA     05-11 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERFORMING-SPACE-THEATER-ART-3RDTAKE-$ASDV16-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: June 7.)  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Now, unfortunately, I can't commission a work from Danny Hoch
because, God help him, he's become a popular sensation,'' Russell
said. ``But I have no bitterness when these guys move on. I'm proud
that John Leguizamo developed parts of his show `Freak' here and
then went on to be nominated for a Tony Award on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   ``And those mainstream artists nourish P.S. 122 in other ways.
We wouldn't have air-conditioning upstairs if it weren't for Danny
Hoch. And Eric Bogosian did a $10,000 benefit for us.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Russell said that the biggest corporate donor is Blue
Man Group, a troupe that appeared at P.S. 122 in 1989 and went on
to an Off Broadway commercial engagement in 1991 at the Astor Place
Theater that is still running.
</P>
<P>
   While Russell said he had observed a transformation over the
years in the audience at his institution, it is still an audience
interested in what is new. ``Sure, they want a subway line near the
theater,'' he said, ``and they want comfortable seats. Not that
they're not hungry for an adventure _ they just want the cream of
the adventure.''
</P>
<P>
   He characterized the audience as ``pretty young, with a majority
in their mid-20s to mid-30s.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Depending on the program,'' he said, ``we always have many
different areas of the city represented: a lot of people from the
Bronx and Harlem as well as from here in the East Village.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe as the elder gentleman,'' he added with a smile, ``I can
be just the right screen for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Russell was born in Menomonee, Wis., but spent much of his
childhood in Austin, Texas. After graduating from the University of
Texas, he went to Poland in the summer of 1977 and studied with the
experimental directors Jerzy Grotowski and Tadeusz Kantor.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to New York, he said, his taste for the avant-garde
was well formed, but: ``I had no illusions about being an artist
working in New York. I trained in school as a director, but being a
presenter really suits my pH balance. I like every aspect of
producing, from concept to posters.'' He lives on the edge of
Chinatown with Sarah Skaggs, a choreographer.
</P>
<P>
   His institution, Russell believes, led a charmed life in the
1980s. But the political climate was changing and in 1990, the
National Endowment for the Arts revoked grants for the solo artists
Holly Hughes, John Fleck and Ms. Finley and Miller.
</P>
<P>
   In response, a number of artists and organizations refused NEA
grant money because they were unwilling to sign a pledge not to use
the funds to produce work that in the judgment of the NEA might be
considered obscene.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Kitchen and Franklin Furnace, P.S. 122 went
unmentioned in congressional testimony as a presenter of high-risk
performance art. Russell speculated that because P.S. 122 sounded
like a school, it evaded notice. Still, it has not received NEA
money for three years, though there has been recent word that a
possible $75,000 grant may be in the offing earmarked for
improvements to the organization's infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   ``But until I see the check, I'm not getting money from the
NEA,'' Russell said.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of consistent federal support has changed things.
``Now, 50 percent of my budget comes from box office, and it used
to be 10 to 20 percent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such challenges, Russell has no plans to move on. ``It
helps to have an active board of directors, many of whom are
artists,'' he said. ``Sure, we have the usual lawyers and
accountants, but our board president, Lucy Sexton, is a member of
Dancenoise,'' a duo who perform frequently at P.S. 122, and are
known for presenting outrageous dance works. ``It's nice to see
your board president once a year, naked and covered in blood.''
</P>
</TEXT>
