<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENTURE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 VC Firms Put Wads of Cash Into Internet Companies
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Peter Sinton &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Internet companies, including equipment and access providers and
online retailers, snared a record amount of venture capital
financing in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, VCs poured $2.1 billion into fast-growing
Internet companies in the quarter ended March 31, according to
VentureOne Corp., a San Francisco research firm. That was nearly a
third more than the previous quarter and represented a whopping 58
percent of the record $3.6 billion that flowed to 464 U.S.
venture-backed companies from January &LR;   &LR; through March.
</P>
<P>
   And as a sign that San Francisco is as much the center of the
online universe as anywhere else, five of the 10 U.S. companies
that received the most venture capital financing in the first
quarter of 1999 are based in the city.
</P>
<P>
   In Northern California, a similar percentage of funds invested
by VC firms and their institutional partners went to Internet
startups in the past quarter: $1 billion out of $1.7 billion. By
contrast, VC investments in all local companies in the same quarter
a year earlier totaled just $806 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The extraordinary volume of Internet investments turned a
normally slow quarter into a record breaker,'' said Rolf Selvig,
VentureOne's director of business development. Unlike the biotech
and semiconductor industries, he noted, ``The Internet is an area
where you can build a successful company in a short period of time
and not have to wait for FDA approval or build a huge fab plant.''
</P>
<P>
   That means venture capital investors can recoup their
investments in Internet companies a lot faster than they might in
other types of investments.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the time it takes to develop and finance an Internet
idea is getting so compressed that several companies announced
plans to go public in the same quarter they received their final
infusion from VC firms.
</P>
<P>
   For example, NorthPoint Communications, a San Francisco provider
of high-speed Internet access services, won $63.6 million from VCs
in February. The firm announced plans the following month to raise
$125 million in an IPO, which it launched last week and netted
nearly $400 million.
</P>
<P>
   The top local venture deals in the past quarter also included
these companies:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ LookSmart &LR; . The Internet's largest directory of reviewed Web
sites raised $60 million. The company, headquartered in Multimedia
Gulch at Bryant and Third streets, has about 350 employees with
nearly half of them researching and writing about Web sites.
LookSmart provides its directory of more than 750,000 sites in some
30,000 categories to more than 4.5 million Internet service
subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Financial Officer Patricia Cole said that the company is
considering a public stock offering. ``If you do acquisitions, it's
nice to have a currency that people understand,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Digital Island.  &LR; Another San Francisco company that offers
companies Web network services, the firm raised $50 million in the
first quarter and then raised $75 million more in an IPO two weeks
ago. The 5-year-old company leases dedicated telecommunications
circuits to provide faster online connections and other Web
services for companies such as E-Trade and Cisco Systems.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ WineShopper.com &LR; . The online wine emporium received $46
million in VC commitments, including $35 million in the past
quarter, according to VentureOne.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some other services that may run afoul of complicated and
cumbersome laws that ban direct shipment of alcoholic beverages
from producer to retailer or end-user, WineShopper.com works within
the existing three-tier system of producers, wholesale distributors
and retail stores.
</P>
<P>
   The company has received financial backing from blue-chip VC
firm Kleiner Perkins Caufield &AMP; Byers and support from the Wine and
Spirits Wholesalers Association. WineShopper.com is the brainchild
of Peter Sisson, who has a master's degree in computer science from
Stanford, an MBA from Tuck and until a year ago was a
telecommunications analyst at Montgomery Securities.
</P>
<P>
   CEO Sisson expects his e-commerce service, which will be
launched later this year, will make it as easy for the consumer to
buy a broad selection of wines as it is to buy books on Amazon.com.
That ease of use is the result of a very intricate system for using
the existing patchwork quilt of wholesale and retail distribution
channels in various parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Total Entertainment Network &LR; . The San Francisco online game
company, raised $30 million. The 60-employee startup, which has 2
million registered members, has shifted its focus from pay-to-play
games like Duke Nuke 'Em to classic and family games like cards,
crossword puzzle and bingo where it picks up money from
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Other local companies.  &LR; Several e-commerce and online
information companies received $25 million each in the past
quarter. They include Ask Jeeves, the question-answering service
that announced plans on April 30 for an IPO; E-greetings, an online
greeting card company; Food.com, the Internet's largest food
takeout and delivery service; and PlanetRX, an online provider of
pharmaceutical and other drug store products.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 167 Northern California companies received venture
capital financing in the past quarter. That compares with 158
companies in the previous quarter and 128 companies in the first
three months of last year.
</P>
<P>
   VentureOne also reports that 22 venture-backed companies in the
United States went public in the first quarter, raising $1.5
billion. Local IPOs included Covad Communications of Santa Clara,
Critical Path of San Francisco, Autoweb.com of Santa Clara and
Intraware of Orinda.
</P>
<P>
   During the same time, 36 VC-financed companies were acquired for
a total of $5.5 billion in the past quarter. These included local
companies Lightera Networks, Assured Access Technology, Sqribe,
Diamond Lane Communications and CityAuction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
