<SLUG> BC-CISCO-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CISCO SYSTEMS CITES 33 PERCENT EARNINGS GAIN FOR QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Cisco Systems Inc. beat analysts' third-quarter
earnings estimates by 1 cent per share, as the company continued
its robust growth.
</P>
<P>
   The leading maker of specialized hardware for computer networks
attributed its strong results to the rapid expansion of the
Internet. Cisco reported its results after the close of the regular
market trading, but earlier shares of Cisco closed at $111.875, up
$2.625, in NASDAQ trading. The shares jumped as high as $115.25 in
after-hours trading, according to Instinet.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Cisco may be the leading beneficiary of Internet
growth. Nothing is so ubiquitous on the Internet as Cisco's
routers, specialized computers that manage data traffic on a
network using the Internet Protocol, known as IP. More than 80
percent of the routers connected to the Internet are Cisco
machines. Whether any of the new Internet ventures succeed or not,
the greater the traffic on the network, the more Cisco routers are
needed.
</P>
<P>
   But from primarily selling routers to corporations to manage
internal data, Cisco has shifted its emphasis to major telephone
service providers, to whom it offers a vision of multiple services
over their networks. Sales to telecommunication service providers
rose more than 70 percent from a year ago, and now contribute about
a third of Cisco's revenue, Cisco executives told analysts on a
conference call.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter ended May 1, Cisco reported earnings of $646
million, or 38 cents per diluted share, up 33 percent from $484
million, or 30 cents a share in the period a year ago. Sales rose
44 percent, to $3.15 billion, from $2.18 billion for the third
quarter. The year-ago earnings are a pro-forma number that has been
adjusted to eliminate one-time charges of $419 million for the
write-off of research and development it acquired.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts expected Cisco to earn 37 cents a share, according to
First Call.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with analysts after the earnings were
announced, Cisco warned that said gross margins would fall in the
next few quarters.
</P>
<P>
   During the quarter, Cisco announced it will acquire Geotel
Communications and Amteva Technologies. Both acquisitions bring
advanced voice capabilities to Cisco's technology portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco also announced a 2-for-1 stock split May 24. The split,
the eighth since Cisco went public in 1990, will take effect June
21. Two-for-one stock splits occurred in 1991, 1992, 1993, 1994 and
1996; and a three-for-two split occurred in 1997 and 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
