<HEADER>
A3156 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NORTHPOINT-SFCHRON &LR;      05-11 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORTHPOINT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 NorthPoint founder stays grounded
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Peter Sinton &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
When NorthPoint Communications founder and CEO Michael Malaga
raised $63.6 million in venture financing last February, he thought
his Internet access service company wouldn't need a public stock
offering until this summer.
</P>
<P>
   But that changed after his major competitors _ Covad
Communications of Santa Clara and Rhythms Netconnections of
Colorado _ raised a combined $290 million in wildly successful
IPOs.
</P>
<P>
   NorthPoint opted to step up &LR;   &LR; its timetable to take advantage of
investors' seemingly insatiable appetite for anything Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, it sold 17.25 million shares at $24 each. By the
end of the day, with the stock trading up 68 percent at $40.25,
NorthPoint suddenly was worth nearly $5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   That's not bad for a company that lost $28.8 million on $931,000
in sales last year and last month had about 3,500 business users
paying an average $130 a month for its services. To put
NorthPoint's financial feat in perspective, the company would now
displace newspaper publisher Knight Ridder Inc. in the 39th spot on
last month's Chronicle 500 ranking of local public companies. It
trails Apple Computer in &UR;  &LR; value by a mere 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the important thing to investors is that NorthPoint
is well positioned in the multibillion-dollar market for faster
Internet connection services.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco company sells online access through
conventional copper phone lines that is at least 25 times faster
than conventional dial-up modems. Its digital subscriber line (DSL)
service is available to businesses through Internet service
providers in 17 major markets and will be expanded to another 11
areas by year's end.
</P>
<P>
   Malaga, 34, overnight became worth $300 million (at least on
paper). But he is not letting NorthPoint's instant stardom on Wall
Street divert his attention. He plans to continue taking the bus to
work, although the firm's headquarters will soon move from four
overcrowded floors above Loehmann's on Sutter Street to six floors
and major tenant status in the former Chevron headquarters building
at 225 Bush St.
</P>
<P>
   Like many entrepreneurs, Malaga is more interested in applied
than theoretical science, or what he calls ``things that work for
people.'' After studying applied physics at Cornell and getting a
master's degree in structural dynamics at the University of
Cincinnati, he worked for Lucas Nova Sensor, which made chips for
automobile air bags.
</P>
<P>
   For seven years, he worked for a Silicon Valley company that
made software to help engineers measure vibration and noise in
cars, planes and disk drives. Then he sought a job at
telecommunications innovator MFS Communications, where he led
strategic development efforts, including high-speed Internet
connections using copper phone lines.
</P>
<P>
   Malaga founded NorthPoint two years ago with five other former
MFS executives who fled after the company was acquired by WorldCom
and focused increasingly on voice rather than data delivery.
</P>
<P>
   NorthPoint started in Malaga's studio apartment and was named
after the street where he lives. After developing ``the initial
recipes'' (with a co-founder sleeping on his couch), Malaga said
the next step was ``raising money to fund them.''
</P>
<P>
   Although good planning was crucial, serendipity helped. Malaga
met venture capitalist Peter Wagner of Accel Partners at a
breakfast meeting. By chance, Accel had invested in related
telecommunications equipment startups and was looking for a company
like NorthPoint. Within weeks, Malaga had a handshake on the first
$3.5 million of venture backing.
</P>
<P>
   NorthPoint chose to locate in the heart of San Francisco's
financial and retail district partly because of access to public
transportation. It also chose to make downtown its first test
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to show investment partners you can execute
your plan _ like proving the dogs will eat the dog food,'' said
Malaga. NorthPoint first served local businesses through Internet
service providers Brainstorm and Concentric Networks in late 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Then it pushed to expand to other places, starting with Silicon
Valley in early 1998. It also forged strategic relationships with
Microsoft, Intel and other high-tech giants along with more than 85
online connection companies.
</P>
<P>
   After growing from 50 to 500 employees, NorthPoint brought in
Pacific Bell and US West veteran Liz Fetter as president and chief
operating officer two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, talk and raise money,'' joked Malaga. ``She runs the
operating lines of the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Malaga says adaptability is one of the essential attributes of
successful entrepreneurs. Most recently that translated into
speeding up the IPO because the the public equity market has become
a cheaper source of capital than the $229 &UR;  &LR; million the company
raised in the private debt and private equity markets. In its IPO,
NorthPoint netted $388 million by selling an 11 percent stake.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner of Accel Partners said one reason companies like
NorthPoint are raising so much venture money is that they want to
make sure they have sufficient funds to operate if the IPO market
cools. Success increasingly depends on the ability to expand
rapidly, he explained. ``It's risky for companies to slow down and
give their competitors a chance to overtake them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
