<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3159 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BULGARIA-ART-2     05-11 1437
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BULGARIA-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULGARIANS BET FUTURE ON LINK TO NATO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOFIA, Bulgaria _ For Yugoslavia's Balkan and Central European
neighbors, the war in Kosovo is becoming part of a familiar pattern
of casting their lot with the perceived victor.
</P>
<P>
   As Europe's first hot war in half a century damages their
economies and public anxiety over the conflict mounts, governments
in this region have made a kind of wager that the future after the
guns fall silent will be promising only if they find themselves on
NATO's side.
</P>
<P>
   Like the other nations ringing Yugoslavia, Bulgaria has taken
this course _ even as NATO's bombing of Yugoslavia and Danube
bridges cuts this Balkan country of more than 8 million people from
its markets in western Europe and its meager export income
plummets. Prospects for foreign investment, crucial for future
recovery, have dimmed, and nipped a brief economic springtime in
the bud.
</P>
<P>
   Then, last week, the military risks of a shared border with
Yugoslavia were brought home to Bulgarians, when a NATO missile
tore into the attic of a home of a family of four on the outskirts
of Sofia. It was the fourth NATO missile to hit Bulgarian soil. No
one has been hurt.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, despite all these events, a broad majority of
Bulgaria's parliament voted last Tuesday, after only five hours of
debate, to make the country the latest in the region to open its
air space for NATO bombing missions, in exchange for security
guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was very much in line with the policies of the
anti-Communist, pro-business government that took office in 1997 to
rescue Bulgaria from economic collapse. Unlike its neo-Communist
predecessor, this government and reformist President Petar
Stoyanov, elected in 1996, have pushed Bulgaria toward NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Support for the alliance now is ``a question of Euro-Atlantic
solidarity, and choosing European values,'' Prime Minister Ivan
Kostov said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   A failure by NATO in Kosovo, he added, would ``give the right to
any government to commit genocide against its people.''
</P>
<P>
   Kostov's arguments echoed those of government leaders lined up
against Yugoslavia and President Slobodan Milosevic, across the
region where Communism once held sway.
</P>
<P>
   But the moral stance, opposing evil with good, masks a far more
complex reality _ a gamble that may not pay off.
</P>
<P>
   For the people of central and eastern Europe, torn by warfare
again and again in this century, the prospect of war breeds fear.
</P>
<P>
   For the past 100 years or more, they have been caught up in a
pattern of inimical pact-making. From the Balkan League of
pre-World War I, which bred the Balkan War pitting Bulgarians
against Serbia and Greece, to the opposing alliances of the two
murderous world wars and finally the nuclear standoff of NATO vs.
the Warsaw Pact in the Cold War, they have taken sides to survive,
trying to minimize the cost.
</P>
<P>
   For a majority of people in the region, said Ognyan Minchev,
director of the Institute for Regional and International Studies in
Sofia, ``the choice, in a very practical sense, is not between good
and evil, but between a lesser and greater evil.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Kosovo, he said, the lesser evil was NATO air
strikes following the brutal purge of hundreds of thousands of
ethnic Albanians from their Kosovo homes.
</P>
<P>
   The greater evil, in this view of things, is ``being isolated in
a security vacuum,'' given NATO's post-Cold War role as the sole
provider of international security in Europe, Minchev said.
</P>
<P>
   To act otherwise, he said, would be ``to remain on the other
side of the dividing line, away from those supporting the war, who
are also those supporting recovery investments after the war. That
is the reason why not a single government could resist saying `Yes'
to that kind of offer from NATO.''
</P>
<P>
   Choosing the lesser evil does not remove the anxiety that stems
from fear of future relations in the Balkans, which could be
poisoned by having taken sides against a neighbor _ in Bulgaria's
case, Serbia, with whom the ties of religion and language are
close.
</P>
<P>
   ``Psychologically, the region is torn apart,'' Minchev said.
</P>
<P>
   But the greater worry is that of a protracted war that causes
even greater economic and human damage than has thus far occurred.
Such a prolonged war might seriously destabilize the fledgling
democracies of the region, born out of the collapse of Communism a
decade ago. New governments emerging from that prolonged war,
Minchev said, could involve political parties and movements not
oriented toward democracy and a market economy _ unlike most
governments in the region now.
</P>
<P>
   As the reality of the war looms, popular enthusiasm for NATO has
dropped. Recent polls say some 42 percent of Bulgarians favor
membership now, compared to 60 percent before the war.
</P>
<P>
   But Kostov, 49, who was swept into office in 1997 on a wave of
discontent with the policies of his former Communist predecessors,
dismissed such findings. ``If you asked Bulgarians whether there is
any other way,'' he said, ``60 percent would say no.''
</P>
<P>
   But the immediate reality is a beleaguered Bulgarian economy
facing a halving of growth this year because of the war.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Zaimov, deputy head of the National Bank, counted off the
economic casualties. Foreign investment was at a standstill, he
said in an interview, because ``people are not even willing to
travel to Bulgaria _ it's not a question of investing.''
</P>
<P>
   With land routes to western Europe cut in Yugoslavia and a
principal waterway _ the Danube _ blocked by bombed out bridges,
Bulgarian exports are collapsing. In the first quarter, export
revenues dropped 26 percent against last year. Bulgarian growth
this year, as a result, is expected to drop by almost half to 2
percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the most devastating effect, Zaimov said, was psychological
and involved Bulgarians' ``perception of the future.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time, we had managed to instill in people a
reality in which they could sit back and have a longer horizon,''
he said. ``Now, people think, `This is war. We should sit and do
nothing, but wait and see.' ''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Bulgaria's political opposition, the former Communist party,
seems poised to exploit the malaise. Emboldened by public
discomfort with the war, the former Communists' resistance to NATO
is stiffening and they publicly question the wisdom of Bulgaria
casting its lot with the Western military alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, said Sergei Stanishev, head of the Socialist
Party's International Relations Department, the nation had little
luck with foreign alliances. The Balkan League led Bulgaria to
bitter defeat when its former allies, Serbia and Greece, turned
against it. In both world wars, Bulgaria lucklessly sided with the
central European powers around Germany, and was punished for doing
so. Its forced adherence to the Soviet-led Warsaw Pact after World
War II left Bulgaria economically backward and militarily exposed
after the collapse of Communism and the Soviet empire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were always on the losing side,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he said, his party's opposition to the war merely
echoed common fears that Bulgaria would ultimately be browbeaten
into allowing air or ground attacks from its territory.
</P>
<P>
   `'If you say a, you have to say b, till the end of the
alphabet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kostov accuses the Socialists of opposing strong measures
against Milosevic out of sympathy for a fellow former Communist.
Milosevic ``has a totalitarian Communist regime which has sought
refuge in the last haven of nationalism and chauvinism,'' much as
Bulgaria's own Communists did in the late 1980s by oppressing and
expelling the country's Turkish minority, Kostov said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Kostov and his government gained power by borrowing
a chapter from the textbook of the Serbian opposition in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the angry strikes, protests and boycotts that forced
Kostov's Socialist predecessor, Zhan Videnov, to resign, were
loosely modeled on the 1996-97 protests in Serbia that fleetingly
forced Milosevic to accept that the Serbian opposition had won
local elections.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Kostov says, the Serbs are called upon to imitate the
Bulgarians and liberate themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Serbs have to depose Milosevic, they have to put their
state into normal conditions,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-99 2122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990511.0384 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3160 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEGISLATURE-RDUP-TEXA     05-11 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEGISLATURE-RDUP-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS HOUSE TENTATIVELY PASSES ANTI-ALCOHOL MEASURE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
and KATHY WALT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In an outburst of anti-drinking fervor, the
Texas House voted Tuesday to ban open containers in vehicles,
prohibit alcohol sales in sexually oriented businesses and declare
bars off limits to unaccompanied minors.
</P>
<P>
   All the changes to Texas liquor and criminal laws were
tentatively approved in a single a bill that was supposed to be a
routine update of liquor regulations. But it turned into what
lawmakers call a ``Christmas tree'' _ a measure that started out
simple but finished up laden with dazzling proposals.
</P>
<P>
   House Bill 3555 by Rep. Ron Wilson, D-Houston, was passed on a
vote of 75-38. After a final House vote Wednesday, the liquor
regulation bill goes to the Senate for further consideration and
possible stripping of the conservative amendments.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said he didn't agree with all the amendments tacked onto
his bill, but collectively they reflected the mood of the House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's anything wrong with that. It speaks well
for this process,'' said Wilson, adding, ``this is not an exact
science.''
</P>
<P>
   Under existing law, open containers are not banned, although
drivers can be cited if an officer observes them in the act of
drinking alcohol while behind the wheel. As approved, Wilson's bill
bans open containers in the passenger compartment, with several
exceptions. A fine of $50 was set for violations.
</P>
<P>
   The exceptions would apply to people other than drivers in
commercial buses and mobile coaches. Liquor could be lawfully kept
in a locked glove box. An amendment for drivers of sport utility
vehicles would allow an open container to be stashed behind the
last fixed seat.
</P>
<P>
   Other defenses to prosecution were allowed, such as not knowing
the open container was in the vehicle, having an emergency that
prevented its proper storage or the driver requesting a
breathalyzer test and registering .02 percent blood alcohol content
or less.
</P>
<P>
   The prohibition on booze in sexually oriented businesses was
proposed by Rep. Joe Nixon, R-Houston, who called strip clubs ``a
real problem in my district.`` Describing his proposal, Nixon said,
``It's a very simple fix. If you take the booze out of the sexually
oriented businesses, they go away.''
</P>
<P>
   To the surprise of many, a move to kill Nixon's amendment was
defeated 111-25. In similar fashion, the proposal to ban
unaccompanied minors in bars was overwhelmingly approved, even
though the ban has struggled as a self-contained bill.
</P>
<P>
   The action on the liquor bill was just part of the day's long
agenda. Members also gave final approval to a measure toughening
drunken-driving law by lowering the intoxication threshold to .08
percent of blood alcohol content, down from the current .10
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to replace a patchwork of inadequate remedies, the House
also approved a $12.6 million state plan to alleviate beach erosion
along the 367-mile Texas Gulf Coast.
</P>
<P>
   With no debate, the House made only minor changes to a bill that
has already won Senate approval. Senate Bill 1690 by Sen. David
Bernsen, D-Beaumont, faces a final House vote Wednesday before
being returned to the Senate for review of the House amendments.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would authorize the General Land Office to create a
coastal erosion response plan designed to address problems along
two-thirds of the coastline.
</P>
<P>
   House sponsor Patricia Gray, D-Galveston, said it was crucial
and that its passage was being demanded by many coastal residents.
``This is the re-election bill for anyone who lives on the Gulf
Coast,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Senate, meanwhile, approved two bills that allocate
about $1.8 billion from the state's first payment in the tobacco
lawsuit settlement to establish permanent endowment funds. The
funds would then generate annual income for various health
programs.
</P>
<P>
   But a key senator said chances aren't good for an extra $30
million that several cancer-fighting groups hoped would remain in
the state budget for an anti-tobacco-use initiative.
</P>
<P>
   One measure, House Bill 1676, would set aside $500 million to
establish four permanent funds for anti-smoking education,
children's health, emergency medical services and rural health care
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The other measure, House Bill 1945, would set aside $580 million
in four higher education funds to cover research, treatment and
health education at public health-related universities.
</P>
<P>
   Both measures have already been approved by the Texas House but
will go back there for consideration of Senate changes. Senate
Finance Chairman Bill Ratliff, R-Mount Pleasant, said he expects
the differences to be worked out in a House-Senate conference
committee.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate also approved a bill that would create covenant
marriage contracts designed to slow down the divorce rate by making
couples undergo premarital counseling and also to seek marriage
counseling when the marriage runs into trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Covenant marriages would be optional, but couples who choose
that route would be able to seek a divorce only on certain grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't force two people to stay together,'' said bill
sponsor Sen. Tom Haywood, R-Wichita Falls. ``Nor can you eliminate
divorce altogether.''
</P>
<P>
   His bill, however, is likely to run into trouble of its own in
getting through the House before the end of the session May 31. A
similar bill never got out of committee in the House.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
