<HEADER>
A3161 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JUVENILE-JUSTICE-NYT &LR;      05-11 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUVENILE-JUSTICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE DEBATES YOUTH-CRIME BILL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By FRANK BRUNI  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the Senate began debate Tuesday on a bill aimed
at reducing crime among children, Republicans focused on stricter
law enforcement, Democrats emphasized better prevention programs
and advocates of new gun-control measures confronted the prospect
that time would run out before their proposals could be considered.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, called the Violent and Repeat Juvenile Offender
Accountability and Rehabilitation Act, is the first legislation
concerning juvenile crime to reach the floor of either chamber of
Congress since the shootings at Columbine High School in Littleton,
Colo., three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Senators from both parties have described the bloodshed at
Columbine as an unignorable summons to action. But the comments of
senators both on and off the floor Tuesday illustrated how diverse
_ and, sometimes, conflicting _ their ideas about what to do are.
</P>
<P>
   The bill has attracted a profusion of suggested amendments,
creating the possibility that there would not be enough time to
discuss many of them and get to a final vote on the bill by
Thursday night. After that point, the Senate is expected to move on
to other business, and further consideration of the juvenile
justice bill could then be delayed for several weeks or months.
</P>
<P>
   If that should happen, the amendments least likely to be
discussed would be those related to gun control. Republican leaders
said on Tuesday that those measures would come up for review last.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the majority leader, said he
would not try to block consideration of any specific amendments,
including those on gun control, but conceded that he would have to
cut off debate at some point.
</P>
<P>
   He said his goal was for discussion of, and votes on, all
aspects of the bill to be completed by the end of the week. ``Is
that going to be achievable?'' Lott said. ``We'll have to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott also made clear that in his view, gun control was not
central to the legislation. ``I hope this is about a bigger
question than guns,'' he said, ``and I wish the press would stop
focusing on guns.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats pushing for more gun control say that if
discussion on the bill is not completed this week, they will have
lost crucial momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's our greatest worry,'' said Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y.
``It'll be much harder to pass then, because right now, people are
focused on this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The unamended juvenile justice bill, whose principal sponsor is
Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, calls for about $1 billion in federal
money to be distributed to local law-enforcement agencies and
governments for measures to crack down on juvenile crime and, in
some cases, to intervene early to rehabilitate offenders. Many
Democrats have complained that there is not enough emphasis on, or
money for, such prevention efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's principal gun-control measure prohibits gun ownership
for anyone who has committed a violent felony as a juvenile.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few amendments to the bill came up for votes early on
Tuesday night, and they highlighted the common ground that does
exist between the parties.
</P>
<P>
   By an overwhelming majority of 94 to 5, senators approved an
amendment calling for $200 million for schools and law-enforcement
agencies to develop strategies and to buy equipment to make schools
safer. By a similar margin, they approved an amendment to provide
$50 million to local prosecutors, mainly to combat gang violence.
</P>
<P>
   But a third amendment, put forward by Democrats, was defeated by
Republican opposition in a party-line vote of 55 to 44. It called
for a national school safety hot line and for more money for mental
health programs for students.
</P>
<P>
   As the bill made its way to the floor, Republicans and Democrats
staged dueling news conferences, each party trying to steer the
outrage over the Columbine shootings into the direction it wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans continued to fix their attention not only on law
enforcement but also on the violence in the movies, video games and
songs to which children are exposed. They outlined several
amendments intended to study and tame those influences and said
that, in general, better enforcement of existing gun control laws
was more important, and potentially more effective, than new ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've already got all kinds of gun laws on the books,'' Hatch
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch, however, responded to Democrats' concern about prevention
programs by agreeing to sponsor, along with Sen. Joseph R. Biden
Jr., D-Del., an amendment that would guarantee that 25 percent of a
$435 million block grant in the bill would be reserved for such
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Biden urged other Democrats to support that compromise, but it
was unclear how many would do so.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
