u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REPORTER-ILLNESS-HOAX     05-11 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPORTER-ILLNESS-HOAX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORTER FIRED FOR LIES ABOUT HER ILLNESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky.)   (bl)  
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a series of newspaper columns written over the past year, a
33-year-old Kentucky reporter described her imminent death from
what she described to her readers as ``terminal brain cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Try to picture a world without dreams, without wishes, without
hope,'' Kim Stacy wrote in The Owensboro Messenger-Inquirer, the
newspaper published in Kentucky's third-largest city. In prose
laden with references to her Christian faith, Ms. Stacy said she
had been told she had less than a year to live. She chronicled in
detail her conversations with oncologists and the metallic taste in
her mouth from chemotherapy treatments, and she wrote of her
friendship with an 8-year-old leukemia patient named Josh, who
died.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I believe I am going to die?'' Ms. Stacy asked in a column
published last week. ``Yes, sometimes. We all are. I'm not so
foolish as to deny it or to pretend my illness doesn't exist.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Stacy admitted to her editors Monday that she had lied,
acknowledging an act of deception that resembles the circumstances
surrounding the resignations of two Boston Globe columnists last
year. She said that, in fact, she had been found to have AIDS four
years ago and that because of the stigma associated with the
disease, she had chosen not to reveal the true nature of her
illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in a small-town atmosphere where you are crucified
for having AIDS or being gay,'' Ms. Stacy, who is a lesbian, told
The Associated Press on Monday. ``Nobody knew until this weekend
that I have AIDS.''
</P>
<P>
   Telephone calls to Ms. Stacy's home were not answered Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Messenger-Inquirer publisher T. Edward Riney said he fired Ms.
Stacy on Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We met with her and asked her to tell the story, and she said
she wrote the cancer story to cover for what she believes to be a
life-threatening case of AIDS,'' Riney said. ``At that point, we
dismissed her because of the deception to our readers, not because
of any other reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Ashley, the newspaper's editor, said in an article published
Tuesday's in The Messenger-Inquirer that his first reaction was
shock. ``Beyond that,'' he wrote, ``my reaction encompassed being
angry, being embarrassed that we had been misled and misled our
readers, and at the same time feeling personal compassion for Kim
Stacy and what she must have been going through, and must be going
through.''
</P>
<P>
   Five of Ms. Stacy's columns were published in The
Messenger-Inquirer, and a sixth had been scheduled to run Sunday,
but was canceled. One of the columns was also distributed in
Kentucky by The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stacy told her editors that the columns were fabricated only
after three former co-workers from The Appalachian News-Express in
Pikeville, Ky., approached her about inconsistencies between what
she had written in her columns and what she had told them in
personal conversations. Ms. Stacy had worked as a reporter at The
News-Express until March 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, while she was a reporter at The News-Express, she
informed the newspaper staff that stomach cancer had been diagnosed
by her doctors. In 1997, she told staff members that the illness
was in remission, and she was featured in a cover story on cancer
survivors.
</P>
<P>
   When she began working at The Messenger-Inquirer last year, she
told that newspaper's staff that she had a brain tumor that would
almost certainly result in her death. Her editors asked her to
write a series of columns about dying.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Riney said he asked her why she had fabricated the
columns. ``She said, once you start telling little lies, you have
to keep covering them up with bigger lies, and then even bigger
lies, and pretty soon the lies are out of your control and take
over,'' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Riney said he did not think that Ms. Stacy had been motivated or
inspired by the fabrications of two Boston Globe columnists last
year. In one incident, a Globe columnist, Patricia Smith, admitted
that she had fabricated characters and quotes; in another case,
columnist Mike Barnicle admitted that he had recycled stories he
had heard from others, and published them without checking whether
they were true.
</P>
<P>
   ``My personal opinion is that she may have been trying to draw
attention to herself,'' Riney said. ``I don't know what her motives
are beyond that.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Ms. Stacy would not reveal the name of the doctor
treating her, and that he had not confirmed that she had AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stacy had told him, Riney said, that she had been undergoing
treatment at an AIDS treatment center at Vanderbilt University
Hospital in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Scanlan, a hospital spokesman, said the hospital did
have an AIDS treatment center but that he could not confirm that
someone was a patient without the consent of the patient and the
doctor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
