<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLUMN-RANKINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A FLAWED RANKING SYSTEM WILL BE GONE NEXT YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 slump has spread through the men's tennis tour like a
computer virus: The No. 1 player lost six straight first rounders;
the No. 2 hasn't won a title since October; the No. 3 would be
ranked 61st based on this year's performance.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad the slump has had little impact on the computer ranking
of the premier hitters, who coast along on a 52-week cushion where
only a player's best 14 results count and first-round losses at
Grand Slams can be wished away.
</P>
<P>
   But the slump has taken a toll on a variety of reputations, and
it prompted the ATP Tour chief, Mark Miles, to make an emergency
trip to Rome over the weekend to instruct the current No. 1 and
head slumper, the Australian Open champion, Yevgeny Kafelnikov, to
start talking and playing like an advertisement for the sport, not
a saboteur.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him three things,'' Miles said. ``First, you get off to
a great start and you're going to be No. 1. Second, you go 0-for-6
and the public wants to know what's happening. Third, you lose in
Monte Carlo and say you don't care even though you really do. I
think he got the point.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Scott, the tour's chief operating officer, said Miles came
away from his Sunday meeting with Kafelnikov convinced that the
player has a better grip on his responsibilities to the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark told him he's doing a disservice to himself, and to his
fellow players, to leave the impression that he doesn't care about
losing,'' Scott said. ``He made it clear that if you connect all
the dots, from Yevgeny becoming No. 1 in the middle of this
horrendous slump to making comments that make people question his
commitment, that we're not going to accept that from him.'' He
termed Kafelnikov's behavior a defense mechanism rather than actual
lack of interest in his results and repute.
</P>
<P>
   Kafelnikov said on Monday: ``Losing six times in a row in the
first round really depressed myself, and seeing a couple of the
most renowned newspapers say it's embarrassing to have me as No. 1,
I can assure you, I feel really bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Kafelnikov, who snapped out of his slump with a first-round
victory at the Italian Open on Monday, also explained that his
comments after a 38-minute loss to 196th-ranked Ivo Ljubicic last
month in Monte Carlo were taken out of his intended context.
``Maybe I said I didn't care at all, but I was devastated,'' said
Kafelnikov, whose slide began on Feb. 25. When you're not winning
any matches since two months, it feels like you'll lose forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Kafelnikov, Pete Sampras and Goran Ivanisevic are just a few of
the players to be accused of questionable conduct in recent months:
i.e., they've ``tanked'' matches (Kafelnikov and Ivanisevic were
accused of this in Prague), or dodged important tournaments
(Sampras opted for a vacation instead of the Australian Open),
because they know their standing won't suffer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dictatorship of the players is deadly dangerous for the
sport,'' Peter Kovarchik, a tournament director and promoter, said
last week from Vienna. ``The players get tremendous money without
100 percent effort.'' Kovarchik rocked the boat two weeks ago at
the Czech Open by refusing to pay Kafelnikov and Ivanisevic their
prearranged $100,000 appearance fees following first-round losses.
</P>
<P>
   After Dominik Hrbaty, one of the 26 different winners of the 29
ATP events played so far this season, won the Prague title,
Kovarchik said stars who don't try ``should be expelled.''
</P>
<P>
   Miles also made a trip to Prague to listen to Kovarchik's
complaints, but after consulting with the chair umpires and other
tour officials at the Czech Open, Miles was not convinced that
Kafelnikov or Ivanisevic deliberately dogged their matches.
Appearance fees are privately negotiated between tournaments and
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that if a guy gets a rap that he doesn't
try, the tournament directors will just stop offering him the
fees,'' said Scott. ``But the situation we have with the ranking
right now, where a guy like Sampras is ranked second even though
he's somewhere like 83rd based on the year's results, makes the
case for a change in the most clear way.''
</P>
<P>
   In the ATP's opinion, if Pete Sampras looked at the number next
to his name and saw an 83, there would be more of a ``sense of
urgency'' about playing.
</P>
<P>
   If this year were next year, an 83 is what he'd see. And U.S.t
Open champion Patrick Rafter, now ranked fourth, would see the
unflattering numeral 117.
</P>
<P>
   In 2000, tennis, like most other sports, will rate its players
on a what-have-you-done-for-me-lately basis, with a ranking race
that starts at ground zero. And every loss at a Slam, or at one of
the men's tour's Super Nine events like Monte Carlo, will count.
</P>
<P>
   Watch for Sampras, who entered 1999 one Slam shy of tying Roy
Emerson's all-time record dozen only to blithely skip the
Australian Open, to show up in Melbourne in 2000. Watch for
Kafelnikov to spend more than 38 minutes in the opening round at
Monte Carlo.
</P>
<P>
   No more living on last year's laurels. Next year the reputation,
and rank, should match.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-99 2124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
