<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3165 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATHOME-SFCHRON &LR;      05-11 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATHOME-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Snafu Lands Cable Modem User in a Jam
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Deborah Solomon &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Some people are willing to pay a high price for fast Internet
access, but going to jail may seem a bit steep for even the most
dedicated Net-heads.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Judy Sammel, a computer scientist in suburban Maryland,
faced the possibility of two years in jail and a $4,000 fine in her
attempt to get a lightening-fast Internet connection.
</P>
<P>
   Her crime? Getting a cable modem from Redwood City's AtHome
Corp. and Comcast Cablevision. When she got the cable Internet
service last March, Comcast accidentally gave her free cable TV.
</P>
<P>
   Although she notified Comcast about the mistake, eight months
after installing the service, Comcast slapped Sammel with four
counts of cable fraud, alleging she stole cable TV.
</P>
<P>
   The charges eventually were dropped and Sammel never went to
jail but she spent two months fighting the charges. During that
time, Sammel said, she was greeted by a uniformed Baltimore
policeman at her doorstep, was forced to appear in court and was
saddled with a temporary mark on her record indicating she was
charged with a crime.
</P>
<P>
   While early adopters of new technology often face problems like
software bugs and incompatible hardware, going to jail isn't a
pitfall most Internet pioneers encounter.
</P>
<P>
   Sammel's bizarre situation stemmed from her desire to get cable
modem service _ but not cable _ from Comcast/AtHome.
</P>
<P>
   A cable modem allows users to connect to the Internet via cable
TV lines at speeds up to 100 times faster than traditional dial-up
modems. AtHome provides the cable modem service through agreements
with various cable providers around the country. The firm operates
through TCI Cable in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   While the AtHome service uses a cable TV wire as its
``pipeline'' to the home, a customer does not need to get cable TV
service to be an AtHome subscriber. Cable subscribers pay an extra
$40 a month for the AtHome service. People who don't subscribe to
cable, like Sammel, usually pay $50 a month for AtHome.
</P>
<P>
   When the technicians came to install Sammel's cable modem
service, they did not attach a piece of equipment needed to block
the cable TV transmissions. So Sammel was able to watch CNN, ESPN
and other cable TV channels at no cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the installers told me to think of it as an incentive
for signing up with Comcast/AtHome,'' Sammel said. They told Sammel
someone would be back to install a ``video trap'' to block the
transmissions.
</P>
<P>
   No one ever came back, and six months later, a policeman showed
up on Sammel's doorstep with a summons.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Rasmus, vice president for Comcast Online in
Philadelphia, said Sammel's case was an isolated incident that
won't happen again.
</P>
<P>
   Rasmus said the problem occurred because the cable arm of
Comcast has a different billing system than Comcast Online, and the
two systems don't talk to each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two billing systems didn't reflect each other's
information and so people in the cable organization didn't see that
this customer was a legitimate online customer,'' Rasmus said.
Thinking that Sammel was pilfering cable TV, the company decided to
file charges.
</P>
<P>
   Rasmus said he knew of no other customer who had been charged
with cable theft but said it could have happened to others.
However, since the majority of customers get both cable TV and
cable modem service, the problem would not be widespread, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Ms. Sammel, she was in an unfortunate situation where the
planets aligned and everything that could go wrong, did go wrong,''
Rasmus said.
</P>
<P>
   Rasmus said the company is working to merge the two billing
systems so the problem doesn't happen again.
</P>
<P>
   AtHome Corp., which was not involved in pressing charges, said
Sammel's case was unusual. ``It was an isolated incident,'' said
AtHome spokesman Matt Wolfrom.
</P>
<P>
   Some other customers who have ordered just a cable modem and not
cable TV service say they've had problems similar to Sammel's,
although none has been charged with cable theft.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Susman, a Comcast/AtHome customer in New Jersey, had his
cable modem service disconnected three times by Comcast, which
accused him of stealing cable TV service. He said that when cable
workers were in the neighborhood and noticed he had a cable line
going to his house, they disconnected him because he didn't show up
as a Comcast subscriber.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Unlike Sammel, Susman, who gets satellite TV, was not
receiving free cable. But that didn't stop the company from
accusing Susman of cable theft.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day of the third disconnect, my service was reconnected by
AtHome, and that night, a Comcast representative showed up at my
house remarking, `I see you hooked your cable up again. Do you
really want to go to jail?''' Susman recalled.
</P>
<P>
   While Susman's problem was resolved quickly, Sammel's journey to
clear her name bordered on the absurd.
</P>
<P>
   Sammel said the minute she heard the words ``cable fraud,'' she
knew it had to do with the uninstalled video filter.
</P>
<P>
   She called Comcast to explain the situation and Comcast seemed
to agree it was a mistake. But five days later, a Comcast attorney
called to tell her the charges could not be dropped. An obscure
Maryland law prevented the plaintiff from dropping charges once the
case had been scheduled for trial. The only person who could drop
the charges, Sammel was told, was the assistant state attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, he was out of town, and Sammel spent the next two
weeks trying to get the state attorney's office to drop the
charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't get in touch with the guys at the state attorney's
office because they won't even let you through if you're a
defendant,'' Sammel said. ``They made me feel like a criminal every
time I called.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Sammel threatened to file a countersuit against Comcast
for malicious prosecution, an action she credits with getting the
charges dropped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threatened to sue Comcast, and within an hour, I got a call
from the state attorney's office, saying they wouldn't prosecute,''
Sammel said.
</P>
<P>
   She also got a year's worth of AtHome service for free, a note
of apology from Comcast and a $50 gift certificate to her favorite
bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   But the ride isn't over yet.
</P>
<P>
   While she wasn't prosecuted, Sammel still has a mark on her
record indicating she was charged with a crime. That eventually
will be removed, but it will take several months.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, anyone who runs a background check on Sammel
could see this on her record, a fact she's not happy with.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just applied for a part-time job teaching flute lessons here
and they made me sign something that agreed to a background
check,'' Sammel said. ``I was debating whether to say `If you find
something about cable fraud, talk to me,''' But she decided that
would make her look suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   She hasn't heard back about the job.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-99 2125EDT &QL; 
