<SLUG> BC-UTILICORP-EMPIRE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UTILICORP UNITED AGREES TO BUY EMPIRE DISTRICT ELECTRIC CO. OF
JOPLIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UtiliCorp United Inc. has agreed to buy Empire District Electric
Co. of Joplin, Mo., in yet another sign that just the prospect of
deregulation is creating fewer but larger electric utilities.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of the Empire deal Tuesday came only two months
after UtiliCorp agreed to buy St. Joseph Light &AMP; Power Co. The
purchases need regulatory approval, and UtiliCorp hopes to complete
both in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of those two utilities, combined with
UtiliCorp's Missouri Public Service Co. in Raytown, will give the
company a geographic reach from the Iowa border to Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   And by cobbling together three relatively small utilities,
UtiliCorp will have more electric customers in Missouri than any
other utility except Ameren UE in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   The Empire acquisition ``is a significant step in growing
UtiliCorp's domestic operations,'' said Robert K. Green,
UtiliCorp's president and chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement has been approved by the directors of both
companies and now must be voted on by Empire's shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   The Empire transaction is valued at about $800 million.
UtiliCorp will spend $505 million to redeem Empire's common shares
and an additional $33 million for its preferred shares. UtiliCorp
also will assume $260 million of Empire's debt.
</P>
<P>
   UtiliCorp will get a utility that has 145,000 customers in
southwest Missouri and in five counties in Kansas, Oklahoma and
Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   The utility, which is to become a UtiliCorp subsidiary, will
keep the Empire name and be treated as a separate entity before
regulators. That probably means no big changes for ratepayers,
although UtiliCorp executives said some cost savings from the
merger should benefit Empire's customers.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those savings will come from an undetermined number of
job cutbacks at Empire, which will see some duties transferred to
UtiliCorp's Kansas City offices. Green said any affected Empire
employees could apply for other jobs at UtiliCorp, which has about
400 openings.
</P>
<P>
   Empire shareholders will receive $29.50 for each share of common
stock. Empire's stock closed Friday at $21.25. Using that figure,
shareholders are receiving a 39 percent premium with the UtiliCorp
offer.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase price, however, can vary, depending on the price of
UtiliCorp stock, which closed Tuesday at $23.94, down 25 cents.
Empire shareholders will get less if UtiliCorp's share price falls
below $22. They will get more if it rises above $26.
</P>
<P>
   Empire shareholders will also get a choice of cash or UtiliCorp
stock, although there will be limits on how much of each can be
used.
</P>
<P>
   Empire was founded 90 years ago and was able to survive various
challenges, including the Great Depression. But the prospect of
deregulation _ even though it's probably years away in Missouri and
Kansas _ helped to force the move Tuesday, said Myron W. McKinney,
Empire's top executive.
</P>
<P>
   He said Empire had been discussing the future of electric
utilities for the past decade and how the company could survive in
the new environment. In the last three years it realized that it
needed to find a larger partner.
</P>
<P>
   UtiliCorp, with more than $12 billion in sales, will give Empire
the platform it needs, McKinney said.
</P>
<P>
   If the St. Joseph Light and Empire acquisitions are completed,
UtiliCorp will have 375,000 electric customers in Missouri. Ameren
UE has more than 1 million and Kansas City Power &AMP; Light has
256,000 in Missouri, according to figures from the Missouri Public
Service Commission.
</P>
<P>
   KCP&AMP;L has 448,000 customers altogether when it counts those in
Kansas. A merger of Western Resources and KCP&AMP;L, which still needs
regulatory approval, would produce a utility with 1 million
customers in Kansas and Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Size matters, said Green of UtiliCorp, as electric utilities are
exposed to the free market. A larger utility, for instance, can
better withstand changes in the wholesale electricity market, which
is already deregulated. Its size can also achieve more economies to
make it more competitive.
</P>
<P>
   That being the case, UtiliCorp will continue buying utilities.
That could include more in Kansas and Missouri and possibly
municipally owned utilities, Green said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to be done for a long, long time,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
