<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    King 'Dream' Speech Box
 &HT;    (EDS: Accompanies MLK-DREAM)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A FEW GOOD WORDS
</P>
<P>
   Many of the key passages in the Rev. Martin Luther King's Aug.
28., 1963, ``I Have a Dream'' speech _ about 600 words that are
among the best remembered and most quoted _ were not in the advance
text given to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The trademark ``I have a dream'' phrase and the thoughts that
follow from it were not in the text handed out that day when King
spoke on the steps of the Lincoln Memorial, nor were the passages
introduced with his ``let freedom ring'' cry.
</P>
<P>
   It is the use of these specific words, among others _ film
archives of his delivery of them _ that has prompted his family to
sue organizations that reprint or replay them without the Kings'
permission.
</P>
<P>
   THE COST OF A DREAM
</P>
<P>
   CBS, which taped and broadcast the ``I Have A Dream'' speech,
licenses segments or ``clips'' of the speech.
</P>
<P>
   According to court motions filed by lawyers for the estate of
the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr., the network charges:
</P>
<P>
   _ $2,500 a minute of the clips to private entities and
</P>
<P>
   _ $1,000 a minute to churches, schools and other non-profits.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
