<DOCNO> NYT19990511.0398 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3178 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUETTEL-MUSIC-ART-NYT     05-11 1294
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUETTEL-MUSIC-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONGWRITER'S INDEPENDENCE ISN'T EASY TO HUM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Adam Guettel, the young songwriter, was initially
reluctant to do the concert of his work scheduled for Wednesday
night at Town Hall.
</P>
<P>
   He says he felt he had been out there enough lately. His musical
``Floyd Collins'' is playing in Chicago after performances in San
Diego and Philadelphia and may return to New York, where it was
produced in 1996. His song cycle ``Saturn Returns'' was performed
at the Joseph Papp Public Theater in April 1998. His CD ``Myths and
Hymns,'' was released in March by Nonesuch Records. The singer
Audra McDonald has included his songs on her recent CD and in
concert performances.
</P>
<P>
   And Guettel has increasingly been referred to as important to
the future of musical theater, along with other young composers
like Ricky Ian Gordon, Michael John LaChiusa, Jeanine Tesori and
Jason Robert Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I resisted this pretty strenuously,'' said Guettel, 34,
speaking about Wednesday night's concert the other day. ``It's not
seemly. I just had these shows in New York. People have already
heard this stuff. I just want to write something new.''
</P>
<P>
   But Nonesuch Records president Robert Hurwitz, who has become a
strong supporter of Guettel, quickly put things into perspective,
Guettel recalled with amused resignation. ``He said: `Now let me
get this straight. You think you're famous or something? No one
knows who you are. You have to do this.'''
</P>
<P>
   To the extent that Guettel is known, he has often been
pigeonholed as the talented composer of inaccessible music, tunes
you don't come out humming. All the more reason, some might argue,
for getting his music out there as often as possible; the more
people hear it, the sooner they will accept it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hummability has to do with how many times you hear
something,'' said Stephen Sondheim, who has encouraged Guettel.
``It's as simple as that.''
</P>
<P>
   Guettel certainly descends from a hummable tradition; his
grandfather was Richard Rodgers. He died when Guettel was 15 and
was trying to chart his own course for his compositions, playing
electric bass in a rock band, listening to Jimi Hendrix, Santana
and Jethro Tull. ``I didn't want to do the obvious, to try to
follow in my family tradition,'' Guettel said. ``I felt that would
be a terrible mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   He played only one composition for his grandfather, just before
he died. Guettel played it loud on the piano so his grandfather,
lying in bed on the other side of the wall, could hear it. Guettel
said his grandfather liked the piece.
</P>
<P>
   As Guettel grew older, he played his music for his mother, Mary
Rodgers Guettel, also a composer, who is now the chairwoman of
Juilliard. She was a tough audience. ``She would say, `That's not a
melody,''' Guettel recalled with affection.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, as Guettel has become more comfortable in his own
voice, he said, his appreciation for his grandfather's gift has
deepened. ``He was able to encode his melodies with essential
emotional information about character, about mood and desire,''
Guettel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more I try to work in this work, the more I am awed by
what he did. It's so clean and confident and instinctive and
loving.'' He continued, ``It has the sound of love.''
</P>
<P>
   Guettel also said he envied the mass appeal of his grandfather's
music. Yet given that a more traditional composer like Frank
Wildhorn currently has three shows on Broadway, Guettel faces a
difficult climb in commercial terms. In addition to writing
sophisticated harmonies, he tackles unorthodox subjects like
abortion and spirituality. ``Floyd Collins'' is based on the true
story of a man trapped in a Kentucky cave in 1925.
</P>
<P>
   Sondheim says Guettel's music is not unapproachable; it is
simply unfamiliar and unexpected. ``People have lazy ears,''
Sondheim said. ``With so much stuff in the theater, before the song
is over you know where it's going. That's not true of Adam. He is
full of surprise. The surprise is seldom arbitrary. It's usually
inevitable.''
</P>
<P>
   Talking about Guettel's music, people often mention Stravinsky,
Sondheim and Leonard Bernstein, composers whose music initially
took some getting used to. Reviewing ``Saturn Returns'' in The New
York Times, Stephen Holden wrote: ``The unifying element of
Guettel's music is a transcendent overarching melodic gift that
envelops and gives order to the often clashing inner voices of his
songs. His finest compositions have long-lined melodies that seem
to go on and on as they reach for the moon and stars, pivoting on
offbeat chromatic harmonies that are as unpredictable as they are
unabashedly romantic.''
</P>
<P>
   Guettel said he did not set out to be original. ``I'm trying to
represent the characters as I understand them and further the
story,'' he said. ``I don't care if I write the most conventional
music. It's something that may not be understood about what I'm
doing.'' He continued, ``That melody really is my main concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Young Adam started learning piano when he was 4 and wrote his
first piece at 8, scratching into the ivory keys which notes to
start on. He started singing as a soloist at the Metropolitan Opera
and the City Opera when he was 10, in productions like ``The Magic
Flute'' and ``Pelleas et Melisande,'' often missing classes at the
Collegiate School. He said his grandfather faithfully came to see
him in these productions.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Yale University in 1987, Guettel's first
major project was the music for ``The Legend of Oedipus,'' an epic
retelling of the Oedipus story directed by Nikos Psacharopoulos,
who ran the Williamstown Theater Festival. He wrote music for
documentary films and started writing ``Floyd Collins'' in 1992,
when he began to focus on theater. ``I loved it,'' Guettel said.
``I thought it was the hardest thing I'd ever tried doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night's concert, presented by Nonesuch in association
with the Public Theater, will feature pieces from Guettel's work in
progress, a new musical based on the novella ``The Light in the
Piazza,'' a love story by Elizabeth Spencer. The show's book is by
Alfred Uhry.
</P>
<P>
   Tina Landau, a director and writer who met Guettel at Yale and
has collaborated with him on several projects, said working with
him is consuming and sometimes arduous because he creates a
cohesive musical vocabulary before he begins to write a note.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike some composers, who will map out where the songs are
going to be and then start writing individual pieces, Adam will
spend months, years, whatever it takes on finding the right
vernacular for the piece as a whole,'' said Ms. Landau, who
directed and wrote the book for ``Floyd Collins.'' ``He won't move
ahead unless he feels he has reinvented some landscape.''
</P>
<P>
   While Guettel seems confident in his own work and his passion
for it, he is less sure of whether musical theater can remain
culturally relevant and commercially viable. In the world of his
grandfather, ``the idea of someone singing a song, an emotion being
pressed into metaphor, was acceptable to the larger public,''
Guettel said. ``And things have changed. The idea of someone
expressing themselves in that way, live, is not as natural a thing
and is much more difficult to put over. It feels like an impossible
chasm between what he did, getting his music out into the world,
and what I've done and hope to do.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``When I talk about that, I can feel sad. Not by
comparison, but because I want to give people something beautiful.
And it's kind of a hard business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-99 2141EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
