<HEADER>
A3179 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EVEREST-CLIMBERS-COX     05-11 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVEREST-CLIMBERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mount Everest climbers telephone LBJ students
 &HT;    By Dick Stanley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Mockingbirds were chorusing Tuesday at LBJ High
School in Northeast Austin while landscapers trimmed the campus's
trees.
</P>
<P>
   But students of LBJ's Science Academy were in a different world.
They were paying rapt attention to the words of some climbers who
were pinned down by a blizzard, 20,833 feet high on Mount Everest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some are definitely getting homesick and ready to go home,''
climber Jacek Maselko, a 1989 LBJ graduate, told the students via
satellite telephone. ``But we go on.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people here are on pins and needles,'' Jackson Pace,
Maselko's former science teacher at LBJ, told him. Pace is
coordinating the students' share in the adventure.
</P>
<P>
   Heather Saegert, 15, shook her head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad I'm not there freezing,'' Saegert said.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Baden, 16, agreed but added, ``I think they're handling it
OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Maselko, 29, is a professional guide for an Alaska
mountaineering company on his first attempt to join the more than
1,000 people who have reached the summit of the world's highest
mountain, without joining the more than 140 who have lost their
lives in the process.
</P>
<P>
   There were fears Tuesday that the toll would go higher. Some in
a group of Ukrainian climbers _ one of 23 commercial or private
groups ascending the Himalayan mountain this spring _ may have died
in the unexpected snowstorm.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago this month, 12 adventurers lost their lives in a
similar storm on what climbers call the Big E, whose 29,028-foot
summit is the roof of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Maselko said the storm Monday had forced his group of 12,
including seven clients who paid $15,000 each for the climb, to
come down from a camp at 27,230 feet, delaying their attempt at the
summit until Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very iffy,'' Maselko told the students. ``But we hope to
summit'' on Sunday or Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Farther down the mountain, Eric Brown, a 1990 LBJ graduate who
lives in Austin, is managing the group's base camp. But conditions
there aren't much better.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a very inviting place,'' Brown told the students on
the phone. ``You put your mind to it (while) your body is saying,
'No, no.' (The climbers) will be pushing themselves to the limit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Y'all be careful,'' Pace told the adventurers, ending the
conversation that was costing $2.81 a minute. ``We love you.''
</P>
<P>
   The Science Academy students, whose parents and friends are
helping pay the phone costs, applauded.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes well on the other side of the world, Maselko and
Brown will visit LBJ to discuss their adventure. If all doesn't go
well, Pace will have lost a gamble.
</P>
<P>
   ``At any moment,'' he said, ``things could turn bad there. Which
has concerned me about involving the kids. But this is a
once-in-a-lifetime story for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Dick Stanley writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
