<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3180 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PIANO-RECORDING-HISTO     05-11 1282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIANO-RECORDING-HISTORY-2TAKES-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CENTURY OF PIANO THAT CAN LAST FOR WEEKS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 16) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is it possible to sum up the vast recorded legacy of the piano?
One answer has begun to arrive in recent months. Philips has been
releasing the first volumes of Great Pianists of the 20th Century,
which it says is the largest recording project ever.
</P>
<P>
   It may well be: so far, 60 two-CD volumes have been released,
and when all 100 volumes become available by the end of October,
they will include 15,006 minutes of music. If that number is a
little difficult to comprehend, you might do the math this way:
figuring on a 35-hour-per-week listening schedule, which allows
time off for lunch and weekends, you would need nearly two months
to hear everything.
</P>
<P>
   And what do we learn? This is the $2,000 question, that, more or
less, being the cost of all 100 volumes. Has the quality of piano
performance _ the level of invention, spontaneity, rhythmic
suppleness and so on _ declined during the century, as critics
sometimes say? Has technique become an end in itself, and
homogeneity replaced once distinct national styles? Is there even
such a thing as a national school?
</P>
<P>
   If anything in the history of piano recordings can be said to
have an official stamp, this is it. Twenty-five competing record
companies (including EMI, BMG/RCA, Decca/London, Sony and Deutsche
Grammophon) are contributing to it. Tom Deacon of Philips is the
producer; Steinway is the sponsor. Alfred Brendel was one of the
advisers.
</P>
<P>
   A little carping seems in order at the start. The project is
clearly a device for the re-release of a large number of back
catalog items and for the release of a small amount (less than two
hours) of previously recorded but unpublished material, all of it
meant to be given a boost under the rubric of Great Pianists.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 74 pianists included, Artur Schnabel gets one volume,
Brendel three; Dinu Lipatti and Rachmaninoff get one each, Claudio
Arrau three. Odd, no? Arrau and Brendel, by the way, are both on
the Philips label.
</P>
<P>
   More? Glenn Gould's single volume includes no Bach, while
Rosalyn Tureck, playing only Bach, gets two volumes. And so neither
of Gould's familiar versions of Bach's ``Goldberg'' Variations is
here, but there is Ms. Tureck's version of it and a version in a
volume devoted to Maria Yudina, a little-known Soviet-era pianist
of virtuous character and eccentric musicality whose inclusion
among the greats of the century is one of the curiosities of the
series.
</P>
<P>
   Among the pianists who did not make the cut are Ferruccio
Busoni, Simon Barere, Moriz Rosenthal, Heinrich Neuhaus, Alexander
Goldenweiser, Magda Tagliaferro, Jacques Fevrier, Carl Friedberg,
Samuel Feinberg, Mark Hambourg, Percy Grainger, Emil von Sauer _
shall we go on? _ Egon Petri, Guiomar Novaes, Alexander Brailowsky,
Vlado Perlemuter, Mieczyslaw Horszowski, Richard Goode, Peter
Serkin, Vladimir de Pachmann, Paul Badura-Skoda and Garrick
Ohlsson. I could add two other pianist-composers, as well, Grieg
and Saint-Saens.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone's choices would differ, of course, though some of the
omissions seem careless or obtuse, not to mention biased against
artists who did not leave enough recorded music to fill a two-CD
set. And specific selections of recordings aren't easily explained
away. They may cause you to wonder just how much they were affected
by the desire to push recordings that aren't current sellers.
</P>
<P>
   Gould minus Bach is, in fact, defensible, because we may judge
his musicianship freshly, for better and worse, by hearing him play
Byrd (gloriously) and Mozart (disgracefully). But what about
performances that are clearly inferior to versions of the same
works recorded by the same artists?
</P>
<P>
   Alfred Cortot's performance of Schumann's ``Kreisleriana'' is an
example. The discographic information in the volume indicates that
it is his 1935 recording of the work, but it isn't: Philips
(without meaning to?) has published a different recording,
previously unreleased and, from the sound of it, evidently made
during the 1950s, when Cortot was close to 80 and declining.
</P>
<P>
   It is an interesting document but a bizarre error. His
performance of Ravel's ``Jeux d'Eau'' in the same volume,
incidentally, is also mistakenly dated: marked 1923, it's his 1931
recording.
</P>
<P>
   And there are other slapdash errors throughout the series. The
volume devoted to Paderewski includes a performance of Liszt's
famous F minor Etude, ``La Leggierezza,'' with an ending, according
to the album notes, ``revised by Benno Moiseiwitsch.'' In fact, the
recording is by Moiseiwitsch, not Paderewski, and the ending is by
Theodor Leschetizky, Moiseiwitsch's teacher, not by Moiseiwitsch.
</P>
<P>
   But enough complaining: let's just say that despite its flaws,
Great Pianists is a vast, valuable trove of piano recordings, and
among other things, it reminds us of many midcentury artists, like
Clara Haskil, Arturo Benedetti Michelangeli, Wilhelm Kempff,
William Kapell, Clifford Curzon and Friedrich Gulda, who are no
longer familiar enough to a general audience.
</P>
<P>
   The Romanian-born Haskil, for example, a student of Cortot at
the turn of the century, a woman of catastrophic health who fled
the Nazis, began to achieve the success she deserved only shortly
before she died in 1960. She has always had more of a following in
Europe than in the United States. The two volumes devoted to her in
Great Pianists feature Mozart, Schubert and Schumann, and should
rectify whatever discrepancy exists in her status on the two sides
of the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   There isn't a more humane performance on record of Schubert's
Sonata in B flat, neither of its sublime slow movement nor of the
last movement, which gallops, all buoyancy and wit.
</P>
<P>
   Curzon's Schubert is slightly foursquare by comparison with
Haskil's but a paragon of seriousness and proportion.
</P>
<P>
   Michelangeli, like Curzon, was a cultish figure of the third
quarter of the century, the two of them nearly opposite in style.
Michelangeli's version of Ravel's ``Gaspard de la Nuit'' is
hypnotic, a model of his pianism, astonishing in its variety of
colors and sonorities, and as such, reflecting an approach to the
music that is less analytic than Romantic, which is to say less
modern and more connected to the sensibilities of the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Gulda, the singular Viennese pianist and sometime
saxophonist, who made his name in the 1950s playing Bach and
Beethoven, increasingly devoting himself after that to jazz. One of
his two volumes includes Beethoven's Concerto in C, the four Chopin
ballades and George Shearing's ``Lullaby of Birdland'' _ soup to
nuts, musically speaking _ and you hear him listening, thinking,
making decisions in the process, which is how music ought to be
made.
</P>
<P>
   (``Lullaby of Birdland'' is the only jazz I noticed in the
series, not counting Andre Previn's performances of Gershwin.
Perhaps we should have added Art Tatum and Oscar Peterson to the
list of pianists not included.)
</P>
<P>
   As to the volumes devoted to giants like Vladimir Horowitz,
Arthur Rubinstein, Rachmaninoff and Lipatti (and also, judging by
the list of recordings for his album, which has not yet been
released, Leopold Godowsky), suffice it to say that they are solid
introductions for anyone who doesn't already own their recordings.
</P>
<P>
   I'll just note that the Paderewski album, notwithstanding the
Moiseiwitsch slip-up and despite the fact that he recorded after
his peak years, demonstrates in several Chopin etudes what it means
to have tremendous sensibility and a big heart.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   I don't want to stress dead pianists. Music critics sometimes
bemoan the evolution of piano performance in this century, as if
pianists used to have soul and have increasingly become machines.
The supposed decline is attributed partly to technology, editing
equipment now permitting recording companies to produce technically
flawless performances that have altered the public's expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Partly the decline is fixed on what you might call the industry
of the music conservatories and piano competitions, and partly on a
shift in approach to performance as performance has been divorced
from composition. The great pianists from Mozart through
Rachmaninoff were composers. Increasingly, they're specialists. And
the result is said to be a loss of spontaneity and originality.
</P>
<P>
   This view betrays, I think, a morose nostalgia, and Great
Pianists shows why. Four versions of Beethoven's Sonata in C minor
(Op. 111), for example, have been released in the series so far _
Schnabel's, Sviatoslav Richter's, Wilhelm Backhaus' and Stephen
Kovacevich's _ and conventional wisdom would dictate that the best
performance is one of the older ones: Schnabel's or Richter's or
Backhaus'.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the youngest player, Kovacevich, who leaves the lasting
impression. His performance is exact and melancholic at the start,
unfolding organically, coherently, with a tender Arietta that ends
up heaven-storming. Richter, a genius, in this live performance
sounds uncharacteristically uncooked. Backhaus is stolid.
Schnabel's version, one of several he left on disk, lurches. It's
sloppy, even for him.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Kovacevich, Radu Lupu, Andras Schiff, Martha Argerich
and Mitsuko Uchida are all among the active performers in this
series who belie the lazy cliche of a decline in pianistic
sensibility. Ms. Argerich plays too fast and aggressively at times,
but her interpretations of Bach, Liszt, Rachmaninoff and Chopin on
these disks are solid and long-lined: an exemplar of modern
pianism.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, a volume devoted to Van Cliburn shows why he was so
widely embraced even before he became a cold war celebrity. He
performs warhorses like Rachmaninoff's Concerto in D minor with an
astonishing delicacy and soulfulness. Rachmaninoff's B flat minor
Sonata, a crazy, sprawling work in Horowitz's frenetic accounts, in
Cliburn's hands becomes a moving, cogent minor masterpiece of late
Romanticism.
</P>
<P>
   Cliburn is a modern player, though I might add that his
honey-colored sound is a link to Arthur Friedheim, the Russian-born
student of Liszt, who taught Cliburn's mother, who taught him.
</P>
<P>
   Genealogy is sometimes deceptive. Lipatti was a Cortot pupil,
and are there two more diametrically opposite pianists in the 20th
century? Still, knowing a pianist's particular pedagogical lineage
can be useful, more so than relying on vague categories like
national schools. Listen, for example, to the recordings in this
series of Vladimir Ashkenazy, Horowitz and Richter and you'll see
why the conventional notion of a Russian school is nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   Ashkenazy, a pianist of moderation and laser precision, studied
at the Moscow Conservatory with Lev Oborin. Oborin was a different
kind of musician from Heinrich Neuhaus, who taught Richter and also
Lupu, the Romanian pianist. Richter's and Lupu's renderings of
Beethoven sonatas, several of which are included on these disks,
have more in common _ call it a certain ponderous, strong-willed
physicality _ than Richter has in common stylistically with either
Ashkenazy or Horowitz.
</P>
<P>
   Their only link, you might say, is that they are all virtuosos
of one sort or another, true virtuosity having little to do with
note-perfection or speedy hands. It describes artists in this
series like Myra Hess, Solomon and Edwin Fischer no less than it
does pyrotechnicians like Josef Hofmann, Evgeny Kissin and
Moisewitsch.
</P>
<P>
   I return, finally, to Moisewitsch, because he was a great
character, a modern virtuoso, increasingly forgotten: a
Russian-born pupil of Leschetizky's, a warm, funny man who
developed a reputation among his friends in London, where he had
settled, for being a deadpan cardsharp, he died in 1963, at 73, a
beloved figure in England.
</P>
<P>
   At the keyboard he played with Olympian ease, exquisite taste
and a radiant tone. During Lincoln Center's recent series ``Great
Pianists of the 20th Century on Film,'' he gave a jaw-dropping
traversal of Liszt's transcription of Wagner's ``Tannhauser''
Overture, a bombastic work of herculean difficulty, which he
disposed of without sweat, seated quietly, as if reading the
morning newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   His single volume in the Philips series is a serious
contribution to the discography, because most of the music has not
previously been available on CD. It includes Chopin _ the
Barcarolle and a suave reading of the Scherzo in E _ along with
Rachmaninoff, Liszt and others, all of it smooth as silk.
</P>
<P>
   In his case, I could have stood a second volume, maybe including
his 1938 recording of the Wagner-Liszt overture, his Beethoven
Third Piano Concerto, his Schumann Fantasie and his performance of
Tausig's arrangement of Weber's ``Invitation to a Dance,'' which, I
gather, is terrific.
</P>
<P>
   There is an excellent Moiseiwitsch disk from Pearl, the finest
producer of old piano recordings, which, besides the overture,
includes the Mendelssohn Concerto in G minor and Brahms' Variations
and Fugue on a Theme of Handel; neither of them is here. And I was
bothered, once again, that much of the discographic information in
the existing volume is incomplete and careless. And _ I am
quibbling again.
</P>
<P>
   But, after all, what is the point of a collection of the
greatest hits of the century if not to give know-it-alls something
to complain about into the next century?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
