<HEADER>
A3185 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CEO-GROUP-KAN &LR;      05-11 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CEO-GROUP-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CEO SUPPORT GROUP PROVIDES FORUM FOR NONBIASED COUNSEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Take it from Deb Turpin: It is lonely at the
top.
</P>
<P>
   Turpin, founder and chief executive of River City Studio, is a
visible and honored small-business leader in Kansas City. She is
chairwoman of the Metropolitan Entrepreneurs Council of the Greater
Kansas City Chamber of Commerce. She won the 1999 Advertising
Executive of the Year award from the Ad Club of Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Yet she's the first to admit she doesn't have all the answers _
or even all the questions. So, once a month, she leaves her graphic
design business for a day to meet with a small group of fellow
CEOs.
</P>
<P>
   In the Kansas City area, four such groups meet monthly under the
TEC umbrella. TEC, formerly known as The Executive Committee, was
founded in 1957 as an educational forum for company presidents and
business owners.
</P>
<P>
   TEC is an organization, said group convener Tony Lewis, ``where
members go to get their answers questioned.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis is chairwoman of two of the four areawide TEC groups
meeting in the Kansas City region. Joe Edwards, based in Leawood,
Kan., is chairman of another TEC group, which includes Turpin. Ted
Davis, based in Leavenworth, Kan., is chairman of a fourth TEC
group.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen members is considered to be the optimum size for TEC
groups, and all the organizers say they can handle more members.
</P>
<P>
   The three Kansas City area conveners help plan meetings and
advise TEC members. Membership, which is by invitation, is aimed at
CEOs of companies with $3 million or more in annual sales and 25 or
more employees.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to learning from her peers, Turpin said, ``Probably
the most valuable thing about TEC is that it makes me accountable
to someone.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the CEO, I'm not held accountable to anyone within my own
organization. I am held accountable to my TEC group. We give each
other honest, and sometimes brutal, advice. ... It's better than
having a board of directors.''
</P>
<P>
   Participant Joe Lawson said one of TEC's values was that ``it
costs less than hiring a consultant _ and the results come from
folks who do know what they are talking about, not from folks who
talk about what they probably haven't done.''
</P>
<P>
   TEC membership costs $825 a month, payable quarterly, which
works out to nearly $10,000 a year. Members say it's worth it,
given the value of information exchanged.
</P>
<P>
   The international TEC organization provides printed and Web site
educational materials and recommends expert speakers. Typical TEC
meetings feature a speaker for half a day and a closed-door,
no-holds-barred discussion among peers for the other half. Topics
range from business to personal.
</P>
<P>
   Groups rotate meetings among their members' work sites or
occasionally hotels if a CEO's business doesn't have a conference
room to hold the group.
</P>
<P>
   The format, said participant Bob Cutler, provides ``a nonbiased
forum'' for second-guessing the kinds of questions and answers that
land on a CEO's desk. Cutler said he saved much time and money by
drawing on other CEOs' experiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find there's a lot of value for the dollars invested,''
agreed participant Bob Niles. Furthermore, he said, the meetings
offer CEO-level training and education that can be difficult to
find.
</P>
<P>
   Each TEC group is organized on a principle similar to many
breakfast clubs _ only one CEO from a particular kind of business
is allowed in a group. So a group couldn't have two CEOs of mutual
fund companies, for example.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a CEO can't join a TEC group that already has a
chief executive from a company with which he or she does business,
competes or has any other kind of relationship.
</P>
<P>
   That policy keeps the give-and-take sessions confidential and
eliminates conflicts of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Participants say they are religious about attending sessions
because of the value they think they get from and give to one
another. It's also good discipline, Cutler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a CEO says they do not have time for this or anything else
in their lives, then they are probably not in control of their
time, and the business is thus managing them,'' Cutler said.
</P>
<P>
   Turpin, who founded her business backed by a fine-arts degree
and no business training, said TEC was her business professor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other thing I find is that a day away from the day-to-day
operations and phone calls really is important,'' she said. ``(It)
helps clear my head so I can have the opportunity to think about
the big picture, rather than always be immersed in the small
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   For further information about TEC groups in the Kansas City
area, call Joe Edwards at 491-0030, Ted Davis at (913) 682-2589 or
Tony Lewis at 587-6499.
</P>
<P>
   Information about the organization also is available from TEC
headquarters in San Diego at (800) 274-2367 or tec &LR; tecceo.com. The
organization's Web site is http://www.tecceo.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
