<HEADER>
A3191 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Monti-Trial-KAN &LR;      05-11 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Monti-Trial-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENDANT CONVICTED IN KILLING OF CLAIRE-MARIE MONTI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD ESPINOZA  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Three times as juror Mike Bradley left the
Johnson County, Kan., Courthouse last week, he thought that he had
heard the worst about the murder of Claire-Marie Monti. But the
evidence in Rodney Wayne Henry's murder trial kept getting worse.
</P>
<P>
   First, there were the photos of the Lenexa hotel room where
Monti was sexually abused and murdered. The next day, the eight
women and four men on the jury had to stare at poster-sized photos
of Monti's injuries. The worst, Bradley said, was when prosecutors
played a videotape of Henry detailing how Monti was attacked and
murdered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was traumatic,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the jurors found Henry, 25, guilty of first-degree
murder, rape and aggravated criminal sodomy. Judge Peter Ruddick
will hear post-trial motions July 15 and might sentence Henry then.
The mandatory sentence is life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Paul Morrison said he hasn't decided whether
to ask for a ``hard 40'' sentence, which would keep Henry from
being paroled for at least 40 years, but he will ask that Henry
serve more than the minimum 25 years before parole.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure he's a very old man before he sees a
parole board,'' Morrison said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Monti, a 32-year-old computer trainer from
suburban Philadelphia, was in Johnson County for a job in April
1998 when she met Henry and Carl Dean Rails at a Westport bar. The
three went to Monti's Lenexa hotel, and the men attacked her when
she refused a sexual advance, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   Henry's culpability came from the help he gave Rails during the
attack, Morrison said.
</P>
<P>
   Rails is charged with capital murder. Prosecutors and defense
lawyers don't expect his trial to begin until fall or winter.
</P>
<P>
   Morrison said he doesn't plan to offer Henry a sentencing deal
in exchange for testimony in Rails' trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very, very careful about negotiating with criminals and
turning them into witnesses,'' Morrison said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors are seeking the death penalty for Rails.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Henry told the court that he held Monti's arms behind
her back while Rails pummeled her. He sobbed as he testified that
he was afraid of Rails and didn't know what to do during the
attack.
</P>
<P>
   Henry's breakdown didn't sway jurors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all had a real hesitancy to place much faith or credibility
in the defendant's words,'' Bradley, the presiding juror, said
outside court. ``...A couple of the jurors noticed a lack of
physical tears, and there was some comment about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Monti's parents, Vic and Claire Monti, found the sobbing
insincere.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's bawling not for Claire-Marie Monti, but because of the
situation he's in,'' Vic Monti said. ``I think he's crying because
he got caught.''
</P>
<P>
   The jury's main considerations were whether the murder was
premeditated and whether Monti was sexually assaulted before or
after she died. Henry could not have been convicted of the sex
crimes if Monti had been dead when the assault occurred.
</P>
<P>
   About 9:30 a.m. Tuesday, 3 hours into deliberations that began
Monday night, the jury asked to review Henry's confession and a
pathologist's testimony about Monti's injuries.
</P>
<P>
   After watching the videotaped confession, the jurors who had
been unsure when the sexual assault took place were certain that
Monti had still been alive, Bradley said. They didn't need a court
reporter to read back the pathologist's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The jury reached its verdicts by 10:20 a.m. Henry, clad in a
dark blue suit, rubbed his upper lip while he waited for jurors to
enter the courtroom. He looked at his lap as the verdicts were read
but showed little emotion.
</P>
<P>
   As Henry was led from the courtroom, he stopped and called
Morrison a liar until deputies tugged to get him to continue
walking down a hallway. Henry's mother sat silently in court for a
few minutes and declined to talk to a reporter as she walked out.
</P>
<P>
   Monti's parents, who flew in from Pennsylvania, were pleased
that the first murder case is drawing to a close, but they know
their ordeal is not over. They plan to return for Rails' trial, and
they know they'll hear much of the same traumatic testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the last thing I can do for my daughter,'' Claire Monti
said. ``There's nothing more I can do after that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
