u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHOTO-FULL-UPDATE-NYT     05-11 2513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-FULL-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 05/11/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) NEW YORK -- May 11, 1999 -- GUETTEL-MUSIC, 5-11 -- Adam
Guettel at home in Manhattan. Guettel, the young songwriter, has
increasingly been referred to as important to the future of musical
theater, along with other young composers like Ricky Ian Gordon,
Michael John LaChiusa, Jeanine Tesori and Jason Robert Brown. ``I
want to give people something beautiful,'' says Guettel, 34. (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. -- May 11, 1999 --
NJ-CORZINE-POLITICS, 5-11 -- Jon S. Corzine, former chairman of
Goldman Sachs Group, is at a New Jersey Democratic Party conference
in Atlantic City, angling for a run for the U.S. Senate. To the
surprise of many New Jersey democrats, Corzine, 52, has emerged as
a leading contender in a crowded field to replace Sen. Frank G.
Lautenberg, the three-term democrat who plans to retire next year.
(Frank C. Dougherty/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) UNDATED -- May 11, 1999 -- CHINA-MONEY, 5-11 -- Henry
Hwang, vice president of the Far East National Bank, in his office,
right, and an undated photo of Nan Nan Xu, who left the bank in
1996 as the highest-paid executive after the chairman. A complex
trail of tens of millions of dollars has flowed from China into the
small American bank. Since the transactions were noticed in 1996,
the money's purpose has been a mystery. But now some investigators
have begun to suspect that it may have been to pay for intelligence
operations. Hwang and Ms. Nan deny any wrongdoing in regards to the
transactions. (Marissa Roth, right/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) WASHINGTON -- May 11, 1999 -- CHINA-FUNDRAISING-3, 5-11
-- Former Democratic fund-raiser Johnny Chung testifies before the
House Government Reform and Oversight Committee on Tuesday. Chung
testified that he took $300,000 from a Chinese intelligence
official who wanted to help re-elect President Clinton and later
was offered hush money to discourage him from cooperating with the
FBI. (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) WASHINGTON -- May 11, 1999 -- JUVENILE-JUSTICE, 5-11 --
Flanked by Sens. Orin Hatch, R-Utah, and Sen. Joe Biden, D-Del.,
with back to cacmera, Sen. Jeff Sessions, R-Ala., talks to
reporters about gun control legislation on Tuesday. Three weeks
after the Colorado high school shootings, Republicans and Democrats
skirmished over gun control and youth violence Wednesday in the
prelude to an expected Senate showdown later in the week. (Shana
Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- May 11, 1999 -- ROSALYNN-CARTER, 5-11 --
Rosalynn Carter during an interview last week. Mrs. Carter was the
prelude to Hillary Rodham Clinton, a quietly rebellious first lady
of the late 1970's who sat in on Cabinet meetings, pushed Congress
to pass mental health legislation and was asked by her party to run
for the U.S. Senate seat from Georgia.''What would I have done in
Washington with Jimmy at home?'' said Mrs. Carter on commenting on
why she did not run for the Senate. (Librado Romero/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) SKOPJE, Macedonia -- May 11, 1999 -- KOSOVO-REFUGEES --
5-11 -- Dr. Mustafe Abdyli, an ethnic Albanian from the village of
Smire, in southern Kosovo, at a relatives home where he now lives.
Abdyli was wisked out of his village by one of a dozen Serb and
Macedonian smugglers in Skopje willing to enter Kosovo, retrieve
trapped ethnic Albanians, and ferry them back to Macedonia.
Abdyli's brother paid the driver $2,000 to smuggle him and his
family out of Kosovo. (Tyler Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) PRISTINA, Yugoslavia -- May 11, 1999 --
KOSOVO-PRISTINA-2, 5-11 -- Damage in the Dragadon neighborhood of
Pristina on Monday. The Serbs rampaged through Dragodan, where
Washington once put an American cultural center. The bigger and
gaudier the house, it seemed, the bigger the fire. The streets are
blocked with broken masonry and burned cars, and no one seems to
live there anymore, except for a few very elderly Albanian men.
(Steve Erlanger/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) PRISTINA, Yugoslavia -- May 11, 1999 --
KOSOVO-PRISTINA-1, 5-11 -- A deserted street with gutted stores in
Dragodan, a wealthy Albanian neighborhood of Pristina, on Monday.
The Serbs rampaged through Dragodan, where Washington put an
American cultural center. The bigger and gaudier the house, it
seemed, the bigger the fire. The streets are blocked with broken
masonry and burned cars, and no one seems to live there anymore,
except for a few very elderly Albanian men. (Steve Erlanger/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) EFRAT, West Bank -- May 11, 1999 -- ISRAEL-POLITICS-3,
5-11 -- Patrons at a cafe are surrounded with campaign posters
including ones for the incumbent, Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu, on Tuesday. Israelis go to the polls on May 17 to cast
their ballot in parliamentary and prime ministerial elections.
(Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) ISTANBUL, Turkey -- May 11, 1999 -- TURKEY-LAWMAKER,
5-11 -- Merve Kavakci, who left the floor of the Turkish parliament
last week after her attire caused a raucous during her swearing-in
ceremony, during an interview in her office. Kavakci, who was
elected to parliament last month, does not look like someone who
could send a nation of 65 million into turmoil. But because the
parliamentary chamber, considered in Turkey as the cathedral of the
secular republic, decided that it was no place for a woman with a
Muslim scarf, she has done exactly that. (Staton R. Winter/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEWARK, N.J. -- May 11, 1999 -- HOUSE-HASTERT, 5-11 --
House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert greets students at North Star
Academy during a visit on Tuesday. Five months after he was tapped
as the accidental speaker, Hastert has turned out to be just what
most House Republicans want: nearly invisible. Instead of charging
the ideological ramparts like his predecessor Newt Gingrich,
Hastert, a former high school coach, limits his public appearances
mostly to schools. (G. Paul Burnett/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- May 11, 1999 -- MARKET-EVOLUTION, 5-11 --
Matt Andresen, president of Island ECN, left, and Ed Nicoll, the
chief financial officer of Island ECN's parent group, Datek
Holdings, inside the data center which runs the virtual stock
market. As Americans gallop into the stock market seeking instant
riches or retirement security, the basic trading machinery is also
being made up on the fly. Driven by technology, upstarts like
Island ECN are luring trades away from Nasdaq and the New York
Stock Exchange by offering nanosecond service and microscopic fees.
(Jeffrey A. Salter/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) WASHINGTON -- May 11, 1999 -- CHINA-FUNDRAISING-2, 5-11
-- Former Democratic fund-raiser Johnny Chung testifies before the
House Government Reform and Oversight Committee on Tuesday. Chung
testified that he took $300,000 from a Chinese intelligence
official who wanted to help re-elect President Clinton and later
was offered hush money to discourage him from cooperating with the
FBI. (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) WASHINGTON -- May 11, 1999 -- KOSOVO-CONGRESS, 5-11 --
Sen. Robert Byrd, D-Del., turns to an aide during a Senate
Appropriations Committee meeting on Tuesday. With billions of
dollars on the line for battles in the Balkans, military projects
for the Pentagon and disaster victims in Central America, Congress
bargained on Tuesday over multibillion-dollar emergency bills
larded with benefits for corporate interests and favored
constituents. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WASHINGTON -- May 11, 1999 -- CLINTON, 5-11 -- President
Clinton is applauded after a speech touting his tax incentives and
loan guarantees to encourage businesses to invest in urban and
rural areas in need of economic stimulus, on Tuesday at the White
House. With Clinton are are, from left, Vice President Al Gore,
Secretary of Agriculture Dan Glickman and Labor Secretary Alexis
Herman. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) WASHINGTON -- May 11, 1999 -- CHINA-FUNDRAISING, 5-11 --
Former Democratic fund raiser Johnny Chung, center, listens to
attorney Brian Sun, while attorney Paul Murphy looks on in the
background during his testimony on Capitol Hill on Tuesday. After
pleading guilty to making illegal campaign contributions to
President Clinton, Chung said he was threatened and offered money
from Beijing ``to take care of'' his legal expenses and family if
he refused to cooperate with the FBI. (Shana Raab/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) UNDATED -- May 11, 1999 -- ROSEMARY-BUSH, 5-11 -- Used
judiciously, rosemary performs a subtle magic to cooking. The herb
brings a hint forest and briny sea air, camphorlike and breezy, to
anything from wild game to delicate seafood, from pasta and
potatoes to custards and sorbet. (Jeffery A. Salter/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) LAKELAND, Fla. -- May 11, 1999 -- ELLIS-WATER-SKI, 5-11
-- Scot Ellis, the world's top-ranked jumper in the sport of water
skiing, performing his craft. After a spectacular crash in July
1995, doctors told Ellis he would not be able to ski again. ``I
admit that did motivate me a little bit,'' Ellis now says. A year
after the injury, he made it to the U.S. Water Ski team. Two years
after the crash, he finished second in jumping on the pro water
skiing tour. Now at 27, he is ranked first in the world. (David
Mills/The Lakeland Ledger)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) SARASOTA, Fla. -- May 11, 1999 -- RARE-FLOWER, 5-11 -- A
Titan arum, or Amorphophallus Titanum, is rapidly approaching its
blooming stage at Marie Selby Botanical Gardens. When Titan arum
blooms, which has only occurred seven times this century in the
United States, it will exude a potent foul odor. The bloom only
lasts 48 hours however. (Bill Speer/Sarasota Herald-Tribune)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) BOSTON -- May 11, 1999 -- TRAVELING-SAFELY-BOS, 5-11 --
Rochelle Sobel's son Aron died in a 1995 bus accident while on
vacation in Turkey after finishing medical school. With the support
of her husband, Ms. Sobel, seen recenlty crossing a street, has
launched a campaign to alert young Americans to the dangers of road
travel around the world. (Pat Greenhouse/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) STENKOVEC, Macedonia -- May 11, 1999 --
KOSOVO-REFUGEES-FLOATER-2, 5-11 -- Ethnic Albanian men at a refugee
camp wait inside a tent for their chance to register for
transportation to the local airport on Tuesday. The Macedonian
government has stepped up efforts to move refugees from Kosovo out
of the camps and onto flights bound for countries which have agreed
to house them. (Tyler Hicks/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) STENKOVEC, Macedonia -- May 11, 1999 --
KOSOVO-REFUGEES-FLOATER-1, 5-11 -- An ethnic Albanian man becomes
angry on Tuesday after complications arose while registering
refugees at the camp for transportation out of the country. The
Macedonian government has stepped up efforts to move refugees from
Kosovo out of the camps and onto flights bound for countries which
have agreed to house them. (Tyler Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) SOMERVILLE, Mass. -- May 11, 1999 -- BOX-ROSENBLATT-BOS,
5-11 -- Dana Rosenblatt prepares for his upcoming match at Foxwoods
Casino where he will fight against Lloyd Bryan of Baltimore in an
ESPN2 main event. Rosenblatt four years ago was rated in the top 10
by the World Boxing Council and World Boxing Association and
reached No. 1 in the World Boxing Union only to be knocked cold by
an opponent. After suffering a broken hand in a subsequent
come-back fight, his progression in the boxing world slowed even
more. (Pat Greenhouse/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) SEOUL, South Korea -- May 11, 1999 -- KOREA-ARTS, 5-11 --
Ji Hyun Eun in her art class which consists of copying classical
busts. There is a growing sense in South Korea that the system of
nurturing young artists is catastrophically flawed. The problem is
that many art departments admit students largely based on their
ability to copy classical busts, so that is what artistically
inclined children spend years learning to do. (Nicholas D.
Kristof/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- May 11, 1999 -- SALINGER-LETTERS, 5-11 --
Fourteen letters by J.D. Salinger, the most private of literary
figures, are about to be auctioned by Sotheby's in a move likely to
raise anew vexing questions about the private rights of public
figures. The letters were written between April 25, 1972, and
August 17, 1973, to the writer Joyce Maynard, with whom Salinger
carried on a nine-month romance that began when she was an
18-year-old Yale University freshman and he was a celebrated
53-year old author. (Sotheby's/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) RAMAT AVIV, Israel -- May 11, 1999 -- ISRAEL-POLITICS-2,
5-11 -- An advertisement placed by the Shinui Party at a bus stop
calls on voters to resist pressures by Orthodox Jewish parties in
choosing their candidates in upcoming elections. With less than a
week to go before Israelis go to the polls, a trip through southern
Israel finds voters more interested in issues and less interested
in personalities. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) ASHKELON, Israel -- May 11, 1999 -- ISRAEL-POLITICS, 5-11
-- ``And You Will Do As You Are Told,'' reads a campaign billboard
for the Shas Party hanging over a major street in the southern
Israeli city. The poster reminds Shas supporters to follow
instructions on whom to vote for in upcoming elections issued by
party leaders, mostly rabbis. With less than a week to go before
the election, a trip through southern Israel finds voters more
interested in issues and less interested in personalities. (Rina
Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) UNDATED -- May 11, 1999 -- BROWN-SUGAR, 5-11 -- Samples
of various forms of brown sugar including, from left, Demerara
sugar in cubes, dark brown sugar by Domino, crystallized Demerara,
dark muscovado and Golden Baker's. There is much more to reap from
a sugar than sweetness, like richness of texture, a molasses
bouquet and an old-fashioned aroma. These are qualities only brown
sugar can provide. (Jeffery A. Salter/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- May 11, 1999 -- URBAN-HERBS, 5-11 -- From
left, basil, mint, thyme, chives, and parsley are grown on the fire
escape of a Brooklyn apartment. Every spring, when the urge to grow
sets in, New Yorkers carry home pots of herbs, imagining a garden
on the windowsill where fresh basil and dill can be plucked with
abandon. (Jeffery A. Salter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
