<P>
   (NYT12) LAKELAND, Fla. -- May 11, 1999 -- ELLIS-WATER-SKI, 5-11
-- Scot Ellis, the world's top-ranked jumper in the sport of water
skiing, performing his craft. After a spectacular crash in July
1995, doctors told Ellis he would not be able to ski again. ``I
admit that did motivate me a little bit,'' Ellis now says. A year
after the injury, he made it to the U.S. Water Ski team. Two years
after the crash, he finished second in jumping on the pro water
skiing tour. Now at 27, he is ranked first in the world. (David
Mills/The Lakeland Ledger)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) SARASOTA, Fla. -- May 11, 1999 -- RARE-FLOWER, 5-11 -- A
Titan arum, or Amorphophallus Titanum, is rapidly approaching its
blooming stage at Marie Selby Botanical Gardens. When Titan arum
blooms, which has only occurred seven times this century in the
United States, it will exude a potent foul odor. The bloom only
lasts 48 hours however. (Bill Speer/Sarasota Herald-Tribune)
</P>
<P>
