<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3219 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANDRE-DINNER-FILM-3TA     05-11 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDRE-DINNER-FILM-3TAKES-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MY LUNCH WITH ANDRE (AND WALLY)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 16) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MEL GUSSOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (italics)``MY DINNER WITH ANDRE,'' directed by Louis Malle, was
a surprise success in 1981 and quickly became a cult movie
favorite: a virtuosic colloquy between two old friends whose wide
disparities were philosophical as well as personal.
</P>
<P>
   Over dinner, Andre Gregory, an experimental theater director,
tells of his theatrical and spiritual adventures, and Wallace
Shawn, a playwright with a more sedentary approach to life, listens
in amazement while offering his own pithy comments. The interplay
is both amusing and poignant as each man searches for
self-expression.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, the movie was shown as part of an archival series of
classic films at the Hamptons International Festival on Long
Island, and it has just been re-released, beginning with an
exclusive engagement at Lincoln Plaza Cinemas in Manhattan. This
seemed a propitious time to bring the two together for another
conversation _ about the film, questions of art and reality, and
what has happened to them since that first ``Dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   I have known them both for many years, but this was the first
time the three of us had had lunch together. We met at Mesa Grill
on lower Fifth Avenue, a restaurant of Gregory's choice, and we all
ordered quail salad, a tribute to ``My Dinner With Andre,'' in
which they dined on quail. What follows is an edited version of my
lunch with Andre and Wally.
</P>
<P>
   At the festival in East Hampton, neither of them had watched the
entire movie. I had seen it again on television and said I was more
aware that they were acting, even though they were playing
characters based on themselves.(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ANDRE GREGORY. In the rehearsal process I was completely
floundering because I was trying to play myself as really me,
whatever that means. Once I could get a handle on myself as a
character, I actually started using four different voices. One was
the sort of Peter Brook guru voice. One was a kind of flaky
upper-middle-class, spoiled, off-the-wall voice. One was a kind of
religious fanatic who would sell out his best friend for
enlightenment. And the fourth was my sincere voice, which only
appeared toward the end of the movie.
</P>
<P>
   MEL GUSSOW. All are aspects of your personality?
</P>
<P>
   GREGORY. Oh, but that's true of any role you play.
</P>
<P>
   GUSSOW. But it's rare that anyone has four such contrasting
personalities.
</P>
<P>
   GREGORY. That's part of what's interesting about being a
character actor.
</P>
<P>
   GUSSOW. You're both character actors, aren't you?
</P>
<P>
   WALLACE SHAWN. Well, that's not by choice. It's involuntary.
That's just due to the stupidity of the people who hire us.
</P>
<P>
   GUSSOW. You would prefer to be a leading man?
</P>
<P>
   SHAWN. In one's own life, one imagines oneself to be a leading
man, and we could easily be leading men if people made films of
different kinds.
</P>
<P>
   Could I comment on what Andre said? I couldn't watch the parts
of the film with me in it, but I watched the beginning where it's
mostly Andre talking. I was impressed by what a wonderful actor he
is, and what a wonderful director Louis is. But the character that
they settled on, this very manic figure who is a compulsive talker,
is not in any way what Andre Gregory ever was. Now maybe in his
head he's the fanatic or the guru dispensing wisdom, but in real
life he doesn't ever show those aspects, and he doesn't show that
driving need to dominate the conversation.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, it was the biggest trap that we had in rehearsal,
this danger of trying to be the way you really are. In my case, I
was much more confrontational and truculent than I would ever be in
life.
</P>
<P>
   GUSSOW. At the time, you said you were ``determined to defend
myself against Andre and not to let him upset me,'' and that he was
determined to evoke a response from you. In a sense, that's the
storyline.
</P>
<P>
   SHAWN. That seems right, although with hindsight I might
redescribe our objectives today slightly more in terms of wanting
to be enlightened by the other. Each of us comes to the dinner, in
a way, hoping to be cracked by the other, particularly my
character.
</P>
<P>
   GREGORY. A very famous director who will remain nameless thought
the movie could only work if it was a man and a woman, probably
because there could be an undercurrent of flirtatiousness and
seductiveness. But I think it's a men's movie on one level because
one man has trouble articulating. The other guy just talks at him;
he doesn't really talk with him. So I see one line of the movie as
two men who are hidden: one through introversion, the other through
extroversion.
</P>
<P>
   SHAWN. In a sense, you could say I was getting ready to become a
little bit more like the character he plays, and maybe he was ready
to become slightly more like the better side of the character I
play. I had the intention of murdering the side of myself that was
shown in the film. Not that anyone would care, but that's the
secret story behind the story.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   GUSSOW. If you were to remake the movie, could you play each
other's roles?
</P>
<P>
   SHAWN. Well, we did think of a movie in which I would sort of go
berserk and he would be trying to calm me down. In a certain way,
``Vanya on 42d Street'' is that movie.
</P>
<P>
   GREGORY. I personally think that Wally is one of our great
actors. In ``My Dinner With Andre,'' he has an ability to do
something which, as an actor, I have great trouble with. In life,
I'm a great listener. When I'm acting, I'm a very bad listener
because I'm always so worried about my next response, or my cue. So
I'm not sure how good I would have been playing Wally's role, and
also, Wally's role is amazingly comedic. I would probably play him
more as a Jungian therapist.
</P>
<P>
   SHAWN. When Louis was alive, the idea of a sequel was never
totally out of the question, but I certainly didn't want to do it
unless it would be better than the first one. I had a picture of it
that would have been the opposite way from ``My Dinner With
Andre.'' I would have been talking about my experiences.
</P>
<P>
   GUSSOW. Do you also think of your character as having different
aspects?
</P>
<P>
   SHAWN. I suppose I conceived of it as starting off entirely in a
defensive mode, trying not to be upset by the somewhat anarchic
forces that are being unleashed at the dinner table and are
threatening to my complacency. Then later making a kind of
last-ditch protest and in a way giving in and allowing myself to be
affected by Andre. Louis had a much less satirical approach to both
of our characters than I did. Or at least he allowed the affection
that he felt for us personally to color his interpretation. He
painted a much warmer and more compassionate portrait of both of us
than if another person had directed the movie.
</P>
<P>
   GUSSOW. How much free play of the imagination went into the
writing?
</P>
<P>
   SHAWN. In a way, no free play of the imagination went into it.
The imagination was only in figuring out what the discussion was
going to be about and making it out of the pieces that were
available. There are some connective bits that string it all
together. But basically it's made up of fragments from the real
conversations, and certainly there are no stories or facts that are
made up out of my head _ except the dinner itself.
</P>
<P>
   GUSSOW. Did you ever have a dinner or a lunch together before
you shot the movie?
</P>
<P>
   SHAWN. That wasn't something that we ever did.
</P>
<P>
   GREGORY. Breaking old habits changed both of us: mine to listen,
yours to speak.
</P>
<P>
   SHAWN. It's a film about a couple of men making a stab at
intimacy, which remains quite a challenge for most men.
</P>
<P>
   GREGORY. A lot of people have described the experience of
watching the movie as being sort of trippy or druglike, which is
partly the speed at which we're talking, partly the amount of
imagery.
</P>
<P>
   SHAWN. That speed was driven by Louis. We both spoke in the
movie much faster than either of us really speak. It was an
inspired idea on Louis' part.
</P>
<P>
   GREGORY. Because the camera's in close-up, it can see lots of
things in me that I'm not even aware of. I was in a Peter Weir
movie and he actually burst out laughing in the middle of a take. I
said, ``What's so funny?'' And he said, ``The camera goes into
close-up and looks into your eyes and sees such depth of
existential terror, that it's just very funny.'' One thing for
sure: the movie sort of stopped me telling stories at dinner
parties. Because I love to tell stories, I did it compulsively.
When I was going through those things I talk about in the movie,
one of my best friends, a lawyer, took Chiquita (Gregory's wife,
who died in 1992) out to lunch and suggested that I be
hospitalized. I also think the character in the movie has reached a
real impasse in his creative life because he can't direct anymore.
I guess he sort of hates the theater.
</P>
<P>
   GUSSOW. And this was true of you at the time?
</P>
<P>
   GREGORY. Yes. With the exception of one play, I didn't direct
anything between 1975 and whenever we began ``Vanya on 42d
Street.'' There was a very, very long and painful hiatus where I
just could not get back to directing. Part of the result of the
movie was a desire to stop doing that kind of Grotowski-influenced
para-theatrical work and to try to return to my life as a director.
And another change was discovering a passionate love of acting,
which is what I had originally wanted to do in the theater.
</P>
<P>
   SHAWN. In a weird way, the movie affected us less than some
people might imagine _ in that we went back to doing sort of what
we were doing before. I think it probably had an effect on our
relationship that was beneficial. There was a kind of bond formed
that hadn't been there before. I'd never done anything that was at
all successful before, and I've never done anything subsequently
that was as successful.
</P>
<P>
   GREGORY. People have an affection for this movie. I guess it's
similar to the way I feel about ``Casablanca'' or ``The Wizard of
Oz.'' I've met many people who see the movie over and over and over
and over and over again.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   SHAWN. The things that I've written just out of my own head have
never been as likable as ``My Dinner With Andre.'' Like certain
kinds of dogs are very likable and people want to pet them, and
others are little more in the snarling or slightly scary category.
It's not something you can control.
</P>
<P>
   GUSSOW. The title has become a catch-phrase.
</P>
<P>
   GREGORY. There was even a headline about the baseball strike,
something like ``Endless Talks, No Resolution, My Dinner With
Andre.''
</P>
<P>
   GUSSOW. In East Hampton, why didn't you watch it all the way
through?
</P>
<P>
   GREGORY. I couldn't stand that character. I went for a walk and
found Wally out on the curb because he hadn't been able to watch
himself on the screen. One of the things the movie is also about is
narcissism, and I think the Andre character is certainly an amazing
portrayal in depth of a narcissist. I just looked up there and
thought, ``Oh my God, why would anybody in the world want to sit
here and listen to this awful character going on and on?'' Then I
got confused and thought this man was me.
</P>
<P>
   SHAWN. The film is a sort of mock-documentary, so we'll never
really know to what extent we were like those characters. You know,
I don't mind seeing myself on screen at all. If I'm going to appear
on ``Star Trek,'' I'll move heaven and earth to get to my mother's
house and watch myself on television, because I find it very
amusing. But this was too upsetting. I was enjoying the movie
enormously when he was talking and when I started talking I got out
of there.
</P>
<P>
   GREGORY. If I were to see myself in ``The Last Temptation of
Christ,'' it wouldn't bring up any memories except the memories of
playing John the Baptist. But going to see this, there's the
sadness of Chiquita being gone, Louis being gone.
</P>
<P>
   SHAWN. I suppose that one of the reasons I ran out was watching
that movie has a slight last-act-of-``Our Town'' quality, for us to
be transported into the past the way Emily goes back for her
birthday when she's a child. You can't see the movie without
thinking: that was our life. I felt that whole period leaping back.
Just the way a song brings back certain periods.
</P>
<P>
   GREGORY. When we were rehearsing ``The Designated Mourner'' the
other day, Wally was talking about memory. He was saying how
difficult it is to really look at the past because we're not
looking at the past as the person we were then, but as the person
we are now. Seeing the movie, Chiquita's alive, and the person I
was then is talking about her. It's just kind of bewildering and
sad. The time I saw it before, the painful moment for me was when I
say something about being in the desert and hallucinating about her
and seeing her grow old.
</P>
<P>
   GUSSOW. Wally, when you were picketing the pickets at Terrence
McNally's play ``Corpus Christi,'' all the newspapers referred to
you as an actor. None of them said ``playwright'' or ``playwright
and actor.''
</P>
<P>
   SHAWN. I interpret that through the paranoid and narcissistic
lens of thinking that people on The New York Times have gotten
together and decided that because they hate my plays, they're going
to call me an actor.
</P>
<P>
   GUSSOW. It wasn't just The Times, it was all the newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   SHAWN. Really? Well, that's painful, but I have vowed to rise
above narcissism and complaining.
</P>
<P>
   GREGORY. Just getting Wally off the hook: Europe is different. A
European director described an evening in Berlin in which six or
seven noted directors, playwrights and film people spent the night
arguing about ``Vanya on 42d Street.'' One attacking it, another
defending it. I can't imagine that happening here.
</P>
<P>
   GUSSOW. But here we are talking about a film 18 years after it
was made _ and people have never stopped talking about it. Would
you see ``My Dinner With Andre'' again?
</P>
<P>
   GREGORY. Oh, I could see it again, but I would never do the
Norma Desmond thing, because I love to hear an audience laughing.
That's really one of my greatest pleasures. It's why I go to every
performance of every play I've ever directed.
</P>
<P>
   SHAWN. I'll try to live long enough so that I could see the
whole movie without getting upset.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
