<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TUINEI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUG MIX KILLED TUINEI, POLICE SAY
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ANTHONY RAMIREZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mark Tuinei, the former Dallas Cowboys offensive lineman who was
found dead in his car last Thursday, died of a fatal mixture of
heroin and a popular recreational drug known as ecstasy,
authorities said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   An autopsy by the Collin County medical examiner's office showed
that Tuinei, who was on three Super Bowl teams before he retired
from the Cowboys last year, had used, apparently for the first
time, an undisclosed but small amount of heroin after extended use
for at least two weeks of the drug ecstasy, which is related to
amphetamines.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you had was a 39-year-old male, 6-foot-5, in excess of
300 pounds, a healthy individual, took one shot of heroin and
basically dropped dead as a result,'' Bruce Glasscock, police chief
of Plano, Tex., said at a news conference Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Glasscock said he believed Tuinei had never used heroin before.
</P>
<P>
   Tuinei, a native of Honolulu, came to the Cowboys as an
undrafted defensive lineman out of the University of Hawaii in 1983
and played with Dallas through 1997. A powerful player with a
youthful history of brawling and substance abuse, Tuinei had said
his problems were behind him.
</P>
<P>
   His death was the latest of several drug-related setbacks for
the Cowboys in recent years. Leon Lett, one of the team's best
defensive linemen, faces suspension after failing a drug test for
the third time last month. In 1996, the All-Pro receiver Michael
Irvin pleaded no contest to a felony charge of cocaine possession
and was suspended for five games.
</P>
<P>
   Tuinei had difficulty breathing Wednesday night and was driven
back to his home by his friend, Nicky Sualua, 24, a reserve
fullback with the Cowboys. Sualua has told investigators that he
and Tuinei had driven to a North Dallas apartment in search of
heroin.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   According to a police affidavit that led to a search of Tunei's
home in Plano, near Dallas, after his death, Sualua, who said he
had not taken any drugs, said Tuinei had swallowed at least one
ecstasy tablet. Experts say amphetamines and heroin can cause a
loss of consciousness and sometimes death. A police search of
Tuinei's home led to the seizure of a pipe, a marijuana cigarette
and one ecstasy pill.
</P>
<P>
   After disappearing into the bedroom of the North Dallas
apartment, Tuinei, who said he wanted to inject heroin, emerged
drowsy, out of breath and soon passed out, according to the
affidavit. Sualua administered cardiopulmonary resuscitation , he
told investigators, and got Tuinei breathing more normally. He then
dragged the unconscious former lineman, who weighs more than 300
pounds, to Tuinei's customized 1933 Ford roadster.
</P>
<P>
   Sualua then drove back to Tuinei's home, where Sualua covered
him with two blankets. When Tuinei started snoring, Sualua also
fell asleep. In the morning, Sualua could not revive him.
</P>
<P>
   Sualua could not be reached for comment, and the Plano police
said there were no plans to arrest Sualua.
</P>
<P>
   Tuinei was a respected if taciturn player whose signature phrase
was ``I will crush you like a grape.'' Once he heard his friend
Jesse Sapolu, a center for the 49ers, say before the 1992 NFC title
game that the road to the Super Bowl ran through Candlestick Park.
After the Cowboys won, he told Sapolu, ``Jesse, thanks for the
directions.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
