<SLUG> BC-BKN-HEAT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAT GETS A HOLIDAY (RILEY MUST BE SOFT WITH WINNING)
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Pat Riley, whose affinity for three-hour practices is
legendary, tried something different Tuesday. He gave the Heat the
entire day off.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Majerle needed the time off. He injured his right shoulder
as he tried to get around a screen set by Patrick Ewing during
Monday's victory over the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Majerle told P.J. Brown he thought the shoulder was separated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think he was going to come back in the game,'' Brown
said.
</P>
<P>
   After a trip to the locker room, Majerle returned with 7 minutes
48 seconds left _ just in time to sink a pair of huge 3-pointers to
stymie the Knicks' comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those two shots were warrior-type shots,'' Brown said. ``They
were two of the biggest shots of the year. Kind of like nails in a
coffin.''
</P>
<P>
   Majerle, who did some shot-inhibiting work on Allan Houston and
Latrell Sprewell, didn't want to consider the idea of not playing
on Wednesday in Game 3 at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty painful,'' he said. ``But if it doesn't get any
worse, I'm sure I'll be able to play. The adrenaline will kick in
the closer we get to the game.''
</P>
<P>
   A larger concern, he noted, is the probability of getting hit on
the shoulder again. Which is likely to happen, given the nature of
the series.
</P>
<P>
   With the series tied at 1-1, Brown, the ex-Net, said he was
hopeful the Knicks would feel the hot glare of an expectant home
crowd on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the pressure kind of shifts to them,'' he said. ``I
think their fans expect them to close out the series on their home
floor. We're looking forward to playing them. We're a better road
team than a home team. That's definitely in our favor, but that
doesn't mean we're guaranteed anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown has found a way to cope with the tension of this series:
Don't treat it like the end of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my wife that before the first game, I was maybe too
emotional, too hyped,'' he said. ``I kind of changed up my routine
a little bit and started doing some crazy things I usually don't
do. I feel a lot better now.''
</P>
<P>
   To a man, the Heat players know that defense enabled them to
have the Eastern Conference's best regular-season record, just as
it enabled them to stem the bleeding after the Knicks won Game 1.
Still, the Heat is not suddenly one big happy juggernaut. A major
question remains about the viability of Jamal Mashburn as the
team's No. 3 scoring alternative after Tim Hardaway and Alonzo
Mourning.
</P>
<P>
   Though he finished with 11 points on Monday, and contributed
mightily to the Heat's fast start, Mashburn did not play in the
fourth quarter. Riley went with the veterans Terry Porter, 36;
Majerle, 33, and Keith Askins, 31.
</P>
<P>
   Riley acknowledged some concern about the 26-year-old Mashburn's
three turnovers, all while dribbling to maneuver a defensive man
out of position. ``He lost his handle on the ball too much, was too
careless,'' said Riley, who is notoriously severe on players who
show any hint of weakness during the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the Heat's confidence heading into Wednesday's game has
skyrocketed since Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had a huge amount of success in New York, but we
know we're capable of playing well and winning there,'' Mourning
said. ``It's just a matter of us taking the attitude there that
worked for us at home and making some good things happen for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
