<HEADER>
A3229 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARSONS-DANCE-ART-2TA     05-11 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARSONS-DANCE-ART-2TAKES-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANCING ON TOP OF THE WORLD, WITH MALAISE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mo.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 16)  
 (af)  
 Valerie Gladstone's most recent article for Arts and Leisure was on
the dancer-choreographer Bebe Miller.  
 By VALERIE GLADSTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ David Parsons sounded distressed. ``Lately, every
time I start a new project, I get unnerved,'' he said over lunch in
Manhattan recently. Although this 39-year-old dancer-choreographer
looks like a hunky, happy-go-lucky movie star, during this
conversation he came across as an angst-ridden artist. ``In the
back of my mind, there's always the word `accessible' that's
constantly thrown at me as an insult. What does it mean? That I
attract the masses? That's bad? My work's not about getting people
to love me. It's about following what I want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since he established his modern-dance company 12 years ago,
some critics have called his work superficial, accusing him of
catering to the lowest common denominator. But why do their
opinions affect him so deeply now? After all, he has had plenty of
time to build defenses. Moreover, his company consistently attracts
new fans, makes money and pleases many more critics than it
disappoints. Obviously something else was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Events of the last two years have made him especially
vulnerable, Parsons said. His confidence became seriously eroded.
``I hit bottom,'' he said. ``I became mean. I gave my dancers a
hard time. I had a terrible breakup with a woman. I didn't have a
permanent place to stay in the city. I tore the cartilage in my
knee and had to have an operation.'' He winced. ``It's coming back
very slowly.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet in spite of his malaise, Parsons acknowledges that he still
has ample reasons to feel positive. The Parsons Dance Company
attracts large audiences, in locations as diverse as Brazil, Italy,
Australia and St. Louis. And its two-week engagement at the Joyce
Theater, starting Tuesday, is nearly sold out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost all the music will be live,'' he said proudly; troupes
appearing at the Joyce usually can't afford musicians. On the first
week's program is his newest work, ``Fill the Woods With Light,''
which had its world premiere at the American Dance Festival in
Durham, N.C., last summer.
</P>
<P>
   It is set to a commissioned score by the jazz saxophonist Phil
Woods, who will play it at the Joyce with his Little Big Band. To a
mix of funky rock-and-roll, blues and bossa nova, Parsons created,
according to Woods, ``a warm dance, sort of down and dirty.''
</P>
<P>
   The second week's program features six works by Robert Battle, a
veteran Parsons dancer. A choreographer new to the New York stage,
Battle offers ``Rush Hour,'' a world premiere, and four New York
premieres, all of them to commissioned scores by John Mackey, 28, a
contemporary composer, who will perform with his ensemble of 10
Juilliard musicians. ``Takademe,'' Battle's sixth New York
premiere, is to the recorded songs of the Indian singer Sheila
Chandra.
</P>
<P>
   Parsons' widest exposure yet will come on New Year's Eve. The
Times Square Business Improvement District chose him to stage a
continuous outdoor show on 42d Street from 7 a.m., Dec. 31 until 7
a.m., Jan. 1. ``Basically, it's a TV program going by satellite to
a billion people,'' Parsons said.
</P>
<P>
   As chief of a creative team that includes Michael Curry,
designer of the oversize puppets in the Broadway musical ``The Lion
King,'' Parsons has been asked to create a series of theatrical
events, full of pageantry and with universal appeal. Although the
show is still in the planning stage, he already knows he'll use 150
performers, 10 of them his company members, and that well-known
composers around the world will do the music.
</P>
<P>
   Parsons got the job for several reasons. ``David has a devoted
and very extensive following,'' said Peter Kohlmann, the executive
producer of Times Square 2000. ``We also knew he had standing in
the dance world. Those qualifications, plus his visual sense and
his reputation for being easy to work with, made us pick him.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Kohlmann, presenters and booking agents find Parsons' wide
popularity pure gold. ``Last year, David filled our 2,300-seat
opera house five nights running,'' said Maria Rita Stumpf,
president of Antares Promotions in Rio de Janeiro. ``It's the
joyfulness, the exuberant physicality of his work and his
dancers.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, he did as well in Italy. According to Antonio
Gnecchi, a producer who began representing Parsons 10 years ago,
his troupe sold out in 18 cities. ``David communicates directly,
without pretension,'' Gnecchi said. Sally Bliss, executive director
of Dance St. Louis, was equally enthusiastic. ``Both little kids
and the elderly love his work,'' she said. ``You can't imagine how
many friends his company makes here.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   How does Parsons accomplish this? With a catholic repertory that
includes the show-stopping ``Caught'' (1982), in which a dancer
appears to fly; ``Anthem'' (1998), inspired by the dissolution of
Eastern-bloc dictatorships, and ``Ring Around the Rosie'' (1993),
which refers to AIDS. The first two, along with ``Union'' (1993),
to ``Nefertiti'' by the jazz composer Wayne Shorter, will be
presented this season.
</P>
<P>
   But accomplishments aren't enough, and beneath them are deep
reasons for Parsons' blue mood. ``Sometimes you get so confused,''
he said earnestly. ``You don't know how to separate your personal
life from your professional life. I became bogged down, erratic.
There's always a deadline; every time we do a show, there's a
critic. I feared my creative juices were drying up. I was afraid of
losing the joy in creation.''
</P>
<P>
   Parsons fell in love with dance as a 12-year-old in Kansas City,
Mo., and has been immersed in it since, so it's not surprising that
he eventually reached an impasse. Frequently dancer-choreographers
become devastatingly discouraged in their late '30s and early '40s,
when they must look to a future when they can no longer perform.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Taylor, with whose company Parsons starred for nine years,
weathered a similar crisis, as did Twyla Tharp. But it wasn't just
the inevitable physical changes that got to Parsons. The
responsibility for his dancers _ he provides at least 45 weeks of
work and full health and unemployment insurance _ and the constant
touring became too much. He had little energy for choreographing.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of changes have slowly begun to turn the tide; for one,
Parsons travels less with the troupe. ``The pressures built up in
David, and he took it out on us,'' said Jaime Martinez, who
recently became assistant artistic director of the company. ``Today
he gives older members, Liz Koeppen and me, a lot more
responsibility, and it's been great for all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Second, Parsons now plans to produce work by other
choreographers regularly, shifting the weight of creating all the
company's new dances. Battle is the first choreographer to benefit
from Parsons' decision. ``David sees this as the future of dance,''
said Battle. ``No more one-choreographer companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Parsons says when he auditions now, he looks for dancers who
want to choreograph as well. Before being hired, his three new
company members, Kate Skarpetowska, George Smallwood and Sumayah
McRae, submitted videotape of pieces they had created. The idea
wasn't new to Parsons; putting it into practice was. For nine
years, his troupe spent time every summer at the New Arts Summer
Festival in Fort Myers, Fla., teaching choreography and technique.
Now he is trying to establish a school in New York, a permanent
place to nurture dancers and choreographers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My school will be open to everybody,'' he said, dreaming out
loud. ``I'll have a summer session where semiprofessionals from
around the world can come and taste the city and get a feel for
other choreographers and our technique and repertory.''
</P>
<P>
   His mood picked up. ``I want to do more video. I've already used
video to teach disadvantaged kids to dance. I'll do my own
productions and make films for television to get people who don't
go to theater interested in dance.''
</P>
<P>
   Parsons likes collaborations. This season, Missoni and Donna
Karan created many of the company's costumes, and he talked
excitedly about the possibility of working with Mikhail Baryshnikov
on a piece using Vari-Lite, a lighting system run by computers.
Made famous in the shows of the rock group Genesis, Vari-Lite can
rotate 360 degrees, fading from one color and pattern to another.
</P>
<P>
   He then switched to explaining that he might try as backdrops
the underwater photographs of Howard Schatz, or enormous close-ups
of the dancers: ``In film, close-ups are usually what get you
emotionally involved,'' he said. ``I'll have to figure out how we
can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rising to leave, he paused to say: ``You know, I'm actually
feeling better. Something's coming back that is very beautiful.''
And he was smiling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-99 2219EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
