<DOCNO> NYT19990511.0430 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3233 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WOZZECK-OPERA-ART-$AD     05-11 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOZZECK-OPERA-ART-$ADV16-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO PATHS, INTELLECTUAL AND EARTHY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 16)  
 (af)  
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The two operas are closely linked: ``Wozzeck,'' a devastating
success; ``Moses und Aron,'' a failure of epic stature. The pupil,
Alban Berg, wrote the first; the teacher, Arnold Schoenberg, the
second. Perhaps no opera since Mozart feels as complete as
``Wozzeck.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Moses und Aron'' lies unfinished, although its first two acts
were written some 20 years before the composer's death in 1951. The
words for a third act awaited only the music for them.
</P>
<P>
   Both works played at the Metropolitan Opera this season, showing
us two minds going in opposite directions. Schoenberg is the man of
ideas; he looks for operatic characters able to portray them. His
opera begins at the altitudes of thought and descends into the
everyday particulars of life.
</P>
<P>
   Berg starts at the bottom: with humanity, dirt-real if
grotesquely enhanced. Whatever ideas of social injustice or
spiritual suffering his opera gives off arrive as afterthoughts.
Confronted by the soldier Wozzeck and his tormentors, one smells
the sweat of their bodies. The senses come first; speculation is
deferred. ``Wozzeck'' begins with everyday particulars of life and
works its way upward.
</P>
<P>
   Could Schoenberg have acted in any other way? He was, after all,
the self-appointed Moses of 20th-century music, a man of
extraordinary gifts who had an idea about rescuing Western music
from its corruption and enervation. It may be overly cute to say
it, but if Moses came down from the mountaintop with 10
commandments, Schoenberg arrived with 12.
</P>
<P>
   Arranging a systematic usage for the 12 notes of the chromatic
scale would provide an esthetic umbrella under which all the
strands of played-out tonality could gather for safety and new
nourishment. A new freedom, a new world order for music, would
result from overarching speculation.
</P>
<P>
   Do it Schoenberg's way, or at least think in Schoenberg's way,
and you will prosper. Given the time in which he lived, his
Jewishness and his persecution by the Nazis, Schoenberg's view of
himself is an unsettling paradox.
</P>
<P>
   Berg learned the 12-tone method at his teacher's knee but
strayed from its commandments. Schoenberg was tactful but did not
approve. Yet if opera is words, action and, not least, music
together onstage, ``Wozzeck'' synthesizes all three. Swift scenes,
with thought and word pared to the bone, send it forward.
</P>
<P>
   Miraculously, music speaks to theater and theater to music. The
two are indissoluble. Stunning interludes between scenes form a
kind of subliminal plot. The final instrumental segment is perhaps
Berg's most beautiful creation. Berg gives us not the concepts of
cruelty, arrogance, lust, brutality and madness, but instead, the
Captain, the Doctor, Marie, the Drum Major and Wozzeck. Theater is
not philosophy, although philosophy can be a byproduct.
</P>
<P>
   Schoenberg's spirit was big enough to accommodate self-doubt,
and this is the subject of ``Moses und Aron.'' For Moses, ideas are
incorruptible, abstract, untouchable. We cannot describe God,
because his essence is unimaginable. (Philosophers might point out
that ``unimaginable'' is a description in itself.)
</P>
<P>
   Aron is the communicator, and the wavering Israelite population
certainly needs reaching. It wants a god in its image but superior:
a doer of magic and miracles. Aron is like a politician's advance
man, putting up posters in the form of graven images, preparing the
way for the Supreme Being's ultimate arrival.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers argue back and forth without clear conclusion,
although in the written but uncomposed third act, Aron is argued
down by his peers, collapses and dies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moses und Aron'' illustrates with sets and costumes a
conversation going on within the composer's head. The people
onstage, not least the elaborate and powerful chorus, are a public
outlet for private thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Schoenberg is Moses and, reluctantly, partly Aron as well. It is
assuredly a long way from the essence of God to 12-tone
composition, but there is an ever so faint metaphor at work.
</P>
<P>
   Extenuating circumstances try to explain why Schoenberg never
finished his opera _ the dislocations of emigration to the United
States, the difficulties of earning a living _ but it is just as
easy to believe that the third act never completed represents a
loss of will or, perhaps, conviction. Maybe a truncated ``Moses und
Aron'' is really the complete one: a tortuous inner argument
destined never to be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Set in the middle of all this ontological head-scratching is a
wondrous orgy. Nude women are specified (although the Met decided
on underwear); lascivious dancing and carnal excess of every type
are implied. What better way to enjoy evil than to summon it in
great detail and then renounce it.
</P>
<P>
   (Think of Jimmy Swaggart's motel escapades.) Maybe the dance
before the golden calf simply confesses that even the religious
have naughty dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Berg's other opera, ``Lulu,'' is fascinating, but its studied
geometry of plot reduces characters to chess pieces. Two other
operas of our time compete with ``Wozzeck'' as pure theater.
``Pelleas et Melisande,'' from 1902, makes Debussy's orchestra a
wordless narrator and commentator.
</P>
<P>
   Pit speaks to audience, telling us secrets that are withheld
from the lost and clueless souls onstage. In its unusual way,
``Pelleas'' approaches theater we can hear. The singers are like an
obbligato, an almost secondary decoration to the instrumental
writing.
</P>
<P>
   Please don't laugh if my other example is ``Cavalleria
Rusticana'': not quite 20th-century (1890 to be exact) but a
rapid-firing explosion of music drama. The music of ``Cavalleria''
comes as close to hot tempers, lust, violence and the cold sweat of
fear as pure sound can. Mascagni never again came close to that
first success. Such things do happen on the opera stage but not
often.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
