<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
 ( rk ) 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIVIDUALS WILL RECEIVE PRIORITY IN NASDAQ LAWSUIT
</P>
<P>
   Individual investors will be given an edge over institutional
investors in the distribution of about $1 billion that Nasdaq
dealers paid to settle a 1994 antitrust class-action case accusing
them of fixing prices on Nasdaq shares.
</P>
<P>
   Under a plan that lawyers will send to investors next month, all
investors will share in the settlement fund based on how many
Nasdaq trades they made during the seven years the agreement
covers.
</P>
<P>
   CISCO RESULTS SURPASS ESTIMATES
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems beat analysts' earnings estimates by a penny. It
reported results after the close of trading, but earlier shares of
Cisco closed at $111.875, up $2.625. The shares jumped as high as
$115.25 in after-hours trading. Analysts said Cisco benefited from
the growth of the Internet, because more than 80 percent of the
routers connected to the Internet are Cisco machines.
</P>
<P>
   SONY PLANS TO SELL MUSIC ON INTERNET
</P>
<P>
   Sony Music Entertainment plans to begin selling songs online
using Microsoft technology that requires users to pay for the music
before playing it. The move accelerates the rush of record
companies to the Internet even before the industry settles on a
standard.
</P>
<P>
   IBM SETS DATA STORAGE RECORD
</P>
<P>
   IBM plans to announce Wednesday that company researchers have
set a world record in magnetic disk storage density, writing and
reading data bits so small that 20 billion of them would fit within
a square inch.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS RISE DESPITE BOND SELL-OFF
</P>
<P>
   Stocks were buffeted by a further sell-off in the bond market
but recovered and moved higher. The Dow Jones industrial average
rose 18.90 points, to 11,026.15. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index gained 15.31 points, to 1,355.61, and the Nasdaq composite
index rose 40.29 points, to 2,566.68.
</P>
<P>
   U S WEST ELECTS TRUJILLO AS CHAIRMAN
</P>
<P>
   U S West, the regional Bell telephone companies, elected Solomon
D. Trujillo, its chief executive, as chairman. He succeeds Richard
D. McCormick, who was elected chairman emeritus. U S West has been
the leader among the Bells in deploying high-speed Internet service
using an advanced technology, digital subscriber line.
</P>
<P>
   ALLIANCES FOR RIVALS IN STOCK TRADING
</P>
<P>
   The landscape of the stock trading business continued to shift
with both Instinet, the dominant private trading system, and its
rival, Island ECN, announcing potentially important alliances with
other players.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL PRESSES DEBT-SWAP PLAN
</P>
<P>
   Brazil is going ahead with a widely criticized plan to swap debt
issued abroad by dozens of large private companies for safer
securities partly backed by the government.
</P>
<P>
   BRE-X EXECUTIVE IS CHARGED
</P>
<P>
   The vice chairman of Bre-X Minerals, John Felderhof, was charged
by the Ontario Securities Commission with illegal insider trading
and other securities law violations in connection with the
company's fraudulent reports of a huge gold discovery in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   POSSIBLE SALE SEEN FOR NEWSPAPER
</P>
<P>
   The family that owns Chronicle Publishing, which includes The
San Francisco Chronicle, has called in the investment bank
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette to advise it on possible financial
strategies, including a possible sale.
</P>
<P>
   Hersant Group, the heavily indebted French company, is seeking
bids for up to 49 percent of its flagship newspaper, Le Figaro.
</P>
<P>
   WAL-MART PROFIT BEATS FORECASTS
</P>
<P>
   First-quarter profits at Wal-Mart Stores rose 34 percent,
beating estimates.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTIVITY INCREASED 4 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   The productivity of the nation's workers rose at a annualized
rate of 4 percent in the first quarter of 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
