<SLUG> BC-BUSH-POLITICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE'S BUSH? TEXAS LEGISLATORS SAY GOVERNOR'S LEADERSHIP `ABSENT' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
and JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush's promise to stay in Texas
until the Legislature ends later this month has led some political
activists in Iowa and New Hampshire to grumble that Bush is too
busy being governor to run for president.
</P>
<P>
   And now many Texas lawmakers are grumbling aloud that Bush has
been too busy running for president to take care of his legislative
business at home.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, they say, the governor's major proposals for $2.6
billion in tax cuts and teacher pay raises are in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 Democratic legislators held a news conference Tuesday
to complain, among other things, about Bush's leadership being
``absent'' this session.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where's Waldo?'' one legislator blurted out, referring to a
series of children's books in which the reader must search for
Waldo in a sea of faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I'd say he's been missing in action, but it's
been pretty close to that,'' said Rep. Kevin Bailey, D-Houston.
``He's a lot less involved than in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   A Houston Chronicle review of Bush's office calendars shows the
governor has had about half the personal involvement in this
legislative session that he had during the 1997 Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   The major issues on which he campaigned _ tax cuts, a
requirement for girls to notify their parents before they can get
an abortion and vouchers that would allow parents to use public
money to send their children to private school, all are in trouble.
If the bills fail, it will give Bush's presidential campaign
opponents ammunition to attack him as an ineffective leader.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush was adamant Tuesday that in the end he will get most of
what he asked for from the Legislature, including a ``significant''
tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   Bush noted that measures to lower the maximum alcohol level for
drunken driving and to restrict Y2K lawsuits were on their way to
his desk or about to pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a part of the Bush agenda that seems to be moving along
quite nicely,'' Bush said. ``Most of the issues I campaigned on
came out of the Senate, and there will be a moment of
reconciliation (with the House.)''
</P>
<P>
   But an education finance bill that recently came out of the
Senate only delivered half of Bush's promised $2 billion property
tax cut, with the rest set for teacher pay.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is now hung up in the House Education Committee because
Democrats do not believe there is enough money to pay for tax cuts
and teacher pay increases.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Chairman Paul Sadler, D-Henderson, said he is delaying
the bill until he gets a new state revenue estimate from
Comptroller Carole Rylander, not to any lack of effort by Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been fine with me,'' Sadler said. ``He's been very
responsive. I've never been put off. I've never been told he's
meeting with somebody else he can't meet with me.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bush's program has been struggling in the Texas session,
his brother, Gov. Jeb Bush, ended his first legislative session in
Florida two weeks ago by getting virtually everything he asked for,
including $1 billion in tax cuts and a private school voucher
program. The Texas voucher bill pushed by this state's Bush is all
but dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe Republicans need a Bush primary to make sure they're
running the right sibling (for president),'' Wall Street Journal
columnist Paul Gigot wrote last week.
</P>
<P>
   University of Texas political scientist Bruce Buchanan said
Republican primary voters around the country are more likely to
judge Bush by his legislative successes than on a failure to
deliver on all that he promised.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Bush) always chooses his issues in such a way that he can
declare victory no matter what happens,'' Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   However, it is clear that Bush's presidential ambitions have
distracted from his attention to legislative detail.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the governor's own apointments calendars, Bush has
been less involved overall with this Legislature than the one held
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush has held about 30 hours of scheduled meetings with
legislators, his ``private'' schedule, which has set aside the time
he uses for presidential politics, has consumed about 64 hours of
Bush's time.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has attended 63 scheduled meetings with legislators in the
1999 session, compared to 134 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The schedules surveyed by the Chronicle began Dec. 1, before the
Legislature opened, through April 26 for both the 1997 and 1999
legislative sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Linda Edwards said the governor has numerous
unscheduled meetings with lawmakers, particularly late in the day.
She said she believes he has kept the same pace of unscheduled
meetings that he had in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's one-on-one interviews with the Texas news media
has remained almost steady, but Bush's 32 national news media
interviews _ including five with The New York Times _ is almost
triple the number he granted in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Calls on Bush by foreign dignitaries and ambassadors are up from
eight in 1997 to 29 this year. That includes a telephone call Bush
received last month from President Eduard Shevardnadze of the
former Soviet republic of Georgia. Shevardnadze was the Soviet
foreign minister when Bush's father was in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Shevardnadze called while in Houston to meet with former
Secretary of State James A. Baker III and Houston oil companies
interested in Caspian Sea exploration. Shevardnadze also met with
President Clinton in Washington during that trip.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said Tuesday he is using persuasion to lead the
Legislature. That includes his personal involvement, staff
involvment and announcing his stands on issues important to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I meet with people all the time. My staff members meet with
people all the time. People know exactly what my position is,''
Bush told reporters. ``When I say things and you put it in the
press, it actually reflects my view that I believe we can have a
substantial tax cut and teacher pay.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he meets regularly with Lt. Gov. Rick Perry and House
Speaker Pete Laney.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's staff also joined a series of intense negotiations Sunday
in an effort to pry a compromise bill out of the Legislature to
require parental notification before a minor can receive an
abortion. Bush has promised such a bill since he first ran for
governor in 1994, and anti-abortion activists are holding his feet
to the fire in this session to come through.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said there is still plenty of time to get what he wants
from this Legislature. And he said he has no concern about whether
the results of this session affect his presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's important for the work product of this session is that
it is important for Texas,'' Bush said. ``We'll worry about the
exploratory business later on. Right now, it's what's best for
Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
