<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-STRIP-SEARCH-1000&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$5 MILLION JURY AWARD IN STRIP-SEARCH CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal jury has ordered New York City to pay $5
million to a woman who was strip-searched by jail guards, a verdict
that could have broad financial ramifications for the city as it
faces a class-action lawsuit filed on behalf of 63,000 people who
say they were illegally strip-searched.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first decision against the city for its policy of
strip-searching all people arrested and arraigned on minor charges
in Manhattan and Queens over a period of about 10 months in 1996
and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The city Department of Correction said at the time that it
adopted the policy ``for security purposes,'' even though a federal
appeals court had ruled in 1986 that the Fourth Amendment precluded
strip-searches of people charged with misdemeanors or other minor
offenses unless there was a reasonable suspicion that weapons or
contraband was being concealed.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict, which the city will appeal, was returned on
Thursday in U.S. District Court in Manhattan. It granted a smaller
compensatory award of $19,600 to cover the woman's pain and
suffering as well as her medical expenses, in addition to its award
of $5 million in punitive damages, city officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict, along with a recent settlement in which the city
agreed to pay $25,000 each to four Fordham University students who
were strip-searched by the police, suggests that the city may be
facing a staggering bill as it attempts to resolve yet another
case: about 63,000 people who say they were strip-searched while
the policy was in force.
</P>
<P>
   While the city has not conceded any liability, it acknowledged
in court papers that the searches were conducted by jail guards who
had not been told of legal requirements of reasonable suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   A senior city official said Tuesday night that the Giuliani
administration was negotiating with lawyers for the class-action
suit in hopes of resolving the matter before trial.
</P>
<P>
   The class action, said Michael Hess, the corporation counsel for
the city, ``is a very serious case, and we're attempting to address
the issues in a way that is fair to the class as well as to the
city.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The money can't come from the sky,'' he added. ``It would come
from the taxpayers. There are multiple concerns that our office has
to address.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials said Tuesday night that although they were
concerned about what might lie ahead in the case, they believed
that most of the people subjected to the searches had been
previously charged with crimes like drug offenses or prostitution.
They said that, therefore, many of the searches might have been
reasonable.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Emery and Matthew Brinckerhoff, the lawyers handling the
class-action lawsuit, said that even if the punitive damages award
is overturned, the compensatory verdict would be a useful gauge of
what a jury might award in their case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that the city is going to be constructive in their
approach to settling this case,'' Emery said, citing what he called
``the extreme nature of the jury's reaction, which demonstrates the
city's exposure for its cavalier attitude'' in adopting the
strip-search policy.
</P>
<P>
   The city had argued that the policy was necessary because
crowded conditions in the cells where people are held while
awaiting arraignment heightened security concerns.
</P>
<P>
   In an affidavit filed last year, the chief of the Department of
Correction, Edward Reilly, said, ``I believe these searches were
necessary to detect and remove dangerous contraband from the
pre-arraignment inmates and area, and to insure, as far as
practicable, a reasonable level of safety'' to inmates and others.
</P>
<P>
   At last week's trial of the suit brought on behalf of Debra
Ciraolo, Judge Robert Patterson said the 1986 appeals court ruling
left the city without a defense and told the the jury to ignore the
question of whether the city was liable and to decide only the size
of the damage award.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the judge recognized that there was a clear
constitutional standard that applied to strip-searches of people
charged with misdemeanors,'' said Stephen Weiner, who represented
Ms. Ciraolo.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ciraolo, a Greenwich Village resident who works as an
interpreter for the deaf in the city's schools, courts and
hospitals, had maintained in her suit that she was falsely arrested
in January 1997 after a domestic dispute and taken to a holding
cell near the Criminal Court at 100 Centre Street.
</P>
<P>
   Two female guards ordered her to disrobe completely, Ms. Ciraolo
testified, and then ``they told me to walk towards the wall and to
turn around.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that the guards, who were wearing rubber gloves, then
told her to bend over.
</P>
<P>
   She squatted instead, she said. ``They told me to cough. And I
was still bending, squatting over, and I said, `What?' And they
said, `Cough.' And so I coughed.''
</P>
<P>
   She was then allowed to get dressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt so shamed,'' said Ms. Ciraolo, 43. ``I felt as if I was
taken to the lowest human emotion that anyone could possibly
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The jury found that the city had ``acted in wanton disregard of
or wanton indifference'' to Ms. Ciraolo's rights, the transcript
shows.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly, in an affidavit filed in the class action suit, said the
strip-search policy did not include searches of body cavities but
rather visual inspections in which there was no contact between
prisoners and guards.
</P>
<P>
   The policy included a ``visual inspection of the inmate's
armpits, mouth, ears, nose, and navel while the inmate is
undressed,'' Reilly said, but not ``visual inspection of an
inmate's anal or vaginal cavity.'' He also said the policy did not
require inmates to lift their breasts or genitals or to bend over.
However, Reilly said, inmates may have been ordered ``to perform a
deep knee bend in order to expel any contraband that may be
secreted in the anal or vaginal cavity.''
</P>
<P>
   In court papers, the city called such searches ``strip-frisks.''
</P>
<P>
   But Brinckerhoff, one of the lawyers in the class-action case,
disputed Reilly's account, saying that the jail guards routinely
ordered inmates to bend over, and to lift their breasts or genitals
for visual inspection.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   When the class action lawsuit was originally filed in May 1997,
it attacked the policy of strip-searching all suspects in
Manhattan, a total estimated at 25,000 people. But the number of
plaintiffs kept rising as new information about strip-searches in
Manhattan and in Queens was revealed by the city.
</P>
<P>
   In the lawsuit involving the Fordham students, the city agreed
to pay $25,000 to each of them, to settle claims that they were
strip-searched illegally by police after they were arrested last
year for doubling up as they passed through a subway turnstile,
said their lawyer, Martha Rayner.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the four women was taken to a bathroom at the 46th
Precinct station house in the Bronx and told to disrobe completely,
the lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   Each was then told to squat and cough, and a female officer
examined one under her breasts, the suit said. No contraband was
found, and the the women had had no prior contact with police, the
suit said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rayner said that from a practical point of view, the
settlements with her clients and last week's jury verdict suggested
that the city has a real incentive to curtail illegal searches and
retrain police and correction officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never mind the morality or the civil rights aspects of it,''
she said. ``They're liable for an awful lot of money, and it seems
to me that they would want to right this wrong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
