<SLUG> BC-NJ-CORZINE-POLITICS-ART-1,100(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICH, UNKNOWN AND A TOP CONTENDER FOR SENATE
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Ill.)  (ART ADV: Photo of Corzine is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Goldman Sachs Group went public last week, its
former chairman, Jon S. Corzine, became a very rich man. He also
effectively became unemployed. Having lost a power struggle earlier
this year, Corzine ended his formal relationship with the Wall
Street firm once the public offering was completed.
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't take him long to rebound. By week's end, Corzine
was in Atlantic City for a conference of New Jersey's Democratic
Party, using his gentle Midwestern charms to audition for a job
even his closest associates never realized he wanted: U.S. senator.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been interested in public service,'' Corzine (the
last syllable of his name rhymes with ``pine'') said in his hoarse,
whispery voice between handshakes at the conference, where few
people knew what he looked like but almost everyone had heard
estimates of his net worth. (More than $300 million).
</P>
<P>
   To the surprise of many New Jersey Democrats, Corzine, has
emerged as a leading contender in a crowded Democratic field to
replace Sen. Frank Lautenberg, the three-term Democrat who plans to
retire next year. Virtually unknown in state political circles,
Corzine, a 52-year-old native of Illinois who now lives in Summit,
N.J., has leaped ahead of more seasoned politicians largely on the
strength of his fortune, which he has vowed to use lavishly on a
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But he has also been quietly promoted by a coterie of
influential Democrats, many of them close to Sen. Robert G.
Torricelli, New Jersey's other Democratic senator, who do not want
the nomination to go to the best organized of the Democratic
candidates, former Gov. Jim Florio. Those Democrats say Florio,
while capable of winning a primary, will certainly lose in a
general election, particularly if his opponent is Christie Whitman,
the Republican who ousted him as governor in '93.
</P>
<P>
   Though Torricelli says it is premature for him to back anyone,
he came close to endorsing Corzine in an interview Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the Democratic Party in New Jersey and the Democratic
caucus in the Senate to have a candidate from the most prestigious
banking house in the world has some merit,'' he said. ``This is a
guy who can speak on economic and tax issues with some authority.
And that is going to be appealing to many Democrats in New
Jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   Corzine's supporters are now trying to winnow the field of other
candidates and unify leaders from the state's populous northern
counties behind the investment banker. They are hoping to set up a
one-on-one primary against Florio, who has the support of seven
southern county chairmen. A crowded Democratic field, Corzine's
advisers say, would benefit Florio.
</P>
<P>
   The other candidates, including Rep. Frank Pallone; Michael
Murphy, a former Prosecutor, and Thomas Byrne, a former state party
chairman, say they have no plans to drop out. But many party
leaders think the pressure on them to step aside will be intense if
Corzine formally jumps in.
</P>
<P>
   ``This issue of his money is going to be pretty daunting to the
other candidates,'' said Thomas P. Giblin, the state Democratic
chairman, who has met with Corzine several times but remains
neutral in the race.
</P>
<P>
   But while Corzine's immense wealth may win him fans among some
political leaders, some Democrats worry that it could also offend
Democratic primary voters who might view it as evidence that he is
out of touch with them.
</P>
<P>
   Though he does not plan to make an official announcement for
several days, Corzine has told friends he plans to run, and in an
interview last Friday, he said he was leaning strongly in that
direction. Two things could hold him back, friends say: opposition
from his family and a desire to start a business. Asked about his
wife's feelings, Corzine replied, ``She's not opposed.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the meantime, he has taken firm steps toward starting a
campaign. He has hired Doug Schoen, who does polling for President
Clinton, to measure public support for Florio and Whitman. He has
talked to Robert Shrum, the veteran Democratic media consultant,
about working on the campaign. And he has recruited a former state
director for Lautenberg, Christy Davis, to help him meet New Jersey
Democratic officials.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all his immense wealth and growing support, Corzine is
not a shoo-in, even among the anti-Florio forces. Though he has
given nearly $1 million to the Democratic Party over the past
decade, almost none of that money went to New Jersey candidates,
leaving him with no base of support in the state.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike Lautenberg, another rich
businessman-turned-politician, Corzine has not been active in local
politics, has not run for office and even failed to vote on
numerous occasions. Many of his critics think Corzine is running
solely because Torricelli nudged him into it.
</P>
<P>
   More important to many Democrats, Corzine must answer some
fundamental questions about what he stands for and whether an
untested candidate like him can endure the strain of a long
campaign. Last weekend, many Democrats were openly wondering
whether the party of urban poor and organized labor should endorse
a wealthy banker who lives in the suburbs and who ran a Wall Street
firm known for helping big companies gobble up smaller ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a concern about sending the wrong message,'' said Paul
M. Bangiola, chairman of the Morris County Democratic Committee,
who is leaning toward supporting Murphy. ``He's charming. But the
rich guy rap is a tough one to overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   In perhaps the surest sign that Corzine is viewed in some
quarters as the man to beat, labor supporters of other Democratic
candidates have begun circulating a memo asserting that under
Corzine, Goldman Sachs helped finance mergers and acquisitions that
led to the layoffs of 74,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we really need another multimillionaire businessman in
politics?'' asked Jimmy Tarlau, president of the Mercer County
Labor Union Council, who favors Pallone. ``If it's between him and
Florio, I think I'd have to support Florio. At least I know what
Florio stands for.''
</P>
<P>
   Corzine's supporters have worked hard to paint a different
picture of the candidate. They describe him as a modest farm boy
who has been New Deal Democrat all his life. Though he owns a
summer home on Long Island's East End, he has also contributed $2
million to help poor minority students attend parochial schools in
New York City, and millions more to support public libraries and
the performing arts. As co-chairman of Goldman Sachs, they say, he
helped create more jobs than were lost through mergers and
takeovers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Corzine grew up on a 120-acre farm in Willys Station, Ill. (pop.
17), where his father grew corn and soybeans. His mother taught
first- and second-grade in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   In his senior year at the University of Illinois, he married a
childhood friend, Joanne Dougherty. The couple, who settled in
Summit in the 1970s, have three children.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with a business degree from the University of Chicago, he
joined Goldman Sachs in 1975. He rose through the ranks, earning a
reputation as an accessible manager and consensus builder, and
became chief executive in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine has clearly succeeded on one front: convincing
Democratic leaders that, for all his money, he is a regular guy.
Tall, lean and balding, with a thick graying beard and mitt-like
hands, Corzine speaks in a soft, slow, serene voice that seems
reassuringly down home.
</P>
<P>
   But Corzine acknowledged that he has much to do to sell himself
to New Jersey's skeptical politicians and wary electorate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an underdog,'' he said. ``I don't enter this under any
preconception that this is anything other than a very difficult
thing to accomplish.''
</P>
</TEXT>
