<SLUG> BC-NY-HEROIN-DEATHS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
4 HEROIN DEATHS IN 4 PLACES REFLECT DRUG'S SPREAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A dentist from New Jersey is found dead in his maroon
Oldsmobile on an East Village street. A young drifter dies on the
same street in a tenement that he shared with squatters. A pressman
dies at the Tribeca printing company where he worked. And a
35-year-old man is found dead in his room at a YMCA. in Greenpoint,
Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   The four men were from different walks of life, but the police
said that they apparently all died Monday or Tuesday in the same
way: from heroin overdoses. Their deaths have sparked unease among
drug users as well as police investigation that will seek to
determine if the four men bought tainted or unusually strong heroin
from a common source.
</P>
<P>
   Their deaths underscored the sense that as heroin use has spread
in New York, many addicts no longer fit the stereotype of junkies
as byproducts of inner-city poverty.
</P>
<P>
   That was painfully evident Tuesday in Summit, N.J., where
friends, neighbors and patients were trying to grapple with the
news that Dr. Peter Brown, 39, whom they knew as a dentist, a
long-distance runner and an avid gardener, had apparently died of a
heroin overdose.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had a picture of a heroin addict, it just wouldn't be
him,'' said James Ralston, the president of a software company with
its office in the same building as Brown's dental practice, on a
genteel stretch of road.
</P>
<P>
   If the news that a suburban dentist had died of an overdose
stunned his neighbors in New Jersey, it was little surprise to the
people who run the Lower East Side Needle Exchange Program, a
storefront operation on Avenue C near East Fourth Street in
Manhattan where addicts trade their old needles for new ones as a
protective measure against AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see men in business attire, women with Prada bags, some who
look like grandmothers,'' said Drew Kramer, the executive director
of the Lower East Side Harm Reduction Center, which runs the needle
exchange along with a number of other services for heroin users and
people with AIDS. He said heroin users have become younger and more
diverse, with nearly a third of recent enrollees under 23.
</P>
<P>
   The four deaths, while an unusually large number for so short a
period, nevertheless reflect the deadly toll that heroin and
morphine continue to take in the city. In 1996, the most recent
year for which figures are available, 560 lives were claimed by the
two drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Brown was found dead in his car at 6:30 a.m. on Monday on Ninth
Street between Avenues C and D. Some empty glassine envelopes were
beside his body, police said. An autopsy conducted Tuesday was
inconclusive, and pathologists are awaiting the results of
toxicology tests before they announce the cause of his death, said
Ellen Borakove, a spokeswoman for the office of the chief medical
examiner.
</P>
<P>
   On the same block, Matthew Boyd, 26, was found dead at 733 E.
Ninth St., a tenement filled with squatters. Across town Richard
Spadafora, 42, a pressman, died Monday at De Jay Litho, a printing
company at 200 Hudson St. in Tribeca. The man who was found dead in
Brooklyn, with a syringe in a nearby sink, had yet to be identified
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   After learning about the deaths of Brown and of Boyd, workers at
the exchange began trying to get the word out about possible
dangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Warning: Dangerous Dope!'' read a leaflet handed out by staff
members. Inside their office, a green chalkboard bore the heading:
``Know Dangerous Drugs? Tell the staff.'' Tuesday, the chalkboard
warned of ``Chocolate colored dope,'' because many users said that
the heroin that caused the overdoses was dark.
</P>
<P>
   But such warnings carry their own risks ``Telling people to be
really careful because someone is selling pure heroin is like
telling people to be really careful because someone is giving away
fast cars that go 200 miles an hour,'' Drew said.
</P>
<P>
   And Steve Finkel, a counselor at the center, said: ``Everybody's
looking for it. They want to know where it is, who has it.''
</P>
<P>
   That was borne out in Tompkins Square Park, where a 28-year-old
heroin user with an inverted Mohawk haircut who gave his name only
as Junior said: ``If the dope's killing people, I want some. That
means it's really good dope. It's just natural to want to get the
best quality of anything in life. Don't you want to go to the best
restaurant?''
</P>
<P>
   As Junior spoke he tried to prop up his friend Frank, who was
nodding out.
</P>
<P>
   The precise causes of death and any possible link between them
were still unclear Tuesday. A police official said that preliminary
laboratory tests conducted on some of the heroin that was recovered
indicated that it was not tainted. He said that the heroin was
stronger than usual _ 70 percent pure _ but that heroin even 85- or
90-percent pure was no longer rare.
</P>
<P>
   Pathologists were awaiting the results of toxicology tests
before determining a cause of death in the three Manhattan cases,
Ms. Borakove said, and an autopsy is scheduled to be performed
Wednesday on the man's body found in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the building where Boyd was found, a resident who gave
his name only as Michael remembered him as an artist who had
planned to go to Maine this week. ``He was found over his
doper-kit,'' said Michael, who accompanied him to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   In Summit, friends said Brown had struggled with alcohol but
that they had never suspected drug use. ``I can't get over this,''
a friend said. ``I didn't sleep a wink last night.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside a church in Summit where Brown had attended Alcoholics
Anonymous meetings, people shook their heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peter tried his hardest,'' said Steve, a patient and friend
who in keeping with the group's tradition gave only his first name.
``It hurt me that he couldn't stay sober, and it's sad that he
couldn't pass away sober. But his death will make me more diligent
about staying sober.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
