<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3245 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAMSEY-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      05-11 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAMSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASE POINTS UP THE `FREEDOM' OF USING ENCRYPTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Do you have freedom of speech if you're writing
computer code?
</P>
<P>
   Last week the 9th Circuit Court of Appeals ruled in Bernstein
vs. Dept. of Justice that you do. The ruling was a milestone in the
commercial use of encryption.
</P>
<P>
   The case concerned a two-page program called Snuffle. Its
author, Daniel Bernstein, was a graduate student when he wrote it,
and is now a professor of mathematics at the University of Chicago.
Snuffle was a neat way to put messages into secret code. To
cryptographers, it was ``a zero delay private-key stream encryptor
based upon a one-way hash function.'' To the State Department it
was munitions, exactly as if Bernstein had devised a new kind of
grenade launcher.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government couldn't stop Bernstein from showing his
program to an American, but if he showed it to a foreigner, he had
to get a license.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because encryption is the bane of police. FBI Director
Louis Freeh told Congress last year that strong encryption is
allowing ``drug lords, terrorists and even violent gangs to
communicate about their criminal intentions with impunity and
maintain electronically stored evidence of their crimes impervious
to lawful search and seizure.''
</P>
<P>
   Encryption was once the tool of spies; now it is as common as
keyboards. Like curtains on windows, it shields both the innocent
and the wicked.
</P>
<P>
   That's the police's worry, and it's real. The question was
whether government could stop Bernstein from publishing Snuffle on
the Internet, where foreigners could download it. Did its demand
that Bernstein get a license, which officials could refuse, violate
his constitutional rights?
</P>
<P>
   Two judges said it did. One said it didn't.
</P>
<P>
   The dissenting judge, Thomas Nelson, argued that the language
Snuffle was written in, C, is one that ``only a few people can
actually understand.'' To him, the program was a tool to manipulate
a machine, and was ``more like conduct than speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the court, Judge Betty Fletcher noted that Snuffle
was in source code unreadable by a machine unless compiled into
ones and zeroes. Source code, she wrote, is ``meant to be read and
understood by humans.'' Programmers use source code ``in much the
same way that mathematicians use equations or economists use
graphs'' _ to communicate ideas. That's speech, she wrote, and
therefore cannot be subject to ``the boundless discretion'' of
federal officials.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling ended there, but she made two observations. First,
she wrote, the export controls are an attempt to ``interdict the
flow of scientific ideas,'' which ``would appear to strike deep
into the heartland of the First Amendment.'' Second, she wrote,
encryption is a way for people to protect their privacy while using
cell phones, e-mail and the Internet. Taking that away may violate
people's Fourth Amendment right to be secure in their persons and
papers.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department has not given up. It has asked the full
9th Circuit to rehear the case, and if it loses there, will likely
appeal to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   All this is more than academic interest. Ira Rubinstein, senior
corporate attorney at Microsoft Corp., says that company uses
strong encryption for ``virtually every product we ship that does
any kind of network communications.'' Even its Internet Explorer
browser, which it provides for free, comes in two versions: a U.S.
version, with strong encryption, and a foreign version, with
encryption easier to crack.
</P>
<P>
   Until 1997, this common browser, on millions of computers in the
United States, was classified under the U.S. International Traffic
in Arms Regulations as munitions. Jurisdiction has been moved to
the Commerce Department, so that absurdity has been removed. But it
is still illegal to give the U.S. version of Explorer to, say, a
Frenchman.
</P>
<P>
   The foreigner, however, can turn to a number of companies that
offer upgrades to U.S. products. One example is Baltimore
Technologies (www.baltimore.ie), which, despite its name, is based
in Ireland. There are lots of other ways to get software; it is a
product, Rubinstein says, ``that does not lend itself to this kind
of control.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's hope is a bill in Congress called the SAFE Act,
which would remove export controls on consumer software. The bill,
which has been pushed for several years now, is supported by the
Washington state delegation except Rep. Norm Dicks, who has sided
with the FBI. Rubinstein says the SAFE Act is on a fast track in
Congress and should be out of committees by the July 4 recess.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that will do it. If not, there is always the Bernstein
case, slowly winding its way toward the high court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
