<SLUG> BC-NJ-COURT-WHITMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITMAN VOWS TO BYPASS BAR ASSOCIATION
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JERRY GRAY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Gov. Christie Whitman, still angry over the
state Bar Association's rejection of her nomination of Attorney
General Peter Verniero to the state Supreme Court, said Tuesday
that she would not send any future Supreme Court nominees to the
bar for review.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, it's not my intention to go to the bar for
Supreme Court nominations,'' said Whitman, who has criticized the
association harshly for leaks of what was supposed to be a
confidential process of reviewing Verniero's qualifications. ``For
other court nominations, we need to review and make sure we will
continue confidentiality that can be guaranteed by the bar. We're
reviewing it all.''
</P>
<P>
   In just over five years in office, Whitman has already made her
mark on New Jersey's Supreme Court. She has made three appointments
to the seven-member court, and two other justices will reach the
mandatory retirement age of 70 before her term expires in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   In explaining her decision during a bill-signing ceremony in
Princeton Tuesday, Whitman said a governor does not need the bar
association's assessment for a Supreme Court nominee in the same
way that he or she would need help judging lower court candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know those candidates,'' she said of the Supreme Court
nominees. ``It's not the same as many of the lower court justices
that we don't have the time or the ability to review in the kind of
depth that we should, and that's why we have relied on the bar.''
</P>
<P>
   The bar association rejected the Verniero nomination in a 17-6
vote. But in the 40-member Republican-controlled Senate on Monday,
Verniero received 21 votes, the minimum needed for approval, after
a bitter partisan fight.
</P>
<P>
   And Whitman's comments Tuesday angered Democrats all over again.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Minority Leader Richard Codey called it ``an act of
spite'' that should be put on hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``A decision that significant shouldn't be made in a climate of
such high emotions,'' Codey said in a statement. ``It would have
been wiser had the governor simply accepted her ultimate victory
instead of reacting to the bar's rejection of her nominee.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph A. Bottitta, the president of the New Jersey State Bar
Association, said he would ``reach out'' to Whitman to discuss her
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Under a 30-year-old compact, governors of New Jersey have
traditionally sent judicial nominations to the bar association for
confidential reviews. The purpose of the compact _ modeled after a
longstanding agreement between the president of the United States
and the American Bar Association _ was to try to remove politics
from judicial choices.
</P>
<P>
   The bar's decision is not binding, but it has traditionally
carried significant weight. Whitman is the first governor to ignore
the bar association's recommendation when it came to a nominee for
the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process was not what we would have hoped for, certainly
not from the confidentiality aspect of the bar's review,'' Whitman
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did not live up to the compact.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
