<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: ANNIVERSARY OF NUCLEAR TESTS
</P>
<P>
   Standing in front of a mural depicting a mushroom cloud, Prime
Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee _ a lame duck since his coalition
lost a confidence vote last month _ cited the tests as one of the
main achievements of his year in office. Vajpayee, the leader of
Hindu nationalist Bharatiya Janata Party, also said the threat to
peace from NATO ``aggression'' in Yugoslavia further justified
India's decision to develop nuclear weapons and added, ``If need be
we will take further steps to bolster India's defenses.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By Celia W. Dugger
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: SENTENCES IN GANDHI KILLING
</P>
<P>
   Eight years after former Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi was
assassinated by a Sri Lankan terrorist, the Supreme Court affirmed
a lower court's death sentence for 4 conspirators, commuted the
death sentence of 3 others to life imprisonment and acquitted 19
people. Last year the trial court sentenced all 26 to death by
hanging.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Celia W. Dugger
</P>
<P>
   VIETNAM: DISSIDENT SPEAKS OUT
</P>
<P>
   Nguyen Dan Que said the National Assembly should move toward
free elections. His statement, issued on the Internet, was his
first since being released from detention nine months ago. Que, a
doctor in his mid-50s, was sentenced in 1991 to 20 years in prison
for advocating democratic reform. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ By Seth Mydans
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA: OIL PIPELINE ATTACKED
</P>
<P>
   Leftist rebels have bombed Colombia's second most important oil
pipeline for the 31st time this year. The attack, in an area where
both the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia and the National
Liberation Army are active, halted oil-pumping operations.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Larry Rohter
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: ANOTHER POLICEMAN CLEARED
</P>
<P>
   A top police official in Guerrero state has become the 16th
person to be cleared of wrongdoing in the massacre of 17 peasants
in July 1995. The official, Rosendo Armijo, was accused of failing
to control policemen who fired on farm workers traveling to a
political protest. The scandal led to prison terms for 28 police
officers, 15 of whom were freed in April.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Rick Wills
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: ACCORD WITH INUIT
</P>
<P>
   The last Eskimo group in Canada has reached a settlement on land
claims with the government after 22 years of negotiations. The
agreement would increase self-government for the Inuit on their
lands in Labrador, provide them with a share of the royalties in
mineral resources and include approximately $180 US million in aid.
The Inuit will vote in a referendum on the accord this summer.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN
</P>
<P>
   JORDAN'S KING VISITS
</P>
<P>
   Abdullah II of Jordan is in Britain on his first tour of Western
capitals since becoming monarch three months ago after the death of
his father, King Hussein. The 37-year-old, a graduate of the Royal
Military College at Sandhurst, is seeking easier terms on Jordan's
debt and is pledging to continue his father's efforts to bring
peace to the Middle East. He goes on to the United States later
this week. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ By Warren Hoge
</P>
<P>
   NO POWER-SHARING IN WALES
</P>
<P>
   The new National Welsh Assembly, which opens Wednesday, will be
run by Labor alone even though the party did not receive a majority
in an election Thursday. The Labor leader in Wales, Alun Michael,
decided not to seek a coalition with the centrist Liberal Democrats
and will instead seek to persuade rival parties to support Labor
positions. In Scotland, which elected a new parliament of its own
Thursday, talks continued on an expected Labor-Liberal Democratic
coalition.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Warren Hoge'
</P>
<P>
   KEEPING UP WITH THE JONESES
</P>
<P>
   The British Consumers Association rates Buckingham Palace the
worst of 21 tourist attractions in Britain. The palace, which
attracts 300,000 visitors a year, was faulted for being sterile and
stuffy, with ``little effort made to bring the succession of state
rooms to life.'' A palace spokesman responded: ``I'm not terribly
sure what they want _ waxwork dummies?''
</P>
<P>
   _ By Warren Hoge
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
