<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDS-BREWERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reds aren't the worst after game against Brewers
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ For only the fourth time this season, the enigmatic
Cincinnati Reds own a two-game winning streak. And for the first
time in 10 days they are not the National League Central division
bottom-feeders.
</P>
<P>
   With a 9-1 victory over Milwaukee in front of 31,435 Kid Glove
Night fans Tuesday in Cinergy Field, the Reds vaulted over the
Brewers into fifth place.
</P>
<P>
   Can they make it three straight? They haven't won three in a row
all season and get that chance tonight against the Brewers.
</P>
<P>
   Two-run home runs by Barry Larkin, Dmitri Young and Michae
Tucker were the loudest of nine hits as the Reds won for the fifth
time in seven games.
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Mike Cameron contributed three hits, two stolen
bases and a run scored to provide starter Steve Avery with his
second victory against three losses, although he needed help from
the bullpen when he had to leave after five innings with a blister
on his middle finger.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds accosted Milwaukee starter Cal Eldred for three runs in
the first when Cameron led with a single, stole second and scored
on Sean Casey's single. Larkin ripped his sixth homer over the
right field wall for a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Larkin's second error of the season led to a Milwaukee run in
the second, but the Reds barged back for three more runs in the
fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Avery needed 91 pitches to travel five innings and the blister
forced manager Jack McKeon to take him down for pinch-hitter Mark
Sweeney to lead the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney, who is expected to be handed a ticket to Triple-A
Indianapolis Friday when the Reds call up left-handed relief
pitcher Ron Villone, lined a single to center - his fifth pinch-hit
in 13 assignments.
</P>
<P>
   Young cleared the right field wall with his first homer to make
it 5-1, Greg Vaughn reached when center fielder Marquis Grissom
dropped his long fly ball and Vaughn scored on Eddie Taubensee's
two-out single. Hal Morris doubled home a run in the eighth and
Tucker clobbered the team's third two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   Avery gave up no earned runs and two hits, then the bullpen was
dead-solid, perfect again.
</P>
<P>
   Dennys Reyes pitched two innings and struck out three, giving
him eight strikeouts over his last four innings without giving up a
hit.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Sullivan made his sixth appearance in the first seven
games of this homestand and pitched a 1-2-3 eighth and has retired
16 of his last 18 batters, then Gabe White closed the Reds' fun
festivities in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Hal McCoy writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
