<HEADER>
A3253 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-DRAGGING-DEATH-CO     05-11 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-DRAGGING-DEATH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Teenager didn't know woman's body was dragged from stolen
vehicle
 &HT;    By Matt Mossman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOCA RATON, Fla. _ A 14-year-old boy charged Tuesday in the
weekend dragging death of 84-year-old Ida Mirel told police he
didn't realize she was stuck under a fleeing getaway car for almost
a quarter-mile.
</P>
<P>
   When Jimmy Lee Williams and two accomplices saw Mirel's mangled
body trailing behind the stolen 1991 Dodge Spirit, they fled onto
Interstate 95, then dumped the car in a Riviera Beach canal,
according to an arrest report released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't realize that the victim was under there, but he did
acknowledge that he felt a bump,'' Boca Raton Police Chief Andrew
Scott said Tuesday at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Police arrested Williams after his mother turned him in Sunday,
Scott said. He was charged with homicide, robbery and burglary in
the purse-snatching and dragging, and faces life in jail without
parole if convicted, State Attorney's Office Spokesman Mike
Edmondson said.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Williams confessed to yanking Mirel's purse from her
while she was in her car in the parking lot of Wolfie Cohen's
Rascal House, the Boca Raton version of the storied Miami Beach
deli.
</P>
<P>
   Allan and Ida Mirel, who ate there three times a week, were just
leaving Saturday morning, waitress Sylvia Terenzio said. Ida Mirel
had ordered smoked salmon and cream cheese on a bagel.
</P>
<P>
   Scott said detectives are making progress in their search for
Williams' two partners. One is from southern Palm Beach County, and
one is 17 years old, Scott said. He wouldn't release more details.
</P>
<P>
   They are the passenger and driver of the Dodge that ran over Ida
Mirel. After Williams took her purse, she left her car and stood in
front of the Dodge to block their escape.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a spry woman,'' Terenzio said.
</P>
<P>
   The driver inched forward as if to scare her off before speeding
up and hitting her, a witness told police.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis DellaFave told police he rammed the fleeing Dodge with
his black Acura, but couldn't stop it from escaping onto Executive
Center Drive.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was suspected after Riviera Beach Police, Delray Beach
Police, and the Broward County sheriff's deputies chipped in
information and evidence leading to him. The fingerprints in the
Dodge matched Williams', police said.
</P>
<P>
   The boy also confessed to a purse-snatching Friday outside a
Denny's restaurant, Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   If a grand jury approves the charges, Williams will face them as
an adult, Edmondson said. Williams is being held without bond at
the Juvenile Detention Facility in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Mirel's family would not comment, but released a statement
praising the detectives' quick work.
</P>
<P>
   ''We truly appreciate the hard work, dedication, and compassion
shown,'' the family wrote in a fax to police.
</P>
<P>
   At the Rascal House, manager George Burgos said the incident has
spurred talk of increased security. Representatives from the
adjacent Courtyard by Marriott hotel, Rascal House, Houston's and
Macaroni Grill will meet Friday afternoon and have invited police,
hotel manager Jo Luppion said.
</P>
<P>
   In Tallahassee, the Florida Legislature recently passed a bill
to increase the penalty for purse-snatchings from a first-degree
misdemeanor to a second- or third-degree felony. The bill was
sponsored by Sen. Tom Rossin, D-West Palm Beach, and Rep. Debby
Sanderson, D-Fort Lauderdale, whose district includes Boca Raton.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Mossman writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. Alexandra Navarro Clifton contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
