<HEADER>
A3254 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-ENDANGERED-SPECIES     05-11 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ENDANGERED-SPECIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK REVISES ENDANGERED SPECIES LIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ANDREW C. REVKIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the first time since 1987, New York state on Tuesday
proposed changing its list of imperiled animals to remove a handful
of creatures that are clearly faring better _ like the Eastern
bluebird _ and to add scores of species of fish, butterflies,
turtles and waterfowl that are now in danger of being wiped out.
</P>
<P>
   Because so many more species are now in jeopardy _ listed by
state officials as endangered, threatened or of special concern _
the total number of protected species would leap to 133 from 88,
even after some species came off the list.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Nye, the director of the endangered species unit of the
state Department of Environmental Conservation, said that many new
listings were a result of increased development.
</P>
<P>
   In the good news portion of the proposal, 11 species, including
some of the state's most renowned birds, showed sufficient
improvement to move down a category or drop from the list entirely.
</P>
<P>
   Bald eagles dropped from endangered to threatened, reflecting a
recent sharp rise in the number of pairs nesting in upstate New
York and the Hudson River Valley. The Eastern bluebird, the state
bird, dropped from the list entirely, thanks largely to a burst of
private efforts to build tens of thousands of bluebird houses over
the past decade, Nye said. And the barn owl, a ghostly white-faced
predator, also left the list.
</P>
<P>
   But dozens of other creatures that are less visible but still
important to the ecology were added or moved upward to categories
indicating they were in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``The changes to the list reflect changes to the landscape,''
said David Miller, the executive director of the New York chapter
of the National Audubon Society. ``As we add more people and
development, we're going to have more conflicts with species and
our ability to protect biodiversity.''
</P>
<P>
   Several bird species that rely on wetlands or open grasslands
were added to the list of endangered or threatened species,
reflecting a steady loss of these kinds of habitats on Long Island
and in the Hudson River Valley. These include the black rail, which
will now be endangered, and the least bittern, which moved up to
threatened.
</P>
<P>
   In a released statement, Gov. George Pataki stressed the good
news about eagles and bluebirds, but also said it was important now
to focus on less flashy creatures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the species we are adding do not capture our
imagination as easily as the bald eagle,'' he said. ``Nonetheless,
these organisms are important to preserving the biodiversity of our
state.''
</P>
<P>
   The changes will take effect after they are published in the
State Register later this spring and after a 45-day public comment
period. State officials do not expect to make any changes to the
list, which can be found on the Web site of the state Department of
Environmental Conservation: www.dec.state.ny.us.
</P>
<P>
   The new list adds 39 species of insects, mollusks and other
invertebrates, categories that were neglected in past efforts to
determine which species needed protection, Nye said. The new
invertebrate arrivals include the dwarf wedgemussel, a mussel whose
New York range is limited to the Neversink River, and Hessel's
hairstreak, a butterfly that lives only in Atlantic white cedar
swamps.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of so many inconspicuous animals reflects current
thinking by biologists on the best strategies for preserving
ecosystems _ working from the bottom of the chain of complexity
upward instead of focusing on so-called flagship species, like
eagles or bobcats.
</P>
<P>
   The state's endangered species law went into effect in 1970,
paralleling the Federal Endangered Species Act, although lacking
some of that law's punch.
</P>
<P>
   When a species is listed by the state as endangered or
threatened, it cannot be killed or its habitat destroyed without
permission of state environmental officials. Violators can be fined
$1,000, with an added penalty of $250 for each affected creature.
But because the law is difficult to enforce, fines are rare.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
