<HEADER>
A3381 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-PBS-AUDIT-COX     05-11 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-PBS-AUDIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia public television in crisis, auditor warns
 &HT;    By Peter Mantius and Kathey Pruitt
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ongoing budget deficits at Georgia Public Broadcasting
during the past several years are projected to top $7 million by
this summer and could cause problems for the state agency in paying
vendors and meeting payroll, according to a draft report issued
Tuesday by the state auditor.
</P>
<P>
   The report to Gov. Roy Barnes states that the state agency,
which operates Atlanta's WGTV and 22 other TV and radio stations,
suffers from ``systemic management problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Lack of appropriate controls ``has created a climate that would
allow fraud and abuse to occur with little chance of being
detected,'' State Auditor Claude Vickers wrote in an 11-page letter
to the governor.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said he will withhold specific comment until he has had
time to fully review the auditor's interim findings. However,
Barnes indicated that problems pointed out in the draft report
won't be ignored.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to make sure anything in state government operates
in a businesslike manner. I want to make sure we remedy any
situation that exists,'' said Barnes, who released the preliminary
report to the news media.
</P>
<P>
   Werner Rogers, the agency's executive director, said he plans to
ask for a meeting with the auditor before Vickers issues his final
report. He said the auditing team that prepared the draft didn't
meet with him or his deputy during their most recent three-week
inspection.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers said he disagreed with several conclusions in the draft,
notably the prediction that the agency would have trouble paying
its vendors or staff by the end of the fiscal year on June 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't anticipate not being able to pay vendors or meet our
payrolls,'' Rogers said. ``We're not concerned about that.''
</P>
<P>
   The report predicts the agency will run in the red for the third
straight year by spending $1.7 million more than it takes in during
the fiscal year ending June 30. That will increase its deficit to a
projected $7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Without elaborating, the report said the deficit will create
``significant cash flow problems in paying vendors and meeting
employee payrolls.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers blamed the red ink on higher dues charged by the Public
Broadcasting Service and payments on a $4.5 million loan for
telecommunications equipment. PBS raised the agency's dues from $3
million to $5 million the year it moved into a new $45 million
headquarters on 14th Street, Rogers said.
</P>
<P>
   But the report said Georgia Public Broadcasting gets annual
funding from the federal Corporation for Public Broadcasting that
nearly offsets the PBS dues.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes acknowledged Georgia Public Broadcasting's arguments that
the cost of operating the new building and additional dues to
public radio have had an impact on the agency's revenue stream, but
he appeared unwilling to accept that rationale as the principal
cause of the agency's financial problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll just have to examine that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The report also states that the agency used public funds for
unnecessary or questionable expenditures and failed to properly
safeguard expensive parts and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other findings, the report found the agency had:
</P>
<P>
   _ Used $442,000 in state funds to pay a private firm to provide
PeachStar, a distance-learning program, for 475 out-of-state
students.
</P>
<P>
   _ Paid $472,350 to another private firm for which it has no
written contract.
</P>
<P>
   _ Made travel advances of more than $25,000 for which it did not
maintain records from those who received the money.
</P>
<P>
   _ Held $613,000 in accounts receivable which are more than nine
months old as of March 31.
</P>
<P>
   _ Renewed without rebidding a $790,000 contract with a private
firm to operate a PeachStar ``help desk'' and to provide extended
warranty coverage for satellite dishes and equipment used to
provide the program.
</P>
<P>
   The agency intends to explain many of the items cited, Rogers
said. For example, he said, the agency chose to renegotiate rather
than rebid $790,000 contract and won a $110,000 price cut.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers also said the report failed to properly acknowledge the
success the agency has had in correcting problems cited in previous
audit reports.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes wouldn't discuss the possibility of top management
changes at Georgia Public Broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Mantius and Kathey Pruitt write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
