<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3383 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOTOROLA-AZR &LR;      05-11 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTOROLA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTOROLA PLANS TO SELL LOW-END CHIP UNIT TO TEXAS PACIFIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By REBECCA ROLWING  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A day after a group of former executives announced an ambitious
buyout bid for Motorola's low-end chip business, the company said
it's already sewn up a $1.6 billion deal to sell the division to a
Texas buyout firm.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola Inc. said Tuesday it plans to sell its Phoenix-based
Semiconductor Components Group to Texas Pacific Group, the
investment vehicle of prominent financier David Bonderman.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement apparently quashes a competing bid from an
obscure Tempe company created by former Motorola executives seeking
to buy the division, which has 10,000 employees, including 2,500 in
the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   While the principals of TFG Acquisition Corp. say they will make
a counter offer of $1.76 billion, Motorola says it's too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deal is done; it's over,'' said Bob Growney, Motorola
president and chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have suspected for months that the world's No. 3
chipmaker would sell off the group that makes low-end chips for
everything from household appliances to cars.
</P>
<P>
   The commodities component division has fallen outside of
Motorola's strategy to concentrate on customized chips that bring
in fatter profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   The transaction, subject to regulatory approval, is expected to
become final in the second half of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Pacific Group and Motorola promise the buyout will bring
few changes to Phoenix where the new company will keep its
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   In October, Motorola culminated a massive restructuring that
slashed 2,075 jobs from its divisions throughout the Valley. The
semiconductor group took the brunt of the cuts, losing 1,400
positions.
</P>
<P>
   The new company plans to add rather than cut jobs, said Texas
Pacific principal Dipanjan Deb.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the hard (restructuring) work has been done,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The sale could be a boon to the Valley, said Ray Jodoin, senior
analyst with the market research firm Cahners In-Stat Group in
Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could end up being very good with a management group that
wants to take what Motorola considered old technology and make it
grow,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some warned that more cost cutting may come if the new
investors are seeking a quick jump in profits. ``Motorola has moved
in the past couple of years to implement cost cuts,'' said Dale
Pfau, an analyst with CIBC Oppenheimer. ``As a private company,
they are able to make changes more rapidly.''
</P>
<P>
   Helping to ease the transition, Texas Pacific officials said
they would keep the management team that ran the division for
Motorola including 28-year veteran Steve Hanson, who will be
president of the business.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are creating here is the No. 1-largest supplier of
semiconductor components in the industry,'' Hanson said.
</P>
<P>
   Cheers and applause erupted after local employees learned of the
change Tuesday, Hanson said.
</P>
<P>
   But some workers, including eight-year Motorola employee Dave
Rimer, said the changes caused them concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would force us to re-evaluate our work situation and decide
if we want to stay with the company or move,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Employees have nervously questioned the fate of the division
since Motorola said nine months ago that it was considering selling
the business.
</P>
<P>
   Growney said about five groups approached Motorola to talk about
buying the division that has suffered in recent years the largest
drop in orders and sales within its $7.3 billion semiconductor
division.
</P>
<P>
   After weighing how a sale would affect employees, customers and
shareholders and whether the suitor had the financial backing to
close the deal quickly, Motorola decided to move foward with the
Texas Pacific offer.
</P>
<P>
   The buyout group, which last year acquired ZiLOG Inc., a
producer of chips used in TV remote controls and telephone
answering machines, gravitated to the division for a couple of
reasons. It's somewhat resistant to the dramatic boom and bust
cycles that define the chip industry and it demands less capital
spending than other semiconductor businesses, Deb said.
</P>
<P>
   The offer ranks as Texas Pacific's largest deal yet.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the proposed transaction, Motorola would receive
$1.6 billion in cash, notes and about 10 percent of the stock of
the new company.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street responded favorably to the news. Motorola stock
touched a record 86 1/2 Tuesday to close at 85 7/8, up 4.
</P>
<P>
   TFG Acquisitions, which incorporated in February, apparantly
caught wind of the Bonderman group's offer and revealed Monday its
own $1.6 billion bid for the components group.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Harris, TFG vice president, said Tuesday that it would
boost its offering price to $1.76 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've upped the ante on this enough that Motorola can afford
to get out of the (Texas Pacific) agreement,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Motorola board has considered its options and made its
decision, Growney said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Pacific will own the sector's buildings on 52nd Street and
McDowell Road, however Motorola will retain the 105 acres of
property and lease them back to the new company.
</P>
<P>
   The campus is a federal Superfund site, a designation acquired
after pollutants and other chemicals from the plant seeped into
groundwater, sparking numerous lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola is working to clean up the site and will continue its
efforts until they are complete, said Motorola spokesman Bill
Seiferth. &QL; 
Rebecca Rolwing can be reached at 444-8305 or
rebecca.rolwing(at)pni.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-99 2330EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
