<SLUG> BC-GEN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS' SLOW START NO SURPRISE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's pitching-starved edition of The Sporting Muse:
</P>
<P>
   Angels fans who check the American League standings daily
shouldn't look first at their deficit behind Texas. They should
instead note their team is only a half-game better than the
wretched Orioles and rank 12th in the 14 team A.L.
</P>
<P>
   This was as predictable as a Tim Belcher fifth-inning eruption.
The Angels entered the season with the same uncertain pitching
staff as they concluded 1998, and it is living down to
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   One only has to look at what happened to Seattle last season to
see where the Angels are headed in '99. The Mariners' unsettled
pitching needs, accented by Randy Johnson's contract situation, led
to a slow start that neither Ken Griffey nor Alex Rodriguez could
overcome.
</P>
<P>
   If that duo couldn't makeup for horrid pitching, why should we
expect any better from Tim Salmon and Mo Vaughn? ...
</P>
<P>
   Am I the only person surprised that the Dodgers' Gary Sheffield
convened a players-only team meeting because the team was playing
lackadaisically?
</P>
<P>
   It's great that Sheffield is involved in the team process, but
of all the Dodgers contributing to an inconsistent start, his play
seemed as lackadaisical as anyone else's.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have all been guilty of too much talk about effort
and solidarity. They need to stop talking and start acting like
their play is the most important thing in their lives. ...
</P>
<P>
   News item: Pete Rose becomes hitting coach for an independent
minor league team. Reaction: Pete should stop staging these minor
playlets regarding his love for baseball and do the one thing he
has yet to do admit he made a huge mistake betting on baseball and
beg forgiveness. ...
</P>
<P>
   Paul Silas, who just signed a multiyear deal to coach the
Charlotte Hornets, has set what has to be a world record for
longest span between head coaching jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Silas was named interim coach earlier this year when Dave Cowens
quit, 16 seasons after being fired by the Clippers after the
1982-83 season. This is just the latest testimony to the black hole
that is Clippers basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Silas wasn't ready to be a head coach when he was hired in
1980-81, scant months after retiring as a player. He won 36, 17 and
25 games in three years, the Clips' last years in San Diego before
moving north. But waiting 16 years before another opportunity?
</P>
<P>
   All those who find themselves in Clipperland are united in their
desire to get out. But checking Silas' record made me scan the
archives to see if anyone ever has accomplished anything after
escape.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Harper signed with Chicago as a free agent for the 1994-95
season, then hit the lottery when Michael Jordan returned from
baseball. Bill Walton played with the Clips for one season (1985),
then was traded to Boston, which won a title in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   That's it for the success stories. Michael Cage? He got to the
Western Conference finals once. Charles Smith? Retired without
success. Danny Manning? Dogged by injuries. Brent Barry? Cut loose
by Miami and booed by Bulls fans. Larry Brown? Got as close as the
Eastern finals one year in Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the Clippers are like a virus that never leaves
your body. ...
</P>
<P>
   I like Scottie Pippen, but if I own the Houston Rockets, I'm
disappointed with his performance and what he's done for the team.
It probably doesn't help that Pippen and Charles Barkley seem to be
working independently of each other. ...
</P>
<P>
   The Detroit Pistons' play this season and in the playoffs (0-2)
should make it very easy for Grant Hill to jump to the Bulls as a
free agent this offseason assuming Grant wants the attention that
will come from being the first team leader after Michael Jordan.
...
</P>
<P>
   With Dennis Rodman out of the game, the only thing seemingly
standing between Alonzo Mourning and the greatness expected of him
would be his long-time tormentor, the Knicks. If 'Zo can outlast
New York's thuggery, maybe this is Miami's turn to at least make
the finals. ...
</P>
<P>
   Watching Long Beach State's men's volleyball team last week
rammed home two unique points. One, the sport of volleyball has
reached the point where it can turn a profit for colleges with
powerful programs.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Ratelle said the Mountain Pacific federation has stockpiled
$1000,000 from its last three tournaments. The NCAA in the past has
used money losses as a reason for limiting the size of the playoff
field, Ratelle said, ``but they can't use that excuse any longer,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   He would like to see regional tournaments, a la women's
volleyball, that would give more teams an opportunity to play for a
Final Four berth. As it stands now, two conferences outside the
west get automatic berths whether they are deserved or not.
</P>
<P>
   Secondly, men's volleyball is suffering from gender inequity.
The point of Title IX was to offer the same opportunities to women
sports-wise as they were the men. But the process of raising those
standards have come at the expense of men's program, and often in
the same sport, like volleyball.
</P>
<P>
   Ratelle only has 4{ scholarships to go around, while Brian
Gimmillaro has 11 for his women's team. The presence of nine
Californians and not a single player from Utah on the BYU roster is
an example of the talent that leaves the state each year because of
scholarship limitations. ...
</P>
<P>
   The odds are 1-20 that Bob Baffert will enter his other filly,
the outstanding Silverbulletday, in the Preakness this weekend.
There's good depth in the 1999 3-year-old field, but few standouts.
Baffert openly second-guessed his decision to have her run (and
win) the Kentucky Oaks the day before the derby. ...
</P>
<P>
   News item: Pete Sampras struggles on clay court in the Italian
tourney prep for French Open. Reaction: Why doesn't Sampras just
bag Paris once and for all? Being unable to win on clay doesn't
diminish the other 11 grand slam titles he's won. Indeed, why does
anyone play on clay?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
