<SLUG> BC-SOTHEBY'S-AUCTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MYSTERY BIDDER PUSHES UP PRICES AT SOTHEBY'S IMPRESSIONIST AUCTION
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A mystery telephone bidder known only to the audience
as L036 went on a wild shopping spree at Sotheby's sale of
Impressionist and modern art Monday night, spending nearly $25
million for three Monets, a Rodin, a Sisley and a Signac. That was
all it took to push prices for some offerings way above what many
experts said they were worth.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say the evening was a total success. There were
eerily quiet stretches where the crowded salesroom went dead. Then
there were moments of tension, when several buyers were determined
to bring something home, no matter what the cost.
</P>
<P>
   The evening's sale totaled $55.5 million, below Sotheby's
pre-sale estimate of $74 million to $102 millon. Of the 48 lots on
offer, 18 works failed to sell.
</P>
<P>
   These figures were a letdown after the high of Monday evening
when Sotheby's was hopping with bids for the 50 artworks from the
estate of Betsey Cushing Roosevelt Whitney, the philanthropist and
socialite who died last year. The evening made a total of $128.3
million.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the works at the Whitney sale, what was on offer
Monday night had little in the way of distinguished provenances and
many were familiar to auctiongoers since they had been in sales not
that long ago.
</P>
<P>
   The evening's two most expensive paintings were being sold by
the Nahmad family, Lebanese dealers who run galleries in New York
and London and who have been among Sotheby's and Christie's biggest
buyers for years now.
</P>
<P>
   The Nahmads owned the evening's top seller, Monet's ``Haystack''
(1891), a single haystack that was included in an exhibition of 15
haystack paintings at the Durand-Ruel Gallery in Paris the year it
was painted. The painting was estimated at $8 million to $12
million; it sold for $11.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Nahmads, however, were not as successful with
Toulouse-Lautrec's ``Red-Haired Woman Seated in Mr. Forest's
Garden,'' (1889) a portrait of a young seamstress that was
estimated at between $6 million and $8 million. It failed to sell,
becoming one of the evening's biggest casualties. No one was
willing to pay more than $4.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   This is a big week for Monets: between Sotheby's and Christie's,
13 are up for sale. Last night Sotheby's had six on offer. L036
bought two of them: ``Waterloo Bridge in the Fog'' (1889-1903) for
$6.1 million, and ``The Custom House, in the Morning'' (1882) for
$1.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Not every Monet sold; the artist's ``Rouen Cathedral: The
Courtyard of Albane'' (1892), was expected to bring $1 million to
$1.5 million. Bidding stopped at $850,000. Not a bid came from the
room.
</P>
<P>
   Other Impressionist offerings that failed to sell include:
Pissarro's ``Saint-Sever Pier at Rouen'' (1896), estimated at $1.5
million to $2 million; Degas' ``Woman at Her Dressing Table''
(1895-1900), for which bidding stopped at $2.2 million, under its
low $3 million estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Besides works that failed to sell, some were mysteriously
withdrawn. Hours before the sale, Bonnard's ``Interior,'' (1913)
was withdrawn at the request of the Rosenberg family, who believe
the painting may have been stolen by the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Rosenberg, a leading Parisian art dealer in 1940, had other
works plundered by German occupation forces, and last month the
French government returned a 1904 Monet, one of the ``Waterlilies''
series, to his heirs. ``Sotheby's is cooperating with both parties
and hopes for a speedy resolution,'' Matthew Weigman, a Sotheby's
spokesman, said.
</P>
<P>
   Two still lifes were withdrawn, one by Cezanne and one by
Picasso; no reason was given.
</P>
<P>
   Two other Bonnards were up for sale. ``The Woman in the Tub
(Woman Crouching in a Tub)'' (1912) sold to an unidentified
telephone bidder for $1.8 million, just at its low estimate. A
later painting, ``The Daily Accounting''(1924) was bought by
Abigail Asher, a private dealer, for its high estimate of $1.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a fair price,'' said Ms. Asher. ``People were prepared
to stretch for good things.''
</P>
<P>
   Diana D. Brooks, Sotheby's chief executive, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an enormous amount of interest out there but the
market is very discriminating. If estimates are too aggressive,
people know it. But if it's something someone loves, they'll go for
it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Final prices include the auction house's commission, 15 percent
of the first $50,000 plus 10 percent of the rest. Estimates do not
reflect commissions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
