<HEADER>
A3390 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABORT-LAW-KAN &LR;      05-11 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORT-LAW-KAN </SLUG>
  
 MISSOURI HOUSE OKs BILL BANNING `PARTIAL-BIRTH' ABORTIONS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL SENTELL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JEFFERSON CITY _ A bill that would criminalize a certain
abortion procedure cleared its final legislative hurdle Tuesday
when the House approved it 127-29.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which passed the Senate last week, goes to Gov. Mel
Carnahan, who is expected to veto it.
</P>
<P>
   Backers said the measure is designed to ban ``partial birth''
abortions by classifying them as infanticide. The procedure would
be a felony unless it was done to save the mother's life.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan has said he will not veto the bill before the session
adjourns this week. Legislators say they will try to override his
action at their annual veto session, which starts Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   But an early count shows they could prevail in the end, unlike
two years ago, when Carnahan vetoed a similar measure and
supporters of that bill narrowly missed an override.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsors need 109 votes in the House to overcome a veto. If the
bill's 116 sponsors stick by the bill, the House would have the
votes needed.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate passed the bill 27-6 after more than 38 hours of
debate; 23 of those votes would be needed to overcome a veto.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters hailed the passage of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill is very clear,'' said Rep. Vicky Hartzler, a
Harrisonville Republican. ``It bans a hideous procedure.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Luetkenhaus, a Josephville Democrat, said the bill had
the support of 25 of the 40 women in General Assembly who voted on
the issue.
</P>
<P>
   He said his proposal was not designed to make all abortions
illegal.
</P>
<P>
   ``My intent is, these are human beings and should be protected
once the birthing process begins,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But some critics, including Planned Parenthood, say outlawing
all abortions is just what the bill seems to do. They say the bill
is riddled with flaws, including the absence of a provision to
allow such abortions to protect a woman's health.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Barbara Fraser, a St. Louis Democrat, was among those who
charged that the legislation would ban all abortions. The bill's
prohibition against killing a ``living infant'' is too broad, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does not make it clear when one commits the act of
infanticide,'' Fraser said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. May Scheve, a St. Louis County Democrat, said doctors took
steps that were ``medically necesssary'' when her blood pressure
plummeted in the birth of her son 18 weeks ago. Although everything
turned out fine, she said the experience pointed up the need for
laws protecting a woman's health.
</P>
<P>
   ``It risks the health and lives of real women,'' Scheve said of
the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the bill contend that a health exception would be
abused and make the bill meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   Luetkenhaus said backers went to great lengths to answer
opponents' concerns. A provision in his bill attempts to defuse
criticism by exempting from charges ``any person who performs or
attempts to perform a legal abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents said that the measure was suspicious because it did
not even describe a ``partial birth'' abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Backers said they only wanted to ban the procedure that calls
for the partial, feet-first extraction of the fetus. The barely
visible skull is then punctured with scissors and the brain is
drained before the skull is collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared statement, Carnahan labeled the legislation
``totally deceitful.'' He said it was really aimed at overturning
the 1973 U.S. Supreme Court ruling that made abortions legal.
</P>
<P>
   Lou DeFeo, general counsel for the Missouri Catholic Conference,
said this year's bill had a better chance of taking effect over the
governor's veto than the 1997 measure did.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
