<HEADLINE>
WINONA M. LIPMAN; NORMAN WEISSMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; WINONA M. LIPMAN, 67, VETERAN IN THE NEW JERSEY STATE SENATE &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Wynona M. Lipman, who in 1971 became the first
African-American woman to be elected to the New Jersey Senate, died
Sunday at her home in Newark. She was 67.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was cancer, her office said.
</P>
<P>
   Lipman, a Democrat who represented Newark, was the
longest-serving member of the state Senate. For 27 years she
championed the causes of women, minority groups, children and small
businesses. One bill she sponsored that became law increased
penalties for adults who patronize under-age prostitutes. Another
broadened the statutes on domestic violence to protect more victims
and increase services to the children of troubled families.
</P>
<P>
   She sat on the governor's Council on AIDS, the Task Force on
Child Abuse and Neglect and the New Jersey Court Team on Domestic
Violence.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Georgia, she was educated at Talladega College,
Tulane University and Columbia University, where she received a
doctorate in philosophy on a Rockefeller Grant. She studied at the
Sorbonne as a Fulbright scholar and taught high school. While
serving in the Senate, she was also an associate professor at Essex
County College.
</P>
<P>
   For years she was not only the sole black but also the lone
woman in a house she called a ``men's club'' some years ago. She
held ranking positions on important committees, including those
dealing with human services, the budget and appropriations.
</P>
<P>
   Lipman's survivors include her daughter, Karyne Anne Lipman of
Atlanta, and a sister, Eloise Ransome of Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NORMAN WEISSMAN, 74, EX-HEAD OF AGENCY &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Norman Weissman, a former president of the Ruder Finn
public relations agency in New York, died on Sunday at his home in
Manhattan. He was 74.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of death was cancer, according to a statement from
Norman Weissman Inc., the firm he most recently headed, in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, he had also served as chairman of Citigate
Communications, a subsidiary of the British firm of the same name,
and as vice chairman of the GCI Group, a subsidiary of Grey
Advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Much of his career was spent at Ruder Finn, which he joined in
1958 when it was known as Ruder &AMP; Finn. He served as the agency's
president from 1969 to 1986. He was also Ruder Finn's foreign
specialist, handling clients that included Nippon Telegraph and
Telephone, the Jamaica Tourist Board and the government of
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, he worked four years as editor of a trade magazine, and
three years for the City of New York's Department of Air Pollution
Control, where he was in charge of public relations.
</P>
<P>
   He received his bachelor's degree from Rutgers University in
1949 and a master's degree from the University of Wisconsin in
1951.
</P>
<P>
   Weissman is survived by his son, Lee, of Manhattan and a
brother, Seymour, of Verona, N.J.
</P>
</TEXT>
