<SLUG> BC-SHERIFF-CORRUPTION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE ACCUSES SHERIFF'S DEPARTMENT OF CORRUPTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN L. PETTERSON  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOPEKA _ In a blistering opinion Tuesday, a Shawnee County judge
said crime and corruption had permeated the Shawnee County
Sheriff's Department to such an extent that scores of drug cases
may have to be dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the ruling dismissing drug charges against one
defendant, District Attorney Joan Hamilton said she will file
ouster proceedings against Shawnee County Sheriff Dave Meneley.
That could come by the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that we'll have any alternative but to file it
because of the court's ruling and to ensure that we can get the
credibility back in the department and the cases worked,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   A recall petition drive already is under way. If enough
signatures are collected, Shawnee County voters will decide whether
to remove Meneley.
</P>
<P>
   If Hamilton files an action to oust the sheriff, the matter will
be decided in District Court.
</P>
<P>
   Because of missing evidence from the sheriff's evidence holding
areas, Judge Eric Rosen dismissed drug charges against Carlos
Hernandez on Tuesday, saying it now is impossible to prove the case
against the Topeka man.
</P>
<P>
   The Hernandez case included extensive testimony about drug use
by a former sheriff's deputy, missing drug evidence and a
departmentwide coverup.
</P>
<P>
   Rosen said similar evidence problems may exist with 106
Sheriff's Department drug cases from 1994, 1995 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crime and corruption that occurred within the Shawnee
County Sheriff's Department and has been allowed to continue to
exist by the willful blindness, if not outright support, of several
supervisory and higher echelon employees of the Shawnee County
Sheriff's Department, including the sheriff himself, precludes the
defendant from receiving the fair trial that he is guaranteed by
law,'' Rosen wrote in his 74-page decision.
</P>
<P>
   Meneley, who already has been charged with two counts of perjury
stemming from his testimony in the Hernandez case concerning the
alleged coverup of drugs missing in his department, dismissed
Rosen's allegations as ``one man's opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Judges aren't gods,'' he said. ``They make mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton said she has yet to determine how many of the 106 cases
Rosen cited resulted in charges being filed or convictions being
obtained.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, who filed the perjury charges against Meneley, one of
his deputies and a former deputy, said, ``Something has to be done
to change the Sheriff's Department unless we want criminals
to...walk out.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to a question about his possible resignation,
Meneley said, ``Absolutely not.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the judge's opinion will have an impact on the
day-to-day operations of his office, he said, ``No, we'll continue
to work as we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosen wrote that a former sheriff's narcotics officer, Timothy
Oblander, had a drug addiction and was using cocaine and other
drugs he obtained from evidence holding areas while working for the
sheriff. Oblander resigned in late February and admitted to a
cocaine addiction.
</P>
<P>
   Oblander's partner, Sgt. Frank Good, ``knew of this behavior and
was an enabler in Oblander's procuring drugs and in hiding this
activity,'' Rosen wrote.
</P>
<P>
   He went on to write that at least since June 1995, ``Meneley
knew of the use of cocaine and other drugs and thereafter became
personally involved in covering up this activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosen termed the department's conduct ``outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is inconceivable that the persons charged with the duty of
protecting society and enforcing the law are not only breaking the
law themselves but have engaged in a departmentwide conspiracy to
conceal the illegal conduct,'' the judge wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Rosen wrote that Meneley, ``through calculated investigative
indifference and purposeful personnel promotions, transfers and
demotions, attempted to keep this illegal activity secret within
his department.''
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff, in testimony in the Hernandez case, denied knowing
of his deputy's drug addiction, the stealing of drugs from the
property room or any attempt to cover up the crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Meneley said he was particularly upset that the judge painted
his entire department with a broad brush, indicating that every
officer was corrupt.
</P>
<P>
   ``To paint this whole department as a corrupt department is
absolutely asinine,'' Meneley said. ``He has no evidence of that.
Absolutely none whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   In his conclusion, Rosen wrote that the court cannot let
misconduct by law-enforcement officers to be ignored and excused
while citizens are convicted of similar crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Decency, security and the liberty interests of all our
citizens are threatened by the circumstances surrounding this
case,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The matters brought before this court are shocking and
represent egregious violations of the right of a defendant to a
fair trail. They strain our judicial system and mock the ideal of
justice under the law. They shake not only public confidence in the
system but the system itself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
