<HEADER>
A3406 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-1STLD     05-11 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-680&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSIONAL NEGOTIATORS TRY TO HAMMER OUT EMERGENCY SPENDING
BILLS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: CORRECTS billion to trillion in 14th graf) 
(ATTN: Ala., Alaska, Fla., Ohio, W.Va.)  (Also moving in `w' category) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With $13 billion on the table, congressional
negotiators wheeled and dealed Tuesday over emergency bills to
finance battles in the Balkans, military projects for the Pentagon,
disaster victims in Central America, struggling farmers, big
corporations and favored constituents.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-two members of the House and Senate Appropriations
Committees, meeting deep into the night around a square table in
the Senate's basement, wrangled over three different emergency
spending measures. The bills contain more than double the money
originally sought by the White House, which threatens to veto the
bill if it becomes laden with political provender unrelated to war
or disaster.
</P>
<P>
   The members battled over $1.1 billion in military money sought
by the House to refurbish overseas bases. ``This is going too
far,'' said the Senate Appropriations Committee chairman, Ted
Stevens, R-Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   They fought over hundreds of millions of dollars in amendments
and riders sponsored by senators to benefit corporate interests and
home-state residents. ``We're not prepared to accept any of them,''
said the House Appropriations Committee chairman, Bill Young,
R-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The beginnings of a deal emerged by nightfall: money for the
bases and the riders may die, and $1.8 billion for the first year
of military pay raise that the Congress and the administration plan
to enact may be removed from the bill, key members said, before the
bill is done. The appropriators may also add $500 million for
tornado and storm victims in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   This all began with bad weather and a war. In February,
President Clinton asked Congress for about $1 billion in disaster
relief for millions of people in Central America and the Caribbean
devastated by last year's hurricanes, which killed 9,000 people and
ruined the lives of thousands of others. In April, he sought $6
billion to pay for the continuing bombing of Yugoslavia and to
assists refugees from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Now three main ingredients are in the legislative stew.
</P>
<P>
   One is a $13 billion House bill, which added $7 billion in
Pentagon programs to the White House request for NATO's air war.
Another is a $1.3 billion House disaster relief bill to help the
hurricane victims, which includes White House requests to finance
loans for American farmers and shore up Jordan's role in the
Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
   The third is a Senate version of the disaster bill, which is $1
billion more expensive than the one passed by the House. That extra
money includes a fourth ingredient: pet projects.
</P>
<P>
   Examples from senators' wish lists include $2 million for a
feasibility study for wood veneer products in Alaska, home of
Stevens; $4 million for forestry research in Alabama, home of Sen.
Richard C. Shelby, a Republican member of the committee; $20
million for three jails for criminal aliens, one in West Virginia,
home of Sen. Robert C. Byrd, the committee's ranking Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   They also include royalty rebates and loan guarantees for
industries _ steel, oil, gas and mining interests in senators' home
states _ which add up to $330 million.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd, at 81 the acknowledged master of returning federal money
to his home state, joked about the projects he and his fellow
senators sought. ``That great philosopher, Mae West, once said:
``Too much of anything is simply wonderful.'''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there are riders in the Senate bill that may cost no
money, but that the White House contends could exact a political or
social cost.
</P>
<P>
   One is a provision to block the White House from claiming a
share of the states' quarter-trillion dollar settlement with the
tobacco industry; President Clinton wants to use some of the money
for federal programs like discouraging children from smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Others are more narrowly focused, like proposals easing
commercial mining and fishing regulations. Shelby wants to keep the
Alabama sturgeon off the endangered species list, pleasing business
interests, enraging environmentalists and amusing some of his
fellow members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``This species was declared extinct, and Senator Shelby
sponsored a study that found some,'' said Rep. Ralph Regula,
R-Ohio. ``Three. If there are only three, they probably are
endangered.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There remains the question of how to pay for it all.
</P>
<P>
   The likeliest source is surplus Social Security money. But both
political parties have pledged to keep their hands off that money.
So members in both Houses have proposed offsets, or cuts in other
programs, to help foot the bill.
</P>
<P>
   These include cutting $827 million from anti-terrorism
activities, $521 million in food stamps, $289 million from
drug-control programs, and $150 million from projects to dispose of
50 tons of weapons-grade plutonium in Russia, enough for 15,000
nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The White House budget director, Jacob J. Lew, said Clinton's
senior advisers will recommend a veto unless many of the riders and
cuts are removed or resolved. ``Our goal isn't to have a fight,''
Lew said in an interview. ``Our goal is to have a workable bill
that addresses our concerns.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
