<HEADLINE>
RECALLING A CAT WHO GOT AROUND  
 ALBANY SOUL FOOD 
NO PREDICTIONS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ohio)  (rk) 
 By JAMES BARRON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Norton, a grayish cat with small, folded ears whose far-flung
adventures were described in two books, died on Saturday. He was
16, said the person with whom he lived, author Peter Gethers.
</P>
<P>
   He had kidney trouble and cancer, said Gethers, a former
executive at Random House who has also written novels and
screenplays.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a gift from an ex-girlfriend,'' Gethers said. ``I
didn't like cats at all. She brought him back from Los Angeles and
gave him to me. It was an instant relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon they were going everywhere together. One early trip was to
a weeklong writers' conference in San Diego, Calif. During one
workshop Leona Nevler, an editor at Ballantine Books, became
concerned that Gethers had left Norton (unattended and unleashed)
by the swimming pool at their hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``She couldn't get over why I wasn't worried,'' he said. ``I
went to the last place I had seen him and whistled, and he came out
of the bushes.''
</P>
<P>
   Later Gethers told her that Norton had flown on the Concorde,
had lived in a hotel with views of the Parisian skyline (as well as
open-window access to nearby rooftops) and had attended meetings
with director Roman Polanski &UR;  &LR; and actor Harrison Ford.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said, `You should write a book called, `The Cat Who Went
to Paris.''' Gethers recalled Tuesday. ``I'm supposed to have my
finger on the pulse of American culture, but I totally blew it off.
I said, `Right.'''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Nevler called Gethers' agent and worked out a deal for
the book. That first volume, published in 1991, was followed by ``A
Cat Abroad'' (Crown, 1993).
</P>
<P>
   Eventually Gethers' traveling companion became so well known
that mail addressed to ``Norton, Sag Harbor, N.Y.'' was delivered _
naturally, Norton had a place in the Hamptons. He was recognized
throughout Europe. Once, on a walk through Amsterdam _ Gethers was
doing the walking; Norton was riding on his shoulders _ someone
stopped the pair and said, ``Excuse me, is that the cat who went to
Paris?''
</P>
<P>
   It was. And as Gethers' readers came to understand, Norton was a
cat with a distinct _ and distinctive _ personality. ``He was
independent without being standoffish,'' said Ms. Newberg.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Gethers, Norton is survived by Gethers' friend, Janis
Donnaud.
</P>
<P>
   Albany Soul Food
</P>
<P>
   It has, by now, become something of a custom in Albany: Gov.
George E. Pataki's annual prayer breakfast. Pataki said he
scheduled the first Albany gathering after realizing that all 49
other governors had prayer breakfasts.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 people attended the one Tuesday. Darryl
Strawberry had been invited. (``He opted out after he had his
run-in with the police,'' said a spokesman for the governor.) But
one of his bosses from the Yankees _ Brian Cashman, the general
manager, spoke. So did The Rev. Calvin O. Butts 3rd, pastor of the
Abyssinian Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   As for music, Jennifer Grove, a 17-year-old actress from
Columbus, Ohio, sang ``Over the Rainbow'' from ``The Wizard of
Oz.'' She is appearing in the production at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play Dorothy, so obviously that's part of why I sang it,''
she said, but she added that the rainbow was a biblical symbol of
reassurance. ``I sang the verse before it, that says when the world
is a hopeless jumble and the raindrops tumble all around, heaven
opens a magic lane. It's a song of hope.''
</P>
<P>
   No Predictions
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that was Joe Torre in the trumpet section at Birdland, a
jazz club on West 44th Street near Eighth Avenue, on Monday night.
He was not riffing _ the band had not assembled yet, and he was
looking for an empty chair so he could sit down while autographing
baseballs with the Yankees' former general manager, Bob Watson.
They were raising money for prostate cancer research for the
American Cancer Society.
</P>
<P>
   Torre, who had surgery for prostate cancer in March, would not
say when he would return to work. ``I'm not telling anybody,'' he
said, ``because last time, I said I would have a better idea by May
1. Then you had all the cameras and trucks up at the stadium that
day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
