<HEADLINE>
ADVISORY GROUP STUDIES HMO-STYLE PACKAGES FOR MEDICARE RECIPIENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN BAVLEY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The 52,000 area Medicare beneficiaries in
health maintenance organizations are likely to get cheaper and more
comprehensive vision, hearing and dental coverage next year.
</P>
<P>
   But they will probably pay a little more for doctor's office
visits or brand-name prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Those are among the benefit changes being considered today by a
federal advisory panel preparing Kansas City for an experiment. The
aim is to see whether the government can save money by making HMOs
bid for Medicare business.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City and Phoenix are the first metropolitan areas to take
part in this congressionally mandated pilot project. In both cities
the project has run into opposition from doctors and insurance
plans.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City HMOs are scheduled to submit bids in early July for
Medicare contracts for the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe competition can bring better and more efficient
health care, and I don't mean just cheap,'' said E.J. Holland Jr.,
assistant vice president for corporate benefits of Sprint Corp. and
chairman of the advisory committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it makes eminent good sense to pilot it in some
communities before Congress adopts it'' nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Participation in Medicare HMOs is voluntary. About 23 percent of
the 230,000 Medicare beneficiaries in 11 area counties are HMO
members. Seven companies provide a total of 13 different benefit
packages.
</P>
<P>
   Those enrolled in traditional fee-for-service Medicare generally
receive fewer benefits than those in HMOs, but they have greater
choices of doctors and hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   HMO members typically must use only those providers listed in
their plans, but they receive added benefits, such as low-cost
prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   In most places Medicare gives HMOs a set amount of money to
provide care for each member. HMOs set the benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Under the model being tried here, HMOs will bid on what they
will charge Medicare for a standard benefits package. The advisory
panel, made up largely of health-care and business executives and
Medicare beneficiaries, considers the benefits package today at the
Kansas City Airport Hilton, 8801 N.W. 112th St. The meeting, which
runs from 8:30 a.m. to 5:30 p.m., is open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   The benefits package for next year would be available without a
premium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were taking the benefits that existed (in HMO plans) and
selected among them for benefits that were desirable but wouldn't
break the bank,'' Holland said.  &LR; brk:Benefits comparison
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star compared the proposed benefits to benefits
offered this year by HMO plans that do not charge premiums. Among
the differences:
</P>
<P>
   - Office visits to primary care physicians will be $12; visits
to specialists $17. Most plans now charge $10 per physician visit.
Physical exams, which plans provide free or for a $10 fee, will
cost $12.
</P>
<P>
   - Visits to physical and occupational therapists will cost $12;
most plans now charge $10.
</P>
<P>
   - Ambulance rides will cost $25. Most plans now charge $25 or
more, although certain Cigna HealthCare and HealthNet plans provide
free rides. Emergency room visits will cost $50, the same as most
plans now charge.
</P>
<P>
   - Urgent care, at $25 per visit, will be cheaper than what most
plans charge now for unscheduled doctor visits.
</P>
<P>
   - Beneficiaries will receive one free vision exam a year and a
pair of glasses for $20. Most plans now do not cover glasses.
</P>
<P>
   - A free annual hearing test and a $500 hearing-aid allowance
every three years are provided. Most plans now charge for or do not
offer hearing tests and have small or no hearing-aid allowances.
</P>
<P>
   - Beneficiaries will get up to two dental exams a year for $17
each. Most plans now do not include dental benefits.
</P>
<P>
   - Prescription drug coverage, not offered by traditional
Medicare, is one of the most popular features of Medicare HMOs. But
sharply rising drug costs have made it difficult for HMOs to
maintain this benefit.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed benefits package provides generic drugs for a $10
co-pay, the same as most HMOs now charge. Brand-name drugs will
cost $20; most HMOs now charge $10.
</P>
<P>
   All the HMOs set an annual limit on drug benefits ranging from
$500 to $1,000. The proposed plan sets a cap of $800.
</P>
<P>
   Holland said the committee probably would approve the benefits
package with few or no alterations. A slight improvement in
prescription drug benefits is the only change likely, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be surprised to see the benefit raised a little,
but it won't be unlimited. There will be a cap,'' Holland said.
 &LR; brk:Seeking a delay
</P>
<P>
   Competitive bidding has met with stiff opposition from some
doctors and health insurance plans. The Health Care Financing
Administration, the federal agency that manages Medicare, tried it
in Denver and Baltimore but was stopped by intense insurance
industry opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with strong health-plan lobbying, the Phoenix advisory
panel asked Health Care Financing in March to postpone competitive
bidding there for a year.
</P>
<P>
   Some HMOs and physicians also want a delay in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to rush it through,'' said Mary Jacobi,
spokeswoman for the Missouri Association of Health Plans. ``We have
to do this right and if right takes a little longer, so be it.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles W. Van Way III, a physician and member of the advisory
committee, said he would ask the committee today to seek a delay in
Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're squeezing a process that should take a year-and-a-half
into six or eight months. We just can't do it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Holland dismissed the concerns as a self-interested attempt to
stop competitive bidding.
</P>
<P>
   Holland said he would ask Health Care Financing for a
postponement if the agency granted Phoenix an extension. But he was
confident the committee could stay on schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, we're very close to being finished with what we have
to do, very close,'' he said. ``Instead of spending our time
whining, we spent our time trying to make it work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
