<SLUG> BC-NY-DEATH-PENALTY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNOR PROPOSES TO BROADEN STATE'S DEATH PENALTY LAW
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Gov. George Pataki on Tuesday proposed broadening
the state's death penalty law, including a change that would allow
death sentences for defendants who have pleaded guilty to a murder
charge, and not just those found guilty at trial.
</P>
<P>
   The idea comes in response to a ruling in December by the Court
of Appeals, New York's highest court, that struck down the
plea-bargaining provisions of the death penalty law that was
enacted in 1995. Under that law, a person can be sentenced to die
only at trial, not after a guilty plea. The court ruled in December
that the distinction unfairly penalized defendants for exercising
their right to a trial.
</P>
<P>
   The 1995 law created a crime of first-degree murder, punishable
by either death or life in prison without possibility of parole,
penalties that did not exist in New York at the time. Prosecutors
complained that the court's decision made it impossible to
plea-bargain first-degree murder cases to obtain life sentences,
leaving them with the choice of going to trial or trying to obtain
guilty pleas to second-degree murder, which carries a maximum
penalty of 25 years to life.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, a Republican, proposed allowing a first-degree murder
defendant to enter an ``open plea'' _ a guilty plea without there
being a plea deal with prosecutors _ but only if the prosecutors
and judge agreed. A jury would then decide the penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's plan would also resolve another problem in the
current law, one that has not yet arisen in any case. If a jury,
after convicting someone of first-degree murder, deadlocks between
death and life in prison, the judge cannot impose any greater
penalty than 25 years to life. Pataki would give the judge the same
choice of penalties the jury had.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's proposal includes several other provisions that
would add certain crimes to the list of possible capital offenses
and give prosecutors new advantages in capital cases. Most of those
changes he proposed last year, in a bill that was passed by the
Republican-controlled Senate, but was not acted on by the
Democrat-controlled Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   The assembly speaker, Sheldon Silver, does not yet have a
position on the governor's plan, said his spokeswoman, Patricia
Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   The list of possible first-degree murder offenses now includes
torture killing, killing a police officer and mass murder. Pataki
would add ``thrill kills,'' gang initiation murders, killings to
gain inheritance or collect on insurance, and some accessories to
murder who neither committed nor ordered the killing.
</P>
<P>
   The governor would also let prosecutors give the final summation
in capital trials, rather than defense lawyers, and he would allow
testimony in the penalty phase about the effect of a slaying on the
victim's family and community.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-99 2350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
