A3412 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIGARETTE-TRIAL-KAN &LR;      05-11 0470
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIGARETTE-TRIAL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOBACCO EXECUTIVE TESTIFIES AT TRIAL OF MISSOURI LAWSUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A top U.S. tobacco executive acknowledged in
testimony Tuesday that cigarette smoking can be harmful, but he
defended the way his company has addressed health issues over the
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly believe smoking has been shown to be a risky
behavior,'' said Nicholas Brookes, chairman of the Brown &AMP;
Williamson Tobacco Corp. ``...The statistics are sufficient for us
to conclude that smoking causes these diseases.''
</P>
<P>
   Brookes' company has been sued in federal court by the family of
Charles Steele, who died of lung cancer in 1995 while living in
Vandalia, Mo. They contend Brown &AMP; Williamson was responsible for
maintaining Steele's addiction to nicotine by selling him an
unreasonably dangerous product. They are asking for more than $25
million in damages.
</P>
<P>
   In his testimony Tuesday in U.S. District Court in Kansas City,
Brookes pointed to more than $300 million in health research Brown
&AMP; Williamson has helped to fund with independent scientists since
the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Brown &AMP; Williamson also markets a range of products for smokers
looking to reduce their exposure to cancer-causing substances,
including the lowest tar and nicotine cigarette in the United
States, Carlton Ultra.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a clear responsibility to make cigarettes as safe as
we can with the highest possible materials and to the highest
possible standards,'' Brookes said. ``We have a responsibility to
understand our product.''
</P>
<P>
   But even though Brookes acknowledged that smoking carries health
risks, including lung cancer, he would not say how many Americans
die prematurely each year because of cigarette smoking.
</P>
<P>
   When pressed by lawyer J. Michael Cronan, who represents
Steele's family, Brookes said he didn't agree with health
authorities who estimate about 430,000 people a year die from
smoking.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quite impossible to make those calculations,'' Brookes
said. ``I don't challenge health authorities' right to put that
figure out.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, Cronan sought to refute testimony from two company
witnesses, who said that identifying the cause of Steele's lung
cancer was impossible, in part because of his exposure to
industrial chemicals at work.
</P>
<P>
   Oncologist Ace Allen testified for the Steele family. Allen
showed jurors a chart that calculated Steele's lung cancer risk
from smoking at up to 10 times higher than his risks from chemicals
he may have encountered at work at an aluminum foundry and a brick
manufacturing plant.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers defending Brown &AMP; Williamson rested their case Tuesday
afternoon. The jury will return this morning for instructions from
the judge and closing arguments. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
