<SLUG> BC-FUEL-ADDITIVES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY: SOME ADDITIVES IN REFORMULATED GASOLINE HELP LITTLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MANSUR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Reformulated gasoline _ the key to efforts to
reduce automotive air pollution in the area _ has hit another speed
bump on its road to Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   A federal study released Tuesday reported that some of the
additives used in the new fuel did not do much to reduce urban
smog.
</P>
<P>
   The study did not question the overall effectiveness of
reformulated gasoline in reducing ozone, a component of urban smog.
The study focused on additives that add oxygen to the fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Reformulated gasoline has many components other than oxygen
additives that help reduce ozone. Oxygen additives, however, have
been linked to other environmental concerns, such as groundwater
contamination from leaking gasoline storage tanks.
</P>
<P>
   What these latest findings will mean for Kansas City remains
unclear. The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency has announced it
will not approve the area's long-range transportation plans _ which
call for reformulated gasoline as the linchpin of ozone-reduction
efforts _ until the governors of Missouri and Kansas formally
request the gasoline for Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Both states have so far declined to formally request the fuel.
Instead, they will wait until a ``fuel summit'' early next month in
Kansas City, Kan., when such issues as the additives can be
discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Many local highway construction projects, which require federal
approval, could be endangered by the delay.
</P>
<P>
   The oxygen-adding chemicals, ethanol and methyl tertiary-butyl
ether, or MTBE, ``have little impact on lowering ozone levels,''
said William Chameides, chairman of the National Research Council
committee that conducted the study.
</P>
<P>
   But the study did not find reformulated gasoline ineffective in
general. ``We found reformulated gasoline has some significant
impacts on emissions (of chemicals that form ozone),'' said
Chameides, who is a professor of atmospheric sciences at the
Georgia Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when we look at what the oxygenates (ethanol and MTBE) are
doing, it's not clear they're doing anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The study's findings may add to the growing concern about the
additives.
</P>
<P>
   MTBE, for example, has contaminated drinking water supplies in
other states when it has leaked from gasoline storage tanks, pipes
and motors. In California, state officials have decided recently to
phase out its use in reformulated fuels sold there.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, federal law requires a certain percentage of oxygen
in reformulated gasoline. The additives _ ethanol and MTBE _ have
been used for years in fuels but at lower levels than are required
in reformulated gas.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis-area stations will begin selling the new fuel in June.
State officials said the fuel would include ethanol and MTBE
blends.
</P>
<P>
   Eileen Hiney, environmental manager for the Mid-America Regional
Council, said the new study might further complicate the complex
situation of reformulated gas. But Kansas City should benefit in
the long run, she added.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the metro area brings the fuel here, many of the
questions about the additives may be settled, she said.
</P>
<P>
   To the American Petroleum Institute, the study verified what it
has been saying for years: There's little pollution benefit to
oxygen-adding chemicals in the fuel.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no compelling environmental benefit to them,'' said
Bill O'Keefe, the petroleum institute's executive vice president
and chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   Don Zinger, assistant director of the Environmental Protection
Agency's Office of Mobile Sources, in Washington, said the
additives reduced the level of more-toxic chemicals, including
benzene, which resulted in fewer toxic emissions from tailpipes.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, a special Environmental Protection Agency panel is
expected to recommend in late June whether MTBE should continue to
be used in reformulated fuel.
</P>
<P>
   The National Research Council is the operating arm of the
National Academy of Science and the National Academy of
Engineering. It is a private, nonprofit institution that provides
scientific advice. The Environmental Protection Agency paid for the
study. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
