u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKEES-ANGELS-NY     05-11 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-ANGELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAUGHN MAKES YANKS PAY FOR ERRORS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Anaheim's master plan was to place Mo Vaughn into the
middle of its lineup, surround him with All-Star caliber players
and create an offense that would surely result in more runs than
New York taxis. But Vaughn's supporting cast has been decimated by
injuries, and as he was in Boston, Vaughn is left to carry his
team.
</P>
<P>
   He can certainly do that, as the Yankees know too well. Vaughn
blasted a pivotal three-run homer _ his 13th at Yankee Stadium _
and the Yankees pitched and fielded horribly in a 9-7 loss to the
Angels on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Ramiro Mendoza, told earlier in the day he was being switched
from the rotation to the bullpen, was knocked around for three runs
in three innings and suffered the defeat. Shane Spencer, called up
from Class AAA Columbus to be the Yankees' fulltime left fielder,
pounded a single and a home run.
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom of the ninth, the Yankees (20-11) began to rally
against reliever Troy Percival, but Paul O'Neill took a called
third strike and then began screaming at the home-plate umpire,
Greg Kosc. O'Neill returned to the dugout, but then tossed a water
cooler onto the field. Kosc ejected O'Neill, who approached the
umpire, angrily gesturing, while being held by teammate Bernie
Williams and the first-base coach, Jose Cardenal.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim (14-19), already without outfielder Jim Edmonds
(surgery), shortstop Gary DiSarcina (broken arm) and second baseman
Randy Velarde (stiff lower back), placed right fielder Tim Salmon
on the 15-day disabled list with a sprained wrist before Tuesday
night's game. Angels Manager Terry Collins started a lineup that
included Dave Silvestri, a journeyman with a .207 career average,
as his No. 2 hitter.
</P>
<P>
   But the Angels do have Vaughn, the slugger they signed as a free
agent in the off-season, one of many Angel batters who capitalized
on the ineffectiveness of Andy Pettitte, the Yankees' starter.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte's fastball has been clocked about 86-88 mph so far this
season, slower than last year, and whether it's because of his
diminished fastball or not, Pettitte pitched Monday night as if he
does not trust his stuff. Over a span of 11 batters, from Vaughn in
the third inning through Todd Greene to close the fourth, Pettitte
threw 65 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte would have been the losing pitcher on most nights, but
he happened to be throwing in one of those games that vendors dream
of and Little League parents hate, when all pitchers seem
physically incapable of throwing strikes.
</P>
<P>
   And much of the little movement wasn't exactly picturesque.
Steve Sparks, Anaheim's knuckleballer, carried a 3-1 lead into the
third inning and walked two batters and hit another, and two of the
Yankees' first three runs in the inning stemmed from passed balls
by Greene. The Yankees took a 4-3 lead and added another run when
Tim Unroe, the Angels' right fielder, misplayed Chili Davis' line
drive.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte immediately gave back the runs, walking Orlando
Palmeiro and surrendering a single to Andy Sheets _ the No. 8 and
No. 9 batters _ and with two outs and first base open, Pettitte
kept spinning breaking balls to Vaughn until he made a mistake and
Vaughn blasted a three-run home run. The Angels had six runs, the
Yankees five runs, and the vendors had a killing.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth, Paul O'Neill tagged up on Davis' fly ball and
raced home with the tying run. When Spencer stepped in front of the
weak-armed Bernie Williams to take a fly ball and throw out Sheets
at home plate to save a run in the top of the sixth, the momentum
appeared to belong to the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Not for long.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza, who had been saved by Spencer's play in the sixth,
allowed a solo home run to Garret Anderson with one out in the
seventh. Troy Glaus followed by smashing a one-hopper off Scott
Brosius, the Yankees' third baseman, for a single. Glaus took
second on a groundout, but Mendoza appeared to be out of the inning
when Unroe grounded to first and Mendoza raced over to cover the
bag and Martinez flipped him the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza missed it. Another error, the Yankees' second of the
game and 29th of the season.
</P>
</TEXT>
